<HEAD><TITLE>The DO - September, 1996</TITLE>
<META name="description" content="American Osteopathic Association.">
<META name="keywords" content="Osteopathic, Osteopathic Medicine, Doctor of Osteopathy, DO, Healthcare">
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../bkgd.gif"
         BGCOLOR="#7093DB"
            text="#000000"
            link="#ff0000"
           vlink="#00009c"
           alink="#ffffff">

<!-- Insert HTML  -->

<center>
<h1>The D.O.<br>
September, 1996</h1>
<img src="docover.jpg">
</center>
<br>

<h2>Table of Contents</h2>

<B>Newsbriefs.</b>  Political strategist Ed Rollins will be the keynote
speaker at the AOA's annual convention in Las Vegas in October.<p>

<B>Northwestern DOs review care of patients with Kawasaki.</b>  Children
who develop Kawasaki syndrome can suffer from coronary aneurysms, 
myocardiopathy and pericardial effusion into adulthood, explains
pediatric cardiologist Dennis P. Ruggiere, DO.<p>

<b>Northwestern DOs evaluate trials on stroke treatment, prevention.</b>
Neurologist Roger S. Williams, MD, outlines the current thinking on 
tissue plasminogen activator, carotid endarterectomy and anticoagulants.<p>

<b>AOA creates Web site.</b>  The AOA has created <I></I>access AOA</I> to
provide members of the profession and the public with information on the
World Wide Web.<p>

<b>South Carolina DOs learn to counsel teens on contraception.</b>  One of
the key problems in contraceptive counseling is that many teenagers are
incapable of grasping the long-term consequences of sexual intercourse,
argues adolescent medicine expert Daniel Thad Earl, DO.<p>

<b>DO outlines pneumonia guidelines at South Carolina conference.</b>  
Anthony J. Silvagni, PharmD, DO, urges primary care osteopathic physicians
to follow the pneumonia guidelines of the American Thoracic Society.<p>

<img src="../cover.gif"><p>

 <B>Off the Cuff.</b>  Most patients
with cumulative trauma disorders of the wrist and hand respond to
conservative therapy, such as altering or eliminating the activities
that exacerbate the disorders, performing stretching and strengthening
exercises, and splinting wrists.<p>

<b>Elbow doom.</b>  The elbow is particularly susceptible to cumulative
trauma disorders because it is the relay center between the hand and
the shoulder.<p>

<b>Shouldering pain.</b>  The treatment for thoracic outlet syndrome
should consist of decreasing the patient's pain, relaxing the patient's
muscles, stretching and releasing the patient's myofascia, and correcting
the patient's posture.<p>

<h2>Commencement '96</h2>

<b>New DOs advised to prepare for change, opportunity.</b>  More than
1,900 osteopathic medical graduates are assured that the nation is
looking for healthcare providers with their skills and philosophy.<p>

<h2>Departments</h2>

<B>Editor's bookshelf</b><p>

<b>Graduate physician forum.</b>  Ten osteopathic residents will attend
the AOA's annual convention in Las Vegas as recipients of the AOA's
Glaxo Wellcome Resident Leadership Awards.<p>

<b>In Memoriam</b><p>

<b>Patient health guide.</b>  Parents are advised on how to buy and
install child car seats.<p>

<b>Coming events</b><p>

<b>DO marketplace</b><p>

<b>Classified ads</b><p>

<b>Advertisers' index</b><p>

<h2>Coming up in <I>The DO</I></h2>

The October issue of <I>The DO</I> will be devoted to the annual
meetings of the AOA House of Delegates and Board of Trustees, which
were held in mid-July in Nashville, Tenn.<p>


<center><hr></center>
