<HEAD><TITLE>The DO - August, 1996</TITLE>
<META name="description" content="American Osteopathic Association.">
<META name="keywords" content="Osteopathic, Osteopathic Medicine, Doctor of Osteopathy, DO, Healthcare">
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../bkgd.gif"
         BGCOLOR="#7093DB"
            text="#000000"
            link="#ff0000"
           vlink="#00009c"
           alink="#ffffff">

<!-- Insert HTML  -->

<center>
<h1>The D.O.<br>
August, 1996</h1>
<img src="docover.jpg">
</center>
<br>

<h2>Table of Contents</h2>

<b>Newsbriefs.</b>  John P. Sevastos, DO, became the AOA's 99th president 
on July 21, and Howard M. Levine, DO, became the AOA's president-elect.<p>

<b>New AOA president urges DOs to be accountable.</b>  In his inaugural address, John P. Sevastos, DO, insists that the osteopathic medical 
profession must be accountable to patients and to state and federal 
officials.<p>

<b>Osteopathic medicine runs wild at 100th Boston Marathon.</b>  Robert 
L. Shepler, DO, and Thomas Wesley Allen, DO, were among the approximately 
37,000 people who ran the Boston Marathon in April. In addition, the 
University of New England College of Osteopathic Medicine and the 
Maine Osteopathic Association used the marathon to educate the public 
about osteopathic medicine.<p>

<b>Next AOA education conference to focus on practical solutions.</b>  
The AOA's seventh annual leadership conference on osteopathic medical 
education will examine examples of how medical education programs have 
been modified to meet the needs of the changing healthcare environment.<p>


<b>Retraining for a new era.</b>  In response to changes in healthcare 
economics, some specialists are becoming generalists. While internal 
medicine subspecialists are making the transition to primary care by 
relying on their early training, other  specialists are retraining.<p>


<b>About-face.</b>  Now that it is strategically and economically wise to 
practice primary care, some physicians are trying to have their 
specialties reclassified as primary care fields. Among those physicians 
are obstetricians and gynecologists, specialists in osteopathic manipulative medicine, and emergency physicians.<p><br>


<h2>AOA Convention Preview</h2>

<b>Entertainment capital hosts AOA convention.</b>  The AOA's 101st 
annual convention will be held in Las Vegas for the first time since 
1990. The convention's theme will be <b>"21st Century Challenges and Solutions in Osteopathic Medicine."</b><p><br>

<h2>Departments</h2>

<UL>
<LI>Request form for The DO  and the JAOA
<LI>Editors bookshelf
<LI>Hotel registration form for the AOA's 101st Annual<br>
    Convention and Scientific Seminar
<LI>AOA fact sheet
<LI>Advance registration form for the AOA;s 101st Annual<br>
    Convention and Scientific Seminar
<LI>In memoriam
<LI>Coming events.

<center><Table width=75%><tr><td>
The AOA's 101st annual convention, the American College of Osteopathic Internists' 56th annual convention, and the 69th annual Clinical Assembly of Osteopathic Specialists are among the programs listed in this month's column.
</td></tr></table></center>

<LI>DO marketplace
<LI>Classified ads
<LI>Advertisers; index
<LI>Classified ad order form
</UL>

<H2>Coming up in The DO</h2>
The September issue of The DO  will explore cumulative trauma disorders 
of the upper extremities.  The issue also will provide coverage of the 
spring graduation ceremonies at the nation's osteopathic medical colleges.<p>


<center><hr></center>
<p>


