<HEAD><TITLE>access! A.O.A. News</TITLE>
<META name="description" content="American Osteopathic Association.">
<META name="keywords" content="Osteopathic, Osteopathic Medicine, Doctor of Osteopathy, DO, Healthcare">
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../bkgd.gif"
      BGCOLOR="#7093DB"
      text="#000000"
      link="#ff0000"
      vlink="#00009c"
      alink="#ffffff">

<!-- Insert HTML  -->


<center>
<img src="../../news1.gif"><br>
<img src="../../rule2.gif"><p><br>
<p>
</center>

<img src="blanck.jpg" align=right>


<h3>Major General Ronald R. Blank, U.S. Army,
DO, First Osteopathic Physician Sworn in as Surgeon General of the
United States Army</h3>
<p>

<!-- insert HTML here -->

<b>Chicago -- </b>Major General Ronald R. Blanck, U.S. Army, DO, a board certified osteopathic physician, was sworn in as the 39th surgeon general of the Army and was promoted to the three-star rank of lieutenant general on October 1.
<p>
A 1967 graduate of the Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine, General Blanck is currently the commander of Walter Reed Army Medical Center and the North Atlantic Regional Medical Command.  As the Army's surgeon general, he will also command the U.S. Army Medical Command at Fort Sam Houston, Texas.  The medical command operates eigth medical centers, nearly 30 community hospitals, as well as research and teaching institutions around the world.
<p>
Entering the Army in 1968, General Blanck was assigned as a general medical officer in Vietnam.  Following an assignment as a general medical officer at Fort Myer, General Blanck completed a residency in internal medicine at Walter Reed in 1973.  He went on to serve as assistant chief of the general medicine service and as the assistant chief in the department of medicine at Walter Reed.  Later assignments included serving as assistant dean of student affairs at Uniformed Services University School of Medicine; chief of the department of medicine at Brooke Army Medical Center at Fort Sam Houston; and chief of the medical corps career activities office in the office of the surgeon general.  General Blanck also served as commander of the Frankfurt Army Regional Medical Center in Frankfurt, Germany and as the director of professional services and chief of medical corps affairs in the office of the surgeon general.
<p>
General Blanck's military awards include the Defense Superior Service Medal, the Legion of Merit, the Bronze Star, and the Meritorious Service and Army Commendation Medals.
<p>
A graduate of the Army War College, General Blanck has held many academic positions throughout his military career.  He was assistant professor of clinical medicine at Georgetown University; associate professor of medicine at the Uniformed Services University School of Medicine; and clinical professor of medicine at the University of Texas at San Antonio.
<p>
General Blanck's memberships include:  the American Osteopathic Association, the Association of Military Osteopathic Physicians and Surgeons, the Association of Military Surgeons of the United States, and the American College of Physician Executives.  He is a fellow and past governor of the American College of Physicians.
<p>

<!-- end of text -->
