<HEAD><TITLE>The DO - October, 1996</TITLE>
<META name="description" content="American Osteopathic Association.">
<META name="keywords" content="Osteopathic, Osteopathic Medicine, Doctor of Osteopathy, DO, Healthcare">
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../bkgd.gif"
         BGCOLOR="#7093DB"
            text="#000000"
            link="#ff0000"
           vlink="#00009c"
           alink="#ffffff">

<!-- Insert HTML  -->

<center>
<h1>The D.O.<br>
October, 1996</h1>
<img src="docover.jpg">
<br>
<B>COVER</b><P>

<P>The cover portrait of AOA President John P. Sevastos, DO, was created by illustrator Robert Flori. The artwork was sponsored by the Ross Products Division of Abbott Laboratories.

</center>
<br>

<h2>Table of Contents</h2>

<B>Newsbriefs.</b>  The US Congress unanimously passed legislation that recognizes AOA board certification under Medicaid.<p>



<B>AOA House adopts policy on maternity, newborn stays.</b>  At its 1996 meeting, the AOA House of Delegates took a stand on issues ranging from the care and discharge of newborns and their mothers to the need for all medical forms to have signature blocks imprinted with the degrees "MD/DO."<p>

<B>Dr Sevastos works to strengthen, broaden profession.</b>  AOA President John P. Sevastos, DO, is laying down a foundation that he hopes will allow the profession to become three times larger and three times stronger in the next 15 years.<p>

<B>Dr Levine foresees renaissance in OMT.  </b>AOA President-elect Howard M. Levine, DO, predicts that the recent publication of AOA's <I>Foundations for Osteopathic Medicine</I> textbook will lead to a rebirth of interest in osteopathic manipulative treatment.<p>

<B>Dr Neer recounts year of political gains for DOs.  </b>Howard L. Neer, DO, spent his year as the AOA's president encouraging his colleagues to become involved in grassroots efforts to influence federal and state legislation.<p>

<B>The survival of osteopathic medicine.  </b>In his Andrew Taylor Still Memorial Address, Joseph W. Stella, DO, calls on all osteopathic physicians to take pride in their hard-earned DO degrees, to help select highly motivated students for osteopathic medical colleges, and to be active in the AOA and other osteopathic medical organizations.<p>


<B>LISTS</b><br>
<UL>
<LI>Officers and members of the AOA Board of Trustees
<LI>Members of the AOA House of Delegates
<LI>Reference committees of the 1996 AOA House of Delegates
<LI>Appointments to AOA departments, bureaus, councils and committees for 1996-97
</UL>


<B>HOUSE AND BOARD REPORTS:</b><br>

<UL>
<LI>Senior staff
<LI>Department of Educational Affairs
<LI>Department of Professional Affairs
<LI>Department of Public Affairs
<LI>Department of Business Affairs
<LI>Department of Governmental Affairs
<LI>Affiliated organization

</UL>


<B>DEPARTMENTS</b><br>

<UL>
<LI>Editor's bookshelf
<LI><b>In memoriam.</b>  A former AOA trustee is remembered, as is the first dean of the profession's New York college.
<LI>Coming events
<LI>DO marketplace
<LI>Advertisers' index
<LI>Classified ads

</UL>


<B>Coming up in <I>The DO</I>:</b><p>

In the coming months, <I>The DO</I> will feature articles on osteopathic physicians who have been in the national spotlight, including the new surgeon general of the US Army and DOs who provided medical services at the Summer Olympic Games.<p>

