<HEAD><TITLE>The DO - December, 1996</TITLE>
<META name="description" content="American Osteopathic Association.">
<META name="keywords" content="Osteopathic, Osteopathic Medicine, Doctor of Osteopathy, DO, Healthcare">
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../../bkgd.gif"
         BGCOLOR="#7093DB"
            text="#000000"
            link="#ff0000"
           vlink="#00009c"
           alink="#ffffff">

<!-- Insert HTML  -->

<center>
<h1>The D.O.<br>
December, 1996</h1>
<img src="docover.jpg" alt="Kerri Strug">
<br>
<B>COVER</b>
<P><br>Cover photo by Daniel Garcia, courtesy of Agence France-Presse. Cover artwork designed by Michele T. Bojan.
<p>
During one of the most poignant moments at the XXVIth Summer Olympic Games, Larry G. Nassar, DO (right), meets injured US gymnast Kerri Strug as she is carried off the competition floor by two coaches.
<p>
<hr>
</center>

<img src="tocfoto.gif" align=left alt="Kenneth S. Parker, DO">
Photo courtesy of Kenneth S. Parker, DO
<br>For Kenneth S. Parker, DO (left), one of the highlights of serving as a medical volunteer at the Centennial Olympic Games was meeting healthcare professionals from across the country.<P>
Dr Parker's story and the stories of the other DOs who worked at the Olympics and the Paralympic Games, begin on Page 26.<P>


<br>

<h2>Table of Contents</h2>
<br>
<B>NEWS</b>
<p>
<B>Newsbriefs.</b>
Osteopathic medical organizations across the United States celebrated National Osteopathic Medicine Week in early November.
<p>
<B>AOA leaders laud healthcare reform measures.</B>
The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act and the Mothers and Newborns Health Protection Act will improve the health and well-being of the nation.
<p>
<B>DOs staff field hospital at Democratic convention.</b>
Paula J. Willoughby, DO, was in charge of the field hospital that was set up to provide emergency disaster care at the Democratic National Convention in Chicago. Among those who assisted her were David H. Warner, DO, Louis G. Poulos, DO, and Andrew Michael Basile, DO.
<p>
<B>Air Force DO leads care of Saudi Arabia bomb victims.</b>
Within 15 minutes of the June 25 terrorist bombing at the air base in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, Lt Col Douglas John Robb, DO, MPH, MC, USAF, began coordinating the triage and care of more than 400 bomb victims. He was joined 18 hours later by Maj Stephen E. Garner, DO, MC, USAF, a member of a flying ambulance surgical trauma team that flew in from Turkey.
<p>

<img src="../cover.gif">
<P>
<B>Caring for dreams.</B>While Alan R. Stockard, DO, escorted Olympic judoists as they underwent drug testing, Eric Deal, DO, directed emergency services at the Olympic Village. And as Stanley John Sczecienski, DO, provided osteopathic manipulative treatment to Olympic boxers, Kenneth S. Parker, DO, looked after the medical needs of reporters from around the world.<br>
No matter what medical services were required, osteopathic physicians were on hand to help athletes and spectators fulfill their dreams at the Centennial Olympic Games in Atlanta.
<P>
<B>Bomb shatters Olympics.</b> 
Andrew S. Khan, DO, and John J. Vogel, DO, were among the first healthcare professionals to respond to the bombing that turned a massive celebration at Centennial Olympic Park into a mass casualty.
<p>
<B>True spirit of competition.</b> 
The DOs who provided medical care at the Xth Paralympic Games were awed by the performances given by the elite athletes who competed in those Games. Compared to Olympic athletes, Paralympians are just as intense, but they are tougher and friendlier, the DOs discovered.<p>
<p>
<B>STATE CONVENTION</b>
<p>
<B>Physical pain can signal depression, Missouri DOs told. </b>
Shoulder pain that makes a patient feel nervous or back pain that makes a patient cry may have a psychological rather than a physical cause, explains John L. Hart, DO.
<p>
<B>Missouri DOs learn about bacterial vaginosis.</b>
Susan L. Hendrix, DO, outlines common mistakes made in diagnosing and treating patients with bacterial vaginosis.
<p>
<B>Colorado DO offers pearls on wound closure.</b>
To prepare primary care physicians to close and manage most wounds, Peter M. Schmid, DO, describes the dynamics of wound healing and the basics of wound preparation and suturing.
<p>
<B>Cutting allergen exposure explored at Colorado meeting.</b>
According to Louis B. Kasunic, DO, the sources of allergens can be as inconspicuous as house plants, old newspapers, humidifiers, refrigerator drip pans, and nonstick cooking sprays.
<P>
<B>First AROC attracts 600 DOs from around nation.</b>
US Rep Robert G. Torricelli, D-NJ, was one of the featured speakers at the inaugural Atlantic Regional Osteopathic Convention.
<P>
<B>DEPARTMENTS</b><P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Editor's bookshelf. </b>

<LI><B>In memoriam</b>

<LI><B>Coming events.</b> This column describes continuing medical education programs scheduled throughout 1997.

<LI><B>DO marketplace</b>

<LI><B>Classified ads</b>

<LI><B>Advertisers' index</b>
</UL>

<B>Coming up in <I>The DO</I></B>
<P>
The January 1997 issue of <I>The DO </I>will outline the AOA's plans for celebrating its 100th anniversary. The issue also will include coverage of the AOA's seventh annual leadership conference on osteopathic medical education.

