<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">National Osteopathic Foundation</FONT></H1>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#8000FF">CME Medical Seminar<BR>
August 3-11, 1997</FONT></H3>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Vancouver, BC, and Alaska's Inside
Passage<BR>
<IMG SRC="glacier.gif" HEIGHT=239 WIDTH=326><BR>
</FONT><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">CME Program Coordinator: <BR>
</FONT><FONT COLOR="#8000FF">William G. Anderson, D.O. <BR>
Past President, American Osteopathic Association</FONT></H3>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><BR>
<FONT COLOR="#000000">21<SUP>st</SUP> Century Osteopathic Medicine:<BR>
What Will It Look Like in the Next Century?</FONT></H3>

<H3><BR>
<FONT COLOR="#400040">Preliminary Program</FONT>
<!--                                               -->
<!--                                               -->
<BR>
</H3>

<UL>
<LI><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>Living With Managed Care<BR>
</FONT></FONT>By the year 2001, Managed Care will be everywhere. This
section will examine the continuing changes which will occur in the application
of Managed Care between 1997 and 2001 and how physicians can manage its
effect on their practices.<BR>
<BR>
</LI>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>Tele-Medicine<BR>
</FONT></FONT>The Information Superhighway has already become part
of the osteopathic physician's life. There will continue to be rapid and
comprehensive changes in the next few years which could change the way
D.O.s practice medicine. Physicians On-Line and the Internet are just the
beginning. How will tele-medicine effect D.O.s in the future?<BR>
<BR>
</LI>

<LI><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>Integrated Health Systems<BR>
</FONT></FONT>Physician offices, ambulatory ancillary services, in-patient
and out-patient as well as home health care all integrated into a single
delivery system is the trend for many hospitals. Hospitals have perceived
the necessity of expanding their scope of service beyond in-patient care.
more and more hospitals are acquiring ambulatory clinics, employing physicians,
forming physician-hospital organizations (PHOs), and starting home health
care services to position themselves better to compete and negotiate effective
ly with the Managed Care Organizations (MCOs). Some hospitals also have
incorporated an MCO into their system.<BR>
<BR>
</LI>

<LI><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>Medical Education Continuum<BR>
</FONT></FONT>Increasingly, the undergraduate and graduate curricula
at medical schools and hospitals are being integrated. What will the path
of medical education look like in the 21st Century?<BR>
<BR>
</LI>

<LI><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>Emerging Health Policy<BR>
</FONT></FONT>The federal government's presence is being felt ever
more strongly by physicians and patients alike. Learn more about government
intervention and its effects on your practice. Also, find out what the
osteopathic medical community is doing to steer future legislation too
address the needs of osteopathic physicians and their patients.</LI>
</UL>
