<html>
<head>
<title>CHAPTER 1: AN INTRODUCTION TO MARKETING</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">

<h1><center>CHAPTER 1</h1>
<h1> AN INTRODUCTION TO MARKETING</center></h1>

<a href="#abstract">Chapter Abstract </a><br>
<a href="#teaching tips">Some Teaching Tips </a><br>
<a href="#outline">Chapter Outline </a><br> 
<a href="#answer">Suggested Answers To Chapter Questions </a><br>
<a href="#internet">Using The Internet  </a><br>
<a href="#marketing">Marketing Applications</a><br>
<a href="#consumer">Consumer Insights And International Marketing</a><br>

<h2><a name="abstract">CHAPTER ABSTRACT</a></h2>

<p>Chapter 1, like all the text chapters, is organized around a

series of numbered learning objectives.  These objectives also

provide the framework for the chapter summary statements and

correspond to similarly numbered sections in the Student Study

Guide, the Test Bank, and chapter abstracts in this Manual.</p>



<ol>

<li><b>Define marketing and explain its origins and contemporary

meanings.</b>  Chapter one introduces marketing and explains how it

is performed by individuals and many different types of organizations, businesses, and governments.  Marketing activities are

designed to satisfy consumers and meet organizational needs.  In

a business, this specifically means generating revenue and contributing to profitability.  Marketing had its origins in simple

barter.  Today, it is a highly sophisticated series of activities

designed to fill gaps in the marketplace and add value to

exchanges with consumers.  



<li><b>Identify the key foundation concepts of marketing. </b> The foundation concepts of marketing are exchange, products, sellers,

buyers, and satisfaction.  These are the central concepts that

help define marketing, direct research efforts, and guide applications.



<li><b>Explain why it is important to study marketing.</b>  It is important to study marketing because it is pervasive in our daily

lives and has powerful effects on individual consumers,

businesses, and society.  Many students find employment in a

variety of marketing careers.  Marketing is very important to

business profitability and it plays a role of growing

significance in establishing competitiveness domestically and

internationally.



<li><b>Discuss how and why marketing is evolving.</b>  Marketing has

evolved dramatically since the earliest days of simple barter. 

It continues to evolve as society changes.  Initially, marketing

was an individual activity.  Because of the Industrial

Revolution, it became oriented toward organizational activities. 

Dominant business operating philosophies have evolved from

production, product, and selling orientations, to the marketing

concept philosophy.  Some marketers now practice societal

marketing, where the good of society is a primary consideration

in how the business operates.



<li><b>Describe how marketers use the marketing mix variables to

satisfy consumers and achieve organizational goals.</b>  The chapter

concludes with an introduction to the 4 Ps, the marketing mix

variables of product, price, place, and promotion.  These are the

tools marketers use to add value to exchanges with consumers and

achieve their strategic goals.

</ol>



<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>



<p>These suggestions provide ideas for you to adapt to your

individual teaching situation.  They are  recommendations based

on methods that have worked for me or others.  Please change them

to suit your own needs, particularly your class length.  Class

lengths are variable.  Some are 45 minutes long, while others may

be 50, 60, 75, 90 minutes, or for an evening class, 150 minutes

or longer.  Class length will significantly affect how the class

is organized.</p>  



<p>Experience suggests that students are more interested when

the instructor varies teaching methods and uses interactive

activities as frequently as possible.  This includes asking

questions and getting students involved in the answers.  Many

different types of activities and methods are suggested in the

text and this Manual.  The challenge for the individual

instructor is to select the activities and methods that are most

effective for his or her particular class, then improve on them.</p>



<p>For the first teaching day of the term, establish a set of

expectations for the rest of the term.  For example, I emphasize

the importance of using the chapter objectives as a guide for

reading, studying, and learning.  I show a transparency of

questions based on the chapter objective statements for Chapter 1

(see PART III of this Manual).  Students should be able to answer

each of these questions by the time they have completed reading

Chapter 1.  To provide an added incentive, I explain that the

chapter statements often are used as quiz or examination

questions.</p> 



<p>Students are firmly reminded that assigned chapters must be

read by the assigned date, before the chapter is discussed in

class.  The goal is to get students to read the text and be

prepared to use the information in class so that you can use

class time more productively.  If you spend all of your class

time repeating the text, you are penalizing the students who have

read it and rewarding the students who have not done so.</P>



<p>To reinforce the importance of reading the text assignment

on time, assign one or more of the chapter learning objectives in

question form as homework, due on the day the chapter is

assigned.  Alternately, assign questions that require searching

for an answer within the chapter, information that is in a table

or box.  Assign questions from the end of chapter Discussion

Questions, Check Your Understanding, What Do You Think?, or a

chapter Mini-Case.  This method can be used even in large classes

without creating a heavy grading burden.  If use an assignment

for each chapter, set a total value for the 15 assignments, for

example five points each and 75 points in total.  Use a simple

grading scale, such as five is "outstanding"; three is "average";

one is "below average."  The homework can be evaluated quickly to

detect whether the work is outstanding, average, or below

average.</p>  



<p>You might alternate the homework assignments with announced

quizzes.  For example, if Chapter 2 is due next Wednesday,

announce that there will be a short quiz using questions from the

Chapter 2 Discussion Questions Wednesday.  If you use quizzes as

a substitute for a written homework assignment, be sure that the

points awarded also substitute.</p>              



<P>There are a variety of approaches for introducing the first

chapter.  For example, ask students to write their definition of

marketing on notebook paper or three by five inch cards that you

provide.  Canvass the class to detect dominant themes in their

definitions.  How many say that marketing is just advertising or

selling?  This presents a good point to introduce the American

Marketing Association's definition of marketing on page 7 of the

text and begin discussing the diversity of marketing activities.</P>



<p>Alternately, have students share with the class some of

their marketing knowledge and observations.  Administer a

"marketing knowledge test," for fun and not a grade!  This is an

expansion of the questions asked on page 7 of the text.  Have

students write answers for the following questions.  This goes

much faster if the questions (or ones that you substitute) are

presented both verbally and on a transparency (overhead

projector).  Student responses will lead to discussions about the

marketing mix (4Ps).  You can also discuss the extent of the

marketing knowledge consumers accumulate over a lifetime and how

they learn it all.</p>  



 Some suggested "marketing knowledge" questions are:



<ol><li>Which product will do a greater number of different kinds of   

   jobs for the user, a computer or an electric typewriter?



<li>Is $5.00 a reasonable price to pay for a gallon of regular     

   unleaded gasoline in the United States?   



<li>In what place would a consumer be more likely to find:<br>

   (a) Hard-to-find, odd size tires, at a Wal-Mart or a tire      

       store?  Use the name of a local tire store to make this    

       more relevant.<br>

   (b) One-of-a-kind, made-to-order expensive jewelry, at a       

       Service Merchandise or a fine jewelry store?  Use the name 

       of a local fine jewelry store.     



<li>What brands do these promotional slogans promote?<br>

   (a) "At _____, Quality Is Job 1."  (Ford)<br>

   (b) "Pizza. Pizza."   (Little Caesar's)<br>

   (c) "Have A ____ And A Smile"  (Coke)<br>

(d) Always _____"  (Coca-Cola)<br>

   (e) "Where's The Beef?"  (Wendy's)<br>

   (f) "The King of Beers"  (Budweiser)<br>

</ol>

     



<p>After defining marketing (chapter objective 1), identifying

the foundation concepts (chapter objective 2), and explaining the

importance of studying marketing (chapter objective 3), pose the

question from the end of the chapter introduction (page 5 of the

text), What would your life be like if there were no marketing? 

This can be asked generally of the entire class.  Rather than

tackling the whole question of life without marketing at once,

begin with the question, What would your life be like if there

were no promotion?  This means no advertising, no salespeople, no

product samples or coupons?  How would you find out about new

products?  How would you learn about sales or price reductions? 

How would retail stores let customers know their hours of

operation or what forms of payment they accept for product

purchases?  Who would help you with a purchase decision?</p>



<p>Other teaching suggestions are provided in Teaching Tips For

Marketing Applications.  If you intend to use the consumer letter

Marketing Application 1.5 (page 29 of text), this is a good place

to introduce it.  Students need several days to make their

selection, find an address, and write the letter.</p> 



<p>A proven way to stimulate class discussions is to start

class by citing an article about marketing that has appeared

recently in a business or general interest periodical.  Excellent

sources for current marketing event articles are The Wall Street

Journal, Business Week, INC., Forbes, The Economist, Sales &

Marketing Management, and Marketing News.  Look for articles that

are about the day's topic.  You can prepare in advance by

labeling a manila folder for each chapter's topic.  File each

article in the appropriate folder and select the best article for

the classes when it is needed.</p>



<p>Another approach is to make a current events class

assignment.  I assign current events readings with due dates

staggered over the entire term to spread the grading load.  For

example, in a class of 45 students, each student has three

reading assignments, therefore 135 article reviews must be graded

during the term.  By alternating due dates in a 15-week term,

only nine papers must be graded each week.  Be sure to place a

limit on the length of the article review, set a format that

everyone must follow, and require that a copy of the article be

submitted with the review.  You will need to read the article (if

you haven't already seen it) before evaluating the student's

paper.  This assignment provides you with a steady stream of

articles that you might otherwise have missed.  If time permits,

have a student briefly present their article to the class and

explain its relevance to the day's topic.  Depending on class

size and length, ideally every student should have an opportunity

to make a presentation during the term.</p>



<p>A variation of this assignment requires students to seek

current marketing articles from selected periodicals.  In advance

of the assignment, key chapter topics to appropriate periodical

choices.  For example, articles to accompany Chapter 12

Understanding Promotion must be from Advertising Age, Sales &

Marketing Management, or another periodical whose main focus

parallels the chapter topic.  Students assigned an article for

Chapter 3 Segmenting the Marketing: Consumer Buying Decisions

must use American Demographics, Consumer Reports, or another

consumer-oriented periodical.  This way you can ensure that

students will read more broadly and be exposed to a variety of

important periodicals.  Be certain that students have easy access

to a periodical in the school library before you assign it.</p>



<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>


I.   Define marketing, explain its origins and contemporary

meanings<br>

<br>
<ol>
<li>
 Marketing is more than just selling; it requires

satisfying consumer needs and wants along with achieving

organizational goals<br>

<li>Marketing is defined by the American Marketing

Association as the process of planning and executing the

conception, pricing, promotion and distribution of ideas, goods

and services to create exchanges that satisfy individual and

organizational objectives<br>

<li>Most people have been involved with marketing from an

early age and know more about marketing than they think<br>

<li>Marketing's origins can be traced to early barter

activities<br>

<li>Contemporary marketing is practiced by many groups and

individuals who are trying to identify gaps in the marketplace

and fill these gaps with products that satisfy consumers, thereby

creating value<br>

<li>Marketers perform various marketing functions designed 

to fill gaps and satisfy consumers; they bring offers to markets

and persuade consumers to make exchanges<br></ol>

<br>

II.  Identify the key foundation concepts of marketing



<ol>
<li>Marketing is constructed on foundation concepts

<li>Exchange -- a voluntary trading of things of value

between parties with the expectation that all parties will

benefit 

<li>Products -- the things of value that are the offers

marketers make to consumers

<li>Sellers -- the exchange partners that make the offer to

consumer buyers

<li>Buyers -- individuals, households, businesses,

professionals and others who are party to marketing exchanges and

seek to satisfy their needs and wants from the exchange

<li>Need Satisfaction -- in a marketing exchange means that

a gap has been filled for the buyer, a tension is reduced when a

need or want is satisfied

<li>Consumer Satisfaction -- is very important to marketers

and consumers, but it is not always clear what it takes to

satisfy consumers and satisfaction is often a function of

situations and circumstances</ol>



III. Explain why it is important to study marketing


<ol>
     <li>Marketing is important in our daily lives

    <li>Consumers have responsibilities to be efficient

     <li>Marketing offers many attractive career opportunities

    <li>Marketing is an important business process

     <li>Marketing contributes to businesses' global

competitiveness</ol>



IV.  Discuss why and how marketing is still evolving


<ol>
    <li>Marketing as a process and as an academic discipline

continues to evolve as society, technologies and markets change

    <li> The Individual Era was a time of self-sufficiency,

where marketing was primarily local and associated with simple,

mostly individual transactions; barter was common

<br>        
<ul>
<li>
During the American Colonial Period, centralized

markets developed along with small businesses, middlemen and some

small factories

          <li>Barter continues to this day, even in

technologically advanced countries</ul>

<li>Marketing evolved with the country's industrialization

into an organizational activity during the Organizational Era 

 <ul>
 <li>The Production Concept stressed production

efficiencies and products

<li>The Selling Concept stressed selling

<li>The Marketing Concept, which evolved after World

War II,  recognizes the importance of consumer satisfaction to

marketing success

<li>The Societal Marketing Concept moves a step

further and also recognizes an obligation to work for societal

good</ol></ul>



V.   Describe how marketers use the marketing mix variables to

satisfy consumers and achieve organizational goals



<ol>
<li> The 4 Ps are the marketing mix variables of product,

price, place and promotion
<ul>
<li>Product is the offer made in the marketplace

<li>Price is the amount charged for the product

<li>Place is where, when and how the product is made

available to the market

<li>Promotion is how marketers communicate with

consumers and includes advertising, personal selling, sales

promotions and public relations</ul>

<li>These are the tactical tools marketers use to achieve

their goals</ol>





<h2><a name="answer">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>



<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>


<ol>
<li>
What is being exchanged between each of the following pairs   

of sellers and buyers?  


<ul>
    <li>Colleges - Students   Education, career preparation        

       exchanged for tuition.

   <li> American Cancer Society - Contributors   Information, hope 

       of a cure exchanged for money used to support              

       organization's programs and operations.

    <li>Presidential Candidate - Voters   Promises exchanged for   

       votes.

    <li>Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD) - General Driving     

       Public   Promise to lobby to get drunk drivers off the     

       roads, safer driving conditions exchanged for              

       contributions of time, money.

   <li>Local Government Garbage Disposal Service - Citizens       

       Collection of garbage, sanitary disposal exchanged for tax 

       dollars.</ul>



<li>"Marketing is responsible for our materialistic society." 

Comment on this statement.  While some consumers may indulge in

materialism, marketing provides valuable information and by

stimulating competition, helps keep prices down and product

choices up.



<li>Do each of the following perform marketing activities?  If    

so, what is the goal of their marketing effort?  


<ul>
   <li>Arthur Andersen (accounting firm) Yes, marketing goal is   

       to provide accounting services for customers and make a    

       profit.

   <li>American Express (bank card) Yes, marketing goal to        

       provide financial service convenience for customers and    

       make a profit.

    <li>Good Samaritan Hospital (not-for-profit public hospital)   

       Yes, marketing goal to deliver top quality medical         

       services while keeping costs down and generating operating 

       revenues.

    <li>U.S. Army Yes, marketing goal is to attract good quality   

       recruits, offering them training and money for their       

       education, build public support for the Army.

    <li>Toyota U.S.A. Motor Manufacturing Company Yes, marketing   

       goal to product top quality automobiles that satisfy       

       consumers and make a profit.

</ul>

<li>Is the societal marketing concept a realistic concept for a

business  to adopt?  Why or why not?  Many businesses have shown

that they can be good corporate citizens and generate a profit. 

Value comes from the public goodwill generated; can help build

employee morale.  On the other hand, some economists argue that a

business' sole goal should be to generate wealth for its

stockholders.



<li>Explain why consumer insights are important to marketing.

Marketers whose businesses operate by the marketing concept

philosophy strive to satisfy consumers.  Consumer insights

provide information that marketers can use to decide what it will

take to satisfy consumers.



<li>What types of utility are created by each of the following?

a. Blockbuster Video; b. Mr. Suds' automated, drive-through car

wash; c. BancTwo Automatic Teller Machine.  All create time and

place utility; Automatic Teller Machine also creates possession

utility.



<li>Explain which is more difficult to market, an idea or a

place. Generally, an idea is more difficult to market because its

intangible and subject to misinterpretation. 



<li>Describe the foundation concepts of marketing.  These concepts

are exchange, products, sellers, buyers, and satisfaction. 

Exchange is the core process of marketing.  Products are the

things of value exchanged.  Sellers and buyers make up a market. 

Satisfaction means filling a gap between what consumers need or

want, and what they have available to them.



<li>If you were a marketing teacher, how would you explain to

your class the importance of studying marketing?  I would make

the explanation very personal, stressing that marketing affects

their lives on a daily basis and that it could provide them with

a very satisfying career.  It is vital to businesses because it

provides revenues and contributes to profitability, which can

also affect them on a personal level because the success of

marketing affects jobs.  Because of the growing competition in

the United States domestic market and abroad, marketing is

becoming even more important to a business' competitiveness.  



<li>Describe how marketing has evolved in the United States.  Do

you think it will continue to evolve?  Marketing has evolved

through two eras, first the individual era, then the

organizational era after the Industrial Revolution.  In the

latter period, several operating philosophies have dominated the

way marketing is performed.  These are the production concept,

the selling concept, and the marketing concept.  Some marketers

believe that the next step will be the adoption of the societal

marketing concept.  Marketing will continue to evolve because it

is affected by changes in its environment, particularly in

society, technology, and the economy.

</ol>

</ol>



<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>



<h4>Check Your Understanding 1.1 </h4>



<p>1. In your own words, what is marketing? <i>Marketing is a process

that involves planning and executing the creation of products,

their pricing, promotion and distribution to satisfy individual

and organizational goals.</i>



<p>2. Explain how sending a resume to a prospective employer is

marketing.  Who is the buyer?  Who is the seller?  <i>The exchange

can be viewed as the buyer (employer) giving up money, training,

benefits and the seller (employee) giving up time, ability,

effort and expertise.</i>



<p>3. Does marketing occur when seven families on your street get   

    together to have a garage sale?  Explain.  <i>Yes, regardless of

the number of people involved, exchange occurs at a garage sale

when goods are traded for money.</i>                     



<h4>Check Your Understanding 1.2 </h4>

<p>1. What are the foundation concepts of marketing? <i>Exchange,

products, sellers, buyers, need satisfaction, consumer

satisfaction.</i>



<p>2. Explain the concept of exchange.  <i>Exchange takes place when

two or more parties voluntarily trade things they value to their

mutual benefit.  Conditions for exchange to occur include: Two

parties are voluntarily involved; each has something of value to

exchange; parties can communicate; both are willing to trade;

both have the authority to exchange.</i>



<p>3. Why is satisfaction such an important concept in marketing? 

<i>Because it is at the core of the marketing concept.  Marketers

operating by the marketing concept consumer satisfaction an

important business goals because satisfied consumers purchase

their products.</i>





<h4>Check Your Understanding 1.3 

</h4>

<p>1. Of the reasons given for studying marketing, identify the

ones that are most important to you.  <i>Responses will vary

according to student interests.</i>



<p>2. How can marketing contribute to a standard of living? <i>By

stimulating competition that lowers prices and provides more

choices.</i>

            

<p>3. How is your daily life affected by marketing? <i>Responses will

vary. </i>



<h4>Check Your Understanding 1.4</h4>



<p>1. Explain the focus and scope of the Individual and

Organizational Eras of marketing.  <i>During the Individual Era, the

focus was on individual exchanges and exchanges involving

consumers and smaller sized businesses.  The Industrial

Revolution meant that businesses could mass produce products. 

With the development of the mass market and organizations, the

focus shifted to marketing by organizations and the scope

broadened to include large businesses as well as small and mid-size businesses.</i>



<p>2. What is the marketing concept?  Give an example of a company  

that you believe is operating on this philosophy; explain your    

answer. <i>The marketing concept is an operating philosophy that can

be adopted both by businesses and other organizations; it gives

primacy to consumer satisfaction, but also strives to meet

organizational objectives as well.  Examples can vary, popular

choices include General Electric, Dell Computer, McDonald's, Wal-Mart.</i>



<p>3. Should businesses adopt the societal marketing concept?  <i>This

question commonly generates different views.  One says that

businesses should not meddle in areas where they're not expert,

instead they should concentrate on making profits.  The other

view says that all businesses must be held responsible for their

actions, they have an obligation to behave in a responsible way.</i>



<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>

                                

<h4>Mini-Case 1.1: 'Pig's Eye' Beats Out 'Landmark' As Customers'     

               Favorite

</h4>

    <p>This case illustrates how a business that ignores consumer

insights can get in deep trouble.  This trouble affects their

profitability and the bottom line.  MBC's mistakes include the

product's name, formulation, price, and promotions.  They

squandered consumer goodwill and name recognition, then not

surprisingly experienced disappointing sales.</p>



<p>1.  Is MBC using the marketing concept philosophy?  Explain your

answer.  <i>If MBC had used the marketing concept philosophy

effectively, they wouldn't have ignored consumer preferences and

made the mistakes identified in the case.</i>  



<p>2.  Evaluate the mistakes made by MBC for each of the marketing

mix  variables (product, price, place, promotion). <i>Product was

reformulated and an unpopular name selected; the price was higher

than consumers had been paying or were willing to pay; promotions

were misleading; no information was provided about any place

(distribution) mistakes. </i>



<p>3.  How can MBC fix its mistakes?  What changes should it make? 

<i>A number of suggestions can be made.  Student suggestions can be

used for a class debate on strategies to correct MBC's marketing

mistakes.  Ask students to form teams and each is to present

his/her suggestions to the team.  Through discussion and

negotiation, each team is to arrive at a team consensus on what

strategies they recommend.  Each team can present their

strategies to the class.</i>





<h4>Mini-Case 1.2: Twentysomethings: The Consumers That Marketers     

               Almost Forgot  </h4>

 

     <p>The popular press has spent considerable time recently

dissecting the twentysomethings.  Since many of your students may

be from this age group, this case should interest them and

stimulate class discussion.   You might ask their opinions about

popular stereotypes of this age cohort and their responses to the

following statements:

<ul>

<li>This generation is relatively neglected by marketers.

<li>They are angry, cynical, dissatisfied and hopeless.

<li>They are bright, brash, intelligent, funny and like baby     

boomers but younger.

<li>They hate being marketed to and are anti-marketing.</ul>





<p>1.  Mazda ran a very conservative advertising campaign directed at baby

boomers and used cues like a woman wearing pearls and classical music in the background.  How might Mazda change their advertising for generation X

targets?  <i>Student responses will vary but the key point is that their

suggestions will reflect their own perceptions.  Point out the risks of any

business basing marketing decisions on information obtained from small

samples.  If Mazda could get a representative sample of consumers across the

country to answer this question, they could develop consumer insights to guide their advertising strategy.</i>



<p>2.  How can marketers find out what the generation X market is really all

about?  What would it take to develop consumer insight about the

twentysomethings?  <i>This question also gets to the issue of basing marketing

decisions on representative samples, small but appropriate groups of consumers whose comments and opinions can be generalized to the larger population from which they were drawn.</i>   





<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?

</h3>

     <p>This section can be assigned for a class debate over the pros and cons of

marketing tobacco and other products that have health hazards.  Student teams

should focus their remarks on the questions, <b>Is there a conflict between the

marketing concept's focus on delivering consumer satisfaction and the

marketing of products that are potentially harmful to consumers?  Whose

marketing standards should be followed, those of the seller's country or the

buyer's?</b> </p>



<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a>

</h2>



     <p>Marketing On The Internet (page 23 in text) introduces the topic and sets

the stage for subsequent discussions about how the Internet is affecting

marketing.  Many schools can Net-connect using Lynx, a text-only browser. 

Therefore, the following suggestions for getting students on the Net are based

on a Lynx system.  The first Internet activity also is Lynx-based.  If you

school connects through a paid commercial service (such as America On Line,

Prodigy, CompuServe) or through a graphical browser (Mosaic, Netscape), please

adapt these suggestions to that system.</p>



    <p> Some marketing students already know how to connect to the Internet.  In

the future, this number will grow as more primary and secondary schools Net-connect.  Students with this knowledge may help their classmates in getting on

the Internet; however, their role should support the marketing instructor's

effort, not substitute for it.</p>



<h3>Suggestions For Net-Connecting Your Students

</h3>

    <p>When teaching students to Net-connect, provide each student with clear,

concise, step-by-step written instructions to avoid misunderstandings and to

give them a record of the process in case they forget.  This includes e-mail

instructions and specifics on how to connect from various points on campus

(including dormitories) and through off-campus gateways.  If feasible, take

the class to the college or university computer center and demonstrate how to

Internet connect.  Coach students as they work through the process. 

Alternately, bring a portable computer with an overhead projector to class to

show connect procedures.  The goal is to teach students how to connect, then

let them explore through directed class applications.



    <p> For schools that Net-connect using Lynx, show students how to form

Internet addresses.  For example, once in Lynx, type G (the G)o command) to

open the URL (uniform resource locator) where the Internet address is typed. 

The letters http (hypertext transport protocol) identify an Internet address

with hyperlinks.  The last two or three letters of an address (the domain)

identifies its organizational or country origin.  For example:</p>

<center>com = commercial; <br>

gov = government;<br>

 edu = educational; <br>

net = a network; <br>

UK = United Kingdom;<br>

 CA = Canada.  </center>



<h3>A Personal Experience On The Net</h3>

     

     <p>I launched two undergraduate classes into cyberspace at the beginning of

the Spring 1995 Semester, immediately after Lynx became available at my

school.  Using class time, I introduced the Internet and explained how we

would be using it in class.  Students were cautioned about the Internet's

unregulated nature and told that they were to use the Internet principally for

work, not play.  Each student received a hard copy written description of Net-cautions and advice about Net-iquette.  



    <p> A demonstration was held in the College computer laboratory, showing

students how to use the system, set up an e-mail account, enter and use the

Internet.  In order for students to see what a graphical browser could do, I

also showed them an Internet connection using Mosaic.  If you can demonstrate

a graphical browser, start by taking your class to the <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov">White House home page</a>

(a unique main menu of text, visual images, and sometimes sound prepared by

the addressee) at the White House address <b>http://www.whitehouse.gov. </b> When you

get there you will see a large color photograph of the White House building,

flanked by images and text.  Click on the image of the Presidential Seal and a

request is sent for the document that contains the President's welcome

message.  Seconds later, you'll hear the President deliver a short welcome

statement.  Return to the White House home page and listen to the Vice

President's message, go on a virtual tour of the White House, visit the First

Family, or leave a message.  



    <p> Once all students were on the Net, I assigned them three short directed

information searches.  For example, one project required a visit to the United

States Bureau of the Census, Statistical Abstract of the United States.  A

copy of the assignment, including a detailed roadmap to the site and questions

to be answered, was e-mailed to each student and students e-mailed their

answers back.  Feedback was sent to each student via e-mail reply.  The

assignment required an examination of population trends in several states, a

demographic comparison, and the identification of possible product market

matches.



     <p>Class discussions and current readings complemented student Internet

explorations.  Running Internet activities out-of-class while also

interweaving the topics in-class significantly raised student interest levels

and led to greater student participation.  Despite some problems (for example,

students deleting their e-mail addresses, forgetting to purge old mail, maxing

out their storage space), both classes were highly enthusiastic about their

Internet projects.  Several sent me e-mail messages saying that this was the

best thing they had ever done in college.    



<h3>Timing Of Internet Activities

</h3>

    <p> At what point in the term (semester or quarter) should the Internet be

introduced?  Log on as early as possible to allow time for students to

familiarize themselves with Internet search processes and capacities.  The

timing of Internet projects during a term will vary with the educational

environment, time and equipment constraints, and the number of Internet

activities assigned.  Ideally, Internet projects should be spread out over the

term, culminating with an integrative Internet project that requires using the

Internet to solve a timely marketing problem.



<h3>Internet Assignments

</h3>

     <p>Remember, things change very rapidly on the Internet.  Before making an

Internet assignment, you must check out the site to make sure that what you

are asking students to do can be done!  The information presented below on

Internet sites was current as of the publication of this <b>Manual. </b>



     <p>Initial Internet assignment should be short and easy to complete.  A

simple information retrieval assignment provides the opportunity for students

to master the process of getting on the Internet, retrieve information, and e-mail results.  For example:



<b><p>Visit the Web Page of the <a href="http://nsns.com/Mix">American Marketing Association (AMA)</a>, called the

Marketing Mix, located at address http://nsns.com/Mix.  This home page offers

the AMA's mission statement, service contacts, links to AMA special interest

groups, and a conference calendar.  Your assignment is to e-mail me the

following information, in your own words: 

<ol><li>What is the American Marketing Association?  

<li>What is its mission?  

<li>What is the nearest local professional chapter?  

<li>Select one of the AMA's journals (Under Journals and Publications)

and briefly explain the nature of its contents.</ol></b>



<p>Alternately, have students retrieve population information from the

Census Bureau.  Before making this assignment, you should visit the site,

enter the National Projections Directory and identify specific information

that you want your students to analyze.



<b><p>Visit the<a href="http://www.census.gov"> United State's Bureau of the Census</a> at  http://www.census.gov 



Follow the path:  topics in text <br>      

Population and Housing <br>                

Population Division Home Page<br>                           

<ol><li>Enter POPClock and briefly describe its contents.  

<li>Enter Population Projections.

<li>Enter National Projections and describe trends in the United States

population.  

<li>Enter State Projections and describe population trends for

our state. </ol></b>                                                



<p>These suggestions are designed to get you thinking about how to use the

Internet in your marketing class.  Please use them as a starting point and

change them to reflect your needs.  I believe that you will find this activity

well worth the time and effort.  Just remember, check out a site <strong>BEFORE</strong> you

assign it!



<h2><a name="marketing">MARKETING APPLICATIONS</a></h2>





<h3>MARKETING APPLICATION 1.1</h3>



     <p>Most Marketing Applications are designed to be small scale hands-on

learning activities that call for individual, team, and small group activities

that lead to class discussion.  The first Marketing Application also

introduces a key concept, consumer insight.  Contemporary marketing decisions

rely on information about consumers, their behaviors, likes and dislikes,

wants and needs.  In this activity, each student's responses will be personal

yet when they are compared, there are bound to be commonalities.  This can be

pointed out when the lists are compared in class and students are challenged

to answer the question What conclusions can you draw from this activity about

obstacles to developing consumer insights? 





<h3>MARKETING APPLICATION 1.2</h3>



     <p>Marketers often talk in professional shorthand, a trait common to most

professions.  Gap or opportunity analysis is frequently used when seeking a

marketing opportunity.  Students can be introduced to the concept using their

own experiences by asking them to identify what gaps the three products

(automobile, ATM and fat-free bakery goods) fill.  This can be related to the

utilities provided by each of these products and the needs being satisfied. 

An extension of this application is to have a class discussion of the gaps

identified by the students and the products that could fill the gaps.







<h3>MARKETING APPLICATION 1.3</h3>



    <p>While students are familiar with marketing activities designed to

stimulate consumer demand, few consider situations where demarketing is

required.  This Marketing Application introduces the concept of demarketing

and asks students to consider strategies for demarketing a park to protect it

from excessive crowds but doing so without ruining the market.  This may

require a combination of strategic responses.  Students may suggest raising

the price of admission, setting an entry quota for each day, launching a

public relations campaign to explain to the public why such measures are

critical and appealing to them for their support and understanding.  For each

strategy, students should consider both the benefits and possible costs.





<h3>MARKETING APPLICATION 1.4 </h3>



     <p>This is a role playing exercise that challenges students to start

thinking like marketers.  Drawing from their own experiences as consumers,

students can probably design a simple customer satisfaction survey.  You can

help them by bringing one or two samples to class.  They are often found on

tables or at the cashier in Shoney's, McDonald's and other popular fast food

chains.  This research activity is introduced early in the text to emphasize

the importance of consumer research in making marketing decisions.  Individual

student efforts can be channeled into the construction of a class survey with

your assistance as moderator.  One way to show students how challenging it is

to write good survey questions is to have them try it themselves. 

Alternately, have student teams critique surveys that they have collected from

various retail businesses.  Note the commonalities and the differences in the

questions asked, and compare the target markets these businesses seek to

serve.  







<h3>MARKETING APPLICATION 1.5</h3>



     <p>This activity is one used often with great success.  It is important to

emphasize to students that they must be honest in their communications.  This

is an ethical imperative.  They should include in their letter a current phone

number and address.  Students are often surprised by the results of their

effort.  In the past, students have received personal letters or telephone

calls from company vice presidents, coupons, free samples and in one case (a

complaint about a boot that was not wearing well), a new product.  Some

students never receive a reply.  Be sure to remind them several times

throughout the semester to bring responses to class when they're received.  At

the end of the term, conclude this application by having students recount

their experiences and whether they have changed their opinion of the business

to  which they wrote.



<h2><a name="consumer">CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING </a></h2>





<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHT 1.1</h3>



     <p>Students must be reminded that there are millions of consumers outside

the United States.  You might review Figure 1.1 (page 10 in text) in class,

compare the population statistics and discuss why marketers find it important

to characterize populations within countries and regions.  You can also

initiate a discussion of the opening of the China market and its economic

importance to the United States, Japan and many other countries.







<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHT 1.2</h3>



     <p>This Consumer Insight (page 20 in text) serves a dual purpose.  It

emphasizes the significance of smaller businesses to marketing and the

economy, and it highlights a consumer group that most students don't consider,

businesses and organizations.  You might ask students to draw on their own

experiences for observations about the business environment in your community

and how smaller businesses are doing, are they successful or not?







<h3>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h3>



     <p>PepsiCo. bartering for vodka and ships in the former Soviet Union is an

entertaining way to introduce an important topic, International Marketing

(page 24 in text).  International marketing examples are woven throughout the

text and emphasized because international markets are of growing importance to

the success of businesses of all sizes.

</p>
<hr>
