<h1><center>CHAPTER 4</h1> 
<h1>THE MARKETING ENVIRONMENT</center></h1>  
 
 <a href="#abstract">Chapter Abstract </a><br>
<a href="#teaching tips">Some Teaching Tips </a><br>
<a href="#outline">Chapter Outline </a><br> 
<a href="#answer">Suggested Answers To Chapter Questions </a><br>
<a href="#internet">Using The Internet  </a><br>
<a href="#marketing">Marketing Applications</a><br>
<a href="#consumer">Consumer Insights And International Marketing</a><br>

<h2><a name="abstract">CHAPTER ABSTRACT</a></h2>              

<p><b>1. Define the dual roles of marketing in society: micromarketing
and macromarketing.</b>  Marketing is very important to society as it
helps deliver the standard of living that most Americans enjoy. 
It plays two important roles, at the micro and macro levels. 
Micromarketing is the way marketing connects a business, its
suppliers, distributors, and consumers in activities designed to
deliver consumer satisfaction.  Macromarketing is marketing on a
broader, societal level that describes how marketing contributes
to the economy and societal welfare by balancing supply and
demand.</p>


<p><b>2. Describe the rights, responsibilities, and ethical dilemmas of
marketers.</b>  Marketers are granted broad rights in society, but
they are also expected to act legally and ethically.  Along with
rights come responsibilities.  Some businesses take this societal
obligation very seriously and make it an integral part of their
business and marketing activities.  Most marketers behave
ethically, adhering to the unwritten principles and values that
govern and bring order to society.  Marketers abide by a written
professional code of conduct as well as codes of behavior
established within their business or organization.  Self-regulation, an important behavioral monitor, is also practiced by
such groups as local Better Business Bureaus and trade
associations.</p>

<p><b>3. Identify government controls on marketing.</b>  Government
controls marketing activities through laws, rules, and
regulations.  Formal legal controls cannot possibly encompass
every activity that occurs in a complex marketplace, such as the
United States.  As a result, situations occur for which no clear
behavioral guidelines exit.  This can lead to ethical dilemmas
for marketers and sometimes, ethical lapses.  Laws are formal
statements that guide actions and set limits and penalties for
infractions.  Federal business laws are procompetitive and many
are designed to protect consumers.  The Federal Trade Commission
is the federal regulatory body that most directly controls
marketing,  including competitive and consumer protection
activities.  State and local laws, rules, and regulations control
marketing activities within these jurisdictions.  Regulations are
the rules, standards, and guidelines that government agencies
issue to implement laws.</p>


<p><b>4. Explain consumerism and the Consumer Bill of Rights.</b> 
Consumers sometimes suffer serious consequences from the
imbalance in the marketplace caused by the advantages sellers
have over buyers.  Consumerism, a response to consumer abuses in
the marketplace, is embodied in the cooperation of concerned
individuals and organizations with many diverse interests who 
respond to issues of shared distress.  President John Kennedy was
the first incumbent president to send a formal message to the
Congress identifying rights that consumers should be free to
enjoy.</p>


<p><b>5. Identify some important contemporary societal issues involving
marketing.</b>  There are many contemporary societal issues involving
marketing that capture the public imagination at various times. 
Three issues of lasting concern are green marketing, the
marketing of harmful products, and marketing to children.</p>

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>The Chapter 4 goal is to introduce the concept of micro and
macro roles for marketing in society, state broadly the written
and unwritten guidelines by which marketing actions are bound,
raise the issue of ethical dilemmas that can lead to ethical
lapses, introduce the topic of consumerism, and identify three
societal issues involving marketing that continue to draw public
debate and criticism.  Because most business majors take a
required legal issues course, this chapter makes no attempt to
substitute for the depth of coverage found in a typical business
law course.</p>  

<p> Problems in the marketplace often receive considerable
attention when they occur.  Exemplary acts usually go unnoticed,
although they are appreciated by the consumer.  <b>Marketing
Application 4.1</b> (page 110 of the text) provides an opportunity to
personalize this issue by asking students to recount their own
observations of problems in the marketplace.  By acting as
<u>participant observers</u>, they can identify problem areas then pool
their observations to develop a consensus list of marketing
problems.  You must stress, however, that generalizing from a
small sample is not recommended.  This application can be
extended to a larger sample in order to provide a somewhat more
reliable picture of the nature and scope of marketing problems. 
Each student can ask several friends to identify marketing
problems they have encountered.  Ask open ended research
questions, such as <i>Recently, have you had any problems with 
products, prices, places where products are sold, or promotions? 
What were these problems?</i>   The results from the expanded sample
can be compared to class results to determine generally if they
are similar or not.  Be sure to have students review the list of
complaints about the marketing mix elements on pages 108-109 of
the text before they expand the sample.</p>

<p>     The issue of deviant consumer behavior was introduced in
Chapter 3.  This is a good place to consider deviant behaviors by
consumers <u>and</u> marketers.  What are some of the underlying human
characteristics and shortcomings that may be at the heart of both
types of deviant behaviors?  Contrast consumers and marketers by
their illegal and unethical behaviors.  What are the costs of
these behaviors?  Do consumers experience ethical dilemmas?  Are
they anything like those experienced by marketers?  Are there any
acceptable justifications for these behaviors by consumers or
marketers?   Do students think that these behaviors only occur in
the United States?  If you have international students in your
class, or others who have traveled or lived abroad, perhaps they
can comment on the occurrence of deviant consumer and marketer
behaviors in other countries.</p>

<p>Most people hold conflicting views about the question of the
impact of marketing on society.  Some believe it mirrors society;
others believe it influences society.  A lively student debate
can be held about the role of marketing as a societal mirror or
leader.  If it is mirror, what does this say about society?  Is
the mirror shiny and bright, or dark and cracked?  Does marketing
reflect all segments of society?  Do all segments benefit equally
from marketing activities?</p>

<p>What do students think about the rights of marketers (page
111 of the text)?  Have them consider the rights and discuss how
far the rights extend.  What roles do consumers and the
government play in limiting these rights?  Should existing limits
be changed on any of these rights?  Address this issue from three
perspectives: the consumer's, the government's, and the
marketer's.</p>

<p>Students often are interested in learning about business
support for community and societal causes.  A suggested Internet
activity presents an opportunity to learn how some major
multinational businesses are acting on their societal
responsibilities. <b>Marketing Application 4.2</b> suggests finding out
more about local businesses that support community activities and
causes.  If a local business is particularly visible in
supporting local causes, you might contact that business and ask
for more information about their activities.  Alternately, ask
your working students whether their employers are similarly
involved.  What are the benefits from societal and civic
sponsorships and support activities?  Do your students seek out
businesses that support certain causes in order to buy their
products?  Are there some causes that might backfire and turn
consumers away from the supporting businesses' products?</p>

<p>A debate over values appears to be gaining momentum
throughout the country.  How might a more conservative approach
to values affect societal ethics that govern consumer and
marketer behaviors?  How might this affect marketers and
marketing activities?  Relate the issue of values to the rules
suggested on page 115 of the text.  What do your students think
of the power of the Golden Rule, the Mom Rule, and the TV Rule
for governing consumer <u>and</u> marketer behaviors?</p>

<p>Have your students read the Code of Ethics of the American
Marketing Association (AMA) on page 116 of the text.  What do
they think of the strength of the sanctions that the AMA
threatens to invoke for members who violate the Code?  What else
may happen to marketers who violate the Code?  Relate this Code
to <b>Marketing Application 4.3</b> and contrast codes issues by other
professional organizations.  What are the similarities and
differences?</p>

<p>I strongly recommend that students who can Net-connect visit
the home page of the Federal Trade Commission (FTC).  This is
described in the Internet section of this chapter.  Because of
the great influence of this agency on marketing and consumers,
students should learn more about it, directly from the source. 
The FTC home page is highly informative and well organized.  Any
student in business now or planning to go into business should
learn more about the FTC and other government agencies that
monitor and control business activities.</p>
         
<p> The periods of consumerism in recent U.S. history (page 124
of the text) can be assigned as research topics.  For example,
student teams could read about the first consumerism period which
began at the turn of the century and lasted until American
entered World War I.  Consumer problems during this period
included mail order fraud, tainted meat, spiraling prices, child
labor exploitation, and outrageous claims for health cures by
patent medicine sellers.  A catalyst spurring public outrage was
the 1906 publication of Upton Sinclair's book <u>The Jungle</u>.  Your
students may be shocked by this expose of unsanitary conditions
in the Chicago meat packing industry.  For example, the following
passage and others like it in Sinclair's book inflamed consumers
from coast-to-coast, including then President Theodore Roosevelt,
and prompted federal intervention to clean up business and
protect consumers' health and safety.</p>
<pre>
        These rats were nuisances, and the packers would put
        poisoned bread out for them and they would die, and then
        rats, bread and meat would go into the hoppers together.. 
        Men, who worked in the tank rooms full of steam...fell into
        the vats; and when they were fished out, there was never 
        enough of them to be worth exhibiting - sometimes they
        would be overlooked for days, till all but the bones of them
        had gone out to the world as Durham's Pure Leaf Lard!

        Source: Herrmann, Robert O. (1970), "The Consumer Movement
        in Historical Perspective," in Aaker, David A. and George S. Day 
        (1978), Consumerism: Search for the Consumer Interest, 3rd 
        Edition, New York: The Free Press (Macmillan): 27-36. </pre>
</p>

<p>     Ask students to relate this market problem to contemporary
issues of meat inspection.  Recent incidences of E coli
contaminated ground beef should personalize this issue.  Outcomes
of the first consumerism period included passage of meat
inspection legislation and a Pure Food Bill, as well as other
laws designed to increase competition in the marketplace and
protect consumers.  What outcomes might the recent incidences
have for business and consumers?</p>
     
 <p>    Students can debate the issues raised by green marketing,
marketing harmful products, and marketing to children.  These
topics typically provoke strong opinions, pro and con.  Student
teams can be assigned the pro or con of marketing to children, or
marketing harmful products.  What do your students think of Old
Joe Camel?  Is it a great product mascot or an engaging hook to
interest children in a harmful product?</p>

<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>  
    
I.   Marketing plays roles at the micro and macro levels of
     society </p>                    

       <li> A. Micromarketing is a smaller scale, narrower perspective
          of the role of marketing by a business, organization,
          supplier, or individual marketer engaged in consumer
          exchanges </li></p>
<ol>
<li>
On a micromarketing level, most marketers seek to
            satisfy consumers 
<ul>
<li>
 Many consumers complain that, on a personal
                    level, marketing is not working well for them

<li>However, consumers are not always easy to
                    satisfy, and in some cases, what consumers
                    want is harmful 

<li>Some marketing criticisms concern unsafe
                    products, high prices, restrictions on where
                    products are made available, aggressive and
                    misleading promotions, unwholesome demand
                    stimulation, and privacy issues</ul>

<li>Macromarketing takes the broader, system
               perspective
<ul>
<li>       
Governments set national goals that
                    businesses help the country achieve
<li>Marketing is criticized at the macro level
                    for adding costs, wasting resources,
                    stimulating unnecessary demand, and
                    undermining societal moral values </ul></ol>


<p>II.  Describe the rights, responsibilities, and ethical dilemmas
     of marketers</p>

<p><li> A.   Marketing has societal responsibilities</li></p>
 <p><li>B.   Some businesses take their societal responsibilities
          very seriously and believe that they have an obligation
          to contribute to society</li></p>
<p><li>C.   Although social programs can be costly, they can also
          be beneficial marketing tools</li></p>   
<p><li>D.   Marketers must be knowledgeable of and adhere to the
          laws and regulations that govern marketing activities</p>

<ol>
<li>
Ethical behavior requires adhering to the societal
               rules of conduct that govern interactions
<li>Marketers often face ethical dilemmas where the
               rules of conduct may not be clear</ol>

<p><li>E.  Marketing is also governed by professional codes of
          conduct</p>

<p><li>F.   Self-regulation provides guidance to marketers through
          such mechanisms as the Better Business Bureaus and
          internal behavioral monitoring systems</p>

III. Identify governmental controls on marketing<p>

<li>     A.   Laws are formal statements that guide actions and set
          limits and penalties for infractions<p>
          <ol><li>Generally, what is illegal is also unethical; what
               is unethical is not necessarily also illegal
         <li>Marketers are bound by federal laws with
               nationwide jurisdiction
               <ul><li>Many federal laws are procompetitive and
                    protect consumers
               <li>The Federal Trade Commission more than other
                    federal agencies, oversees marketing
                    activities
              <li>Marketers are bound by many different state
                   and local laws whose jurisdiction is limited
                    to a specific area </ul></ol>
  <li>   B.   Regulations are the rules, standards, and guidelines
          that government agencies issue to implement laws</ol><p>


IV.  Consumerism refers to a constantly changing association of
     people, organizations, agencies and businesses that arise
     because people believe the imbalance in the market between
     sellers and buyers has gone too far; the goal is to correct
     the imbalance and protect consumers<p>

    <li> A.   Since the 1890s, three periods of consumerism have
          peaked in the United States<p>
   <li>B.   In 1962, President John Kennedy sent a Consumer Bill of
          Rights message to the Congress that identified problem
          areas and stated consumer rights in each<p>
<ol>
          <li>Consumers have the right to safe products
          <li>Consumers have the right to be informed about
               products
          <li>Consumers have the right to choose from among a
               variety of products
         <li>Consumers have the right to be heard and have
               complaints resolved<p></ol>


V.   Identify some important contemporary societal issues
     involving marketing<p>

    <li> A.   Many marketers are demonstrating their concern for the
          environment through green marketing, activities that
          are environmentally friendly rather than
          environmentally harmful<p>
    <li> B.   Some marketers of harmful but legal products are trying
          to show greater social responsibility, as shown by 
          beer and liquor industry campaigns against drinking and
          driving<p>
    <li> C.   Marketing to children is easier in the United States
          than in many other countries; however, it remains
                    highly controversial and criticized <p>    

<h2><a name="answer">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>
                     <b> DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</b>
<ol>
<li> Why is the buyer (consumer) often at a disadvantage in an
exchange with a seller?  <i>At its core, the imbalance involves
information, which the seller has and the buyer often can't
easily obtain.  Imbalances occur because of the control that
sellers have over price, place (where and how products are
offered), and promotion.  The latter should provide useful
information but often is exaggerated or even misleading. 
Consumers mostly act as individuals or in small family groups,
which means they cannot exert the market power that could be
yielded by a large bloc or federation of consumers.</i><p>
    

<li>Identify some of the criticisms leveled at marketing, and
discuss how they might be corrected.  <i>Some criticisms concern
illegal practices like price fixing, bait and switch, and false
advertising.  Far more involve ethical issues that are less
clearly defined by strict legal boundaries.  These issues 
include irritating advertisements, dinner time telemarketing
calls,  exaggerated advertising claims, overpriced products, mean
spirited comparative advertisements, privacy issues, and
environmentally unfriendly products. </i><p>

<li>Should consumers be satisfied all the time?  Should the
marketer work to accomplish this goal?  Explain your answers. 
<i>Although the marketing concept stresses consumer satisfaction, it
is not always possible to satisfy consumers nor is it always in 
consumers' best interests to do so.  Consumer satisfaction is a
moving target; consumers don't always know what they need or
want.  Tastes change, and what is satisfying today may not be
tomorrow.  Consumers want things they don't need and products
that can harm them, such as alcoholic beverages, cigarettes,
unhealthy foods, and drugs. </i><p>

<li>What is materialism?  Is it good or bad?   <i>Materialism is a
preference for material possessions over spiritual and
intellectual pursuits.  The ideal is to establish a healthy
balance between the two.  The problem occurs when materialism and
the activities that support a materialistic lifestyle leave no
time or energy for less material ventures.  Few of us would want
to live in a society where everyone was a strict materialist,
with no time for intellectual or spiritual pursuits.</i><p>

<li>What are some types of controls on marketing? <i> There are
formal controls exerted by governments, courts, and regulatory
agencies through laws, rules, and regulations.  There are codes
of conduct and ethics codes enacted by professional organizations
to guide their members through difficult situations.  Self-regulation also is exerted by trade and professional
associations, as well as by businesses and organizations.</i><p>

<li>Explain how some things that are unethical might still be
legal?  <i>Ethics are unwritten rules of conduct that a society
formulates to provide guidelines for acceptable behaviors and
interactions.  They are moral principles or values.  Laws are
written descriptions of acceptable and unacceptable conduct that
set behavioral limits and establish penalties for infractions. 
Laws cannot govern every possible behavior and situation.  Ethics
describe general ways to behave consistently in many different
types of situations.  In some cases, a behavior may not be
considered by any laws, yet ethical standards will govern what is
and is not acceptable behavior.  
</i><p>
<li>Are all marketers evil?  If not, what explanations could be
offered for the mistakes they make?   <i>Certainly not!  People
perform marketing activities and people make mistakes and
sometimes do unacceptable things.  Honest marketers may fail to
do the right thing because they have poor judgment, possess
incomplete information, misunderstand, lack guidance, or fail to
consider a decision's consequences.  Although all businesspeople
should be held to high standards, some will fail to perform as
desired or even as expected.  To condemn all marketers for the
misdeeds of a few is unfair and irresponsible.  However, illegal
and unethical marketers should be punished.</i><p>

<li>Is price skimming illegal?  Is it ethical?  Is it good
marketing?   <i>A skimming pricing strategy is often used when a
unique product is offered for the first time to a market.  A high
price is charged to skim the cream off the market.  This means
generating as much revenue as possible from a captive market
segment, consumers who really need or want the product, but have
no alternatives.  As time passes and competitors enter the
market, and the original marketer achieves economies of scale,
prices typically fall, sometimes considerably, and new market
segments are reached.  Think back to the introduction of the
first handheld calculators.  When the product was new, it was a
revolutionary advance over desk calculators and slide rules.  The
price was very high, often several hundred or thousand dollars
per unit.  As time passed and more competitors arrived, prices
fell.  Now, a reliable handheld solar powered calculator sells 
in discount stores for under five dollars per unit.  This is not
illegal.  It is good marketing, since profitability is a priority
business goal and price skimming increases revenues which
contribute to profitability.  Ethically, it is acceptable for
most products.  However, for products such as the first
pharmaceutical approved in the treatment of AIDS patients, the
ethical dimensions of price skimming for this life prolonging
drug upset many people. </i><p> 
 
<li>Discuss how marketers are often caught in crossfires. 
Explain how this can affect their ability to make the right
decisions. <i> Marketers are boundary spanners.  They must satisfy
their company and produce revenue.  This means selling products,
generating revenue, and contributing to profitability.  At the
same time, they must satisfy consumers so that they will make
repurchases.  This crossfire between sometimes opposing demands
can affect marketers' ability to make the right decision.
</i><p>
<li>Compare and contrast the society marketing concept and the
marketing concept.  Do you think that the societal marketing
concept will be readily accepted by all businesses?  Why or why
not?   <i>The societal marketing concept is the marketing concept
with an added goal, to act responsibly for the greater good of
society.  Since many businesses have great difficulty
successfully implementing the marketing concept, it is likely
that they will have comparable problems with the societal
marketing concept.  Some critics believe that a business must
only satisfy its stockholders and to engage in social marketing
is irresponsible.  </i><p></ol>
<b>
                    CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</b><p>

<b>Check Your Understanding 4.1 </b><p>
<ol>
<li>Distinguish between the dual societal roles of marketing:
micro and macro.  <i>Micromarketing is the way marketing connects a
business, its suppliers, distributors, and consumers in
activities designed to deliver satisfaction.  Macromarketing is a
broader perspective of marketing, how overall it contributes to
an economic system and societal welfare.
</i><p>
<li>Should marketers be concerned when consumers believe that
marketing is not working well for them?  Explain your answer.  <i>If
the marketer has adopted the marketing concept philosophy of
doing business, then consumer satisfaction is a critically
important concern.  If consumers complain that marketing is not
working well for them, marketers should be alarmed.</i><p>
</ol>
<b>Check Your Understanding 4.2</b> <p>
<ol>
<li>What rights do marketers have in the United States? 
<i>Marketers have the right to seek profit in a free market economy. 
Specific marketing activities are controlled by laws, rules, and
regulations.  However, marketers may compete in any way they wish
as long as they do not break any laws, rules, or regulations. 
They must behave legally and ethically.  There is no formal,
written statement of marketers' rights; however, their unwritten
right to compete in a capitalistic free market is extremely
broad.</i><p>

<li>Discuss marketing's societal responsibilities.  <i>Some believe
that marketers have an obligation to operate in the public
interest.  Many businesses already demonstrate their concern for
society because they feel an obligation to "give back" something
to the society that allows them to profit.</i><p>

<li>What kinds of ethical dilemmas do marketers sometimes face? 
<i>Ethical dilemmas often occur in grey areas, where there are no
clearly defined laws, rules, or regulations.  For example, price
skimming on essential products, fear appeals in advertising, high
pressure personal selling, and product overdesign. 
</i><p>
</ol>
<b>Check Your Understanding 4.3</b> <p>
<ol>
<li>Compare and contrast laws and regulations. <i> Laws are formal
statements that guide actions and set limits and penalties for
infractions.  They are passed by legislative bodies, enforced by
administrative and executive agencies, and interpreted by courts. 
Regulations are the rules, standards, and guidelines that
government agencies issue to enact laws.  </i><p>

<li>Identify some federal laws that affect marketing. <i> Federal
laws broadly fall into two categories, those that promote
competitiveness and others that protect consumers.  Among the
most important procompetitive laws are the Sherman Antitrust Act,
Federal Trade Commission Act, and Lanham Trademark Protection
Act.  Important consumer protection laws are the Pure Food and
Drug Act, Auto Disclosure Act, and Consumer Product Safety Act.</i><p>
            
<li>What federal agency exerts the greatest control over
marketing?   <i>The Federal Trade Commission</i>.<p>
</ol>
<b>Check Your Understanding 4.4</b><p>
<ol>
<li>Define consumerism.  <i>Consumerism is "a broad reaction against
bureaucratic neglect and corporate disregard of the rights of the
public."  It occurs when a coalition of people in organizations,
groups, and associations come together to protest an issue over
which they feel common distress.</i><p>

<li>Describe the major consumerism periods in U.S. history.  <i> In
the recent past, there have been three major periods of
consumerism.  Each accompanied periods of economic distress and
public perceptions that the imbalance between sellers and buyers
had shifted too far in favor of sellers.  These broad periods
were from the 1890s to World War I, the late 1920s through World
War II, and the late 1950s through the late 1970s. </i><p>

<li>Identify the rights specified in the Consumer Bill of Rights.
<i> Although it does not have the force of law, the Consumer Bill of
Rights is often cited as an important document.  It marked the
first time that an incumbent president sent a consumer rights
message to the Congress.  In this case, John Kennedy proposed
that consumers have the right to have safe products, the right to
be informed about products, the right to choose from among a
variety of products, and the right to be heard and have
complaints resolved.</i><p>
</ol>
<b>Check Your Understanding 4.5
</b><p><ol>

<li>What is green marketing? <i> This is the term applied to the
activities of marketers who offer products that are
environmentally friendly and not environmentally harmful.</i><p>

<li>Should all products that could be harmful to consumers be
banned?   <i>A distinction should be drawn between products that are
known to be widely harmful and those that are harmful in rare 
situations.  For example, to the person with a serious nut
allergy, peanut butter is poison.  Does this mean that all
consumers should be denied access to peanut butter because it
could harm a very small consumer segment?  Contrast this example
with the large numbers of consumers who are alcoholic or addicted
to nicotine.  As long as a product is legal, and some like
cocaine and heroin are not, a marketer has the legal right to
offer the product to the market.  Individual marketers always
have the right to refuse to work for a business that markets
products that are legal but potentially harmful.</i> <p> 

<li>Should marketers be allowed to target children? <i> This is a
matter of opinion.  Some people believe that children should not
be targeted under any circumstances.  Others believe that
children become better adult consumers if they learn from an
early age how to distinguish between market offers.  General
public opinion falls somewhere between the two extremes.  If
enough consumers believe that marketing to children is wrong,
they will inform marketers and legislators of their discontent. 
Public pressure often results in the passage of laws and the
enactment of rules and regulations that limit or even ban the
offending activity.  
</i><p></ol>

                         <b>  MINI-CASES</b><p>
                                
<b>Mini-Case 4.1: Diet Disasters: The FTC, FDA, and Others Take      
               Action</b><p>
           
    Americans are obsessed with being thin.  Some marketers take
advantage of this consumer insight and aggressively market diet
products to receptive targets.  Despite their vows to pursue
thinness, most dieters who do lose weight can't keep it off. 
It's highly probably that one or more students in your class has
some pronounced views on the diet industry and diet marketing. 
When you assign this case, also ask students to bring in print
advertisements for diet aids.  Some will probably be outrageous,
particularly the ones on the back pages of monthly women's
magazines.  Use the print advertisements along with the case to 
stir a class debate about ethical limits and dilemmas in
marketing.<p>
<ol>
<li>Why is there such an obsession with thinness in the United
States?  <i>There is no easy answer to this question.  Advertising
certainly shares some of the blame for this obsession by its use
of ultrathin models in advertisements.  However, thin is also
promoted in motion pictures, television programs, and magazine
articles.  The barrage of "thin is beautiful" images and
suggestions affect women primarily.  If society endorses and
promotes an idealized body size and shape, it is extremely
difficult for individuals to withstand the pressure to conform.</i> <p>  
 
<li>Is diet marketing legal?  Is it ethical?  <i>Most diet products
are marketed legally.  The ethical question is more difficult to
resolve.  Some diet product promises are outrageous.  They
clearly are not going to deliver the bodies pictured in their
advertisements.  Most consumers are able to distinguish between
products and avoid those whose benefits are obviously
exaggerated.  However, many people believe these products are
marketed unethically if they target woman with eating disorders
who are highly susceptible to products that promise thinness.</i>  <p>
<li>Do you think the antidiet movement in the United States will
grow?  Explain your answer.  <i>Probably not.  If anything, aging
baby boomers will probably need to diet, or at least be careful
about what they eat, to complement their exercise programs. 
Aging baby boomers present a very enticing target for diet
marketers, so one expects more diet marketing in the near future
and not less.</i><p></ol>


<b>Mini-Case 4.2: Fear Appeals Sell Products</b><p>
 
     Fear appeals can sell products.  However, there are risks. 
Extreme fear and fear used inappropriately, with the wrong
products, can backfire.  Fear is a potent emotion, but it is just
one of the emotions that marketers use to communicate with
consumers.  Like Mini-Case 4.1, print advertisements can be used
to complement the case contents.  Some print advertisements are
entertaining, others are not.  See if you can find several
different fear appeals for the same product type.  For example,
automobile advertisements that stress car safety, or insurance
advertisements that promote the need to take care of your family
if anything happens to you, the breadwinner.<p>
<ol>
<li>Do consumers react to fear appeals in the same way?  <i>No,
there is a considerable variation in reactions that reflect
personal experiences, involvement, and perceptions.
</i><p>
<li> Are fear appeals legal?  Are they ethical?   <i>Yes, as long as
they contain information that is not illegal.  Mild fear appeals
are acceptable; extreme fear appeals that seriously affect
consumers and scare them into unnecessary product purchases are
not.</i><p>

<li>Do fear appeals exploit consumers' weaknesses, or do they
instead use powerful images to market important products?    
<i>Both.  It depends on the consumer, product, situation, and
appeal.</i><p></ol>
                                
                       <b>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</b><p>

     Consumer's Digest and Consumer Reports are very popular
consumer magazines with different approaches.  One method for
stimulating student discussion over the preferable approach a
consumer magazine <i>should</i> take, is to bring in current issues of
both magazines and have student analyze them.  Then, have them
can address the question, <i>Should consumer product testing
magazines accept products and advertisements?</i><p>               

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

     Many informative Web sites can be used in Chapter 4. 
Remember to verify Internet addresses, confirm the feasibility of
an Internet assignment <i>before</i> you make it, and stress that
students exhibit professionally responsible behavior on the Net.<p> 

<b>
Internet Assignments</b><p>

     If you have time for only one Chapter 4 Internet assignment,
have students research the government agencies most involved in
monitoring and controlling marketing activities, particularly the
Federal Trade Commission.  Visit the Federal Trade Commission
(FTC) to learn about their mission, "What's New at the FTC," and
their organizational structure.  A link describes the Bureau of
Consumer Protection, the Bureau of Competition, and Consumerline. 
Several recent FTC cases are reviewed in the "What's New at the
FTC" link.  Using the FTC site as a model, have student teams
compare Web sites for several other agencies, such as the Federal
Communications Commission (FCC), Government Services Agency
(GSA), Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), and Consumer
Product Safety Commission (CPSC).  How well organized are the
sites?  How informative?  What is their potential value to the
consumer and marketer?  Compare agency missions and operations. 
What else might the sites offer in order to make them more
valuable to consumers and marketers?<p>          
<pre>
     Using Lynx, press G)o to open the URL link.  Type in the
     address <a href="http://www.ftc.gov">http://www.ftc.gov</a>                                  
             <a href="http://www.fcc.gov">http://www.fcc.gov</a>                                   
             <a href="http://www.gsa.gov">http://www.gsa.gov</a> Visit the Consumer Information Center
             <a href="http://www.epa.gov">http://www.epa.gov</a>                                           
             <a href="http://www.cpsc.gov">http://www.cpsc.gov</a>   </pre>                                       


     Students can learn more about the laws that control
marketing activities by visiting<p>
<pre>
     <a href="http://fatty.law.cornell.edu">http://fatty.law.cornell.edu</a>                              
     <i>(DIR) U.S. Law: Primary Documents and Commentary
           (DIR) Copyright Law                                    
           (DIR) Patent Law                                       
           (DIR) Trademark Law                                    
           (DIR) Commercial Law</i></pre><p>


     A local chapter of Score, the Service Corps of Retired
Executives, may provide a guest speaker who can provide insights
into how businesspeople learn about government laws, rules, and
regulations, and cope with them.  Information about SCORE can be
located at:<p> 
<pre>     
     <a href="http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov">http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov</a>                                
     <i>select SBA's Gopher Server                                   
     (DIR) Business Development                                   
     (file) SCORE Business Advisory Services</i>
</pre><p>

     Some corporations have made long term commitments to social
and community activities.  These corporations are models for
others who are interested in demonstrating their societal
responsibility.  Web sites with information about corporate
involvement in societal activities include:<p>
<pre>                   
     <i>AT&T</i>                                                         
         <a href="http://www.att.com">http://www.att.com</a>                                       
         <i>Contents                                                 
         Education and Community Activities                       
         AT&T Foundation
</i>
     <i>Eastman Kodak </i>                                               
         <a href ="http://www.kodak.com">http://www.kodak.com</a>                                     
        <i> Special Olympics</i> 
                                        
     <i>3M Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing         </i>               
         <a href="http://www.mmm.com">http://www.mmm.com</a>                                       
        <i> Environmental Report                                     
         Community and Sponsorships </i> 
                             
    <i> Stoli    </i>                                                    
         <a href="http://www.stoli.com">http://www.stoli.com</a>                                    
        <i> Charities</i>  </pre><p>  


<h2><a name="marketing">MARKETING APPLICATIONS</a></h2>          

<b>MARKETING APPLICATION 4.1</b><p>

     Most consumers have experienced problems in the marketplace. 
Students can use their own observations to compile a list of
common marketing problems.  Working from the lists compiled
individually, small groups can collaborate on developing a master
list of problems and citing the most serious ones.  As a class,
form a consensus about the nature of the problems, their relative
seriousness, what should be done about them, and who should do
it.<p> 


<b>MARKETING APPLICATION 4.2</b><p>

     Another way to learn about corporate social responsibility
is to evaluate information they place on their Web home page. 
For example, students can visit the home pages of AT&T, IBM, or
General Electric (addresses provided previously) to learn about
their involvement in philanthropic and volunteer programs. 
Alternately, ask some of your non-traditional students about such
programs in their businesses.  Perhaps they can suggest the name
and title of someone in their company who could speak to the
class about their sponsorships or other social programs.<p>  


<b>MARKETING APPLICATION 4.3</b><p>

     Marketers should take the AMA's Code of Ethics (page 116 of
the text) seriously.  What about other professions?  Since it is
likely that the majority of students in your class are non-marketing majors, ask them what they know about the professional
code of ethics in their major.  Assign each the task of finding
the copy (if there is one) and bringing it to class.  Assign this
in advance, so when you reach this point in the chapter, students
have the codes to content analyze and can determine their
similarities and differences.<p>   


<b>MARKETING APPLICATION 4.4</b><p> 

     Most cities have a local Better Business Bureau.  The head
of the local BBB is often an excellent source of information and
a good guest speaker for your class.  Some of the larger BBBs
have a speaker's bureau of professionals from member
organizations who are willing to speak to schools about their
consumer activities.<p>



<b>MARKETING APPLICATION 4.5</b><p> 

     A simple approach to this Application is to have students
contact their employers to ask how they found out about the laws
and regulations governing their activities.  Another approach is
to ask the marketing specialist in your local Small Business
Administration Small Business Development Center (SBDC) to visit
your class and explain the procedures for starting up.  If there
is a SCORE chapter in your city, these retired businesspeople are
excellent resources to draw on for this type of information.  For
more information about SCORE, see the Internet activity in this
chapter.<p>


 
<h2><a name="consumer">CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING </a></h2>

<b>CONSUMER INSIGHT 4.1</b><p>

     Ask your students if they have complained about a product. 
Certainly at least one has complained about food served in a
restaurant, or a product that broke the first time it was used. 
What was the outcome of their complaint?  See <b>Marketing
Application 4.12 </b>(page 110 of the text) for a complementary
activity.  This is a good time to refer to the consumer letter
from Chapter 1.  If you assigned this application, ask some of
the complaint letter writers the nature of their complaints.  If
anyone has received a reply, have them read it to the class. 
Most complaints are legitimate and marketers need to have
complaint information so they can improve their product. 
However, ask your students what they think about complainers who
make a business of complaining.  Is this legal?  Is it ethical?<p>



<b>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</b><p>

     Ethical dilemmas also occur in international marketing.  A
fairly common problem faces marketers in countries where the
common practice is to "grease" transactions through bribes.  The
U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act specifically forbids giving or
taking kickbacks, payoffs, dash, mordida, or baksheesh.  If you
have international students in your class, ask them whether any
of these practices are common in their countries.  If so, ask
them to describe some of the situations where payments are a
necessary part of daily life and commerce.<p>

