<h1><center>CHAPTER 2</h1>
<h1> MAKING MARKETING DECISIONS - DEVELOPING MARKETING PLANS</center></h1>

<a href="#abstract">Chapter Abstract </a><br>
<a href="#teaching tips">Some Teaching Tips </a><br>
<a href="#outline">Chapter Outline </a><br> 
<a href="#answer">Suggested Answers To Chapter Questions </a><br>
<a href="#internet">Using The Internet  </a><br>
<a href="#marketing">Marketing Applications</a><br>
<a href="#consumer">Consumer Insights And International Marketing</a><br>

<h2><a name="abstract">CHAPTER ABSTRACT</a></h2>

<b>1. Describe the characteristics of marketing decisions.</b>  Marketing decisions require choices between sets of alternatives in the marketing functions of exchange, physical distribution, and servicing.  Marketing decisions also are about products,

 prices, places, and promotions.  They vary in their complexity, timing, focus, scope, risk, and participants.</p>

<p><b>2. Explain the importance of planning and describe the building blocks of plans.</b>  Plans are blueprints for action.  Plans, along with the planning process, can help a business cope with uncertainty and prepare it to seize opportunities.  Plannin

g horizons show how far into the future a plan extends.  While planning occurs at all business levels, significant differences exist between plans.  The building blocks of plans are goals and objectives; strategies and tactics.

<p><b>3. Describe how plans are developed.</b>  Marketers contribute to planning at all business levels.  Companywide planning requires developing a mission statement, establishing priorities, developing a strategic plan, and for a multibusiness company, 

forming a portfolio of business units.</p>

<p><b> 4. Discuss marketing planning at the business level. </b> The business level refers to an independent business or a strategic business unit of a multibusiness corporation.  Marketing plans at the business level require performing a situation analys

is, segmenting markets, selecting target markets, developing marketing mix strategies, writing a marketing plan, implementing the plan, and controlling the results.</p>

<p><b>5. Distinguish between the different environments that affect marketing decisions and plans.</b>  Marketing decisions and plans are affected by what is happening in many different environments.  Some of these environments are internal, others are ex

ternal.  Internal environments are very close to the business and include its own operating departments and other businesses in a multibusiness corporation.  External environments include the immediate external environment, along with the greater domestic

 environment and international environment.  The effects of these environments vary, along with the ability of a business to directly influence them.  Environmental volatility is a potent factor that often works to undermine even the best laid plans.</p>

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

Many marketing instructors find the contents of this chapter among the more difficult to teach.  This is because most students, particularly traditional ones, have little full-time work experience, let alone professional experience in making marketing 

decisions or developing marketing plans.  As a result, there are few anchors for this material in traditional student lives.  Non-traditional students with considerable work experience should find it easier to relate Chapter 2 concepts to their own work backgrounds.</p>

<p>If your class is composed primarily of traditional students, you may want to introduce the learning objectives in Chapter 2 by personalizing them, relating them to student lives.  Apply the characteristics of marketing decision to individuals.  For exa

mple, students make choices between alternatives.  They make very important decisions about which school to attend or what job to accept after graduation.  Other decisions are less critical and some are trivial.  Some individual decisions are highly compl

ex, others are simple.  Individual decisions also vary in timing and focus, and also scope and risk.  Some decisions are made solely by the individual, while others require the participation of others.</p>

<p><i>Marketing Application 2.1</i> (page 39 of the text) provides a hands-on approach to considering some decisions facing marketers.  Although competing grocery stores are used as the example, if your students rarely visit this type of retailer, select 

an alternative, such as fast food retailers.  Consider all of the marketing decisions that must be made in respect to the 4Ps -- product, price, place, and promotion.  Challenge student teams to list some decisions that a fast food retailer must make to c

ompete successfully against burger competitors as McDonald's, Wendy's, and Burger King; chicken competitors such as KFC; and fish competitors such as Long John Silver's.  How do customers and the competition, and other environmental factors affect these m

arketing decisions?</p>

<p>Planning is not a particularly exciting topic for most students, yet it is something that should concern them.  One planning activity that should be important personally is career planning.  The topic of marketing planning can be developed by establish

ing parallels with career planning.  For example, have students adapt Kirby Warren's definition of planning (page 42 of the text) to a personal planning context.  Similarly, Figure 2.2 (page 43 of the text) can be modified so that it is relevant for indiv

idual decisions and career planning.</p>  

<p>The concept of decision processes under the corporate umbrella, as illustrated by Figure 2.4 (page 48 of the text), may be difficult for students to grasp.  Traditional students with little if any work experience in multibusiness corporations often can

not relate to the size and complexity of a global giant like AT&T, General Electric, or Procter & Gamble.  As a result, they have trouble imagining the types of marketing decisions and plans made in the business units of these companies.  To learn how suc

h companies describe their organization's structure, visit the Securities and Exchange Commission EDGAR site on the Internet (see instructions in the Chapter 2: Using the Internet).  Look in Part I under the General Business heading of the 10-K report to 

find business unit descriptions.  For example, General Electric reports 12 businesses under its global corporate umbrella;  AT&T reports four broad groups. </p>  

<p>Segmentation, targeting, and positioning are critical processes to most marketers.  As a result, they are referred to throughout the text.  For some unexplained reason, many students seem to have trouble distinguishing these processes.  One suggested s

tarting point is to use the Consumer Insight (page 57 of the text) and the application suggested at the end of this chapter.</p>

<p>Chapter 2 is a good place to explore the topic of careers in marketing, particularly if you parallel planning process in marketing and for individuals, as in career planning.  Use the career appendix in the text and materials in the student study guide

 to supplement the discussion.  Invite a guest speaker to talk about careers in marketing with your students.  If you visit the American Marketing Association's (AMA) MouseTracks World Wide Web home page (see Chapter 1 of this Manual for instructions on h

ow to get to the site), you will find local AMA chapter contacts and addresses.  This is a good place to start if you are looking for knowledgeable guest speakers who can answer student questions about marketing career opportunities.</p>


<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I. Describe the characteristics of marketing decisions<br>
<br><ol>
<li>
Making the right marketing decision is extremely important, yet it is not always easy for the marketer to make the best choice between sets of alternatives<br>

<li>Marketing decisions vary by their complexity, timing, focus, scope, risk, and participants</ol>

II. Explain the importance of planning horizons and describe the building blocks of plans<br>
<br>
<ol>
<li>
Plans are blueprints for future actions<br>
<li>Planning can help marketers cope with uncertainty and seize opportunities
<li>Planning horizons show how far into the future plans extend
<ul>
<li>
Short-range plans are specific, detailed and designed to cope with imminent situations
<li>Mid-range plans are made for two to five years in the future
<li>Long-range plans are far more difficult to make with any certainty of being accurate and meaningful because of the uncertainty of most business environments</ul>                      
<li>Plans are made by marketers at all business levels
<li>The building blocks of plans are goals and objectives; strategies and tactics
<ul>
<li>
Goals and objectives are the ends being sought
<li>Strategies and tactics define how the goals and objectives will be achieved</ul></ol>

III. Explain how plans are developed<br>               
<br><ol>
<li>
Companywide, the first planning step requires formulating a mission statement
<li>Priorities must reflect actionable goals and objectives that are compatible with the mission
<li>A companywide strategic plan is developed
<li>In a multibusiness corporation, plans guide the formation of a portfolio of business units</ol>

IV. Discuss marketing planning at the business level<br>
<br><ol>
<li>
At the business level, marketing planning provides details on how marketing will be used to satisfy consumers and achieve business goals, particularly profit goals
<li>Marketers do a situation analysis to evaluate the environments that affect marketing activities     
<li>Market segments are formed and target markets are selected
<li>Decisions are made about the marketing mix
<li>A marketing plan is written
<li>The marketing plan includes directions for implementation and control</ol>

V. Distinguish between the different environments that affect marketing decisions and plans<br>
<br><ol>
<li>
Internal environments are the most proximate influences on marketing activities; they include other departments in the same business, other company business units, the company or corporation itself
<li>External environments are external factors affecting marketing activities and include the immediate external environment, the greater domestic environment, and the international environment</ol>

<h2><a name="answer">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1. Marketers make many different kinds of decisions.  Describe some of them.  <i>Many marketing decisions are about exchange functions, others involve physical distribution and servicing.  Marketers make decisions about the kinds of products to offer t

o markets.  Other decisions involve the price to charge for a product, when to change a price and by how much.  Place decisions focus on where to offer products.  Promotion decisions are about what types of promotion to use, when promotions are scheduled,

 and how often.</i>   

<p>2. Why is it important to do the right thing rather than just do things right? <i> Peter Drucker is credited with making this observation.  Applied to marketing, it means that making the right decision is critical to marketplace success.  If you are do

ing the wrong thing, then no matter how well you do it, it is still wrong.</i>

<p>3. Why do some individuals plan for their personal lives?  Why do marketers plan? <i>Planning, both in marketing and in one's life, helps bring order to decisions, set priorities, and anticipate uncertainties and opportunities.</i> 

<p>4. Why is a mission statement important to a business?  <i>A mission statement is an announcement to many different people and organizations about the present and future of the business.  It is a vision and a commitment.</i>

<p>5.  What is a distinctive competency?  List a distinctive competency of each of the following: <i> A distinctive competency is something that a business does best.  For example, a distinctive competency of Walt Disney Company is the production of highl

y imaginative animated films that entertain and delight consumers.  This is what Disney does extremely well.  It gives Disney a competitive advantage in the market where it competes.</i>
<ul>
<li>
Dallas Cowboys Football Team.  <i> Bone crushing defense;   smart offense; entertaining cheerleaders.</i>

<li>The University of California.  <i>Theoretical and applied   research; depth and breadth of academic programs; large  number of faculty members who are Nobel Laureates.</i>

<li>The U.S. Army.  <i>Combat trained; rapid deployment;   overwhelming, sophisticated fire power.</i>

<li>Ben and Jerry's Ice Cream Company.  <i>Creamy, tasty, rich  ice cream; unusual flavors; appealing textures.</i></ul>

<p>6. What is environmental analysis?  Why is it so important? <i>An environmental analysis involves collecting information from many sources and analyzing that information for ways that the environment affects the business and marketing activities.  It i

s important to monitor the businesses' environments because they  are so volatile and have such a great impact on marketing activities.</i> 

<p>7. What is the most important outcome for marketing decisions?  Why?  <i>Marketing is the only business functional area that is responsible for revenue production.  Marketing decisions must produce outcomes that satisfy consumers and achieve organizati

onal objectives, mostly to meet profit objectives.</i>

<p>8. Why is it important for marketers to carefully identify their target markets?  <i>Target markets are the businesses, organizations and/or personal use consumers who are already purchasing your products, have purchased them in the past and may do so 

again, or are potential purchasers.  If target markets are not carefully identified, then marketing efforts will be wasted because marketing decisions will be carried out in the wrong direction.</i> 

<p>9. Describe the major parts of a marketing plan.  How are these parts related? <i>The major sections or parts of a marketing plan are the executive summary, situation analysis, marketing objectives statement, marketing strategies statement, budget, and

 appendixes.  The executive summary is usually written last as it is a summation of all other key elements in the plan.  Other parts of the plan are written sequentially.  For example, you must do a situation analysis before establishing marketing objecti

ves.  Once goals and objectives have been set, then you can formulate strategies and tactics.</i>

<p>10. List some external environmental factors that influence the marketing decisions of each of the following:
<ul>
<li>
McDonald's.   <i>Like all retailers, McDonald's is affected by such external environmental factors as the  economy (people lose their jobs, have less money to spend, eat fewer burgers); regulations (for food handling, personnel, advertising); competition 

(other fast food retailers, other restaurants); culture (healthy food  trends).</i>

<li>A local bank.   <i>Banks are affected by government banking  regulations, the economy, technology (Automatic Teller  Machines), competitors, consumers.</i> 

<li>A local police force.   <i>Since the local police are a unit  of local government, they are affected by such external environmental factors as the economy (a recession reduces  tax collections, which affect operating budgets including  salaries), cult

ure and society, the public, laws, regulations.</i></ul></ol><br>

<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 2.1</h4> 

<p>1.  Explain this statement: " Marketing decisions are as varied as the profession itself." <i> Marketing occurs in small independent businesses, global multibusiness corporations, government units, not-for-profit organizations, and is practiced by indi

viduals.  It includes exchange, physical distribution, and servicing activities.  Because of this diversity, it is difficult to describe a <u>typical </u>marketing decision.</i>

<p>2.  What is a window of opportunity?  Why are windows of opportunity so important to marketers?  <i>A window of opportunity occurs when a business has the distinctive competencies to fill a gap in the market.  A window of opportunity often means that t

he first business to take advantage of the opportunity has a competitive advantage and a greater chance of being profitable.</i>

<p>3.  Explain why plans are called blueprints. <i>To an architect, a blueprint is a set of drawings that show how parts of a building or other physical structure fit together.  By studying a blueprint, a builder can calculate the materials needed for the

 project and when they should be ordered.  A blueprint is a guide for future actions.  This is the same whether it is an architect's blueprint or a marketer's plan.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 2.2 </h4>

<p>1.  Why is planning important to achieving marketing success?<i>Planning is important because it encourages marketers to focus their decisions and concentrate on desirable outcomes, particularly those activities that will result in consumer satisfactio

n and profitability.  By planning ahead, marketers can reduce uncertainty, avoid problems and seize opportunities.</i>

<p>2.  Should all organizations plan ahead?  Explain your answer.  <i>Yes, even if the plan is not written, the process of planning can be extremely beneficial to marketers and the business or organization.</i>

<p>3.  What differences are there among short-range, mid-range, and long-range planning horizons?  <i>Plans are made for different periods.  These periods are horizons that show how far into the future plans extend.  Short-range plans are oriented toward 

problem solving over an immediate time period, often no more than several weeks, months, or a year.  Annual plans are short-range plans.  Mid-range plans are for a longer period and are less specific than short-range plans.  The longest planning horizon o

ccurs with long-range plans that may be five or more years in the future and typically are the least specific because of the increased uncertainty of planning so far ahead.
</i>
<h4>Check Your Understanding 2.3 </h4>

<p>1.  How are goals and objectives related?  <i>Goals and objectives are the ends that the marketer seeks.  Goals are considered longer range than objectives, more general and unbounded.  Objectives are shorter-range subgoals.</i>

<p>2.  What is the difference between strategy and tactics? <i> A strategy is an overriding broad direction for future action to achieve goals and objectives.  Tactics are the short-range details that describe how strategies will be achieved.</i>
            
<p>3.  Give examples of how individuals also use strategies and tactics, and goals and objectives in their daily lives.  <i>Responses will vary.  For example, a career goal for Pete is to become a category manager within the large consumer products compan

y where he is an assistant brand manager.  An objective is to earn a reputation in the company for being a very effective marketer.  A strategy for achieving this objective is to complete his bachelor's degree in marketing with honors as soon as possible.

  A tactic is to take two courses a term at night so he can graduate early.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 2.4</h4>

<p>1.  What is a mission statement?  How does a mission statement affect marketing activities?  <i>A mission statement is a written description of the present state of the business and what it intends to do in the future.  It is a proclamation about what 

the company believes is important.  It affects marketing decisions because the mission statement decides priorities, goals and objectives.  Marketing strategies and tactics must serve the goals and objectives.</i>

<p>2.  Peter Drucker believes that a business should be defined by answering three questions.  What are these questions?  <i>Who are our customers?  What do they buy from us?  What are they looking for in our products?</i> 

<p>3.  Do nonprofit organizations and governments have mission statements?  Should they?  Explain your answer. <i>Often a nonprofit (also called a not-for-profit) or government agency will provide a vision statement.  Others have mission statements.  It i

s important for all organizations to establish a consensus statement about what they are and what they intend to become. </i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>

<h4>Mini-Case 2.1: Small Can Be Beautiful for Niche Marketers</h4>
                     
<p>Niche marketers seek parts of a market that typically are smaller and more tightly targeted.  Niche marketers are the opposite of mass marketers who offer their products to the mass market or very large parts of the mass.  Larder of Lady Bustle (LLB) i

s an unusual name for a profitable niche marketer that illustrates how developing your distinctive competencies and working hard to satisfy customers can be profitable. 

<p>1.  What do you think is in LLB's mission statement? <i> A statement that stresses how the business will deliver only the finest quality products that continue to delight customers. </i> 

<p>2.  What environmental factors might influence LLB's business?  <i>The economy is a factor because a downturn (recession) could erode their customer base as they are selling a nonessential product.  Competition from other niche marketers offering their

 products through specialty catalogs could challenge their market share.  Changes in culture and society, particularly an increased emphasis on healthy foods can affect their sales if their products are perceived by consumers as too rich. </i>

<p>3.  Do you think that small niche businesses plan?  Do they have marketing plans?  Explain your answers.  <i>To get an SBA or bank business loan, a small business must submit a business plan that includes a marketing plan.  To be profitable, the busine

ss should continue to plan to avoid problems and seize opportunities.</i>


<h4>Mini-Case 2.2: Euro Disney: Even a Master Marketer's Plans Can Go  Wrong</h4>
 
<p> Walt Disney Co. is an entertainment giant.  It is very successful with its entertainment parks in Florida (Disney World), California (Disney Land), and Japan (Tokyo Disney).  It has not performed as well in Europe, where Euro Disney opened outside Par

is in 1992.  Many factors have contributed to Disney's inability to turn a profit in Europe.  This case identifies some of these environmental influences.

<p>1.  Disney's Older parks (in Orlando, Anaheim, and Tokyo) are all profitable.  What effect might their profitability have had on Disney's decisions for Euro Disney? <i> Being successful in the other locations may have lulled Disney into a sense of infa

llibility.  Disney's planners might not have anticipated some unique problems that would face them in France, from the climate to French coolness toward many parts of American culture.</i>

<p>2.  Even a company of Disney's size cannot directly affect the European economy.  Does this mean that what a marketer can't control shouldn't be considered in planning?   <i>No!  If this were the case, marketers wouldn't ever make plans because so many

 environmental factors are beyond their control.</i>  


<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>This section introduces the idea that marketing is a boundary spanning activity.  Marketers link the businesses' internal environments with its external environments.  Because marketers interact directly with consumers, competitors, and other external 

environment factors, they are in an excellent position to collect information that can be used to make marketing decisions and develop marketing plans.  Another way of collecting commercial intelligence is to purchase products made by competitors and auto

psy them, looking ways to make improvements in your own product.  This is commercial intelligence, not commercial espionage, which is illegal and unethical.  What do you think about the practice of product autopsy?  Is it a good idea?  Why or why not? <i>

It is essential to know what differentiates your product from competing products.  You also assume that as you are examining the competition's products, they are doing the same to your products.  Remember, the key is to collect commercial intelligence and

 not commit commercial espionage.</i>


<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>Those of you connecting to the Internet by Lynx have found that it provides very rapid information transfer.  This full featured Web browser is a product of the Academic Computing Services of The University of Kansas.  It is copyrighted by the Universi

ty and provided free for noncommercial, educational use.  For more information on Lynx, look for a file "About Lynx" that typically is located on the home page of those educational institutions using the Lynx browser.</p>  

<p>If you are getting ready to make Internet assignments, remember to caution students about the downside of Internet use.  Stress again that their conduct on the Internet through your class must be professional always.  There are enough Net-nuisances alr

eady out there already, so please don't add to their numbers! </p>

<p>Because of the Web's volatility, the accuracy of information and addresses provided cannot be guaranteed.  Internet assignments in this Manual have been checked and rechecked.  However, sites on the Web change so rapidly that it would be impossible to 

maintain 100 percent accuracy.  That is why it is essential that you verify Internet addresses and confirm the feasibility of an Internet assignment before you make it.</p>

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>Chapter 2 has several topics that lend themselves to Internet explorations.  For example:</p>

<p>Students who are interested in the <b>International Marketing Report</b> (page 40 of the text) can learn more about NAFTA on the Internet.  The agreement is located at the Department of Commerce and at several universities.  If your school has access t

o an on-line document search system such as CARL (Colorado Alliance of Research Libraries) or FirstSearch, students can find many current articles about NAFTA.  Use this information in a class debate about whether NAFTA will have positive or negative effe

cts on marketing products in the three countries -- the United States, Mexico, and Canada. </p>

<i>Using Lynx, press G)o to open the URL link. <br>
 Type in the address http://gopher.fedworld.gov. <br>
<br>
<i>Alternately,</i>
<a href="http://the-tech.mit.edu/Bulletins/nafta.html">http://the-tech.mit.edu/Bulletins/nafta.html</a>
        

<p><b>Marketing Application 2.1</b> (page 39 of the text) emphasizes the importance of satisfying consumers.  It presents an opportunity for students to compare local retail stores by the success of their customer satisfaction efforts.  This important iss

ue can also be explored on the Internet.  Teams of students can visit Web sites to learn if and how businesses state their intention of satisfying consumers.  Students can do a content analysis and comparison of consumer satisfaction statements made by se

veral businesses in the same industry.  These statements can be evaluated within home pages, often through links that provide information about company history or with AT&T, its Fact Book.  They must search because the information appears at different loc

ations on business home pages.  As you cruise the Web, you'll find other sites that can be used for this assignment.  Caution your students that a visit to a business home page is analogous to a visit in person to a corporate office.  Professional behavio

r is expected.  Some sites to visit and content analyze include <br>

<a href="http://www.hp.com">http://www.hp.com</a> Hewlett Packard<br> 
<a href="http://www.att.com">http://www.att.com</a>  AT&T <br>
<a href="http://www.dell.com">http://www.dell.com</a> Dell Computer <br>
<a href="http://www.ibm.com">http://www.ibm.com </a> IBM Corp.
   
<p>The <b>Consumer Insight</b> (page 47 of the text) about Small Business Development Centers can be updated on the Internet.  Visit the Small Business Administration to find out what kind of marketing assistance the SBDC's provide.<br>

<a href="http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov">http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov</a> </p>
    
<p><b>Marketing Application 2.3</b> (page 54 of the text) challenges students to write a mission statement.  Some mission statements can be found on business home pages; others can be inferred from the business description presented in  filings with the S

ecurities and Exchange Commission (SEC) at the EDGAR site.  Mission statements (or vision statements) are available at government sites on the Web for the United States Postal Service and the Small Business Administration<br>

<a href="http://www.usps.gov">http://www.usps.gov</a><br>
<a href="http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov">http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov</a></p>

<p>Student teams can compare the mission (or vision) statements of the United States Postal Service (USPS)  and United Parcel Service (UPS).  EDGAR, the Electronic Data Gathering And Retrieval System, is funded by the National Science Foundation, whose fu

nding of the project ended in 1995 (Flynn 1994).  EDGAR became operational in 1992.  Publicly traded companies can file their required SEC reports directly on-line, including the 10-K annual report, 10-Q quarterly reports, and 8-K current report (Coffey 1

994).<br>     

<a href="http://www.usps.gov">http://www.usps.gov</a><br>
<a href="http://www.ups.com">http://www.ups.com</a><br></p>
