<a href="gopher://town.hall.org">gopher://town.hall.org  </a><br>                  
        <i>(DIR) EDGAR 
        (?) Search of 1994 or 1995 EDGAR Archives
        Type in the name of the business at the Search command</i><br>


<p><b>References</b></p>

<p>Flynn, Laurie (1994), "Need Timely S.E.C. Corporate Filings?  Look on the Internet," <i>The New York Times</i>, June 19: F10.</p>

<p>Coffey, William J. (1994), "A Precocious Kid Named 'EDGAR'
        Reaches Adolescence," <i>The CPA Journal</i>, January: 52-55.</p>

<h2><a name="marketing">MARKETING APPLICATIONS</a></h2>

<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 2.1</h4>

<p>Marketers' observations of consumers and consuming situations are frequently used in planning and marketing decision making.  In this <b>Application</b>, students are asked to record their own observations of how retail stores satisfy consumers.  It ca

lls for them to evaluate a store on dimensions that are often important to consumers.  If grocery stores are not appropriate to your class, let them select other types of retail stores, for example fast food, sports equipment, athletic shoes, or music.  I

f they use other retailers, be sure that they also develop a suitable list of features for their evaluation.  Rather than have a general discussion of their findings, you might have students form small discussion groups.  Each group can compare their anal

yses and answer the questions in the <b>Application</b> on page 39 of the text.  Ask each group to prepare a short oral summation of their analysis for presentation to the class.</p>  


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 2.2</h4>

<p>While this Application deals directly with media planning, specifically advertising scheduling, impress on your students how plans are made for all kinds of marketing activities.  Students in teams or small groups should block out a 12-month time line 

on which they can record their media buying decisions.  They need to estimate demand cycles.  For example, students should analyze the times when flowers are most in demand and when they are least in demand.  For what situations do consumers purchase flow

ers?  Which holidays are associated with flower gifts?  Media spending decisions are based on observations about consumer demand and particularly, peak demand periods.  Allow sufficient time <u>before</u> each demand peak so advertising can be heavied up 

before that peak.  You can extend this planning exercise by having a guest speaker meet with the class to discuss advertising media planning for a florist or other specialty retailer. </p>  


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 2.3</h4>

 <p>Mission statements are not easy to write, as your students will find out when they try to write one for the U.S. Postal Service and another delivery service.  Two differences between the Postal Service and other delivery systems are the government aff

iliation of the former and the profitability of the latter.  As an alternative to delivery services, have student teams write mission statements for two competitors in other industries, for example Coca Cola and PepsiCo; Apple Computer and Dell Computer; 

AT&T and Sprint.  An Internet application relates to this task, as it provides a roadmap to the United States Postal Service, UPS, and Securities and Exchange Commission reports in the EDGAR-SEC files.  Mission statements can be inferred from the Part I G

eneral Business discussion in  10-K Reports.  Alternately, students can find mission statements on home pages of competing businesses, then compare their contents.</p>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 2.4</h4> 

<p>Many different environments affect not-for-profit organizations and governments.  For example, a not-for-profit hospital faces the same environments, internal and external, as a for-profit hospital faces, with one exception.  The not-for-profit hospita

l does not have to satisfy stockholders by earning a profit.  However, both must market their services and face such internal environments as other operating departments within the hospital, other hospital units, and the hospital's culture.  External envi

ronments include suppliers, customers, competitors, society, the economy, government, laws and regulations, science/technology, and the public.</p>



<h2><a name="consumer">CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING </a></h2>

<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 2.1</h4>

<p>The Small Business Administration's (SBA) Small Business Development Centers (SBDCs) have been extremely helpful to small businesses in such practical areas as marketing planning.  However, as the <b>Consumer Insight</b> (page 47 of the text) was writt

en, the SBA and SBDCs were under Congressional attack and their future funding was seriously in doubt.  At least for the immediate future, SBDCs are a resource that small businesses can rely on to provide marketing assistance.  A related Internet activity

 provides a roadmap to SBAONLINE, the Internet files of the Small Business Administration.  This site offers marketing success stories of real SBA clients, and information about the SBA and SBDCs.  Ask your students if they, their families, or employers h

ave ever used the services of an SBDC, particularly for assistance in developing a marketing plan.  Alternately, if there is an SBDC nearby, invite the marketing specialist to class as a guest speaker to discuss marketing services they offer.  A list of S

BDC contacts in each state is provided at the SBAONLINE home page.  You may also find a local SBDC under U.S. Government listing in your local telephone directory.

<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 2.2</h4>

<p>This <b>Consumer Insight</b> (page 57 in text) focuses on tools for identifying consumer segments.  Stress that consumer segmentation is used for businesses as well as personal use consumers.  Ask your students about zip code demographic information fo

r your city or state.  Get a zip code map from the local post office or possibly, your telephone book.  Identify different neighborhoods within the zip codes.  Using class knowledge of the kinds of homes in these areas and where the owners are employed, a

ssign names to the zip code areas that describe the inhabitants.  For example, following Claritas' example, you may identify zip codes with segments such as "profs and docs", a zip code with many professors and doctors from the local university and its me

dical center; "horses and buggies", where horse farms and riding stables are located; and "auto alley" where many assembly line workers from a local automobile factory live.</p>



<h3>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h3>

<p>The North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) is providing marketing successes for American businesses, despite the rapid devaluation of the Mexican peso during early 1995.  The economic destabilization was a setback to many businesses' plans; howeve

r, it has not stopped others from forging ahead to take advantage of the opportunities that NAFTA offers.  Now, there is growing support for an extension of NAFTA to include other Latin and South American countries.  Prime target countries are Chile and T

rinidad and Tobago.  Unexpected volatility in international markets, as illustrated by the Mexican financial crisis, can disrupt even the most carefully developed marketing plans.</p>

<p>
