<head>
<title>CHAPTER 9: UNDERSTANDING PRICE</title>
</head>
                                
<h1><center>CHAPTER 9</h1>
<h1>UNDERSTANDING PRICE</center></h1>
                                
<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>


<p><b>1. Explain how different perspectives on price influence the
pricing process.  </b>Price is known by many different names.  There
are many different perspectives on price.  Concern about price
has risen in the past several decades, fueled by changes in the
economic environment, swings in consumer confidence, and
increased domestic and international price competition.  Consumer
confidence is an important indicator of future purchase
behaviors.  This has obvious price implications.  When consumers
are not confident of their jobs and futures, their spending
usually declines, they become more price sensitivity, and
marketers consider this in their price decisions.


<p><b>2. Describe how pricing decisions are made.  </b>The many different
perspectives on price also affect the marketer's pricing
decisions.  Consumers often perceive price as a surrogate for
value cues.  Some consumers are price conscious, others are not. 
Consumers make price comparisons between products, using this
information in their purchase decisions.  Price is an allocation
device, rationing products among consumers and balancing supply
and demand.  For most products, the law of demand holds so that
price and demand move in opposite directions.  For essential
products, inelastic demand prevails so that a change in price
does not have the expected effect on demand.  Because these
products are necessities, consumers will continue to purchase
them (up to a point) even when prices are raised.  A marketer
must be aware of the various perspectives on price, including
those of the government, consumers, the business, the
competition, and channel of distribution members.


<p><b>3. Discuss further influences on price.  </b>There are other
influences on price, including such factors as costs, the
economy, seasons, special events, nature, and suppliers.


<p><b>4. Describe the four decisions made during pricing.  </b>Good
information, collected from internal and external sources, is
essential to making good price decisions.  Some price decisions
follow the price set by the market leader, others are seat of the
pants price decisions, highly intuitive and subjective.  Pricing
decisions generally follow four steps: setting price objectives,
formulating a pricing strategy, setting price tactics, and making
price adjustments, if and as needed.


<p><b>5. Discuss popular pricing practices.  </b>Prices change as a result
of the influence of many different factors.  Marketers use a
variety of pricing approaches, including odd/even, loss leader,
bundled, prestige, time-period, and trial pricing.  All of these
approaches serve different goals that price must accomplish for
the marketer.


<p><b>6. Decide if price is an art or a science.  </b>Most marketers will
tell you that pricing is both an art and a science.  While many
marketers use statistical models and computer simulations to help
set prices, often the final price is determined with considerable
input from experienced marketers who have developed a keen sense
of what the market will tolerate.  There is a place for both
objective, statistical and subjective, judgmental input to price
decisions.


<p><b>7. Discuss the interrelationship among price and the other
marketing mix variables (product, place, and promotion).  </b>Price
is a critical marketing mix variable and the one that most
directly and quickly affects revenue.  However, price cannot be
considered apart from the other marketing mix variables (product,
place, and promotion) that also significantly affect the price
that consumers are willing to pay for a product.  

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>The Chapter 9 opening question asks: "Why is it so difficult
for marketers to arrive at the right price for a product?  The
crux of this question relates to the question of self-interest.
From the marketer's perspective, the right price for a product
will achieve the marketer's self-interest goals of covering
costs, generating revenue, and achieving profit goals.  The
marketer's price may not be the right price for consumers, who
are operating on their own rules of self-interest.  When there is
a misalignment between marketer and consumer perspectives about
the right price, the result can be disaster as consumer purchases
dry up.  The determination of what is right in pricing has to
satisfy multiple parties and still be in line with the
competition's prices.

<p>     Consumer self-interest expresses itself differently
according to the situation and what the consumer values.  For
price conscious consumers, the self-interest rule usually calls
for paying as little as possible for as much product as possible. 
For quality conscious consumers, the self-interest rule states
that the consumer values quality and will correlate price and
quality, when other product quality information is absent.

<p>     An excellent illustration of the strong influence of price
on consumer perceptions of quality appears in a book by Robert B.
Cialdini (1993).  The author sites a true case (paraphrased
below) as an example of the power of price to convey messages
about product quality, particularly when other quality cues are
absent.  

<p>     The owner of a Native American jewelry store in Arizona was
     having difficulty selling some good quality turquoise
     jewelry at a fair price.  She tried everything, from
     displaying the jewelry in a central store location to having
     her sales staff hard sell the pieces.  It was the height of
     the tourist season, the store was jammed with tourists, but
     the jewelry wasn't selling.  

<p>     The night before she was due to leave town on a business
     trip, the store owner wrote her head salesperson a note
     telling her to sell the jewelry at "price X 1/2", even
     though this meant a loss.  When she returned several days
     later, she wasn't surprised to find the jewelry sold out. 
     However, she was shocked to find that the salesperson had
     misread her note and instead of marking the jewelry down
     half price, each piece had been remarked to "2 X" and sold
     at twice the original price! 

<p>The explanation for the tourists' behavior lies in their
having very little knowledge about the quality of the turquoise
jewelry.  They perceived the initial price as too low for good
quality jewelry, when it actually was a fair price.  They bought
the jewelry at double the price because they were following a
stereotype that price equals quality, when no other quality
information is available.  For quality conscious consumers, price
often is the surrogate for quality.

<p>     Students can provide examples of other products for which
price is a quality proxy.  Ask them to consider service products
along with tangible goods where price conveys information that
some consumers need in order to make a purchase decision.
          
<p><b>Reference</b>
<p>     Cialdini, Robert B. (1993), Influence: Science and Practice
     Third Edition, New York: HarperCollins College Publishers,
     Chapter 1.

<p><b>The Dollar Standard</b>

<p>     The <b>International Marketing Report</b> (page 269 of the text)
highlights the use of the U.S. dollar at the currency standard in
many countries.  An activity in the Using the Internet section of
this chapter identifies an information source for students to
check current country currency rates of exchange.  Rates of
exchange and their fluctuation can have dramatic effects on
price.  For example, in mid-1995 the dollar was sinking in value
against the Japanese yen and the United States government was
threatening a trade war over the closed Japanese automobile
market.  A weak dollar means American goods are cheaper in
countries that have a strong currency against the dollar.  A
strong dollar means American goods are priced higher because the
foreign currency is weaker.  Which situation (weak or strong
dollar) favors the pricing of American products abroad?  Which
situation (weak or strong dollar) means that American consumers
will pay a higher price for imported foreign products in the
United States?

<p>     This point can be emphasized by having students track the
dollar against several major foreign currencies over several
months.  Currency exchange rates can be tracked in hard copy
publications such as The Wall Street Journal, in a local
newspaper, or on the Internet.  At the end of the tracking
period, have students consider whether any swings in currency
rates that occurred might have been sufficient to increase prices
for consumer products.  Would the effects have been experienced
equally by personal use and business/organization consumers
making product purchases?

<p><b>Consumer Confidence And Business Cycles</b>

<p>     Consumer confidence is an important concept for marketers
trying to predict how prices will affect demand.  Consumer
confidence is often cited as a numerical representation of
consumer willingness to make purchases and invest in the future,
as a function of their current feelings about their job security
and future.  It is used to track changes in consumer attitudes
over time.  The information is derived from surveys most often
associated with the University of Michigan's Survey Research
Center and the nonpartisan Conference Board's Consumer Confidence
Index.

<p>     Sales forecasts can be made regionally, based on regional
differences in levels of consumer confidence.  Since consumer
confidence is a gauge of consumers' attitudes toward making
purchases, marketers can use the information to forecast demand
and make corresponding geographic supply adjustments.  Chrysler
Corporation places a high priority on the use of consumer
confidence data to predict purchase behavior (Shaver 1992). 
Surveys also provide information about consumers' intentions to
purchase major appliances, homes, and furniture.  This is
valuable demand information for these industries.  When consumer
confidence begins to grow, marketers can stimulate demand even
further by providing price incentives and sales promotions.  

<p>     Consumer confidence is closely linked to business cycles and
changes in the economic environment.  These cycles are periods
when levels of business activity change as a result of many
converging factors including imbalances in supply and demand, raw
materials shortages, government spending and policies, and
international conditions.  Over time, business and the economy
experience different activity level cycles that affect the entire
society.  For the most part, all the economies of the world's
industrialized countries generally tend to run parallel business
cycles because of their economic interdependency.  However, the
point at which a cycle begins to turn (begins or ends) may not be
the same in each country.   

<p>     The business cycles we hear the most about are prosperity,
recession, depression, and recovery.

<ul>
<li>Prosperity describes a period when business activity,
     production, employment, and consumption are high. 
     Generally, personal use consumers "feel good" about their
     jobs and their futures; businesses are willing to invest
     capital in expansion, employees, and future growth.  A sense
     of optimism is reflected in greater purchases of
     nonessential and luxury products, and indulgence in
     vacations and consumer durable products.  Consumer
     confidence is high as consumers feel great optimism for the
     future and make big ticket purchases that can be paid off
     over time.

<li>Recession occurs as business activity slows, production
     declines, demand falls, and inventory rises, at least in the
     short run.  Unemployment rises as businesses delay
     investment and reduce production.  Purchases by both
     personal use and business/organization consumers tend to
     return to essentials, frill and luxury purchases are
     delayed, and consumers of both types become more price
     sensitive.  Consumer confidence falls, consumers become more
     apprehensive about the future, and are less willing to make
     big ticket purchases or incur large debt.

<li>Depression is the most severe period where business activity
     is heavily curtailed, unemployment rises to a peak, demand
     and production fall, and capital investments virtually
     cease.  Consumer confidence falls to its lowest levels, and
     consumers struggle to hold on to what they have and not lose
     their investments, homes, or jobs.  The United States and
     the industrialized countries experienced The Great
     Depression beginning in 1929 and running through the early
     1930s to the beginning of World War II.  The terrible
     economic times, high unemployment, and consumer pessimism
     contributed to political unrest and social turmoil.

<li>Recovery occurs when conditions start to improve. 
     Unemployment begins to fall as production increases.  Demand
     rises, and as it does, businesses begin to invest more in
     production and the future.  Consumer confidence rises, but
     consumers  are cautious, waiting for a full recovery.
</ul>

<p>     Two other influences on consumer spending, inflation and
deflation, also affect the economy and prices.  Inflation occurs
when prices rise more rapidly than incomes and is most often
associated with growth and prosperity.  As this occurs, consumer
buying power shrinks and consumers have a tendency to accelerate
their purchases because they are apprehensive about future price
rises.  As they "stock up" at lower current prices, the
purchasing frenzy also reduces the rate of savings.  Deflation
occurs when prices fall because demand is reduced.  As this
occurs, revenues fall off and profits dry up.  Deflation often
accompanies the beginning of a recession.

<p>     Marketers can't afford to hide when the economy swings into
a new cycle.  They must respond to changes in the marketplace and
business activity in order to increase their chance of profiting
and surviving.  To emphasize this point, guide students through a
discussion of marketer responses to changes in business cycles. 
Begin by having them complete a simple table (example below) that
describes what happens generally to demand, employment,
production, investment, and consumer confidence during each
business cycle.  This can be conveyed by using arrows: up arrow =
increasing, down arrow = decreasing.  For each business cycle,
have students identify what happens to consumer spending by using
a plus (+) or a minus (-) in the consumer confidence column. 
Stress that these are generalizations and exceptions can be found
of businesses thriving in a depression and others perishing in a
growth period.
 

<p><b>BUSINESS CYCLE CHANGES</b>
<pre>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
|            Demand  Unemployment  Production  Investment  Confidence | 
|---------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Prosperity                                                          |
|---------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Recession                                                           |
|---------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Depression                                                          |
|---------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Recovery                                                            |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
</pre>
           
<p>     Ask students to consider the following questions.

<ul>
<li>During a period of prosperity, marketers of what types of
     products should find it easier to stimulate consumer
     purchases of their products?

<li>During a period of recession, marketers of what types of
     products should find it easier to stimulate consumer
     purchases of their products?  

<li>During which cycle(s) could marketers increase product
     prices and probably not dampen demand?

<li>During which cycle(s) could marketers decrease product
     prices and probably not stimulate consumer purchases?

<li>During which cycle(s) might marketers use credit as a way to
     encourage consumer spending?
</ul>

<p><b>Reference</b>
<p>     Shaver, Kim Darden (1992), "Don't Worry, Be Happy: (Buy a
     Car)," <i>American Demographics</i> (September): 59-60.

<p><b>Price and Mass Customization </b>

<p>     Unless a consumer is willing to pay a high price for a
custom made product, the alternative is a mass produced product
with a few model variations offered at different price points. 
However, increasingly sophisticated computer technology is
changing mass production to mass customization.  Mass
customization is also called agile manufacturing and agile
marketing.  It occurs when a producer offers a design base on
which consumers can make changes to suit their preferences,
needs, and in many cases, price constraints.  Changes are
accepted within certain categories of specifications, often
called modules.  The flexibility offered consumer types is far
greater than what is found in traditional mass production.  

<p>     In personal computers (PC), mass customization means that a
producer might ship five different basic PC models to resellers. 
The resellers offer their customers the chance to customize their
own PC at various price points depending on the options selected
(Goldberg 1995).  

<p>     In clothing, a jeans maker might offer several basic jeans
styles.  A salesperson measures the consumer and inputs the
measurements into a computer program that matches the
measurements to the nearest jeans size, often selecting from
hundreds of alternative pattern sizes.  The customer pays for the
jeans, the pattern order is sent by computer to the factory, the
pattern is cut, the jeans sewn to size, packaged, and delivered
to the customer.  The price reflects the design module selected.

<p>     In furniture, some retailers allow consumers to select from
among a series of sofa frame sizes, styles, wood types, and
cushion designs.  After the frame is selected, the consumer
selects a fabric from hundreds of possible alternative colors,
textures, and weaves.  The sofa order is placed and built to the
customer's specifications.  The price also is customized because
each selection module carries its own price point.  The consumer
has customized a sofa by selecting from a broad selection of
alternatives or modules, and prices.

<p>     In publishing, The Wall Street Journal has introduced
"...the first newspaper published for a circulation of one."  The
Personal Journal is a customized newspaper delivered to the
consumer's personal computer each business day morning.  It
contains information in categories that the consumer preselects,
such as  Wall Street Journal columns and editorials, stocks,
mutual funds, and news.  The Personal Journal is updated
continuously.  The price is less than a dollar per business day
(WSJ 1995).

<p>     Mass customization is being hailed as the next major trend
in marketing.  Some marketers believe that mass customization
will end the emphasis on segmentation and eliminate the need for
place by distributing products directly to the customer (Schultz
1994).  It also will accelerate the trend toward customized
promotion and pricing.  Production will focus on modules and
product life cycles will become even shorter (Andel 1995).

<p>     Students may have experienced mass customization if recently
they have made a personal computer or new automobile purchase. 
If anyone has remodeled their home, some window companies are
using this process so customers can customize product design.  

<p>     Ask your students to consider the questions

<ul>
<li>Is this the way marketing will be performed in the next
     century; is this the end of mass marketing and segmentation? 
     
<li>Are there any products that do not lend themselves to mass
     customization?  

<li>Are there other products that are ideal candidates for mass
     customization?  

<li>Can marketers generate greater profits from mass
     customization even as individual product prices may be
     lowered?
</ul>

  
<p><b>References</b>
<p>     Andel, Tom (1995), "Why Did Dad Kick Tires Before He Bought
     A Car?", <i>Transportation & Distribution</i> (February): 78-79.

<p>     Goldberg, Aaron (1995), "Mass Customization is the Latest
     High-Tech Oxymoron," <i>PC Week</i> (January 23): A6-7.

<p>     Schultz, Don E. (1994), "Driving Integration is What IT is
     All About," <i>Marketing News</i> (October 10): 12-13.

<p>     Advertisement for The Personal Journal (1995), <i>The Wall
     Street Journal</i> (July 3): B3.

<p><b>Problem Areas in Pricing</b>

<p>     Pricing often is a controversial part of marketing because
of a number of illegal practices, particularly those shown in
Figure 9.4 (page 277 of the text), namely price fixing, deceptive
pricing, predatory pricing, and discriminatory pricing.  Student
teams can research these practices and report to the class about
their incidence and recent actions taken against offending
businesses.  Have any students been victimized by one of these
practices?  How did they handle the problem?  Were they satisfied
with the outcome?

<p>     Other pricing problem topics can be developed for class
debate, such as the issue of ethical concerns over pricing
particularly of ethical pharmaceutical products.  Students can
investigate the pricing of early AIDS drugs amid claims of
unfairness because of skimming pricing tactics.  Should
government regulate drug prices more stringently and force price
reductions?  What might happen to drug company research and
development if price controls are implemented?  What has been the
outcome in the past when price controls have been tried?  

<p><b>Price Wars</b>
  
<p>     There was a time when consumers loved gasoline price wars. 
Back in the days when gasoline was less than a dollar a gallon,
competing gasoline stations would sometimes get into a price war. 
Each would try to outdo the other in reducing prices, often to
the point where consumers could buy gasoline at far less than
dealers' costs.  Do consumers really benefit from a price war? 
Have any of your students experienced a price war as a consumer
or as an employee of a warring retailer?  Students often can
provide interesting perspectives on the harmful fallout of a
price war for a business and its employees.

<p><b>Setting Prices</b>

<p>     Several years ago I spent some airport waiting time in
Cincinnati talking with a marketer who worked for, as he
described it, "a big soap maker" in that city.  Since his company
is the market leader in most markets where it competes, I asked
him how the competition priced its products in these markets.  He
replied that he could predict to the penny what competing prices
would be because each company had a set rule.  Their price would
always be 1 percent, 5 percent, or even 10 percent less than his
company's price.  In other words, the competition followed the
leader, always by the same percentage, which simplified the
pricing process for them, but also gave the soap maker even
greater power in the marketplace.

<p>     The pricing process differs greatly between businesses and
industries.  If possible, invite a guest speaker to class to talk
about pricing from a first hand perspective.  Often a local
chapter of the American Marketing Association can provide a
speaker.  You can find local chapter contacts on the Internet
(see <a href="#internet">Using the Internet</a> in this chapter).

<p><b>Creative Pricing</b>

<p>     Have student teams perform a content analysis of current
newspaper, magazine, and television advertisements, as well as
their own direct mail, looking for examples of some of the
different pricing approaches identified in Figure 9.9 (page 294
of the text).  Their findings can be the basis for a class
discussion of creative pricing practices.  Are some of these
approaches difficult to understand?  Might some consumers be
misled?  Consider the last line in Figure 9.9 and discuss its
meaning for marketers and consumers.

<p>     "Note: Once you've been creative, make sure you're covered. 
     <b>The most important aspect of any pricing approach is that it
     is legal and ethical.</b>  Check with counsel."  

<p><b>Price And The Other Marketing Mix Variables</b>

<p>     If your students participated in the egg delivery system or
wooden pencil exercise, they set a price for their new product. 
Ask them to rethink how they decided on a price and what effect
the other marketing mix variables had on their price decisions. 
For example, ask them to consider

<ul>
<li>how their pricing decisions were influenced by their
     product, what changes in price could be associated with
     changes in product design and features, whether there might
     be a luxury version of their product with a prestige price

<li>how their pricing decisions were influenced by place, where
     the product could be sold and the type of retailer involved

<li>how their pricing decisions were influenced by promotion,
     decisions about how, when, and for what period of time to 
     promote the product
</ul>

<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Explain how different perspectives on price influence the
     pricing process
<ol>
<li>Price represents many things, including what it takes
          to purchase products and the value of things traded in
          a marketing exchange; there are many different
          perspectives about price
<li>Price has grown in importance because of many changes
          in the economic environment, swings in consumer
          confidence, and the increased incidence of price
          competition
<li>Consumer confidence influences price because of its
          relationship with price sensitivity and attitude toward
          a purchase 
</ol>

II.  Describe how pricing decisions are made
<ol>

<li>The principal meaning of price to a marketer relates to
          how price affects total revenue and profit
<li>To consumers, price is a signal used to indicate a
          product's value, particularly in the absence of other
          information
<ul>
<li>Some consumers are price conscious; others may be
               status conscious, service conscious, or quality
               conscious
<li>Consumers make price comparisons and typically
               evaluate the acceptability of a price within a
               price range
<li>Price is an allocative device 
<ol>
<li>For nonessential products, the law of demand
                    holds in predicting that when price falls,
                    demand rises; when price rises, demand falls
<li>For essential products, products that
                    consumers consider necessities of life, a
                    change in price does not result in a
                    comparable percent change in demand
</ol>
</ul>
<li>To government, price is an important factor in the
          efficient functioning of the marketplace as it brings
          supply and demand into balance
<li>Government works to ensure competitive pricing and
               currency stability
<li>The marketer's pricing authority is limited by
               government
<li>The marketer and the business view price as a marketing
          mix factor that can be changed swiftly and is a key
          element affecting revenue and profit
<ul>
<li>Marketers use price to differentiate products
<li>Price can be used to reward members of the channel
               of distribution
<li>Price is a competitive weapon
<li>Price is an area where ethical abuses are prone to
               occur
</ul>
<li>To the competition, price is a weapon that sometimes
          gets out of control and price wars can result
<ul>
<li>Price wars usually are highly destructive to the
               participants
<li>Nonprice competition has advantages over price
               competition, it is harder for the competition to
               match, but it is also usually harder for the
               marketer to implement
</ul>
<li>Channel of distribution members view price as the
          mechanism for generating revenue and profit  
</ol>

III. Discuss further influences on price
<ol>

<li>All of the perspectives on price should be considered
          when setting a price; they often are not
<li>There are many other important influences on price,
          including costs, economic conditions, seasons, special
          events, nature, and suppliers
</ol>

IV.  Describe the four decisions made during pricing
<ol>
<li>Pricing decisions often involve marketers and others
          involved in product production and delivery
<li>Pricing decisions depend on good information from both
          internal and external sources
<li>Pricing requires decisions in four areas
<ul>
<li>Setting price objectives
<li>Formulating a pricing strategy 
<li>Setting price tactics
<li>Making price adjustments, if and as needed
</ul>
</ol>

V.   Discuss popular pricing practices
<ol>

<li>Acceptable prices occur when the marketer's prices fall
          within an acceptable range, between a price ceiling and
          a price floor
<li>There are many different pricing practices, including
          odd/even, loss leader, bundling, prestige, time-period,
          and trial pricing
</ol>

VI.  Decide if price is an art or a science
<ol>
<li>Some people think pricing is an art, developed through
          years of experience, judgment, and a sense of what the
          market will tolerate
<li>Others believe that it is art and science, and that
          effective pricing requires skill in both
</ol>

VII. Discuss the interrelationship among price and the other
     marketing mix variables (product, place, and promotion)
<ol>
<li>Price is the critical marketing mix variable that most
          directly affects revenue and profit
<li>Price must be considered along with the other variables
                    of product, place, and promotion
</ol>
                    
<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>


<p>1.  Why is it so difficult for marketers to arrive at the right
price for a product.  <i>The difficulty of arriving at the right
price addresses the question of perspective.  We assume that
everyone involved in pricing has certain goals and that these
goals may conflict.  Therefore, the right price to meet the
marketer's goals can be the wrong price for consumers, and vice
versa.</i>

<p>2.  Following are some of the names used for price - explain what
the consumer gets for each price: rent, tuition, toll, charitable
donation.  <i>Standard exchanges for each of the prices are that
rent gives the consumer a product to use for a predetermined time
period; tuition gives the consumer access to an educational
opportunity; a toll gives a consumer permission to travel on a
road or pass over a bridge; a charitable donation gives a
consumer a feeling of satisfaction for contributing to a worthy
cause.</i>

<p>3.  Discuss some of the reasons for the increasing importance of
price to marketers and consumers.  <i>Price has grown in importance
because the latter years of the 20th century have seen an
increase in price competition.  It has been a period of economic
growth and then recession, economic uncertainty, swings in
consumer confidence, deregulation, and increased foreign
competition domestically and abroad. </i>

<p>4.  What is consumer confidence?  Why should marketers be
concerned when consumers lack confidence?   <i>Consumer confidence
describes the positive or negative feelings consumers have about
the present, the future, their job security, and their spending
ability.  It is a predictor of consumer spending and can be used
to forecast demand.</i>

<p>5.  Give an example of the purchase behavior of each of the
following consumers: status conscious, price conscious, service
conscious.  <i>A status conscious consumer purchases high price
products in order to demonstrate economic well being, social
status, or prestige; a price conscious consumer prefers to pay as
little as possible for as much product as possible; a service
conscious consumer values service and will pay a higher price in
order to get it.</i>

<p>6.  In your own words, explain the relationship between price and
quantity sold, as expressed in the law of demand.  <i>The law of
demand states that there is an inverse relationship between price
and quantity demanded (sold), so that when price rises, demand
falls; when price falls, demand rises.  </i>

<p>7.  Milk, gasoline, and urgent medical treatment are examples of
inelastic products.  What does this mean?  <i>These products are
essential to consumers, so they continue to purchase the products
even when their prices rise because the products are extremely
important in their lives.  </i>

<p>8.  Why is the government concerned about the prices charged for
products?  Should the government be concerned about prices?  What
do you think?  <i>Government is very concerned about price because
it plays such an important allocative role in the economy. 
Government wants to ensure fair price competition to keep the
free market healthy and protect consumers against illegal pricing
practices.  Government has a legitimate role in pricing, although
sometimes it overreacts and does harm.  Government also plays an
important role in setting national policy which affects price,
and tries to maintain the stability of the currency. </i>

<p>9.  What is a price war?  Is it good for consumers?  <i>When
aggressive price competition gets out of hand, it sometimes
results in a price war.  This means competitors intensify their
efforts to undercut each other on price.  It may benefit
consumers in the short term, as they take advantage of price
cuts.  However, in the long term it can be harmful because it can
drive competitors from the market, which ultimately reduces
choices and raises prices.</i>

<p>10.  Explain this statement: "Price and costs are inextricably
linked."  <i>Most businesses link the two because the first part of
the goal for price to accomplish is to raise sufficient revenue
to cover costs, then an additional amount to provide a profit.</i>

<p>11.  What happens if the marketer's price range for a product and
the consumer's range of acceptable prices are not similar?  <i>This
means price incompatible.  Generally the result is that the
consumer will not make a purchase.  However, if the product is
essential (demand is inelastic) and there are no alternatives,
the consumer may still make a purchase, at least in the short
term.</i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 9.1 </h4>

<p>1.  Describe some of the meanings commonly applied to price.  
<i>Price can be identified in terms of currency used, for example as
dollars, yen, or pesos.  Price is the value of things traded in a
marketing exchange.  It is a measure of what must be given up in
order to make an exchange.  It is called many different things,
including rent, tuition, fee, ticket, and tax.</i>

<p>2.  Explain this statement: "Price is a matter of perspective."
<i>Price has different meanings depending on whose perspective is
taken.  Price often reflects self-interest, for example marketers
serve their self-interest by using price to generate revenue and
profit; price conscious consumers serve their self-interest by
trying to get as much product as possible for as low a price as
possible. </i>
 
<p>3.  Discuss the various perspectives on price.  <i>Among the most
important perspectives are those of the marketer and the
business, consumers, government, the competition, and members of
the channel of distribution.  Each has a different perspective on
price and each attempts to satisfy their self-interest in the
process.  For example, consumers look at price as a signal, a cue
about quality, value, status, and quantity.  Marketers view price
as a means to achieve goals.  Government's perspective on price
is complex because price serves such an important allocative role
in the economy.  </i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 9.2 </h4>

<p>Describe the many factors that influence price.  <i>Price is
influenced by many factors because it does not exist in a vacuum. 
All of the different perspectives on price can influence it.  It
also is affected by costs, the economy, seasons, special events,
nature, and suppliers.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 9.3 </h4>

<p>Describe the steps in making a price decision.  <i>Although some
marketers follow the market leader is setting their product
prices and others price "by the seat of their pants," most follow
some general pricing steps.  These steps are setting price
objectives, formulating a pricing strategy, setting price
tactics, and making price adjustments, if and as needed. </i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 9.4</h4>

<p>1.  Discuss commonly used pricing practices.  <i>There are many
different approaches used in pricing, including leader pricing,
demand-based, odd/even, loss leader, bundled, and prestige
pricing.  Each approach may provide a different price in order to
serve a different goal.  Several different price approaches are
typically used over a product's life.  </i>

<p>2.  Is price art or science?  <i>Most marketers believe it is both
and effective pricing requires use of demand forecasts and
mathematical models along with good judgment and experience.</i>

<p>3.  Describe the interrelationships of price and the other
marketing mix variables.  <i>Price directly generates revenue;
however, price affects and is affected by product, place, and
promotion.  Marketers must take all the marketing mix variables
into consideration when setting prices.</i>



<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 9.1: The Price You See Is The Price You Pay - No Haggling</h4>

<p>     No-dicker car shopping has its advantages for many
consumers.  Some of your students may have had experience with
no-haggling at a local Saturn dealership.  If so, ask them to
share their observations of the process and make comparisons with
traditional car shopping.  One point to investigate is whether or
not there was any flexibility to the process.  For example, was
their room to negotiate over a discount for a trade-in.

<p>1.  Do you think that a no-negotiating pricing policy will appeal
to all consumers?  What types of consumers might not like this
price strategy?  <i>It is probably impossible to come up with any
marketing strategy that will appeal to all consumers, and that
includes pricing.  Price-conscious consumers might prefer to
negotiate, believing that they can dicker the price down.  Some
consumers enjoy the sport of negotiating; most do not!</i>

<p>2.  What is the risk for the car dealer who adopts the no-haggling pricing strategy?  <i>There is a threat from the Department
of Justice, as it considers whether or not no-haggling is
anticonsumer and in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act. 
Another risk is that the dealer will be undercut by the
competition, which will cost the dealer sales.  By adopting the
no-haggling strategy, dealers lock themselves into an inflexible
position that can backfire when price competition becomes
aggressive.</i>

<p>3.  Do you think no-negotiating pricing is anticonsumer?     
<i>Answers will vary.  It can be interpreted as being anticonsumer,
if it is also assumed that consumers can do better by
negotiating.  Others believe that consumers benefit because car
dealers always have the upper hand in the negotiations.</i>

<h4>Mini-Case 6.2: To Lease Or Not To Lease: Is There A Question?</h4>
 
<p>     With the price of new cars soaring, many consumers have
turned to leasing as an attractive alternative.  There is a high
probability that some of your students have leased cars.  Ask
them what they believe are the advantages of leasing.  Others
will probably feel very strongly that leasing is bad economics. 
This topic lends itself to a student debate.  Since there is a
considerable literature on automobile leasing, student teams can
research the pros and cons, then present their results to the
class.

<p>1.  Do you think leasing rather than purchasing a new automobile
is a good idea for all consumers?  <i>No idea can possibly be good
for all consumers.  It certainly is a good idea for some
consumers.</i>

<p>2.  Could automobile leasing be bad for the economy?  <i>It possibly
will have negative effects on new car production, because the
market will be flooded with cars coming off lease.  As a result,
the used car market will boom, both as a result of the stock of
good used cars and the high price of new cars.  This will reduce
demand for new cars.</i>

<p>3.  What are automakers and dealers going to do with all the cars
coming back from being leased?  <i>They are going to expand their
used car lots and profit from used car sales.</i>
                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     FlaskBake is a great new product.  Most busy consumers will
be very interested in this time saving product, once the price
becomes more competitive with traditional ovens.  Ask your
students whether they would be interested.  At what price would
they begin to be interested; at what price would they certainly
purchase the oven?

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>     Please verify all Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment <b>before</b> you make it.  No
guarantee of any Internet address or information can be made past
this <b><i>Manual's</b></i> publication date.  However, suggestions for <b>Using
the Internet</i> should provide ideas for ways that you can use the
Internet productively in your marketing class.  Be sure to
impress on your students the importance of professional behavior
on the Net, at all times.

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>
 
     <p>Students should learn to use the Internet to search for
information.  Since the Internet can be used to make product
comparisons, and price information is often included, students
can compare the relative advantages of several different search
tools for gathering product and price information.

<p>     Consider the example of a consumer who wants to find out
more about an Apple Macintosh computer.  This includes obtaining
information about product specifications, retail prices, and
purchase options.  Since this exercise seeks to compare how
different search engines locate "Apple Computer" links, it is not
designed for in-depth product or price comparisons, although that
can be added, if time permits.  

<p>     The assignment can be approached in several ways.  It can be
performed individually, with each student selecting one search
tool, then collaborating with others to compare tools. 
Alternately, each student can use two search tools and compare
them.  A dyad or small team of students can work together, using
several different search tools.  Two outcomes are expected: a
short written memo (describing how the assignment was conducted
and presenting the results) and a short oral presentation to the
class.  

<p>     Although six search tools are identified, there are many
others.  Personal experience with veronica suggests that it is
often "too busy" to offer much help.  If you prefer other search
engines, please use them.  Likewise, if you prefer to use a
different product for the search comparison, check it out
carefully before assigning it and if it is feasible, use it. 

<p><b>jughead</b>
<i><br>     Using Lynx, go to Internet Starting Points, find Inter-links
     or type in the URL
<br><a href="http://www.nova.edu/Inter-Links">http://www.nova.edu/Inter-Links</a>
<br>     * Search the Net
<br>     Search Goperspace
<br>     * Search the World Wide Web
<br>     jughead 
<br>     search:  Apple Computer
<br>     <b>Results:</b>  Links to 4 directories including Macintosh 
</i>

<p><b>Yahoo</b>
<i>
<br><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>
<br>     * Computers
<br>     * Hardware
<br>     PCs
<br>     * Macintosh
<br>     <b>Results:</b>  3 pages of links, several to Apple and Macintosh
</i>

<p><b>GNN</b>
<i><br><a href="http://nearnet.gnn.com">http://nearnet.gnn.com</a>
<br>     Business Pages
<br>     Alphabetical List
<br>     * Computing & Networking
<br>     * Hardware
