<br>     <b>Results:</b>  direct link to Maciintosh


<p>     Can high priced, prestige, luxury-type products be purchased
on the Internet?  Students can find out by performing a search
for various high priced products.  For example a WebCrawler
search for "turquoise jewelry" found 16 documents, from export
jewelry companies to the Smithsonian's Gem and Mineral
Collection.  Many luxury automobiles are offered on the Net, from
traditional to exotic models.

<p><i>     WebCrawler at <a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     Search:  turquoise jewelry
<br>     Search:  automobiles</i>

<p>     The <b>International Marketing Report</b> (page 269 of the text)
and in the <b>Some Teaching Tips</b> section in this chapter introduces
the use of the greenback as a worldwide currency.  Students can
learn more about currency exchanges and rates through a
WebCrawler search that links to Foreign Exchange Rates.  This
link allows the visitor to select a primary and secondary
currency to compare.  The rates are current, usually same day.

<p><i>     WebCrawler at <a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     Search:  currency exchange rates
<br>     0448  Foreign Exchange Rates </i>

<p>     To learn more about business cycles and consumer confidence,
students can investigate almost 60 links identified through a
WebCrawler search.  Follow the link to the BCI Series of US
Business Cycle Indicators and composite indexes.  

<p><i>     WebCrawler at <a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     Search:  consumer confidence
<br>     1000  BCI - PERSONAL INCOME AND CONSUMER ATTITUDES</i>


<p>     Although mass customization, agile production, and agile
marketing are relatively new terms, there are some links on the
Internet to search; more links will doubtlessly appear in the
future.  A search of mass customization found 13 documents,
several of which were usuable for identifying examples of how
this marketing tool is being used by a variety of businesses.

<p><i>     WebCrawler at <a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     Search:  mass customization     
<br>     1000  What is agile?                 </i>


<p>     Guest speakers who can share their experiences and
observations about pricing may be located through a local chapter
of the American Marketing Association.

<br><a href="http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks">http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks</a>


<p>     To learn more about Saturn and the consumer focus of this
company, visit the Saturn home page.  The Saturn Site contains a
welcome, information about the Saturn car line, the Saturn
Magazine, a list of retailers, and product brochures.  The
"Magazine" section has news about Saturn and letters from
customers.

<br><a href="http://www.saturncars.com ">http://www.saturncars.com </a>
          
<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 9.1</h4>


<p>     Comparison shopping can be performed in stores, using print
advertisements, and on the Internet.  However the comparisons are
made, students should draw conclusions about pricing practices
from their observations.  Their conclusions can be reported in
memo form and/or in a short oral presentation to the class. 
Comparison shopping is a routinely practiced part of collecting
competitive intelligence.  If you haven't debated the issue of
competitive intelligence versus competitive espionage previously,
it can be introduced at this point.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 9.2</h4>

<p>     Special event pricing is fairly common.  Students should be
familiar with higher than usual movie ticket prices for highly
promoted, eagerly anticipated motion pictures.  Likewise, concert
tours by popular bands use special event pricing.  A content
analysis of your local newspaper's entertainment listings may
provide prices for special events.  A comparison of prices for
these events should provide insight into the value that the
ticket sellers are placing on the event in anticipation of what
consumers are willing to pay.  Students typically are eager to
express their opinions about special event pricing, particularly
for events they dearly wish to attend but whose ticket prices are
beyond their budgets.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 9.3</h4>

<p>     Price discounting by age rarely causes complaints.  However,
when such discounting is withdrawn, consumers usually protest
quite vocally.  This was the case when airlines began charging
fares for small children rather than letting them sit on parent's
laps.  Safety concerns were the cause of the change, yet that did
little to soften the blow.  Students can investigate the use of
senior citizen discounts by friends and relatives who qualify for
such price benefits.  Are the age discounts popular?  Which types
of products are most often associated with senior discounts?


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 9.4 </h4>

<p>     Loss leaders are usually featured quite prominently in
weekly newspaper advertisements for local grocery stores.  Often
they are accompanied by cents off coupons.  Do loss leaders draw
consumers into stores?  Students can research this question by
constructing a simple survey and administering it to other
students, friends, and relatives.  Compile the results in class
to determine why consumers shop where they do, and whether or not
they pay attention to loss leaders in the print advertisements or
in the store.


<h3>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING </h3>


<h4>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>     One certainty about the U.S. dollar is that nothing is
certain.  It is being used worldwide as a currency standard, yet
it continues to lose strength against most major currencies.  At
the same time, it is strong compared to our major trading
partners, Mexico and Canada.  Because of the dollar's
fluctuations, students can get a better picture of its current
status by conducting research on the subject, either in the
library or on the Internet.</p>

<p>

