<head>
<title>  CHAPTER 5: MULTICULTURAL AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</title>  
 </head>                        
                       
<h1><center>CHAPTER 5</h1>
<h1> MULTICULTURAL AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</center></h1>

 <h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>

<p><b>1. Explain why marketers should develop cultural understanding.</b>  
The United States is the world's most culturally diverse society. 
Even if marketers have no intention of marketing internationally,
where cultural differences are expected, they face increasing
cultural diversity in their own domestic market.  As a result,
successful marketers develop cultural understanding and
sensitivity to cultural differences, and avoid cultural myopia
and the self-reference criteria.  Learning to market to
culturally diverse consumers increases the probability of being
able to satisfy them.  Marketers also are culture change agents
and must recognize how powerful marketing can be in speeding
culture change.


<p><b>2. Identify the three largest ethnic microcultures in the United
States.</b>   The three largest ethnic microcultures in the United
States are African-Americans, Hispanic-Americans, and Asian-Americans.  Even though consumers may be identified with one of
these groups and group members may share some consumer
preferences and behaviors, individual differences occur and they
may be quite profound.

<p><b>3. Discuss how and why businesses go international.</b>  Businesses
go international for a number of different reasons.  Some
businesses go international by accident, when faced with
unexpected foreign demand for their products.  Others follow key
customers abroad in order to service them.  The most common
reasons are to generate revenue, escape domestic competition,
prolong product life, receive tax incentives, and dispose of
discontinued goods.  The ways that businesses go international
are equally diverse.  Entry strategies include direct and
indirect exporting, joint ventures, wholly owned subsidiaries,
licensing, and franchising.

<p><b>4. Describe the environment of international marketing. </b>
Successful international marketers must consider environmental
factors when planning and implementing marketing activities. 
Among the most important environmental factors are culture,
political and legal factors, and economic factors, including
technology and level of economic development.


<p><b>5. Analyze the contemporary issues facing international
marketers.</b>  Three extremely important contemporary issues facing
international marketers involve the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA), European integration, and the emergence of the
Pacific Rim.  All of these issues have implications for free
trade and international competitiveness.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>
                 
<p>Some of us teach in schools that are culturally homogeneous;
others teach in schools whose students come from diverse national
and cultural backgrounds.  In the former situation, I have drawn
on the resources of the school's international student office to
find volunteers for cross-cultural interviews with marketing
students.  International students, or domestic students whose
parents are foreign-born, are valuable class resources for
providing insights about consumer activities in their ancestral
countries.       

<b>Conducting Cross-Cultural Interviews</b>

 <p><b>Marketing Application 5.5</b> (page 157 of the text) presents a
marketing problem that would benefit from information obtained
through cross-cultural interviews.  This process can be broadened
to learn more generally about a country and its consumers.  If
possible, arrange to match each of your students with an
international student so they can participate in a cross-cultural
interview.  As an ice breaker, I sponsor a cookies and punch
social in the school cafeteria for my class and the cooperating
international students.  To ensure that everyone clearly
understands the process, I spend several minutes introducing
myself, my class, and the purpose of the activity.  For the rest
of the time, students meet with their interview partner and begin
the interview process.  Often it can be completed in one session;
other times the interview extends to several meetings.  The
interviews are based on questions developed by the class.  An
example of the types of question categories generated by students
is provided on the next page.  This assignment requires that
students conduct the interview, analyze the results, identify one
good product opportunity for the country, and report on the
product opportunity orally to the class and in written memo form.

<p>If you have enough international students participating in
the cross-cultural interviews, you will find that several are
from the same country.  If so, have your students compare 
results from shared country interviews.  See if they can arrive
at a consensus good product opportunity based on an analysis of</p>

         <b><center>SUGGESTED CROSS-CULTURAL INTERVIEW QUESTIONS</center> </b>

<p>Categories of information that can be addressed in student-conducted cross-cultural interviews.

