<p>all the interviews from that country.  Focus class discussion on
the generalizability of these exploratory results.  Consider what
might be done next in order to gain greater confidence in the 
product opportunity match.  Identify information sources needed
to expand the analysis.  Analyze whether these consumer insights
might be used for products marketed in the U.S. domestic market.  

<b>Student Memo Writing</b>

<p>Students need to develop good communication skills. 
Marketing professionals frequently criticize students for their
communication deficiencies, and marketing educators for failing
to correct the deficiencies.

<p>The memorandum is the principal mechanism for transferring
important information within a business or organization.  Memos
are workhorses, essential to efficient information flow yet often
misused and abused.  You can help your students develop effective
memo writing skills by providing memo writing guidelines in
class, linking memo writing to marketing assignments, and giving
students constructive feedback for improving their writing
skills.

<p>Before making a memo writing assignment, I provide a list of
memo guidelines.  If you have other suggestions, add them to the
following list.

                   <p><b><center>Memo Guidelines</center></b>         

<ul>
<li>
Clearly state to yourself the purpose of the memo; what you
     hope to achieve by sending it 

<li>Know who you are sending the memo to, his or her level of
     responsibility, technical expertise, and knowledge of the
     memo's topic

<li>Consider who else might read the memo and whether this will
     affect what you say and how you say it

<li>Make an outline of the points you intend to make in the memo
     before you begin to write

<li>Use a heading that is standard for your business or
     organization.  This usually includes the date, name(s) of
     the recipient(s), your name, titles if commonly used, and
     the memo's subject.  A typical heading is </ul>                   
                                                                  
<p>               <b><center>M E M O R A N D U M</center></b>                               
                                                                 
<p> TO:                     
<p> FROM:                            
<p>SUBJECT:                          
<p>DATE: 

<p><ul>
<li>  
Because you are using a heading, it is not necessary to
     begin with a salutation (Dear :) nor have a signed
     ending (Sincerely,), but you should initial or sign
     your name after the FROM in the heading

<li>Strive for a memo that is clear, concise, complete, and
     short, no more than two pages long (if possible)

<li>Use bullets where appropriate, particularly to highlight key
     points and simplify reading

<li>Spell and grammar check your work, edit it carefully to
     ensure that your words are effective and accurate

<li>Because this is a business communication, avoid non-business
     content, small talk, pleasantries, repetition of unnecessary
     information

<li>If additional materials are enclosed with the memo, note
     this at the end of the memo by adding a separate, last line
     with the statement  </ul>                                         
                                                                 
<p><center>Enclosure:</center>                                                   
        
<ul>
<li>
If the memo concerns a highly controversial or sensitive
     topic, <u>if you have the time</u>, let it sit overnight, reread it
     the next morning, and make necessary corrections before you
     send it

<li>Establish a standard memo-naming system for each memo you
     send, so you can file and later retrieve the memo on disk or
     hard drive.  For example, a memo written to Jane Wong on
     11/2/96 is stored on an A: drive data disk as         
     A:/wong.mem   11/2/96                                        
     which identifies the recipient and the communication form
     memo = mem; the word processing program notes the date on
     which the memo was stored</ul>   

<b>Multicultural Marketing</b>

<p>Many marketers specialize in microcultural marketing,
concentrate mainly or solely on marketing to African-Americans,
Hispanic-Americans, Asian-Americans, or others.  Students can
learn about these marketing efforts by content analyzing print
advertisements in culturally targeted magazines.  Your school
library is a good place to begin.  Have student teams pick a
particular product category, for example hair products including
shampoo, conditioner, and coloring agents.  Next, locate same
date copies for three months (January, June, September) of two
magazines, one mass market and the other targeted.  For example,
students might select <i>Vanity Fair </i>and <i>Ebony</i>.  Content analyze the
advertisements for the selected products, looking at such things
as models, message, and activities pictured.  Evaluate the
results and report them to the class.

<p><b>International Marketing</b>

<p>Start your discussion of international marketing by relating
the topic to student experiences.  Compile a list of businesses
that appear to be American-owned, but are not, like Burger King,
Pillsbury, CBS Records, Bridgestone Tires, and Carnation.  Some
students may have worked for one of these companies, others have
bought their products.  There is a high probability that even if
your students never work abroad, they may work for a foreign-owned business in the United States, or work for an American
business that actively markets products internationally.       
 
<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

<p>I.   Explain why marketers should develop cultural understanding

<ul>
<li>    
Culture is how a society lives through its social
          institutions, values, beliefs, attitudes, customs,
          languages and preferences

<li> The United States is a multicultural society that
          presents challenges and opportunities for marketers
          because of its diversity

<li> The United States macroculture is composed of many
          smaller microcultures

<li>Even though Americans are highly diverse, they share
          core values

<li>Language is an important cultural force that unifies or
          separates communities

<li>Cultural sensitivity means viewing people from other
          cultures objectively, respectfully, and nonjudgmentally
<ol>
<li>
Growing cultural diversity in the United States
               revenues greater cultural sensitivity

<li>Marketers often proceed through states of cultural
               perception that include ignorance, awareness,
               knowledge, and understanding

<li>Marketers are culture change agents, bringing
               products into a society and in the process,
               influencing its culture</ol></ul>



<p>II.  Identify the three largest ethnic microcultures in the
     United States
<ul>
<li>
Marketers recognize the value of targeting ethnic
          microcultures, particularly the three largest
<li> African-Americans are currently the largest
          microculture in the United States
<li>Hispanic-Americans comprise the most rapidly growing
          American microculture
<li>Asian-Americans tend to be the most highly educated of
          the microcultures</ul>


<p>III. Discuss why and how businesses go international
<ul>
<li>
Many businesses go international in order to generate
          revenue, escape domestic competition, prolong product
          life, receive tax incentives, or dispose of
          discontinued surplus merchandise

<li>Some businesses become international marketers by
          accident, others follow a major customer abroad

<li>There are many different sources of information that
          provide valuable assistance to businesses considering
          going international including the U.S. Department of
          Commerce, state and world trade offices</ul>


<p>IV.  Describe the environment of international marketing    
<ul>
<li>
 Marketers must evaluate many environmental factors
          before going international, including
 <ol>
<li>
Culture factors
<li>Political and legal factors
<li>Economic factors including market technology and
               level of economic development  </ol>
 <li> Entry strategies are how a company goes international
 <ol>
<li>
Entry barriers stop or slow entry of foreign
               products into a market
<li>Entry alternatives include direct and indirect
               exporting, joint ventures, direct ownership,
               franchising and licensing
<li>Marketing mix strategies require decisions about
          standardization and how each of the marketing tools
          will be used in a market</ol></ul>

<p>V.   Analyze the contemporary issues facing international
     marketers
<ul>
<li>
The North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) will
          present many marketing opportunities and challenges for
          both the members (the United States, Mexico, and
          Canada), as well as competitors from other countries
<li>European integration establishes a free trade zone for
          its member countries

<li> Some marketing experts expect the 21st Century to be
          dominated by the activities of countries in the 
          Pacific Rim, including Japan, China, the Philippines,
          Malaysia, and city-states Hong Kong and Singapore</ul>
   
       
<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

 <h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  What are the three largest ethnic microcultures in the United
States?  <i>African-Americans, Hispanic-Americans, and Asian-Americans.</i>

<p>2.  What is the difference between a macroculture and a
microculture?  <i>In the United States, the macroculture is the
culture of the entire society, over 262 million people;
microcultures are homogeneous segments within the macroculture
that are smaller in numbers but still important influences on
society and marketing.</i> 

<p>3.  Explain what is meant by the term multicultural society.<i> A
multicultural society is heterogenous, composed of many different
cultures.  For example, the United States, the world's most
culturally diverse country, is made up of such important
microcultures as African-Americans, Hispanic-Americans, and
Asian-Americans, as well as many other definable groups.</i>

<p>4.  What are American core values?  Explain how they are used in
describing a nation.  <i>Core values are the things that a society
holds in high esteem, for example core values that are generally
associated with Americans include achievement and success,
efficiency and practicality, progress, freedom, and
individualism.  They are important to understand because values
often provide insights into how people will respond to objects,
people, and situations, as well as marketing activities.</i>

<p>5.  Compare and contrast the terms homogeneous and heterogeneous.
<i>When referring to a population like Japan's, we say that it is
culturally extremely homogeneous, which means that the Japanese
people are more culturally alike than different, they share many
values, outlooks, and behaviors.  On the other hand, the
population in the United States is highly heterogeneous, which
means that there is great cultural diversity and many different
values, outlooks, and behaviors.</i> 

<p>6.  Do you think body language is important in marketing? 
Explain.  <i>Yes.  It is estimated that 60 percent of all
communication is nonverbal.  Body language can affect business
interactions and marketing success.</i>

<p>7.  Can cultural sensitivity be overdone?  Might it threaten the
unity of the United States if immigrants don't assimilate?  
<i>Opinions will vary, but most people agree that at the least,
linguistic homogeneity is essential.  If people cannot share a
language, it is problematic whether they can successfully share
much else.  Linguistic assimilation is probably critical to long
term survival as a united nation.</i>

<p>8.  Are marketers cultural change agents?  Could this be the case
even in the United States?  Explain. <i> Absolutely, and it
certainly happens in the United States with marketers introducing
new products to existing or new markets.  This is the case with
the introduction of new products from abroad, as well as products
that incorporate new technologies.  For example, the marketing of
microwave ovens changed how many consumers viewed cooking.  At
one time, traditional expectations for women held that they spent
a considerable part of their time over a hot stove, cooking
family meals.  Today, with the microwave and other labor saving
devices, home cooked often means home assembled, microwaving many
ingredients in minutes, as opposed to hours with a traditional
stove and oven.</i>

<p>9.  How are recent immigrants to the United States contributing
to international marketing?  <i>Cultural diversity in the American
workforce leads to marketing opportunities.  Workers with
international contacts can be helpful in facilitating
international marketing activities for their employers.</i>           
                        
<p>10.  Why do businesses go international?  Describe the important
factors a marketer must consider when going international and
selecting target markets.  <i>Often businesses go international by
accident or to follow a key customer.  They seek international
markets to generate revenue, escape domestic competition, prolong
product life, receive tax incentives, or dispose of discontinued
surplus merchandise.  Factors to be considered include culture
factors, political and legal factors, and economic factors
including market technology and economic development. </i>


<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 5.1</h4> 

<p>1.  Compare and contrast the U.S. macro- with the principal U.S.
and microcultures.  <i>The macroculture is the entire society of
over 262 million people; the microcultures are segments within
the macroculture.  Approximately 30 million are African-Americans, 25 million are Hispanic-Americans, and 9 million are
Asian-American.</i>

<p>2.  What is the self-reference criterion and why is it important? 
<i>This refers to the practice of judging other cultures by
comparison to your own, which tends to lead to cultural bias
which undermines the ability to make rational, objective
decisions.</i>
 
<p>3.  Why is language an important element in culture?  <i>Language is
an extremely strong force that unifies or separates a culture.</i>  

<h4>Check Your Understanding 5.2 </h4>

<p>1.  Define the term cultural sensitivity and explain its
importance to marketers in a multicultural society.  <i>This means
viewing people from other cultures objectively, respectfully, and
nonjudgmentally.  Failure to be respectful of other cultures can
lead to misunderstandings and for marketers, failure to sell
their products.</i>

<p>2.  Are marketers cultural change agents?  Explain your answer. 
<i>Yes, by introducing new products to a market, marketers can
influence culture. </i>

<p>3.  Identify the largest ethnic microcultures in the United
States and describe some of their characteristics.  <i>These are
<u>generalizations</u> and do not represent all members of an ethnic
microculture.  Several recent studies indicate that African-Americans have a high preference for products made in the United
States, are very mindful of product quality and will select a
store based on the quality of its products, and watch more
television than the other two major microcultures.  Fewer
Hispanic-Americans have bank accounts than the other two
microcultures; they are quality-minded, and listen more to radio. 
Asian-Americans are the most highly educated micro-culture, they
are less apt to prefer products made in the United States, have
the highest incidence of bank accounts and watch the least
television.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 5.3</h4> 

<p>1.  Why should businesses consider going international? <i> No
business should consider going international unless it can
profit.  Otherwise, businesses become international marketers by
accident, to follow an important customer, to avoid competition
in the domestic market, to receive tax incentives, prolong
product life, or to dispose of discontinued surplus merchandise.</i> 

<p>2.  What kind of help can businesses get in going abroad?  <i>Many
different organizations and agencies are interested in helping
businesses market abroad.  These include the United States
Department of Commerce, state and world trade organizations, the
Department of Agriculture, and others.</i>
            
<p>3.  What is the Triad?  What are the emerging nations? <i> The Triad
are the major trading blocks of North America (the United States,
Canada, and Mexico), Europe (the integrated states), and Japan,
which dominates many emerging markets in the Pacific Rim. 
Emerging nations are markets that are growing and represent great
potential, including China, Thailand, Indonesia, the Philippines,
India, some countries in Eastern Europe, and some countries in
Latin and South America.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 5.4</h4>

<p>1.  Is international marketing more complex than domestic
marketing? <i> Yes, it is NOT domestic marketing in another country. 
Many additional factors must be considered in each international
market entered.  An additional layer of complexity is added with
each country.</i>

2.  What are some common barriers to entry?   <i>Barriers to entry
fall into two categories: tariffs, taxes on selected imports, and
non-tariff barriers, such as quotas, exchange controls, local
content laws, and embargoes.</i>

<p>3.  What is global marketing?  <i>Global marketing assumes that all
markets are the same, wherever they are located.  It assumes that
one product offer will be accepted anywhere, promotions can be
the same worldwide, and products are priced and distributed
without consideration of local cultures, political systems,
economies, and the like.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 5.5</h4>

<p>1.  Discuss different product alternatives that can be offered to
international markets.  <i>A straight product extension means that
the same product offered in a domestic market is marketed abroad
unchanged.  It is more likely that a product adaptation will be
required.  For less developed markets, some products have to be
simplified; this is backward invention.  Forward invention means
making product more technically sophisticated to suit a market's
requirements.</i>
 
<p>2.  Why is pricing more complex in international markets? <i>More
elements must be considered in pricing products internationally
than when pricing domestically.  For example, currency
fluctuations, distribution costs, risk, and the costs of
competition must be compensated for in order to reach
profitability.</i>

<p>3.  Describe the contemporary issues concerning international
marketing.  <i>Three important contemporary issues facing marketers
are the effects on international trade of the North American Free
Trade Agreement (NAFTA), European integration, and the emergence
of aggressive competition from nations in the Pacific Rim.</i>

<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 5.1:  Pier 1: Retailer of Global Goods Goes  International  </h4>  
                         
<p>     Many of your students will be familiar with Pier 1 or
similar importers.  Have them critique the company's plans to
offer American goods in Asian stores.  What goods would they
recommend that Pier 1 offer in its Asian stores?  Similarly,
after reading this chapter and drawing from their own
experiences, what do they think of the idea of offering the same
inventory that sells well to Cuban-Americans and other Latinos in
Puerto Rico to other Latin and South American countries?  

<p>1.  What do you think of Pier 1's plans?  Is their strategy an
example of "go global, think local?"<i> Answers will vary, but
probably the most common response is that the retailer is "right
on target."  This is a very good example of cultural good sense
that should translate into profitability and marketing success.</i>

<p>2.  Would you recommend that Pier 1 find a local partner in the
countries where it plans to open stores?  Explain your answer. 
Probably they should.  <i>Again, answers will vary.  However,
overall, finding joint venture partners in the various markets
Pier 1 seeks to enter should make their entry easier.  While they
will share the profits, they will also share the risks.</i>

<p>3.  Is the plan to market to Puerto Rico the same way Pier 1
markets to Florida a good one?  Explain. <i> Unless the company has
performed extensive market research to determine that this is a
reasonable approach, it appears on the surface to be quite risky. 
Again, unless they have solid information to support their
contention about the similarity of these markets, they run a
significant risk of misreading consumers and not doing a good job
of predicting local tastes and what will sell.</i>

<h4>Mini-Case 5.2: Joint Ventures at Home and Abroad</h4>
 
 <p>    Ask your students if they are working for or have worked for
a company that joint ventures?  Many probably do but don't
realize it.  Examples of domestic joint venture partners are
increasing, particularly in high technology fields.  In part,
this reflects the added risks and costs associated with high tech
fields.  Point out some recent joint ventures and ask students
what each partner can bring to the table, what unique
competencies they contribute, and the risks inherent in any
partnership.

<p>1.  What do you think of joint ventures?  What are the benefits
and shortcomings?  <i>Generally, a good joint venture partnership
can be very profitable because it shares expertise and risk, as
well as capital.  However, the downside occurs when joint venture
partners disagree or don't meet the expectations of the other. 
Another problem involves sharing profits, since profits must be
shared in a joint venture. </i>

<p>2.  What can a catalog company gain from forming a joint venture
partnership with a magazine targeted to African-American women?
<i>Expertise and market penetration are two reasonable expectations
for the partnership.</i>  

<p>3.  What can AT&T gain from having joint venture partners in
China?  <i> AT&T gains a foothold in the largest consumer market in
the world, over one billion people!  They gain contacts and
market knowledge; the Chinese gain access to technology and
expertise.  AT&T should benefit from reducing some risk, but 
considerable risk remains even with joint venture partners.  See
this chapter's What Do You Think? for more China information.</i>
                                
<h3> WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

 <p>    China is a mystery and a magnet for many Americans.  Some
people assume China can make the transition from the last major
Communist nation to a free market economy without bloodshed.  Ask
your students for their opinions on this question.  International
students from China or students of Chinese descent may be able to
add a more personal perspective to this problem.  An Internet
activity is included in this chapter that provides a source for
information about China that can complement class discussion.  

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>     Although Internet discussion groups can be time consuming,
there still are many benefits to joining.  You can make contacts 
through these lists with marketing instructors at other
universities as well as professionals in the United States and
abroad.  You may find marketing educators from other countries
who are interested in having their students cooperate in cross-cultural interviews on the Internet.  This has worked quite
successfully for some instructors.  Other international contacts
can provide insights into how marketing works in their countries. 
For list information, visit the American Marketing Association
Home Page at http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks.  Access The List of
Lists, where you'll find information about such marketing
discussion groups as Market-L, MKTSEG, and MKTTEACH.

<p>     One of the most intriguing characteristics of the Internet
is that many different paths lead to the same place.  For
example, if you wish to access a federal government source such
as the Department of Commerce's Census Bureau, you can get there
by taking any of the following paths, and many others, as well. <br>
<br>
<a href="http://www.yahoo.com"> http://www.yahoo.com</a>       Search for Government<br>
<a href="http://www.census.gov">http://www.census.gov </a>    Census Home Page<br>
