 <br>                                                  
     If one path is blocked, try another.  When it was announced
that the gopher site for the U.S. Census Bureau through 
http://gopher.census.gov would be disconnected, instructions were
given on how to download Lynx from the University of Kansas as
visitors with Lynx (or a graphical browser) could access the
Bureau by http://www.census.gov.  When a site changes its
address, a connecting link to the new address usually is kept
active for a period of time so visitors can find the new site. 
Savvy Internet visitors keep their own address book with
bookmarks either in their browser or separately on a data disk or
hard copy.

 <p>    Remember to verify Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment before you make it.  Stress
Net-etiquette with each student assignment.

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>     Information about ethnic micro-cultures and population 
trends, and some product usage information, can be obtained
through the United States Census Bureau.  The data on computer
usage raise troubling questions about access to technology by all
microcultures.  The directory Population Components of Change has
files on population trends for Whites, Blacks, Asians, and
Hispanics, as well as groupings within these segments.  These
data clearly show where population growth is occurring.  Direct
students to the United States Department of Commerce, Bureau of
the Census, by the path<br>
