<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>

<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 5.1</h4>

<p>     Given the cultural diversity in the United States, it might
be difficult to convince someone that Americans share many core
values.  However, looking at the list of American core values
shown in Figure 5.1 (page 141 of the text), it also might be
difficult to imagine anyone not agreeing with most, if not all of
these values.  Use the print advertisements that students bring
to class as a point of departure for a discussion and debate of
core values and the question Do these core values hold true of
all Americans?  If there is a consensus, are certain of the
values more important than others?  

<p>     If your class is large enough, 25 to 30 students or more,
test the question of relative importance (also called rank) among
your students and possibly, extend the sample to their families
or other students.  Prepare a simple survey for your students (an
example is provided on the next page) by listing each of the 11
values.  Ask students to assign a numerical value that signifies
the personal importance of each value on the blank line beside
the value.  One demographic question, about gender, is also
included on the sample survey.  

<p>     If students tabulate the surveys, clearly explain the
tabulation process.  Sort all male-completed surveys into one
pile; female-completed surveys into a second pile.  Add together
all male importance scores for each value, starting with
Achievement and Success.  Divide the sum by the total number of
male surveys.  For example, if there are 30 males and their total
Achievement and Success score is 163, 163/30 = 5.433.  Tabulate
all male scores and all female scores, then calculate combined
scores for each value.  A sample tabulation form students can use
follows the sample survey.  

<p>     Have student teams analyze the results and identify the five
most important values for each category.  These are the values
with the five lowest total scores.  What inferences can be drawn
about the importance of the values to both genders?  Are there    

            <b><center>SURVEY OF THE IMPORTANCE OF CORE VALUES</center> </b>          
           
<p>     This survey is designed to find out how important each of
the following values is to YOU.  Please read the list and
carefully consider each value.  How important is it in your life? 
Identify the importance by assigning a number to each value using
the scale: <b># 1 = most important - to - #11 = least important </b>
<u>Do not leave any value blank</u>.   Use each number (1 through 11)
only once.  Do not sign your name or otherwise identify yourself
on this survey.  Thank you.
