<p>any differences?  Can the results be generalized?  If they could
be generalized, how might a marketer apply the consumer insights? 
Relate this to the print advertisements used in class.  If
differences exist between males and females on the importance of
the values, how might this information be used in marketing?  Ask
students to identify other variables that can influence value
importance, for example age, ethnic background, education, and
occupation.  Are these important segmentation variables?          
 

<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 5.2 </h4>                                       

<p>     While it is relatively easy to identify ethnic influences on
American eating habits, it is less obvious which American foods
have been successfully exported.  Students should be able to name
such well-known global foods as Coke, hamburgers, and french
fries; franchises such as KFC and McDonald's.  Ask your
international students or any students who have traveled abroad
what American foods are found in other countries and whether or
not they taste the same.  Often, they do not.  What does this
indicate? 


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 5.3</h4>

<p>     You can assign this Application on the Internet.  See Using
the Internet in this chapter for directions.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 5.4 </h4>

<p>     You can assign this Application on the Internet.  See Using
the Internet in this chapter for directions.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 5.5 </h4>

<p>     Cross-cultural interviews are discussed at length
previously.  You can assign cross-cultural interviews on the
Internet, see Using the Internet in this chapter for directions.

<h3>CHAPTER  5: CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>

<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 5.1</h4>

<p>     Barbie dolls are tailored to market characteristics.  This
is a customization or adapted marketing strategy that recognizes
an opportunity in ethnic marketing.  Students can learn more
about ethnic Barbies by visiting local toy stores when they are
fully stocked with Christmas toys.  Observe whether or not there
are any ethnic Barbies.  Do they reflect the ethnic composition
of your area?  Students can find information about the ethnic
composition of your city from the local government, Chamber of
Commerce, or by visiting the Census Bureau, Population Data and
Social and Demographic Data on the Internet (see Using the
Internet in this chapter).  If your area is highly multicultural,
is this diversity reflected in the availability of ethnic
Barbies?  


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 5.2</h4>

<p>     Contact the local Small Business Development Center, a World
Trade Center, state agency or other organization that promotes
international business and ask for help in identifying a local
small business that is marketing internationally.  With their
help, ask a small business international marketer to speak to
your class about his or her experiences abroad.  Addresses of
local Small Business Administration offices are in the government
section of most local telephone directories and on the Internet
(see Using the Internet in this chapter).


<h3>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h3>

<p>     The full text of the NAFTA Agreement can be found on the
Internet (see <b>Using the Internet</b> in this chapter).  Some students
in your class have probably visited Canada or Mexico; others may
have relatives living in these countries.  Ask what they have
observed about American products offered in these countries.  How
well do consumers accept products from the United States?<p>

