<head>
<title>CHAPTER 6: MARKETING RESEARCH AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY</title>
</head>

<h1><center>CHAPTER 6</h1>
<h1> MARKETING RESEARCH AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY</center></h1>

<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>

<p><b>1. Explain why information is so important to marketers.</b>
Marketers need information in order to be able to make good
marketing decisions.  Good information used wisely can help
marketers recognize and take advantage of windows of opportunity,
avoid threats, and achieve competitive advantage.  In order to be
usable, information must be current, reliable, suitable,
sufficient, affordable, and available.  The information
revolution, fueled by advances in computer technology, is
affecting the way marketers collect and use information.  While
there are many benefits to the information revolution,
information overload and technology overkill are among its
hazards.


<p><b>2. Understand that all marketers need information.</b>  Marketing is
information-intensive.  Marketers must have information to make
good decisions involving the marketing mix variables, product,
price, place, and promotion.  They use both descriptive and
prescriptive information.  Marketers must manage information
effectively in order to make decisions that satisfy consumers and
achieve business goals.


<p><b>3. Describe a marketing information system (MIS) and explain how
it works.</b>  A marketing information system (MIS) is an organized,
systematic process designed to help marketers effectively manage
and use information.  Contemporary MIS systems integrate three
sets of interrelated activities: information collection,
information analysis, and information dissemination.  Most MIS
systems rely heavily on computers to aid in these activities.  
Some use sophisticated computer-based systems called Marketing
Decision Support Systems (MDSS) that rely on highly complex
statistical programs to suggest answers to specific marketing
problems.

<p><b>4. Identify the steps in marketing research.</b>  Marketing research,
according to the American Marketing Association, links the
consumer, customer, and public to the marketer through
information .  Marketing research is a systematic process for
establishing that link and facilitating the use of information in
making marketing decisions.  Research should be conducted
whenever information is needed.  It is used in all aspects of
marketing activities.  Marketing research is performed by
individuals and groups, in small, mid-size, and large businesses,
as well as by businesses whose sole mission is to conduct
research and sell the results.  Marketing research generally
follows a prescribed set of steps.  Marketers strive to perform
research that is valid, reliable, and generalizable.


<p><b>5. Discuss how recent advances in information technology are
pushing marketing in new directions.</b>  In the last 30 years, the
information revolution has accelerated, fueled in great part by
advances in computer technology.  This is affecting marketing, as
well as society and business generally.  Electronic measuring
devices, facsimile machines, virtual reality, and the Internet
are just some examples of new technologies that are changing the
ways that marketing activities are conducted.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>We are living in an information age: We are part of an
information revolution.  Information travels around the world in
seconds on the Internet, by telephone and fax machine, and
through satellite television transmission.  The challenge for
marketers is to effectively use information in making marketing
decisions and solving marketing problems.  This chapter presents
some hands-on opportunities for students to see for themselves
how information and the computer are affecting marketers and
marketing activities.  Introduce this topic by asking students to
consider how their daily lives are affected by computers and the
information they transmit.  For example, many cities use
computers to analyze highway traffic flow information and control
traffic light changes.  People often make clothing decisions
based on weather information transmitted by satellites, analyzed
by computers, and relayed on television.  Consumers rarely
experience product stockouts because scanner data signal when
product inventory is approaching the reorder point.</p>

<p><b>Information and Competitive Advantage</b></p>

<p>Begin the discussion of marketing research and information
technology with the question that introduces the chapter (on page
171 of the text), "How can information be used by marketers to
gain competitive advantage?"   Have student teams select a
national business that is the acknowledged market leader in its
industry, such as McDonald's, Wal-Mart, or Microsoft.  Using the
Information Needs of Marketing Managers from Figure 6.2 (page 175
of the text), ask each team to </p>

<ul>
<li> relate several of the ranked items specifically to their selected business,
<li> suggest where and how needed information can be obtained,
<li> explain how it relates to competitive advantage.
</ul>

<p>For example, it is reasonable to assume that McDonald's
marketing managers use information to "identify, anticipate, and
respond to competitors" (rank 6 of the Main Information Needs in
Figure 6.2).  Therefore, McDonald's needs competitive
intelligence, information obtained by marketing researchers who
systematically and objectively evaluate the competitions'</p>

<ul>
<li> product (taste the food, experience the service)
<li> prices (compare product prices)
<li> place (observe convenience, cleanliness)
<li> promotion (look for sales promotions, observe advertising)
</ul>

<p>McDonald's own customers can be surveyed to determine if
they eat at competitors and if they do, how these consumers
compare the competition to McDonald's.  Information about the
competition is critical to McDonald's continued success because
McDonald's can learn what the competition is doing right, then
improve on it.  By determining if the competition poses a threat,
McDonald's can respond and protect their competitive advantage.</p>

<p>Once each team has completed their analysis, have them draft
a memo reporting their results, then present their analysis to
the class.  As a group, analyze whether or not each business
appears to be using information effectively.</p>

<b><p>International Marketing Information Needs</b></p>
 
<p>Introduce the topic of the information needs of
international marketers by referring to the chapter opening
story.  Have students consider the information needs facing
Isabelle Ono in determining whether or not Japan is a good market
for her company's health foods.  Students can identify questions
that Isabelle must answer before proceeding with the product
market match decision.  For example, a critical question that
must be answered is whether the concern for eating healthy food 
expressed by government officials and health researchers is
shared by consumers.  It is essential to forecast consumer
demand.  Consumers must buy enough of Isabelle's product for her
company to profit.  If demand is very weak and cannot be
stimulated, entering the market could be a disaster.  Ask
students how consumer demand can be evaluated.  What information
must Isabell have and how can it be obtained?</p>

<b><p>Marketing Tasks Performed Using Computers</b></p>

<p>Figure 6.1 (page 174 of the text) identifies some marketing
tasks performed using computers.  In order to develop a more
thorough understanding of how computers are affecting marketing
activities, ask student teams to investigate a task from Figure
6.1 that they find particularly interesting or applicable to
their career interests.  For example, students specializing in
promotions and advertising should investigate desktop publishing,
advertising design and layout, or media scheduling using computer
technology; students interested in distribution should look at
inventory control and logistics.  They can begin their research
by using secondary sources, learning about the technology from
articles in journals and trade publications.  This effort can be
extended to include primary research, first person interviews
with professionals using the technology.  If the latter approach
is used, interview subjects often can be identified by contacting
local professional groups and asking their assistance. 
Alternately, a professional may discuss the topic in class. 
Guest speakers can add an exciting practical dimensions to class
discussions, particularly if they demonstrate an applied
technology, such as advertising design, desktop publishing,
inventory control, or database management.</p>

<b><p>Information Collection Frequency</b></p>

<p>Personal use consumers, like businesses and marketers, have
different information needs.  Some information is collected
routinely; other information is collected once or only rarely. 
Students can compare their personal information needs to
marketing information needs as presented in Figure 6.3 (page 177
of the text).  Fold a sheet of paper vertically into three equal
columns.  Label the columns "Routine", "Periodic", and
"Nonroutine" respectively.  In the "Routine" section, identify
routine information needs, such as daily weather and traffic
reports, daily television programming, weekly specials at the
grocery store, and weekend movie schedules.  Do the same for the
other columns, then identify sources for the information.</p>

<p>Generally, information collected routinely involves an
almost effortless, habitual information search.  Have students
contrast this with "Nonroutine" information search.  Make the
point that marketers work very hard to provide consumers with
information that they can use to make purchase decisions.  Survey
students to determine if any have identified product advertising
as a source of information.  Students often don't associate
advertising with information, yet this is a key advertising
function.</p>

<p>Many people view the Internet as the ultimate information
source.  It is a source for routine information, such as traffic
reports on Los Angeles freeways, the time of day, the weather
forecast, or spot currency exchange rates.  The Internet can be
used to collect information for periodic needs, like product
comparison shopping for computer hardware, automobiles, or real
estate.  It provides access to information that personal use
consumers need infrequently or only once.  For a complementary
activity, see this chapter's Using the Internet.</p>

<b><p>Marketing Research</p></b>

<p>Marketing research, like all research, comes in many forms
and is designed to serve many purposes.  It is important to
stress that marketing research is the broadest type of research
in marketing because it can include any aspect of marketing
activity.  Other types of research, for example consumer
research, advertising research, or market research, focus
narrowly on a specific area of marketing interest, in this case,
consumers, advertising, or markets.</p>

<p>Most marketing research is applied research designed to
transfer technology or apply concepts developed through empirical
research.  Marketing research can be formal, involving highly
structured activities, many researchers, and considerable time
and expense.  It can also be informal, involving one or several
researchers quickly seeking answers to specific, applied
marketing problems.  Some research is exploratory, designed to
collect additional information or explore approaches that can be
used in the next research stage.  Other research is descriptive,
describing markets and consumers, and developing summary
statistics.  Causal research seeks to develop and test
relationships between variables, while predictive research seeks
to predict relationships and forecast trends.</p>

<p>It is important for students to become familiar with the
steps of marketing research.  Although the names given these
steps and the number of steps identified may vary, there is no
exception to the demand for research that is systematic,
organized, and objective.  The best way to teach these steps is
to have students experience them.  Marketing Application 6.3
(page 191 of the text), a mini-research project that involves a
class survey, can be used for this purpose.  Review the steps in
marketing research (page 186 of the text) and relate them to the
task in this Application.</p>

<b><p>The Mystery Shopper</b></p>
     
<p>Another approach to teaching about marketing research is to
have students engage in an applied observational research
activity such as becoming mystery shoppers.  This is a technique
often used by marketing professionals to collect competitive
intelligence.  It is particularly useful where published data are
not available or for new product introductions (Czepiec 1983). 
It is very common in services, particularly banks and fast food
restaurants, and grocery stores.</p>

<p>This is an opportunity for students to develop applied
research skills like those routinely used by marketing
professionals.  Ask students to form teams or small groups.  Each
team or group selects a different tangible good that lends itself
to comparison shopping in multiple retail outlets.  Ideally, it
should be a product that students are interested in purchasing or
have recently purchased, or a product about which students are
knowledgeable.  For example, steel belted radial tires, a
computer fax modem, color television set, or compact disc player.</p>

<p>Refer to the marketing research steps (page 186 of the text)
and ask students to work together to</p>

<ul>
<li> Identify the problem - a statement of the research question
     which, in this case, relates to determining competitive
     pricing strategies for the same product at five different
     retail outlets
<li> Develop a plan - how students will make their price
     comparisons, including developing a standard reporting form
     that each student can use to analyze a retailer and identify
     product prices
<li> Execute the plan - conduct the price comparisons in five
     different stores within a one-week period
<li> Analyze and interpret the results - while a statistical
     comparison is not appropriate to this research, a
     descriptive analysis should identify price differences and 
     the price strategies each retailer is following
<li> Report findings and recommendations - using memo form, each
     reports their analysis and makes a recommendation.  Have the
     teams imagine that they are suggesting competitive product
     pricing strategies that can be used by a hypothetical
     marketer who is entering the market and will compete
     directly with the five existing retailers
</ul>
 
<p>You might ask students what products they "shop around" for
in order to get the best price.  These examples can form
conceptual anchors for the mystery shopper exercise.  For
example, I had one student volunteer that her hands were very
sensitive to soap, so there was one brand that she purchased
exclusively.  Because this brand was expensive, she routinely
comparison shopped for it.  As a result, she told us to the
penny, the price of the soap at a major grocery chain, an
independent grocery, a discount club, a mass merchandise
discounter, and a chain drug store!</p>

<p>In order to ensure some standardization between teams, work
as a class to establish common data categories.  Data to collect
should include (but not be limited to)</p>

<ul>
<li> Store name
<li> Type of store (descriptive categories such as catalog,
     department, discounter, specialty, grocery, supermarket,
     category killer, club, or other)
<li> Type of customer (descriptive categories such as bargain
     hunters, quality shoppers, value conscious, upper class)
<li> Product (including brand name, model, color, size, and other
     important features)
<li> Price (full price, discounted price, sale price)
<li> Competing products (description of directly competitive
     products also offered, including prices and features)
<li> Other comments
</ul>

<p>At the conclusion of the research, ask each team to present
their findings to the class.  These research results often
provoke interesting class discussions about the pricing
strategies of different retailers.</p>

<b><p>A Class Focus Group</b></p>

<p>Focus groups are the most widely used form of exploratory
research (Solomon 1994).  They are used to determine consumer
feelings about products through directed group interviews with 5
to 9 consumers.  The participants are usually seated around a
conference table in a specially designed room that has hidden
recorders and video cameras.  A trained focus group leader guides
the group through a directed discussion.  Focus group
participants usually have some involvement with the product
category.  For example, when a major contact lens producer was
preparing to introduce a revolutionary (at that time) innovation,
disposable contact lenses, focus groups were held with people 
already wearing contacts.  Video tapes of the focus groups
revealed that lens wearers' major complaint was cleaning them. 
This theme was repeated consistently across groups.  Consumers
hated using cleaning solutions, day after day.  This consumer
insight was integrated into a highly successful advertising
campaign that stressed how the best solution to lens cleaning was
"no solution", meaning the manufacturer's disposable lenses!</p>

<p>Focus groups are used in most product categories.  They have
even been used with motion pictures, where groups of consumers
are invited into a special screening room to preview a soon-to-be
released motion picture.  As viewers watch the film, their
responses are observed and sometimes recorded.  Afterwards, they
participate in a focus group discussion that gauges their
response to the film.  Movies have been recut because of focus
group responses.  In some recent focus groups, a computer
analysis of recorded voices has been used to reveal more of what
consumers are really thinking (Hoeffel 1994).</p>

<p>Introduce the topic of focus group research to your class
and ask for six to eight student volunteers to participate in a
focus group study.  Set up a scenario for the focus group using a
product that students know and find interesting.  For example,
previous successfully used topics include a popular movie, a new
non-alcoholic beer, and student class registration procedures. 
These focus groups respectively sought student opinions about the
controversial movie ending (what should it have been?), the
appeal of the new non-alcoholic beer (will students buy it?), and
pre-registration (what can be changed to make it easier?).  Avoid
topics that polarize or are too controversial.</p>

<p>With the participant/volunteers out of the room, ask the
remaining students (the observers) to brainstorm the types of
questions that the focus group should explore.  Assemble 10 to 15
usable questions, which you will probably need to edit.  Explain
to the student observers that their assignment during the focus
group interview will be to observe, listen carefully to what is
said, and write short statements about their observations.</p>

<p>At the next class meeting, arrange the room so that you have
space in the front for the focus group volunteers to sit as a
group, preferably turned so they are not directly facing the rest
of the class.  This prevents interactions and distractions. 
Introduce the topic and explain that you are seeking their
opinions, so no answer is "right."  Work through the questions,
allow each student ample time to comment, and encourage
discussion.  Do not allow any student to dominate or disrupt. 
Complete as many questions as you can, allowing sufficient time
to wrap up the focus group, thank all participants, and collect
the observers' written comments at the end.</p>

<p>At the next class meeting, ask students to identify some of
the strengths and weaknesses of this type of marketing research. 
In particular, identify such problems as subjectivity, low
numbers, and generalizability; such advantages as greater
willingness to express opinions in a group and stimulating group
interactions.  Describe some of the observers' written comments
(without identifying any observer by name) and ask for comments
on them.  Guide the discussion so that it stays focused on the
marketing applications of this type of exploratory research.</p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<i><b><p>References</p></b>
<p>Czepiec, Helena (1983), "The Mystery Shopper Technique as an
     Experiential Exercise to Teach Undergraduate Marketing
     Principles," <i>Journal of Marketing Education</i> (Spring): 33-36.</p>

<p>Solomon, Michael R. (1994), Consumer Behavior, Second
     Edition, Needham Heights, Massachusetts: Allyn and Bacon:  
     24-25.</p>

<p>Hoeffel, John (1994), "The Secret Life of Focus Groups:
     Computer Analysis of Taped Interviews Can Reveal What
     Customers Are Really Saying, In Ways That Go Beyond Words,"
          <i>American Demographics</i> (December): 17-20.</p></i>
          
    
<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I. Explain why information is so important to marketers
<ol>
<li>Marketers need information for making marketing decisions and solving marketing problems
<li>The information explosion, particularly continuous advances in computer technology over the past three decades, has radically changed business and society
</ol>

II. Understand that all marketers need information
<ol>
<li>Marketing is information intensive
<li>Marketers use information to make decisions about the marketing mix variables
<ul>
<li>Descriptive information describes what consumers do, buy, and say
<li>Prescriptive information helps marketers make decisions and solve marketing problems
</ul>
<li>Marketers must manage information effectively and avoid being overwhelmed by the mass of available information 
</ol>

III. Describe a marketing information system (MIS) and explain how it works
<ol>
<li>A marketing information system (MIS) is a systematic process of managing information so that it can be used in making marketing decisions
<ul>
<li>Most MIS systems are computerized
<li>They include information collection, information analysis, and information dissemination activities
</ul>
<li>Commonly used sources of marketing information include internal company records, external information, and the results of marketing research
<ul>
<li>Quantitative information includes objective facts and figures
<li>Qualitative information is more subjective and includes observations and anecdotal reports
</ul>
<li>Information analysis, also called information integration, is often computer-aided particularly in large businesses and for complex problems
<li>Information dissemination requires conveying information to the right decision makers
</ol>

IV.  Identify the steps in marketing research
<ol>
<li>Marketing research, according to the American Marketing Association, links the consumer, customer, and public to the marketer through information
<li>Marketing research is used to make critical marketing mix decisions, market research focuses on market decisions, advertising research on advertising decisions
<li>Marketing research is performed by individuals and groups within a business, and by companies whose sole business is performing research and selling the results to others
<li>Marketing research is conducted in a systematic way, following specific steps
<ul>
<li>Step 1 - identify the problem and state the research question
<li>Step 2 - develop a plan
<li>Step 3 - execute the plan and collect information
<li>Step 4 - analyze the data and interpret the results
<li>Step 5 - report findings and recommendations
</ul>
<li>Marketing researchers must ensure that their efforts are valid, reliable, and generalizable
<li>Primary research is original research designed to collect data unique to a project
</ol>

V.   Discuss how recent advances in information technology are pushing marketing in new directions
<ol>
<li>The end of the 20th century has been characterized as the dawn of the information age
<li>Electronic measuring devices are helping marketers collect information about consumers
<li>Check-out scanners are used to record consumer purchase behaviors as they happen
<li>Facsimile machines allow marketers to collect and disseminate information electronically worldwide
<li>Virtual reality, computer generated images, are used in a variety of business settings including product development and studying consumers in shopping situations
<li>The Internet, and particularly the World Wide Web, is emerging as an exciting system for marketing products to consumers through their personal computers and interlinked world wide computer systems
</ol>

<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  Explain this statement: "We are in the midst of an
information explosion."  <i>Computer technology has made it possible
to collect masses of data, analyze it, and provide valuable
information for use in making marketing decisions and solving
marketing problems.  Because computers make it so easy to
collect, analyze, and disseminate information, the result has
been an information explosion, a vast abundance of information
suddenly made available that previously would not have been
accessible to most people.  As people become more dependent on
computers at work, home, and play, their impact on society and
business will steadily increase.</i>

<p>2.  What do computers have to do with the information explosion?
<i>They are directly responsible for the vast abundance of
information that is available to help in making marketing
decisions and solving marketing problems.</i>

<p>3.  Distinguish between computer hardware and software.  <i>The term
"computer hardware" means the computer itself, its case, central
processing unit, chip, keyboard, and screen, along with printers,
scanners, fax modems, and associated devices.  "Computer
software" are programs run on computers, including spreadsheets,
word processing programs, database management programs, and
statistical analysis packages.</i>

<p>4.  Explain what is meant by the term marketing information
system.  <i>A marketing information system (MIS) is a process by
which people manage information for use in making marketing
decisions and solving marketing problems.  The system requires
information collection, information analysis, and information
dissemination.</i>

<p>5.  Describe the three common sources of information collected by
marketers.  <i>Information collection in a marketing information
system uses such common sources of information as internal
company records, external information, and the results of
marketing research.</i>

<p>6.  Contrast primary and secondary data, and primary and
secondary research.  <i>Primary research is conducted to solve an
original problem and primary data are collected specifically to
answer the primary research question.  Secondary research is
conducted by evaluating existing research and existing data that
have been collected for other purposes.</i>

<p>7.  Describe the steps in marketing research.  <i>Marketing
research requires adherence to a series of required steps that
are designed to provide a systematic, objective, bias-free
inquiry that can withstand careful scrutiny.  The steps include
identifying the problem, developing a plan, executing the plan,
analyzing and interpreting the results, and reporting the
findings and recommendations. </i>

<p>8.  What three research considerations are very important to the
marketer and underlie his or her confidence in research results? 
<i>In order to have confidence in the value of the research
findings, researchers must ensure that their work meets standards
for validity, reliability, and generalizability.</i>

<p>9.  Why are customer surveys such a popular form of marketing
research?  <i>Surveys are popular for a number of reasons.  They can
be used for small numbers and large, from hundreds to thousands
of people or businesses.  Survey results can be obtained quickly
and relatively cheaply.  These results lend themselves to
statistical analysis.  However, there is a growing problem with 
people who are asked to complete a survey but refuse.  Response
rates are declining.</i>

<p>10.  What are some of the new technologies affecting marketing?   
<i>New technologies affecting marketing relate to advances in
computer technology or computer-related systems.  These include
electronic measuring devices, scanners, facsimile (fax) machines,
virtual reality, and the Internet.</i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 6.1</h4>

<p>1.  What is information and how is it used in marketing? 
<i>Information is knowledge that can be used to solve a problem.  In
marketing, this can include deciding whether or not to market a
company's products in a particular market.  Information is used
to make decisions about products, prices, places (distribution),
and promotion.</i>

<p>2.  Explain this statement: "Marketing is information-intensive." 
<i>Because marketing occurs in volatile environments, it is
necessary to continually monitor the environment and collect
information that can be used in decision making.  Marketing
decisions and problem solving require information about
consumers, customers, the competition, and other environmental
factors.</i>
 
<p>3.  Why must marketers be concerned about managing information?
<i>Computers have greatly increased the amount of information that
is available to marketers.  Therefore, it is essential that
marketers manage information efficiently so it can be used in
effective decision making and problem solving.  Information must
be collected and made available when and where needed.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 6.2</h4>

<p>1.  Describe what takes place in a marketing information system.
<i>A marketing information system (MIS) is a systematic process for
collecting information, analyzing it, and disseminating the
results and recommendations.</i>

<p>2.  Identify sources for information collected internally in an
MIS.  <i>Internal information comes from such sources as
salespeople, sales reports, accounting records, expense records,
profit statements, production and shipment schedules, salesperson
logs.</i>

<p>3.  Distinguish between commercial intelligence and espionage. 
<i>Commercial intelligence is the legal and ethical collection of
information about the competition from sources that are readily
available to the general public.  Commercial espionage is
stealing information that is not generally available.  It is
illegal and unethical.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 6.3 </h4>

<p>1.  What is marketing research?  What are market and advertising
research?  <i>Marketing research is a systematic, organized process
that links the marketer and consumers, customers, and public
through information.  Marketing research is very broad and can
include research on any marketing activities.  Market research is
designed to answer questions about markets; advertising research
answers questions related to advertising.  The research methods
may be similar or the same; however, with marketing research, the
topics of interest are far broader than with the much more
narrowly focused market or advertising research.</i>

<p>2.  Identify the steps in marketing research.  <i>Marketing research
typically occurs in several well defined steps or stages.  These
are identify the problem, develop a research plan, execute the
plan, analyze results, and report recommendations.</i>
            
<p>3.  Compare and contrast primary and secondary data/research.  
<i>Primary research is original research that uses data collected
specifically for the research purpose.  Secondary research uses 
secondary data which was collected for other purposes.  Many
research designs use both secondary and primary methods and data.</i>

<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 6.1: Vons Does it the Customers' Way</h4>

<p>Vons is an example of a retailer that has embraced computer
technology and research in order to gain a competitive advantage. 
Vons' management has kept its eye firmly on satisfying customers. 
This case can lead to a comparison of Vons with local
supermarkets and a discussion of how local retailers could use
marketing research to become more consumer oriented.

<p>1.  Could the Vons approach be used in all supermarkets?  <i>There
is a limitation, particularly because of the investment needed to
adopt the Vons model, in time and technology.  However, all
retailers would be wise to determine how well they are satisfying
consumers by conducting consumer research.</i>

<p>2.  Could Vons carry this customization process too far?  Explain
your answer.  <i>There is always a problem with too much of a good
thing.  In this case, if the costs of the process exceed the
benefits, then it has gone too far.</i>

<p>3.  Are there any consumer privacy issues involved in this case? 
Explain your answer.  <i>Yes, and this is an issue of growing
importance.  As more consumer information is accumulated, stored,
and disseminated, there is a greater change of misuse.  Many
consumers and marketing professionals are concerned about
consumer privacy and trying to ensure it.  This is also a problem
that will extend to the Internet which is a very insecure place
at this time.</i>

<h4>Mini-Case 6.2: Marketing Research Serves Different Needs</h4>
 
<p>Do religious organizations in your area use marketing?  This
is an interesting topic to explore with your students, discussing
personal experiences with marketing and marketing research in
religious organizations.

<p>1.  Many churches are using marketing research, advertisements,
and direct marketing to reach their markets.  Do you think there
is any opposition to churches using marketing?  What might be the
basis for this opposition?  <i>There is resistance to church
marketing by some church members as well as others who believe
that a distinction should be made between religious institutions
and marketing activities.  This opposition is directed more
toward profit centered, money raising activities than the use of
marketing to determine consumer satisfaction and opinions.</i>

<p>2.  If a church decides to use a marketing research survey to
determine its market's preferences, who should be surveyed? 
Should only current members be questioned?  Explain your answer. 
<i>It depends on the reason for conducting the research.  If the
research seeks to determine what prospective members want in a
church, then they must be included in the research.  Some
research will focus specifically on the needs and satisfaction of
existing members.</i>
                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>Japanese marketing researchers are known for getting close
to customers who have already bought their products.  Have
students consider whether any American businesses use this
method.  If anyone has purchased a new automobile recently, they
may have experienced this type of consumer research, with follow-up telephone calls at various times post-purchase to evaluate
continuing satisfaction.  Are there other examples?

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>The Internet is the place to find information.  It offers
vast stores of secondary information and some researchers are
conducting primary research there, primarily through interactive
Internet surveys.  As with all Internet activities, verify
Internet addresses and confirm the feasibility of an Internet
assignment before you make it.  Stress professional behavior and
responsibility to your students.  

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>Isabelle Ono, from the chapter opening story, needs
information about Japanese consumer food preferences.  She must
answer a research question about whether or not Japanese
consumers will purchase health foods, like those made by
Isabelle's company.  This question probably can be answered best
by conducting primary research, collecting original data from
consumers that will answer this specific question.  However,
Isabelle can learn quite a bit about marketing in Asia, and Asian
consumers, on the Internet.  This type of consumer information is
bound to increase in the coming years as the Internet, and
particularly the World Wide Web, expands.           

<i><p>     Students can compare Asian and European marketing
     opportunities on the Internet by evaluating two sites.  The
     European site offers databases with information on business
     opportunities in the European Union (EU); the Asian site is
     similiar to the EU site, but for Asian countries, including
     Japan (Vine 1995).

<p>     The European Union
<a href="http://www.echo.lu">http://www.echo.lu</a>

<p>     Asian Business Directories
<a href="http://sashimi.wwa.com:80/~bruno">http://sashimi.wwa.com:80/~bruno</a>
</i>

<p>     As commercial sites on the World Wide Web (WWW) begin to
report greater profits, more marketers will be drawn to the Web
and the number of sites and products offered will increase
dramatically.  Students can research the question:  <i>What products
currently are being marketed on the WWW?</i>   It is impossible to
get an exact count of businesses on the Web because the Web is
virtually unregulated, thus there is no central "sign-in" point
for new Net businesses.  Also, the number of business home pages
and sites in multibusiness malls change daily.  However, students
can develop insights into Web commerce by conducting topical
searches and collecting commercial intelligence.  Assign student
teams the task of researching a product category to determine if
it is being marketed on the Web.  Let each team select a
different product category, preferably one that interests them. 
Previously, successful Web product searches have been conducted
for bicycles (mountain bikes), floral arrangements, guitars,
automobiles, advertising agencies, and real estate.  

<p>     Competitive intelligence is also readily available on the
Internet through mailing lists and newsgroups (Maloff 1995). 
However, because many schools limit student storage space,
students would find it difficult if not impossible to keep up
with the mailings from a very active list or newsgroup.  These
sources are best left for the marketing instructor to access.

<i><p>     Students can perform a topical search by using Lynx to get
     to jughead or veronica.  Initiate the search by typing in
     the name of the product category, for example

<p>     search: bicycles

<p>     Alternately, a search can be conducted using Yahoo or
     another powerful index.  

<p>     Yahoo
<br><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>

<p>     The Whole Internet Catalog
<br><a href="http://nearnet.gnn.com">http://nearnet.gnn.com</a>
</i>

<p>     Small businesses can find valuable information on the
Internet that otherwise might be too expensive or too difficult
for them to collect.  Small business use of the Internet for
information retrieval and secondary research is expected to
increase. 

<i><p>     Students should already be familiar with the information
     available for small businesses from the federal government
     at

<p>     SBA On-line
<br><a href="http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov">http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov</a>

<p>     Another resource is the Lexis/Nexis Small Business Advisor,
     which has over 5,000 articles for small and home businesses. 
     There is no cost for the search; however, a nominal fee is
     charged to download articles. 

<p>     Lexis-Nexis Small Business Advisor (SBA) at
<br><a href="http://www.directory.net/lexis-nexis">http://www.directory.net/lexis-nexis</a>
</i>

<p>     If you wish to find a guest speaker to discuss how computers
and information technology are changing marketing, you may be
able to get help from a professional organization on the
Internet.  Several national professional organizations are
already there, others will doubtlessly join them.  These
organizations list their local chapters, which often is a good
way to locate guest speakers.

<i><p>     The American Marketing Association, local chapters
<br><a href="http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks">http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks</a>

<p>     The American Association of Advertising Agencies, local
     chapters
<br><a href="http://www.commercepark.com/AAAA/AAAA.html">http://www.commercepark.com/AAAA/AAAA.html</a>
     
</i>
<p>    A number of najor marketing research businesses are on the
Internet.  Students can learn about the work of these businesses
by accessing their home pages.  Remind students that professional
behavior is expected at all times when they visit an Internet
site.  Some of these businesses ask visitors to take a survey, so
at the same time the visitor is collecting information at the
site, the business is collecting information from the visitor. 
An interesting topic for class discussion is how the Internet can
be used for consumer research.  There is at least one example of
the use of focus groups on the Internet, conducted by SRI. 
Research is being conducted about the Internet, as well as on the
Internet.

<i><p>     Gallup
<br><a href="http://www.gallup.com">http://www.gallup.com</a>

<p>     Nielsen
<br><a href="http://www.nielsen.com/home/index.html">http://www.nielsen.com/home/index.html</a>

<p>     UK NOP Research Service
<br><a href="http://www.maires.co.uk/panel">http://www.maires.co.uk/panel</a>

<p>     SRI (Values and Lifestyles Research)
<br><a href="http://www.sri.com">http://www.sri.com</a>

<p>     Internet Demographics
<br><a href="http://www.netsurfer.com/surveys.html">http://www.netsurfer.com/surveys.html</a>


<p>     Marketing Application 6.1 and 6.2</i> require the identification
of information sources for the collection of secondary data. 
Some of the sites used in previous chapters can be accessed for
these tasks.  Have students visit the Census Bureau for age
trends, population and housing statistics, information about the
economy, and computer usage statistics.

<i><p>     Census Bureau
<br><a href="http://www.census.gov">http://www.census.gov</a>

</i>
<p>     If you use the mystery shopper activity, you might consider
extending it to a collaborative project with students at other
schools.  This requires contacting other marketing instructors
through one of the marketing lists (see the List of Lists at the
American Marketing Association's MouseTracks site) and planning
for market basket price comparisons run by students in different
locations.  A simple market basket study would have student teams
track gasoline prices (three grades, three price points) over the
term.  Students at each school can record prices at multiple
stations once a week, then post the results to the Internet
student list.  If enough different student groups collaborated, a
broad picture of multicity, multistate, or multinational gasoline
pricing could be developed.

<i>
<p>     The American Marketing Association
<br>     The List of Lists at 
<br><a href="http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks">http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks</a>
</i>

