<p>Vine, David (1995), "Euro-Eco Promo," <i>Internet World</i> (July):86-87.

<p>Maloff, Joel (1995), "The Virtual Corporation: The Internet, Global Markets, and Social Mobility Are Creating New Ways of Working," <i>Internet World</i> (July): 46-50.

<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 6.1</h4>

<p>The purpose of this Application is to have students consider
broadly the types of information a marketer needs in order to
make a market entry decision.  This is directly analogous to
making a market entry decision in international markets, so you
might note the commonality.  The goal is to make the best product
and market match; one that is low in cost and risk, while high in
demand and the potential for revenue and profit.  Although this
Marketing Application uses disposable diapers as a product
example, substitute another product if it is more applicable and
interesting to your students.  Likewise, if you prefer to use
states close to your own, please do so to personalize the
assignment.  Some alternatives are a marketer of

<ul>
<li> planned retirement communities
<li> financial planning seminars for professional women
<li> computer learning centers for small business owners 
</ul>

<p>Begin with internal sources that can provide information
about the potential markets (selected cities in three states). 
If the marketer is already offering the product in other cities
in these states, then useful comparative information can be
obtained from such sources as product sales in the cities,
scanner data (if applicable to the product type), reports on
competitors, and salesperson and supplier observations.  External
information should be collected for each potential market from
such sources as trade journals and professional publications,
state or regional publications, government reports and documents,
and commercial intelligence.  The marketer must predict demand
for the product, entry costs for each market, competitive
resistance, and the possible effects of other environmental
factors on costs and revenues.  

<p>The disposable diaper marketer must assess demographic
trends that will affect demand, particularly birth rate trends
and the number of women approaching childbearing age, as well as
the competitive environment, including competitors already in the
market, the breadth of product distribution, products offered,
and product prices.  Competition includes both disposable diapers
and diaper laundry services.  

<p>Information needs for the other marketers will vary
according to product type.  For example, the marketer for planned
retirement communities will need information about population age
structure in the potential new markets, in addition to the
information previously identified.  A marketer of financial
planning seminars for professional women will need information
about the population of working women in the new markets.  A
marketer of computer learning centers for small business owners
will need information about small businesses in the new markets.  
      

<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 6.2</h4>

<p>This <b>Application</b> extends <b>Marketing Application 6.1</b> and
directly leads to a <b>Using the Internet</b> activity.  It assumes that
all needed internal information has been collected and now the
marketer must seek external information.  Often a business will
hire a outside research company to perform a market analysis,
which includes an in-depth study of the potential new markets and
entry recommendations.  If the research is to be performed in-house, then a good place to begin is with secondary information
that is readily accessible, timely, and often, free.  

<p>     The United States government is the most prolific data
collecting body in the world.  Many government publications use
data collected by the Census Bureau.  Census Bureau data can be
accessed in publications found in most public, college, and
university libraries.  It is available in universities that house 
federal government document depositories.  The United States
Government Printing Office (USGPO) sells many publications to the
general public.  Finally, a considerable amount of government
information is available on the Internet and data can be ordered
on-line.  

<p>     Age is a demographic variable that is often critical to
marketing decisions.  This <b>Application</b> can single out the age
variable for its descriptive and predictive value to the product
market matches for diapers, retirement communities, and financial
planning seminars.  To simplify the market match problem, which
is actually an extremely complex one, have students pretend that
age is the only relevant decision variable.  Stress that in real
life, no decision is ever this simple!  Students can evaluate age
tables for several cities in each state and make product market
match decisions based solely on age trends.  


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 6.3</h4>

<p>     This <b>Application</b> personalizes the marketing research process
for students.  It has them learn by doing.  Tally the anonymous
class survey scores and have student teams analyze the results,
comparing class scores to those of other Americans in 1983 and
1992.  Consider each question and determine whether or not your
students are like or unlike those who were surveyed in 1992. 
What trends emerge from these data?  What types of product
opportunities can be identified if we assume that the survey
results are generalizable?

<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 6.1</h4>

<p>Computers are an inescapable part of our daily lives, at
work, home, and play.  This Insight can be extended by the
complementary activity in Using the Internet in this chapter,
which examines computer usage in the United States.  Computer
literate consumers are of growing importance to marketers, both
as targets for computer-related products and because computers
are needed to take consumers to the Internet, where products of
all types are being sold.


<h4>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>     Have students consider some of the difficulties of
conducting marketing research abroad.  For example, many consumer
surveys in the United States are conducted by mail, but in many
developing countries, relatively few people may be literate.  Can
telephone surveys be conducted around the world with the same
ease as they are conducted in the United States?  What about
written surveys? </p>

<p>

