<h1><center>CHAPTER 3</h1>        
<h1>SEGMENTING THE MARKET: CONSUMER BUYING DECISIONS</center></h1>                

<a href="#abstract">Chapter Abstract </a><br>

<a href="#teaching tips">Some Teaching Tips </a><br>

<a href="#outline">Chapter Outline </a><br> 

<a href="#answer">Suggested Answers To Chapter Questions </a><br>

<a href="#internet">Using The Internet  </a><br>

<a href="#marketing">Marketing Applications</a><br>

<a href="#consumer">Consumer Insights And International Marketing

</a><br>


<h3><a name="abstract">CHAPTER ABSTRACT</a></h3>


<p><b>1. Describe the two segments of consumers: business/organization
and personal use. </b> Consumers in the United States represent a
very large and profitable market.  They can be grouped into two
broad segments of unequal size, business/organization consumers
and personal use consumers.  The smaller business/organization
segment includes industrial, reseller, government, and not-for-profit consumer markets.  The larger personal use consumer market
includes over 260 million individuals.  Although many marketers
direct their offers toward a mass market, most group consumers
into segments, then target the segments with the greatest
purchase potential.  Consumer segments are formed by identifying
important shared characteristics.  These may be demographic,
psychographic, geographic, behavioral, or a combination of
characteristics.  Marketers try to influence consumers
perceptions of their products so that their brands will be
favorably positioned compared to the competition.  The goal is to
effectively use the marketing mix tools to satisfy consumers. 
Consumer satisfaction is a primary goal of marketing activities
in both business/organization and personal use consumer markets. 
Marketers must understand that not all consumer behavior is
rational or acceptable.  Deviant consumer behaviors represent a
variety of actions that are different from acceptable norms and
may also represent illegal behaviors.</p>


<p><b>2. Identify the characteristics of consumer purchase decisions. </b> 
Although it is not always easy to predict or understand consumer
purchase decisions, some aspects of the process are known.  Both 
business/organization and personal use consumers must decide
whether to make, lease, or buy products.  Some product purchases
are rebuys, others are modified rebuys, or new task buys.  Some
purchase decisions are made independently; more often they
involve others, often working together in formal or informal
buying centers.  Steps in the purchase decision process also
vary.  Most personal use consumer purchase decisions are far less
formal than those made by business/organization consumers.  The
latter often face greater risk and uncertainty in making a
purchase decision.</p>


<p><b>3. Describe influences on business/organization consumers.</b> 
Business/organization purchase decisions are influenced by many
factors.  Some influences are organizational, particularly the
priorities and strategies established for the buying unit. 
Others influences reflect organizational characteristics and
demand.  While most business/organization purchase decisions are
rational and objective, human emotions can affect the outcomes. 
Professional buyers are evaluated by the effectiveness of their
purchase decisions about the core product and such associated
services as terms of delivery, installations, and product
guarantees.</p>


<p><b>4. Recognize external influences on personal use consumers.</b> 
Consumer behavior is all the activities involved in selecting,
purchasing, evaluating, and disposing of products.  Personal use
consumers experience many different external influences on their 
behavior, and particularly their purchase decisions.  External
influences may affect many consumers concurrently and similarly. 
Some of the most important social influences are the family,
reference groups, and social class.  Consumers' culture and
microculture affect their behaviors.  Other external influences
are those applied by marketers, the buying situation, technology,
product supply, and even the weather.</p>


<p><b>5. Recognize internal influences on personal use consumers. </b>  
Internal influences are personal, unique, and not observable. 
These are psychological factors that sometimes can be inferred by
observing consumer behavior.  Powerful internal influences
include needs and wants, involvement, perception, learning,
attitudes and attitude change, and personality.  Marketers must
understand the nature of these influences in order to be able to
understand consumers and try to satisfy them.</p>   
          
<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>
    
<p> The emphasis in most introductory marketing textbooks is on
personal use consumers, while comparatively little attention is
given to business/organization consumers.  There are several
probable reasons for this myopia.  One reason relates to the way
that marketing instructors are educated.  Most have little formal
training in business-to-business, not-for-profit, or public
sector marketing, which makes teaching it more challenging for
them.  On the other hand, they often are required to take one or
more consumer behavior courses that focus on personal use
consumers. </p> 

<p> Because many introductory marketing students are not
marketing majors, they don't have a great need to study
business/organization consumers in depth.  This removes an
incentive for teaching the topic.  As for the marketing majors,
they typically will learn more about business/organization
consumers in advanced marketing classes.</p>  
     
<p>     Another reason for the emphasis on personal use consumers is
the relative size of the two broad consumer markets.  There are
many more personal use consumers (hundreds of millions) compared
to several million business/organization consumers combined. 
This is also reflected in student employment opportunities, where
there are more jobs available in personal use consumer marketing
activities.  It is shown in the numbers of different products
needed to serve this market, tens of thousands of products in a
neighborhood grocery store alone.  Finally, many students and
marketing educators find it easier to relate to personal use
consumers and more interesting to explore related marketing
activities because of shared personal experiences.</p>

<p>     If you haven't already used a mini-case in class, this would
be a good place to introduce one.  Select a mini-case from the
text or reproduce one from <b>PART IV ADDITIONAL MINI-CASES</b> in this
Manual.  A short introduction to using mini-cases in class is
provided for those instructors who have not used them previously
and for others who might benefit from another perspective on case
methods.</p>

<h4>Teaching Mini-Cases In Class</h4>

<p>     The first and perhaps most highly respected version of the 
case method was developed at Harvard University Law School in the
1880s.  The goal was to present a nondirectional way for students
to work independently.  Cases meant to encourage independent
thinking are widely used today in law, medicine, social work,
business, and other disciplines (Paget 1988).</p>

<p>     A business case can take different forms.  It may be a
fictional representation of a frequently experienced type of
business situation or an abbreviated version of a true story. 
Some cases are extremely complex, include detailed financial and
market information, and may extend for a hundred or more written
pages.  Students at the doctoral, master's or advanced
undergraduate levels may work for weeks or an entire term solving
these cases.  Advanced cases typically are team projects.</p>

<p>     Cases have many different titles.  There are vignettes,
critical incidents, and anecdotes, as well as long and short
cases.  The mini-cases in the text and PART IV in this Manual are
highly simplified, abbreviated marketing cases.  They are based
on actual contemporary marketing incidents and illustrate a
chapter topic.  Each is referenced so you can review the material
from which the case was developed and find additional background
information to add to class discussions.</p>

<p>     The goal in using mini-cases in <b><u>Marketing: Foundations and
Applications</u></b> is to use interesting examples that provide an
opportunity for students to analyze marketing situations and
solve marketing problems.  The cases are short intentionally 
because it is difficult to justify spending a great amount of
time on a highly detailed case in one area of marketing when
there is so much marketing to discuss in a term. </p>

<p>     The mini-cases are meant to be read, worked, and discussed
in class.  They classify as an interactive teaching method
because they are designed for students to work in twos (dyads) or
small teams, then discuss as a class.  Students are encouraged to
analyze, interpret, draw inferences, and relate the cases to
other marketing applications.</p>

<p>     A clear advantage of working through the case process is
that students are exposed to real marketing problems, which
broaden their experiences.  A limitation is that no matter how
long, detailed, and complex the case is, it cannot possibly
represent reality fully and with total accuracy. </p> 

 <p>    Some marketing instructors find it easier to use a straight
lecture method than assign cases.  This is because the instructor
must prepare for case instruction and be comfortable in providing
constructive, non-intrusive guidance.  Most of us use some cases
in class because they offer a rich learning opportunity for
students to develop their analytical and communication skills. 
Cases also promote active and often lively student discussions.</p>

<p>     My experiences using mini-cases in class have been very
positive.  Typically, I ask students to form themselves into
dyads (two-person teams) or small groups (no more than four
members).  Depending on available class time, students are
allowed several minutes to read the case, then approximately ten
to fifteen minutes to answer the case questions.  I often add 
information to the case and an additional question or two. 
Students write their analysis and prepare to present it.  If time
allows, the dyads or small teams are merged.  If you have dyads,
they form teams of four members; three-person teams form teams of
six.  Give the teams another ten minutes to debate a consolidated
team response.  At the end of that time, ask each team to briefly
present their analysis.  Useful class discussions are encouraged
by establishing class rapport and encouraging students to openly
express their opinions.  Perhaps the greatest challenge for the
marketing instructor is to encourage student comments and not
dominate the discussion with his or her own views.</p>

<p>     If you are using cases for the first time, start by
considering the reasons why you are using them.  Frey and Keyes
(1985, p.53), provide a useful list that includes

<ul>
<li>
  to give students experience in applying marketing concepts
  and principles to real world situations.

<li> to help students reason through problems.

<li> to improve students' communications skills, oral and
     written.

<li> to assist students in identifying key problems.</ul></p>

<p>     Be prepared to give special attention to students who need
it.  Some students never open their mouths in class and others
never shut them.  For the former, you can encourage participation
by drawing them out, ask several students for their opinions and,
unobtrusively include the shy student among them.  The chatterbox
may require an out-of-class conference.  You can devote a few
class minutes to discuss how developing good listening skills can
contribute to business success.  Since students read the case in
class, you'll avoid the problem of unprepared students.  Have
copies of the case available for students who forgot to bring the
text with them; sufficient copies for the entire class if you use
an additional mini-case from this Manual. </p> 
     
<h4>Other Teaching Suggestions For Chapter 3</h4>

<p>     If you use Mini-Case 3.1 in class, you can extend it by
asking students how a marketer of low- and no-fat cookies might 
segment the cookie market.  Some of the segments that can be
identified are</p>

<p>At the broadest level, the groups are
<ul>
<li><i>non-cookie eaters</i>, consumers who dislike sweets and never
     eat cookies

<li><i>cookie eaters</i>, consumers who like sweets and eat cookies</ul></p>

<p>Among the cookie eaters, the groups are
<ul>
<li>
<i> fat-free fanatics</i>, cookie-eating consumers who are dedicated
to controlling fats in their diets, eat <u>only</u> no-fat or very-low fat cookies, and if offered a good tasting, high fat
     cookie, will always refuse it

<li><i> wishy-washy eaters</i>, consumers who try to maintain control
     over the fats in their diets, but if they are offered a good
     tasting, high fat cookie, will eat it without remorse

<li><i> taste is everything fat-aholics</i>, consumers who believe that
     taste is everything, don't care about fats, pay absolutely
     no attention to fats, eat all good tasting cookies that are
     offered

<li><i>healthy eaters</i>, consumers who care about fats and also
     restrict their intake of sugars and sodium, they will only
     eat cookies that are low in all three ingredients</ul></p>

<p>     Which segment(s) are the best prospects for a low- and/or
fat-free cookie?  If this cookie also is extremely rich tasting,
could it be targeted to all segments?  If so, would this be mass
marketing?  What are the advantages of mass marketing in this
situation?  Could you satisfy all consumer segments through mass
marketing?</p>

<p>     You can go further with this thread by introducing the other
marketing mix elements.  Suspend your targeting decision for a
minute and talk about price.  Ask students if it is cheaper to
eat healthy (no-fat and low-fat foods) or eat for taste, without
concern about fats.  Personal observation suggests that consumers
often pay a premium for healthy foods.  If there is a greater
profit margin from healthy foods, how might price affect
segmentation and targeting decisions?  If the decision is made to
target.  Where would you place the products?  How would you
promote them?</p>

<h4>Segmenting Consumers On The Internet</h4>

<p>     Ask students to consider how consumers can be segmented on
the Internet (page 71 in the text).  The first grouping is one of
access, consumers who can Net-connect and those who cannot.  Is
this a volatile distinction that will change over time?  Is it
technological segmentation?</p>

 <p>    Next, group according to the broadest classification, that
of business/organization or personal use consumers.  What
generalization can be made about the potential size of these
segments?  Which segment will eventually be the largest and why? </p> 

<p>     Within the personal use consumer segment, consumers can be
grouped according to the types of products they are seeking on
the Internet.  For example, consumers looking for tangible goods
(particularly computer hardware and software), services
(particularly entertainment), social outlets (bulletin boards and
chat lines), or information.  </p>

 <p>    You can add insights from <b>Mini-Case 3.3</b> by suggesting a
segmentation grouping by gender.  How do men and women differ in
their use of computers?  Might this extend to their use of the
Internet?  Is this a potentially meaningful way to segment
consumers?</p>  

<p>    Pose a marketing problem that relates to these topics.  If
you were marketing computer hardware and software on the
Internet, which segment(s) would you target?  If you target men,
particularly those men who like computers and find them
entertaining, how would you manage the marketing mix variables to
appeal to this profitable segment? </p> 

<h4>Deviant Consumer Behavior</h4>

<p>     A particularly troubling aspect of consumer behavior
involves deviant behaviors.  Unfortunately, the incidence of
retailer-directed deviant behaviors is growing.  Consider the
statement on page 75 of the text, "As many as 60 percent of all
personal use consumers may shoplift at one time or another."  Ask
students what they think of this figure.  Can it possibly be
correct?  What are some of the reasons people shoplift?  What are
some retailer responses?  Is shoplifting a victimless crime?  If
not, who suffers and how?</p>


<b>References</b>

<p>Frey, Cynthia J. and Raymond F. Keyes (1985), "Marketing Case
     Instruction at the Undergraduate Level," <i>Journal of
     Marketing Education (Summer): 51-59.</i></p>

<p>Paget, Neil (1988), "Using Case Methods Effectively," <i>Journal of
     Education for Business (January): 175-180.</i></p>

 
 <h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>  

I.   Describe the two segments of consumers:
     business/organization and personal use
<ol>
<li>
Business/organization consumers are classified into
          groups by standard industrial classification (SIC) code
          which describe people buying products for thousands of
          businesses and organizations, for use in production, to
          operate their business/organization, or for resale 
<ul>
<li>
 These consumers include the industrial market,
               reseller market, government market, and
               nonclassified institutional market

<li> There are far fewer business/organization
               consumers than personal use consumers</ul>

<li>Personal use consumers are the hundreds of millions of
          people purchasing products for their own use, for
          family, or friends
<ul>
<li>
Marketing segmentation means breaking a large
group of consumers into smaller groups that are
similar to one another and different from others
because of shared characteristics

<li>Targeting means directing a market offer at
selected segments that represent the greatest
purchase potential

<li> Positioning is how consumers mentally compare
 products; marketers try to help consumers form
 preferential positioning for their products </ul>

<li>Consumer satisfaction means narrowing the gap between
what the consumer expects and values and what the
marketer delivers

<li>Some consumers demonstrate deviant consumer behaviors
including shoplifting, writing bad checks, and other
actions that deviate from generally accepted societal
norms</ol>
<p>
II.  Identify the characteristics of consumer purchase decisions 
<ol>
<li>
 Understanding consumers is critical to marketing
  success, but it is rarely simple or easy to do so

 <li> There are many similarities between the two broad
segments of consumers, particularly the type of
purchase decision made - whether to make, lease, or buy

<li>Buying decisions fall along a continuum from unchanged
          repeat purchases to new purchases
<ul>
<li>
           Straight rebuys are repeat purchases of products
               bought and consumed on a regular basis

         <li> Modified rebuys are purchases that reflect some
               deviation from the previous buy

        <li>  New task buys are first time purchases</ul>

<li>Participants in the purchase decision often reflect the
          magnitude, importance, and risk of the purchase; many
          involve people making purchase decisions in buying
          centers
<ul>
<li>
Buying centers are very common in businesses and
               organizations

<li>Personal use consumers, and particularly families
               and households, also form informal buying centers

<li>Buying center roles include the initiator,
               gatekeeper, influencer, buyer, and user</ul>

<li>Many business/organization purchases follow formal
          procedures, as illustrated by government contracts;
          most personal use consumer purchases require less
          formal decision steps</ol>


<p>III. Describe influences on business/organization consumers
<ol>
<li>
 Business/organization purchase decisions are influenced
by its mission, goals, and strategies
 <li>Demand, particularly derived demand, is a powerful
 influence on business/organization purchase decisions
<ul>
<li>
Elastic demand means that a change in price
stretches demand, price and demand change in
opposite directions

<li>Inelastic demand is common for essential products
so that when price rises, demand may not change 

<li>Fluctuating demand reflects economic conditions</ul>

<li>Other influences on purchase decisions relate to the
          nature of the purchase situation</ol>

<p>IV.  Recognize external influences on personal use consumers
<ol>
<li>
Consumer behavior is all of the activities involved in
selecting, purchasing, evaluating, and disposing of
products

<li>Other people exert social influences on personal use
          consumers
<ul>
<li>
Family is the social influence closest to the
consumer and it is often the most powerful
external influence on purchase decisions

<li>Reference groups are both groups of people that
consumers want to be like and those that they
don't want to be like; both influence consumer
purchase decisions

<li>Social class is not as potent an influence in the
United States as it is in other countries, but it
still can influence consumer purchases

<li>The microcultures a consumer is part of and the
larger culture of the entire country influence
purchase decisions

<li>Marketers influence consumer purchase decisions
               particularly through promotions and the other
               marketing mix variables

<li>Situational influences are nonmarketing factors
               like the weather, technology, buying purpose, that
               influence purchase decisions</ul></ol>

<p>V.   Recognize internal influences on personal use consumers
<ol>
<li>
Internal influences are individual and unique

<li>Needs are gaps between reality and a desired state that
          create a tension that is often satisfied through a
          purchase

<li>Involvement indicates the level of personal important
          that influences a purchase decision

<li>Perception is how consumers select, organize, interpret
          and give meaning to information related to purchase

<li> Almost all consumer behavior is learned; marketers seek
          to help consumers learn in order to influence their
          purchase decisions

<li> Attitudes are learned predispositions, marketers seek
          to establish positive attitudes toward their products

<li>Personality, the unique totality of traits that
          distinguish individuals, has not been shown to be a
                    strong influence on purchase behaviors</ol> 
 
<h2><a name="answer">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>                

<p>1.  Explain why you think consumer behavior is such a puzzle to
many marketers.  <i>Consumer behavior is a puzzle to many marketers
because there are so many different consumers, behaviors, and
influences on both.  Because of this, many marketers don't bother
trying to understand consumers; they feel it's impossible to
figure out why consumers behave as they do.  Others operate on
the belief that one offer will appeal to almost all consumers, so
as mass marketers they aren't concerned with understanding
variations in behaviors.</i> </p> 

<p>2.  Can someone be both a business/organization and personal use
consumer?  Explain your answer.  <i>Absolutely, yes.  In fact, all
professionals making purchases for their business or organization
are also personal use consumers when they are not making purchase
decisions professionally. </i> </p>

<p>3.  What is deviant consumer behavior?  Why is it important that
marketers be aware of such behaviors?  <i>Deviant consumer behaviors
are behaviors that are contrary to socially acceptable norms
and/or are illegal.  They include such behaviors as not reporting
billing and change errors, shoplifting, switching price tags, and
other retailer-directed behaviors.  They are important because
they cost retailers and consumers hundreds of millions of dollars
annually, as much as 2% of all U.S. retail sales!</i></p>

<p>4.  Explain the difference between a make, lease, or buy decision
by both consumer segments.  <i>Fundamentally, they are much the
same.  Both personal use and business/organization consumers must
decide whether to make, lease, or buy products.  People make
purchase decisions, but for business/organization purchases, the
products will be used in production, to operate the business or
organization, or for resale.  There are differences in risk,
volume, cost, and timing.</i></p>

<p>5.  Pretend that your school is purchasing its first-ever
schoolwide computer system.  This system will be used for
academic, administrative, research, and teaching purposes.  Who
should sit on the school's buying center committee? 
<i>Representatives from each group that will be affected by the
purchase, including teachers, administrators, researchers, and
students, as well as the school's purchasing agent.</i></p>

<p>6.  Of the following product purchases, which has the highest
financial risk, the highest physical risk, or the highest social
risk?

<ul>
<li> 
New clothes to wear on a first date - social risk

<li>New 486SX personal computer - financial risk,
     particularly if it is being bought for a business and its
     use will affect profitability

<li>Fifteen-year old used car - physical risk, but because it
     is a used car, the financial risk is far less than it would
     be with the purchase of a new car</ul></p>

<p>7.  Jim is walking through Cherry Blossom Mall.  A pair of boots
in a store window attract his eye.  He doesn't need boots, but
decides to try them on.  He likes them so much, he purchases
them.  Is than an impulse purchase?  Explain your answer?  <i>Since
Jim had not planned to buy boots and doesn't need them, it is an
impulse purchase.  This is like impulsively buying candy in a
grocery check-out lane, just because the wrapper attracts your
eye, you smell the chocolate, or you are tired and think
chocolate can give you a quick energy lift.  You don't
necessarily need it, didn't plan to buy it, but on impulse do so.</i></p>

<p>8.  What is the baby boom generation?  Why is it of such interest
to marketers?   <i>Baby boomers are people born between 1946 and
1964 in the boom years immediately following the end of World War
II.  This population bulge has affected the economy and marketers
through each of its life stages.  When boomers crowded into
elementary schools, there were so many of them that new schools
had to be built.  When they reached college age, new teachers had
to be hired and programs expanded.  Marketers are now looking to
the days when they boomers begin to retire.  This will drive
increased demand for such age-related products as retirement
communities, recreational activities, and home health care
specialists.</i></p>

<p>9.  Who influenced your choice to attend school?  What were your
internal influences?  Your external influences? <i> Although answers
will vary, internal influences should be such things as the need
for a job that requires a degree, the satisfaction of completing
a degree program, or wanting to learn at a higher level. 
External influences include family, friends, society, and class
expectations.</i> </p>

<p>10.  What is a multigenerational family?  What different opinions
might members of such a family give when faced with a decision
about a family vacation?  <i>A multigenerational family includes
members of different generations, for example children, parents,
grandparents, aunts, uncles, and even great grandparents.  Each
may prefer a different type of family vacation based on their
perception of what constitutes a good vacation.  For example, the
kids want Disney World, mom and dad prefer San Francisco, grandpa
and grandma want Branson, Missouri.</i></p>

<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 3.1</h4> 

<p>1.  Why do some marketers prefer to mass market their products? 
<i>Primarily because they believe that their product has mass
appeal.  Alternately, because it is too expensive, time
consuming, and/or too much trouble to differentiate the product
and the other elements of the marketing mix in a targeted
strategy.</i></p>

<p>2.  How are business/organization consumers classified?  <i>They are
classified into 1 of 11 major groups by Standard Industrial Code
(SIC) that includes the industrial market, the reseller market,
the government market, and the nonclassified institutional
market.</i></p>

<p>3.  Explain why consumer satisfaction is so important to
marketers.  <i>There are several million business/organization
consumers and hundreds of millions of personal use consumers. 
The competition to sell products to these markets is intense. 
Therefore, for a marketer to be competitive, consumer
satisfaction is essential.  A dissatisfied consumer won't
purchase or repurchase, which means the marketer doesn't generate
revenue or contribute to profit. </i></p>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 3.2 </h4>

<p>1.  Describe these alternatives: make, lease, or buy.  <i>Consumers
who make a product must gather materials and supplies, then use
their talent and labor to create a product.  A lease is a
contract to rent a product for a period of time, often with an
option to buy the product at the end of the contracted period.  A
buy decision transfers product ownership from the seller to the
buyer.</i></p>

<p>2.  Contrast rebuy and new task buying decisions. <i> A rebuy is a
repeat purchase without modification, therefore it requires
little if any additional information or search for alternatives.  
A new task buy requires information search because it is a
purchase made for the first time, which implies that there is
little history or prior knowledge of the product.</i></p>

<p>3.  What is a buying center?  <i>A buying center is a more or less
formal group of people who work together to make a purchase
decision.  Families often act as buying centers.</i></p>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 3.3 </h4>

<p>1.  How can a mission statement direct purchase decisions? <i> A
mission statement sets goals and establishes priorities for a
business or organization.  It affects purchase decisions by
establishing a broad framework for purchase decisions.</i>  </p>

<p>2.  Explain the terms: Derived, elastic, and inelastic demand. 
<i>Demand exerts a powerful force on purchase decisions made by
businesses and organizations.  Derived demand occurs when demand
for one product increases demand for others.  This is much like a
domino effect.  Elastic demand means that a change in price
stretches demand, so that when price falls, demand rises; when
price rises, demand falls.  Price and demand move in opposite
directions.  Inelastic demand describes many essential products
so that a change in price does not have a corresponding change in
demand.  Consumers are willing to pay the price or have no choice
but to do so.</i></p>
            
<p>3.  Describe other purchase factors that influence
business/organization consumers.  <i>The state of the economy
influences their purchase decisions.  Other influences are a
product's price, costs, product quality, associated terms, and
sometimes, personal interactions between purchasing agents and
product sellers.</i></p>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 3.4</h4>

<p>1.  Describe the types of external influences on personal use
consumer purchase decisions.  <i>Social influences are very
powerful.  These include family, reference groups, social class,
microculture and culture.  Other external influences are
marketers, the purchase situation, technology, and even the
weather.</i></p>

<p>2.  How can life stages influence a family's purchases?  <i>The
stages family's move through are important because each stage has
different purchase needs.  For example, young family expecting a
first child makes child-related purchases.  A retirement-aged
couple downsizing their living accommodations makes different
purchase decisions based on their needs and wants.</i></p>

<p>3.  Explain how roles, reference groups, and opinion leaders
influence personal use consumers. <i> All of these external
influences exert pressure on consumers to make acceptable
decisions.  The consumer often must interpret the pressure, which
can distort the message.  However, depending on how vulnerable
the consumer is to these pressures, the influence on his or her
purchases can be significant.</i></p>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 3.5</h4>

<p>1.  What are needs?  How are they related to motives? <i> Needs are
internal influences on consumer behavior.  They are gaps between
reality and a desired state that create a tension that can be
released by a behavior.  A motive is a need that has been
energized and directed toward a goal.</i></p>

<p>2.  How does involvement influence perception?  <i>Involvement is
the level of interest that a consumer has in a particular object,
activity, or idea.  It also is an internal influence on consumer
behavior.  How deeply involved a consumer is with something
affects their interest in purchases related to the involvement
object.</i></p>

<p>3.  What is an attitude?  Can consumer attitudes be changed? <i> An
attitude is a lasting feeling, an overall like or dislike.  A
consumer attitude can be changed, but often it requires
considerable skill and consumer knowledge to do so successfully.</i></p>

<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>

<h4>Mini-Case 3.1: What Has Happened to the Fat-Conscious Consumer? </h4>  
              
<p>     Although many consumers say they are watching their fat
intake, their behaviors tell a different story.  The market for
fat-free and low fat foods is growing, yet so are markets for
rich ice creams and loaded cheeseburgers.  This apparent
contradiction underscores the difficulty of understanding
consumers and predicting their behaviors.</p>

<p>1.  What do you think is happening to consumers' commitment to
eating healthy?  <i>It takes considerable commitment to maintain a
low fat diet, along with a willingness to sometimes pay more. 
This is a fad for some consumers, a temporary involvement with a
way of eating that will not last.  For other consumers, it is
lasting and signals a deep commitment to controlling their diets. 
Many Americans talk about their diets and exercise programs, yet
easily fall off the good food wagon.</i></p>

<p>2.  If you were a marketer of a line of healthy foods, would you
abandon the healthy food market?  <i>With a market as large as the
United States, a small segment could easily include several
million consumers.  If I were marketing a healthy food product
line, I would stick with it and explore the possibilities of also
promoting the line for its good taste.</i></p>

<p>3.  Do you think this trend toward more flavorful foods will
last?  Why or why not?  Can you explain your answer in terms of
demographics?   <i>As baby boomers age, they will probably become
more health conscious.  This has very good implications for an
expanding market for healthy foods.</i></p>

<h4>Mini-Case 3.2: Gender Differences Show Up in Consumer Behaviors</h4>
 
<p>     Gender differences in consumers show up in many different
consuming situations.  Certainly it is reflected in some gender-specific products.  It is evident in the way men and women
grocery shop, use computers, and approach business travel.  An
understanding of these differences can lead to profitable target
marketing.</p>

<p>1.  Do you think social pressures could have anything to do with
these gender differences?  <i>Social influences on consumer
behaviors are very powerful.  There is no doubt that they could
also influence the specific consumer behaviors identified in this
mini-case.  On the other hand, particularly in the case of how
the genders approach computers, there is some evidence that the
differences lie in the way that men and women process
information.  Brain structure and chemistry may be more important
in explaining these gender differences.</i></p>

<p>2.  Are these gender differences important to marketers?  Explain
your answer.   <i>Absolutely!  They can provide powerful consumer
insights that marketers use to better target their market offers. 
For example, knowing that men are generally more prone to impulse
purchases suggests that marketers of impulse-type products should
target men and use signage and other promotion tools to attract
male consumers.</i></p>

<p>3.  Will some of these differences change as (1) more men have to
do the grocery shopping and (2) more women have to use computers?
<i>Not necessarily.  If the differences are internally influenced,
then usage rates probably won't have much effect.  However, if
they are externally moderated, then changes may occur.</i></p>

 <h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     The green consumer movement ebbs and flows.  A sudden, well
publicized crisis, like an oil spill or a decrease in the
atmosphere's ozone layer, sparks fear and increases consumer
interest in environmentally friendly actions and products.  Other
times consumer interest in and support of the environment appears
to subside.  Many, but not all, consumers remain convinced that
protecting the environment is a good thing.  However, they don't
necessarily follow-through with their behaviors.  Sometimes it is
because environmentally friendly products are more costly to
purchase and not available in convenient places.  In the case of
clothing, which has social as well as price considerations,
environmentally correct may not be fashionable.  This is a
complex issue that can be used to stimulate a class debate about
the viability of environmental targeting, as well as the
mysteries of consumer behaviors.</p>  
            
<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>     Several Internet applications may be used to complement the
topics developed in Chapter 3.  Remember to check addresses and
paths before you assign them to confirm that addresses are still
accurate and operational.  Likewise, stress professional student
behavior on the Internet at all times, along with Net-cautions. </p> 

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>To develop a better understanding of the number of
business/organization consumers, direct students to the United
States Department of Commerce, Census Bureau.  Follow the path  

<a href="http://www.census.gov"><i>http://www.census.gov</i> </a><br>                                  
     select  topics in text                                       
     Population and Housing                                     
<ul>
<li>
 Statistical Abstract of the United States                
 <li>Frequently Requested Tables</ul>                             
     Establishments, Employees, and Payrolls </i>                
                      

<p>     Internet demographics (see Marketing on the Internet, page
71 of the text) can be obtained through a search of Yahoo.  Have
student teams take different paths to determine how may consumers
can Net-connect and how many business sites are now offering
their products on the Net. </p>    

<a href="http://www.yahoo.com"><i>http://www.yahoo.com</i></a><br>                                 
     Perform a Yahoo Search for: Internet Statistics and          
                                 Demographics </i></p>

 <p>     SRI International is a respected source for information
about consumer psychographics.  Remind students that a visit to a
corporate home page is analogous to a visit to a corporate
office.  You can learn more about their Values and Lifestyles
(VALS) work by following the path</p>

<i>   * List of Public SRI WWW Servers                             
     1. SRI International                                         
     Main Operating Groups   <br>                                     

    * Business and Policy  <br>                                    
    * Business Intelligence<br>                                        
       Values and Lifestyles Program (VALS)                       
       (examples of VALS in use) </i>                               


<p>     Photo 3.2 (page 75 of the text) is reprinted with the
permission of Fujitsu.  Students can visit their home page and
analyze the contents to determine if the home page conveys the
same urgency about satisfying consumers as shown in their print
advertisement.  This site is extremely rich in information about
the company.  It provides a needed reference for students who are
not familiar with business consumers. </p>                            

<a href="http://www.fujitsu.com"><i>http://www.fujitsu.com</i></a> 


 <p>    The Marketing Application 3.5 (page 93 of the text)
addresses the issue of finding information to use in making
consumer purchases.  The example cited is automobiles.  Many
automobile sites are on the Internet, with additional ones added
regularly.  Have students compare the relative benefits and value
of automobile information found in hardcopy sources and on the
Internet.  A particularly impressive site is located at
Dealernet, accessible through Yahoo.  To check out automobile
information on the Web, go to</p>

<a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a><br>                                   
     Perform a Yahoo Search for: Automobiles </i>   
                   
    
<h2><a name="marketing">MARKETING APPLICATIONS</a></h2>
<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 3.1</h4>

<p>     If you have some non-traditional students in class, ask if
any of them make purchase decisions for their employers.  Even
some of the traditional students may be able to contribute with
their experiences as purchasing agents.  Contrast some of these
purchases with those made by personal use consumers. 
Alternately, invite a purchasing agent from your school to speak
to your class.  Have them describe the different ways that
purchases are made.  In particular, ask them to contrast straight
rebuys from new task.</p>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 3.2</h4>

 <p>    Many print advertisements use fear appeals.  In addition to
tire ads, there are fear appeals for products designed to reduce
aging, facial lines, or body fat; eliminate perspiration odor or
bad breath; and provide immediate access to repairs should your
car break down.  Assemble the students' fear appeal ads and have
everyone analyze them.  Which are the most effective?  Why?  What
is the most extreme of the appeals?  Is there a risk in making a
fear appeal too realistic?</p>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 3.3</h4>

<p>     A role inventory can be an intriguing activity for many
students, particularly non-traditional students who are currently
balancing the demands of many different roles.  In order to
illustrate these differences, have students form themselves into
dyads or small teams with members mixed between traditional and
non-traditional students.  Have them compare their roles and the
influences on them.  What conclusions can they draw from their
analysis?  Are these results generalizable?  Is there a
commonality of roles that can be used as a basis for grouping
consumers?  You can find many print advertisements that answer
this question; one appears on page 90 of the text (Photo 3.7). 
Bring other examples to class to illustrate how marketers are
making use of this consumer insight.</p>

<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 3.4 </h4>

<p>     Have students bring their observations to class, compile the
results, and arrive at a class consensus on the multicultural
influences in your city.  How do these results compare
proportionally to your city's ethnic composition?  Are some
ethnic restaurants preferred?  Discuss how a marketing researcher
might determine whether the restaurants have altered their
products to conform to local tastes of your city.  </p>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 3.5</h4>

<p>     This assignment usually sparks considerable student interest
because it always seems as if someone in the class is in the
middle of car shopping.  In addition to the listed sources, have
them visit some automobile sites on the Internet to determine the
type of information available there.  Many credit unions will
provide printouts of the list price on specific car models.  This
can be cited as an information source that is often used in
arming consumers to enter into car price negotiations.</p>



<h2><a name="consumer">CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING </a></h2>
<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 3.1</h4>

<p>     It is important for students to develop an understanding of
the comparative size of each of the two broadest consumer
segments, business/organization consumers and personal use
consumers.  In this Consumer Insight (page 72 of the text), some
recent numbers are provided for the business/organization market. 
These numbers do not change significantly from year to year.  In
order to place the numbers in perspective, assign the Internet
activity in this chapter and have them bring the results to class
for discussion.</p>


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 3.2</h4>

 <p>    This Consumer Insight (page 74 in text) focuses on an
important insight that is guiding many advertising campaigns. 
Have students look for print advertisements for products directed
at older Americans.  What age groups are the most likely targets
for the products?  Now, carefully examine the people pictured in
these advertisements.  Are they younger looking than you might
expect for product users?  What can explain this discrepancy?</p>


<h3>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h3>

<p>     Should children be the targets of advertising?  Should
children be seen in advertisements promoting products?  These
questions are more negatively answered in many other countries
than they are in the United States.  We have some of the most
liberal rules government advertising to and with children.  If
you have international students in your class, use this
opportunity to ask them to comment on how their country stands on
this issue.  You can invite international students or other
teachers to visit your class to discuss this issue.  Alternately,
students can content analyze print advertisements in periodicals
from other countries to determine trends in advertising to and
with children.  This can also be the topic for a lively class
debate.</p>

<p>
