<head>
<title>CHAPTER 7: UNDERSTANDING PRODUCT</title>
</head>
                                
<h1><center>CHAPTER 7</h1>
<h1>UNDERSTANDING PRODUCT</center></h1>
                                
<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>


<p><b>1. Recognize the nature of product.</b>  Product is a focal point for
decisions involving the other marketing mix variables of price,
place, and promotion.  A product is anything offered to buyers to
satisfy their wants and needs in exchange for something of value. 
Product is a complex bundle of benefits.  Marketers use the
marketing mix variables to differentiate their products from
others and establish a competitive advantage.  Products are
classified in order to promote understanding, establish
relationships, and determine how successful marketing strategies
can be used for similar products.  Two important product
classifications identify the nature of products (goods and
services) and product target markets (personal use and
business/organization consumers). 


<p><b>2. Describe the total product concept.</b>  Products are often
represented as having three parts.  The core is the basic
product.  The augmented product is what the consumer expects
beyond the core and the seller adds to make the core product
more attractive and differentiate it from the competition.  This
is also called the extended product.  The potential product is
what might be added to further enhance the product and add to the
value of the product for consumers.


<p><b>3. Identify different perspectives on product.</b>  Many different
individuals and groups hold important views about products and
their perspectives affect product marketing.  Government views
product as something to be monitored to ensure consumer safety
and free market competition.  The competition views product as
something to closely observe, sometimes dissect and copy, and 
threaten their own profitability.  The members of a product's
distribution system view product as their reason for being and
source of profit.  Within a business, product can elicit
differing and sometimes opposing views.  To the consumer, product
solves needs and satisfies wants.


<p><b>4. Explain the issues involved in making product decisions.</b> 
Marketers must make a number of important decisions about
products.  These decisions contribute to the development of a
product strategy.  Among them are decisions about product
features, lines and mixes, quality, design, branding, legal
protection, packaging, labeling, and at the end of the product
life cycle, the product termination decision.


<p><b>5. Describe how product assets are protected.</b>  Legal protection
is essential to defend product assets.  Packaging protects goods
physically, as well as contribute to product image and promotion. 
A label provides information that consumers need to make informed
product decisions.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>Chapter 7 begins the discussion of the marketing mix
variables with product, the focus of many important marketing
decisions.  To personalize the topic of product, ask students to
consider what their lives would be like without such contemporary
products as color televisions, personal computers, video games,
automobile air bags, microwave ovens, cellular telephones, and
video cassette recorders.  These products either were not
invented or were not available as personal use consumer products
in 1950, nearly half a century ago.  While we certainly could
live our lives without these products, ask whether anyone wants
to do so.

<p>Continue personalizing the product topic by asking the
Chapter 7 opening question, "What product opportunities will
emerge in the next century?"  Answers will doubtlessly vary. 
However, analysts suggest that three broad product categories
will become increasingly important in the next century.  These
are entertainment and leisure products, information technology
and dissemination products, and products related to health care,
health maintenance, and elder care.

<p><b>A Product Challenge: Building An Egg Delivery System</b>

<p>I introduce the egg delivery system activity at this point
in order to build a foundation for the discussion of product, as
well as provide a reference for later discussions of price,
place, and promotion.  The origin of this activity is obscure,
however, it was recently distributed to the MKTTEACH list on the
Internet.  Variations have appeared elsewhere, particularly in
colleges of engineering across the country.  Local newspapers
often publish stories about engineering students who build egg
delivery systems patterned after shoes, windmills, helicopters,
and space ships.  The students contest which delivery system can
withstand a several story drop and deliver an unbroken egg to the
cement below.  They rarely work as expected!

<p>Ask your students to form 3 to 4 person teams.  Set up a
scenario, something like the following, or add embellishments, as
desired.  Tell the teams that you, the customer, have a problem. 
You live in an apartment building and hate to cook.  You do make
scrambled eggs, so you always have eggs in the refrigerator. 
Luckily, your downstairs neighbor is a great cook, and she likes
to share what she cooks.  The only bad part is that she is very
absent minded and is always running out of eggs.  You're happy to
provide her with eggs, particularly since you enjoy her cooking. 
To save time and energy, you deliver the eggs your downstairs
neighbor needs by leaning out over your balcony railing and
dropping the eggs into her hands, as she leans out over her
balcony railing.  This works most of the time, but sometimes you
miss and she gets egg all over herself and her balcony!  You have
seen some egg delivery systems in a specialty catalog but they
are too expensive.  Instead, you want each team to make an egg
delivery system that will delivery an unbroken egg to your
downstairs neighbor.  

<p>Give each team the following materials 

<ul>
<li>30 straws
<li>one long strip of masking tape (about a yard in length)
<li>a half sheet of poster paper or an 11" x 14" sheet of paper
<li>crayons or marking pens
<li>an uncooked egg
</ul>

<p>Since you want to complete this activity in one class
period, set a time limit of about 50 percent of the class period
for students to design and build the egg delivery system.  The
remaining time will be used to have each team describe their
marketing strategy and test their product.  Explain the time
frame in which they must work.  Also, tell them that each team
may ask you one question if they need clarification.

<p>In addition to building the product, each team must

<ul>
<li>decide on a company name
<li>decide on a brand name (may be the same or different from
     the company name)
<li>set a price for the product
<li>identify a distribution strategy, where the product will be
     sold
<li>sketch a print advertisement for the product that provides 
     product, price, and place information, and a unique selling
     proposition (UPS) that gives consumers a good reason to buy
     the product
</ul>

<p>When the design and production phase is complete, ask each
team to briefly present their product, the company name, brand
name, pricing and distribution strategy, and the print
advertisement with its selling proposition.  I run the delivery
system test in the classroom, however, you may prefer other
alternatives.  We move the classroom chairs out of the way, cover
the floor at the center of the room with cut-open plastic yard
bags, and place a ladder in the middle of the bags.  Two student
volunteers hold the ladder and another student volunteer acts as
head tester.  Each delivery system is first tested at the three-foot drop level.  Surviving systems go to the five-foot drop;
then, the six and eight foot drops.  Take all necessary
precautions to secure the ladder and keep the room clean.  I
always bring extra eggs because some team inevitably gets overly
excited about they're doing and crushes their egg during the
design phase.

<p>Students enjoy this activity and it usually attracts outside
observers, lured by the laughter coming from your classroom.  The
activity itself establishes a firm conceptual anchor for your
class discussions of product, price, place, and promotion.  For
example, considering how the product line can be extended to
include related items such as delivery systems designed for rainy
weather or extreme cold; the price points that should be
established to satisfy different consumer preferences for luxury
or economy models; or the different types of promotions that can
be used to inform and persuade consumers to buy this product.  It
also can be referred to when you're discussing such topics as
customer satisfaction, inventory control, packaging, and
distribution strategies.


<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Recognize the nature of product
<ol>
<li>A product is anything offered to buyers to satisfy
          their wants and needs in exchange for something of
          value
<li>Product differentiation means using the marketing mix
          variables to make a unique product offer that stands
          out from the competition
<li>Products are classified in order to facilitate
          understanding, establish relationships, advance the
          field, and aid in making decisions about similar
          products
<ul>
<li>Some products are tangible goods, physical
               products that can be felt, stored, inventoried,
               mass produced, transported, tested in advance of
               purchase, and controlled for quality
<ol>
<li>Durable goods are long lasting and infrequently replaced
<li>Nondurable goods are replaced frequently
</ol>
<li>Services are intangible and cannot be stored,
               inventoried, mass produced, transported, tested in
               advanced, or controlled through standardized
               quality checks
<li>Personal use consumer products are often
               classified by how consumers buy them and include
               such goods classifications as convenience,
               shopping, specialty, and unsought goods
<li>Business/organizational products include goods and
               services, with goods categorized as
               materials/parts, capital items, and
               supplies/services
</ul>
</ol>          


II.  Describe the total product concept
<ol>
<li>The total or whole product offer is often represented as the sum of three parts
<ul>
<li>The core is the basic product
<li>The augmented product is the added value of the product beyond the core and what differentiates it from the competition
<li>The potential product is what could be added
</ul>
<li>Marketing opportunities also exist for product disposal and recycling
</ol>

III. Identify different perspectives on product
<ol>
<li>Many people and organizations have different
          perspectives on product
<li>Government views product as something to be monitored
          and encouraged to advance competition
<li>To the competition, product is something to be closely
          observed, sometimes dissected and copied, other times
          product is something to be driven from the market
<li>To the marketer, product is something designed to bring
          success, reach goals, generate revenue
<li>To consumers, product is something to fill a gap,
          satisfy needs and wants
<li>To the distribution channel, product is something to be
          moved from producer to consumer in order to generate
          profits
<li>To other operational units of the company, product has
          variable meanings
</ol>

IV.  Explain the issues involved in making product decisions
<ol>
<li>Marketers are responsible for making important product
          decisions and developing a product strategy
<li>Decisions about product features reflect what the
          product is and does
<li>Product line decisions determine what different related
          products will be offered while product mix decisions
          are about what different lines will be offered
<li>Product quality in production means conformity to
          standards; to consumers it often is a mixture of
          tangible and intangible product characteristics that
          indicate how well a product satisfies valuable criteria
<li>Design refers to those elements that determine how a
          product functions to solve a consumer problem, from
          making the product easier to wear, or better
          performing, to being aesthetically pleasing
<li>Branding is an identification of product ownership
          through a name, symbol, design, or other element
<ul>
<li>Brand decisions can be highly complex, ranging
               from distribution strategies to naming,
               cobranding, and brand extension
<li>Cannibalizing means stealing market share from a
               company's own brands by another in the same
               category
</ul>
<li>Product termination is among the most difficult product
          decisions
</ol>

V.   Describe how product assets are protected
<ol>
<li>Unique product attributes are usually protected legally
<li>Packaging is an important product decision because it
          is protects the product physically, is the product's
          delivery system, helps to project brand image, and
          promotes the product
<li>The label, which is often incorporated into the
          package, offers important information about the brand
          and product contents
</ol>

<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  Explain the concept of product as core, extended, and
augmented parts.  <i>The core is the basic product; the augmented or
extended product includes all the features that differentiate one
product from another including brand name, package, warranties,
special features.</i>

<p>2.  Identify some tools used to differentiate products.  <i>Some of
the tools used to differentiate products are branding, quality,
image, product features, packaging, location, promotion,
innovation, and different service levels.  The marketing mix
variables (price, place, and promotion) are powerful tools used
to differentiate products.</i>

<p>3.  Why is it important to distinguish among various types of
products?  <i>Product classification interests marketers more than
consumers.  However, it is important to distinguish among
products in order to understand them better, establish
relationships, extend marketing knowledge (advance the field),
and establish commonalities so that similar products can benefit
from the same types of successful marketing mix strategies.</i>

<p>4.  Describe Copeland's classification system and explain its
importance to a marketer.  <i>Melvin Copeland was the first to
present a classification system for merchandise sold in retail
stores.  His system is based on buyer habits and differentiates
convenience, shopping, specialty, and unsought goods.  These
classifications are often extended to products.  They are
important to marketers because they serve to distinguish between
product types (see question number 3).</i>

<p>5.  Discuss the types of product decisions that a marketer must
make.  Are all of the decisions made solely by marketers? 
Explain.  <i>Types of decisions are about product features, product
lines, quality, design, branding, legal protection, packaging,
labeling, and product termination.  Not all the decisions are
made solely by marketers.  For example, many decisions about the
core product and product features and design are made primarily
by production and manufacturing, with important contributions
from marketers.</i>

<p>6.  What is a product line?  Give an example of one.  <i>A product
line is a group of related products that accommodate different
levels of consumer needs.  For example, the Bayer Select product
line of analgesics for headache, arthritis, menstrual, sinus, or
nighttime pain.</i>

<p>7.  Compare and contrast: product line, product category, product
mix.  <i>A product line is a group of related products that
accommodate different levels of consumer need.  A product
category describes items in different but related product lines
or in the same product line but with different features.  A
product mix is all of the products offered by a business,
including lines and items.  The mix is the broadest description
of different products offered; the line is the narrowest
description.</i>

<p>8.  What is value?  Why is it important to the consumer?  To the
marketer?  <i>Value is the eye of the consumer.  It is the
consumer's evaluation of the relationship between a product's
relative price, quality, and image.  It is important to the
consumer because consumers make value comparisons between
products and will favor products that have the right combination
of price, quality, and image.  To the marketer, it is critical to
determine what consumers value in order to provide products that
consumers will purchase.  Value differentiates the product from
the competition, so it is a potent factor in establishing
competitive advantage.</i>

<p>9.  If you were marketing national manufacturer's brands, how
might you feel about private-label brands?  <i>It depends.  Some
national manufacturers use a mixed branding strategy, offering
products under their own national brands, as well as under store
brands.  However, if I were solely marketing national brands (no
mixed branding strategy) I wouldn't necessarily like store
brands, particularly if they held a large market share.  I would
want to differentiate my national brand from store brands,
probably by strongly emphasizing quality and value differences.</i>

<p>10.  What is cobranding?  <i>If you like Heath Bars, you'll probably
love Ben & Jerry's Heath Bar-flavored ice cream.  That's what
marketers count on, that by uniting two or more popular brands,
the consumer will find double- or triple-branded products
irresistible.</i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 7.1</h4>

<p>1.  Explain this statement: "The T-shirt is the Big Mac of the
international clothing industry."  Do you agree or disagree?  <i>The
Big Mac is close to becoming a global product, offered worldwide,
with some modifications to accommodate cultural differences.  As
an article of clothing, the T-shirt may actually eclipse the Big
Mac in distribution because the tee is already worn globally,
from trendy parts of London to tribal Africa and rural South
America.  The basic article of clothing is unchanged while the
design offers opportunities for endless variation.</i>

<p>2.  Provide your own definition of product.  <i>Answers will vary,
but essentially a product is anything that a seller offers and a
buyer wants and is willing to exchange something of value for it. 
It is a complex bundle of benefits that can mean different things
to different consumers.</i>
 
<p>3.  Distinguish between the nature of goods and services, and
personal use and business/organization products.  <i>Goods and
services are distinguished by the former being products that can
be felt, stored, inventoried, mass produced, transported, tested
in advance of purchase and controlled for quality.  Services are
the opposite.  Many products are a combination of goods and
services.  Personal use products are those that are used
primarily by end use consumers and often are classified by buyer
habits as convenience, shopping, specialty, or unsought products. 
Business/organization products are bought for use in production,
for resale, or to operate a business or organization.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 7.2</h4>

<p>1.  What is the core product?  <i>The core product is the basic
product, without any additions.</i>

<p>2.  What is the augmented product?  <i>The augmented or extended
product is what is added to the core product to make it more
attractive to consumers and add value.  This includes brand name,
packaging, delivery terms, installations, guarantees, and
features.</i>

<p>3.  What is the potential product?  <i>The potential product is what
might be added to increase the value of the product for
consumers.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 7.3</h4>

<p>1.  What product perspective should a business take?  Explain
your answer.  <i>A business must consider all product perspectives
because all of them can influence product marketing.  However,
for business that operate according to the marketing concept
philosophy, the customer's philosophy should be paramount, all
things being equal.</i>

<p>2.  What is the government's perspective on product?  <i>The
government desires to maintain and encourage competitiveness and
consumer safety and well being.</i>
            
<p>3.  Explain why there may be different perspectives on product
within a business.  Why might this result in conflict?  <i>Different
functional areas within a business have different
responsibilities, therefore, their perspective of product will
vary according to what they expect product to do.  This can
result in conflict when different product expectations collide.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 7.4</h4>

<p>1.  Discuss the types of product decisions that must be made. 
<i>Many different important product decisions must be made,
including decisions about product features, lines, mixes,
quality, design, branding, legal protection, packaging, labeling,
and product termination.</i>

<p>2.  Explain the difference between national manufacturer's
branding and store branding.  <i>A national manufacturer's brand is
one that is designated by the manufacturer and used nationally. 
A store brand is associated with a retailer and not the producer. 
Some businesses use a mixed branding strategy, where the same
product may be both nationally branded and have various store
brands.</i>

<p>3.  Discuss the difficulty of defining quality.  <i>For tangible
goods, quality in production can be defined on the basis of
product specifications and how well the product meets those
standards.  To the personal use consumer, quality is less
tangible and more difficult to define.  It relates to how well
the product meets consumer expectations for valued features. 
Quality differs according to the product.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 7.5</h4>

<p>1.  Why is it important to protect product assets?  <i>Their
protection is very important because product assets are valuable
to a company in terms of establishing competitive differentiation
and advantage.  A distinctive look, taste, or feature establishes
a unique value for consumers which translates into profits.</i>
 
<p>2.  Why is packaging often called the "last five seconds of
marketing?"  <i>This is primarily the case because many businesses
do not spend more than a relatively short time considering
packaging.  For many businesses, packaging is given very little
attention.  However, it is very important because packaging
protects, as well as helps establish a brand image and passively
promotes the product on the shelf.</i>

<p>3.  What does a label do for consumers?  <i>Labels provide valuable
information that consumers need to have in order to make good
decisions.  The recent change in food labeling has made it easier
for consumers to identify the ingredients used in prepared foods.</i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 7.1: The Best Brand In The World?</h4>

<p>What brands do your students think are "tops?"  Ask them to
list what they think are the top 10 quality brands sold in the
United States.  These are brands that they consider to be the
best quality in any product categories.  Evaluate the lists and
compare them with the list in this Case.  How similar are they? 
Do your student include Coca-Cola?  Should it have been included
in the EquiTrend list?  If you have international students in
your class, ask them how Coca-Cola is sold in their countries. 
Is there a social benefit to offering guests a Coke in their
country ?

<p>1.  What value is there to a brand in being named to a top 10
list like EquiTrend's?  <i>The most obvious benefit comes from the
brand equity that is associated with being on this list.  The
brand equity comes from consumer recognition of product quality. 
Being on the list simply confirms what consumers already know.</i>

<p>2.  Explain Coca-Cola's popularity worldwide.  <i>Advertising and
sales promotions account for much of Coca-Cola's success, along
with its being available almost anywhere.  The association of
Coke with American culture is extremely valuable in most
countries and helps explain the product's social benefits for
consumers who want to demonstrate their familiarity with America.</i>

<p>3.  Discuss possible meanings for the statement, "Coca-Cola is
the best brand in the world.  <i>"Best brand" can have several
meanings, depending on whether it refers to market share, name
recognition, social acceptance, revenues, profits, or
distribution.</i>

<h4>Mini-Case 6.2: Buyers and Marketers Beware: Fakes Flood Markets</h4>
 
<p>Counterfeit products are a serious problem.  Local
newspapers often report instances of counterfeit products being
sold at country fairs, court days, or flea markets.  Some of your
students may have experienced this problem.  Producers of branded
products get a double slap from counterfeits because they lose
revenue since no licensing fee is paid, and if the products are
shoddy (which they often are), their reputations suffer.

<p>1.  Who should bear the responsibility for defective fake
products - the owner of the brand name or the counterfeiter? 
<i>Technically, the counterfeiter, but many brand name manufacturers
will accept some product responsibility if only to protect their
good name.</i>

<p>2.  Why might some consumers want product counterfeiting to
continue?  <i>Low cost counterfeit products, even if they are of
inferior quality, are cheaper than the originals.  Some consumers
prefer price over quality and want the products.</i>

<p>3.  What, if anything, can governments do to stop the flow of
counterfeit products?  <i>The United States government threatened
trade sanctions against China if that country didn't crack down
on counterfeiters.  Governments can exert considerably more
pressure than individual businesses or even industry
associations.  However, there has to be a willingness on the part
of the government where the counterfeiting is occurring to crack
down on the perpetrators, otherwise no long term relief can be
achieved.</i>
                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>Is more of a product always better?  How will your students
react to "movies on demand?"  How many television channels are
available in your area?  Will more channels frustrate viewers or
benefit them?  Students can discuss this question or broaden the
exercise to include others who can be asked the question.

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>Considerable opportunities exit on the Internet to compare
products and learn about the product decisions that marketers
must make.  Remember to verify Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment before you make it.  Remind
students to practice responsible, professional Net-etiquette at
all times.

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>The United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) has an
extensive home page that offers information about its own
operations as well as links to other related sources.  Students
can visit this site to explore

<ul<
<li>how product assets are legally protected
<li>a searchable index of the Trademark Acceptable
     Identification of Goods and Services Manual
<li>information on important patent law changes
<li>The Copyright Office at the Library of Congress (link)
<li>the World Intellectual Property Organization (link) 
</ul>

<p>At the end of the USPTO home page, there is a link to a
tabulation of weekly statistics on use of the Patent and
Trademark Office Web server.  For example, total accesses for the
week of Sunday, June 18, 1995 was 39,623.  This number represents
"hits" or visits.  While it is unknown how many of these are
duplicate visits, for the time being, this is the typical method
for registering activity at a Web site.

<p><a href="http://www.uspto.gov">http://www.uspto.gov</a>


<p>Businesses that market information products are expanding
their product mixes into shopping products on the World Wide Web. 
For example, The Chicago Tribune's on-line service is also
offering a grocery delivery service, the New York Times is
developing a system to offer on-line purchases of theatre and
movie tickets, and Gannett Co. is planning to extend its product
offers into travel, entertainment, and possibly products offered
in its USA Weekend supplement (Reilly 1995).  At the Gannett Co.,
Inc. home page, students can learn about one of the largest news
and information product marketers in the United States.  Gannett
is a highly diversified company with extensive holdings in
newspapers, broadcasting, outdoor advertising, and other
ventures.

<p><a href="http://www.gannett.com">http://www.gannett.com</a>

     
<p><b>Reference</b>

<p>Reilly, Patrick M. (1995), "Extra! Extra! Read All About It!! And Order Your Corn Flakes Here!", <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (April 26): B12.    


<p>To learn more about ISO 9000 quality standards, as well as
products that U.S. businesses are offering internationally,
students can visit the U.S. Department of Commerce's National
Trade Data Base.

<p><a href="gopher://sunny.stat-usa.gov/11/STAT-USA/NTDB">gopher://sunny.stat-usa.gov/11/STAT-USA/NTDB</a>

    
<p>Even political products are offered on the Internet. 
Students can compare the offers of the Republicans (GOP) and the
Democrats, as well as evaluate their marketing efforts at

<p>GOP <a href="http://www.gop.org">http://www.gop.org</a>
<br>Democrats <a href="http://www.house.gov/democrats">http://www.house.gov/democrats</a>

<p>To assess the types of products being offered at various
Internet shopping malls, and see how products are grouped by
lines, visit the Home Shopping Network's Internet Shopping
Network, the Internet Shopkeeper, and the GNN Website for links
to shopping.

<p><a href="http://www.internet.net">http://www.internet.net</a>
<br><a href="http://shops.net/cgi-bin/shopkeeper">http://shops.net/cgi-bin/shopkeeper</a>
<br><a href="http://nearnet.gnn.com">http://nearnet.gnn.com</a>


<p>Student teams can evaluate services through the product
offers of various travel marketers.  Consumers will find that the
Internet can reduce the stress of travel planning and dealing
with the unexpected (Wolff 1995).  Some places to evaluate
include

<ul>
<li>The Gnn Travel Center which offers entertaining dispatches
     about travel adventures, travel guides to various parts of
     the world, links to Web pages on water sports (at the Cyber
     Wharf), Fodor's Worldview, Travelers' Tales Books of
     personal accounts of travel trips, and links to Travel in
     the GNN Business Pages

<li>Travel information at DigiMark, including the Ottawa
     Tourist, Monterey Peninsula travel, the Rec. Travel Library,
     the Internet Guide to Hostelling, and information on
     Branson, MO, among other travel sites

<li>The Traveler's Checklist Homepage includes a product
     catalog, information about foreign electricity, and shopping
     information about hard-to-find travel accessories

<li>PCTRAVEL is an air reservation and ticketing service that
     allows the visitor to check airline fares and schedules,
     with ticket delivery overnight from FedEx

<p><a href="http://nearnet.gnn.com/gnn/meta/travel/index/html">http://nearnet.gnn.com/gnn/meta/travel/index/html</a>
<br><a href="http://www.digimark.net">http://www.digimark.net</a>  to Travel and Sightseeing
<br><a href="http://www.ag.com/Travelers/Checklist/homepage">http://www.ag.com/Travelers/Checklist/homepage</a>
<br><a href="http://www.pctravel.com">http://www.pctravel.com</a>
</ul>

<p><b>Reference</b>
     Wolff, Michael (1995), "Net Buying: Making Travel Easy,"
          Forbes ASAP (June 5): 35-37

<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 7.1</h4>

<p>The consumer needs being solved by each of the products in
the list (automobile, microwave oven, telephone answering
machine, automobile insurance policy, videocassette recorder,
automobile air bags) are clear, while the success of each is open
to debate.  Students may have differing opinions on how well each
product satisfies a need.  Dyads or small teams can consider each
list or part of a list, then report to the class on their
deliberations.  This research can be extended by having the class
develop a short questionnaire for one or several of the products,
then administer the questionnaire to others and report the
results to the class.  


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 7.2</h4>

<p>This Application calls for students to design a simple
exploratory survey, administer it, then discuss the results. 
When it comes to product difficulty, electronic products rate
high, particularly when it comes to programming videocassette
recorders.  The videocassette recorder is often the one product
most widely identified as being least satisfactory in satisfying
consumer needs.  Ask students to consider recommendations for
product design improvements based on consumer opinions.  What do
they suggest?


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 7.3</h4>

<p>High quality products often are associated with high cost. 
You can make this point by setting up a perceptual map on the
chalk board patterned on the following sketch.  Use price and
quality as the two key dimensions and ask students where they
would place certain well-known brands within the map, associating
the brands with high to low price, and high to low quality.  With
very few exceptions, price and quality will associate very
closely in most consumers' minds.  For example, if you use
automobile brands, your map will show such brands as Lexus at the
high end of quality and price, while the Hundai is at the low end
of quality and price.  

<p><b>A Perceptual Map: Price/Quality Association</b>

<pre>
                                  QUALITY
                                    High
                                     |
                                     |
                                     |   
                                     |
                                     |
               P                     |
               R H                   |                     L
               I i-----------------------------------------o
               C g                   |                     w
               E h                   |
                                     |
                                     |
                                     |
                                     |
                                    Low
</pre>
                                      
                                      
<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 7.4</h4>
                                      
<p>Product naming is a difficult task, as students will find as
they brainstorm a name for the revolutionary heating and cooling
microwave oven.  Another alternative is to have them try their
hand at naming a food product.  For example, El Paso Chile Co.
brainstormed names for their brands that would make them stand
out on the grocery shelf.  Some of their choices include Hellfire
& Damnation hot sauce, Sweet Texas Fire jalapeno honey mustard,
and Snakebite Salsa (Block 1995).  Considering the competition
for shelf space, a food brand name must offer a quick hook to
grab  consumer's attention.  Have students survey a grocery shelf
of Salsa or hot sauce.  Which names stand out?  Alternately, have
students brainstorm a name for a barbecue sauce that would be
attractive to local consumers.  These sauce brand names are often
associated with a place or a local personality, such as Texas
Jack or Pistol Pete.  Why?

<p><b>Reference</b>
<p>Block, Toddi Gutner (1995), "Mother Knew Best," Forbes (July
     3): 52-53.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 7.5</h4>

<p>Most consumers find the new food labels to be informative
and easy to read.  However, there still are problems particularly
when it comes to such ingredients as MSG, which can be listed
under a variety of names.  For consumers with MSG allergies, the
new food labels don't go far enough.  Have students bring to
class labels taken off foods they have recently eaten.  Evaluate
the labels and determine which are the most informative and
helpful to consumers making product decisions.      
<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 7.1</h4>

<p>The Dodge Ram truck's "rolling office" design is an
excellent example of collecting information about consumers and
then using it to make a product to satisfy them.  Students can
probably identify others, such as the snake light flashlight with
its flexible neck that can be anchored to nearby objects and
provide light while freeing the user's hands for other tasks.


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 7.2</h4>

<p>Students can find out more about the J.D. Power and
Associates quality surveys as well as the Malcolm Baldridge
National Quality Award.  If a nearby businesses has been
recognized for high quality products, ask them to provide your
class with a guest speaker who will talk about their quality
control processes and the marketing advantages of being
recognized for a quality award.


<h4>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>Store brands are growing in importance internationally.  If
you have international students in class, ask them about the use
of store brands in their country.  This question can be
incorporated into cross-cultural interviews. </p>

<p>

