<head>
<title>CHAPTER 8: PRODUCT PROCESSES</title>
</head>

<h1><center>CHAPTER 8</h1>
<h1> PRODUCT PROCESSES</h1>
</center>

<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>

<p><b>1. Explain how businesses obtain products.</b>  New products are
called the lifeblood of a company.  However, newness is a matter
of perspective.  A product may be new to the business offering
it, to consumers, an industry, or even a country.  Product
newness is often classified according to whether the product is
revolutionary, evolutionary, or somewhere between the two. 
Product strategies are developed so that products can achieve the
business goals set for them.  Some frequently used product
strategies designed to obtain new products are to revitalize
existing products, extend them, acquire new products, duplicate
existing products, cooperate with others to jointly develop
products, and generate new products through research and
development processes.


<p><b>2. Characterize the new product development process and explain
the importance of new products.</b>  Some businesses spend millions
on research and the development of new products in the hope that
they will gain profits, market leadership, and a competitive
advantage.  New product development typically proceeds through a
series of steps.  In some cases, consumers are involved with new
product development from the start of the process.  Development
steps include opportunity scanning, idea generation, idea
screening, concept testing, market analysis and marketing plan
development, product production, test marketing, and
commercialization.  Product development requires teamwork.  New
product failure rates are high.  As a result, some businesses are
taking aggressive steps to reduce the failure rate.


<p><b>3. Recognize the methods used to describe consumer responses to
products.  </b>It is important for marketers to understand and
describe consumer responses to products.  The product adoption
process describes how consumers proceed from awareness of a new
product, ultimately to a product purchase.  Innovations diffuse
through a society, with some consumers rushing to be among the
first to purchase a new product.  The majority of consumers hold
back, waiting to see how well the product is accepted by others
before they adopt it.  The product life cycle is a descriptive
device for characterizing generally how consumers respond to
products over time.  The international product life cycle model
suggests that product life cycles can be extended by introducing
a product to international markets where it may be new, even as
the same product is maturing or declining in the home market. 
Product positioning is another important consumer response that
explains how consumers mentally perceive products and compare
them on valued features.  Sometimes a product must be
repositioned, often because the initial consumer positioning was
unfavorable or because of changes in the competition or
environment.


<p><b>4. Compare different product management strategies.  </b>Once a
product is launched, it must be managed in order to gain and
sustain profitability.  No single form of product management is
effective for all businesses or products.  Some businesses use
brand managers, others use category managers, or form business
groups to manage products.


<p><b>5. Identify contemporary product issues.  </b>Some important product
issues confronting marketers are complaints about planned product
obsolescence, consumer rights, product recalls, and product
liability.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>     The Chapter 8 opening question asks, "If new products are so
crucial to business success (if not survival), why do so many of
them fail despite efforts to ensure their success?"  The new
product failure rate is estimated by some marketers to be
approaching 90 percent!  While there are many different causes of
product failure, from poor quality to high price, some blame lies
with the proliferation of products, as highlighted in the
Consumer Insight (page 237 of the text).  Students can check the
extent of product proliferation with Marketing Application 8.2
(page 241 of the text).  This activity can be expanded to include
look-alikes in such product categories as deodorants, shampoos,
dry cereals, cookies and crackers.  Keep in mind that while
marketers may not be happy with product proliferation, consumers
often are because it gives them a greater choice among products
and between prices.

<p><b>Fads</b>

<p>Fads are another product issue to consider and discuss. 
They include such things as pet rocks, wacky wall walkers,
volcano lamps, and pop rock candies.  Why do consumers buy such
products?  Ask your students.  It is likely that some have
purchased one or more of these products and can probably identify
other fad product purchases.  The question, "What influences
consumers to purchase a fad product?", can lead to a discussion
of consumer variety seeking behavior and the influence of
referent others on purchase decisions.  Do fad product purchases
undermine the economic concept of the rational consumer?  Do
successful fad products encourage competition, and if they do,
what is the risk to the late market entrant?  If possible, bring
examples of fads to class as visual aids.  A demonstration of a
wacky wall walker or one of its look alike imitators can enhance
a class discussion. 

<p>     Are clear products a fad?  Ask students what they think of
clear products.  If anyone has tried or currently uses a clear
deodorant, ask what they think of the concept and the result.  Is
there a gap between expectation and delivery, or are they
satisfied?   What product extensions could be developed from a
clear deodorant?  For example, might some consumer segments
prefer 

<ul>
<li> a clear and unscented deodorant
<li> a clear, unscented, and spray dispensed deodorant
<li> a clear, unscented, spray dispensed, and antiperspirant
     deodorant
</ul>

<p>     What product categories are most appropriate for a clear
product feature?  Have students debate the probable value to
consumers of a 

<ul>
<li> clear cooking oil
<li> clear gasoline
<li> clear perfume
<li> clear tea
</ul>

<p>     Of the strongly marketed clear beverages introduced in 1993,
only Coors' Zima Clearmart appears to have excited consumers
(Triplett 1994).  Crystal Pepsi, Coke's clear Tab, and Miller
Clear have not been so fortunate.  Perhaps one reason for Zima's
popularity is that Coors didn't rely just on the clear feature to
market the product.  Instead, their focus was on drinkability,
freshness, and light taste.  The Zima home page can be visited on
the Internet (see <a href="#internet">Using the Internet</a> in this chapter). 

<p><b>     Reference</b>
<p>     Triplett, Tim (1994), "Consumers Show Little Taste for Clear
     Beverages," <i>Marketing News</i> (May 23): 1-2.

<p><b>New And Improved Products</b>
 
<p>     Many consumers distrust marketers because of the abundance
of product claims about "new and improved" formulations that, in
reality, have no clear advantage over the original.  This is a
serious ethical issue that students can research and debate. 
Marketing Application 8.1 (page 239 of the text) considers this
problem by having students evaluate several grocery product
categories for the use and overuse of this claim.  Broaden the
discussion by examining other product categories where "new and
improved" claims are often made.  For example, students can
perform a content analysis of print advertisements for
automobiles in current popular magazines to determine whether
this is an automobile selling point.  What are the marketer's
legal and ethical responsibilities to be truthful about "new and
improved" claims?  What are the options open to consumers who
believe that these responsibilities have not been met?       

<p><b>Product Strategies</b>

<p>     The product line extension strategy can be illustrated by
bringing examples to class.  For example, Dial Corporation has
been highly successful in extending its popular Dial bar soap to
other products in the body soap line, hand soap line, shampoo,
and deodorant lines.  Ask students why Dial has been well
received by consumers.  Point out that 

<ul>
<li> Dial began with a strong, respected brand name, positive
     brand image, and good brand equity,
<li> the product extensions are appropriate, reasonable, and
     credible, and
<li> it has a profitable, brand loyal market segment that
     provides a solid market base on which the extension product
     strategy can be developed
</ul>

<p>Could Dial have extended the line as successfully to bread,
cookies, pasta sauce, or canned fruits?  If not, why?  What other
products and lines could Dial develop with a great expectation
for success?  

<p>     A product extension discussion lends itself to presentation
as a decision tree.  For example, begin with the original Dial
soap as the main trunk, then extend major branches to other
soaps, shampoos, deodorants, and related products.  Some branches
may lead to risky product extensions, in categories far removed
from the business' original competency in soaps.  Keep the focus
on the core competencies that a business brings to the line
extension strategy.  Usually the most successful extensions are
the ones that build on a company's principal competencies.

<p><b>DIAL PRODUCT EXTENSIONS</b>
<pre>

              |==> Deodorant Bar Soap  ==> Body Deodorant
            |=|   
            | |==> Moisturizing Bar Soap  
            |                           
Original    |                     |==> Moisturizing Hand Soap
Dial      =====> Pump Hand Soap  =|==> Antibacterial Hand Soap
Bar Soap    |                     |==> Kid's Hand Soap
            |                     |==> Clear Hand Soap
            |==> Shampoo
            |
            |==> _____________
            |    (Other extensions)
            |==> _____________ 
                 (Other extensions)
</pre>

<p>     Other examples that can be used are Healthy Choice cookies,
crackers, breakfast dry cereals, and breakfast bars; and Jell-O
dry pudding, pudding and pie filling, prepared pudding pops, pie
mix.  Students can suggest other cases that also illustrate this
product strategy.

New Product Development     

     If you used the Egg Delivery System in Chapter 7, relate it
to the steps in the new product development process in Chapter 8. 
If you didn't assign it for the last chapter, you might consider
doing so here.  As an alternative, use the Wooden Pencil project,
which requires less preparation and cleanup.  

<b><p>     The Wooden Pencil Project</b>

<p>     Ask students to form small work teams and give each team 
<ul>
<li> a wooden graphite pencil with an eraser for each team member
     (if possible, use old fashioned yellow school pencils)
<li> a half sheet of poster paper (or an 11 by 14 inch sheet of
     white paper)
<li> marking pens or crayons
</ul>

<p>     Each group acts as a new product development team.  You have
come to them with an opportunity (the opportunity scanning step). 
Your salesforce has determined that consumers, personal use and
business/organization, increasingly are requesting products made
from natural materials.  They are rejecting synthetic products,
like plastic, and seeking natural alternatives, like wood.  You
forecast great profit opportunities if the teams can develop new
products, using the ubiquitous wooden pencil, that will tap into
this emerging market.  

<p>     Since the opportunity has been identified, the first team
task is to brainstorm ideas for new uses for the wooden pencil
(the idea generation step).  Give each team member 5-10 minutes
to <b>individually</b> brainstorm ideas and write them down.  New
product ideas can be for a single pencil or many pencils, joined
by a natural material, such as animal or plant fibers.  Point out
that opportunity scanning and idea generation often occur
concurrently. 

<p>     At the conclusion of the individual brainstorming time,
allow each team 10-15 minutes to brainstorm together.  Begin by
having team members alternately contribute ideas.  Set firm
guidelines that no idea can be discarded or criticized at this
stage, and everyone must contribute.  Encourage team members to
piggyback product ideas and elaborate on previously offered
ideas.  The goal is to generate as many different uses for the
wooden pencil as possible.  One team member should written down
ideas as they are presented.

<p>     Next, the teams must evaluate the ideas, rank them, and
identify the ones with the greatest potential (the idea screening
step).  For example, a recent list generated by a student new
product development team included such new uses for wooden
pencils as

<ul>
<li> chopsticks
<li> houseplant stem supports (used individually or in a trellis
     form)
<li> back scratchers
<li> ladies' hair pins
<li> hot mats (several pencils woven together by natural fibers
     into a square mat designed to a hot pot or cup)
<li> hair brush cleaners (to remove hairs from brush bristles)
</ul>

<p>     Students must decide what product features are most
important in order to be able to rank the ideas.  They should
consider each idea's marketability, produceability, and profit
potential.  Once a "top" product idea is identified, the concept
should be tested on potential consumers (the concept testing
step).  Since the goal is to complete this activity within a
single class session, it would be counterproductive to actually
conduct a concept test.  Instead, ask each team to describe 

<ul>
<li> how they would conduct the concept test
<li> what market segment should be used in the test
<li> what questions should be asked
</ul>

<p>     Assume that the concept test is a rousing success and a
market analysis and test market indicate that the product should
be commercialized.  Conclude the simulation by asking each team
to

<ul>
<li> decide on a company name
<li> decide on a brand name (may be the same or different from
     the company name)
<li> set a price for the product
<li> identify a distribution strategy, where the product will be
     sold
<li> sketch a print advertisement for the product that provides 
     product, price, and place information, and a unique selling
     proposition (UPS) that gives consumers a good reason to buy
     the product
</ul>

<p><b>Consumer Resistance To Change</b>

<p>     Many new products fail or diffuse very slowly because
consumers resist change.  Change is frightening to some people,
and marketers must take this into consideration.  Use the
<b>Consumer Insight</b> (page 250 of the text) as an example of a
product innovation that some consumers will resist, even if it
proves to be more effective than existing alternatives.  Explore
other recent product innovations that consumers have purchased,
but are not using to the product's full potential, such as
microwave ovens, videocassette recorders, and personal computers. 
What might account for this situation?

<p><b>Test Marketing</b>

<p>     Many marketers are turning away from the traditional test
marketing of new products.  They cite serious problems associated
with traditional test marketing, including the

<ul>
<li> high cost of setting up, running, and evaluating a test
     market,
<li> time required,
<li> probability that competitors may try to sabotage your test
     market results by running counter promotions on similar
     products at the same time you are running the test market
<li> advance notice given competitors about your new product,
     which gives them time to react and plan strategies to combat
     the new product rollout.
</ul>

<p>     An alternative to traditional test marketing is to use a
simulated test market (STM), a computer-based system that tests
consumer responses to new products.  Some popular simulations are
ASSESSOR, LITMUS, and Visionary Shopper.  

<p>     The Visionary Shopper computer system lets consumers who are
participating in the test market "walk" through a virtual store
presented on a computer screen.  Consumers see products as they
would actually appear on the self.  They can use a mouse-like
track ball to have the computer take a product off the shelf to
be examined, and even rotate a product to see all sides.  Product
prices and promotional offers are manipulated so test subjects
are exposed to a real-life simulation of the factors considered
by consumers as they make a product choice.  While traditional
test markets can cost in the hundreds of thousands to millions of
dollars to implement, this system costs around $40,000 (Grocer
1995).  Simulated test markets using virtual reality run best
with certain product categories and poorly with others.  Goodyear
Tire & Rubber was the first company to purchase and pilot test
Visionary Shopper (Rickard 1993).  Goodyear Tire & Rubber can be
visited on the Internet (see Using the Internet in this chapter). 
 

<p><b>     References</b>
<p>     ___ (1995), "Test Marketing Goes On-Screen," <i>Grocer</i> (January
     14): 5-6.

<p>     Rickard, Leah (1993), "Goodyear Test-Drives the Visionary
     Shopper for Market Research," <i>Advertising Age</i> (October 25):
     24-25.

<p><b>Secondhand Product Markets</b>

<p>     Even a resold or secondhand product is new to the most
recent purchaser.  Considerable marketing effort goes into the
resale market.  Marketers run the gamut from luxury resellers
such as Christie's and Sotheby's, which sell works of art,
antiques, and unique articles; to used car and furniture dealers
listed in your local telephone directory; garage sales that
individuals have at their homes on weekends; and secondhand
clothing and furniture consignment shops.  Students can evaluate
the extent of such marketing activity locally by performing a
content analysis of garage sale listings, estate auctions, and
used car sales in your weekend newspaper, and checking product
listings in the yellow pages of the telephone directory.    
    
<p><b>Product Recalls</b>

<p>     If your students are unfamiliar with product recalls, have
them check current issues of Consumer Reports to see the variety
of products that can be recalled.  It is quite likely that one or
more have participated in a product recall.  If so, how was it
handled and were they satisfied with the results?  Botched
recalls that leave consumers dissatisfied can be devastating to
future sales and a company's reputation, at least in the short
term.  

<p>     How should a business handle a recall?  Students can debate
this issue by researching examples of recent recalls and
evaluating what went wrong.  Two companies that received poor
reviews for their recent handling of product recalls are General
Motors and Intel Corp. (Bissell 1995).  Instead of facing their
product problems head on and communicating directly with affected
consumers, there were denials and attempts to negotiate
settlements and avoid recalls.  Recent recalls extend across
product categories and include zippered beanbag chairs,
computers, tax software, and flammable brushed fleece clothing.

<p><b>     References</b>
<p>     Bissell, John (1995), "Product Recall: The Litmus Test of
     Learning to Focus on Consumers," <i>Brandweek </i>(January 23): 17.

<p>     ___ (1995), "Zippered Beanbag Chairs Recalled," <i>Los Angeles
     Times</i> (March 17): D3.

<p>     Aragon, Lawrence (1995), "Detroit Deja Vu," <i>PC Week</i> (March
     20): A1.

<p><b>Product Liability</b>
     
<p>     Another product issue that lends itself to student debate is
that of product liability.  A rapid increase in product liability
suits in the United States has made this issue one of growing
concern.  Part of the problem in getting a grasp on the issue
involves the maze of different liability laws in different
states.  Responding to business concern over liability damage
awards in the millions of dollars, Congress is debating a product
liability reform bill (Hoffman 1995).  Some states are already
acting to restrict awards for product liability damages (Jones
1995).  In the meantime, this is a topic that concerns consumers
and marketers, and affects the welfare of both.

<p>     Product liability extends internationally.  European product
liability laws have been broadened recently so that company
directors are now liable to criminal prosecution if their
company's products are proven dangerous and have harmed
consumers.  The European Directive on Product Liability holds
producers and distributors liable.  This Directive also covers
secondhand products (Edgar 1994).  Information on the European
Union can be found on the Internet (see Using the Internet in
this chapter).

<p><b>     References</b>
<p>     Hoffman, Mark (1995), "Product Liability Reform Bill Moves
     to Full Senate for Debate," <i>Business Insurance </i>(April 10):
     2-4.

<p>     Jones, David C. (1995), "Illinois Passes Sweeping Tort
     Reform," <i>National Underwriter Property & Casualty-Risk &
     Benefits Management</i> (March 13): 3-4.

<p>     Edgar, Andrew (1994), "If It's Broke, Fix It - Quick," <i>The
     Director</i> (July 1994): 73-74.

<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Explain how businesses obtain products
<ol>

<li>New products are the lifeblood of a company, but
          product newness depends on whose perspective is taken,
          a business, consumers, an industry, or even a country
<ul>
<li>Continuous product innovations differ only
               slightly from existing products
<li>Discontinuous product innovations are
               revolutionary new products
<li>Dynamically continuous product innovations fall
               between the two extremes, products different from
               existing ones, but not dramatically so
</ul>
<li>Businesses alter marketing mixes for products in order
          to reach goals for growth, profitability, or market
          share protection; they also obtain new products through
          different strategies
<ul>
<li><i>Revitalize </i>means reformulating, repackaging,
               and/or relaunching an old product, typically as
               "new and improved"
<li><i>Extend </i>means stretching a popular brand name to
               include other products in the same line, products
               in a related line, or sometimes, a different
               product category
<li><i>Acquire</i> means buying a business for its branks
<li>Duplicate means copying an existing product, with
               or without modification
<li><i>Cooperate </i>means entering into a joint venture with
               others to jointly develop new products and share
               the costs, risks, and profits
<li><i>Generate</i> means developing a new product, which
               often is the costliest, riskiest, and most
               profitable product strategy
</ul>
</ol>

II.  Characterize the new product development process and explain
     the importance of new products
<ol>

<li>A successful new product development can mean big
          profits and a sustainable competitive advantage, at
          least temporarily
<li>Product development typically proceeds through a series
          of interrelated steps
<ul>
<li>Opportunity screening
<li>Idea generation
<li>Idea screening
<li>Concept testing
<li>Market analysis and marketing plan development
<li>Product production
<li>Test marketing
<li>Commercialization
</ul>
<li>Product development requires teamwork and often
          includes professionals from many different business
          functional areas
<li>New products fail for many reasons, from problems with
          product quality or high prices, to redundancy and
          product proliferation
<li>Many businesses are aggressively attempting to reduce
          the new product failure rate, particularly by
          consulting customers at every stage of the development
          process
</ol>

III. Recognize the methods used to describe consumer responses to
     products
<ol>
<li>Marketers must be able to describe and understand how
          consumer react to products, for example, through the
          product adoption process that represents purchase
          patterns when consumers are faced with new products
<li>The product life cycle model is a descriptive
          generalization about the pattern of market acceptance
          for products over a period time, from their
          introduction through their decline and eventual
          termination
<li>The international product life cycle describes how the
          life cycle of a product can be extended by introducing
          it to international markets where the product is new
<li>Product positioning refers to how consumers perceive
          brands comparatively and develop mental perceptual maps
          which locate products (particularly brands) in relation
          to one another on key attributes, as judged by the
          consumer
<li>Product repositioning is required when the initial
          positioning needs alteration, or changes in the
          competition or environment affect consumers' perception
          of the product
</ol>

IV.  Compare different product management strategies
<ol>
<li>Once a product is launched, it must be managed in order
          to achieve profitability and business goals
<li>No single management strategy is equally effective for
          all businesses
<li>Widely used management techniques include the use of
          brand managers, category managers, and a
          multifunctional business group
</ol>

V.   Identify contemporary product issues
<ol>
<li>Planned product obsolescence is a problem that
          frustrates consumers and marketers must heed, because
          consumers increasingly value durability and reliability
          in many different product categories, which is
          reflected in their purchase decisions 
<li>Consumer rights and government protection of those
          rights is an issue of continuing tension in the
          marketplace
<li>Product recalls are often undertaken voluntarily by
          producers but sometimes must be mandated by government
<li>Product liability is a complex and confusing issue
                    because liability laws differ among the states
</ol>
                    
<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  Why is product newness a matter of perspective?  <i>Product
newness depends on whose perspective is taken because a product
may be new to a business, an industry, consumers, or even a
country.</i>

<p>2.  Compare and contrast the three levels of product newness.  <i>A
continuous product innovation is a product that differs only
slightly from existing products.  A discontinuous product
innovation differs radically from existing products.  In between,
dynamically continuous product innovations differ from existing
products, but not dramatically.</i>

<p>3.  What are the ways businesses obtain products?  <i>Businesses
obtain products through such strategies as revitalize, extend,
acquire, duplicate, cooperate, and generate. </i>

<p>4.  Why would a business copy other businesses' products?  <i>A
business may copy products because it saves the costs associated
with research and development, as well as the risks associated
with new product introductions.  Many businesses are content to
collect less profits in return for less cost and risk.  </i>

<p>5.  Describe the product strategy with the greatest inherent
risk.  <i>New product development carries the greatest risk, but
also the greatest potential for profit and competitive advantage.</i>

<p>6.  Compare and contrast idea generation and idea screening. 
<i>Idea generation is a new product development step that calls for
offering as many different ideas as possible, without judging
their relative value.  In the idea screening step, ideas are
judged for their marketability, produceability, and potential
profitability.</i>

<p>7.  How are product concepts tested?  <i>Potential customers,
consumers who may purchase the new product and/or are purchasers
of similar products, are shown a model of the new product or
given a product description.  They are asked to respond to a
series of survey questions designed to determine their reactions
to the new product, particularly whether or not they would
purchase it.</i>

<p>8.  What is a test market?  <i>A traditional test market requires
selecting one or several test market locations, offering the
product there, evaluating consumer responses, and using that
information to project how the product may sell on a regional or
national basis.</i>

<p>9.  Why do so many new products fail?  What can be done to
reverse this trend?  <i>New products fail for a number of reasons,
including poor quality, high price, redundancy, bad timing, and
selecting the wrong target market.  One important way to combat
this problem is to get consumers (current or potential customers)
involved in the development process from the start, providing
their input so that product problems can be eliminated or reduced
before commercialization.</i>

<p>10.  Compare and contrast such consumer responses to products as
adoption, diffusion, and positioning.  <i>Consumers adopt (purchase)
products according to a process that includes awareness,
interest, evaluation, trial, decision, and adoption.  Innovations
diffuse through a market as different groups of consumers adopt a
new product, beginning with the innovators, then the mass market
(early and late adopters), and ending with the laggards. 
Positioning is a mental process where consumers develop mental
comparisons of products based on their perceptions of how 
products (brands) compare on valued attributes.  Marketers
influence consumer product positioning by providing information
and cues about product attributes for consumers to use in
establishing the mental comparisons.</i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 8.1 </h4>

<p>1.  Why are new products called the "lifeblood of a company?" 
<i>Because they promise profits, growth, and even survival. 
Consumers want new products and marketers deliver them.</i>

<p>2.  Explain this statement: "Newness is a matter of perspective." 
<i>Newness depends on who or what is evaluating the product.  A
product may be new to a business, an industry, a consumer, or a
country.</i>
 
3.  Discuss the different ways a business may obtain products.
<i>Businesses obtain products through such strategies as revitalize,
extend, acquire, duplicate, cooperate, and generate.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 8.2 </h4>

<p>Identify the steps in the new product development process and
explain what happens in each step. 

<ul>
<i>
<li> Opportunity scanning - determining gaps in the marketplace
<li> Idea generation - brainstorming new product ideas
<li> Idea screening - ranking the ideas for their marketability,
     produceability, and potential profitability
<li> Concept testing - trying out the concept on consumers
<li> Market analysis and marketing plan development - evaluating
     the marketability of the product and developing a marketing
     plan
<li> Product production - making enough of the product so that it
     can be test marketed
<li> Test marketing - testing the product on consumers in one or
     several test market locations
<li> Commercialization - if the test market results are good,
     launching the product 
</i>
</ul>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 8.3 </h4>

<p>1.  What advantages do multifunctional development teams have in
the development of new products?  <i>Interactions between
professionals representing different business areas can cut
development times and lead to greater development effectiveness.</i>

<p>2.  Provide several explanations for why products fail.  <i>Products
fail for many reasons, including poor quality, high price,
redundancy, bad timing, and market size and target market
identity miscalculations.</i>

<p>3.  What steps can be taken to ensure product success?  <i.Perhaps
the most important thing a business can do is get consumers
involved in the development process from the beginning, listen to
their comments, take their suggestions, and integrate this
information into the development of the new product.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 8.4</h4>

<p>1.  Describe the product adoption process. <i>The individual becomes
aware of the product, becomes interested in it, evaluates it,
tries the product, decides whether to like it, then adopts
(purchases) the product.  Post-purchase confirmation determines
whether or not it was a "good" purchase.</i>

<p>2.  What is the product life cycle?  <i>The product life cycle
describes generally a process where products move through stages
from pre-introduction to introduction, growth, maturity, and
decline.  These stages reflect market adoption of the process
through purchase and repurchase.</i>

<p>3.  Explain the concept of product positioning and repositioning. 
<i>Product positioning is how consumers mentally perceive products
(brands) in relation to one another on several key attributes.
Marketers help consumers develop these perceptions through use of
price, place, and promotion, particularly advertisements,
personal selling, and sales promotions.  Repositioning is
sometimes needed, particularly when the original positioning
wasn't beneficial or when conditions change.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 8.5</h4>

<p>1.  Why do products need to be managed?  <i>Guidance is needed to
introduce the product, guide it in the marketplace, and ensure
profitability.  Managers make decisions about products, price,
place and promotion.</i>
 
<p>2.  Discuss the difference between a brand manager and a category
manager.  <i>A brand manager is responsible for managing a brand; a
category manager manages many brands within a category.</i>

<p>3.  Identify several contemporary product issues.  <i>Contemporary
product issues that concern marketers include consumer complaints
about planned product obsolescence, consumer rights, product
recalls, and product liability.</i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 8.1: Gillette's "Sensor for Women" Takes a Big Slice of the Market</h4>

<p>    This is an example of a company that did things right in the
development of a new product.  This product is so good that even
some men prefer using the Sensor for Women to other products! 
Students can collect consumer insights about Sensor and its main
competition, Warner-Lambert's Schick Silk Effects and Bic for
Sensitive Skin.  Survey the class and others about their
experiences with the Sensor, Schick, or Bic.  Have they tried any
of these products?  If so, how do they rate the products? 
Students can observe Sensor and its competitors on retailer's
shelves.  Are Schick and Bic serious threats to Sensor?  

<p>1.  Most new products "wear out" after a relatively short time,
particularly when their reign as market leader is threatened by
knockoff me-too products.  What can Gillette do to extend the
success of the Sensor for Women and repel knockoffs?  <i>What
Gillette can do is listen to consumers, find out what they want,
and continue to develop products to satisfy them.  They certainly
were successful with the original Sensor for Women, and it
appears they are successfully maintaining their brand leadership,
at least for the time being.</i>

<p>2.  If a brand life cycle were drawn for Sensor for Women, what
stage would it be in?  Explain your answer.  <i>From the information
provided in the case, it is still in its growth phase as
described by its continuing sales growth, but with the
competition heating up, it may soon enter into maturity when
sales level off. </i>

<p>3.  Considering the brand's market share, where is it in both the
adoption and diffusion of innovations processes?   <i>Judging from
its market share dominance, a majority of the target market has
purchased it and it has diffused to the mass market.</i>


<h4>Mini-Case 8.2: Brands Have Personalities, Too</h4>
 
<p>     Some brand personalities are obvious, particularly as
illustrated in print advertisements.  For example, a cleaning
product whose advertisements show the product's bottle dressed as
a knight in shining armor.  Many brands are heroes, at least in
the eyes of their brand managers!  Naturally, all brands need a
positive image to convey to consumers.  This is certainly the
case with personal use consumer products, far less so with
business/organization products. 

<p>     Have students collect print advertisements that show a
brand's personality.  Evaluate how these advertisements can help
consumers mentally position the brands in relation to the
competition.  Some successful brand personalities to look for are

<ul>
<li> Jello-O brand products' fun, playful, childlike personality
<li> Charmin bathroom tissues' soft, tender image
<li> Michelin tires' protecting, strong personality
<li> Mazda Miata's sporty, youthful personality
</ul>

<p>     Are there some brand personalities that don't make sense or
fail to match the product's characteristics?  Might these cases
call for repositioning the brand?  How could a brand manager
reposition the brand for consumers?

<p>1.  Why should a brand's personality be managed?  What might
happen if it were not managed correctly?  <i>Brands must be managed
successfully in order for them to be competitive in the
marketplace and gain profits.  If they are not managed well, they
can fail.</i>

<p>2.  Brands are also associated with colors.  Can you think of
some brands that are associated with certain colors?  <i>Kodak has
received legal protection for its distinctive colors, as has
Coca-Cola.  Print advertisements are an excellent source of
insight into colors that are used to identify products.</i>

<p>3.  For each of the following brands, think of one adjective that
describes the brand's personality (use stream-of-consciousness
thoughts to select the first adjective that pops into your mind): 
Coca-Cola, Jell-O, Mr. Coffee, Betty Crocker, IBM, Apple
Computer, and Disney.  <i>Student answers will vary, but some past
responses include</i>

<ul>
<li> Coca-Cola is friends, fun, good times
<li> Jell-O is fun, feel good, taste good
<li> Mr. Coffee is reliable, dependable
<li> Betty Crocker is sweet, warm, smells good
<li> IBM is strong, serious
<li> Apple Computer is friendly, fun, helpful
<li> Disney is for kids, good times, sharing
</ul>

                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     Procter & Gamble (P&G) is first and foremost a soap company. 
It has developed many market leading consumer workhorse brands
that are the polar opposites of luxury brands.  P&G is taking a
considerable risk marketing brands that cannot benefit from the
company's core competencies and image.  However, if P&G limits
its visible association with the luxury perfume brands and
maintains their European names, Laura Biagiotti's Venezia and
Ferragamo, the company's marketing expertise can make them
winners.  Have students debate this issue and if possible,
evaluate the brands as they are being sold at different
retailers.  How are the brands displayed?  Are they close to P&G
perfumes or are they physically located near other, European-imaged brands?  Is there such a thing as establishing an image by
association?

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>     Many of the Internet suggestions from Chapter 7 can also be
applied to this chapter.  It is extremely important that you
verify Internet addresses and confirm the feasibility of an
Internet assignment <b>before</b> you make it.  No guarantee of any
Internet address or information can be verified past the
publication date of this <b><i>Manual</b></i>.  Be sure to impress on your
students the importance of professional behavior on the Net, at
all times.

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>     Products of all kinds are offered on the Internet.  A recent
jughead search, using the word products, resulted in 24 computer
screens of product directories!  These screens provide links to
directories with menus of consumer products, shopping malls,
business in cyberspace, a product registry, and store fronts.  A
search with the words new products results in one screen of links
to new product directories.

<p>     Students can perform new product searches in different
product categories on the Internet through directories identified
in the jughead search, by searching with other search engines
(Yahoo, WebCrawler, Global Network Navigator) or by going
directly to the home pages of competing businesses to evaluate
their new product offers.

<i>
<p>     Access jughead and at the search URL
<br>     search:   products
<br>     -- or --
<br>     search:   new products

<p>     Yahoo          <a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>
<br>     WebCrawler     <a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     GNN            <a href="http://nearnet.gnn.com">http://nearnet.gnn.com</a>
</i>

<p>     Several businesses identified in this chapter can be visited
on the Internet.  They can be accessed through one of the search
engines by typing in the name of the company, or students can
visit their home pages directly.

<p>     Coors
<br><a href="http://www.zima.com/zimah.html">http://www.zima.com/zimah.html</a>
     
<p>     Goodyear Tire & Rubber Company
<br><a href="http://www.goodyear.com">http://www.goodyear.com</a>
     
<p>     The European Union can be reached through one of the search
engines or directly at
   
<br><a href="http://www.echo.lu">http://www.echo.lu</a>


<p>     The Consumer Product Safety Commission site was still on a
gopher server as this Manual was written.  Since some federal
government gopher servers, notably the Census Bureau's STAT-USA, 
are closing down and converting to Web sites only, the gopher
address for the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC)
must be checked for accuracy.  If it cannot be reached by gopher,
try fedworld or one of the search engines.  At the CPSC site,
students will find a description of what the agency does, as well
as a public calendar of CPSC activities, publications, and
hotline information.  Students might find some of the press
releases interesting.  For example, Release #95-135 reports on a
sharp increase in injuries suffered by in-line skating.  The
Commission estimates 105,000 in-line skating related injuries in
1995, which represents a 184 percent increase in two years.  It
outlines how in-line skate producers are cooperating with the
Commission to promote the use of safety gear by skaters.  

<p>     CPSC 
<br><a href="gopher://cpsc.gov">gopher://cpsc.gov</a>

<p>     alternately use a search engine -- or --
<br><a href="http://www.fedworld.gov">http://www.fedworld.gov</a>

<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 8.1</h4>

<p>     New and improved claims are common on grocery products in
certain categories, particularly laundry detergents and other
cleaning products.  The current interest in fat-free and low-fat
foods has led to a flurry of product revitalizations,
particularly in snack foods, deserts, and cereals that are "new
and improved".  This Application can also be used for gasoline
and pharmacy products.  Because of a recent federal regulation
that requires the addition of cleansing ingredients to gasoline
that will reduce air pollution, many gasoline brands are claiming
new and improved products.     


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 8.2</h4>

<p>     Private labels that mirror national brands are common in
many product categories.  Most consumers seem to like the look-alikes because they are usually cheaper than the originals. 
Other consumers are brand loyal and refuse to purchase look-alike
products, even if they are cheaper.  Students can debate the
benefits and costs of knock-offs, as well as relate their own
personal experiences with these products.  Have they mistakenly
purchased a look-alike and been pleased to discover that it
performs as well or better than the original?  Or, have they been
disappointed?


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 8.3</h4>

<p>     This informal survey of consumer adoption patterns for
microwave ovens, videocassette machines, cellular telephones,
personal computers, hand-held calculators, and fat-free cookies
can be extended to include others who may be more likely to have
purchased these products.  A survey of mostly traditional
students may provide limited insights into consumer adoption
processes because students may not have the discretionary income
to purchase most of the products.  However, this can lead to a
discussion of the relationship between product price and
involvement, and consumer adoption.  Ask how a consumer's
involvement (interest) can affect their adoption of new products,
and how their financial situation moderates the adoption process. 
In some cases, a consumer's need to be an innovator is the
strongest influence on new product adoption.  All of us probably
know at least one person or family that has to purchase every
electronic gadget the minute it is marketed.  A popular network
television situation comedy features just such a person, who has
a passionate interest in power tools that also extends to
household appliances.  He is a pushover for these new products
and has accumulated a large collection that gathers dust after
the newness has worn off.


<h4>ARKETING APPLICATION 8.4 </h4>

<p>     If you didn't assign the perceptual map in Chapter 7, then
you might want to use it here.  Substitute other car types, if
preferred.  Prices for these cars can be found on the Internet
using any of the search engines.


<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>

<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 8.1</h4>

<p>     What has happened to clear colas?  They were really hot when
they were first introduced, but the marketing push appears to
have fallen off considerably.  Have students perform a quick
product inventory at several local retailers to determine the
current state of clear colas and relate this to the topic of fads
and product proliferation.


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 8.2</h4>

<p>     Not all innovative new products come from large
multinational corporations.  Many outstanding product ideas are
generated by observant small businesspeople who recognize an
opportunity and seize on it.  For example, in my hometown a 
warehouse owner recognized an opportunity to market his 176,000
square foot space as a mini-mall.  The previously vacant
warehouse is adjacent to a major state university.  Retailers
with products that appeal to teens and college age consumers are
flocking to rent space.  New tenants in this highly successful
location include a nightclub, a new and used compact disc shop, a
comic book and gaming store, tanning salon, laser game center,
and several restaurants (Pack 1995).

<p><b>Reference </b>
<p>     Pack, Todd (1995), "Center's Businesses Focus on Teens,
     College Students," <i>Lexington Herald-Leader</i> (June 29): C9.


<h4>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>     The Russian market is still highly risky.  While many
Western businesses are profiting there, others are pulling back
or out, unwilling to continue trying to cope with the
disorganization, uncertainty, and bureaucracy.  Product newness
in international markets has initial advantages; however, the
benefits must outweigh the costs.</p>
<p>

