<head>
<title>CHAPTER 15: MANAGING MARKETING</title>
</head>

<h1><center>CHAPTER 15</h1>
<h1>MANAGING MARKETING</h1>
</center>

<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>

<p><b>1. Explain the role of the marketing manager.  </b>Marketing managers
guide marketing programs and people in the many different
activities associated with offering products to markets. 
Marketers are information conduits, communicating information
about products to personal use and business/organization
consumers, and bringing information back to the business about
consumers, the competition, and other important factors in the
environment.  There is no single marketing organization structure
that fits all businesses equally well.  Recent trends toward
flattening corporations, reducing the number of layers of
bureaucracy, gives greater power to individuals to take
responsibility for their jobs and make decisions.  In
multibusiness corporations, marketing management begins at the
top with a corporate level vice president for marketing.  Some
marketing managers are responsible for marketing in all of the
corporation's businesses.  At lower levels, category managers
oversee the marketing of entire categories of products with their
many different brands.  Brand managers are responsible for
managing the marketing of one or several related brands.  Other
forms include marketing managers for geographical territories,
consumer targets, or different operations such as personal
selling or new product development.  Marketing managers are often
called mini-general managers because they perform many of the
same tasks as a general manager, but only for marketing
activities.  Marketing activities are also managed in small and
mid-size businesses.  Marketing management means making decisions
about people, money, technology, and materials through the
interlinked processes of planning, implementation, and control. 
The marketing program is all the various operating marketing
plans and activities that represent the total marketing effort at
any particular time.


<p><b>2. Explain the role of the marketing plan.  </b>The marketing plan is
the blueprint for what marketing is to accomplish over a period
of time, usually one year and sometimes two.  The marketing plan
must be compatible with and complement plans for other
operational areas.  Marketing plans specify product-market
matches, marketing mix tactics, evaluation and control
mechanisms, and resource allocations.  A marketing plan for a
small business usually is less formal and complex than a
marketing plan for a large company.  A large company may have
hundreds of different marketing plans operating at one time; a
small business may have only one marketing plan.  There are many
advantages to marketing planning.  One is that it forces
marketers to systematically address issues that affect business
success and possibly, survival.  The planning process calls for
evaluating the business's customer base.  This often reveals that
relatively few customers are responsible for most of the sales. 
This is the 80-20 Rule, where 80 percent of sales are generated
by as few as 20 percent of the customers. 


<p><b>3. Describe implementation activities.  </b>Marketing plans are
meaningless unless and until they are implemented. 
Implementation is the activation of a marketing plan, when
people, money, technology, and materials are brought together to
execute marketing mix tactics and achieve marketing objectives. 
Implementation requires organizing people to perform marketing
activities.  Good implementation cannot save a flawed marketing
plan.  Three key activities involved in implementation are
organizing, staffing, and supervising employees.  Implementation
often is difficult because it involves change and people have a
tendency to resist change.  Other implementation problems
frequently are the result of communication problems and internal
disputes over resources.  


<p><b>4. Explain the function of marketing control.  </b>Control is the
evaluation of marketing performance and outcomes in order to
learn whether or not marketing goals have been met, and, if not,
why not.  Controls provide information that can be used to change
marketing plans and their implementation.  Control is extremely
important when the competition is intense because good controls
can lead to a competitive advantage by improving the efficiency
and effectiveness of marketing activities.  Control tracks
performance and outcomes using such measures as sales, market
share, costs, and customer satisfaction.  Many businesses use a
marketing audit to determine how effectively marketing is being
managed.  This audit of the business's marketing activities is
usually conducted by impartial external consultants hired for the
purpose.


<p><b>5. Describe how control results may be applied in marketing.</b>
Control results may indicate that things are running smoothly and
only slight corrections are needed.  In other cases, control
results may show that there are serious problems, so a more
drastic response may be needed.  Some U.S. companies faced with
quality control problems have turned to Japanese quality control
methods.  This includes kaizen, a commitment to continual
improvement that seeks to make products and processes better, and
thereby enhance quality.  Control results may indicate that
changes should be made in product and market mixes or in
strategies designed to grow the business.  Product portfolio
models may be used to differentiate the relative market share or
profit contribution of different products to the business.  While
product portfolio models may have descriptive value, their
prescriptive value is dubious.  Growth decisions in products and
markets can be categorized within a product/market opportunity
matrix.  The four cells of the matrix include a market
penetration strategy which calls for increasing sales of existing
products among current target markets without changing the
products or markets.  A market development strategy calls for
entering new markets with the same products.  A product
development strategy calls for changing products, or adding new
ones, to existing markets.  Diversifying means offering new
products to new markets.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>     The chapter opening questions ask: What does it take to
manage marketing successfully?  Why is it sometimes so difficult
to do?  Being a successful marketing manager is like being a
successful manager in any profession.  Some of the skills
required for good management are general, shared by managers in
many different professions.  Other skills are specific to the
marketing activities in which the manager is engaged.  Some of
the most important general skills involve people, communications,
and decisions.  Good managers must be able to work effectively
and productively with other people, including peers, superiors,
and subordinates, whether inside or outside the business.  Good
managers must be able to communicating clearly and decisively. 
They must make good and timely decisions after carefully weighing
all the facts and considering possible outcomes.  These decisions
often involve people, resources, technology, and time.
 
<p>     Good marketing managers also must have good marketing skills
that are specific to the marketing activities in which they are
engaged.  This means that if they are involved in marketing
research, they must have solid skills in being able to plan,
implement, and evaluate research results, and apply outcomes to
marketing problems.  If they are involved in retailing,
wholesaling, or any of the myriad activities that comprise
marketing, they must possess relevant skills in these area, as
well as the general skills required of any manager.

<p>     Even when a marketing manager has both general and specific
skills, circumstances can compromise his or her ability to
manage.  Marketing is not conducted in a vacuum.  The environment
is volatile and the competition doesn't sit around waiting for
your next move.  Sometimes dissension within the manager's own
company can play havoc with decisions and plans.  Squabbles over
resources and turf conflicts over power and control can undermine
even the best manager.  Consequently, considering all of the
factors that can compromise good marketing management, it is
probably a wonder that so much good marketing management occurs.

<p><b>Wrapping Up The Consumer And New Product Letters</b>

<p>     If you assigned the consumer and new product letters at the
beginning of the term, this is a good point to evaluate the
results of those efforts.  Ask any student who has not previously
brought a response to class, to do so now.  I usually spend about
20 to 25 minutes on this concluding activity.  Each student is
given an opportunity to restate the nature of their letter,
identify the product and company, and describe any response that
was received.  Students are encouraged to consider whether or not
they have changed their opinion about their target company based
on the outcome.  Sometimes they are disappointed that they
received nothing or only a cursory form letter.  Other times they
are so impressed with the response that as a result, they form a
new and better image of the company.  Ask the question: How does
good customer service affect the positioning of the product in
the consumer's mind?  This can be answered from the perspective
of student consumers who have received good or bad customer
service.  Ask students to consider what this has to do with
relationship marketing.  

<p><b>Guest Speakers</b>

<p>     The topics covered in this, the final chapter, lend
themselves to guest speakers, experienced marketing managers who
can add new perspectives based on years of observation and
personal experience.  In addition to asking any guest to speak
about their area of expertise, you might want to also ask them to
share their perspectives about career opportunities in their
professional specialty and specific skills that entry level
employees must hold.  Brand and category managers; advertising,
sales, and promotions are among the specialists that you might
consider inviting to class.

<p><b>Developing Student Self-Marketing Skills</b>

<p>     Even if a student does not intend to major in marketing or
become a marketer, he or she can use the skills learned in your
class to market themselves to prospective employers.  This is a
topic in Appendix C of the textbook and is addressed in the Study
Guide.  Encourage your students to develop a self-marketing plan. 
The process of systematically addressing each of the questions
outlined in a self-marketing plan will help them realistically
assess their strengths and weaknesses, as well as their
opportunities and the threats to their landing the job that they
really want.  

<p>     From my experience, students typically wait until the last
minute to start their job search.  At the end of every term, I am
approached by students who are nearing graduation and have
panicked because they don't have a job waiting for them.  Their
excuse for delaying the job hunt usually is that they've been too
busy!  Unless they're very luck, if you meet them in the next few
months, they are still looking for a job.  The competition is too
intense and the job market too volatile for most students to
blithely walk directly from the classroom to the office without a
considerable and lengthy effort.

<p><b>Business Etiquette</b>

<p>     If your school is like mine, there is no room in the
curriculum for students to learn about business etiquette.  This
is an area that should be discussed because it has grave
implications for how others perceive the recent graduate, as a
polished beginning professional or as someone prone to
embarrassing mistakes in business protocol.

<p>     This topic can be introduced as a complement to discussions
of customer service and relationship marketing.  When identified
with these activities, it becomes clear why proper business
behavior is very important to marketing success.

<p>     Some of the areas where students must be wary of business
faux pas are

<ul>
<li>in telephone communications, taking too long to return calls
     or not returning them, being abrupt or impolite with
     callers, failing to name yourself and your business, not
     apologizing for dialing wrong numbers, speaking indistinctly
     or too loudly, letting distracting background noise
     (including music on an office radio) interrupt the
     conversation

<li>in shaking hands, using the bone crushing grasp, a slap, or
     an overly gentle shake.  For men, failing to shake hands
     with a professional woman or holding a woman's hand too
     long.  For women, failing to shake hands at all

<li>in using first names, calling a customer or a manager by
     their first name, which is inappropriate unless told to do
     so by the person 

<li>in thanking people, failing to do so or waiting too long to
     call or send a thank you note

<li>in meetings, not paying attention to other speakers, reading
     mail during the meeting, doodling, coming late to meetings
     or leaving early without reason
</ul>

<p>     As you think about your experiences with businesspeople, you
will probably think of many other suggestions to pass on to your
students.  If you have non-traditional students in class, ask
them to share some of their observations on the importance of
business etiquette and faux pas they have experienced.


<p><b>     Reference</b>
<p>     Kelley, Craig A. (1992), "Educating Marketing Students in
     the Art of Business Etiquette," <i>Journal of Marketing
     Education</i> (Summer): 34-37.

<p><b>A Final Word About Marketing</b>

<p>     I began this writing project because I wanted to share my
enthusiasm for teaching marketing.  My fondest hope is that my
efforts will help make teaching marketing easier and more
enjoyable for you and others.  Please let me know if you have
suggestions for improving the textbook and this Manual.  Thank
you.


<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Explain the role of the marketing manager
<ol>
<li>Marketing managers guide marketing programs and people
          in the diverse activities associated with offering
          products to markets
<ul>
<li>Marketers act as information conduits, bringing
               information from outside into the business;
               transmitting information about products outside,
               to consumers
<li>There is no single marketing organization
               structure that is best suited to all businesses
<li>A recent trend in management is to reengineer the
               business and adopt the flattened hierarchy of the
               horizontal corporation in order to eliminate
               barriers between employees, improve processes that
               add value to products, and ultimately better serve
               consumers
</ul>
<li>In multibusiness corporations with traditional
          organizational structures, the top marketing manager
          usually is a vice president who reports directly to the
          CEO, the corporation's top manager
<ul>
<li>Some marketing managers are responsible for
               marketing activities in all of a corporation's
               strategic business units (SBU); others may manage
               marketing in one SBU     
<li>Category managers manage the marketing of an
               entire category of products, typically with many
               different product lines
<li>Brand managers are responsible for marketing a
               single brand
<li>Other organizational marketing management forms
               include having marketing managers for different
               operations like sales force, promotion, and
               marketing research; marketing managers for
               different geographical operations; and marketing
               managers for different target customer groups
<li>Marketing managers may focus on only one part of
               the entire organization, marketing, but they often
               are regarded as mini-general managers because they
               perform the same tasks as general managers,
               although in a smaller, more concentrated, focused
               operational area
</ul>
<li>Marketing activities also must be managed in small and
          mid-size businesses
<ul>
<li>In a small business, marketing management often is
               mostly sales force management because the sales
               force represents the largest part of the workforce
<li>Marketing management in a small business differs
               in formality and complexity from marketing
               management in a large organization; however, what
               a small business marketer lacks in resources can
               be overcome through creativity and quick responses
               to changes in the environment
</ul>
<li>Marketing management means making decisions about
          people, money, technology, and materials through the
          interlinked processes of planning, implementing, and
          control, specifically through
<ul>
<li>Formulating marketing strategies
<li>Planning marketing activities
<li>Implementing marketing programs
<li>Supervising and leading marketing personnel
<li>Allocating resources
<li>Evaluating marketing outcomes
</ul>
<li>The marketing program is all the various operating
          marketing plans and activities that represent the total
          marketing effort at a particular time
</ol>

II.  Explain the role of the marketing plan
<ol>
<li>The marketing plan is the blueprint for what marketing
          is to accomplish
<ul>
<li>It typically covers a one year period, but
               sometimes may be written for two years
<li>The marketing plan must be compatible with and
               complement plans from other operational areas
<li>Marketing plans specify product-market matches,
               marketing mix tactics, evaluation and control
               mechanisms, and resource allocations
</ul>
<li>The small business marketing plan usually is not as
          detailed or formal as marketing plans written in large
          businesses
<ul>
<li>The value of planning is that by addressing each
               of the marketing plan's sections, the business is
               forced to confront issues that are key to its
               future success, if not survival
<li>By evaluating its customer base during the
               planning process, it may be found that a large
               volume of sales is generated by a small number of
               customers, this often follows the 80-20 rule,
               where 80 percent of the revenue is generated by 20
               percent of the customers
</ul>
</ol>


III. Describe implementation activities
<ol>
<li>Marketing plans by themselves are meaningless, unless
          and until they are activated
<ul>
<li>Implementation is the activation of a marketing
               plan, when people, money, technology, and
               materials are brought together in an organized way
               to execute marketing mix tactics and achieve
               marketing objectives
<li>Implementation requires organizing people to get
               marketing done, as well as filling in the details
               of the work they are to perform, and providing
               sufficient money, materials, technology, and
               leadership so they can do their jobs well 
<li>Good implementation cannot save a flawed marketing
               plan
</ul>
<li>Three key activities associated with implementation are
          organizing, staffing, and supervising
<ul>
<li>Leadership is an important ingredient in
               successful implementation because it has a direct
               impact on performance
<li>Many contemporary marketing managers are
               empowering employees to made decisions and take
               responsibility for their work
</ul>
<li>Implementation is not always easy because people often
          resist change and sometimes, implementation requires it
<ul>
<li>Other implementation problems are associated with
               communication problems
<li>Internal disputes over resources can distract
               attention from implementation activities
<li>Marketing managers must identify threats to
               implementation before they can begin to resolve
               them
</ul>
</ol>

IV.  Explain the function of marketing control
<ol>
<li>Control is the evaluation of marketing performance and
          outcomes in order to learn whether or not marketing
          goals have been met and, if not, why not
<ul>
<li>Controls can provide useful information that can
               lead to changes in marketing plans and
               implementation activities
<li>Control is particularly important when the
               business faces intense competition, because an
               effective control system can be a way to achieve
               competitive advantage
<li>Control must be systematic
</ul>
<li>Control tracks performance and outcomes using such
          common measures as sales, market share, costs, and
          customer satisfaction
<li>A marketing audit is an unbiased, comprehensive
          examination of the business's marketing activities that
          is conducted periodically by impartial auditors as a
          control activity
</ol>


V.   Discuss how control results may be applied in marketing  
<ol>
<li>Control results are meaningless unless they activate a
          response
<li>When faced with control results that indicate quality
          problems, some U.S. businesses adopted the Japanese
          philosophy of kaizen, a commitment to continual
          improvement that seeks to make products and processes
          better, and, thereby enhance quality
<li>Control results may indicate that product and/or market
          changes are needed
<ul>
<li>Product portfolio models have descriptive value
               but often result in dubious prescriptions of what
               to do with a portfolio of products 
<li>Growth decisions in products and markets may be
               placed in the context of a product/market growth
               opportunity matrix
<ol>
<li>A market penetration strategy calls for
                    increasing sales of existing products among
                    current target markets without changing the
                    products or markets
<li>A market development strategy calls for
                    entering new markets with the same products
<li>A product development strategy calls for
                    changing products, or adding new ones, to
                    existing markets
<li>Sometimes, the strategy calls for
                    diversifying, offering new products to new
                    markets
</ol>
<li>Other product decisions include maintaining the status quo, divestment, and product termination
</ul>
</ul>

<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  Why are marketers called boundary spanners?  Do you think
this is an appropriate designation?  <i>Marketers are boundary
spanners because they connect the business with its external
environments and facilitate exchanges between the business
(through its products) and consumers.</i>

<p>2.  Contrast the jobs of category manager and brand manager.
<i>Category managers are marketing managers who are responsible for
marketing a business unit's related product lines, as in laundry
detergents, diapers, or deodorants.  A brand manager is a
marketing manager who is responsible for marketing one or more
related brands.</i>

<p>3.  How are the jobs of general manager and marketing manager
alike? <i>A company's general manager is responsible for the
operations of a business or a business unit.  Broadly this
manager accomplishes organizational goals through planning,
organizing, directing, and controlling organizational resources. 
A marketing manager performs the same kinds of tasks, but in a
more focused, concentrated way, to manage marketing activities.</i>

<p>4.  Why are small businesses important to the economy and
marketing?  <i>Small businesses create new jobs, generate employee
salaries, produce revenues, and contribute to the general running
of the economy.  They help balance supply and demand, and clear
the market.  Small businesses operate in retailing, wholesaling,
and services.</i>

<p>5.  What is the marketing program?  Why does it require careful
coordination?  <i>A marketing program is all the various operating
marketing plans and activities that represent the total marketing
effort at a particular time.  To keep everything operating,
without duplications and conflict, requires careful coordination
of people, resources, and activities.</i>

<p>6.  Discuss the interrelationship and interdependence of
planning, implementation, and control. <i>These interlinked
processes are the way that marketing activities are managed, by
marketing managers who make decisions about people, money,
technology, and materials.  Plans must be implemented before they
can be of value to the business.  Once implemented, they must be
controlled in order to determine shortcomings and successes, and
collect feedback that can be used to modify marketing activities
and make new marketing plans.</i>

<p>7.  Explain why ignoring the 80-20 rule can be a serious mistake
for the marketing manager.  <i>This rule, which is an observation,
states that 80 percent of a business's revenue often is generated
by only 20 percent of its customers.  Ignoring this rule can be
costly, particularly if excessive marketing effort is directed at
the 80 percent of customers who account for only 20 percent of
the revenue.</i>

<p>8.  Compare and contrast authoritarian and participative
management styles.  <i>Traditional authoritarian management styles
usually fit pyramid shaped organizations where power and control
are top down and people do what they are told.  In a
participative management system, employees participate in
decision making and are empowered to make decisions for
themselves, take responsibility, and develop ways to work more
productively.</i>

<p>9.  Could a business exist for long without some controls? 
<i>Controls are essential to a business, for they determine whether
or not implemented marketing plans are meeting their goals.</i>

<p>10. What role does marketing play in the consumer's life?  In
society?  <i>Marketing plays a very important role in the life of
consumers and society.  Some of the ways that marketing
contributes is by </i>

<ul>
<li>providing products that consumers need and want

<li>offering products at prices that consumers find acceptable

<li>placing products where consumers want them, when they are
     wanted
<li>informing consumers about products, prices, and places

<li>employing millions of people in the United States and abroad

<li>contributing to the economic health of the nation by
     encouraging competition and the free market

<li>bringing supply and demand into balance

<li>helping clear the market of excess supply

<li>generally contributing to the high quality of life that most
     people enjoy
</ul>

<p>     Marketing is also criticized for many shortcomings,
including contributing to excessive consumption, cluttering
society with too many products and promotions, and engaging in
questionable practices, some of which are illegal and others are
both illegal and unethical.  
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 15.1 </h4>

<p>1.  What is the role of the marketing manager?  <i>Marketing
managers guide marketing programs and people in the diverse
activities associated with offering products to markets. They
make critical decisions involving people, resources, technology,
materials, and time.  They plan, implement plans, and control
them. </i>

<p>2.  Why are marketers called mini-general managers?  <i>Because the
tasks that they perform in marketing management are a small scale
equivalent of the tasks performed by general managers for the
entire business, strategic business unit, or corporation.</i>
 
<p>3.  What tasks are performed by marketing managers?  <i>They plan,
implement, and control marketing activities.  </i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 15.2 </h4>

<p>1.  How do marketing plans differ in large and small businesses? 
<i>Large businesses and corporations will typically have formal,
complex marketing plans.  They may have hundreds or even
thousands of marketing plans running concurrently.  Marketing
plans in a small business are less formal, less complex, and
there may be one marketing plan for the entire business.</i>

<p>2.  Explain how implementation activates the marketing plan.
<i>Implementation begins with the marketing plan, then brings
people, money, technology, and materials together in an organized
way to execute marketing mix tactics and achieve marketing
objectives, as defined in the plan.</i>
 
<p>3.  What are some implementation problems that marketing managers
may experience?  <i>Good implementation cannot save a flawed
marketing plan.  Communications problems and internal conflicts
over resources can undermine implementation activities.  Another
problem is when implementation requires change and many people
resist change as a threat.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 15.3 </h4>

<p>1.  Explain the use of marketing control systems.  <i>Marketing
control systems evaluate marketing performance and outcomes,
identify deficiencies and problems, then suggest places for
improvement.  Control also collects feedback information that can
be used in the formulation of new marketing plans.</i>

<p>2.  What is a marketing audit?  <i>A marketing audit is like an
accounting audit, only of marketing activities.  It is usually
performed by an external consultant, someone who can be objective
in evaluating how well the organization is implementing the
marketing plan and achieving marketing goals.</i>
            
<p>3.  How may control system results be used? <i>Control results can
be used to make corrections in the implementation process and as
feedback to new marketing plans.  Sometimes control results
indicate that changes must be made in the products that a company
offers.  If the company has growth goals, control results can
indicate whether growth strategies are working and if changes
should be made.</i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 15.1: China Coast Restaurants - Coast To Coast</h4>
    
<p>    Restaurants, like any retail business, need marketing.  Large
restaurant operations have marketing managers who are responsible
for planning, implementing, and controlling the company's
marketing.  Identify a restaurant or chain in your area that
actively markets itself.  If possible, invite its marketing
manager to speak to your class about managing the restaurant's
marketing program.  

<p>1.  Explain how marketing managers may use planning,
implementation, and control in determining whether or not to
expand the China Coast chain nationwide. <i>They will have to
construct a marketing plan for the chain, and plans for each of
the initial outlets.  Approved plans must be implemented. 
Implemented plans must be controlled.  This means monitoring
marketing activities to determine if marketing goals and
objectives are being met.  Control activities provide feedback
which can be used to make needed alterations in implementing the
marketing plan(s).  The information collected through control
activities can be used in developing new marketing plans.</i>

<p>2.  General Mills is trying to grow a new business.  <i>Where would
this fit in the product/market growth opportunity matrix shown in
Figure 15.7 (i.e., what strategy is it?  Explain your answer. The
company already has other restaurant chains, so this is not
diversification.  The restaurants will probably be located in the
same markets as other General Mills restaurants, so it is not
market development.  Since the new restaurants can be considered
changes from existing company products (its other restaurants),
the strategy is product development.</i>


<h4>Mini-Case 15.2  Managing Marketing And The Information Revolution</h4>

<p>     Marketing managers can realize many advantages from the
effective use of information technology.  However, the abundance
of information that is readily available can also be
overwhelming.  If you have a marketing manager come to class as a
guest speaker, include this issue among the topics he or she is
asked to address.  How is the information revolution and new
technologies affecting marketing management in his or her
company?  Are the new technologies making workers more productive
or are some of the technologies actually impeding them?

<p>1.  How can the information revolution help marketing management?
<i>The information revolution can help marketing managers if the
information is used effectively in getting people to work more
productively.  Productivity is an issue of great significance, 
and businesses must continually seek new ways of increasing
productivity in order to stay competitive.  Many new technologies
offer the hope of improving information management and therefore,
improving the ability of workers to do their jobs effectively.  </i>

<p>2.  How can the information revolution frustrate marketing
management?  <i>The volume of information that is now available at
people's fingertips can be overwhelming.  Instead of helping
people make better decisions and work more productively, this
information clutter can make it more difficult to sort through
and find usable information.  Therefore, instead of being a help,
it can be a hindrance.</i>

<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     How much of a contribution do small businesses make in your
city?  You can research the size and composition of your local
population of small businesses by contacting the chamber of
commerce or a Small Business Development Center.  If any of your
students currently work for a small business, ask them to share
their observations about how small businesses improve their
productivity.  Are they using some of the strategies identified
in this chapter?  Are they working?

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>     Please verify all Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment <b>before</b> you make it.  No
Internet address or information can be guaranteed past the date
of this <b><i>Manual's</b></i> publication.  Be sure to insist that students
demonstrate professional conduct at all times on the Internet. 
If they seek job information, urge them to be cautious in
evaluating information and job offers; be extremely wary of "get
rich quick schemes."  The safest course is to concentrate on
information from universities, well known businesses, government
offices, and established Internet job information providers.

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>     Traditional students who aspire to become marketing managers
must take the same first step, they must obtain an entry level
job.  Non-traditional students who wish to change career paths
also must become job seekers.  The Internet can help both types
of job seekers.  The Net is emerging as a rich resource for job
and career information.  You can help your students find their
way through the maze of Internet addresses by checking sites in
advance.  The following suggestions are starting points that can
lead to career and job sites that may prove of value to you and
your class.

<p>     A job hunt can proceed along many different Internet paths.  
    A Yahoo search provides links to many sources of career and
     job information.

<i>
<br><a href="http://www.Yahoo.com">http://www.Yahoo.com</a>
<br>     Business
<br>     Employment
<br>     Careers
<br>     -- or --
<br>     Employment Services
<br>     -- or --
<br>     Jobs
</i>

<p>   Many large companies have job information at their sites on
     the World Wide Web.  Students can visit these sites to
     determine if the listed employment opportunities are
     appropriate to their interests and level of training.  Use
     the URLs for any companies previously identified, or run a
     search for a specific company through one of the primary
     search engines.

<p>    Two government publications provide information about
     careers and employment trends.  There are many different
     paths to these publications.  The publications to look for
     are the  "Occupational Outlook Handbook", U.S. Department of
     Labor, and the "U.S. Industrial Outlook", Department of
     Commerce.

<i>
<p>     University of Missouri-St. Louis

<p>     Occupational Handbook 1993-1994
<br><a href="gopher://umslvma.umsl.edu:70/11/library/govdocs/ooha">gopher://umslvma.umsl.edu:70/11/library/govdocs/ooha</a>

<p>     U.S. Industrial Outlook 1994
<br><a href="gopher://umslvma.umsl.edu:70/11/library/govdocs/usio94">gopher://umslvma.umsl.edu:70/11/library/govdocs/usio94</a>

<p>    Many universities offer career guides and links to other
     career sources.

<p><a href="gopher://riceinfo.rice.edu:70/11/Subject/Jobs">gopher://riceinfo.rice.edu:70/11/Subject/Jobs</a>

<p>     West Georgia College Gopher
<br>          JobNet
<br><a href="http://sun.cc.westga.edu/~coop/">http://sun.cc.westga.edu/~coop/</a>
     
<p>    The federal government has an address where federal jobs are
     listed.  Check individual agencies for listings.

<p><a href="http://www.fedworld.gov">http://www.fedworld.gov</a>
</i>

<p>    Other search engines can be used with an appropriate query,
     such as "job hunting on the Internet", "career guides",
     "jobs", and "employment".  See previous sections for URLs to
     WebCrawler, World Wide Web Worm, and others.

<h4>Small Business Jobs</h4>

<p>     Small businesses are given considerable credit for job
creation in the past decade.  For more information about the
Small Business Administration (SBA) and job creation by small
businesses, visit the SBA home page.

<i>
<p><a href="http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov">http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov</a>
</i>


<h4>Japanese Management</h4>

<p>     U.S. marketers must learn about their competition, and in
many product categories, strong competition comes from the
Japanese.  American business also has learned from the Japanese
about quality, team work, and inventory control methods.  You can
learn more about Japan by visiting Yahoo or searching with one of
the search engines.

<i>
<p><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>
<br>     * Regional Information
<br>     * Regions
<br>     * Asia
<br>     * Asia in Cyberspace
<br>     Select: Country
<br>     Select: Japan
</i>


<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>

<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 15.1</h4>

<p>     As with any small sample study, students must be cautioned
that because their study involves small numbers, their
observations on the job creation situation locally are tentative
and exploratory, at best.  These data cannot be used to form
generalizations about job creation.  However, that said, their
findings should spark a good discussion about where new jobs are
being formed and the types of skills they require.  Do the
students' results indicate that there is greater job creation in
higher technology companies?  Are computer skills being sought? 
What about the demand for people with good communication skills? 
Local information about job creation often can be obtained from
the city government, chamber of commerce, or state department of
labor.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 15.2</h4>

<p>     A panel of marketers can provide a more lively discussion
than a single speaker.  Discuss with your class the type of
format that would facilitate good coverage of the marketing
management topic.  Each speaker could be allowed several minutes
to make a presentation, or each could be asked to address several
questions about marketing management.  Your students can develop
questions to ask the panel.  Marketers representing different
professional backgrounds will provide a glimpse of the wide
variety of forms of marketing management that occur today. 
However, their presentations will also show that, despite the
differences, they perform the same basic type of job when it
comes to managing marketing, people, and resources.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 15.3</h4>

<p>     Contraseasonal marketing is one tactic to support a market
penetration strategy.  What are some others?  While students are
working to identify other contraseasonal tactics, they can also
think more broadly and consider other tactics that can be used to
penetrate markets.  Market penetration means growth through
stimulating sales in the existing markets.  This includes getting
consumers to stock up.  From their own experiences, what
marketing tactics get them to stock up, i.e., purchase a greater
than normal amount of a product?  What would a fast food
franchise do to grow through market penetration?  What about a
bookstore, a carpet cleaning company, or a florist?  

<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 15.1</h4>

<p>     To learn more about small businesses nationally, students
can investigate the Using the Internet section in this chapter.


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 15.2</h4>

<p>     Staffing is an important part of marketing management, in
both large and small businesses.  Your school placement or career
office may be able to provide information on differences in
hiring practices between the two extremes, the large corporation
and the small business.  Seek answers to such questions as

<ul>
<li>How do small businesses and large corporations recruit?

<li>Where can you find information about them?

<li>What is the selection process like for an entry level
     employee?  

<li>What type of interview are they likely to use?

<li>Who does the recruiting, interviewing, and selecting?

<li>What kind of training can be expected?
</ul>


<h4>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>     How are other U.S. businesses doing in Japan?  While U.S.
automobile companies are struggling, others are doing quite well. 
For more information on Japan see Using the Internet in this
chapter.</p>

