<head>
<title>CHAPTER 11: PLACE: DISTRIBUTION AND WHOLESALING</title>
</head>

<h1><center>CHAPTER 11</h1>
<h1>PLACE: DISTRIBUTION AND WHOLESALING</h1>
</center>

<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>

<p><b>1. Explain how distribution facilitates the flow of products from
producer to consumer.  </b>The modern channel of distribution is
composed of individuals and businesses that cooperate to
facilitate the movement of products from producers, at the point-
of-production, to consumers, at the point-of-sale.  Distribution
expedites marketing exchanges.  Many producers engage in dual
distribution, using dual channels to get products to consumers;
some use more channels.  Most product purchases require the use
of intermediaries.  Agents are intermediaries with legal
authority to act in the name of a manufacturer.  Brokers directly
bring sellers and buyers together.  A wholesaler is an
intermediary who sells to other intermediaries, most often to
retailers, the last member of the channel of distribution at the
point-of-sale to personal use consumers.  Both goods and services
must be distributed.  Distribution provides the utilities of
place, time, form, and possession.  Distributors perform such
marketing activities as exchange, physical distribution, and
servicing functions.


<p><b>2. Identify the factors that influence the development of a
channel structure.  </b>Channel structure is the form that a channel
takes, its length, arrangement, and size.  Some channel
structures are characteristic of a particular industry.  Most
channels are a function of company attributes, product type,
markets, competitors, custom, and conditions in the marketing
environment.  Channel structure is also influenced by
distribution strategy, how broadly or narrowly a product is
distributed.  The three principal strategic distribution
alternatives are intensive, selective, and exclusive
distribution.  Channels must be managed in order to run
efficiently and to avoid conflict and encourage cooperation. 
While manufacturers were at one time typically the captains of
their channels, considerable power has shifted to large
retailers.  Some channel members exert control over their
channels by buying other members through a process called
vertical integration.  Others buy out competitors at the same
level, through horizontal integration.  Just-in-time systems are
an attempt to make channels more effective and efficient. 
Reverse channels work to return products to producers for recall,
repair, or for recycling.


<p><b>3. Describe the different perspectives on channels of
distribution.  </b>Channels of distribution are changing due in large
part to the widespread use of sophisticated computer technology,
new information management techniques, and the blurring of
channel member roles.  Like most aspects of marketing, there are
many different perspectives on channels of distribution. 
Consumers sometimes complain about the added costs from
distribution, yet are unwilling to accept stockouts.  Large
retailers view channels as ways for them to achieve cost savings
and increase profitability by forcing members to be more
efficient.  Smaller retailers may believe they are at a cost
disadvantage in a channel because of the domination of large
retailers who exert their power to their own advantage.  
Efficient wholesalers view channels as their source of profit. 
Large manufactures realize that their days of unchallenged
channel power are over, now they must work to cooperate with
other channel members and particularly with powerful retailers.


<p><b>4. Explain the role of wholesalers.  </b>Wholesalers are channel of
distribution members that provide retailers with the products
they need.  They expedite the distribution of manufacturer's
products, and provide other businesses and organizations with
products.  Wholesalers undertake marketing tasks such as
purchasing, sorting, accumulating, storing, transporting, and
financing products.  Wholesaling is an important part of the U.S.
economy.  Wholesalers are typically classified as merchant
wholesalers, brokers and agents, and manufacturer's
representatives.  There are many subclassifications within the
types.  Wholesalers make decisions about products, prices,
promotions, and markets.


<p><b>5. Characterize the logistics/physical distribution functions.
</b>Some people make a distinction between logistics and physical
distribution.  Others consider them two functions within the same
general physical distribution process.  Physical distribution is
the marketing activity that moves raw materials and supplies into
production and finished products from producer to point of sale. 
Transportation is a large part of physical distribution, but it
also includes other activities such as packaging, order
processing, inventory control, and servicing.  Physical
distribution is expensive, so marketers must carefully decide
what level of service they need.  Several factors influence
physical distribution decisions including company resources,
product characteristics, and geography.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>     The chapter's opening question is, "If distribution is so
important a marketing function, why is it so invisible to most
personal use consumers?"  This is a problem for marketers,
because distribution adds value to the marketing exchange and
benefits consumers, yet most consumers are ignorant of the tasks
that distribution performs for them.  Have students consider the
question and decide whether it is important for marketers to
educate consumers about the role of distribution as it benefits
them personally.  Should consumers be educated about distribution
as it contributes to a smoothly operating business and, at the
level of the national economy, as it facilitates the clearing of
the market by keeping product supply flowing to accommodate
demand?  

<p>     Continue the discussion of the opening question by exploring
whether distribution is equally invisible to business and
organization consumers.  Should it be invisible or should a
business or organization be concerned about distribution and how
efficiently it is performed?  What are the risks if a business or
organization ignores its channels of distribution?  Consider this
question both from the standpoint of products needed at the
point-of-production and at the point-of-sale.

<p>     Because most students will not be familiar with distribution
activities, this is a good place to bring a guest speaker to
class.  Speakers may be found through a local American Marketing
Association chapter, other resources identified in Part V of this
<b><i>Manual</b></i>, or your local newspaper's business section, where the
dates and locations of professional meetings are listed.  You can
use this list to identify a distribution-related professional
organization to contact.  A guest could discuss distribution
generally, explaining how distribution adds value and serves
consumers, marketers, businesses, and the economy.  Alternately,
the discussion could be specific to a distribution topic, several
of which are identified in the following sections.  Suggestions
on planning for a guest speaker are offered in Part V of this
<b><i>Manual</b></i>.

<p><b>     The Distribution Of Flowers</b>

<p>     Channels of distribution for flowers are an interesting and
somewhat unusual topic to explore.  Flowers are big business in
Europe and parts of Asia for their cultural significance, as
gifts, and for aesthetic reasons.  Plant businesses are growing
in importance in the United States, particularly as plants are
used to enhance property value.  Many business opportunities
exist for marketers of cut flowers and houseplants, and in
related fields such as property landscaping.  Efficient
distribution of floral materials is critical because of their
perishability.  Students can research this topic on the Internet
(see <a href="#internet">Using the Internet</a> in this chapter).  A discussion of
channels of distribution for flowers also provides an opportunity
to introduce the broader topic of agricultural marketing, which
often is ignored in traditional marketing classes.

<p><b>     Real Estate Brokers</b>

<p>     Some of your students may be real estate brokers; others may
have family or friends who work in this field.  Brokers work as
mediators, bringing buyers and sellers together and helping them
negotiate a mutually satisfying exchange.  They perform highly
specialized functions and are usually paid primarily by
commission.

<p>     Real estate, like other products, is being offered on the
Internet (see <a href="#internet">Using the Internet</a> in this chapter).  Students can
investigate Internet real estate sites even without a graphical
browser, although the experience is much richer if they can view
the properties being offered using Mosaic or NetScape.  Can the
Internet replace real estate brokers?  This topic can be explored
by a guest speaker.  Ask this professional to discuss recent
innovations in the marketing of real estate, including cable real
estate television programs that show viewers homes that are for
sale, and marketing real estate on the Internet.  

<p><b>     Entertainment Distribution</b>

<p>     Another topic that usually interests students is the
distribution of entertainment products, such as music and motion
pictures.  The film industry has its own unique distribution
system, which has been featured recently in popular business
magazines.  Students can research the topic and report their
results to the class.  Faculty in a film or drama department at
your school may be able to provide a contact in the film
industry.  Alternately, try your local American Marketing
Association chapter or Chamber of Commerce for suggestions.  If
there is an independent movie theater in your city, the owner
might be able to share some insights on the difficulty of booking
films in competition with major theater chains.

<p><b>     Automobile Distribution</b>

<p>     In almost every introductory marketing class, there seems to
be at least one student who currently works for an automobile
dealer or has worked for one in the past.  This is another
channel of distribution system that interests students, often
because of the job opportunities it offers and because most of
them have experience at the automobile point-of-sale.  How does
the American automobile distribution system work?  Who dominates
an automobile channel of distribution?  For insights on
automobile distribution, contact a prominent auto dealer in your
area who can provide insights into how the automobile
distribution system is under pressure to change.

<p>     If you have international students in your class, ask them
to share their observations about automobile distribution in
their countries.  In many countries, automobile distribution is
quite different from distribution in the United States.  For
example, in Japan, automobiles are sold door-to-door, a very low
tech type of distribution in a very high tech society.  About
half of all automobiles are sold this way, often to the housewife
who traditionally makes most of the family's financial decisions
(Reitman 1994).  Japan is the world's second largest market for
automobiles, yet the United States has less than one percent of
the market.  Although Japan is about the size of California,
Toyota Motor Corp. by itself fields 100,000 salespeople, many of
whom walk door-to-door selling cars.  This example also
illustrates the importance of relationship marketing.  Japanese
automobile salesmen excel at building trust and long term
relationships with their customers, something American car makers
will find almost impossible to counter in the Japanese market.

<p><b>     Reference</b>
<p>     Reitman, Valerie (1994), "Toyota Calling: In Japan's Car
     Market, Big Three Face Rivals Who Go Door-To-Door, <i>The Wall
     Street Journal</i> (September 28): A1,6.
     

<p><b>     Franchise Distribution</b>

<p>     Many small businesspeople own franchises, such as a
McDonald's, KFC, or Dairy Queen.  Some franchise owners complain
about being captives of their franchisor's distribution system. 
Many are bound to the tight restrictions of a contracted system
where they must make product purchases from the owner of the
system.  While many franchise owners are happy with their
distribution system, others are not.  Students may be able to
share observations based on their experiences working in a
franchise.  If not, you might consider this as a topic for a
guest speaker to address. 

<p><b>The Internet And Distribution</b>

<p>     The Internet offers a serious potential challenge to
traditional distribution systems.  It takes very little effort
for a producer to set up a home page on the World Wide Web and
sell products, often delivering them by Federal Express (FedX) or
United Parcel Service (UPS).  Store retailers and wholesalers can
be eliminated in the process.  Production can be on-demand as
customer orders are received, which reduces inventory, storage,
and holding costs.  

<p>     If you have been assigning Internet activities throughout
the term, students should have developed a fairly sophisticated
perspective about Internet commerce.  The threat of the Internet
to traditional channels can be developed as a topic for class
debate.  One side can prepare the position that the Internet will
not alter traditional channel structures; the other side can
argue the opposite.  Two key questions should be addressed: 
(1) How do consumers benefit from Internet distribution?
(2) How do businesses benefit from Internet distribution?

<p><b>Adding Value Through Distribution</b>

<p>     A business that has a competitive advantage is able to
deliver better value to consumers than the competition.  Most
businesses seek to establish a competitive advantage because that
means that consumers value its products and will purchase and
repurchase them.  Through these purchases (exchanges) the
business collects revenues and, assuming that it is run
efficiently, earns profits at greater than the industry average. 
It is essential for the marketer to determine what consumers
value, in product performance and price, then deliver it at the
lowest possible cost.  Only when the competitive advantage is
sustained over time can it be defined as a strategic competitive
advantage.

<p>     A value delivery system can be conceptualized as having
three component processes: choosing the value, providing the
value, and communicating the value (Czepiel 1992).  To choose the
value means selecting the value that benefits consumers and the
businesses' own competencies.  To provide the value means
focusing every subsequent activity throughout the business on
delivering that value.  Finally, to communicate the value means
informing consumers about the value through effective promotional
activities.  The value chain is all of the processes required to
deliver value, from determining what consumers value, to product
design and production, through distribution and promotion.

<p>     Value is added when raw materials and supplies are brought
into production and transformed into finished products.  The
processing of materials and supplies adds value, but it also adds 
costs.  Value is added as different product forms, sizes, colors,
or models are produced.  The variations are designed to satisfy
different consumer segments.  Product differentiation adds value
for the consumers who will benefit from them; it lessens their
value for consumers who will not benefit from them.  Generally,
greater differentiation also means greater costs.

<p>     Value is added when products are made available for
consumers when and where they need them.  Like product
differentiation, distribution differentiation also adds costs. 
Channel value is the value added by the physical transportation
of products to various points in the delivery system; by 
accumulating, sorting, and assorting products so that the
appropriate selection of products is routed to other middlemen;
through taking and filling orders, financing, inventory control,
storage, and the assumption of risk.  The retailer contributes to
channel value by making good location decisions, providing a
trained staff, offering credit, stocking and restocking, pricing,
and performing the marketing functions needed in order to bring
the right products to the point-of-sale.
    
<p>     Distribution adds value from point-of-production to point-of-sale.  It also adds costs, which explains why distribution can
become a key factor in determining strategic competitive
advantage.  The channel that operates at the greatest efficiency
and lowest cost often creates a competitive advantage that others
will have great difficulty matching, as shown by Wal-Mart. 

<p>     Consumers have grown accustomed to broad product assortments
and well stocked shelves, yet for the most part they remain
unaware of what it takes to deliver place utility.  Students
should learn about value chains both as future business people
and as consumers.  This can be personalized by asking them to
identify value driven retailers.  For example, supermarkets that
recognize how much some consumer segments value fresh produce and
salad bars.  Many supermarket chains are allocating more space to
value added salads and fruits in an attempt to satisfy consumers
and raise revenues (De Santa 1995).  

<p>     What do your students value as consumers?

<ul>
<li>How do they feel about the value of double pizzas for the
     price of one?

<li>Do they agree with a recent survey of almost 3,000
     restaurant consumers that the chains delivering the best
     value are Wendy's (hamburgers), Pizza Hut (pizza), Chi-Chi's
     (Mexican food), and Baskin-Robbins (sweets)? (McDowell 1995) 
     
<li>What do they perceive as the value of a 10-minute oil
     change?  

<li>What is the value added at a laundry that washes, dries, and
     folds your clothes?  

<li>What about the value added at a supermarket that has baggers
     who carry your groceries to your car?

<li>How much do they value a car dealer who provides free rides
     to work for customers bringing in their cars for service?

<li>Do they value a car rental business that will deliver your
     rental car to your home or office?
</ul>

<p>     Stress the point that in each case, while some consumers
will value the product (good or service), others will not!  How
do members of the channel of distribution accommodate different
value perceptions?


<p><b>References</b>
<p>     Czepiel, John A. (1992), Competitive Marketing Strategy,
     Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Prentice Hall.

<p>     De Santa, Richard (1995), "Carving the Value-Added Niche,"
     <i>Supermarket Business</i> (February): 119-121.

<p>     McDowell, Bill (1995), "America's Favorite Chains,"
          <i>Restaurants & Institutions</i> (February 1): 52-61.
        
<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Explain how distribution facilitates the flow of products
     from producer to consumer
<ol>

<li>The modern channel of distribution is the place
          variable in the marketing mix that facilitates and
          expedites marketing exchanges
<ul>
<li>Marketing intermediaries can be individuals or
               businesses
<ol>
<li>Agents are intermediaries with legal
                    authority to act in the name of manufacturers
                    or producers
<li>Brokers are intermediaries who directly bring
                    buyer and seller together
<li>Wholesalers are intermediaries who sell to
                    other intermediaries, mostly to retailers    
</ol>
<li>Both goods and services are distributed
</ul>
<li>Intermediaries add value to the products they move
          through channels
<ul>
<li>Place utility means products are available where
               they are wanted 
<li>Time utility means products are available when
               they are wanted
<li>Form utility means products are available in the
               quantities, colors, sizes, and shapes wanted
<li>Possession utility means consumers can take
               possession of products by exchange something of
               value 
</ul>
<li>Distribution marketing activities are often highly
          specialized and economies can be achieved through 
          efficiencies in the distribution functions of
<ul>
<li>Exchange 
<li>Physical distribution
<li>Servicing 
</ul>
</ol>


II.  Identify the factors that influence the development of a
     channel structure
<ol>
<li>Channel structure refers to the form a channel takes,
          its length, arrangement, size, and ownership
<li>A channel's structure is a function of different
          factors, including
<ul>
<li>Company attributes
<li>Product type
<li>Markets
<li>Competitors    
<li>Custom
<li>The marketing environment
</ul>
<li>Distribution strategy (intensive, selective, or
          exclusive) also influences channel structure
<ul>
<li>Intensive distribution, where products are made
               available in as many different places as possible      
<li>Selective distribution, where a limited number of
               distribution points are used
<li>Exclusive distribution, which restricts
               distribution to a few exclusive places
</ul>
<li>Channel management is not always easy, and sometimes
          channel members disagree and dissolve the channel
<ul>
<li>Channel power is often vested in a captain, a
               powerful member who sets channel policy and often
               dictates terms
<li>Businesses often buy up other channel members and
               become vertically integrated in order to exert
               greater control 
<li>When a channel member purchases others at the same
               level, often competitors, it is horizontal
               integration
<ol>
<li>Just-In-Time systems are a process for
                    cutting delivery times, reducing inventory
                    time, and reducing distribution costs
<li>Reverse channels are the backward
                    distribution of products to the producer or
                    to another business for reprocessing, recall,
                    or repair
</ol>
</ul>
</ol>

III. Describe the different perspectives on channels of
     distribution
<ol>
<li>Channels of distributing are changing, pushed by
          computer technology, automation, demands for
          efficiency, and changing roles in distribution
<li>There are many different perspectives on channels of
          distribution, and sometimes they conflict
<ul>
<li>Consumers may not appreciate channels, yet they
               complain when channels don't work right
<li>Retailers vary in their views of channels, with
               the larger ones viewing channels as a way to wring 
               out cost savings by removing inefficiency and
               waste; smaller retailers may experience cost
               disadvantages because they cannot exert control
               over channel members
<li>Efficient wholesalers can profit handsomely by
               being efficient and advancing with the technology
<li>Some manufacturers, who once controlled channels
               of distribution, now work more closely with
               powerful retailers to produce products that
               retailers want to stock
<li>Government wants channels to run efficiently,
               competitively, and fairly
</ul>
</ol>

IV.  Explain the role of wholesalers
<ol>
<li>A wholesaler is an intermediary that provides retailers
          with products, only rarely selling to the public; they
          transport, redirect, and often transfer title
<li>Wholesalers perform many tasks that benefit
          manufacturers and retailers, these include
<ul>
<li>Purchasing
<li>Sorting
<li>Accumulating
<li>Storing
<li>Transporting
<li>Financing
</ul>
<li>Wholesaling contributes to the U.S. economy by
          providing over 6 million jobs and an annual payroll of
          over $183 billion
<li>Wholesalers are categorized by their job
          characteristics, most are small, family businesses
<ul>
<li>Merchant wholesalers are independent
               businesspeople who take title to the merchandise
               they handle and assume the risks of ownership
<li>Brokers and agents do not take title to the
               merchandise they handle although sometimes they
               may take possession; mainly they facilitate the
               exchange between buyers and sellers
<li>Manufacturer's representatives are employed by one
               or several producers to represent their products
               and distribute them to retailers
</ul>
<li>Wholesalers make decisions about products, prices,
          promotions, and markets
</ol>

V.   Characterize the logistics/physical distribution functions
<ol>
<li>Logistics and physical distribution are often used
          interchangeably to identify the distribution of raw
          materials and supplies into production and the
          distribution of completed products from producer to
          point of sale and includes such tasks as
<ul>
<li>Packing
<li>Order processing
<li>Inventory control
<li>Transportation
<li>Service
</ul>
<li>Physical distribution can be very expensive and the
          extent of the need for physical distribution depends on
          the nature of a business
<li>Physical distribution decisions are influenced by such
          factors as company attributes and resources, product
          characteristics, and geography
</ol>
     
<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  What is the role of distribution in marketing?  <i>Distribution
is an essential marketing activity, responsible for getting
products from production to the point of sale.</i>

<p>2.  Why are intermediaries also called middlemen?  <i>If you think
of a chain reaching from the producer to the point of sale,
intermediaries are in the middle of the chain, which explains the
name middlemen.</i>

<p>3.  Are retailers members of the channel of distribution?  <i>Yes,
they are the final member of the channel at the point of sale,
where the exchange is made with the consumer.</i>

<p>4.  Discuss the utilities provided by distribution.  <i>Distribution
provides 
<ul>
<li>place utility - making products available where they are
     wanted
<li>time utility - making products available when they are
     wanted
<li>form utility - making products available in the quantities,
     colors, sizes, and shapes wanted
<li>possession utility - providing mechanisms by which others
     can take possession of the products
</ul>
</i>

<p>5.  How may the marketing environment affect channel structure? 
<i>Channel structure is the form that a channel takes, its length,
arrangement, size, and legal characteristics.  Marketers facing
stable marketing environments often have relatively stable
channel structures; marketers facing volatile, rapidly changing
environments often have channels that can and often must change
rapidly in order to maintain their profitability.</i>

<p>6.  Explain how intensive, selective, and exclusive distribution
influence the number of middlemen needed in a channel.  <i>Broad
distribution in an intensive distribution strategy typically
involves far more middlemen than exclusive distribution, which
distributes products to a very few places.  Selective
distribution is between the two extremes.</i>

<p>7.  What is JIT?  <i>Just-in-time (JIT) is a system that tracks
inventory and directs supplies and materials to receivers just as
they are needed.  This reduces holding costs and delays by
reducing the handling of products and the time spent in
inventory.  It has been adopted by diverse industries including
automobiles, groceries, and mass merchandisers.</i>

<p>8.  How does wholesaling serve retailing?  <i>How does it serve
producers?  Wholesaling serves retailing by getting the right
products to retailers when and where they are needed. 
Wholesaling serves producers by moving their finished products
through the channel to the point-of-sale, where sales generate
revenue and profit.</i>

<p>9.  Describe the various perspectives on distribution.
<i>Perspectives on distribution vary.  Consumers sometimes complain
that distribution adds costs to the products they purchase, but
they are not willing to forgo distribution and experience
stockouts.  Large retailers see channels as ways to reduce costs
by demanding efficiency, while smaller retailers may believe they
are experiencing cost disadvantages because they cannot exert
power over their channels.  Efficient wholesalers see channels as
their source of healthy profits.  Large manufacturers have seen
their power over channels diminish as retailers have exerted
control.  From the government's perspective, channels must be
efficient, competitive, and fair in order to maintain the healthy
operation of the free market.</i>

<p>10. What are the tasks of wholesaling?  What are the tasks of
physical distribution?   <i>Wholesalers offer many important
services to retailers and manufacturers.  They purchase, store,
accumulate, sort, transport, and finance products.  Physical
distribution includes the marketing activities that transport
products (supplies and raw materials) to the point of production
and bring finished products from the producer to the point of
sale.</i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 11.1 </h4>

<p>1.  What is a marketing intermediary?  <i>A marketing intermediary
is a member of a channel of distribution that is responsible for
getting products from the point-of-production to the point-of-sale.</i>

<p>2.  Identify the utilities provided by distribution. 
<i>Distribution adds value to products through such utilities as
place, time, form, and possession utility.</i>
 
<p>3.  Describe the marketing functions associated with
distribution.  <i>Marketing functions associated with distribution
are exchange, physical distribution, and servicing.  Exchange
includes purchasing products, collecting an inventory, making
selections from that inventory, communicating information about
the products, and facilitating exchanges for the products.  The
physical distribution functions include transporting products,
storage, carrying inventory for various periods of time, sorting,
and delivering products.  Finally, servicing involves promoting
products, performing research about markets, and providing
financial services to other channel members.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 11.2 </h4>

<p>Identify some of the factors that influence channel structure.
<i>Channel structure refers to the form a a channel takes, including
its length, arrangement, and size.  The structure of a channel
may be a function of the industry and types of products it
serves.  For example, automobile distribution is fairly standard
throughout the industry.  Most channels are designed to respond
to company attributes, product type, markets served, competitors,
custom, and conditions in the marketing environment.  Because
channel structure can change, there are not hard and fast rules
about the "best" form for a channel to take.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 11.3 </h4>

<p>1.  Compare and contrast the three distribution coverage
alternatives: intensive, selective, and exclusive distribution. 
<i>Intensive distribution requires placing products everywhere
possible; at the other extreme, exclusive distribution restricts
the number and characteristics of places where products are
distributed.  Somewhere between the two is selective
distribution, which is more limiting than intensive yet makes
products more available than exclusive distribution.</i>

<p>2.  Are all channels managed smoothly?  Explain your answer. 
<i>Absolutely not!  Many articles have been written about the fights
occurring between members in a feuding channel.  Often the fights
are about power and control.  The channel member that controls
the other members exerts a level of power than can sometimes lead
to considerable dissension.  Channels are like marriages, some go
on happily of years, others undertake messy divorces.</i>
            
<p>3.  Discuss the use of reverse channels of distribution.  
<i>Reverse channels of distribution reverse the flow of products
back to the producer.  Sometimes this occurs because of a product
recall or need for repair.  Increasingly it is a result of
efforts to reuse materials and recycle worn products. </i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 11.4</h4>

<p>1.  What is the role of wholesaling in product distribution? 
<i>Wholesalers provide retailers with products, expedite the
distribution of producers' products, and provide products for
other businesses and organizations.</i>

<p>2.  Describe the different wholesale tasks.  <i>Wholesalers
purchase, sort, accumulate, store, transport, and finance
products for the businesses and organizations they serve.</i>

<p>3.  Identify the different types of wholesalers. <i>There are three
broad categories of wholesalers: merchant wholesalers are
independent businesspeople, often small businesses, that usually
take title to the merchandise they handle and assume risks of
ownership.  There are general merchant wholesalers and specialty
wholesalers; some offer a full-line of services and others offer
limited services.  Brokers and agents do not take title, though
they may take possession of products.  They are facilitators,
representing the products and often matching sellers and buyers. 
Manufacturer's representatives are employed by one or more
producers to represent their products and facilitate their sale.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 11.5</h4>

<p>1.  Describe the types of decisions wholesalers make. 
<i>Wholesalers make many different kinds of decisions.  In general,
their decisions focus on such topics as what products to carry,
what prices to charge (within industry standards), how to sell
the products (personal selling), and what markets to serve.</i>
 
<p>2.  What is the role of physical distribution?   <i>Physical
distribution, which includes logistics, is the overall process of
transporting products from producer to point-of-sale.  Most
broadly, the process also includes bringing products to the
point-of-production, as well as from production to point-of-sale.</i>

<p>3.  Discuss the different tasks of physical distribution. 
<i>Physical distribution activities include packaging goods for
shipment, processing orders, controlling inventory,
transportation, and servicing.</i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 11.1: A Tasty Case Of Worldwide Distribution            </h4>
    
<p>    Are your students familiar with some of the foods of CPC
International Inc.?  If you have international students in class,
ask whether they have noticed any differences between CPC foods
distributed in the United States and in their home countries. 
Often students can identify obvious differences in packaging,
sometimes in names, and less frequently in taste.  Distribution
of food products obviously can be more difficult than
distributing consumer durables.  Ask students to consider the
challenge of distributing nondurable and perishable products
internationally, as well as the potential for escalating costs
and risks.  Some students may have experience working in 
distribution and if they do, perhaps they can share their
observations with the class.  Because the activities of channel
of distribution members are relatively hidden from consumers,
this is a good topic for a class speaker.  To arrange for a
speaker, contact a local American Marketing Association Chapter
or one of the national associations of professionals in
wholesaling, manufacturers' agents, manufacturers'
representatives, or wholesalers-distributors (see Part IV of this
<b><i>Manual</i></b> for contacts).

<p>1.  What advantage is there for CPC in using the distribution
channels of brands it acquires in other countries?  <i>Obviously the
greatest advantage to CPC is in acquiring effective, efficient
channels that are successful and well established.  Through these
established channels, CPC can begin to distributed its other
brands.  CPC avoids having to go into established markets and
form new channel partnerships in order to introduce its products.</i>

<p>2.  Why should food products in particular require adaptation to
local tastes?  <i>Food is an integral element in culture and is
often a principal way that culture is perpetuated.  Therefore,
food product marketers must be cautious in introducing new food
products to a market because of the strength of cultural
associations.  </i>

<p>3.  Could this strategy of worldwide marketing synergy in
distribution be used by other businesses?  <i>What types of products
might lend themselves to this strategy?  This is a strategy that
lends itself to related products, in CPC's case, food products. 
By staying within the range of the company's competencies, it
uses its strengths to establish a presence in new markets.  If a
company dramatically changes direction, perhaps acquiring a food
line and its distribution system but intending to introduce
automotive parts, it would find the food distribution system
incompatible with its plans.</i>


<h4>Mini-Case 11.2  Ito-Yokado, Lojas Americana SA, And Wal-Mart </h4>

<p>     Can Wal-Mart work its magic as successfully internationally
as it has domestically?  Many marketers believe that a reason for
Wal-Mart's great success is its state-of-the-art distribution
system.  If any students have worked for Wal-Mart, perhaps they
can comment on this.  Many articles have appeared recently in
popular business journals about the problems Wal-Mart is
experiencing in Mexico.  Students can research this topic, read
the articles, then write a brief analysis (in memo form) of Wal-Mart's potential for short- and long-range success in Mexico and
other markets.  Another direction for this discussion to take is
to research the Japanese market and the complaints against closed
Japanese distribution systems for automobiles and film.  Will
Wal-Mart experience the same kinds of problems or will it avoid
them by joint venturing with Ito-Yokado?

<p>1.  Wal-Mart is the first American retailer to open stores in
Argentina and Brazil.  It is also moving aggressively into Japan
and Asia.  What are the risks of extending its distribution
system beyond North American?  <i>Wal-Mart has an extremely
efficient, sophisticated distribution system in the United
States.  It runs the risk of stretching the system too far and
encountering serious problems in meeting its commitments
internationally.  </i>

<p>2.  How is Wal-Mart countering this risk?  <i>Wal-Mart is countering
this risk by taking on joint venture partners who are already
successful in their home countries.  These partners will share
Wal-Mart's profits, but also its risks.  They should ease the way
for Wal-Mart to become successful.</i>

<p>3.  Do you think Wal-Mart is on the way to becoming as widely
distributed as Coca-Cola, McDonald's, and KFC?  Explain your
answer.  <i>Coca-Cola, McDonald's, and KFC offer far fewer products
than Wal-Mart.  They are intensively distributed while Wal-Mart
has been much more selective in its distribution strategy. 
However, while Wal-Mart will never be as intensively distributed
as the others, barring unforeseen problems, it will doubtless be
highly successful because it is an extremely well run company.</i>
                                
                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     CompDesign is a small business with big potential.  Are
there other small businesses that began as retailers and expanded
into wholesale?  Wholesaling lends itself to small businesses. 
Draw on student experiences for observations about small or mid-size businesses that have expanded from retail into wholesale, or
vice versa.  Alternately, invite a speaker from a local small
business, the Small Business Administration, or the American
Marketing Association to discuss the importance of small
businesses to channels of distribution.

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

     Please verify all Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment <b>before</b> you make it.  No
Internet address or information can be guaranteed past the date
of this <b><i>Manual's</b></i> publication.  Be sure to insist that students
demonstrate professional conduct at all times on the Internet.   

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>     This chapter begins with an opening story about roses.  Lots
of flowers are being offered on the Internet, on home pages and
in malls.  Flower retailers on the Internet can be tracked using
a search tool such as Yahoo, WebCrawler, or jughead.  This is a
product search that definitely benefits from a graphical browser. 
Students should consider how effectively flowers can be
distributed on the Internet while the majority of consumers still
use a text-only browser.  

     In searching the Internet for flowers, I recommend that you
look for a flower case about the Dutch flower auction, The World
Wide Flowers Project.  This is an extremely interesting
multimedia case that is accessible by the World Wide Web.  It
appears to be one of the first efforts to present a multimedia,
interactive case worldwide on the Internet for Netizens (Net
citizens) to access.  The case provides valuable insights into
how flower auctions work as part of the distribution process,
adding value to the product by ensuring that a wide, fresh
assortment is available to consumers worldwide.  The whole case
will be sent on request by contacting the e-mail address in the
document.  The case is listed in a WebCrawler search query
flowers or by searching for the case name.

<i>
<p><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>
<br>     * Business
<br>     * Products and Services
<br>     * Flowers@

<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     search:  flowers
<br>     search:  flower retailers
<br>     search:  roses 
<br>     (some of the documents listed in this query are not about
     roses, but have the word "rose" in the title)
</i>


<h4>Dual Distribution On The Internet</h4>
 
<p>     Some of your students are probably familiar with Sear's
craftsman tools, a very popular and highly regarded brand.  These
tools are sold in stores and on the Internet at the Cybermall. 
If some of your students are knowledgeable about tools, ask them
to share their observations about the relative advantages of
store and Internet tool distribution.  Will dual distribution
using the Internet affect store distribution?

<i>
<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     search:  Sear's tools
<br>     Shopping2000 Home Page   
<br>     Check here for text only browsing
<br>     Directory
<br>     Sears Tools
</i>

<h4>Real Estate Brokers On The Internet</h4>

<p>     A search for real estate on the Internet using Yahoo
uncovers 24 pages of listings.  A WebCrawler search provides
several hundred documents.  The Global Network Navigator (The
Whole Internet Catalog) has an extensive list of real estate
brokers.  Students can determine the types of real estate brokers
using the Internet and their product assortment, but without a
graphical browser, they will be limited in their ability to
evaluate the value of these sites to potential customers.  Most
of the searches will uncover real estate brokers internationally,
nationally, and locally.  Mortgage brokers and other real estate-related businesses usually are included with a real estate
search.  How can consumers use the real estate sites?  What value
do they add to the consumer's search?

<i>
<p><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>
<br>     * Business
<br>     * Products and Services
<br>     * Real Estate@

<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     search:  real estate brokers

<p><a href="http://nearnet.gnn.com">http://nearnet.gnn.com</a>
<br>     Whole Internet Catalog
<br>     All Subjects
<br>     Real Estate
</i>


<h4>Personal Computers Distributed On The Internet</h4>

<p>     As you might expect, the Internet is a very appropriate
place for the distribution of personal computers.  Consumers can
compare prices and product descriptions directly from
manufacturers or through wholesalers or retailers.  Perhaps this
product category more than any other shows the value of the
Internet for members of the distribution channel as well as
consumers.  Two-person student teams or small groups can evaluate
how effectively various producers and retailers are using the
Internet to communicate with consumers, promote their products,
and facilitate exchange.  Any of the search tools can be used
along with home pages for such major computer producers as IBM,
Dell, Gateway, Hewlett Packard, Packard Bell, Compaq, and Apple.

<i>
<p><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>
<br>     * Business
<br>     * Products and Services
<br>     * Computers
</i>


<h4>Other Channel Members</h4>

<p>     Students can research other channel members on the Internet. 
This includes performing searches for wholesalers, shipping
companies, truckers, and warehousers.

<h4>Automobiles On The Internet</h4>

<p>     This is a product category that often surprises people by
the extent of Internet listings.  From family sedans to exotic
cars and antiques, a search of automobiles will return a large
number of links to both new and used car dealers.  Look for
DealerNet, an extensive site for new car purchases.


<h4>The Economic Impact Of Wholesaling</h4>

<p>     Students can visit the United States Bureau of the Census to
analyze the economic impact of wholesaling.  They will find data
on the numbers of firms, their employment, and annual payrolls. 
These data are for the wholesale trade, retail trade, real estate
firms, and transportation.

<i>
<p><a href="http://www.census.gov">http://www.census.gov</a>
          
<p>     -- or --
     
<p><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>
<br>     * Government
<br>     * Agencies
<br>     * Census Bureau
<br>     * U.S. Bureau of the Census
<br>     o view the topics in text
<br>     Economy
<br>     o Statistics of U.S. Businesses
<br>     o Number of Firms by Industrial Division     
<br>     Statistics of U.S. Businesses
</i>

<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 11.1</h4>

<p>     Conflict between channel members is quite common.  Some of
your students may have observed channel conflict while employed
by a retailer, wholesaler, or other channel member.  If so, ask
if they can share their observations with the class.  If some of
your students have worked or are working for a computer retailer,
ask how that retailer counters the problem of producers selling
their product directly, through catalogs, and large discounters. 
The problem identified in this <b>Application</b> lends itself to
discussion by small groups of students, brainstorming to develop
ways to resolve the conflict.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 11.2</h4>

<p>     Education distribution is a topic that often provokes
polarized opinions.  Some favor a public distribution systems,
others prefer private distribution.  Regardless of who does the
distributing, is there a difference between the two other than in
the context of what is being taught?


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 11.3</h4>

<p>     Four products are identified for students to consider in
developing a channel of distribution.  This problem can be set up
as a decision tree, with alternative branches for distributing
the products.  For example, in the case of custom made jewelry,
it can be distributed exclusively in a highly restricted number
of retailers, by catalog, or on the Internet.  Alternately, it
can be distributed selectively, perhaps in up-scale department
stores and better jewelry stores.  Finally, it can be distributed
intensively.  Ask students to explain why this would not be an
alternative used for high quality, expensive jewelry.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 11.4 </h4>

<p>     Instead of having students contact local retailers to
determine what wholesalers do for them, you can identify a
retailer to invite as a guest speaker.  The topic can be related
to a general discussion of how the retailer gets products through
various types of wholesalers.  Several suggestions for guest
speakers are made in the <a href="#teaching tips>Teaching Tips</a> section of this <b><i>Manual</i></b>.

<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 11.1</h4>

<p>     Vending machines are an important mechanism for distributing
products.  What products are distributed in vending machines? 
The list often surprises students, because vending machines
provide distribution for products ranging from alcohol to
umbrellas.  In other countries, including Japan, vending machines
are used even more widely than they are in the United States.
There are vending machines that dispense frozen steaks, beer and
hard liquors, and clothing.  Are there products that students
would like to have distributed in vending machines?


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 11.2</h4>

<p>     Home delivery is very important to Japanese consumers and it
is growing in popularity in the United States.  Takuhaibin is
widely used by personal use and business/organization consumers
alike.  Ask your students if there are equivalents in the United
States?  Think of the types of home delivery they value,
particularly of pizza.  What else is home delivered?  How does
the Internet fit into this picture?  Could it accelerate the
movement toward greater use of home delivery?  Is there a product
opportunity here for small businesses to determine what types of
home delivery consumers value (that are not currently being
offered or not offered well), then fill that gap?


<h4>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>     Distribution in Russia is a challenge far greater than in
most other industrialized countries.  This <b>International
Marketing Report</b> (page 348 of the text) illustrates how difficult
it is to get automobiles delivered to car dealerships in Moscow
and other large Russian cities.  Compare the cost of distribution
automobiles in Russia with the cost in the United States. 
Although distribution costs are far less in the U.S., many new
car buyers complain about destination charges listed on the
invoice.  If you invite a guest speaker to class from the
automobile industry, ask about distribution costs and their
impact of the final price of a new car.  Will the Internet change
the distribution of automobiles?  Can it reduce distribution
costs?</p>

<p>

