<head>
<title>CHAPTER 14: EXTENDING MARKETING: MARKETING SERVICES AND NOT-FOR-PROFIT MARKETING</title>
</head>

<h1><center>CHAPTER 14</h1>
<h1>EXTENDING MARKETING: MARKETING SERVICES AND NOT-FOR-PROFIT MARKETING</h1>
</center>

<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>

<p><b>1. Explain the differences and similarities between goods and
services.  </b>Goods and services are both products.  They are both
marketed to personal use and business/organization consumers. 
Marketing decisions for goods and services are about product,
price, place, and promotion.  A service is an intangible,
perishable product of variable quality whose production and
consumption are inseparable.  Services are offered by businesses,
governments, and not-for-profit organizations.  Products often
are made more tangible through promotion and other marketing
tools in order to provide a visible anchor for consumers to
perceive and use in making product evaluations.  Because a
service is perishable, it is particularly susceptible to demand
fluctuations.  As a result, efforts are made to even out demand
through practices such as peak period pricing, temporary
employees, and automation.  Service production is inseparable
from its performance, so considerable attention must be paid to
the service provider, who represents the business to consumers. 
This includes careful selection, training, and management. 
Because services are affected by many factors related to its
delivery, there is variability in service quality.  Service
quality lies in the consumer's evaluation of the performance. 
Services are classified by product attributes, consumer targets,
provider training, delivery system, and contact closeness.  There
has been a shift to services.  Services dominate the national
economy for a variety of reasons including the number of women
entering the full-time out-of-home workforce, dual income
families with the income to pay and the need for services, the
aging of the population, loss of manufacturing jobs, and the
stresses and time constraints of contemporary life.  Service
providers should be trained to deliver good performance in order
to establish relationships with consumers.  This means ensuring
that service providers have the capacity to perform, the
willingness to perform, and the opportunity to perform.  Service
businesses often undertake internal marketing programs directed
at employees in order to emphasize the importance of their role
as service providers.  In close contact services, the service
consumer both contributes to and evaluates the quality of the
service provided.


<p><b>2. Describe the Four Ps in services and the service advantage.   </b>
A service is a product whose characteristics must be determined
before it can be offered to consumers.  Product decisions
frequently include a service and its associated goods.  Pricing a
service calls for a careful analysis of what is being priced and
its value to consumers.  An equipment-based service can be priced
like a tangible good.  Pricing a people-based service often
requires considering service image, service provider reputation
or credentials, and the price charged by a market leader and the
competition.  Place is important in services because many retail
services are store based, which requires location decisions. 
Channels of distribution exist for financial and other services. 
Service promotion often involves personal selling and advertising
designed to make the product tangible and establish a positive
brand image.  Services marketing requires the formulation of
strategy and the development of tactics to achieve the goals set
for service products by the business.  A service advantage is
often enjoyed by businesses who use service as the key factor in
differentiating their product offers from the competition.


<p><b>3. Recognize the characteristics of not-for-profit marketing. </b>
The not-for-profit designation indicates that earning a profit is
not a primary organizational goal.  However, when it comes to
marketing, there are great similarities between the two.  For
many years not-for-profits wanted little to do with marketing
because they believed that marketing didn't fit their
organizational image.  However, now that competition has
increased and funding is scarce, many not-for-profits are using
sophisticated marketing activities to raise funds and gain
support for their programs.  Marketing in the not-for-profit
sector involves public and private organizations as diverse as
governments, charities, hospitals, politicians, unions, religious
groups, zoos, social causes and activist groups.


<p><b>4. Discuss some other for-profit extensions of marketing.  </b>Many
contemporary marketing applications make sophisticated use of
marketing tools.  Health care marketing is growing in importance
as for-profit and not-for-profit hospitals and clinics, as well
as physicians and other medical professionals, compete for
clients and revenues.  Health care organizations use marketing
techniques to measure customer satisfaction and develop programs
designed to satisfy consumers.  Many people are their own
product.  Marketing is used to market professional athletes,
artists, entertainers, medical professionals, lawyers, and
others.  Entertainment marketing is used by symphony orchestras,
authors, movies, music companies, and leisure activities.  Place
marketing attracts tourists and economic development.  Some of
the events being marketed are sports extravaganzas (Super Bowl,
World Cup), holiday celebrations, trade shows, and conventions. 
Educational institutions market themselves to students, parents,
alumni, faculty, and potential donors.  The information age has
ushered in the marketing of many different kinds of information
services.  


<p><b>5. Characterize the marketing concept in services and not-for-profits.  </b>The marketing concept is an operating philosophy that
has customer satisfaction at its core.  It requires the
integration of all organizational operations in a business to
focus on consumer satisfaction.  The marketing concept is being
applied successfully in both the service and not-for-profit
sectors.  However, there is always room for improvement.  When it
comes to the societal marketing concept, not-for-profits practice
what many for-profits are still debating.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>     Ask your students to comment on the chapter opening
question, Is there anything that cannot be marketed?  Marketing
is defined by the American Marketing Association as the process
of planning and executing the conception, pricing, promotion and
distribution of ideas, goods and services to create exchanges
that satisfy individual and organizational objectives (see
definition of marketing in chapter 1).  This definition is
extremely broad and includes businesses as well as governments
and organizations.  Given the breadth of the definition, few
activities are excluded from being appropriate for marketing.  At
the same time, some things should not be marketed and some not-for-profits choose not to market.  

<p><b>Services Intangibility     </b>
 
<p>     In order to illustrate how advertising is used to
tangibilize services, collect print advertisements for various
services, such as insurance (Traveler's, Met Life, Prudential),
credit cards (Visa, Master Card, American Express), banks and
other financial services (Charles Schwab, Quick and Reilly). 
Bring these advertisements to class and use them to illustrate
how marketers seek to establish a visual and perceptual anchor
for consumers to use in defining their services.  Are some more
successful at tangibilizing services than others?  Bring print
advertisements to class that show the smiling faces of the
employees who deliver service.  Are these people representative
of the ones who actually will be delivering the service?  What is
the purpose of showing people in these advertisements?  Is it
tangibilizing and personalizing at the same time?

<p><b>Coping With Demand Variability</b>

<p>     Ask if any of your students have ever worked as a temporary
employee.  If they worked in customer service, did they receive
training in how to work successfully with customers?  If so, was
it helpful, or did they "learn on the job?"  While hiring temps
has been traditional in seasonal businesses, such as amusement
parks and swimming pools, and in fast food restaurants that
experience demand peaks in the summer, the number of temporary
employees working full-time, year round has increased
significantly in the past decade.  Downsizing and restructuring
are blamed for much of this movement from full-time permanent to
full-time temporary status.  What effect can this have on service
businesses whose survival depends on their ability to deliver
good customer service?  Does it make it easier or harder to
ensure that all parts of the business, and certainly customer
contact employees, adopt the marketing concept philosophy and
work effectively to implement it?

<p><b>Automation And Demand Fluctuation</b>

<p>     Are vending machines the only automatic substitutes for
human customer contact employees?  What do your students think of
automatic telephone answering programs, where callers have to
listen carefully to the instructions, then punch the appropriate 
numbered keys to complete the call.  How much does the caller
contribute to service performance?  Can consumers' failure to
perform as desired undermine service delivery?  Do some consumers
become irritated by these automatic systems?  Why?  What are the
risks of an English-only automated telephone system and what
could be done to avoid problems caused by such a system? 

<p><b>Do Service Employees In The United States Deliver Good Service?</b>

<p>     If you have international students in class, or students who
have traveled extensively, ask them to share their observations
and experiences with services abroad and in the United States. 
As described in the International Marketing Report (page 456 of
the text), customer service in other countries can be much worse
than in the United States; sometimes it's better.  However,
American service providers often disappoint in their inability to
communicate in a language other than English, or sometimes
Spanish.  This is less of a problem in international airports and
tourist destinations.  However, in many parts of the country,
it's English, only.  Should a greater effort be made generally to
have multilingual service providers available for international
customers?  Is this a serious problem in your city?  Are there
particular types of services where it is more important to have a
multilingual person on staff?  What are the alternatives (human
and automated) to a multilingual service provider?  Considering
the growing diversity in U.S. society, might having a
multilingual service provider be a competitive advantage in some
situations?

<p><b>Testing Service Quality Using Comment Cards</b>

<p>     Have any of your students completed a customer comment card? 
Most of us have, at one time or another.  Who is more apt to
complete a card, a customer who is angry about bad service or one
that thinks the service was acceptable?  What incentive might a
business offer customers to get more of them to take the cards
more seriously and complete one?  Are there other and perhaps
better ways of determining how satisfied customers are with the
service they receive?

<p><b>I'll Take The Internet And An Espresso</b>

<p>     A new service business is springing up on both the east and
west coasts.  It's a coffee shop/Internet service, where
customers can log onto the Internet for a nominal charge per hour
of connect time, drink coffee, and have sandwiches and cakes, all
in a congenial atmosphere.  The shops offer their patrons the
opportunity to use a home page and post messages, poetry, art,
and music, as well as furnish mail boxes for their e-mail.  Would
this type of service do well in your city?  Describe by
demographic and psychographic characteristics the types of
consumers who might find this service irresistible.  Could
Internet connect service be offered in malls or other locations? 
Have students brainstorm extensions for this type of new service
business.

<p><b>The Shift To Services For Older Consumers</b>

<p>     A significant population age shift is occurring as the
leading edge of the baby boomers enter their 50s.  Students can
visit the U.S. Census Bureau's home page on the Internet to
examine national population projections (see Using the Internet
in this chapter).  A table of population projections for 1995,
2000, and 2005 is presented on the next page.  The data indicate
how the numbers of baby boomers will affect age segments as they
enter their senior years.   

<p>Table 14.1   Projections of the Population, By Age, Sex, Race,    
               and Hispanic Origin, For the United States: 
                  1993 to 2050, Middle Series

<pre>
         7/1/1995  7/1/2000  7/1/2005
  All     263,434   276,241   288,286
  50-54    13,351    16,640    19,264   
  55-59    11,050    13,047    16,293
  60-64    10,191    10,643    12,577
  65-69    10,099     9,594    10,066
  70-74     8,864     8,957     8,557
  75-79     4,419     7,507     7,655
  80-84     4,419     4,931     5,610
  85-89     2,317     2,692     3,052
  90-94       976     1,193     1,432
  95-99       253       373       477
 100+          52        75       120
</pre>
  
<p>Note:   All population numbers are in thousands for the resident  
        population.

<p>     Students can study national or state data to see how the
shifts occur.  It is extremely interesting to look at the data
for the oldest old (80+) broken down by gender for these years. 
Ask students to consider some of the effects these age shifts
will have on services marketing in the years to come.  What
opportunities may emerge in services?  Is there a market for
services offered on the Internet?  What will be the appeal of the
Internet for older consumers?  What needs and wants can the
Internet serve for older people?

<p><b>Service Consumers</b>

<p>     When service performance goes bad, the provider usually gets
blamed.  However, it's important to appreciate the vital role
that the service consumer plays in close contact services.  The
example in the text (page 464), of bank services at a teller
window, illustrates a close contact service where consumer
performance affects service delivery.  Ask your students to think
of other situations where the service provider's performance
depends to a greater or lesser extent on the consumer's
performance.  For one or two examples, identify what should be
done to help the consumer perform more effectively.  Then, assess
how this can be implemented.  Is it feasible?  

<p><b>Pricing A Service</b>

<p>     Students can make service price comparisons, just as they
can make price comparisons for tangible goods.  Ask them to
consider how they would go about performing a price comparison
for

<ul>
<li>a permanent in a beauty salon
<li>shortening trouser legs at an alteration shop
<li>a manicure
<li>a 1-hour tennis lesson for a beginner
<li>having your teeth cleaned
<li>30-minutes with a marriage counselor
<li>an oil change
<li>tax preparation for a 1040 form 
<li>dry cleaning a suit
<li>grooming a small, short haired dog (regular grooming, no fur
     knots, no fleas)
</ul>

<p>     What are some differences between gathering competitive
intelligence for services and goods?  Are prices more variable
for some services?  Why?  

<p><b>Not-For-Profit Marketing</b>

<p>     Do any of your students currently work for a not-for-profit
that engages in marketing?  If so, ask if they would be willing
to share their observations about how the marketing is performed
and the goals that are set for marketing to accomplish.  You
might find an interesting guest speaker from a not-for-profit in
your area that actively uses marketing.  Investigate the
marketing of zoos, museums, symphony orchestras, and theater
groups.  Students can learn about organizations such as the
United Way, American Red Cross, and American Cancer Society and
their marketing activities.  Who performs their marketing?  Is it
a professional trained as a not-for-profit marketer?

<p><b>Place Marketing </b>

<p>     Most states and many cities engage in place marketing.  Have
students find out about economic development, tourism, and
educational marketing in your state.  Who does it and how is it
performed?  What results has been obtained from the marketing
effort?  Are the results satisfactory?

<p><b>Health Care Marketing</b>

<p>     Many health care providers have actively adopted marketing
practices.  If you have a large hospital or medical clinic in
your area, investigate the extent of the marketing they perform. 
What are their goals?  Do they market specific services, such as
a birthing, sleep disorder, obesity, or wellness center?  How
widely do they target their services?  A guest speaker who
markets health care services can provide valuable insights on how
the services are marketed.

<p><b>Educational Marketing</b>

<p>     Does your school actively market itself?  If so, invite your
school's marketing director to class to discuss higher education
marketing in general, and your school's marketing efforts in
particular.  What are some of the environmental trend factors
that are driving higher education marketing efforts?  How does
your school define its target markets?  Does it market to alumni
as well as prospective students?  How does it promote to these
markets?  Who are the school's major competitors and how are
their marketing efforts tracked?

<p><b>The International Marketing Of Services</b>

<p>   Can services be marketed internationally?  This is an
interesting question to ask your students.  Their first reaction
may be to say that services can't be exported.  If so, ask them
to consider whether or not the following services can be exported
and if so, how can it be done.

<ul>
<li>consulting services

<li>investing services

<li>marketing research services

<li>credit card services

<li>computer services (training, set-up)

<li>medical services

<li>educational services
</ul>

<p>     They can check on the international marketing of services on
the Internet (see <a href="#internet">Using the Internet</a> in this chapter) by visiting
directories and home pages in other countries using one of the
primary search engines.  They will see many familiar names, U.S.
companies marketing their services worldwide.

<p>     Since there is close personal contact in many services,
would this present special problems for the international service
marketer?  What specific cultural problems might arise?  How
could they be overcome?

<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Explain the differences and similarities between goods and
     services                     
<ol>
<li>A service is an intangible, perishable product of
          variable quality whose production and consumption are
          inseparable; it may or may not be associated with a
          tangible good
<li>Services are characterized by their intangibility,
          perishability, inseparability, and variability
<ul>
<li>Intangibility means a product that is not
               palpable, properties that cannot be felt
<li>Perishability refers to the fleeting nature of
               services, which cannot be stored, inventoried, or
               stockpiled
<ol>
<li>Services are prone to the effects of demand
                    fluctuation, where demand shifts between
                    various levels that sometimes are not
                    predictable
<li>Strategies for dealing with demand
                    fluctuating include peak period pricing,
                    temporary employees, and use of alternative
                    service delivery systems such as automated
                    teller machines
</ol>
<li>Inseparability means that the service cannot be
               separated from the service deliverer, so that
               consumption occurs at the same time as service
               performance
<li>Variability in service performance means that
               differences may occur in the quality of the
               service delivered 
<ol>
<li>Service quality lies in the consumer's
                    evaluation of service performance
<li>Customers often are surveyed to determine
                    their perceptions of service quality
</ol>
</ul>
<li>Marketers attempt to classify services; however, it's
          not easy to do because of service variety and the ease
          with which services can be changed
<ul>
<li>Services are classified by product attributes,
               particularly how much a service is associated with
               a tangible good
<li>Services are classified by consumer targets,
               whether personal use, business, or organization
               consumers
<li>Services are classified by the extent of provider
               training required
<li>Services are classified by delivery system,
               whether people- or equipment-based, or both
<li>Services are classified by contact closeness, the
               level of personal interaction between service
               provider and consumer in the service encounter
</ul>
<li>Services have grown in importance during the latter
          half of the 20th century for several reasons
<ul>
<li>Increased numbers of women in the out-of-home
               workforce
<li>Time demands and complexities of contemporary life
<li>Changing population demographics, with growing
               numbers of older people who require more services
<li>income families with the discretionary income
               to have others perform tasks they don't like or
               haven't the time to do for themselves
<li>Expanded services means greater employment in
               service industries
</ul>
<li>Every service employee who makes contact with a
          consumer represents the business to that consumer
<ul>
<li>The concept of the lifetime value of a customer is
               growing in importance 
<li>Service providers must be able to deliver good
               quality service in order to ensure customer
               lifetime loyalty and patronage
<ol>
<li>Service providers must have the capacity to
                    perform good service
<li>Service providers must have the willingness
                    to perform
<li>Service providers must have the opportunity
                    to perform
</ol>
<li>Service businesses often use comprehensive
               internal marketing programs to market the business
               to its employees in order to develop their
               understanding of the importance of their role as
               service provider
</ul>
<li>Consumers both contribute to the service encounter and
          evaluate the quality of the service provided
</ol>
          

II.  Describe the Four Ps in services and the service advantage   
<ol>                         
<li>The marketing mix variables of product, price, place,
          and promotion are as important in marketing services as
          they are in marketing goods
<li>A service is a product whose characteristics must be
          determined before it can be offered to consumers
<li>Pricing a service requires a careful analysis of what
          is being priced and its value to consumers, and often
          it means following a price leader
<li>Place is important in services, both as services are
          distributed and as place conveys cues to consumers
          about the service being offered there
<li>Service promotion often involves personal selling and
          extensive advertising
<li>Marketing services requires formulating strategy and
          developing tactics to achieve the goals set for
          services to achieve
<li>A service advantage is often the only way that a
          business or organization can differentiate itself
</ol>

III. Recognize the characteristics of not-for-profit marketing    
<ol>       
<li>The designation not-for-profit means that earning a
          profit is not a primary organizational goal
<li>Marketing in the not-for-profit sector involves public
          and private organizations, causes, people, events, and
          places
<ul>
<li>Many not-for-profits engage in fund raising, using
               marketing strategies and tools to develop and
               harvest revenue sources in order to run a positive
               cash flow, cover operating expenses, and support
               benevolent activities

<li>Often a not-for-profit organization will hire a
               for-profit business to run its fund raising
               programs
</ul>
</ol>


IV.  Discuss some other for-profit extensions of marketing
<ol>
<li>Health care organizations are using marketing to offer
          niche services, behavior change activities associated
          with wellness goals, recruit staff, and measure
          customer service and satisfaction
<li>Some people actively market themselves, for profit,
          including athletes, lawyers, and medical professionals
<li>Entertainment marketing is big business and includes
          the marketing of individual entertainers as well as
          movies, books, and orchestras
<li>Leisure activities and places are marketed
<li>Events are marketed and include a wide array of
          activities, including trade shows, conventions,
          seminars, holiday celebrations, trade missions, and
          world class sports competitions
<li>Educational institutions market themselves in order to
          attract students, investors, and faculty
<li>The marketing of information services has become highly
          competitive and includes on-line computer services and
          telecommunications giants
</ol>

V.   Characterize the marketing concept in services and not-for-profits
<ol>
<li>The marketing concept is an operating philosophy that
          has customer satisfaction at its core, it requires the
          integration of all organizational operations in this
          effort
<li>The marketing concept is being applied successfully in
          goods and services, for-profits and not-for-profits
<li>When it comes to the societal marketing concept, many
          not-for-profits already practice what most for-profits
                    only think about
</ol>
                    
<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  In your own words, discuss the characteristics that make
services unique.  <i>Answers will vary, but should mention
intangibility, perishability, inseparability, and variability.</i>

<p>2.  In the continuum of goods and services, where would an
automobile tune-up be placed?  A skating lesson?  Five-pound bags
of flour?  Explain your answers.  

<i>
<ul>
<li>An automobile tune-up varies.  If no tangible goods are
     replaced on the automobile, then it is a pure service. 
     However, if examination reveals that something must be
     replaced, the tune-up becomes mixed, a service that also
     includes the provision of a tangible part.

<li>A skating lesson is a pure service.

<li>Five-pound bags of flour are tangible goods.
</ul>
</i>

<p>3.  What might a college do to combat demand fluctuations during
the summer?  <i>Most colleges face declining demand for classes,
dormitory rooms, food, and teachers during the summer.  A growing
number of colleges keep running during the summer by offering
summer school classes, special short courses, summer sports
camps, cheerleading camps, and elder hostels, summer academic and
social programs for people in their late 50s and older who come
to campus for about a week, live in the dormitories, attend
classes and special programs.</i>

<p>4.  Explain how a consumer may affect the outcome of the service
encounter.  <i>A consumer both contributes to many services and
evaluates the outcomes.  In many services, their success depends
on the consumer's contribution and help in getting the job done. 
For example, a patient going to a medical clinic for special
tests is told not to eat anything for 12 hours before the tests. 
If the patient disobeys, does not cooperate with the
instructions, the tests may not yield the expected results.  If
this happens, the patient may become angered at having to repeat
the process.  While blaming the clinic for incompetence, the
patient may not realize how much he contributed to the tests'
failure.   </i>

<p>5.  Compare and contrast the evaluation of quality in a good and
service.  <i>Quality in a good often can be determined by its
deviation from standards, how often it has to be repaired, and if
the repairs are serious.  The quality of a tangible good can
usually be judged more objectively and measurably than a service.
Service quality is in the eye of the beholder.  It is the
consumer's subjective judgment of how well the service met her
expectations.</i>

<p>6.  Discuss the reasons behind the economy's shift to services.
<i>The economy has shifted to being dominated by services for many
reasons, these include

<ul>
<li>the large number of women who are now working full-time out
     of their homes

<li>dual income families who pool their resources and have more
     discretionary income for such things as eating out and
     getting help with jobs that they no longer want to do

<li>the lack of time many people feel because they are commuting
     longer, working harder, and have less time to perform
     services for themselves

<li>increased stresses of modern life have provided
     opportunities for services that help people cope

<li>many manufacturing jobs have left the country

<li>the aging of the population, as the population bulge of the
     baby boomers nears retirement, more services will be needed
     to help older people care for themselves and stay in their
     homes as long as possible to avoid costly stays in nursing
     homes
</ul></i>

<p>7.  What dimensions affect a service provider's performance?
<i>Service provider performances are affected by their capacity to
perform, willingness to perform, and opportunity to perform.</i>

<p>8.  Why did not-for-profits avoid marketing for many years?  Why
are so many using marketing now?  <i>The reason many not-for-profits
avoided marketing was because the for-profit focus of marketing
activities was not compatible, in their view, with a not-for-profit image.  Many are using marketing now because they have to
compete for scarce funding.  They also realize that while their
core function may be not-for-profit, they have to be successful
in fund raising and building a sound financial base or they, too,
can go out of business.</i>

<p>9.  What are some forms of people marketing?  Give both
for-profit and not-for-profit examples.  <i>For-profit people
marketing includes entertainers, professional athletes, artists,
and professional people like lawyers, doctors, and dentists. 
Not-for-profit marketing of people includes politicians and
political parties.</i>

<p>10. Discuss whether or not the marketing concept applies to
services.  <i>It certainly does and is at the core of service
activities that try to satisfy consumers.</i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 14.1 </h4>

<p>1.  What is a service?  Is a service a product?  <i>A service is a
product that is intangible, perishable, inseparable, and variable
in its quality.</i>

<p>2.  Describe the unique characteristics of services.  <i>Services
are not tangible (cannot be felt); they are perishable (cannot be
inventoried, stored); inseparable (production and consumption
take place simultaneously); and vary in their quality due to
fluctuations in service performance.</i>
 
<p>3.  Discuss why a marketer's and a consumer's perception of
service quality may differ.  <i>Both come to the service encounter
with different expectations, thus while the marketer may think
that a good service has been performed, a consumer may be
dissatisfied.  Since each is serving their self-interest, it is
easy to see where a conflict can occur.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 14.2</h4>

<p>1.  Explain why services have become so important to consumers
and the U.S. economy. <i>Services have become so important because
society and the country have changed, more women work out-of-home, dual income families have the discretionary money to
purchase services, growing numbers of older people need more
services, people feel pressures from not enough time and too much
stress and seek services to help, and many manufacturing jobs
have left the country.</i>

<p>2.  What is the role of the consumer in the service encounter?
<i>The consumer assists in the performance of the service, therefore
can also contribute to the outcome.  </i>
 
<p>3.  Discuss the importance of employee capacity, willingness, and
opportunity in the effective delivery of services.  <i?These three
dimensions are extremely important in determining whether or not
the service performer does a good job.  Capacity and willingness
are well know contributors to work performance.  However, in
services in particular, it is important to consider whether or
not the service provider also has the tools and equipment,
materials and supplies to do a good job.  This dimension includes
having the authority to make decisions that will contribute to a
good service outcome.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 14.3 </h4>

<p>1.  Explain some of the ways that services are priced.  <i>Cost-based pricing is often used for equipment-based services. 
People-based pricing often uses competitive pricing or a
consideration of the service provider's image as a factor in
setting price.  Others may just follow a price leader.</i>

<p>2.  Can services be promoted?  Explain your answer.  <i>Promotion is
very important to services, for the same reasons as they are
important to goods but also because promotion helps establish
tangibility for services.  For example, the association of a
service with visual symbols in advertising gives the service an
image and tangibility.  This is the case for credit services
(tangible cards), telecommunications (pins), and insurance
services (umbrellas, rocks).</i>
            
<p>3.  Can a service provide a sustainable competitive advantage for
a business?  <i>For many tangible products that have no other point
of differentiation from competitive and indistinguishable
products, service may be the one factor that sets them apart. 
For example, most gasoline stations are almost identical and have
prices that vary only within pennies of each other.  However,
some stations differentiation themselves by offering customers a
free car wash service with a fill-up.  If others can't or won't
duplicate this service, it can become a competitive advantage.   </i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 14.4</h4>

<p>1.  Explain how profit and not-for-profit marketing differ.  <i>The
difference lies primarily in the profit motive.  Earning a profit
is not a primary organizational goal of not-for-profit
organizations, whereas it is for most for-profit businesses. 
Other than this, the marketing process is quite similar.</i>

<p>2.  Identify some types of not-for-profit marketing.  <i>Not-for-profit marketers include such public and private organizations as
governments, charities, hospitals, politicians, unions, religious
groups, zoos, social causes, and activists.</i>

<p>3.  Are there any not-for-profits that shouldn't market?  <i>Many
noncommercial organizations are marketed.  However, any not-for-profit that believes marketing activities are bad for its image
should not market itself, even if this is not the case.  </i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 14.5</h4>
<p>1.  Identify some of the newer applications of marketing. <i>Some of
the newer marketing applications include health care, people,
entertainment, leisure activities, places, events, educational
institutions, and information services.</i>
 
<p>2.  Do all lawyers agree that the marketing of legal services is
desirable? <i>No, this is still an issue that lawyers and the legal
profession have not resolved.</i>

<p>3.  Are the marketing concept and societal marketing concept
applicable to service businesses and not-for-profit organizations
that engage in marketing?  <i>Services are products and the
marketing concept is directed at all products.  It applies
equally well to not-for-profits, many of which are designed to
satisfy and serve consumers.  When it comes to the societal
marketing concept, many not-for-profits are successfully applying
it when for-profits are still talking about it.</i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 14.1: Mail Room Outsourcing: A Big Service Business  </h4>
    
<p>    Most people rarely spend time thinking about how their mail
gets delivered in a business or organization.  However,
considering its volume and importance, this is an important
service that few businesses or organizations could stand to lose. 
Financial institutions and businesses that must transmit valuable
documents often are more concerned about mailroom efficiency and
security.  Is this important in other types of businesses and
organizations?  Will increased use of the Internet (e-mail), fax
machines, and other telecommunications types lessen the
importance of the traditional mailroom?  Could this service be
ripe for greater automation?

<p>1.  What do you think of the rationale behind Burn's service
proposition?  <i>Answers may vary, but Burns's mailroom business
bundled with its security expertise should make it a highly
attractive service for many consumers.</i>

<p>2.  Do you agree with it?  <i>Yes, it makes good sense to increase
efficiency and security in locations where both may be lacking.</i>

<p>3.  Where else might Burns target its services?  Explain your
answer.  <i>Other targets for Burns's service might include
hospitals, medical centers, and educational institutions.     </i>


<h4>Mini-Case 14.2  Turmoil And Opportunity In Health Care Marketing</h4>

<p>     Health care marketing is big business in the United States. 
Health care insurance is a product that most consumers agree is
essential but some consumers believe is too expensive for them to
afford.  An alternative to traditional health care is offered
through health maintenance organizations that offer a wide array
of health care services to their members.  Where competition
between health care providers is intense, marketing can provide a
competitive advantage.  

<p>In the highly competitive health care market, insurers like
Prudential of America, Aetna Life & Casualty, and the various
Blue Cross/Blue Shields are rivals that seek to sign up
consumers, either through self-purchased health insurance or
employer-purchased insurance.  Do you think that marketing
differs between the for-profit and not-for-profit payors?  For
the most part, the goals and the methods are much the same. 
Differences between the two have blurred.
                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     Typically, burial services are unsought products.  Although
more consumers are prearranging funerals, most burial services
traditionally have not been arranged in advance.  If students
think this is an interesting issue to pursue, contact the funeral
homes in your city and ask for information on how they market
advance burial service plans.  You may locate a funeral home
director who will discuss funeral home marketing with your class.

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>     Please verify all Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment <b>before</b> you make it.  No
Internet address or information can be guaranteed past the date
of this <b><i>Manual's</b></i> publication.  Be sure to insist that students
demonstrate professional conduct at all times on the Internet.   

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>     One of the most successful Internet class activities that I
have used with introductory marketing students is the "Better
Mousetrap" assignment.  

<p>     Using an Internet search engine, search for sites that are
     selling a product of your choice.  For example, you may want
     to select a product that you already know is being sold on
     the Internet, like automobiles, music, or computers. 
     Alternately, you may be interested in searching for service
     products in your major, such as financial services,
     accounting services, advertising services, or real estate
     services.  Whatever you select, please use a product that
     interests you because it will make the search more involving
     and fun.

<p>     Find three to four sites that sell your product.

<ol>
<li>Identify the URL location of each site by gopher or
          http address, or provide a description of links so I
          can visit the sites.

<li>Describe and critique (compare and contrast) the sites.

<li>Imagine that you are the marketing manager for a
          competing product.  You are getting ready to launch
          your product on the Internet and you want to learn from
          your competition (their strengths and weaknesses on the
          Net) so that your product will be more effectively
          marketed in cyberspace.
<ul>

<li>Design a home page (no more than 3 computer
               screens) and identify the information that will be
               in each hypertext box.  Explain why you have used
               these boxes (why this information is important to
               your customers).

<li>Describe how consumers can pay for your product.

<li>Describe how you will establish a long term
               relationship with customers.

<li>Explain what it will take for you to sustain a
               competitive advantage over the competition.
</ul>
</ol>

<p>     This activity can be assigned to individuals or small
student teams of no more than two or three members.  I place no
restrictions on product type and many students select services. 
Past product choices include accounting, real estate, and
financial services, and music event marketing, along with such
tangible goods as guitars, automobiles, bicycles, and computers. 
Results are reported in memo form and an oral presentation to the
class that includes transparencies of their home pages.  

<p>    Any of the primary search engines can be used to identify 
sites, however Yahoo is particularly well suited to this task. 
Extensive listings can be located for almost any product type. 
For example, the Yahoo home page has topic category links to
subcategories with other links to documents and directories (see
below).
  
<ul>
<li> Art
<li> Business
<li> Computers
<li> Economy
<li> Education
<li> Entertainment
<li> Environment and Nature
<li> Events
<li> Government
<li> Health
<li> Humanities
<li> Law
<li> News
<li> Politics
<li> Reference
<li> Regional Information
<li> Science
<li> Social Science
<li> Society and Culture
</ul>

<p>     If a student clicks on Events, it leads to links for such
events as conferences, sports and games, festivals, and other
gatherings.  A click on * Entertainment leads to such topics as
amusement parks, aviation, books, comics, contests, cooking,
dance, fashion, and many others.

<i><p><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a></i>


<p>     Many other services can be investigated on the Net, even
services that generally are unsought, such as burial services. 
The WebCrawler and World Wide Web Worm can lead to such links by
using the search query funeral homes.  The home page sites
currently available are extremely informative.  One site suggests
that with our contemporary mobile society, the Internet is a link
for expressing condolences, irrespective of geographical
boundaries.  Is there a marketing opportunity here, for a service
that sends flowers, a condolence card, and even prepared foods to
the family of the recently deceased? 

<p>     Along with specific product information, these sites offer
information about bereavement.  This includes links to news
groups that help others cope with their loss, information on
grief and loss, frequently asked questions (FAQs) about coping
with chronic illness, children and grief, and support for parents
in their time of grief.  There are definitions of a funeral, and
information about burial insurance.  

<i>
<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br><a href="http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html">http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html</a>
</i>

<p>Population Demographics And Services

<p>     For students who are researching population trends in order
to identify service product opportunities as the population ages,
the U.S. Census Bureau is the most comprehensive site to visit. 
This site includes both national data and state data. 

<i>
<p><a href="http://www.census.gov">http://www.census.gov</a>
<br>     Census Bureau Home Page
<br>     View the topics in text o
<br>     Population and Housing
<br>     o Population
<br>     Population Projections (Forecasts for 1993 and Beyond)
<br>     U.S. Population Projections
<br>     National Projections
<br>          1995 National Projections
<br>          2000 National Projections
<br>          2005 National Projections     
<br>     State Projections
</i>


<h4>State Services Marketing</h4>

<p>     Is your state on the Internet?  Most are, and they are
marketing their parks and other tourist attractions, as well as
their educational facilities, quality of life, and value as a
site for economic development.  For example, a visit to the
Commonwealth of Kentucky Web Server contains a message from the
governor, along with links to colleges and universities, the
Churchill Downs Virtual Backside with information about the
Breeders' Cup, visitor centers in various cities, state parks,
the Kentucky Horse Park, major businesses, and a virtual tour of
the state.  

<i>
<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     search query: Commonwealth of Kentucky
<br>     0835  Commonwealth of Kentucky Web Server    
<br>     Kentucky Web Servers
</i>
     
<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 14.1</h4>

<p>     Some service encounters are extremely pleasant; others are
not.  A marketer who is trying to establish long term
relationships with consumers should be concerned about the
quality of the encounter.  Examples that students often cite of
poor service encounters involve car mechanics, bank tellers,
grocery store checkers, retail salespeople, and hotel desk
clerks.  Their responses on how to improve the service encounter
should begin with the employees involved in customer contact and
service delivery.  Improvements are a function of selecting,
training, motivating, rewarding, and managing customer contact
employees.  Having the right people at the contact point with
consumers is critically important, as is making sure that they
have the tools and equipment to do their jobs well.  Other
improvements are associated with the environment within which the
encounter occurs.  For example, in a car repair waiting room,
providing free coffee, current magazines, comfortable chairs,
soothing music, and a generally pleasant place to wait can make
the wait more bearable.  In a dentist's office, cheerful pictures
and humorous cartoons on the ceiling, where patients leaning back
in the dental chair can see them, soothing music and colors, can
help reduce tension.  


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 14.2</h4>

<p>In a typical day, most people will encounter a mixture of
services, and not stop to think about how the services are
classified, for example as people- or equipment based, or
targeted, to personal use, business, or organization consumers. 
The point of this Application is to make students more aware of
the variety of services they use and from which they benefit. 
Have them contrast the services by such factors as

<ul>
<li>extent of need -- are these services essential or are they
     wanted, but not really needed?

<li>frequency -- how regularly is the service used?

<li>pleasure derived -- does the consumer typically enjoy the
     delivery of the service, or is it something to be endured?

<li>level of participation -- how actively must the consumer
     participate in the service being delivered? 

<li>scheduling -- can the service be performed without advance
     notice, as when a consumer drives up to a bank teller
     window, or must it be scheduled in advance?

<li>price -- how expensive is the service to most consumers; can
     it be paid for with pocket change or is it a "big ticket"
     item that must be paid off in installments?
</ul>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 14.3</h4>

<p>     Responses will vary, but you should be prepared with your
own critical incident experiences to add to the class discussion. 
Critical incidents are used in social science research to capture
people's perceptions about situations in which they were
participants and/or observers (participant observers).  Critical
incidents can be used, as they are in this Application, to
recount consumers' experiences in the service encounter. 
However, in this case, students are taking dual roles, of
participant observers recounting critical incidents of service
delivery, and as marketers seeking to analyze what went wrong in
low-quality service examples.  Small teams of students can take
specific examples of poor service and consider ways to improve
the delivery.  
     
<p>     Alternately, students can consider their examples of high-quality service to find commonalities in what distinguishes the
services.  Often, the most powerful factor in high-quality
service is the effort made by the service provider.  Sometimes,
even when the eventual service outcome may be disappointing, the
service encounter is perceived as pleasant because of the extra
effort involved.  For example, a consumer goes to a bank to get a
home mortgage loan.  The bank loan officer works really hard with
the consumer to get the lowest possible interest rate on the
loan.  However, right before they lock in the loan, the Federal
Reserve unexpectedly raises interest rates, mortgage companies
follow, and the home loan comes in at the slightly higher rate. 
The consumer is disappointed in the final rate.  However, she is
impressed by how hard the loan officer worked to get the lower
rate and that he got the bank to reduce its closing costs in
light of the situation.  As a result, the consumer decides to
move her checking and savings accounts to this bank.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 14.4 </h4>

<p>     Rather than have students perform the research needed to
determine how effectively your local government uses marketing,
invite a guest speaker to class to address this issue. 
Information about city government marketing can be addressed to
the office of the city manager, mayor, or director of economic
development.  A city ombudsman or information office may be able
to provide the information and a contact person.  If you are near
state or federal government offices, you may find a guest speaker
there. 

<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>

<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 14.1</h4>

<p>     Total customer service, as it is practiced at the Phelps
County Bank (PCB), is a model for other banks.  How do banks in
your city compare?  Are they as focused on customer service? 
Students can perform participant observations of their own
banking experiences to answer this question.


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 14.2</h4>

<p>     Do you have a laundry/bar like Duds 'n' Suds near a local
college?  There is one adjacent to our largest state university
and it is very popular with students and area residents.  What do
your students think of the idea of bundling services together in
this way?  Are there other services that have been successfully
bundled?  Are there some that could be bundled?  Do they present
a promising opportunity for an entrepreneur?


<h4>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>     The first McDonald's in the former Soviet Union was a
popular subject of newspaper and magazine articles in the early
1990s.  Students can easily find these articles and learn more
about this remarkable story.  Many Russians resettled in the
United States when the Soviet Union collapsed.  You may be able
to find a recent immigrant through an English As A Second
Language program in your public school system.  If possible, ask
that a contact be identified who can speak to your class about
services in the former Soviet Union and contrast his or her
experiences with services in the United States. </p>

<p>

