<head>
<title>CHAPTER 12: PLACE: DISTRIBUTION AND WHOLESALING</title>
</head>

<h1><center>CHAPTER 12</h1>
<h1>PLACE: DISTRIBUTION AND WHOLESALING</h1>
</center>

<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>

<p><b>1. Explain how promotion works.  </b>Promotion is persuasive,
purposive marketing communication about products.  Promotion
performs many tasks.  It informs consumers, helps build a brand
image, persuades consumers to make a purchase, reminds them about
products, and even entertains them.  Promotion works by breaking
through the clutter and presenting a brand as a champion that can
solve a consumer's problem.  Promotions are used to establish
long term relationships with consumers that focus marketing
activities on getting close to and connecting with them, and
satisfying their needs and wants.  Marketing communications are
described by the communication process model where a source
encodes a message that is transmitted through a communication
channel to a receiver, who decodes the message and provides
feedback.  Noise can come from anyplace, including mechanical,
technical, human sources.  Noise can undermine if not prevent
communication.  Marketing promotion is performed by businesses,
as well as government, organizations, and individuals. 
Integrated marketing communication (IMC) is designed from the
consumer's perspective and uses many promotion types to deliver
integrated, unified, coordinated messages and incentives.  It is
finely targeted to receptive audiences using information obtained
from databases.


<p><b>2. Discuss promotion decisions.  </b>Promotion decisions are about
which types to use (advertising, sales promotions, personal
selling, public relations/publicity, direct marketing), how to
use them, when and for how long, using what media.  Decisions
about promotions are designed to determine how to get the
consumer to act, most often to make a purchase.  The hierarchy of
effects model is used to describe how consumers are moved from
awareness to purchase.  It is more effective for understanding
how consumers are moved from awareness to purchase high
involvement products.  Consumers control promotions in many
different ways, including such activities as selectively
perceiving promotions, changing channels when advertisements
appear, requesting removal of their names from direct mail lists,
using call screening on their telephones to block sales calls,
and refusing to buy products whose promotions irritate or offend
them.


3. Identify the steps in a promotion plan.  The promotion plan is
a blueprint for action that sets objectives for promotion to
achieve and provides a roadmap for doing so.  Promotion planning
is affected by product characteristics including stage in the
life cycle, price and place; the competition; target audience
characteristics; the channel of distribution; and what is
happening in the environment.  Steps in the planning process
include identifying promotion goals, making promotion
assignments, formulating promotion strategy, identifying target
audiences, developing the message, selecting the promotion types,
allocating the budget, and implementing, evaluating, and making
modifications to the promotion plan, as needed.



<p><b>4. Describe promotion budgeting practices.  </b>There are many ways
that promotion budgets are set, including such methods as
percentage of sales, competitive parity, all that's left, seat of
the pants, objective and task, and the use of sophisticated
computer models.



<p><b>5. Address criticisms of promotion. </b>Promotion is the element in
the marketing mix that blatantly calls attention to itself.  It
is criticized for being very costly, which adds to product
prices.  The intensity of promotion and its pervasiveness
encourage consumer materialism and conspicuous consumption. 
Promotion is criticized for being devious and untruthful,
misleading, deceptive, overly harsh, and blighting the landscape. 
Advertising is criticized as being misleading, tasteless, and
toxic.  Promotion is also blamed for invading consumers' privacy. 
In defense of promotion, it provides information that can
increase competition and lower prices.  It subsidizes a free
press and provides a public service through public service
announcements.  Millions of people throughout the world are
employed in promotions.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>     The chapter's opening questions are "How will marketers
promote their products in the next century?  Will promotion as we
know it today via mass media (television, radio, newspapers,
magazines) be as prominent?"  If you have been using Internet
assignments, your students will have a more personal
understanding of the implications of rapid technological change 
for marketers communicating with target audiences.  Ask students
to consider these questions and relate them to their experiences
on the Internet.  What can they conclude about the possible
impact of Web commerce on traditional promotion delivery systems? 
What will be more likely to change, the message or the delivery
system?  Will this mean the death of mass advertising and other
promotions aimed at the mass market?  Will the Internet
accelerate the movement toward mass customization which, in this
case, will be the mass customization of promotion messages and
delivery systems.

<p><b>Planning Promotions For The Egg Delivery System</b>

<p>     This is a good point to refer back to the egg delivery
system and relate the product to its promotion.  How should the
product be promoted?  What factors must be considered in making
promotion decisions?  How important is it to plan promotions from
the consumer's perspective?  This is particularly relevant to the
egg delivery system because the target audience may be quite
small.  Ask the same student teams that designed the egg delivery
system to develop a simplified promotion plan for the product. 
This includes an analysis of the value that promotion adds to
this product, particularly as it informs consumers about product
benefits.  Their results can be reported in memo form or through
brief oral presentations to the class.

<p><b>Ethics And Promotions: An Oxymoron?</b>

<p>     Because of the weight of criticism about promotion, this
chapter provides an opportunity for students to debate the value
of promotion to marketers, consumers, and society.  Many
professional organizations have codes of ethics that state
guidelines for professional behavior in promotions.  Students may
examine some of these codes and decide for themselves whether or
not the codes are comprehensive and helpful to marketers facing
serious ethical dilemmas, or not.  

<p>     Students can evaluate problem areas in promotions by
collecting examples of criticisms as exemplified in print
advertisements, outdoor promotions, and on television.  If each
student brings one example to class, it will provide a good
starting point for determining whether the criticisms are serious
or frivolous.  Consider whether the value that promotions add is
greater than the weight of the criticisms.

<p>     Many current articles describe problems in promotions. 
Students can research such problems as telephone deceptions,
invasions of consumer privacy, sales fraud, and the glut of
television commercials.  Invite a guest speaker from the local
Better Business Bureau to class for a first-hand perspective on
problems in promotions.
     
<p><b>Promoting An Innovative Product To U.S. Consumers</b>

<p>     A search of current business publications will reveal
examples of new product introductions and their promotion plans
that you can use in class discussions.  For example, some of your
students may have been part of the target audience for promotions
introducing Jergens Refreshing Body Shampoo to American consumers
in late 1994.  

<p>     Cincinnati based Andrew Jergens Co. is owned by Kao Company,
Japan's leading detergent business.  Kao is the Japanese market
leader for such personal use consumer products as diapers,
shampoos, and soaps, with worldwide 1994 sales of over $7
billion.  It is also successfully marketing floppy disks,
chemicals, and other products in the United States.

<p>     Despite their successes elsewhere in the world, most
Japanese soaps, cosmetics, and toiletries marketers have not been
very successful in the U.S. market.  Many believe it is because
the Japanese have failed to develop consumer insights about their
target marketers.  They fail to understand the American
mentality.

<p>     Kao calls its new product an innovation for the American
market.  It is a liquid body soap, more expensive than bar soap,
but also longer lasting.  It comes with its own blue and white
application sponge.  Consumers pour a small amount of body soap
into a small depression in the sponge, then squeeze the lather
onto the body.  The liquid soap comes in two formulations, mild
clean scent and deodorant-fresh clean scent.

<p>     Japanese consumers love this type of product, which fits
their perception of a bath as a serious part of a daily cleansing
ritual.  By comparison, American personal cleansing habits are
"... more a frivolous indulgence," according to the senior vice
president of marketing for Jergens (Ono 1994, p.B8).  Moreover,
American consumers prefer showers to baths and hard bar soaps
comprise 97 percent of body cleansing products.  

<p>     In addition to magazine print advertisements and television
commercials, Jergens direct mailed product samples and discount
coupons to consumers in selected zip codes across the country
(zip code demographics).  Trial sizes were offered at discount
prices in retail stores.  The promotional message claimed that
the liquid soap, called a body shampoo system, won't dry skin
like bar soap, is quick to lather, provides a massage through the
action of the sponge, rinses easily, and leaves no soapy film.

<p>     Students can be drawn into a discussion of this case by
asking whether or not they received one of the initial free
samples, have seen the advertisements, and/or have used or
currently use the product.  Bring a sample of the product to
class as a visual aid so students can relate case details to the
physical product.  Questions to discuss include

<ul>
<li>Is this product as innovative as the company claims?

<li>What are the chances that American consumers will change
     their bathing habits and abandon bar soaps for a liquid body
     shampoo?

<li>What promotions could be used to develop consumer awareness
     of this product?

<li>Based on consumer insights about American bathing habits,
     what message(s) should be used to counter initial resistance
     to the product?

<li>What incentive(s) should be offered?

<li>Is this a gender-specific product (more acceptable to one
     gender than the other)?  If so, what are some barriers to
     making it more acceptable to both?

<li>Once the product is introduced and sales begin to grow, what
     promotions should be used during the maturity stage of the
     life cycle?

<li>Can good promotions save a good product that consumers don't
     want?
</ul>

<p><b>     Reference</b>
<p>     Ono, Yumiko (1994), "Kao Tries to Sell Japanese Soap in the
     U.S. Market," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (August 8): B1, 8.

<p><b>Guest Speaker</b>

<p>     A guest speaker from a local professional organization or
promotions business can be invited to class to talk about the
issues introduced in this chapter.  If possible, identify a guest
from an agency engaged in integrated marketing communication
services.  Find out how they develop a promotion plan, implement,
evaluate, and control it.

<p><b>International Promotion</b>

<p>     International promotion environments often differ
substantially from the environment in the United States.  In
addition to the complexities of cross cultural communication,
marketers also have to deal with legal restrictions, delivery
system access problems, and protectionism.  Consider that

<ul>
<li>Australia has strict local content laws restricting where
     television commercials can be filmed

<li>Alcohol and tobacco advertisements are strictly banned in
     many European countries

<li>In countries with large Moslem populations, women must be
     covered, and unmarried couples are not to touch in print or
     television advertisements

<li>In many countries, sales promotions are banned because they
     are thought to give large business, that can afford to offer
     them, advantages over smaller competitors

<li>Illiteracy is common in Africa, Asia, and parts of South
     American, which severely limits the use of written messages
</ul>

<p>     Ask students to find other examples of differences in
promotion environments worldwide.  International students may
contribute to this discussion with observations from their homes
as well as their travels.

<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Explain how promotion works
<ol>
<li>For promotion to work, it must first break through the
          clutter of promotions that bombard consumers on a daily
          basis

<li>Promotion works by establishing a product as a hero,
          able to solve consumer's problems, and by helping to
          form a relationship with consumers, showing how the
          product can solve their problems over a long period
<li>There are different perspectives on promotion
<ul>
<li>Promotion is communication, holding a conversation
               with consumers, usually from a distance, using the
               communication process
<ol>
<li>In the communication process, a source
                    originates a message then encodes and
                    transmits it through a delivery system, where
                    a receiver decodes the message into
                    understandable thoughts
<li>A receiver usually provides feedback
<li>Noise can occur anywhere in the process and
                    often distorts, interrupts, or cancels the
                    process
</ol>
<li>Some promotion is personal, as in personal selling
<li>Promotion is used to stimulate word-of-mouth
               distribution of a message
<li>In order for promotion to work, it must be
               designed for the target audience at which it is
               directed
<li>Promotion must be built around consumer insight in
               order for it to achieve the goals set for it
</ul>
<li>Integrated marketing communication (IMC) is promotion
          designed from the "outside in" that begins with
          consumer insight, relies on databases to finely target
          appropriate messages and incentives, and calls for
          coordinating promotion types so that a consistent,
          unified voice cuts through marketplace clutter
</ol>

II.  Discuss promotion decisions
<ol>
<li>Marketers must decide what promotion types are best for
          each situation
<li>The promotion mix includes advertising, personal
          selling, sales promotions, public relations/publicity
          and direct marketing
<ul>
<li>Advertising (mass and direct) is the use of 
               nonpersonal messages usually paid for by an
               identified sponsor using electronic, print, and
               other media
<li>Sales promotions add value to products by offering
               purchase inducements on a temporary basis to
               stimulate consumer demand, build store traffic, or
               encourage the trade to move products through a
               channel of distribution
<li>Personal selling is the most personal type of
               promotion and involves face-to-face, telephone,
               and other forms of contact 
<li>Public relations/publicity has the goal of
               generating a favorable image and goodwill, and
               providing information without necessarily
               identifying the sponsor
<li>Direct marketing includes a wide array of
               promotion forms that direct highly targeted
               promotional messages and incentives at selected
               consumers
</ul>
<li>Promotion works in mass advertised, high involvement
          products by getting consumers to act through a series
          of steps that move them from awareness, through
          knowledge, liking, preference, and conviction, to
          purchase
<li>Consumers control promotions in many ways, including
          such actions as deciding whether or not to pay
          attention to them, removing their names from direct
          mail lists, changing television channels, and
          boycotting brands whose advertisements irritate or
          offend them
</ol>

III. Identify the steps in a promotion plan
<ol>
<li>A promotion plan is a blueprint for action that sets
          specific objectives for the promotion program to
          achieve over a designated time period
<ul>
<li>Different promotion goals can be identified during
               a product's life cycle, from informing consumers
               when the product is first introduced, to
               persuading and reminding them to purchase the
               product when it is in its maturity
<li>Other influences on promotion planning are such
               factors as price, place, characteristics of the
               product, the competition, channels, and what is
               happening in the economy
</ul>
<li>Generally, promotion planning proceeds through several
          steps, some of which may occur concurrently
<ul>
<li>Identify promotion goals
<ol>
<li>What the promotion is expected to accomplish
<li>By defining promotion goals, outcomes can be
                    measured against the goals to determine
                    promotion effectiveness
</ol>
<li>Make promotion assignments
<ol>
<li>Promotions can be planned and implemented
                    internally, externally, or using both in-house and external promotion professionals
<li>The advantages of these alternatives must be
                    considered before making a decision on
                    promotion responsibilities
</ol>
<li>Formulate promotion strategy
<ol>
<li>Strategy involves making decisions about how
                    to achieve promotion goals
<li>Promotion delivery systems and targets vary
                    according to whether the distribution channel
                    strategy is push, pull, or mixed
<ul>
<li>A push strategy directs promotion at the
                         trade in order to push products through
                         channels; it is often heavily weighted
                         toward personal selling, price deals,
                         and sales promotions
<li>A pull strategy promotes directly to
                         consumers in order to build demand and
                         get consumers to pull products through a
                         channel; it is often heavily weighted
                         toward advertising and sales promotions
<li>A mixed strategy uses both push and
                         pull, and the promotion types identified
                         with them 
</ul>
</ol>
<li>Identify target audiences
<ol>
<li>Effective promotion is built on consumer
                    insight
<li>Information used in targeting includes
                    demographics, psychographics, and past
                    purchase records collected in computer
                    databases
</ol>
<li>Develop the message
<ol>
<li>Two major types of message strategies are
                    emotional and rational appeals
<li>The message must be appropriate to the target
                    audience and the spokesperson must be
                    credible
</ol>
<li>Select the promotion types
<li>Allocate the budget
<li>Implement, evaluate, and make modifications
<ol>
<li>Implement means launching the promotion
                    program and managing it
<li>Evaluating means comparing promotion goals to
                    outcomes
<li>Modifications may be needed when feedback
                    indicates that the promotion needs adjustment 
</ol>
</ul>
</ol>

IV.  Describe promotion budgeting practices
<ol>
<li>The promotion budget specifies how much money can be
          spent on promotion
<li>Allocations are the amounts set aside from the budget
          for specific promotion activities
<li>There are many ways to set a promotion budget,
          including such methods as percentage of sales,
          competitive parity, all that's left, seat of the pants,
          objective and task, and the use of computer-based
          models
</ol>

V.   Address criticisms of promotion
<ol>
<li>Promotion is the marketing mix variable that openly
          calls attention to itself, which often leads to intense
          scrutiny and criticism
<li>Promotion is criticized for many reasons
<ul>
<li>It is costly and critics believe that these
                    costs add to product prices
<li>Promotions are devious and untruthful
<li>Promotions are blamed for encouraging
                    consumers to purchase products they don't
                    need and can't afford
<li>Promotions are criticized because of
                    promotion scams; competitive advertising that 
                    gets hostile; outdoor promotions that lead to
                    visual blight; misleading, tasteless, and
                    even toxic advertisements; and invasions of
                    privacy 
</ul>
<li>Promotion is defended for providing important product
          information that increases competition and lowers
          prices, subsidizing a free press, and supporting many
          worthwhile public causes through public service
          announcements and pro bono (donated) work
<li>Promotion is monitored and regulated by government at
          all levels; through laws, agencies, and professional
          self-regulation through such organizations as the
          American Marketing Association, American Association of
          Advertising Agencies, Direct Marketing Association,
          Council of Better Business Bureaus and local Better
          Business Bureaus
</ol>


<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  If consumer demand exceeded product supply, would there still
be a need for promotion?  Explain your answer?  <i>Yes, even if
demand was greater than supply, promotion would still be needed
to inform consumers about products.  Obviously, a greatly reduced
amount of promotions would be required if demand exceeded supply,
unless it became necessary to demarket products.</i>

<p>2.  What is promotion clutter?  Identify some sources and explain
why it is a problem.  <i>Clutter refers to the often excessive
number of promotion contacts a consumer experiences in a time
period, such as a day, week, or month.  Some of the clutter comes
from obvious product promotions, such as advertising, sales
promotions, personal selling, direct marketing, and
publicity/public relations.  Other clutter comes from more subtle
communications about products through such things as labels on
clothing, product placements in motion pictures, and product
packaging.  It is a problem because consumers become overwhelmed
by the volume and screen out most of the communications in self-defense.  This makes it harder for the marketer to break through
the clutter and consumers' perceptual screens to capture
consumers' attention.</i>

<p>3.  Discuss the simple model of the communication process. 
Explain the importance of this model to promotion.  <i>Marketing
communication is described within a simplified model of the
communication process.  This model states that a source
constructs a message (encodes it), then transmits the message
through a delivery system (the communication channel or medium)
to the receiver, who decodes the message.  The receiver often
sends feedback to the sender (source).  Noise may occur
throughout the communication process and includes everything from
technical interference (radio static, television transmission
problems) to people interrupting the process.  This model is
important because it helps explain how communication occurs and
why communication problems can occur. </i>

<p>4.  Why is relationship marketing of concern to marketers?  Can
it benefit consumers?  <i>Marketing promotions are used to establish
relationships with consumers.  It is important for marketers to
establish a long term relationship in order to build customer
loyalty and facilitate repeat purchases and cross selling.  It is
important to consumers, because when marketers concentrate on
developing a long term relationship, there is a greater
probability that consumer needs will be identified and served.</i>

<p>5.  Compare and contrast integrated marketing communication (IMC)
and traditional promotion.  <i>Integrated marketing communications
develops promotions from the consumer's perspective, creating
unified, coordinated messages and delivery systems based on
information derived from past purchase patterns.  IMC calls for
managing promotion types together, so that all promotions are
unified.  Because the promotions speak with one voice, they can
have greater impact and break through the promotions clutter. 
Traditional promotion is more likely to be designed from the
inside out, from the marketer's perspective.  All promotion types
are not necessarily used or integrated, nor do they always
deliver a unified message.</i>

<p>6.  How is consumer insight important to promotions?   <i>Like all
marketing activities, promotion must be based on knowledge about
consumers, their needs, preferences, and purchase behaviors. 
Consumer insight should be the basis on which relevant messages
are developed, attractive incentives are offered, and appropriate
promotion channels (media) are selected.</i>

<p>7.  What are some of the promotion decisions that marketers must
make?   <i>Marketers must make decisions about which promotions to
use, whether individually or together.  Promotion decisions are
designed to determine how to use promotions to get consumers from
awareness to action.  Decisions are made about when to promote,
how to promote, how much to promote, and for how long.</i>

<p>8.  Identify the types of promotions in the promotion mix. <i>The
promotion types typically identified as elements in the promotion
mix are advertising, sales promotions, personal selling, public
relations/publicity and direct marketing.</i>

<p>9.  What are the steps in promotion planning? <i>Promotion generally
proceeds through several steps, some of which may occur
concurrently.  They include identifying promotion goals, making
promotion assignments, formulating promotion strategy,
identifying target audiences, developing the message, selecting
the promotion types, allocating the promotion budget,
implementing, evaluating and making modifications. </i>

<p>10. Discuss some of the criticisms and defenses of promotion.  
<i>Promotion calls attention to itself far more than the other
marketing mix elements.  It is criticized for costing too much
and adding to product prices; encouraging wasteful consumption;
exaggerating the truth; being deceptive; offending through
hostile competitive advertising; causing visual blight;
delivering misleading, tasteless, and toxic advertisements; and
invading consumers' privacy.  Promotion is defended because it
provides information that encourages competition which lowers
prices; supports a free press; provides employment for millions
of people worldwide; and contributes public service time and
space.  </i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 11.1 </h4>

<p>1.  Describe the role of promotion in marketing.  <i>Promotion is
persuasive, purposive marketing communication about products. 
Promotion informs, persuades, reminds, and even entertains
consumers.  Promotion can differentiate a product from its
competition.  Promotion contributes to sales and revenues through
these processes.</i>

<p>2.  What is relationship marketing?  Why is it important? 
<i>Relationship marketing calls for establishing a long term,
mutually beneficial relationship with consumers.  It is important
because it builds consumer loyalty, encourages repurchases, and
provides opportunities for cross selling.  Because a relationship
is based on consumer insight and understanding, it enables the
marketer to provide products and offers designed to benefit
consumers.</i>
 
<p>3.  Explain how integrated marketing communication differs from
traditional promotion activities.  How are they alike? 
<i>Integrated marketing communications (IMC) and traditional
promotional activities use the same promotion types (advertising,
personal selling, sales promotions, public relations/publicity,
and direct marketing).  However, IMC uses many promotion types in
an integrated, coordinated, unified way to develop messages and
incentives using a database of consumer purchase behaviors. IMC
is developed from the consumer's perspective.  Traditional
promotions are developed from the marketer's perspective, do not
necessarily use more than one promotion type, and are not
necessarily integrated, coordinated, and unified.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 12.2 </h4>

<p>1.  Can good promotion save a bad product?  Can bad promotion
kill a good product?  Explain.  <i>The best promotion cannot save a
truly bad product, because consumers will act in their self-interest and not repurchase.  They may be fooled once, but rarely
twice.  Bad promotion can kill a good product because it will
fail to give consumers information about the product's benefits,
will not build awareness or persuade consumers about the
product's value.  If consumers don't purchase the product, it
will eventually be removed from the market.</i>

<p>2.  What is the hierarchy of effects model?  Does it always
accurately describe consumer responses to promotions?
<i>This model suggests that promotions, particularly mass
advertising, move consumers through a series of steps that climax
with exchange.  These steps are awareness, knowledge, liking,
preference, conviction, and purchase.  It doesn't always
accurately describe consumer responses, because it is a high
involvement model.  Also, not all consumers will be moved to act. 
However, it does offer insights into what happens when consumers
respond to promotions for mass market, highly involving products.</i>

<p>3.  Explain some of the ways that consumers control promotions.
<i>Consumers control promotions using many different methods, some
of which are more effective than others.  Consumers control
promotions because they selective perceive them, consciously or
unconsciously screening out some promotions while attending to
others.  Consumers also control promotions to the extent that
they refuse to purchase products whose promotions irritate or
offend them.  When sales and revenues fall, or complaints rise
because of a widespread reaction to offensive promotions,
marketers often respond by removing or replacing the offending
promotion.  Consumers can control direct mail messages by having
their names taken off direct mail lists.  They can screen out
telephone sales calls by using call screening.  Consumers use
remote controls to change television channels and avoid
advertisements.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 12.3 </h4>

<p>1.  Why is planning an important part of promotions?  <i>A promotion
plan is a blueprint for action for promotions.  It lays out a
roadmap for promotions, from goals to outcomes, and causes the
planners to consider what must be done to accomplish the
promotion goals.  Planning can help marketers avoid costly
mistakes and take advantage of opportunities when they appear. </i>

<p>2.  Describe the steps in promotion planning.  <i>Promotion planning
requires such steps as identifying promotion goals, making
promotion assignments, formulating promotion strategy,
identifying target audiences, developing the message, selecting
the promotion types, allocating the budget, and implementing,
evaluating, and making modifications to the promotions, as
needed.</i>
            
<p>3.  Compare and contrast several promotion budgeting methods.
<i>There are many promotion budgeting methods, including percentage
of sales, competitive parity, all that's left, seat of the pants,
objective and task, and using computer-based statistical models.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 12.4</h4>

<p>1.  What are some of the criticisms of promotion? <i>Promotion is
criticized for many reasons, including such things as its costs,
untruthfulness and deception, encouragement of conspicuous
consumption, scams, hostile competitive advertising, visual
blight, and tasteless, misleading, and toxic advertising.  There
also are growing concerns about promotion and the invasion of
consumer privacy.</i>

<p>2.  What are some of the positive things associated with
promotion?  <i>Promotion informs consumers about products, which
reduces prices.  Promotion encourages competition and the
effective operation of the free market.  Promotion supports a
free press and provides free time and space for public service
announcements.  It provides employment for millions worldwide.</i>

<p>3.  Describe some of the controls on promotion. <i>Promotion is
monitored and regulated by government, laws, and self-regulation
through professional groups.</i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 12.1: Promoting Through Sports Sponsorships             </h4>
   
<p>    Sports sponsorships extend from professional sports
sponsorships and the Olympics to your local soccer or baseball
leagues.  Some sports would find it difficult to survive without
sponsors.  Your students may have experience with sports
sponsorships, because their business is a sponsor or they are on
a sponsored team.  Ask about the pros and cons of sports
sponsorships, from their own perspective and that of the business
sponsor.  How do they feel about Philips Electronics' Ten
Commandments of Sponsorship?  Do all the statements apply at the
local level?  

<p>1.  Is sports sponsorship a good idea for every business?  <i>It is
a good idea for many businesses.  There will always be
exceptions, however, and a business must decide whether or not
sponsorships in general, and a specific team sponsorship is an
appropriate activity.</i>

<p>2.  The Gay Games IV, which were held in New York City, involved
11,000 athletes, had over a half million out-of-town spectators,
and pumped over $100 million into the New York City economy.  In
the United States, there are estimated to be 13 to 14 million
adults who identify themselves as gay or lesbian.  As a group,
they are well educated with higher disposable incomes than
straight consumers; gay consumers are five times more likely to
earn over $100,000 a year.  The next Gay Games will be held in
Amsterdam in 1998.  What are the benefits/costs of being a
business sponsor for the Gay Games?  <i>The benefits for many
businesses come from reaching a desirable target market.  The
costs, in addition to the sponsorship, come from the business
being associated with an activity that bothers some consumers and
raises strong opposition in others. </i>

<p>3.  Was 1994 World Cup sponsorship a good promotion idea? <i>It
certainly promoted sponsors worldwide more effectively than in
the United States, where professional soccer remains relatively
unsupported.  Soccer is the number one sport in the world, but
not in the United States.</i>


<h4>Mini-Case 12.2  Wilma!  A Blowout Of Promotions</h4>

<p>     What do your students think about movie promotions?  <i>Perform
a simple class survey to determine how many have made a recent
purchase decision based on their desire to take advantage of a 
sales promotion linked to a popular movie.  For example, students
with young children may have chosen one fast food restaurant over
another because of a special sales promotion that appealed to
their children.  If this is the case, would it indicate that the
sales promotion has been effective?  </i>

<p>1.  Some members of the film industry are very critical of movies
being reedited for marketing promotion purposes.  How do you feel
about it?  <i>Answers will vary, however, many students will
probably express resentment for the intrusion of marketing into
film decisions.  Others won't find it offensive, as long as they
enjoyed the movie.</i>

<p>2.  Have movie sales promotions and product placements and
product placements become intrusive or are they effective ways to
sell products?  <i>Again, student answers will vary.  Some product
placements are more offensive than others, particularly when the
placement is inappropriate, intrusive, or detracts from the film. 
Other students may believe that having contemporary brands in
contemporary films adds a touch of reality.</i>

<p>3.  Can sales promotions like Barq's and Marlboro's build the
brand?  <i>Many believe that a successful sales promotion can
contribute to brand building; others believe that sales
promotions destroy brand loyalty.  It depends on the brand, the
promotion, and the competition.  This is still a controversial
issue.</i>
                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     U.S. tobacco companies carefully monitor the environment for
changes that affect them, which in the case of Canada, means
support for a ban on all tobacco advertising.  Tobacco use in the
United States has declined significantly in the latter part of
the 20th century.  However, tobacco remains a highly
controversial topic with many different facets fueling public
debate, from health aspects to tobacco subsidies.  Students, like
most consumers generally, probably have strong opinions about
tobacco use and marketing.  Students can debate the pros and cons
of tobacco advertising and sponsorships.  Because of the
continuing controversy, students will find many current articles
about tobacco marketing that can be used to develop debate
topics.

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>     Please verify all Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment <b>before</b> you make it.  No
Internet address or information can be guaranteed past the date
of this <b><i>Manual's</b></i> publication.  Be sure to insist that students
demonstrate responsible conduct on the Internet at all times.   

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>     A search using any of the tools previously identified
reveals many useful documents that students can use to search for
more information about marketing promotions.  For example, the
following queries on WebCrawler (tm) uncovered interesting and
varied links to related topics.  These include

<ul>
<li>advertising (over 2,800 documents)
<li>public relations (over 1,500 documents)
<li>sales promotions (over 270 documents)
<li>coupons (over 70 documents)
</ul>

<p>     Links to sources about Europe, the European Union,
Euroconsumers, and European promotions can be located through
"I'm Europe".

<i><p><a href="http://www.echo.lu">http://www.echo.lu</a></i>
     

<p>     Students can evaluate statements by various professional and
business organizations about promotion ethics and acceptable
behaviors by visiting the Web sites for the American Marketing
Association, American Association of Advertising Agencies, and
Council of Better Business Bureaus.  At the Council of Better
Business Bureaus, students can learn about the services offered
by the Bureaus, including advertising self-regulation,
marketplace complaints, and scam alerts.  A directory of all BBB
offices can be used to obtain contacts for guest speakers.

<i>
<p>     American Marketing Association
<br><a href="http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks">http://www.nsns.com/MouseTracks</a>

<p>     American Association of Adversiting Agencies
<br><a href="http://www.commercepark.com/AAAA/AAAA.html">http://www.commercepark.com/AAAA/AAAA.html</a>

<p>     Council of Better Business Bureaus    
<br><a href="http://www.igc.org/cbbb/">http://www.igc.org/cbbb/</a>
</i>

<p>     Articles printed from Advertising Age are available on the
Internet and often provide worthwhile reading for students
seeking current information about marketing promotions from one
of the top publications in the field.

<i><p><a href="http://www.adage.com">http://www.adage.com</a></i>


<p>     Student teams can perform a content analysis of how various
businesses are promoting their products on the Internet.  This
requires visiting business sites to determine if they are
informing, persuading, reminding, building a brand image, and/or
entertaining.  Many of the business sites cited in previous
chapter Using the Internet sections can be used for this project. 
Businesses in the entertainment industry often are the best sites
to visit for this analysis.


<p>     Promotion oversight can be investigated at the Federal Trade
Commission and various state government home pages through their
Attorney General's office.

<i><p><a href="http://www.ftc.gov">http://www.ftc.gov</a></i>
          
<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 12.1</h4>

<p>     Personal clutter audits will doubtlessly uncover many
promotion contacts with obvious sources, such as television,
radio, and newspapers.  However, by directing students to focus
on promotion clutter, they will become more aware of it and the
variety of clutter sources.  This illustrates the power of
selective perception because most consumers must be selective in
what they attend or risk serious sensory overload.  Develop a
class clutter audit by asking students to contribute to a class
list of clutter types and their sources.  Consider how consumers
defend themselves against clutter yet tune in to promotions that
are important and involving.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 12.2</h4>

<p>     When it comes to promotions that cut through the clutter,
consumers often disagree about which promotions are successful at
cutting through the clutter and the reason why.  This reflects
individual involvement and perception, although segments of
consumers will share both.  A lively class discussion can develop
over why certain promotions are so good at cutting through the
clutter, and others fail.  While some students may think a
particular advertisement or sales promotion is extremely
effective, others will think it boring, stupid, or insulting, as
well as ineffective.  Without fail, over the past several years,
the Energizer Bunny has surfaced as one of my students' most
hated or most liked advertisements (print and television); it
cuts through the clutter because it is so unfunny or funny, take
your pick!  


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 12.3</h4>

<p>     A simply class survey of how consumers perceive advertising
in relation to promotions will most likely demonstrate the
inability of consumers to differentiate between the two, and
their lack of concern about it.  There is a similar inability to
distinguish between marketing and selling.  Students can consider
whether or not this is a problem, either for consumers or
marketers.  The blurring of marketing and selling is more serious
than that of advertising and promotions, principally because it
reflects a failure to recognize the importance of marketing
activities other than selling.  An added problem is that many
consumers lack respect for selling, which spreads to marketing in
general if the two are equated.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 12.4 </h4>

<p>     Small student teams can consider this Application, develop
their promotion tactics, then report them in memo and/or oral
form.  Each team can consider a different client, the florist,
candy store, or diet center.  If several teams consider the same
client, have them develop a consensus program that can be
reported to the class.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 12.5</h4>

<p>     Student opinions about celebrities in this Application
usually are surprisingly consistent.  Students often agree about
what characteristics contribute to an effective spokesperson and
they often name the same celebrities.  For example, a celebrity
spokesperson for home repair tools is often identified with a
popular television situation comedy that involves tools; home
exercise equipment is identified with a successful female
exercise video celebrity.  Try the flip side of this Application. 
Ask students to identify the celebrity who would be the least
credible and effective.  Have them examine the basis for their
selections.


<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 12.1</h4>

<p>     Do your students use advertising circulars?  What types of
circulars are most used?  The answer depends on many factors,
such as consumer age, financial condition, purchase situation,
and timing.  One type of advertising circular that is extremely
popular is the supermarket circular that identifies weekly
specials and often provides product discount coupons.  You'll
often see consumers with circulars in their hands as they walk 
supermarket aisles.  What value is the circular to consumers who
use it?   Other popular circulars arrive in time for back-to-school sales and around Christmas.  Can your students identify
other popular seasonal circulars?


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 12.2</h4>

<p>     Ask students to bring to class representative samples of
direct mail they have received recently.  Evaluate these samples
for their compliance with the writing tips offered in this
Consumer Insight.  How do they compare?  How effective are these
samples for promoting a purchase? 


<h4>INTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>     If you have international students in class, they may be
interested in sharing their observations about how different
cultures influence promotions and particularly, mass advertising. 
Students from Europe can contrast advertising in their country
with the United States and if possible, with advertising in other
countries in the European Union.  Even though many observers
believe that Europe is moving toward greater economic
integration, cultural integration is far slower.  As a result,
products with few cultural implications may benefit from
standardized promotions, while culturally associated products may
not.</p>
<p>

