<head>
<title>CHAPTER 10: PLACE: THE ROLE OF RETAILING</title>
</head>

<h1><center>CHAPTER 10</h1>
<h1>THE ROLE OF RETAILING</h1>
</center>

<h2>CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h2>

<p><b>1. Describe the evolution of retailing in the United States.  </b>The
earliest retailers were general merchandisers, stores offering
products of many different unrelated lines in a scrambled
merchandise strategy.  Specialty stores evolved as alternatives
to general stores offering a limited line but greater depth of
products.  Contemporary scrambled merchandise stores are often
extremely large, with considerable width and depth.  Retailing is
a dynamic activity that continues to change because of intense
competition, the volatility of consumer demands, and changes in
the environment.  Several theories of retail development try to
explain why and how retailers change.  These include the wheel of
retailing and accordion theories.  The development of many new
retail types illustrates how retailers are trying to satisfy
consumer demands for alternative shopping arrangements.  These
new types include such forms as outlet malls, superstores,
warehouse clubs, hypermarkets, and resale shops.


<p><b>2. Explain the contribution of retailing to the U.S. economy. 
</b>Retailing is an important part of the U.S. economy.  It is
relatively easy to become a retailer, but many retailers fail.  
Retailers in the United States generate over $2 trillion in
annual sales and provide almost 20 million jobs.  Retailing as a
whole is expected to grow slowly into the next century. 
Retailers are categorized by the U.S. government as durable goods
stores, nondurable goods stores, and nonstore retailers.


<p><b>3. Identify the retailer's tasks and the decisions they make. </b>
Regardless of retail type, retail tasks are similar to those that
were performed in the general store.  They include buying,
selling and leasing products; communicating information about 
products, their prices, and where they can be obtained; and
negotiating product exchanges with consumers.  Because of the
intense competition among retailers, they often must change in
order to survive.  Retailers must make long-range strategic
decisions, as well as short-range tactical decisions.  One of the
most important decisions retailers make is that of location.


<p><b>4. Recognize some of the common ways of classifying retailers. </b>
Many different retailers typically operate in any geographical
area.  They range in size and product assortment, as well as
along other attributes.  One important attribute is that of store
atmospherics, the tangible and intangible elements that
communicate to consumers what the store is like and the type of
products it sells.  Store image is how consumers mentally
perceive the store.  Pricing philosophy signals consumers about
the retailer's prices.  Service level and form of ownership are
other important factors that provide useful information to
consumers, as well as competitors.


<p><b>5. Discuss the future of retailing.  </b>Some marketers wonder
whether or not there is a future for store retailers.  While
store retailing is very volatile and certainly will change in the
next century, it is extremely doubtful that stores will
disappear.  While store retailing has its ups and downs, nonstore
retailing is thriving.  Many consumers prefer direct selling
because they can make their purchases from home, which saves
time, energy, and expense.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>     The discussion of the place marketing mix variable begins
with retailing rather than with a broader presentation of the
channel of distribution.  This placement of topics is consistent
with the premise of the textbook, namely that learning about
marketing can be made easier and more relevant if it is
personalized.  Since students will have far greater familiarity
with retailing than with the other distribution activities, as
consumers and possibly employees, retailing is introduced first.  
     
<p>     Chapter 10 poses a question that is troubling to many store
retailers, "How will retailing change as more consumers gain the
ability to shop from home through the electronic marriage of
television, computers, and telephones?"  What do your students
think about shopping?  Do they enjoy it or is shopping a
burdensome chore?  Poll students to determine their feelings
about retailing and whether or not they use nonstore retailers. 
If they do, for what product types?  Their observations and the
class discussion can be used to gain insight into consumer
responses to retailing. 

<p><b>Most U.S. Retailers Try To Satisfy Consumers</b>

<p>     Retailing in the United States is highly consumer oriented,
to a great extent because of the intense competition retailers
face from store and nonstore retailers alike.  For example, a
growing number of local retail banks are opening Saturday
mornings and early weekday evenings; bank branches are springing
up in supermarkets and shopping malls.  Bank retailers deal with
an increasingly competitive environment as they vie for customers
with rival store banks, banking by mail, and electronic banking
on the Internet.  As a result, retail banks are making a greater
effort to be open at the hours consumers want, where consumers
shop, delivering services that consumers expect.  

<p>     Many Wal-Marts are open 24 hours a day, as are supermarkets
and gasoline stations.  Often these retailers bundle their
products with others, for example many Ashland Oil gasoline
stations now house Taco Bell restaurants; Wendy's and Baskin
Robbins are joining forces in some locations under a single roof;
many Wal-Marts also house a McDonald's franchise.  A growing
number of supermarkets are carving out prime store space for
retail bank branches.  Students may be able to add to the list of
retailers bundling under one roof.  Are these retailers in the
forefront of a movement toward micromalls, miniature versions of
large shopping malls conveniently housed under one roof,
available in locations that consumers prefer?  Are there some
retailers who shouldn't bundle because their products and target
markets are incompatible?  Can students identify some retailers
who they believe would gain customers if they bundled?  What
retailers other than fast food franchises might attract consumers
to gasoline stations located beside major interstate highways? 
Could a micromall concept turn some consumers away instead of
attract them?  Why?

<p>     Sears, Roebuck & Co. is taking a different approach, yet
also seeking an alternative to large shopping malls.  As the
number of shoppers at malls has declined since 1990, Sears has
mounted an aggressive effort to establish a presence off the
malls (Chandler 1995).  Sears set a goal for 1995 of opening 50
new freestanding Sears Hardware Stores in urban areas and small
towns, at strip malls and commercial strips.  By the turn of the
century, Sears plans to have 500 hardware stores and 250 of its
Homelife furniture and mattress stores open across the country. 
By 2000, it will have opened 800 independently owned rural
stores.  

<p>     What are some of the other ways that retailers seek to
establish a competitive advantage over their competitors in
pleasing consumers?  Will Sears be able to withstand the
established competition in hardware and furniture?  Students can
discuss these questions and compile a list from their own
experiences and observations of what contemporary retailers are
doing to satisfy consumers.

<p>     While service is a key competitive approach in the United
States, this is not always the case in other countries.  Germany
is notorious for bad customer service in everything from Deutsche
Telekom AG, the national telephone monopoly, to stores and
restaurants.  For example, stores close Saturday afternoon and
don't reopen until Monday morning, many German restaurants won't
accept credit cards, and some consumers must wait years for
Telekom to install their telephone (Steinmetz 1995).  Why do
German consumers put up with the situation?  Many believe it is
because they don't know any better.  How long can this retailer
insensitivity to consumers continue?  Ask your students what will
change it?

<p><b>References</b>
<p>     Chandler, Susan (1995), "Where Sears Wants America to Shop
     Now," <i>Business Week</i> (June 12): 39.

<p>     Steinmetz, Greg (1995), "Customer-Service Era Is Reaching
     Germany Late, Hurting Business," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>
     (June 1): A1-6

<p><b>Relationship Marketing And The Life Time Value Of A Customer</b>

<p>     Retailers, like other marketers, want to keep their good
customers because they recognize the life time value of a
customer and the high cost of finding new customers.  Brand
loyalty extends to retailers as well as products like colas and
automobiles.  Many retailers are implementing programs to ensure
that enduring relationships are established with important
customers.  They collect names and addresses of their best
customers, develop in-house computer lists, and work these lists. 
Retailers make regular mailings to list members, notifying them
about special sales for preferred customers, providing
information about new products, and sometimes letting special
customers know when new items in their favorite product lines
have been received.  Frequent contact is one of the keys to
building a long term, profitable retailer-customer relationship.

<p>     In retail banking, relationship marketing has a long history
as a key tactic in holding and expanding a good customer base. 
Since much of retail banking relies on personal selling, bank
salespeople can establish lasting personal relationships with
important accounts and cross-sell them other bank services.  For
example, a consumer comes to a bank to open a checking account. 
That one service can be expanded through effective relationship
marketing to include selling a safety deposit box, savings
account, money market account, home mortgage, escrow and home
equity accounts.  In the near future, banks will probably also be
able to offer their customers a brokerage account for stocks and
bonds.  Through successful relationship marketing, banks and
other retailers can add value to the customer's retail
experience, strengthen the ties that bind retailers and
consumers, and develop a life time exchange relationship.

<p>     Relationship marketing depends on collecting usable
information about consumers and using a well-trained salesforce
armed with that information to cater to customer needs.  However,
what the retailer considers catering may seem to some consumers
as an invasion of their privacy.  This raises a troubling
question about how far marketers should go in collecting consumer
information.  If consumers perceive that retailers have gone too
far, they will react.  An incident was reported recently where a
consumer unexpectedly received a postcard from a store announcing
a shirt sale.  This was the same store where the consumer had
purchased a shirt by credit card the previous week.  The
consumer, upset that the store had used an independent company to
track his address from his credit card number, vowed to never
shop the store again (Silverman 1995).  

<p>     Savvy retailers train their salespeople to be sensitive to
consumers and not press for information if consumers seem
reluctant.  Students have probably encountered situations where
they have been asked for information and been uncomfortable.  Did
the salesperson back off or were they pressed to provide the
information?  How can a retailer collect information that is
needed in establishing a relationship with customers and not
scare the customer off?

<p>     Students should not be left with the impression that only
large retailers collect information about consumers.  More small
and large retailers are taking advantage of cheap personal
computers to set up information tracking systems.  Small mail
order operations track customer orders by computers, just like
giants Sharper Image and L.L. Bean.  A five store bagel retailer
has developed a customer comment database built on a word
processing program's database capacity.  It is used to track
feedback, complaints, and suggestions.  Information in the
database has even led to personalized service for one customer
who repeatedly complained that the store's bagels weren't salty
enough.  With a day's notice, this customer gets a specially
baked batch of extra salty bagels (deJong 1995).  

<p><b>     References</b>
<p>     deJong, Jennifer (1995), "Turbocharging Customer Service,"
     <i>Inc. Technology</i> (June): 35-39.

<p>     Silverman, Stephen M. (1995), "Information Backlash," <i>Inc.
     Technology </i>(June): 27.

<p><b>U.S. Catalog Sales Booming In Japan</b>

<p>     While the Yen has strengthened against the dollar, U.S.
catalog retailers have experienced a boom in sales to Japanese
consumers.  Direct marketers have a clear shot into Japanese
homes, avoiding the distribution problems that have plagued other
U.S. marketers of products such as automobiles and photographic
film.  Catalog retailers in the United States maintain 24-hour
toll-free telephones and fax lines to accommodate different time
zones.  They can deliver overseas orders quickly.  To the
Japanese, U.S. catalog retailers are almost always cheaper than
store retailers in Japan.  U.S. catalog retailers avoid Japanese
tariffs on imported goods and can take advantage of counter
cyclical demand patterns.  For example, back-to-school shopping
occurs in the United States in August and September; in Japan, it
occurs in March (Updike and Kuntz 1995).  Some of the catalog
retailers successfully cracking the Japanese retail market are
L.L. Bean, Lands' End, Eddie Bauer, and the Franklin Mint.  Most
offer consumers Yen-denominated, Japanese language catalogs.    

<p><b>     Reference</b>
<p>     Updike, Edith Hill and Mary Kuntz (1995), "Japan Is Dialing
     1 800 BuyAmerica," <i>Business Week</i> (June 12): 61, 64.

<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Describe the evolution of retailing in the United States
<ol>

<li>Retailing includes a wide range of marketing activities
          designed to present products to consumers for them to
          purchase in stores as well as through nonstore mediums
<ul>
<li>The roots of modern retailing go back to the late
               1700s and early 1800s when general stores offered
               a scrambled merchandise assortment of products to
               consumers
<li>Specialty stores evolved as a retail alternative
               that offered a limited line, but many choices
               within the line
<li>Today, many different types of retailers coexist
               and profit in the same town
</ul>
<li>Retailing is a highly dynamic marketing activity that
          continues to change because of intense competition, the
          volatility of consumer demands, and changes in its
          environments
<ul>
<li>The wheel of retailing is a theory of retail
               development that suggests that as retailers
               prosper, they tend to trade up, grow larger, and
               become higher priced competitors
<li>Other theories explain retail change as a response
               to competitive pressure, or as a cyclical series
               of reactions to opportunities
</ul>
<li>Retailing has changed dramatically, which has resulted
          in the appearance of many new types, including such
          retailers as outlet malls, superstores, warehouse
          clubs, hypermarkets, and resale shops
</ol>

II.  Explain the contribution of retailing to the U.S. economy
<ol>

<li>It is extremely easy to become a retailer, but the rate
          of failure is high
<li>Retailing is big business in the United States, with
          payrolls of over $247 billion annually and almost 20
          million jobs
</ol>

III. Identify the retailer's tasks and the decisions they make
<ol>

<li>Retailers perform marketing activities related to the
          exchange function, this means that retailers must
<ul>
<li>Obtain a desirable assortment of products to offer
               consumers
<li>Inform consumers that the products are available
<li>Ensure that their location is appropriate, safe,
               and convenient
<li>Make products available at convenient times
<li>Take delivery of the products ordered, unpack,
               label, and display them
<li>Make payment arrangements and inform customers
               about them
<li>Sometimes offer associated delivery services
<li>Hire, train, and supervise retail employees
<li>Offer additional services as needed and/or desired
</ul>
<li>Retailers make long-range strategic decisions, as well
          as short-range tactical decisions
<li>Some people believe that the most critical decision a
          retailer makes is about location
</ol>

IV.  Recognize some of the common ways of classifying retailers
<ol>
<li>Many different retailers compete in the same area
<li>Retailers are characterized by their attributes
<ul>
<li>Store atmospherics are a very important attribute
               that communicates information to consumers about
               the retailer and the products it sells 
<li>Store image is the mental perception consumers
               have of a retailer
<li>Product assortment, pricing philosophy, and
               service levels also characterize retailers
</ul>
<li>Ownership form is less important to consumers than it
          is to retailers
</ol>

V.   Discuss the future of retailing
<ol>
<li>in the United States and other industrialized
          countries faces many challenges
<li>Some wonder whether or not there is a future for store
          retailers
<li>The future for nonstore retailers looks bright
<ul>
<li>Direct selling is growing in popularity, as
               products are brought directly to the consumers
               home
<li>Direct response marketing uses various approaches
               to interact with consumers through such devices as
               mail orders, telemarketing, catalogs, direct
               response advertising, and the Internet
</ul>
</ol>

<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  What was retailing like in the early days of this country?  
<i>Retailing was primarily in general stores, which had scrambled
merchandise strategies, and in specialty stores, which
concentrated on a limited line but at a greater depth.        </i>

<p>2.  Describe some of the new retail types. <i>Retailing is
constantly changing, therefore many new retail types have evolved
recently.  These include outlet malls, superstores, discounters,
supermarkets, warehouse clubs, hypermarkets, television shopping
networks, electronic retailers, interactive kiosks, and resale
shops.</i>

<p>3.  What is the significance of retailing for the U.S. economy?
<i>It contributes an annual payroll of over $247 billion and employs
almost 20 million people.  It is an important part of the U.S.
economy.  Retailing is expected to grow slowly into the next
century.</i>

<p>4.  Describe a retailer's tasks.  <i>Regardless of the type of
retailer, there are certain tasks that must be completed.  These
tasks are related to the exchange function of marketing.  This
includes buying, selling, and leasing products; communicating
information about the products, their prices, and where they can
be obtained; and negotiating product exchanges with consumers.</i>

<p>5.  Compare and contrast a general and a specialty retailer.  <i>A
general retailer offers many different products in many product
lines.  A specialty retailer focuses on a limited number of
related lines, but offers greater product depth.</i>

<p>6.  What is a category killer?  Explain the name, and give
examples.  <i>Category killers are extremely large retailers, such
as Home Depot and Toys R Us, that are so big that they can
overwhelm local competitors with their deep discounts and
extensive inventories.  They typically specialize in product
categories, like toys, office supplies, or home repair products.</i>

<p>7.  What factors are often used to classify retailers?  <i>Retailers
are classified by their product assortment, pricing philosophy,
service level, form of ownership, site, and such attributes as
store atmospherics.</i>

<p>8.  Explain what is meant by the term product assortment. <i>A
product assortment is the mix of products that a retailer offers
consumers.  This includes the number of product lines and their
width and depth.</i>

<p>9.  Compare and contrast the operations of store and nonstore
retailers. <i>Store retailers and nonstore retailers are alike in
many ways, except with a nonstore retailer, the consumer doesn't
have to leave home to shop.</i>

<p>10.  What kinds of retailers will be successful in the next
century?  Why?  <i>Indications are that nonstore retailers will be
highly successful in the next century.  However, this does not
mean the disappearance of store retailers.</i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 10.1 </h4>

<p>1.  Describe how retailing has evolved in the United States. 
<i>General stores and specialty stores existed even in the earliest
history of the United States.  They exist today, with
considerable variations.</i>

<p>2.  Compare and contrast the retail strategies of scrambled
merchandising and specialty merchandising.  <i>Scrambled
merchandising is a general approach to retailing with many
different product lines offered to consumers, but usually in
limited assortments.  Specialty merchandising allows the retailer
to focus on one or several related product lines and offers
greater depth to consumers.</i>
            
<p>3.  Explain the wheel of retailing theory.  <i>This is a widely
known theory about the evolution of retail organizations.  The
wheel of retailing suggests that retailers change as they
prosper, grow larger, offer more services, stock a better quality
of products, and trade up.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 10.2</h4>

<p>1.  Identify several new retailer types.  <i>Retailing is
continuously changing, which is reflected in the many new retail
types that are common today.  These types include outlet malls,
superstores, discounters, supermarkets, warehouse clubs,
hypermarkets, television home shopping networks, interactive
kiosks, and resale shops.</i>

<p>2.  What is a resale agent?  <i>A resale agent is a retailer who
accepts used products from sellers in order to resell them,
typically in a store.  Sometimes these products are accepted on
consignment, where the reseller does not take title to the
products, but instead acts as an agent for the seller, accepting
a commission when the products are sold.</i>

<p>3.  Explain the importance of retailing to the U.S. economy. 
<i>Retailing is very important to the U.S. economy because it
employs almost 20 million people and represents sales of over $ 2
trillion.  Retailing is expected to grow slowly into the next
century.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 10.3 </h4>

<p>1.  Describe the types of tasks assumed by retailers. <i>Regardless
of the retailer type, all perform similar tasks related to the
exchange function of marketing.  This includes buying, selling,
and leasing products; communicating information about the
products, their prices, and where they can be obtained; and
negotiating product exchanges with consumers.</i>

<p>2.  Discuss the types of decisions made by retailers.  <i>Retailers
make many decisions, some are long-range strategic decisions,
others are short-range decisions.  Location is one of the most
important decisions a store retailer can make.</i>
 
<p>3.  Explain the importance of retail location decisions. 
<i>Location is a critically important decision because where a store
is located determines to a great extent the type of consumer who
will be drawn to shop there.  </i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 10.4</h4>

<p>1.  What are store atmospherics?  <i>Why are they important and to
whom?  Store atmospherics are the tangible and intangible
attributes that communicate information about the store to
consumers.  They are important to consumers because they indicate
store type.  They also are important to the retailer, because
store atmospherics make a statement on behalf of the retailer
about the nature of his or her business. </i>

<p>2.  Describe the major ways of classifying retailers.  <i>Retailers
are classified by many different factors, including their product
mix, pricing philosophy, service level, ownership form, and site.</i>

<p>3.  What advantages might a retailer achieve by offering products
both in a store and through nonstore means? <i>This strategy, of
using both a store and nonstore approach, covers all bases.  By
mixing strategies, the retailer should appeal to different types
of consumers, both those that enjoy store shopping and consumers
who prefer to shop at home.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 10.5</h4>

<p>1.  Compare and contrast the major forms of store retailers.
<i>Major forms of store retailers are general merchandise, mass
merchandise, and specialty merchandise groups.  The general
merchandise group includes department stores, variety and general
stores.  The mass merchandisers are the workhorses of modern
retailing.  They include such retailers as catalog stores,
warehouse clubs, discount stores, and supermarkets.  The
specialty merchandise group is made up of specialty retailers,
such as limited-line and single-line stores.</i>
 
<p>2.  Why do you think nonstore retailing is growing so fast? <i>There
are many reasons for the growth in popularity of nonstore
retailing.  Consumers and retailers both like the nonstore
alternative.  The consumer saves time and effort shopping a
nonstore retailer; the nonstore retailer saves the time and
expense of having to deal with other marketing intermediaries. </i>

<p>3.  Is vending machine shopping going to be popular with all
consumers?  Explain your answer.  <i>No form of retailing is going
to be popular with all consumers.  Some consumers will like this
alternative, because of its convenience; others will prefer store
retailers or other forms of nonstore retailing.</i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 10.1:  Wal-Mart: Small Retailers' Nightmare?   </h4>

<p>    Wal-Mart is a giant among mass merchandise discounters.  Most
consumers have heard of Wal-Mart; many have highly polarized
opinions about the world's largest retailer.  Wal-Mart Stores is
ranked the 4th largest Fortune 500 company in terms of sales and
revenues; the 12th largest in terms of profits.  Wal-Mart is
innovative and demanding of its suppliers.  Like many large
corporations, it has had its share of ups and downs.  The downs
include the embarrassment of being exposed for selling
merchandise labeled US-made that wasn't, and various lawsuits
charging unfair pricing practices.  Wal-Mart provides an
interesting topic for students to debate.  Information about Wal-Mart can be found on the Internet (see <a href="#internet">Using the Internet</a> in this
chapter), as well as in popular and business magazines and
journals. 

<p>1.  Should Wal-Mart be admired as a well-run corporation or
criticized for squeezing the life out of small town retailers? 
<i>Responses may vary, however, Wal-Mart is the largest and fastest
growing retailer in the United States and the largest retailer in
the world.  It deserves to be admired for the efficient way that
the corporation is managed and the high level of consumer
satisfaction it maintains.  However, many small town retailers
have not found a way to compete with Wal-Mart and as a result,
consumers' available retailer choices have been seriously reduced
in many communities.  Like most topics in marketing, there are
two sides and both have merit.</i>

<p>2.  What do you think of the "niche around" policy?  Will it
work?  <i>It has worked for many well-managed small businesses.  A
poorly managed business probably wouldn't survive long with or
without Wal-Mart.  The "niche around" policy recognizes the
opportunity presented by Wal-Mart's product depth gaps.  It makes
good marketing sense; however, the challenge is in successfully
implementing it.</i>

<p>3.  Is there room enough for both a Wal-Mart and small retailers
in the same town?  <i>Absolutely, as has been demonstrated in the
small towns where Wal-Mart has opened.  Many small businesses
thrive, despite and because of Wal-Mart.  After all, Wal-Mart is
a magnet for many consumers, attracting them to a shopping area
where they might not ordinarily visit.  Therefore, there is
always an opportunity for a small business to capitalize on this
influx of shoppers and capture some of the spillover.</i>


<h4>Mini-Case 10.2: Saving Sears:  A Retailing Challenge</h4>
 
<p>     Sears is definitely reinventing itself, but it is doing so
by returning to its original success, in retailing.  Sears is
returning to its core competencies and early signs indicate that
this is a smart move.  This is still a major company, ranked 33rd
by profits on the Fortune 500 list, and 9th by sales and
revenues.  Students can debate Sear's retailing strategy using
information found on the Internet (see <a href="#internet">Using the Internet</a> in this
chapter), as well as in popular magazines and business journals. 

<p>1.  How important is image to Sears?  <i>Image is extremely
important to Sears, because the image that consumers form of the
retailer will influence their shopping.  If consumers perceive
that Sears' image is compatible with what they want in a
retailer, then they will shop Sears.  Sears' problem is to decide
what image to project, up-scale or mid-scale, a tool store or a
fashionable but reasonably priced clothing store.</i>

<p>2.  What part does store atmospherics play in establishing a
store image?  <i>Store atmospherics contributes considerably to the
formation of image.  It includes the cues that consumers
interpret when forming a store image that will guide their
purchase decisions.</i>

<p>3.  J.C. Penney is challenging Sear's up-scale image remake in
both the United States and Mexico.  If these companies, as well
as other department stores like Dillard's, Saks Fifth Avenue, and
Bloomingdale's, are also entering the Mexican market, what do you
think are the chances that this market will also become
overbuilt?  <i>The Mexican economy is volatile and unstable, as
shown by the peso devaluation in early 1995.  There are
differences in shopping patterns between Americans and Mexicans,
and the Mexican middle class is vastly smaller than the middle
class in the United States.  Therefore, there are fewer consumers
with the purchasing power needed to shop these retailers.  These
retailers, and others who join them, will probably overestimate
the size of the Mexican market and there will be a shakeout as
some leave Mexico, at least temporarily.  A Wal-Mart might have
greater initial success in Mexico, at least in the short-term,
than up-scale retailers.</i>
                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     Supermarket slotting fees are highly controversial.  Some
manufacturers consider them extortion; most supermarket retailers
think they're a good source of added revenue.  What do your
students think?  Some have probably worked for a grocery store or
supermarket that charges slotting fees.  If possible, have them
share their insights with the class.  A comprehensive body of
articles exists about slotting fees.  It is a topic that usually
provokes student reactions and can be used for a class debate.

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>
     
     Please verify all Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment <b>before</b> you make it.  No
Internet address or information can be guaranteed past this
<b><i>Manual's</b></i> publication date.  Be sure to impress on your students
the importance of professional behavior on the Net, at all times.


<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>     Some major national retailers are already on the Internet;
others are making plans to join them.  Sometimes they have a dual
presence, both at a <b>corporate home page</b>, where information about
the company is presented, and as a <b>Net store or catalog site</b>,
where products can be evaluated and purchased.  Some of the
largest retailers in the country, by annual profits and
sales/revenues, are listed below.  As of the publication date of
this <b><i>Manual</b></i>, the retailers marked with an asterisk (*) were on
the Internet.  The search query for a retailer on the Net is
provided beside the company name.

<ul>
<li>Wal-Mart Stores*         - search: Wal-Mart Stores
<li>Sears Roebuck & Co.*     - search: Sear's Tools
<li>McDonald's
<li>J.C. Penney*             - search: J.C. Penney
<li>Toys R Us
<li>Dayton Hudson*           - search: Target Stores
<li>KMart
<li>Spiegel*                 - search: Cybermart - Spiegel
<li>Service Merchandise*     - search: Service Merchandise
</ul>

<p>     Two-person student teams or small groups of students can
select a retailer, then use their Internet search skills to
identify paths to information about the retailers, corporate home
pages and Net store sites, as well as business references on
retailers.  A corporate home page often will have links to the
retailer's Net store or Net catalog.  Sometimes these store sites
are located within Net malls.  The results of their research can
be communicated in a written memo and/or a brief report to the
class.

<p>     J.C. Penney, Sears & Roebuck Co., and Wal-Mart Stores are 
examples of major national retailers on the Internet.  They can
be located in several different ways.  


<p>1.   J.C. Penney can be reached through a WebCrawler search query
     for J.C. Penney.  Enter the J.C. Penney Co. link.  This site
     has documents about the company, its mission, and
     shareholders information.  Penney's, along with other
     retailers, is also in the Yahoo site Business: Corporations:
     Retailers.  

<i>
<p><a href="http://Webcrawler.com">http://Webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     search:  J.C. Penney

<p><a href="http://www.yahoo.com ">http://www.yahoo.com </a>
<br>     select  * Business            
<br>     select  * Corporations
<br>     select  * Retailers     
</i>

<p>2.   Sears & Roebuck Co. can be found by using a WebCrawler
     search query for Sear's Tools.  The link is to the Shopping
     2000 mall home page directory.  The Sear's mall store lists
     Craftsman products, provides descriptions and contacts.

<i>
<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>     Shopping 2000 Home Page
<br>     Click here for text only browsing
<br>     Directory
<br>     Sear's Tools
</i>


<p>3.   Wal-Mart Stores can be found through a WebCrawler search or
     by going directly to the Wal-Mart home page.  It is an
     extensive and well documented site with information about
     the company, career opportunities, store locations, and a
     current Wal-Mart circular with products and prices.

<i>
<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>Wal-Mart Stores
<p><a href="http://www.wal-mart.com">http://www.wal-mart.com</a>
</i>


<p>     National retailers often can be located by running a query
through a search engine such as WebCrawler or the Global Network
Navigator, or by "trolling" for a Web site.  This requires
opening a URL and searching for a site by typing in your educated
guess about a company address.  For example, to troll for a
company named XYZ, you could try http://www.xyz.com  -- or -- 
http://xyz.com.  

<i>
<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>search: _________ (retailer name)  

<p><a href="http://nearnet.gnn.com">http://nearnet.gnn.com</a>
<br>     The Whole Internet Catalog
<br>     All Subjects
<br>     * Internet Commerce
</i>


<p>     Alternately, students can search for business references
about retailers on the Internet.  For example, information about
retailers, as well as other businesses, can be located at the
site of the Fortune 500.  Links from this site can be searched
for business profiles of different companies.

<i>
<p><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>
<br>search: Fortune 500
<br>select  Fortune 500
</i>


<p>     Specialty retailers also are flocking to the Internet. 
Their numbers and the variety of product assortments they offer
are growing daily.  Students can find an abundance of information
about retailers of specific product types by using Yahoo,
WebCrawler, and other search tools.  A recent search using the
query "retailers" identified 413 documents covering 21 computer
screens.  The types of retailers represented included on-line
book retailers, apparel retailers, general shopping malls,
automobile retailers, bicycle shops, travel malls, computer
hardware and software retailers, and various retailer home pages. 
A Yahoo search found specialty retailers along with large catalog
retailers, discounters, and others.

<p>     On-line shopping malls are springing up daily.  Some offer
single product lines; others are mixed, offering a scrambled
product assortment.  Mall shopping on-line is not the same as it
is in stores, although virtual electronic shopping approximates
walking down a mall, looking in store windows, and browsing store
shelves and displays.  

<p>     The Internet Mall is cleverly modeled after a multi-story
store shopping mall.  Automotive and related retailers are
located in the Space Garage.  Space floors one through six offer
such product lines as books, magazines, and media (1st floor),
computer hardware and software (3rd floor), clothes and sporting
goods (5th floor), and food and beverages in the Space Top Floor. 
This Mall is an exciting place to visit and provides a very
sophisticated example of on-line retailing.  It is a heavily
trafficked Internet site.

<i>
<p>The Internet Mall
<br><a href="http://www.mecklerweb.com">http://www.mecklerweb.com</a>
</i>

<p>     There are several advantages to retailers who establish
their presence on-line in a mall.  The costs are far less in a
mall than they would be to set up and maintain an independent Web
site.  If the mall is product line specific, for example a travel
mall, computer mall, or automotive mall, then it will draw
consumers specifically interested in those product lines.  If the
mall is registered with the major search engines, consumers will
use them to find directions to the mall and its retailers from
multiple starting points.  

<p>     There also are drawbacks to on-line malls.  On-line malls
are not like store malls where shoppers can browse and window
shop many stores, and a synergy is built between stores, food
courts, and movie theaters.  On-line malls don't have the same
kinds of attractions.  Few consumers wander Web malls like they
wander store malls.  If they are connected to the Internet by a
commercial service, they have to pay for on-line service, so
wandering an on-line mall can become expensive.  The second
problem relates to how they connect.  Net surfers with a text-only browser can browse a mall's stores more quickly, but they
can't receive graphics or product pictures.  Graphical browsers,
while they can see products visually, take much longer to receive
information and download pictures, particularly with the slow
modems that most consumers use (less than 14,400 baud).

<p>     Because commercial use of the Internet is so new, retailers
are still trying to figure out how to use it.  Although consumers
are just beginning to shop the Net, their numbers will surely
grow.  The consumers who currently Net shop are very desirable
target markets because they generally are younger and have 
higher educations, incomes, and buying power.  Some marketers
believe that for a Net mall to be successful, it must

<ul>
<li>offer quality information about its stores, products, and
     prices

<li>be accessible in a reasonable time frame so that consumers
     can download information without long waits

<li>offer some entertainment value, along with interesting links
     to other sites

<li>have a limited number of stores, avoiding the "overkill" of
     a megamall that is so large it discourages consumers from
     entering

<li>be registered on all of the search engines and as many other
     places as possible, including mentions in hardcopy print
     publications
</ul>


<p>     Students can visit and compare different Internet retail
malls.  This activity is most effective if assigned to two-person
student teams or small groups of students.  They should document
URL addresses so you have a record of their trips and can later
see for yourself what is at the malls.  The results of their
shopping trips can be reported in memo form as well as to the
class in a brief oral presentation.


<h4>Used Product Retailers On The Internet</h4>

<p>     Used product retailers are using the Internet to sell
everything from antiques to used books.  Searches can be run
using any of the following queries.  Students can compare the
results of a search of used product retailers (resellers) locally
(<b>Marketing Application</b> 10.2 on page 310 of the text) with used
product retailers on the Internet.

<ul>
<li>search:  used products
<li>search:  consignment sales
<li>search:  used cars
<li>search:  used furniture
<li>search:  used books
<li>search:  antiques
<li>search:  auctions
</ul>


<h4>Retailing Statistics</h4>

<p>     Students can research retailing statistics through the U.S.
Census Bureau, the source for retailing data in the textbook. 
They can study Table 1281 Retail Trade - Sales, by Kind of
Business, in the Statistical Abstract of the United States at the
Census Bureau site.  Information on small business retailers may
be found at the Small Business Administration site.

<i>
<p><a href="http://www.census.gov">http://www.census.gov</a>
<Bbr>     topics in text
<br>     Population and Housing
<br>     o Statistical Abstract of the United States
<br>     o Frequently Requested Tables
<br>     Retail Sales, by Kind of Business

<p><a href="http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov">http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov</a>

<p>     -- or --

<p><a href="http://www.fedworld.gov">http://www.fedworld.gov</a>
<br>     Business, Commerce and Economics
<br>     Small Business Administration
</i>

<h4>Retail Factors That Consumers Value</h4>

<p>     Ask students to review the retail factors listed in Figure
10.2 (page 317 of the text), then have them modify the items so
they are appropriate to Internet shopping.  For example, the time
factor on the Internet can indicate the time required to find the
retailer, locate a product, and download product information. 
The price factor on the Internet can be restated to include
whether or not prices are current, how easily they are found, and
what type of payment process is offered.  Any of the search
engines can be used to find products and retailers on the
Internet.


<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 10.1</h4>

<p>     Students can perform a local retailer inventory using the
Yellow Pages Index of your telephone directory.  Alternately,
they can evaluate product offers from retailers in on-line malls
that offer the same products.  Have them consider whether or not
they would prefer shopping for the product in a store, a catalog,
or on-line.  What are the advantages and disadvantages of each?


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 10.2</h4>

<p>     Resale retailers of clothing, automobiles, furniture, and
other products are growing in popularity in many places around
the country.  Resale products are also offered on the Internet
(see <a href="#internet">Using the Internet in this chapter</a>).


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 10.3</h4>

<p>     Students can contrast store atmospherics of two retailers
for same product category by conducting careful on-site
observations.  If they compare a national retailer, the
probability is high that they will also be able to find that
retailer on the Internet.  This activity could be extended to
having students compare store and on-line atmospherics for the
same retailer.  However, this is best accomplished using a
graphical browser such as Mosaic or NetScape, since a text-only
browser will not provide the visual images needed to make the
comparisons.  At the least, students can address the issue of how
retailers can establish atmospherics over the Internet and help
consumers form a positive store image.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 10.4 </h4>

<p>     In addition to polling the class for their retail
experience, your local American Marketing Association or other
professional group may be able to provide a guest speaker who can
address a retail topic.  Popular themes are employment
opportunities in retailing, trends in retailing, retail services,
and the future of retailing.  

<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 10.1</h4>

<p>     Time is a major factor for most consumers, which helps
explain why malls are losing shoppers.  It takes more time to
shop in a mall than in a free-standing retailer in a strip mall,
by catalog, or increasingly, on the Internet.  Malls suffer from
congested parking lots and consumer concerns about safety. 
Consumers often believe that prices are higher in malls because
retailers have to pay a steeper rent for their stores.  What
complaints do your students have about mall shopping?  Do they
visit malls for purposes other than shopping?  Can they forecast
changes in malls so that they become destinations in themselves,
as social and entertainment centers?


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 10.2</h4>

<p>     Avon is a master retailer that uses a direct sales force to
establish a long term relationship with consumers.  Have any of
your students had experience with Avon, as a purchaser or an Avon
lady?  If so, ask them to share their observations about how this
giant retailer has used relationship marketing to its advantage. 
Do they believe that the use of catalogs and advertising will
dilute Avon's impact on consumers?  Will it affect the
salesforce?       


<h4>NTERNATIONAL MARKETING REPORT</h4>

<p>     American retailers are going abroad, and some foreign
retailers are highly successful in the United States.  Students
can investigate the progress being made by U.S. retailers.  Many
articles have appeared recently about U.S. retailers entering the
Mexican market, as well as markets in Europe and Japan.  If you
have international students in class, ask them to share their
observations of American retailers in the United States and in
their countries.  </p>

<p>

<hr>
