<title>CHAPTER 13: THE PROMOTION MIX: ADVERTISING, SALES PROMOTIONS, PERSONAL SELLING, PUBLIC RELATIONS, AND DIRECT MARKETING CHAPTER ABSTRACT</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">
<h1><center>CHAPTER 13</h1>
<h1>THE PROMOTION MIX: ADVERTISING, SALES PROMOTIONS, PERSONAL SELLING, PUBLIC RELATIONS, AND DIRECT MARKETING CHAPTER ABSTRACT</h1>
</center>

<p><b>1. Describe the role of advertising in product promotion. </b>
Advertising is nonpersonal persuasive marketing communication,
mostly conveyed in the mass media and paid for by an identified
sponsor who controls the message.  Advertising informs,
persuades, reminds, and entertains.  It is used to build brand
image, establish goodwill, and convey public service
announcements.  Advertising is often classified by coverage
(local, national, international, global), task (commercial,
noncommercial, corporate, public service), media type (indirect
response, direct response), and consumer target (personal use,
business, organization).  Many new forms of advertising are
challenging the dominance of traditional mass advertising.  An
advantage of mass advertising is its relatively low cost in
reaching large numbers of consumers.  Advertising provides
information and image signals that help consumers position
competitive products.  Annual advertising spending worldwide is
almost $500 billion.  Advertising has been around since ancient
times.  The invention of the printing press (mid-1400s) and
advances in technology during the Industrial Revolution
contributed to the growth of advertising.  Advertising has become 
more sophisticated and widely used throughout the world in the
latter part of the 20th century.  The three parts of the
advertising triad are the advertiser (pays for it), the
advertising agency (makes it), and the media (delivers it). 
Advertising decisions involve budgeting, developing a creative
strategy, developing the media strategy, producing the
advertising, implementing and evaluating the results.


<p><b>2. Explain how sales promotions are used.  </b>A sales promotion adds
value through short-term inducements to take action, such as
purchase a product, move it through a channel of distribution,
build store traffic, and increase sales.  Sales promotions may be
directed at personal use consumers, business/organization
consumers, or both.  More is spent on sales promotions than on
advertising, almost half of a typical business's promotion
budget.  Sales promotions can rapidly generate revenue by
providing incentives that increase store traffic and sales.  Some
critics contend that sales promotions undermine brand loyalty by
making consumers more price sensitive.  Not-for-profit
organizations and governments also use sales promotions. 
Effective sales promotion requires planning, a clear statement of
objectives, careful choice of appropriate sales promotion
alternatives, and good timing.  Cents-off coupons are popular
personal use consumer sales promotions.  Others include contests,
free samples, rebates, discounts, and premium incentives.  


<p><b>3. Explain the promotion advantages of personal selling.  </b>Unlike
other forms of promotion, personal selling establishes a personal
link with consumers.  Before the development of modern
electronics and telecommunications, selling was principally a
face-to-face activity, often conducted door-to-door.  Today,
personal selling is performed face-to-face, on the telephone, and
by facsimile machine, computer, and the Internet.  The
salesperson is a boundary spanner, bridging the gap between
company and consumer.  Salespeople can establish an immediate and
personal contact with consumers, counter objections, overcome
sales resistance, and develop long term relationships that can
lead to many cross selling opportunities.  A drawback to personal
selling is its expense.  It is not used to reach a mass market. 
Over 20 million people are employed in some facet of sales in the
United States.  Advances in telecommunications allows a growing
number of industrial salespeople to work at home, linked to their
offices by computer, facsimile machine, and cellular telephone. 
The sales force is an important strategic tool because it
establishes a critical selling link with consumers and has
accessibility to important information about the environment that
can be transmitted back to the business.  There are many
different types of salespeople and selling tasks.  Sales force
management involves recruiting, selecting, hiring, training,
motivating, evaluating, and sometimes firing salespeople.  Every
sales force, even if it is only one person, must be managed. 
Sales force compensation is often a difficult management task
because it involves sensitive matters that affect people deeply. 
Because it is costly to replace salespeople, the business should
be motivated to sustain a consistent effort to field a well
trained, supported, motivated, and compensated sales force.


<p><b>4. Characterize public relations/publicity activities.  </b>Public
relations is the promotion type that establishes a communication
link between a business/organization and various publics. 
Publics are groups of people who have some interest or
involvement in what the business does.  Public relations works to
build and maintain goodwill and a positive image.  Sometimes
public relations opportunities develop unexpectedly; other times
they must be planned and carefully implemented.  While many
marketers believe that public relations and publicity are
interchangeable terms, others believe that there is a significant
difference between them.  One difference is that public relations
activities are paid for, often by an identified sponsor, whereas
publicity is not.  There are many different targets for public
relations activities including employees, stockholders, potential
investors, government, distributors, and consumers.  This type of
marketing is under intense scrutiny for what some members of the
public perceive as visible and overly aggressive attempts to put
a positive spin on sometimes negative events.  Publicity appears
in the mass media encoded by an intermediary sender such as an
editor, reporter, commentator, or other third party.  Therefore,
the original event or information about it risks being distorted. 



<p><b>5. Identify the advantages of direct marketing.  </b>Direct marketing
is the promotion mix element that makes extensive use of computer
databases and lists to direct mail and telephone offers to
consumer targets.  It gives immediate response measurement
capacity to the mass media through direct print and electronic
advertising, can personalize messages and offers, refine
targeting, and reduce the waste of contacting nonreceptive
audiences.  It is measurable, which gives it a distinct advantage
over traditional mass advertising.  The tools of direct marketing
are catalogs, letters, telemarketing, brochures, direct
advertising, direct mail, and other forms.  It is criticized for
contributing to the promotion clutter, but it also suffers
because of it.  It is often criticized for invading consumers'
privacy through the compilation and distribution of lists that
contain intimate details of consumers' financial situation,
personal lives, and purchasing habits.  The computer database is
the backbone of the direct marketing industry.  A list is a prime
set of names and addresses identified by specific characteristics
in a database, set into order, and compiled in a mail or
telephone contact list.  The best list is the in-house list,
compiled from the names of current or past customers.  Other
lists can be compiled by the business or are available from
commercial list brokers.  Direct mail is growing in popularity
among consumers.  Catalogs are very popular for both personal use
and business/organization consumers.  Telemarketing is often
called the most irritating form of direct marketing.

<h2><a name="teaching tips">SOME TEACHING TIPS</a></h2>

<p>     The chapter question asks, "Do most consumers think
marketing and promotion are synonymous?"  This question has been
asked in different forms throughout the text because it reflects
a serious problem with consumer perceptions about marketing. 
While people familiar with marketing recognize the breadth and
importance of marketing activities, to consumers and even some
businesses and organizations, marketing is just advertising or
selling.  Granted, these are two of the most visible marketing
activities, but they certainly are not the only ones. 

<p><b>Developing An Integrated Marketing Communications Strategy</b>

<p>     The chapter opens with a lengthy description of the
promotion decisions facing Alicia Hernandez.  Small student teams
can consider the promotion alternatives and decide on several
choices.  What does Alicia want promotion to do for her business? 
What is the best mix of promotion types that will serve Alicia's
objectives?  What is an optimal integrated marketing
communications strategy for Alicia?  What makes it an integrated
marketing communications strategy?    Why should Alicia keep an
eye on the competition as she launches her promotion campaign? 
What other environmental factors should Alicia also monitor?

<p>     What is a promotion campaign and how does it differ from an
integrated marketing communications campaign?  In this case,
Alicia will be using a variety of different promotions focused on
the same theme over a period of time.  Since her stores are not
open year round, when should she begin and end her promotions? 
Should she maintain contact with customers during the period when
her stores are closed?  If so, which customers?  If she decides
that it is important to maintain awareness of her stores even
during the months when they are closed, how can she do it?  How
could she make this "reminder" activity an integral part of her
promotion campaign?

<p>     Is Alicia practicing relationship marketing?  Does the
nature of her business encourage the formation of relationships
with consumers?  If so, what can Alicia do to ensure that her
sales force actively contributes to the establishment of
relationships?  Can she use relationship marketing to communicate
with consumers about the value that she adds to their shopping
experience?

<p><b>Using Print Advertisements To Illustrate Advertising Types</b>

<p>     Rather than ask students to collect examples of different
advertising types, collect your own samples and bring them to
class for students to analyze.  If you do this over several
terms, you can assemble a collection of print advertisements that
clearly represent the points you wish to emphasize. I have built
such a collection over several years and find it very useful in
illustrating key points about advertising.  Because the print
advertisements are distributed in class, I mount them on poster
board and protect them with clear plastic that can be purchased
in an art supply store or most discount retailers (Wal-Mart,
Kmart, Target).  Most sell clear Contac paper by the yard.  

<p>     In addition to illustrating local (retail), national
(brand), international, corporate (institutional), public
service, and other advertising types, point out examples of
primary demand and selective demand advertising.  For example, a
print advertisement for milk sponsored by the National Dairy
Council is an example of a primary demand advertisement designed
to promote the generic product, milk, not identify a brand. 
Contrast this with a print advertisement for Sealtest milk, a
manufacturer's brand.  Other examples include primary demand for
Columbian coffee and selective demand for Folger's; primary
demand for beef and selective demand for Laura's Lean Beef.

<p>     Your collection of print advertisements should also include
examples of advertising directed toward other businesses, as well
as professionals.  Industrial advertising for raw materials,
supplies, and component parts can be found in specialty business
publications for the various trades as well as in general
business publications, for example Business Week, Inc., Forbes,
and The Wall Street Journal.  Professional advertisements
directed to doctors, lawyers, accountants, and others can be
found in trade publications.  Agricultural products are
advertised in publications directed at growers and
agribusinesspeople.  It is important to show advertisements for
these target audiences because students are less apt to be
familiar with them.

<p>     In examining your print advertisements, ask students to
consider advertisement target audiences and their
characteristics.  The matching of media characteristics with
message strategy can be illustrated by contrasting print
advertisements for the same brand in publications with obviously
different readerships.  For example, select an advertisement from
Modern Maturity, then locate a print advertisement for the
identical brand in a magazine targeted at a broader aged
audience.  It is likely that differences will show up between the
advertisements in the ages of the models used, the background
setting, and the message.  What does this indicate about the
magazines' readership?  How do the advertisements reflect
readership differences?  

<p>     How has the changing role of women been reflected in
advertising?  Students can perform a content analysis of current
print advertisements to determine the breadth of roles portrayed. 
Some print advertisements also show how men have assumed greater
roles in child rearing and household management.  Is advertising
reflecting changes in society or does advertising promote
changes?  This debate of the role of advertising as a mirror or
as a leader raises serious questions about marketing as change
agent.  If advertising is a mirror, what is it reflecting?  Bring
some high fashion advertisements to class in order to illustrate
this point.  It should be very easy to find print advertisement
examples of emaciated female models, a young woman being menaced
by a man, and groups of mean looking teens.  

<p>     In analyzing international advertisements, contrast the
standardized versus customized approaches.  Standardized
advertising strategy requires using a global approach, where
there is virtually no difference in message regardless of the
country in which the advertisement appears.  This assumes great
consumer comparability and disregards consumer differences.  On
the other hand, the customized approach requires adapting
advertisements to local markets.  While some brands may strive
for standardization, some adaptation will still be required, if
only in language.  How can an international advertiser reduce the
necessity of having to translate advertisements into the
different languages for each country market served?  Why would it
be easier to standardize the advertising internationally for a
carbonated cola drink than for a nutritious tomato-based beverage
containing 6 essential minerals and 5 vitamins, that is low
sodium, non-fat, and high in dietary fiber?

<p>     If you have international students in your class, or
domestic students who have traveled internationally, ask them to
share their observations about advertising internationally.  Have
they noticed differences between domestic advertising for U.S.
brands and the advertising internationally for the same brands? 
Have they seen popular advertisements, particularly U.S.
television commercials, reshot with local celebrities in other
countries?  This is a very popular way to extend the life of a
successful commercial.  For example, a number of years ago, Coca-Cola aired a television commercial starring a professional
football player, "Mean" Joe Green.  The commercial begins by
showing Mean Joe limping off the field into the tunnel under the
stands that leads to the team dressing room.  A little boy
follows him and shouts his name.  Mean Joe turns around and in a
dramatic gesture of friendship and sympathy for his injury, the
little boy gives the football player his Coke.  Mean Joe thanks
him by giving the boy his team jersey.  The smile on the child's
face could light up the sky!  The identical commercial was reshot
in several countries in Latin and South America, using national
sports celebrities in place of the U.S. football player.  They
were very popular advertisements, as much for the universality of
the themes of friendship and sharing, as for the interplay
between a tough professional athlete and a little fan.

<p>     Print advertisements can also be used to illustrate an
undifferentiated marketing strategy.  Undifferentiated marketing
ignores differences in markets and among consumers on the
assumption that one product can be offered to the mass market and
enough consumers will accept the undifferentiated product offer
for it to be profitable.  In most cases the costs of
differentiating the product outweigh the probable benefits.  For
example, Henry Ford believed that the only product he had to
offer consumers was a reasonably priced black Ford automobile. 
His competitors quickly proved him wrong.  While some
undifferentiated products are profitable, the trend is toward
greater differentiation as exemplified in the mass customization
approach.  Even Coca-Cola, which at one time had no product
alternatives, now comes in diet, cherry, decaffeinated, and other
product variations.  Contrast differentiated and undifferentiated
marketing strategies through examples in print advertisements. 
Have students suggest product examples that are undifferentiated
and enlist their help in finding print advertisements to
illustrate this strategy.  

<p><b>Segmentation, Targeting, And Positioning Through Promotion   </b>

<p>     Remind students of the importance of segmentation,
targeting, and positioning to marketing.  If necessary, review
what they are and how they work together in marketing products. 
Print advertisements can be used to illustrate these activities. 
Marketing segmentation is dividing up the market into definable
groups.  Print advertisements can be differentiated most easily
by such demographic segments as age, sex, family life cycle
stage, and race.  Examples can be brought to class of such
segmentation bases.  The targeting requires selecting markets to
receive advertising messages.  Contrast the targeting strategies
of such women's magazines as Family Circle and Cosmopolitan, or
such men's magazines as GQ and Playboy.  Positioning is using
advertising and other marketing activities to help consumers
establish a mental image of a product or brand in their minds.
What is the image of identical products advertised in these
magazines?  How is advertising helping readers of these magazines
establish a product position?

<p><b>Television Commercial Appeals</b>
     
<p>     Television commercials promote products in many different
ways.  Some of the alternatives commonly used in delivering a
message are 

<ul>
<li>presenting the facts, using a rational approach to provide
     product information, also called a straight sell

<li>showing a slice of life, a mini-drama about the product as
     it is part of contemporary life

     dramatizing a situation where the product may emerge as a
     hero

<li>offering a testimonial, often a real person telling how the
     product benefitted him or her

<li>showing humor, a funny situation or play on words involving
     the product

<li>demonstrating the product, showing how it works and solves
     consumer problems

<li>using animated characters, puppets, clay figures or computer
     generated characters to draw attention to the product

<li>comparing products, a comparative advertisement that often
     names competitive brands

<li>developing a fantasy including the product 

<li>using a combination of methods
</ul>

<p>     Ask students to note these types, then bring in examples of
one or more television commercials that represent them.  For
example, Energizer Bunny commercials use an animated character
and humor; various automobile commercials use a slice-of-life
approach to show how the product is used for vacations, to take
children to school, or for romantic rides in the moonlight; long
distance telephone companies are good examples of often cutting
comparative advertisements that don't pull any punches in naming
the competition.  Have students critique the commercials and
evaluate their effectiveness in promoting the products to
consumers.


<p><b>Media Measures</b>

<p>     The media are the delivery systems for advertisements, the
channels of distribution.  This is a general categorization and
includes such broad media types as broadcast media (television
and radio) and print media (newspapers and magazines).  A
specific media vehicle is a branded carrier, for example CBS
television, The Wall Street Journal newspaper, and People
magazine.

<p>     When an advertiser purchases time (for the broadcast media) 
or space (for the print media) it is important to know in advance
something about target audience characteristics and audience
numbers.  This type of information allows the advertiser and
media buyer to make comparisons between media vehicles and of the
same vehicle over time to determine trends and the relative
quality of different media purchases.  Some frequently used media
measures include

<ul>
<li>reach - unduplicated hits, the number of different members
     of a target audience exposed at least once to an
     advertisement transmitted in a specific media vehicle (or
     program) in a prespecified period of time

<li>frequency - duplicated hits, the total number of times a
     target audience member is exposed to an advertisement
     transmitted in a specific media vehicle (or program) in a
     prespecified period of time

<li>coverage - the number of target audience members that
     actually receive an advertising message transmitted in a
     specific media vehicle (or program) in a prespecified period
     of time

<li>gross rating points (GRPs) - a measure of the potential
     impact or weight of a particular media schedule, calculated
     by taking reach times frequency

<li>rating - a measure of television viewership, the percent of
     households in a location who could be viewing and are; one
     ratings point is one percent of the households in a location
     viewing a specific program.  On a national basis, each
     ratings point means that 917,000 households are viewing a
     program, so if a program pulls a rating of 10 points, it has
     9.17 million households viewing.  A top rated television
     program may pull ratings in the 20s. A 20 rating means 18.3
     million households viewing.

<li>cost per thousand (CPM) - a measure of the relative costs of
     different media alternatives, primarily print media, for
     their coverage at a cost per thousand reader contacts

<li>cost per ratings point (CPRP) - a measure like CPM that is
     used to compare costs for broadcast media, calculated at the
     cost per rating point
</ul>

<p><b>Ethical Problems In Advertising   </b>

<p>     As indicated in this chapter and the last, advertising is
often severely criticized for ethical shortcomings.  Ethical
problems relate to situations where advertising is believed to
violate the moral standards, values, and principles that society
accepts as limits for acceptable actions and decisions of
individuals and groups.  Ethical problems often differ from legal
problems, which are clear violations of laws and regulations. 
Many ethical dilemmas are not covered by a law or regulation, and
many situations involving advertising are unclear.  

     Some ethical problems in advertising relate to
<ul>
<li>controversial and harmful products

<li>sexually offensive and violent situations

<li>deceptive and misleading claims

<li>advertising to children

<li>fear appeals

<li>stereotyping
</ul>

<p>     Criticisms of advertising often focus on specific
advertisements and products.  Ask your students to identify
examples based on their own observations.  Their observations may
be supported by examples found in print advertisements or
descriptions of television commercials.  Their efforts to
identify and analyze ethical problems in advertising can form the
basis for a class discussion on the topic.     

<p><b>Public Service Announcements: Pro Bono Advertising</b>

<p>     Ask students to find examples of public service advertising
(PSAs) in print and bring them to class.  PSAs often are clearly
marked either as a public service announcement or as a product of
the Ad Council.  What public services are promoted in these
advertisements?  This is donated advertisements, by advertising
agencies and the media.  How does the quality of work in the PSAs
compare to other advertisements?  Are PSAs effective?

<p><b>Infomercials</b>

<p>     If your school has a video library, check to see whether
they have examples of infomercials.  If not, an infomercial often
can be obtained directly from the advertiser.  Show an
infomercial in class and have students evaluate the contents. 
Could consumers be deceived into thinking this is a television
entertainment program?  How effective is it in promoting the
product?  What format is used?  If there is an audience, ask
students whether or not they think audience members are real
people or actors.  Should infomercials be labeled as
advertisements on the screen?  Would this protect consumers?

<p><b>Invited Speakers</b>

<p>     A guest speaker from an advertising agency, a local media
representative, or a direct marketer can add considerable insight
to your students' understanding of promotion processes.  Contacts
can be made through professional organizations, the local chamber
of commerce, or the local telephone directory.

<h2><a name="outline">CHAPTER OUTLINE</a></h2>

I.   Describe the role of advertising in product promotion
<ol>
<li>Advertising is nonpersonal persuasive marketing
          communication, mostly in the mass media and paid for by
          an identified sponsor who controls the message
<li>There are many different types and classifications  of
          advertising
<ul>
<li>Classification by coverage refers to whether the
               advertising is local (retail), national (brand),
               international, and global markets
<li>Classification by task relates to whether
               advertising serves commercial, noncommercial,
               corporate (institutional), or public service
               purposes
<li>Classification by media type refers to whether
               advertising is indirect or direct response 
<li>Classification by consumer target identifies the
               target audience(s) for advertising, including
               personal use consumers, business and organization
               consumers
</ul>
<li>Although the traditional indirect response mass media
          has been dominant historically, direct response
          advertising is gaining ground 
<li>Almost $500 billion is spent yearly on advertising
          worldwide  
<li>Advertising has been around since ancient times
<ul>
<li>The invention of the printing press in the mid-1400s contributed to the spread of literacy, and
               the need for and use of written advertisements
<li>The Industrial Revolution produced many technology
               advances that contributed to the growth of
               advertising and new advertising forms and media
<li>Advertising has become increasingly more
               sophisticated since World War II, distributed
               through new media and using innovative techniques
</ul>
<li>The advertising triad is composed of the advertiser
          (pays for it), the advertising agency (makes it), and
          the media (distributes it)
<ul>
<li>Full-service advertising agencies provide broad
               services to their clients, including advertising
               planning, execution, placement, and evaluation of
               results
<li>Advertisers are businesses, organizations, or
               other sponsors who pay for the advertisement,
               control its contents, and are identified as
               sponsors
<li>The media are the delivery systems that distribute
               advertisements to an audience and include such
               media types as print (newspapers, magazines),
               electronic (radio, television), and outdoor
               (billboards, transit)
</ul>
<li>Advertising decisions are based on the goals
          advertising must accomplish, what the competition is
          doing, the product, company resources, and other
          environmental factors
<ul>
<li>An advertising budget must be set with specific
               amounts allocated to producing advertisements,
               buying media time and space, conducting research
               to evaluate consumer responses, and paying agency
               costs
<li>The creative strategy identifies the creative
               elements that will be used in an advertisement
<li>The media strategy identifies the media that will
               be used
</ul>
</ol>

II.  Explain how sales promotions are used
<ol>
<li>Sales promotions are a type of marketing promotion that
          add value through short-term inducements to take
          action, make a product purchase, move products through
          distribution channels, and ultimately increase sales
<ul>
<li>Sales promotions are popular because they can
               quickly get measurable results
<li>Sales promotions are also used by not-for-profit
               organizations and governments
</ul>
<li>Effective sales promotion requires planning and making
          sales promotion decisions
<ul>
<li>Set objectives
<li>Decide what sales promotions to use
<li>Time the promotion, set a beginning and end date
<li>Evaluate the results, make corrections as needed
</ul>
<li>Sales promotions can be targeted to personal use
          consumers, other businesses (including members of the
          channel of distribution), organizations, government
<ul>
<li>Cents-off coupons are perhaps the most familiar
               sales promotion to personal use consumers
<li>Discounts, trade deals, contests, sales meetings,
               and events are often used for
               business/organization consumers
<li>Channel members often receive incentives designed
               to get them to move more products, faster through
               the channel
<li>The sales force receives promotions designed to
               reward and motivate them to perform more
               effectively
</ul>
</ol>

III. Explain the promotion advantages of personal selling
<ol>
<li>Unlike the other forms of promotion, personal selling
          establishes a personal link with consumers in a direct,
          personal, often face-to-face interchange
<ul>
<li>The salesperson is a boundary spanner, bridging
               the gap between company and consumer
<li>Salesperson and customer comprise a selling dyad
</ul>
<li>Perhaps the greatest advantage of personal selling is 
          immediacy and personal contact with the buyer, which
          allows the seller to counter objections, negotiate
          terms, solve problems, and establish a long-term
          relationship
<ul>
<li>Personal selling is very costly, particularly in
               business/organization personal selling
<li>It is highly cost ineffective for reaching mass
               audiences
<li>Personal selling contributes significantly to the
               economy, employing over 20 million people in the
               United States
</ul>
<li>New technologies are being used to make personal
          selling more effective and efficient
<ul>
<li>Telemarketing allows salespeople to broaden their
               contacts by eliminating the need for face-to-face
               contact
<li>The personal computer, facsimile machine, and
               cellular telephone make it easier for a personal
               sales force to work out of their homes rather than
               from a central headquarters office
</ul>
<li>The sales force is a strategic tool, adding value to 
          products and consumer exchange
<li>There are many different types of sales people and
          sales tasks
<li>Effective sales force management is important because
          salespeople are critical to marketing success
<ul>
<li>Every sales force, whatever its size, must be
               managed
<li>Decisions in sales force management include
               identifying the purpose of the sales force,
               setting objectives, recruiting, selecting,
               training, compensating, motivating, evaluating, 
               and dealing with turnover
<li>One of the most difficult management tasks is
               sales force compensation because it deals with
               very sensitive, often highly emotional issues 
<li>Sales force motivation is an important concern
               because it directly affects sales and is often
               difficult to do right
<li>Sales force evaluation determines how well the
               sales force is doing its job
<li>Sales force turnover must be managed in order to
               retain good salespeople and reduce turnover costs
</ul>
</ol>

IV.  Characterize public relations/publicity activities
<ol>
<li>Public relations is the promotion type that establishes
          a communication link between a business/organization
          and various groups of people who have some interest or
          involvement in what the business does
<ul>
<li>There are many ways that public relations attempts
               to establish goodwill, through press conferences,
               the distribution of printed and electronic
               materials, lobbying, organizing events or
               sponsorships, and advising businesses and
               organizations on how to handle emergencies
<li>Confusion exists about the relationship between
               public relations and publicity, but although they
               have the same goals, public relations is paid for
               by a sponsor while publicity is not
</ul>
<li>Frequent targets of public relations include employees,
          stockholders, potential investors, government, and
          consumers
<li>Public relations/publicity is criticized for
          aggressively and visibly trying to present everything
          in a positive light, even when it is not
<li>Because a third party often conveys information in the
          publicity process, it is vulnerable to
          misinterpretation and misunderstanding
<li>Decisions in the public relations/publicity process
          must be made using complete knowledge of the business
          or organization involved, its environment, and what the
          promotion is expected to accomplish
</ol>

V.   Identify the advantages of direct marketing
<ol>
<li>Direct marketing is the promotion mix element that
          makes extensive use of computer databases and lists to
          direct mail and telephone offers to consumer targets,
          gives immediate response measurement capacity to the
          mass media through direct print and electronic
          advertising, can personalize messages and offers,
          refine targeting, and reduce the waste of contacting
          nonreceptive audiences
<ul>
<li>It is not easy to define because there are so many
               types and there is a controversy about what is or
               is not direct marketing
<li>It is both a cause and a victim of promotion
               clutter
<li>Because direct marketing relies on developing
               information about consumers that is maintained in
               computer databases, it raises serious consumer
               privacy questions 
</ul>
<li>The computer database of consumer information is the
          backbone of contemporary direct marketing and
          telemarketing
<ul>
<li>High speed computers with vast memory storage
               capacity provide tremendous potential for
               compiling lists based on highly personal consumer
               information
<li>An accurate, timely database can eliminate
               considerable waste in a mailing or telephone list
</ul>
<li>The best list is developed in-house from present or
          past customers
<ul>
<li>Lists are available from commercial list brokers
<li>A valuable list provides a reasonable quantity of
               names, accurate selections, and current
               information
</ul>
<li>Direct mail was the first form of direct marketing
<li>Telemarketing is often called the most irritating form
          of direct marketing, which refers more to out-bound
          telemarketing than to in-bound order taking
<li>Direct marketing decisions are somewhat different than
          other promotion decisions, principally because target
          market selection is a critical early step
</ol>

<h2><a name="questions">SUGGESTED ANSWERS TO CHAPTER QUESTIONS</a></h2>

<h3>DISCUSSION QUESTIONS</h3>

<p>1.  What are the tasks of promotion?  <i>The tasks of promotion are
to inform, persuade, remind, and often, entertain.  It is an
extremely varied part of marketing and a very important one,
because promotion communicates directly with target audiences. </i>

<p>2.  How did railroads, communication inventions, and mail
delivery contribute to the need for national mass advertising? 
<i>Railroads, when they finally reached from coast to coast, meant
that products from the west coast could be transported east, and
vice versa.  A national distribution system promoted the
establishment of national brands that could be marketed anywhere
in the country.  As a result, national mass advertising was
needed to inform consumers about nationally distributed, mass
marketed products.  Communications inventions, such as the
teletype and telephone, contributed to national communications
and the development of national mass media.  Universal mail
delivery meant that catalogs could be delivered anywhere in the
country, which promoted the development of direct marketing.</i>

<p>3.  What is an infomercial?  How does it differ from traditional
television commercials?  <i>An infomercial is an extended direct
response television advertisement that runs as long as a 30- or
60-minute program.  It differs from traditional television
commercials because it is delivered in a program format, is
designed to be entertaining, and runs far longer than the
traditional 15 to 30 second commercial.  Most infomercials are
played primarily at night, early morning, or at times when air
time is cheapest.  Most infomercials have live audiences
participating in the presentation and the audience, along with
the program format, sometimes fools viewers who fail to recognize
that this is an advertisement. </i>

<p>4.  Compare and contrast advertising and sales promotions. 
<i>Indirect mass advertising is primarily designed to build image
over a period of time.  Results are not immediately measurable;
effects may not be experienced for months or even years.  Sales
promotions are short-term incentives that expire in a
predetermined period of time.  They provide incentives for
consumers to act, now.  Their results are measurable almost
immediately.  For example, a long running television commercial
for the Energizer Bunny is designed to build the image of the
Energizer battery as long lasting and unstoppable.  The bunny
campaign has aired for years in order to keep reminding consumers
about Energizer.  A sales promotion for a local appliance
retailer promises 10 percent off every purchase and a free three-day Florida vacation for anyone purchasing a 27 inch television
set in the next week.  At the end of the week, the special offer
will be withdrawn.</i>

<p>5.  What groups may be sales promotion targets?  <i>Sales promotions
can be directed toward personal use consumers, salespeople,
members of the distribution channel, other businesses,
organizations, and governments.</i>

<p>6.  Explain the advantages and disadvantages of using:
<i>
<br>a. advertising.
<br>b. sales promotions.
<br>c. personal selling.
<br>d. public relations/publicity.
<br>e. direct marketing.
</i>
     
<p><b>a. advertising.</b>  <i>The advantages of advertising are that it can
reach a mass audience at a very low cost per contact; it can
successfully build brand image and goodwill; it can be highly
creative and entertaining, capturing consumers' attention; it
provides important information to consumers that they can use in
positioning products; and it is an important sector of the
economy, contributing billions of dollars in revenues and
directly creating hundreds of thousands of jobs in the United
States.  The disadvantages of advertising are that it can be very
expensive to create, produce, and distribute an advertisement; it
can be irritating and offensive, and contributes to promotion
clutter; mass advertising does not provide immediate feedback
with measurable results, therefore it can be a very long time
before results become obvious; and it is wasteful, reaching many
uninterested consumers in order to reach a target audience who
are interested in the message.   </i>

<p><b>b. sales promotions.</b>  <i>The advantages of sales promotions are that
they provide a short term boost for such outcomes as sales,
revenues, store traffic, or inventory flow; they provide
measurable results in a short time; personal use consumers like
them; they contribute to the economy with revenues and jobs; and
they are effective in motivating the salesforce and channel
members.  The disadvantages are that they can undermine brand
loyalty by making consumers price sensitive, sensitized to
incentives so that they will purchase any brand, as long as it is
on sale; sales promotions contribute to promotion clutter; they
are easy for the competition to match; and they can be expensive
to run.</i>

<p><b>c. personal selling.</b>  <i>The advantages of personal selling are that
salespeople establish personal relationships with consumers,
which means that over the period of the relationship, they can
better serve customer needs and cross sell them other products;
salespeople can counter objections, negotiate, and solve
problems; they contribute to the economy; and they can provide
feedback to their company about consumers, competitors, and what
is happening in the environment.  The disadvantages are that it
is very expensive to have a salesforce and maintain them,
particularly in industrial or business selling; a salesforce is
highly ineffective for reaching a mass market; and it is
difficult to manage a salesforce, particularly when it involves
compensation and motivation.</i>

<p><b>d. public relations/publicity.</b>  <i>The advantages of public
relations/publicity are that they can effectively promote without
always being directly sponsored, which often lends credibility to
information that comes from a third party; they are flexible
activities that can be used in emergencies and to take advantage
of unexpected opportunities; they provide jobs; and they can be
used to perform damage control in situations when the promoter
needs assistance.  The disadvantages are that the public is
becoming more critical of public relations professionals who
aggressively try to put events and organizations in a good light
when it is inappropriate; they add to the promotion clutter; and
they manipulate the media.  </i>

<p><b>e. direct marketing.</b>  <i>The advantages of direct marketing are that
by finely targeting its audience, it can eliminate much of the
waste experienced in other promotion types that are less
discriminating; it is more measurable than mass advertising and
results can be obtained rapidly; it is flexible and can be
changed quickly.  The disadvantages are that it adds clutter; is
believed to invade consumers' privacy; can be very irritating to
consumers; can be very expensive, particularly in postage; and
adds to environmental waste. </i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>CHECK YOUR UNDERSTANDING</h3>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 13.1</h4>

<p>1.  Compare and contrast indirect mass advertising and direct
action advertising.  <i>Traditional mass advertising is used for
long term brand image building and as a reminder.  Results may be
delayed months or even years.  Direct action advertising uses a
telephone number, mail card, fax number, or e-mail number to
collect immediate consumer responses.  This is measurable and can
be immediate.</i>

<p>2.  Describe some advertising types.  <i>There are many different
types of advertising, some advertising builds brand image, other
advertising builds goodwill, reminds consumers about a product,
or makes public service announcements.  Advertising is classified
by coverage, task, media type, and consumer target.  There are
many different elements within each classification, for example
in media type, there is indirect response which includes
electronic (radio, television), print (newspapers, magazines),
and outdoor (billboards, transit), and direct response which
includes telephone numbers, mail-in coupons, fax numbers, and e-mail addresses.</i>
 
<p>3.  Discuss some of the advertising decisions that must be made. 
<i>Advertising decisions are about setting goals that advertising
must achieve, setting a budget, developing a creative strategy,
developing a media strategy, producing and implementing
advertising, then evaluating the results.</i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 13.2 </h4>

<p>1.  Who are the targets of sales promotions?  <i>Targets of sales
promotions are personal use consumers, business/organization
consumers, employees, and distributors.</i>

<p>2.  What are some sales promotion types?  <i>Types include sales
contests, cents-off coupons, refunds, premiums, events, samples,
discounts, and premiums.</i>
 
<p>3.  Describe what is meant by sales promotion strategy.  <i>A
strategy for sales promotions must state clearly what objectives
are set for the sales promotions and how they will be met.  </i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 13.3 </h4>

<p>1.  Explain the meaning of the term dyad. <i>A dyad is the
connection between buyer and seller in a marketing exchange.  It
is the salesperson and the consumer interacting in a personal
contact to make a marketing exchange.</h4>

<p>2.  How are new technologies affecting personal selling?  <i>New
technologies such as the personal computer, cellular telephone,
and facsimile machine are giving salespeople greater flexibility
in how they do their work.  In a growing number of cases, it has
freed industrial salespeople from the office and allowed them to
work from their homes and cars.</i>
            
<p>3.  Identify some of the activities associated with sales force
management.  <i>Sales force management includes such activities as
recruiting, selecting, hiring, training, motivating, evaluating,
compensating, and sometimes firing.  It is important to
effectively manage a sales force both because it directly affects
sales and revenues, and because salesperson turnover is very
expensive.</i>

<h4>Check Your Understanding 13.4</h4>

<p>1.  Identify some public relations/publicity tasks.  <i>Public
relations/publicity works to build and maintain goodwill and a
positive image through such activities as news conferences,
distributing printed and electronic materials, lobbying,
organizing events and sponsorships, and advising businesses and
organizations on how to handle emergencies and take advantage of
unexpected promotion opportunities.</i>

<p>2.  Describe some criticisms of public relations/publicity.  <i>Like
the other forms of promotion, public relations/publicity suffers
from promotion clutter and contributes to it.  It is criticized
for contributing to clutter, putting a positive spin on
everything regardless of its merit, and manipulating the media.</i>

<p>3.  Contrast public relations/publicity and advertising.
<i>Advertising uses the mass media to deliver a message from an
identified sponsor.  While public relations also may use the mass
media to deliver a message, often the sponsor is not identified
and in the case of publicity, the sponsor does not control the
message.  Public relations is broader than advertising and
includes activities traditionally associated with sales
promotions, direct marketing, and personal selling.     </i>


<h4>Check Your Understanding 13.5</h4>

<p>1.  Why is it difficult to define direct marketing?    <i>Direct
marketing is such a broad set of activities that it is difficult
to define. This has led to controversy about what it is, even to
the extent that some marketers consider it distribution more than
promotion.</i>
 
<p>2.  How is a database used in direct marketing?  <i>Information
about consumers are collected in a database that is the source of
the contact list used in direct marketing.</i>

<p>3.  How are direct marketing lists generated?  <i>In-house lists are
the most valuable as they are composed of consumers who are
already customers or have been customers in the past.  A
generated list is usually purchased from a list broker.  It is a
list developed by capturing consumer names from many different
sources.  These sources include subscription lists, contributor
lists, mail order buyer lists, inquiry lists, and list generated
by public agencies.  These public lists include automobile
registrations, birth registration, and real estate transfers.</i>


<h3>MINI-CASES</h3>
                                
<h4>Mini-Case 13.1: "Mattress Mack's" Winning Ads</h4>
                 
<p>    Do your local television stations air commercials like those
aired by "Mattress Mack?"  If so, how many students have seen the
advertisements?  Of those who have, what do they think of them? 
Are they effective?  Obviously, Mattress Mack is doing well,
enjoying the success of increased sales due in large measure to
his visibility and ability to cut through the promotions clutter.
What is the risk of irritating or offending too many consumers in
an audience?  Is this a case of bad advertising or using very
shrewd consumer insights to embed a value image in the minds of
price sensitive consumers?

<p>1.  Can irritating advertisements be effective?  Explain your
answer?  <i>Actually, they can be effective, if they don't exceed a
threshold of being too irritating.  Because they irritate, they
may be remembered, which is a goal of advertising.  The
irritation threshold varies for different consumers, so what is
terribly irritating to some consumers is still acceptable to
others.  An advertiser will eventually find out if the
advertisements are too irritating and ineffective when sales drop
and there is no other reason for the decline.  Unfortunately,
this can be weeks or months after the advertisements first air.</i>

<p>2.  Which media seems to have more irritating advertisements than
the others?  What is irritating about these advertisements?  <i>Most
consumers are more irritated by television commercials than other
forms.  There are several reasons for this, including seemingly
endless repetitions, increased volume during commercials, and
messages that irritate and offend.  Television also irritates
because it involves more senses than most media, therefore it is
more vivid and engaging.</i>

<p>3.  Would most consumers sit through an irritating commercial? <i>It
depends on the consumer, the situation, the product, and the
degree of irritation the commercial causes.  Because consumers
differ, some will sit through an irritating commercial while
others may flip channels, leave the room, mute the volume, or
read a book until the program resumes.</i>


<h4>Mini-Case 13.2  Is There A Free Lunch?</h4>

<p>     Most grocery shoppers know when samples will be waiting for
them.  Some plan their trips around sample times because it adds
a little variety to a generally disliked chore.  Other consumers
become upset by the mess that sampling can make, the jammed
aisles around popular sampling locations, and piggy people who
eat more than their share of samples.  Research indicates that
there is a greater probability that a consumer will purchase a
product if they sample it first.  In-store food samples are
particularly effective in getting consumers to try new products
and possibly develop a liking for them based on the experience. 
What do your students think about sampling?  Have they ever
sampled food in a grocery store?  Did they follow up by making a
product purchase?  Is this an effective promotion type only for
grocery products or can it be used for other products?

<p>1.  Describe some reasons why consumers like free samples. 
<i>Sampling adds variety to a shopping chore that some consumers 
dislike.  Many shoppers like to munch on foods as they shop and
appreciate the opportunity to try new products to see if they
will like them.</i>

<p>2.  Is sampling a good idea?  <i>For many products, it is definitely 
an excellent idea because it gets consumers to try out new
products and provides an immediate opportunity for them to make a
purchase.  If cents-off coupons are provided along with the
sample, the incentive to purchase becomes even more powerful.</i>

<p>3.  Do any retailers other than supermarkets give away free
samples?  <i>Department stores display perfume bottles for shoppers
to sample.  Drug stores have cosmetic samples available for
shoppers to try lipstick and powder shades before making a
purchase.  Shoppers can sample music compact disks in music
stores and on the Internet.  Software retailers often let
consumers try out demonstration disks to make sure the product
suits the consumer's needs before they purchase a complete
version.  Candy shops and bakeries provide free samples to
customers. </i>
                                
<h3>WHAT DO YOU THINK?</h3>

<p>     Will consumers accept or reject the promotion innovations of
listening to commercials in order to get a free 25 cent telephone
call, and purchasing a diskette with 216 pieces of Absolut Vodka
art?  Ask your students whether or not they would do so.  What
situations or consumer characteristics would make a consumer more
likely to want to get a free telephone call, and therefore
willing to listen to the commercials in order to get it?  Why
would a consumer purchase a diskette of Absolut Vodka art?  What
type of consumer might do so?

<h2><a name="internet">USING THE INTERNET</a></h2>

<p>     Please verify all Internet addresses and confirm the
feasibility of an Internet assignment <b>before</b> you make it.  No
Internet address or information can be guaranteed past the date
of this <b><i>Manual's</b></i> publication.  Be sure to insist that students
demonstrate professional conduct at all times on the Internet.   

<h3>Internet Assignments</h3>

<p>     The Internet is being used for many of the types of
promotions described in this chapter.  For example

<ul>
<li>advertising  -  many home pages advertise products; many
     advertising agencies have Web home pages where they promote
     their traditional and Internet advertising expertise

<li>sales promotions - coupons are offered on the Internet,
     along with contests, free samples, and sales promotions

<li>personal selling - many sites, particularly those targeting
     business/organization consumers, offer e-mail contacts in
     order to service accounts 

<li>public relations/publicity - in addition to public relations
     agencies offering their services on the Internet, the Net is
     also used for publicity purposes.  For example, on the day
     that IBM Corp. sent a letter to Lotus Development informing
     them that IBM intended to initiate a hostile take-over, IBM
     posted the entire contents of the letter on its Internet
     home page to inform interested visitors about the company's
     actions and ensure that the correct information was
     available.  At the same time, Lotus Development posted on
     their home page a copy of the press release that gave their
     reply to the IBM letter. 

<li>direct marketing - some direct marketing companies are
     offering their services on the Internet, many catalogs are
     on the Internet
</ul>

<p>     Small teams of students can investigate the current status
of promotions on the Internet.  In addition to the search tools
already identified in this Manual, students should also learn to
use the 1994 Navigational Tool of the Year (from the World Wide
Web Hall of Fame), the World Wide Web Worm WWWW, developed at the
University of Colorado by Oliver McBryan.  The WWW Worm allows
the user to type in a keyword or phrase to direct the Worm search
engine to a hypertext link or URL address.  For example, a query
for newspapers and internet and a request for 50 matches returned
URLs for links to Newspapers on the Internet (three different
URLs), Internet newspapers, Campus Newspapers on the Internet
(four different URLs), and List of Newspapers on the Internet.  A
query of coupons returned URLs for links to Coupons to "Clip",
alt.coupons, Coupons, Money Saving Coupons, Airline Discount
Coupons, Frequent Flyer Coupons, and Tickets & Coupons - Printers
& Suppliers.

<i><p><a href="http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html">http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html</a></i>
       
<p>     Many advertising agencies are already on the Internet.  If
you have a graphical browser, visit some of these agencies to
gain insight into their creative philosophies.  Many offer visual
and sound galleries of some of their past and often prize winning
work.  Most provide a mission statement and a description of the
type of work that they do and clients they are serving.  Ask your
students to evaluate several sites graphically and decided
whether or not an advertiser might be able to find a creatively
compatible agency just by carefully screening their Web site. 
Use all of the search engines, plus others that you may have
found, to locate major advertising agencies.  

<i>
<p>     Yahoo
<br><a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>

<p>     WebCrawler
<br><a href="http://webcrawler.com">http://webcrawler.com</a>

<p>     Global Network Navigator - The Whole Internet Catalog
<br><a href="http://www.gnn.com">http://www.gnn.com</a>

<p>     WWWW
<br><a href="http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html">http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html</a>
</i>
      

<p>     Students can locate many different media on the Internet. 
In addition to the major national television networks (ABC, CBS,
NBC), there are magazines, newspapers, and yellow pages on the
Internet.  Some offer entertainment links on their sites, others
are more business oriented.  These sites can be located using the
search engines.

<p>     What media measures are being used on the Internet?  At
least for the time being, hits are being counted on Web sites. 
Each time a visitor arrives at a Web site, a hit is registered. 
This is only a measure of contact, not of the length of stay or
whether any follow-up occurred through e-mail, fax, or telephone.
Ask your students what is right and what is wrong with this
measure.  With each hit, the site can capture a visitor's e-mail
address.  Can this information be used in direct marketing? 
Should it be used or is this an invasion of privacy.

<h3>MARKETING APPLICATIONS</h3>


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 13.1</h4>

<p>     Rather than work independently in this Application, student
teams can divide up the task and each member collect an example
of a different advertising type.  When all of the examples have
been collected, ask the student teams to collaborate and
determine how effectively the advertisements reflect consumer
insight.  Are the advertisements effective enough to cut through
the clutter and get consumers to act?  What characteristics are
shared by the effective advertisements and by the ineffective
advertisements?


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 13.2</h4>

<p>     If time is running short, as the end of the term approaches,
instead of sampling other consumers, have students poll the class
as to their experiences with infomercials.  If a class member has
not seen an infomercial, ask them to do so.  Are infomercials
effective?  Students can research recent articles, particularly
in such publications as Advertising Age and AdWeek to determine
how well infomercials generate sales.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 13.3</h4>

<p>     Student teams can be assigned the task of content analyzing
sources for a coupon check.  The results of their analysis can be
checked in recent business publications to determine the major
coupon categories by expenditure.


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 13.4 </h4>

<p>     In addition to using this Application as a means of
compiling participant observations of personal selling, it can
also be valuable for illustrating the variety of job
opportunities in this field.  


<h4>MARKETING APPLICATION 13.5</h4>

<p>     Small student teams can take either the cold pill or oil
tank rupture as their "product" and use it as the focus of their
public relations/publicity brainstorming.  Each team can report
the results of their work in memo form or as a brief oral
presentation.  Students can debate the merit of the different
approaches.


<h3>CONSUMER INSIGHTS AND INTERNATIONAL MARKETING</h3>


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 13.1</h4>

<p>     There is a high probability your students, particularly if
they are 20 year olds, will not have seen the 1984 television
commercial.  Instead of referring to the 1984 commercial, ask if
they can recall a truly memorable commercial like it?  Can they
even recall a commercial that they saw yesterday?  What
commercials can they recall and why?  Does repetition encourage
recall for all commercials?  Does the irritation factor improve
recall?


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 13.2</h4>

<p>     Telemarketing is a very important part of personal selling,
but it irritates many consumers and is often stressful for
telemarketers.  Contrast the roles of in-bound and out-bound
telemarketers.  Which job is more stressful and why?  Which type
of telemarketing is more irritating to consumers and why?


<h4>CONSUMER INSIGHT 13.3</h4>

<p>     College students are prime targets for direct marketers.  As
students near graduation, they often receive direct mail about
new cars, credit cards, clothing, and travel.  If your students
are approaching graduation, ask them to monitor the types of
direct mail they receive and its volume.  How do these direct
marketers get student names?</p>

<p>

<hr>
