<title>Siegel's Instructor's Manual Part V</title>

</head>

<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">




<h1>PART V:   RESOURCE LIST</h1>

     

<h3><b>Introduction</b></h3>



This is a resource list of professional organizations in a variety of marketing specialities that may be helpful in providing specialized information about marketing, career and job information for your students, and suggestions on how to locate guest speakers in your area.  Some of the organizations have speaker's bureaus; many have local chapters in cities across the country.  Several have video films about their organization and profession that they loan to educational institutions.<p>



     While every effort has been made to provide the most current information, organizations like individuals can and do move.  If you have difficulty locating a forwarding address, try a library search of telephone directories or a directory of professional organizations.  In the next several years, as more professional organizations set up sites on the World Wide Web, you will be able to find them through an Internet search using any of the primary search tools cited in this Manual.  Internet addresses are provided for organizations that could be located on the Net in mid-1995.<p>



<b><h3><a name="guest">Guest Speakers</a></h3></b><p>



     Guest speakers can share interesting and valuable observations and experiences that will add a different perspective to class discussions.  They often are rich sources for information about careers in their professional areas.  The following suggestions are derived from personal experiences with hosting guest speakers.  I hope they help.<p>



<ul>

<li>Don't invite too many guests in one term.  Usually, one or two speakers at key points are sufficient to add variety to the class, but not too many to disrupt the class rhythm.



<li>Examine your marketing strengths and weaknesses, likes and dislikes.  If possible, invite guests to speak in areas you least prefer to teach or where your marketing knowledge needs expansion.  Few if any marketing educators are equally well prepared to teach every aspect of marketing.  Therefore, consider this an opportunity to bring variety to your class and learn from an expert.



<li>Ask your guest in advance whether he or she needs visual aids, computers, or other materials, and a lectern.



<li>Prepare the guest with a description of your class and student demographics.  Identify what you have covered thus far in the term that is relevant to the topic.



<li>Ask your guest for information, preferably written, that can be used for an introduction.  This should include present position, a brief description of job responsibilities, previous employment, professional training, and other relevant professional information.



<li>Send maps and parking stickers in advance, along with any special instructions about getting to campus or the meeting room.



<li>If you cannot meet your guest upon his or her arrival, ensure that someone else will guide the way to your classroom.



<li>Have a glass of water available for your guest at a convenient place near the lectern.



<li>Prepare your class in advance for the visit, provide the  name of the guest speaker, company or organization affiliation, and topic.  Ask students to be prepared to ask questions after the presentation and preselect several students to be ready to lead the way into a question and answer session.  Nothing is worse than asking for questions at the end of the presentation and being met with dead silence.



<li>At our school, we always give guest speakers a small gift from the student book store, usually an engraved school coffee mug, as thanks for taking the time and making the effort to visit with us.  If you plan to do the same, have it ready to present at the end of class, after all questions have been answered.



<li>Thank your guest in writing immediately after the presentation.  Always show courtesy and consideration for professionals who are willing to take time away from their business to talk with students.  Remember, they have to take time to prepare their remarks and sometimes there is a financial cost to their leaving the office.</ul>



<h3><b><a name="career">Career Information</a></b></h3><p>



     Students often enter the job market without a clear idea of the types of jobs available to them.  Many of the resources on this list can provide career information for you to relay to your class.  Sometimes they will send brochures and information sheets, on request.  For a brief description of the activities undertaken by these organizations, see <u>The Encyclopedia of Associations, 29th Edition</u>, or another directory.<p>



