<head>
<title>Siegel IM - Part III - Transparency Masters</title>
</head>
Instructor's Resource Manual to accompany<br>
MARKETING: FOUNDATIONS AND APPLICATIONS<br> 
by Carolyn F. Siegel<br><p>

<h2>PART III --  TRANSPARENCY MASTERS FOR CHAPTER OBJECTIVES</h2>

<b>Introduction</b><p>

     Transparencies can be very helpful, if they are used
effectively.  The transparency masters in this section are keyed
to the chapter objectives that organize each text chapter.  They
are designed to:<p>
<ul>
<li> focus attention on key thoughts developed in each chapter<p>

<li> provide a framework and focus for student learning<p>

<li> provide a framework and focus for class discussion<p>
</ul>
     Transparencies can enliven class discussions, or they can
disrupt them.  They should focus attention on key points and
illustrate concepts.  However, if you use too many
transparencies, students may spend their time copying them and
not listening or contributing to class discussion. 
Transparencies can disrupt the flow of the class if you are
distracted by having to flip through a large pile of them.<p>

     I use chapter objective transparencies at the beginning of
each class.  I get to class a few minutes early and have the
transparency projected on the screen as students enter the room. 
This way they copy the questions before class begins.  The act of
writing the questions focuses students' attention on the day's
topics.  This settles everyone down and sets a businesslike tone
for the class.  When everyone has had a chance to copy the
questions, I turn the projector off.  It may be flipped on at
other times during the class, when a relevant point is
emphasized.  <p>

<b><a name="suggest">Suggestions For Using Transparencies</a>       
</b><p>
     The following suggestions reflect personal experience in
using transparencies and overhead projectors.  Please share them
with your students during the term if they are called on to make
a presentation that requires transparencies. <p>   
<ul>
<li> Get to class early to check the overhead projector. 
     Familiarize yourself with its operation, turn it on, focus
     it, and be sure that the bulb works and the mirror is clean.<p>
<li> Pull down the screen and anchor the end, as needed, to
     ensure that it is operable.  If the screen is broken, find a
     clear wall where the transparency can be projected.  This
     may require changing the direction of the projection.<p>

<li> With the transparency in place and the projector on, walk to
     various sections of the room and sit in the seats that will
     be occupied.  Make sure that the transparency can be read
     from all parts of the room.  If necessary, move the
     projector or adjust the image to improve readability.<p>

<li>Practice using the transparency by pointing to it on the
     projector and not on the screen.  Avoid turning around and
     pointing at the screen as this positions your back to the
     class, you lose eye contact and your voice becomes muffled.<p>

<li> Practice using a pencil or pen to emphasize points on the
     transparency.  Again, point to the transparency on the
     projector and not the screen.<p>

<li>The transparency masters in this section are very large and
     typed using large and small letters.  Transparencies cannot
     be read easily or sometimes at all, if they are made without
     enlargement from pica or elite type fonts.  It is easier for
     an audience to read broken type (large and small letters)
     than to read all capitals or all small letters.<p>   

<li>Never use reverse type!  This is light type on a dark
     background.  It is almost impossible to read anywhere other
     than the front row.<p>

<li> If you want to write on the transparency, use special
     marking pens designed for this purpose.  They come in both
     washable and indelible forms.  A highlighter or felt tip pen
     will not write effectively on a transparency.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<b><a name="trans">TRANSPARENCY MASTERS</a></b>
<ul>
<li><a href=partiii/trans1.html>Chapter 1 - An Introduction to Marketing</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans2.html>Chapter 2 - Making Marketing Decisions - Developing Marketing Plans</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans3.html>Chapter 3 - Segmenting the Market: Consumer Buying Decisions</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans4.html>Chapter 4 - The Marketing Environment</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans5.html>Chapter 5 - Multicultural and International Marketing</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans6.html>Chapter 6 - Marketing Research and Information Technology</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans7.html>Chapter 7 - Understanding Product</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans8.html>Chapter 8 - Product Processes</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans9.html>Chapter 9 - Understanding Price</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans10.html>Chapter 10 - Place: The Role of Retailing</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans11.html>Chapter 11 - Place: Distribution and Wholesaling</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans12.html>Chapter 12 - Understanding Promotion</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans13.html>Chapter 13 - The Promotion Mix: Advertsing, Sales Promotions, Personal Selling, Public Relations, and Direct Marketing</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans14.html>Chapter 14 - Extending Marketing: Marketing Services and Not-For-Profit Marketing</a><br>
<li><a href=partiii/trans15.html>Chapter 15 - Managing Marketing</a><br>
</ul>
