<title>Preface to Siegel's Instructor's Manual on MARKETING</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">

<b>INSTRUCTOR'S RESOURCE MANUAL<br>
to accompany<br>
MARKETING: FOUNDATIONS AND APPLICATIONS</b><br>
by Carolyn F. Siegel of Eastern Kentucky University <p>            

<h2>PREFACE</h2><p>

Marketing is such an interesting, varied subject that some
aspect of it is bound to engage the interest of even the most
skeptical student.  Marketing is exciting to teach because what
students learn in the classroom can be applied almost immediately
to what they experience in their daily lives.  Marketing is
ubiquitous.  It is personal, yet also extremely important to
business and society.  Marketing is also a challenge to teach,
largely because there is so much content to deal with in a short
period, a 10-week quarter or 16 week semester.<p>  

Growing student diversity is another challenge facing the
introductory marketing instructor.  There are more non-traditional students today, adult learners with different needs, problems, and expectations.  Many are returning to school after
absences of years or even decades.  Often they work full-time in
addition to carrying a heavy class schedule.  Some have
significant work experience; others are exploring new career
directions.  The majority have home and family responsibilities,
beyond work and school.  Whatever their individual
characteristics, they often offer striking contrasts to the
traditional student, the twenty year old, who entered higher
education directly from high school and will complete degree
requirements within a relatively uninterrupted period.<p>

     Marketing instructors must also consider a third and equally
compelling challenge, this one from prospective employers. 
Employers expect higher education graduates to have good work
skills, particularly in communication, information retrieval,
decision making, team work, and change management.  Marketing
instructors can meet this challenge by using a variety of
teaching methods, particularly interactive, hands-on learning
methods that provide an opportunity for students to develop
effective work skills.<p>
        
     This <i>Instructor's Resource Manual</i> was written to address
these challenges, and others.  The goals are to make teaching the
introductory marketing course easier and more enjoyable, and make
learning about marketing more personal and meaningful for
students.  Strategies for achieving these goals include:<p>
<ul>
<li><b>Organizing</b> chapter objectives and summary statements by
     numbered sections, then similarly numbering associated
     sections in this <i>Manual</i>, the <i>Student Study Guide</i>, and the
     <i>Test Bank</i>.  Information that is systematically organized and
     presented is more apt to be usable to the teacher and used
     by the student.<p>

<li><b>Streamlining</b> the text so that it is shorter, yet covers all
     key marketing topics.  Many marketing textbooks are bloated. 
     These encyclopedic textbooks frustrate teachers, who can't
     complete all the chapters in a term, and students, who won't
     read them because of their size and copious detail.  A
     textbook purchased but not read is a bad investment,
     pedagogically and financially.<p>  

<li><b> Applying</b> marketing in interesting and uncomplicated
     activities that challenge students to see how marketing is
     an important part of their everyday lives.  Several hands-on
     Marketing Applications appear in each text chapter and
     suggestions for their use appear in this <i>Manual</i>.<p>  

<li><b> Contemporizing</b> marketing by using timely, interesting, and
     relevant examples, mini-cases, consumer insights,
     international marketing sections, and a completely new
     feature,<i> Marketing On The Internet</i>.  The text and this
     <i>Manual</i> are among the first to include information on the
     Internet, along with specific suggestions on how to use the
     Internet in the marketing classroom.  Soon the Internet will
     become even more important to marketers and marketing. 
     Students who have meaningful Internet experience should
     improve their employment potential.<p>
</ul>
This <i>Manual</i> includes teaching suggestions used successfully
in my classes, and in those of colleagues.  It also provides
references to other teaching resources, along with names and
addresses of useful sources for class enrichment materials. 
Please adapt any of the teaching suggestions to suit your own
needs and educational environment; improve on them, and share
your success with others.  I hope this <i>Manual</i> is of assistance to
you as you teach this important course.  Your comments and
suggestions on improving the <i>Manual</i> are very welcome, as are your
comments on the text itself.  Please share them with me at this
address:<p>
<dl>
<dd>Carolyn F. Siegel
<dd>c/o Mirror Press
<dd>53 Langley Road, Suite 230
<dd>Newton Centre, MA  02159
</dl>
</p>
<hr>
<h4><i>We want to hear from you!</i></h4>

