<head>
<title>Siegel IM - Using the Internet in Your Marketing Class</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">
Instructor's Resource Manual to accompany<br>
MARKETING: FOUNDATIONS AND APPLICATIONS<br> 
by Carolyn F. Siegel<br>
Part I    Starting Points<br>

<h2>USING THE INTERNET IN YOUR MARKETING CLASS</h2>
     
     The Internet is a powerful new tool in the interactive
teaching method mix.  As more schools connect to the Internet
(Net-connect), students will use it routinely to explore
marketing on a personal level.  Marketing projects on the
Internet will take on new and exciting dimensions.  Even if your
school is not yet on the Net, take the time to read this section
and learn what is in store for you and your students.<p>

<b>The Internet</b><p>

     The Internet is a system of interconnected computer networks
linked together into one great global computer cooperative.  No
single government, organization, or administrative body directly
controls it.  The technical aspects of the Internet are managed
by the Internet Society (ISOC).  Operating costs are shared by
primary users (Hoffman and Novak 1994) and a growing number of
businesses.<p>

     The idea for a powerful, resilient interconnected computer
network can be traced back to the early 1960s, when the United
States Department of Defense decided that the country needed a
communication system able to provide command and control
capability even during a nuclear attack (Hoffman and Novak 1994). 
In response, the Rand Corporation designed a network based on
system redundancy and packet switching technology that could
deliver messages under the most extreme conditions, even if parts
of the system were off-line.<p>

     Technically, what we know as the Internet began in 1969 as
ARPANET, the Department of Defense's Advanced Research Projects
Agency network.  This technology also linked computers and
research scientists at UCLA and Stanford University (Sanford
1995).  Other shared computer links were formed later between
universities, the military, and defense contractors, with the
first international links made to Western Europe in 1973. 
ARPANET was decommissioned in 1990, the year that commercial
Internet mail service began (Sanford 1995).  The National Science
Foundation (NSF), which was principally funding the backbone of
the Internet, set a new use policy in November 1992 that cleared
the path for commercial access to the Net (Johnson 1993).  In
April 1995 the United States government officially turned the
cost of maintaining the Internet over to businesses and
disconnected the NSF Internet gateway (Stavrinou 1995).<p>  

<b>     Internet Demographics</b><p>

     Currently, the Internet connects 75 countries with full
Internet services and 77 more countries with e-mail service
(Verity and Hof 1994) through at least eleven thousand computer
networks (Sanford 1995).  Estimates of Internet size, growth
rate, and commercial activity change, almost daily.  The Internet
may be growing exponentially, doubling in size every year, adding
an estimated million new users each month, with approximately
27.5 million users as of October 1994 (Quarterman 1994).  Half
the Fortune 1000 companies have an Internet mail address;
commercial sites on the World Wide Web have grown from 9,000 in
1991 to over 22,000 in 1995, with even faster growth predicted
for the last years of the 20th century (Verity and Hof 1994).<p>  

     The annual total value of goods sold on the Internet is
estimated to be over $10 million and growing at 10 percent a
month (Solomon 1994).  Business-to-business Internet sales in
1993 were an estimated $20 to $30 billion through 200 to 300
Internet catalogs (Shermach 1995).  Although completely accurate
Internet sales figures are not available currently, what is
certain is that Internet users, sales, and service are all
increasing dramatically and rapidly.<p>  

     <b>Internet Layers<p></b>

     There are several different layers to the Internet.  The
layer of greatest interest to marketers is the World Wide Web
(WWW), which provides global access to information through
hypertext links.  The Web was opened in 1992 (Sanford 1995). 
Hypertext information links appear on screen as highlighted text
or images activated by mouse click or keyboard enter key. 
Computer servers called browsers seek out information that users
request.  Information is retrieved almost instantaneously from
addressed locations anywhere in the Web-linked world.  This
information appears as text, images, and increasingly, sound. <p> 

<b>How Can You Use The Internet In Your Marketing Class?</b><p>

     The Internet is a new factor for most marketers and
marketing instructors to consider.  Many schools still don't have
Internet access.  In other cases, marketing instructors are using
the Internet primarily for e-mail, but they haven't gotten their
students on the Net.  New and highly creative ways to use the
Internet in marketing classes are being developed by marketing
instructors around the world.  Some ideas for Internet activities
are provided in the teaching suggestions for each chapter in this
Manual.  Initially, your students can use the Internet to:<p>
<ul>
<li>retrieve information from sources that otherwise might be
     inaccessible to them<p>

<li>work together in teams via e-mail which allows for
     cooperation regardless of the time or the physical location
     of the team members<p>

<li>interact with business professionals and businesses that
     they would be unlikely to contact through conventional
     means<p>

<li>conduct cross-cultural marketing interviews with students in
     other countries<p>

<li>observe how marketing is evolving on the Internet<p>

<li>find new and useful information about marketing careers<p>

<li>develop communication and information retrieval skills that
     employers value and increasingly, expect from entry level
     employees<p>

<li>solve marketing problems and make marketing decisions<p>

<li>receive class assignments and submit completed ones<p>
</ul>

     The Internet is an exciting place and just cruising it,
looking for information and places to visit, can significantly
raise student interest levels.  For many students, class projects
on the Internet are a natural extension from their involvement
with video games and interactive television.<p>
<b>
How Can You Benefit From Using The Internet?</b><p>

     The first and most obvious benefit is that students who
actively participate in class projects typically are more
attentive, involved, and easier to teach.  From personal
experience, I can verify that students working on Internet class
projects become animated about the experience.  I launched two
classes on the Internet when it first became available at my
school.  The four Internet projects my classes worked on during
that first semester totally captivated my students.  Even the
non-marketing majors, who resented having to take a marketing
class at all, became attentive and involved participants in class
discussions and activities.  As a result, these classes were
among the easiest and most enjoyable that I have ever taught.<p>

     A second benefit is the time saved through use of the
Internet.  If you link a class through an e-mail distribution
list, it means that you can send a message to the entire class at
once.  If students are conscientious in checking their e-mail,
this communication link can bypass the need to distribute
assignments by written hard copy in class, where some student
absences can be expected.  You can alert students to a change in
class schedule, remind them about a coming quiz, refer them to a
just published article, or answer individual student's questions
without their having to visit your office.<p>

     There are other benefits to Internet use.  For example, the
marketing instructor can communicate with colleagues in distant
locations via e-mail.  You can sign on to marketing bulletin
boards that often provide interesting teaching ideas.  The
Internet opens a way for the marketing instructor to leave the
campus electronically and interact with business professionals
worldwide.<p>  

<b>Is There A Downside To Internet Use?</b><p>

     Yes, and it is important to fully recognize and plan for
some of the problems associated with Internet use.  Marketing
teachers have an obligation to ensure that their students do not
contribute to Net problems.<p>
<ul>
<li>The Internet is a time trap.  Before you realize it, you
     have spent hours in front of a computer screen cruising Net
     sites.  Students must stay focused on their marketing
     objective in using the Net.  It is an incredibly exciting,
     useful tool to help them learn to solve marketing problems
     and make marketing decisions, not a video game.<p>  

<li>The Internet is virtually unregulated, so behavior sometimes
     gets out of control.  Perhaps you have heard of flames,
     personal attacks by e-mail message that can be disturbing to
     receive and clog electronic (e-mail) boxes.  Students should
     not participate on unmoderated bulletin boards, unless they
     are willing to risk a flaming.  It may be wiser to tell
     students to avoid such places entirely.  They can be a
     terrible waste of time, and disturbing.  Provide your
     students with lessons in Net-etiquette, how to behave on the
     Net, so they can stay out of trouble.  From my personal
     experience, by participating only on moderated professional
     marketing bulletin boards, I have met wonderful, helpful
     marketing professionals who willingly provide their help to
     Newbies (New Net Users).  My students' experiences on the
     Internet have been positive, without incident.<p>

<li>There is no privacy or complete security on the Internet, at
     least, not yet.  Therefore, assume that any message can be
     read by someone other than the sender or receiver.  Advise
     students not to make a purchase on the Net using a credit
     card.  Similarly, they should not give out their address or
     telephone number.<p>

<li> Sex, alcohol, tobacco, and gambling on the Net offend some
     people; several politicians are even beginning to demand
     regulatory controls over Internet traffic content to protect
     children and adults.<p>  

<li>Many schools have limited Internet access points and
     sometimes students have difficulty getting to a computer
     connection.  Therefore, to avoid adding to the problem,
     students should be strongly cautioned to use their time on
     the Internet wisely, avoid entertaining but nonproductive
     side trips, and not become "net nuisances."<p> 
</ul> 
<b>
How Can I Get On The Internet?</b><p>
                 
     If your school provides you with Internet access, there will
be knowledgeable faculty and staff who can help you learn how to
Net-connect.  Once you learn the procedures, you can teach your
students.  Connection through an educational institution
typically is free of charge.<p>

     If your school does not provide free Internet access, you
can connect through a paid commercial service, such as Prodigy,
American On Line (AOL), CompuServe, or soon, AT&T and Microsoft. 
Prices for a monthly subscription to these services and hourly
access rates are decreasing.  Shop around for the best value;
compare their rates and hourly charges.  The commercial services
provide subscribers with the information needed to use their
services and get to the Internet.<p>

<b>What Do I Do First?</b><p>

     Before you can assign Internet marketing activities to your
students, you must become Net proficient.  Get on the Internet
and learn how to use it.  Browse your school or public library
for books on the Internet.  The best way of becoming comfortable
on the Internet is to spend some time in cyberspace.  Once you
become Net proficient, it will become much easier to get your
students on the Net and coach them through Internet assignments.<p>  

     Review the Internet activities in each chapter in this
Manual.  Use these activities as presented, or better yet, adapt
them to your class needs.  With a little time and experience,
you'll be developing your own class Internet marketing activities
and enjoying the experience.  See you on the Net!
<p>
<hr>
