<html>
<head>
<title>Siegel IM - Designing Your Syllabus</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">
Instructor's Resource Manual to accompany<br>
MARKETING: FOUNDATIONS AND APPLICATIONS<br> 
by Carolyn F. Siegel<br>
Part I    Starting Points<br>
   
<h2>DESIGNING YOUR SYLLABUS</h2>

Many schools offer multiple sections of the introductory
marketing course during a single term (semester or quarter).  To
standardize the course, the instructors make a joint textbook
decision and use a shared syllabus.  In other schools, the
individual instructor is responsible for selecting a textbook and
designing a syllabus.  Whatever your situation, it is important
to plan ahead and schedule topics, assignments, examinations, and
class activities realistically to adapt to the time constraints
of the term, your teaching schedule, and your students'
schedules.<p>  

A syllabus provides important information about the class
that students will need throughout the term.  It is a plan, a
blueprint for how you intend to conduct the course.  It
emphasizes what you think is important and guides students
through their reading, studying, and learning.  A syllabus is a
statement to students about what they can expect, as well as what
is expected of them.  Be sure that every student has a copy of
the syllabus soon after the beginning of the term.  If changes
are made during the semester, as they often are, make sure that
all your students are informed.<p>

Although there are probably as many different syllabus
formats as there are instructors, some general suggestions follow
for the kind of information most often provided in a syllabus. 
For the instructor writing his or her first syllabus, space is
provided for you to follow this guide, enter information, and in
the process, construct a rough draft of a syllabus.  You may not
wish or need to provide all this information.  Decide for
yourself what will benefit your students, while also following
department and school policies on syllabus preparation.<p><p>


<h3>SUGGESTED SYLLABUS FORMAT</h3>
<dl>
<dt><b>A. General Information About The Course</b><p>
<dd>1. Official course title as it 
      appears in the school catalog.    ________________________ <p> 
<dd>2. Official course number.           ________________________<p>
<dd>3. Official section number.          ________________________<p>
<dd>4. Term date, year (Fall 199X).      ________________________<p>
<dd>5. Meeting days and time.            ________________________<p>
<dd>6. Class location (building, room).  ________________________<p>
<dd>7. Required text/other materials.    ________________________<p>

<dt><b>B. Information About The Instructor</b><p>
<dd>1. Name and title.                   ________________________<p>
<dd>2. Office number (building, room).   ________________________ <p>
<dd>3. Office telephone number.          ________________________<p>
<dd>4. e-mail address (if available).    ________________________<p>
<dd>5. Emergency number (often the
      department office).               ________________________<p>
<dd>6. Office hours (day, time).         ________________________<p>

<dt><b>C. Course Description And Objectives</b><p>
<dd>1. Course description.               ________________________<p>
<dd>2. Course prerequisites.             ________________________<p>
<dd>3. Course objectives, for example:
<ul>
<li>To provide a broad overview of marketing.
<li>To explore how marketing affects business and society in interesting and often unexpected ways.
<li>To learn how marketing works and what marketers do.
<li>To apply marketing principles using domestic and international examples. 
<li>To emphasize ethical marketing behaviors.
<li>To develop student communication, analytical, problem solving, and team work skills.
<li>To explore marketing career opportunities. <p>  
</ul>
<dt><b>D. Grading And Evaluation</b><p>
<dd>1. Grading and evaluation policy statement, for example: Your grade in MKT XXX will be based 
         on your performance on examinations, quizzes, in-class projects, term projects.<p>                             
<dd>2. Description of examination format, for example, combination of objective, short essay, problem solving, and other types of questions.<p>
<dd>3. Number of exams during the term.  ________________________<p>
<dd>4. Final (comprehensive or not)      ________________________<p>
<dd>5. Make-up policy for missed exams.  ________________________<p>
<dd>6. Description of quizzes, make-ups. ________________________<p>
<dd>7. Description of projects.          ________________________<p>
<dd>8. Grade calculations should provide as much detail as possible about how the term grade will be calculated, for example:<p>
<b>Example A</b>:<br>
Total points possible = 1,000 points<br>
Two exams during semester @ 200 each = 400 points<br>
Final exam (not comprehensive) = 200 points<br>
Quizzes = 150 points <br>
Projects = 250 points<br>
Grade:<br>
           A = 90% to 100%<br>
           B = 80% to  89%<br>
           C = 70% to  79%<br>
           D = 60% to  69%<br>
           F = Below 60% <p>

<b>Example B:</b><br>
   Examinations (2 during term and final) = 60%<br>
   Quizzes = 15%<br>
   Projects = 25%<p>
                                      
   9. Attendance policy, for example:<br>
      Attendance is required; roll will be taken.  
      Students are expected to be present and 
      prepared for each class session.  Each 
      unexcused absence will result in the 
      loss of 2 points subtracted from the 
      total number of points possible.<p>  

<dt><b>E. Class Assignments</b><p>

<dd>1. Library assignments, if required.<p>

<dd>2. Computer assignments, if required.<p>

<dd>3. Term schedule, including due dates
      and assignments.  Some instructors use a 
      calendar-type schedule grid, others
      use a list.  Blank calendar formats for 
      both a 16-week semester and 10-week
      quarter are provided for you to enter
      class readings and assignments. 
</dl><p><p>
