<HEAD>
<TITLE>Human Anatomy</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><P>

<center><P>
<a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/techdirect/maps/techdrbr.map"><img border=0 src="/techdirect/gifs/techdrbr.gif" ismap></a><br><img src="/techdirect/gifs/mprule.gif"><br><P>
</center><P>
<a href="gifs/humancv.gif"><img border=2 align=left hspace=15 vspace=10 src="smgifs/s_humancv.gif"></a><P>
<BR><P>

<h2>Human Anatomy CD-ROM</h2><BR>
<h4>Windows/Macintosh CD-ROM #35905</h4><P>
<BR clear=left>
<HR><P>

<a href="gifs/human1.gif"><img border=2 align=right hspace=15 vspace=20 src="smgifs/s_human1.gif"></a><P>

Human Anatomy is an electronic gallery of images used to simulate a laboratory cadaveric dissection.  The CD contains over 6,000 color photos of the human body in various stages of dissection along with hundreds of hand-drawn illustrations and photos from models and skeletons.  The images mirror the perspectives of the laboratory while supporting text leads the user step-by-step through the dissection process.  An  assessment and feedback  mode enables students to review what they have seen and test their comprehension in one of three methods.  There are  flash cards  which randomly present images of a selected region, a  self-evaluation  with random multiple choice questions about a region, chapter , or structure type chosen by the student, and a  graded exam  which chooses 50 images from a selected region.  The computer logs student responses and gives feedback accordingly.<P>
<BR clear=right>

<a href="gifs/human2.gif"><img border=2 align=left hspace=15 vspace=20 src="smgifs/s_human2.gif"></a><P>

Features:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>14,000 references to over 6,000 photos of the human body<BR>
<LI>Enlarge photos to full-screen size<BR>
<LI>3-D orientation icons eliminate ambiguity<BR>
<LI>Textual descriptions of the dissection and correlative cadaveric photos<BR>
<LI>Over 4,700 test questions compiled from authors  606 years of teaching anatomy<BR>
</UL>
<BR clear=left>

<hr><P>
