<head>
<title>Siegel IM - Some Observations on Teaching</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">
Instructor's Resource Manual to accompany<br>
MARKETING: FOUNDATIONS AND APPLICATIONS<br> 
by Carolyn F. Siegel<br>
Part I    Starting Points<br>

<h2>SOME OBSERVATIONS ON TEACHING</h2>

All of us can learn to be better teachers.  We learn from
our colleagues, by participating in professional activities,
through reading, and perhaps what is most important, from our
students.  Some teaching tips I have learned include:<p>
<ul>
<li><b>Know Your Students</b>:  Whether you are teaching marketing for
     the first or fortieth time, analyze the students taking your
     class.  For many if not most, their first marketing class is
     also their last.  Marketing is a required course in most
     business schools for students from all business majors. 
     Students from non-business majors often take marketing as an
     elective.  Be prepared to teach an eclectic group of student
     majors.  Keep this in mind throughout the term, because this
     diversity of majors, and also the mixture of traditional and
     non-traditional students, and students from different races
     and cultures, will show up in differing student expectations
     about the course.  Be sure that you use examples that are
     meaningful to all students.  Bring in relevant current
     articles to stimulate their interest in marketing.  Give
     them an opportunity to share their observations and points
     of view.<p>  

<li><b>Vary Your Teaching Methods</b>:  Although many instructors
     prefer to use the lecture method of teaching, others have
     found greater success with more interactive methods,
     particularly individual and team projects.  A mixture of
     methods brings variety to the classroom.  Your teaching
     methods must be appropriate to class size, student
     characteristics, instructor preferences, and goals for the
     class.  While class size is an important factor in deciding
     teaching methods, it should not be the only factor.  One of
     the most lively class discussions I have observed occurred
     with an incredibly dynamic teacher and a lecture section of
     almost 300 students!  On the other hand, one of the dullest
     class sessions was an instructor reading straight from the
     textbook to a class of twenty students.  Students learn best
     by doing, which is why so many short, uncomplicated
     Marketing Application activities are presented in the text. 
     Assign the ones that are the most meaningful for your
     students and appropriate to your teaching situation.  Don't
     overwhelm your students with too many activities; don't deny
     them meaningful learning opportunities by scheduling too
     few.<p>  

<li><b>Show Enthusiasm</b>: You have a greater chance of getting
     students excited about marketing if you express your
     enthusiasm for the subject.  One suggestion for keeping your
     enthusiasm high is to stay up-to-date in the field.  Read
     current journals and periodicals to find interesting and
     timely marketing stories to bring to class.  Participate in
     professional meetings where you can share your experiences
     and learn from others.  Invite stimulating guest speakers to
     class.  Marketing professionals can enthrall students with
     their anecdotes and provide useful observations about
     marketing careers.  Whatever you do, don't get into a
     teaching rut where you teach the same thing, the same way,
     every term.  Be creative in how you teach.  Challenge
     yourself to try new approaches and seek fresh perspectives.<p> 

<li><b>Be Organized</b>:  Focus on what you want to accomplish in each
     class and for the term.  Come to class prepared!  Plan ahead
     and plan carefully what you will do in each class.  Clearly
     introduce the topic under discussion and remind students 
     what comes next.  Change your syllabus when necessary to
     reflect unexpected opportunities as well as scheduling
     conflicts.  Set aside enough time to grade student work
     promptly and provide students with meaningful feedback so
     they can learn from their mistakes.  Don't procrastinate and
     don't expect students to be organized if you're not.<p>  

<li><b>Get The Most Out Of Your Class</b>:  If you want to have lively
     class discussions and active student participation, then you
     have to establish an open, receptive class environment.  You
     stand a far greater chance of involving students in
     marketing if they feel comfortable expressing themselves in
     class.  Intimidation is not a good teaching method;
     coaching, mentoring, and positive encouragement will
     typically have far better results.  Know your role as an
     instructor and be comfortable with it.  Develop your own
     teaching style and continually improve it.  Hold high
     expectations for yourself and your students; you will both
     rise to the occasion.  Challenge your students to succeed
     and their success will reflect favorably on you.<p>
</ul>  
</p>
<hr>
<h4><i>We want to hear from you!</i></h4>
<h5>If you have any questions about this text, please feel free to contact Carl Helwing, Marketing Manager, by phone at 708/789-5382 or by email at <a href="mailto:chelwing@irwin.com">chelwing@irwin.com</h5></a>
