<title>Siegel's Instructor's Manual Part IV</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">


<h1>PART IV - ADDITIONAL MINI-CASES</h1>

<h3><b>Introduction</b></h3>

 Any mini-case in this section can be duplicated and used in your class
<ul>
<li>to substitute for a mini-case in the textbook<p>
<li>to complement a textbook mini-case<p>
<li>as a quiz or part of an examination<p>
<li>as an in-class, small team activity that can be used in case you are unexpectedly absent from school<p>
</ul>
At the beginning of each term, I write a mini-case that can be used in class in case I can't get to school.  My commute to campus in the winter is sometimes delayed or blocked because of icy road conditions.  Even though the weather may be dreadful, school is rarely cancelled because so many students live on or near campus.  Therefore, having a mini-case on hand for students to work in my absence means I am prepared, even if not physically present.<p>

     Each mini-case in this section has extra questions, which makes them more versatile and appropriate to different topical areas.  Add questions of your own to personalize the case and add immediacy to class discussions.<p> 
<br>

<h3><a name="cases">List of Additional Mini-Cases with Respective Questions and References</a></h3>

<a href="/ced/partiv/partivb.html">Product Licensing Is A Big Risk Business For Marketers</a><p> 

<a href="/ced/partiv/partivc.html">Multilevel Marketing - Vilified Or Just Plain Vile?</a><p>

<a href="/ced/partiv/partivd.html">Internet Appeal, Is It For Everyone?</a><p>

<a href="/ced/partiv/partive.html">Change Or Die - Even Market Leaders Feel The Heat</a><p>

<a href="/ced/partiv/partivf.html">Does The World Need or Want A World Car?</a><p>
