<title>Mini-Case:Product Licensing</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">


<h2>Mini-Case:  Product Licensing Is A Big Risk Business For Marketers </h2>
     
     At the Licensing Show, the product licensing industry's annual convention, the big question in 1995 meant trying to guess what would be the product licensing success of 1996.  Product licensing occurs when the owner of a patented product, such as a movie or a television character, grants another company the right to use it on their products.  An up-front licensing fee and a percent of sales and are paid to the patent owner.  The percent of sales typically ranges from five to 15 percent; licensing up-front fees can range from several thousand to hundreds of thousands of dollars.<p>  

     In case you're thinking that licensing is a silly part of marketing, consider the sales figures.  In 1994, licensed products in the U.S. and Canada accounted for $70 billion in sales, a 5 percent increase over the previous year.  Product licensing can mean millions of dollars in sales for many companies, and billions for the major players.  Walt Disney is the biggest winner in product licensing, with annual sales from licensed retail products of $15 billion.  Other licensed products typically have more transitory life spans, lasting for one or several years, then fading away.  For example, the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles racked up sales of over $5 billion from 1987 through 1994, but by 1995 were no longer the really hot item of past years.  Estimates for other recent product licensing successes are Cabbage Patch, $4 billion, 1983-1994; Star Wars, $2.6+ billion, 1978-1983; and Simpsons, $2.0+ billion, 1989-1994 (Goldman 1995). <p> 
     
     Licensing has its risks.  Licensed products for movies that flop can seriously hurt sales.  Even though the Flintstones movie was aggressively marketed, fans stayed away and retailers were left with large amounts of licensed Flintstones products.  The same fate met "The Pagemaster" and "The Jetsons", whose licensed products were rejected just as children rejected the movies.  There is a risk to the patent holder, who must carefully guard against licensing shoddy or dangerous products that create a negative image or result in damage suits, and counterfeiters, that reduce licensing profits and often leave consumers with inferior merchandise.  Too many product tie-ins and fast food promotions can dilute profits and confuse consumers (Stanley 1995).  Demand can be overestimated and licensed characters can lose their allure, particularly if there is a delay in getting licensed products to market (Fitzgerald 1992).<p>

     Retailers who are considering stocking licensed products must carefully evaluate the products' profit potential.  They must also look at scheduling and how the products fit into seasonal merchandise selection.  Looking ahead, retailers must think about when markdowns will be needed and a product termination decision made (Lettich 1993).<p>

     While most Disney licensed products, and those linked to other recent successes, are targeted to a youth market, some marketers are trying to extend their success to adult markets.  Instead of lunch boxes, action figures, drinking glasses, puppets, sun glasses, and tee-shirts, adult product licensing can be much more costly and sophisticated.  The return of James Bond, with a new agent 007 in the movie "GoldenEye", also introduces a licensed $30,000 BMW roadster for adults who want to drive a Bond car just like the one in the movie (Warner 1995).  Licensing partners for the 007 film include BMW, Citgo gasoline, Perrier, and Yves Saint Laurent, who is introducing a spy line of cosmetics.  Other adult-oriented licensing movie tie-in ventures are for the exciting "Apollo 13" and the romantic "The Bridges of Madison County."<p>
     
     In Atlanta, Georgia, hosts of the 1996 Summer Olympic Games are hoping that licensed products will go a long way toward retiring the expected $1.6 billion that the Games will cost the host city (Goldgaber 1995).  Most retail sales of licensed Olympic products are expected to occur during the 17 days that the games run.  The U.S. Olympics Committee is aggressively stopping any unlicensed vendors trying to bootleg the Olympics to use on their products without authorization.<p>      

    
<b><a name="questionsb">Mini-Case Questions</a></b>
<ul>
<li>What types of products would you recommend for licensing with the romantic movie "The Bridges of Madison County?"  Explain your answers.<p>

<li>What types of products might license well with the exciting, heroic movie "Apollo 13?"<p>

<li>"Most children's licensed products are designed for impulse purchases."  Explain that statement.  Do you agree/disagree?<p>

<li>Compared to the amount of product licensing targeted to youth markets, there has been relatively little targeted to adults.  Why do you think this is so?<p>

<li>Why do product marketers seek licensing agreements from those who hold a patent?<p>

<li>Why do children like licensed products?<p>

<li>Why do movie studios like to license their products?<p>

<li>What makes a character, movie, event, or person marketable for licensing?<p>

<li>Product placement, where a business pays a movie studio to place its products visibly in a movie, is big business.  From the product marketer's standpoint, in the end does it accomplish the same thing (if it works) as product licensing?<p>

<li>Do you think some adults will feel that "cashing-in" on a movie like "Apollo 13" or "The Bridges of Madison County" will turn adult consumers away; that they will reject what they perceive as crass commercialism?<p>

<li>What is the marketer's role in promoting licensed products?  How are licensed products targeted at children promoted?  Take as your example PepsiCo's "Casper" promotions, McDonald's "Batman Forever" promotions, or any of the promotions for Disney's "The Lion King".<p>

<li>Consider the statement, "Children are the most unforgiving and fickle audience for licensed products."  Explain what this means to a marketer planning a promotion for licensed products targeted to children.<p>

<li>Can good promotions for licensed products, and the success of those products, help a movie that has been doing poorly at the box office?<p>

<li>What effect can bootlegged (unlicensed products that have illegally used a licensed character or image) products have on a licensee's profits?  On a retailer's profits? <p> 

<li>Do you think the Atlantic Olympic Committee will clear enough profits to retire the city debt from hosting the Olympics?  Explain why/why not.<p>

<li>Geographically, what locations will probably contribute the greatest profits for Olympic merchandisers?<p>

<li>Can Olympics' licensed products be sold worldwide?  What will affect their sales internationally?<p>

<li>Why do some licensed products fail to produce the volume of sales originally projected?<p>
</ul>

<b><a name="referencesb">References</a>
</b><p>

Fitzgerald, Kate (1992), "High-Stakes Gambling Leaves Licensing         Losers," <i>Advertising Age</i>, Special Report: Licensing (June 1): 29-30.<p>

Goldgaber, Arthur (1995), "Olympic Flame on Low For Now,"<i>Discount Store News</i> (March 6): 18-20.<p>

Goldman, Kevin (1995), "Liked the Film?  You Will Love the Lunch Box," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (June 20): B1, 12.<p>

Lettich, Jill (1993), "Jurassic Park, Classics Dominate Licensing Show," <i>Discount Store News</i> (July 5): 2-4.<p>

Stanley, T.L. (1995), "More Hype to Come,"<i> Brandweek</i> (April 3): 26-31.<p>

Warner, Fara (1995), "Movie Tie-Ins Now Aimed At Adults As Well As Kids," <i>The Wall Street Journal </i>(June 22): B1, 9.
<p>

<hr>
