<html>
<head>
<META  name="date" content="August 1996">
<META  name="user" content="Ronald W Tigges">
<META  name="edition" content="Summer 1996">
<!--
revision date: 8-19-96
revision user: Ronald Tigges
revision items: Page Corrections
-->

<title>Mini-Case: Multilevel Marketing</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">



<h2>Mini-Case:  Multilevel Marketing - Vilified Or Just Plain Vile? </h2>

Have you ever purchased Herbalife, Mary Kay Cosmetics, Tupperware, Amway, or other products from a friend, acquaintance, or business contact?  These products are among the hundreds, if not thousands, sold through a direct distribution strategy known as multilevel marketing.  Some critics think it is a legal, sanitized version of illegal pyramid schemes (Tillson 1994); others think it is a great way to realize their entrepreneurial ambitions and reap rewards far greater than they could realize working in an office (Dunkel 1995).  The Direct Selling Association estimates that there are over three million multilevel salespeople in the United States, an increase of 0.8 million since 1990 (Mehta 1995).  Amway is the largest, with a domestic sales force of about one million.<p>

     A multilevel marketing (MLM) program builds on personal contacts to extend the number of people selling a product.  Friends, family, business contacts, and even strangers are recruited to become distributors.  For each person the seller recruits, he or she gets a percent of the recruits' sales (a sales commission), as well as profits from their own sales.  The more recruits a person signs up, the more the profits.  Some distributors make more money from their commissions than from sales.<p>

     Although many laws prevent fraud and misrepresentation in MLM recruiting, it is difficult for law enforcement authorities to keep up with the growing numbers of MLM operations in the United States and Canada (Tillson 1994).  It is a controversial practice that is the subject of lawsuits and investigations (Mehta 1995).<p>

     Most MLM programs require their distributors to purchase a minimum quantity of products each month, so if a distributor fails to make any sales, their personal product inventory builds.  Some critics say these products are overpriced, which contributes to the general bad reputation of MLMs (Mehta 1995).<p> 

     Late entrants into an MLM operation in a specific geographic area often have difficulty making sales quotas and recruiting new distributors because they face a saturated market.  Therefore, while the MLM program's originators and early entrants at the top of the pyramid may profit enormously, later recruits at the base of the pyramid may gain few profits or even incur losses.<p>   

     Because multilevel marketing offers entrepreneurial opportunities, the number of college-educated women entering these businesses is increasing (Dunkel 1995).  Some MLM direct-sales distributors say that the programs give them an opportunity to be "self-responsible" for their own success (Coulombe 1994).  Others take up an MLM distributorship to gain free time and freedom, meaning control over their work situation.  Some prefer MLM marketing because they have difficulty working for large corporations.  Others enjoy the involvement in a company that offers a sense of belonging and regularly has sales meetings to bolster commitment and enthusiasm.<p>

     Multilevel marketing is expanding rapidly internationally.  In Japan, Nu Skin reports almost 70,000 distributors and Amway reportedly has over one million (Yarnell 1994).  Japan lends itself to MLM operations because of the importance of relationship marketing to the society and the widespread popularity of door-to-door sales.<p>

     What should a person look for if they are considering becoming a direct-market distributor?  Company characteristics are important, particularly if it is driven by income or equity concerns (Yarnell 1994).  The product should be unique and one that consumers will want to purchase.  The distribution should be solely through the MLM network and not competing with in-store sales.  Products that are sold through MLM programs include cosmetics, toiletries, vitamins and other health products, diet aids, pain relief gadgets, jewelry, plastic containers, long-distance telephone service, and satellite television services.<p>


<b><a name="questionsc">Mini-Case Questions</a></b>

<ul>

<li>Is multilevel marketing right for everyone?  Define some of the characteristics that you think a really successful MLM distributor should have in order to profit?<p>

<li>Is MLM legal; is it ethical?  Explain your answers.<p>

<li>What are some of the risks of MLMs?<p>

<li>What attracts some people to MLMs?<p>

<li>Do you think MLMs will succeed in other countries as well as they have in Japan?  Explain your answer.<p>

<li>Why are more people becoming MLM distributors?<p>

<li>Do you think an MLM distributor would be upset to learn that the MLM parent company plans to start offering its products in retail stores and mail catalogs?  Explain your answer.<p>

<li>Are there some products than could be sold in an MLM operation more effectively than others?  Explain your answer.<p>

<li>As more well educated people become MLM distributors, do you think this will change the current downscale image of MLM operations?<p>

<li>Why do MLM distributors at the bottom of the pyramid benefit the least?<p>

<li>Why do distributors at the top of the pyramid benefit most?<p>

</ul>

<b><a name="referencesc">References</a></b><p>

Coulombe, Charles A. (1994), "Star Performers," <i>Success</i> (October): 19-21.<p>

Dunkel, Tom (1995), "The Tupperware Lady is an MBA," <i>Working Woman</i> (April): 44-52.<p>

Mehta, Stephanie N. (1995), "Visions of Wealth and Independence Lead Professionals to Try Multilevel Marketing,"<i> The Wall Street Journal</i> (June 23): B1, 2.<p>

Tillson, Tamsen (1994), "Multilevel Marketing Sells Costly      Dreams," <i>Financial Times of Canada</i> (October 8): B1,4.<p>

Yarnell, Mark B. (1944), "A Venture King's Expert Advice," <i>Success </i>(August): 26-27.<p>

Yarnell, Mark B. (1944), "Worldwide Boom: No Industry is Better Suited For Global Expansion,"   <i>Success </i>(March): 26-27.
<p>

