<title>Mini-case: Internet Appeal</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">


<h2>Mini-Case:  Internet Appeal, Is It For Everyone?</h2>

     Articles about the Internet seem to be appearing everywhere, in business magazines, on television and radio, and in the newspapers. The popular press is enthralled by what's happening in cyberspace.  Lots of people are buzzing around, but what happens when they tire of hopping from one Web site to another?  Does the Internet have "staying" power?  What will it take to get people to visit a Web site two, three, or more times?  More critically, what will it take to get them to make a purchase?<p>  

     Part of the Web's problem is that, as a very new entity, it is still relatively undefined.  It is yet to be determined if the Web is an advertising medium, communication channel, information retrieval system, Cybercatalog, or vast yellow pages directory.  Or, is it all of these and more?<p>  

     If novelty is what it takes to get repeat visitors, then hold tight, 3-D is coming!  Cyberspace visitors with graphical browsers and sound cards already can download pictures, text, sound, and video.  Soon, they'll be able to add 3-D (Meyer 1995).  Virtual Reality Modeling Language (VRML) will translate 3-D images on the Web using such 3-D viewers as WebSpace and supplemental programs for Netscape and Mosaic.  The 3-D technology will allow cybershoppers to see products, turn them around on the computer screen, and inspect all sides.  Cybershoppers purchasing tickets for a basketball game, play, or orchestra performance will get a 3-D view of their scope of vision from the seats, as if they were actually there.  This technology offers a sense of realism that the Internet currently lacks.<p>   

     There are many marketplaces on the Web, but far too many of them are dull.  They look and feel like brochures slapped onto computer screens.  Critics equate them to junk mail or drive-by billboards (Ziegler).  However, some creative sites are attracting notice and several appeal to Cybersports.  The ESPNET SportsZone, at http://espnet.sportszone.com, is an exciting resource for sports information, excelling in writing, graphics, depth, and immediacy (Mossberg 1995).  It offers news stories, scores, game highlights, statistics, graphics, player information, and real time narratives of games as they are played.  The strategy of this site is to continue offering a free public area, but later expand into a select, subscription area that will require a fee for entry.<p>

     Many Web visitors will return because of the services offered.  For example, customers shipping parcels using Federal Express Corp. and United Parcel Service of American, Inc. can check the status of their delivery on the Web (Ziegler 1995).  They access the appropriate Web site, follow simple tracking instructions, and type in the number of their shipment.  Others may want to use Web financial services, for example mutual fund owners can visit a site that will help them calculate their potential investment earnings.  Cybershoppers can track stocks on the Web and even purchase them through traditional brokers who have set up shop in cyberspace.  Others will enjoy tapping into cybernews that can help them make business decisions (Wildstrom 1995).<p>

     Some Web visitors will return because they need and want information.  If so, they may be hooked by information on the Web, and particularly by a new Web source.  The Encyclopaedia Britannica, one of the world's preeminent information sources, is beta testing a Web site.  The computer CD Britannica, at 44 million words, vastly out-informs most other computerized encyclopedias, at 8 to 9 million words (Jones, Springen and Sawhill 1995).  It is expected that the Web Britannica will also outweigh its competitors.<p>

     Americans are much more oriented toward interactive shopping on the Internet than their European cousins.  While some worry about what it will take to keep Americans on the Web, others worry about what it will take to get Europeans there.  Europeans are far less interested in video on-demand over the Internet.  While 43 percent of American consumers say they are "very interested" in this service, only 19 percent of the consumers in France and Britain feel the same way (Parker-Pope 1995).  While 75 percent of U.S. households owning a VCR rent at least one video a month, in Western Europe the number drops to under 40 percent.  Only in France, which has enjoyed interactive shopping services through telephone terminal connections for years, is there almost as much interest in home shopping as there is in the United States.<p>


<b><a name="questionsd">Mini-Case Questions</a></b>

</ul>
<li>Explain how the Web is an advertising medium.<p>

<li>Explain how the Web is a communication channel.<p>

<li>Explain how the Web is an information retrieval system.<p>

<li>Explain how the Web is a cybercatalog.<p>
<li>Explain how the Web is a yellow pages directory.<p>

<li>What do you think of 3-D on the Internet?  Will it attract more cybervisitors?  Do you think it will attract shoppers who want to see all sides of a product?<p>

<li>What are the advantages of a Web site like SportsZone for the sports fan who can't seem to get enough of his or her favorite team or athlete?  What types of services might this site offer to get visitors to make return visits?<p>

<li>Consumers often don't know what they want.  However, when something new reaches the market, they suddenly realize how much they want it.  Could this be the case in Europe?  They aren't clamoring for the Internet and technologies such as video on-demand now, but will they adopt them once they become available?  Explain your answers.<p>

<li>Europeans don't have to contend with irritating commercials that interrupt movies shown on their television stations.  How might this affect their interest in uninterrupted movies on the Internet, on-demand?  Do you think this has anything to do with their relatively low video rental rates compared to Americans?<p>

<li>Does the Internet have "staying power?"  What do you think?<p>

<b><a name="referencesd">References</a></b><p>

Jones, Malcolm, Jr., Karen Springen, and Ray Sawhill (1995), "From A-ak to Zywiec," <i>Newsweek</i> (May 29): 61.<p>

Meyer, Michael (1995), "Surfing the Internet in 3-D," <i>Newsweek</i> (May 15): 68-69.<p>

Mossberg, Walter S. (1995), "SportsZone Scores Big Amid Dull Landscape of Web Marketplace," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (June 1): B1.<p>

Parker-Pope, Tara (1995), "Intereactive Offerings Have Less Appeal in Europe Than in U.S., Survey Says," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (June 21): B9.<p>

Wildstrom, Stephen H. (1995), "An Online Feast of Business News," <i>Business Week</i> (April 17): 16.<p>

Ziegler, Bart (1995), "In Cyberspace the Web Delivers Junk Mail," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (June 13): B1,6.<p>

