<title>Mini-case: Change or Die</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">


<h2>Mini-Case:  Change Or Die - Even Market Leaders Feel The Heat</h2>

An old saying goes, "You can lead a horse to water, but you can't make him drink!"  Can this be applied to American's eating habits, as well?  The Center for Science in the Public Interest says most fast foods are too fatty and not good for your health (Sullivan 1995).  The Center has found fault with traditional fast food burgers and fries, Chinese food, and Mexican food, reporting that deep fried burritos and cheese-laden dishes have as much fat as 10 glazed doughnuts (de Lisser 1995).<p>  

America's love of greasy fast foods is held accountable for the third of all U.S. citizens who are overweight.  Yet most people seem to lack the willpower to eat a salad in a place where they can smell the fries and watch others chomp down on a 640 calorie Whopper, or a 510 calorie Big Mac, with its 26 grams of fat.  Will they change their eating habits voluntarily?  Can the fast food chains get them to change?<p>

Many chains have tried to develop good tasting, low fat menu alternatives, only to fail.  Weight Watchers' dietetic foods were sold in Burger King stores for only a short time before being cancelled.   McDonald's McLean Deluxe never caught on after its introduction in 1991, and some franchisees have taken it off their menus (Sullivan 1995).  It is said that some industry analysis dubbed it the McFlopper (de Lisser 1995).  However, McDonald's does offer McGrilled Chicken and lite salad dressing.  Arby's allows its restaurants the option of not offering low-fat items, and 40 percent don't (Sullivan 1995).<p>

As if further proof is needed of America's love of big, beefy hamburgers and crisp fires, McDonald's is serving up  sandwiches with "double the beef", coupled with Super Sized drinks and fries (Gibson 1995).  PepsiCo's Pizza Hut is offering Stuffed Crust pizza, with extra cheese baked into the outside edge of crust (Rudnitsky 1995).  And Wendy's is known for loading on the cheese, bacon, sauce, and extra beef.<p>       

Bucking the trend, PepsiCo's Taco Bell, a low price leader in fast food, is trying to become a low fat leader, as well.  Taco Bell led the industry into a low price, value strategy when it introduced a "value menu" in 1989.  It is trying to do the same with low fat foods.  If it succeeds, it will break away from the competition and reap large profits.<p>

Taco Bell's strategy with its Border Lights menu is to offer reduced fat versions of items on the regular menu.  The low fat versions will be priced the same, but without the fat.  Taco Bell is aggressively targeting the fat conscious consumer, and where others have failed, it intends to succeed.<p> 

If we are what we eat, then Americans might want to take a lesson from the Chinese.  Traditional medicinal restaurants are enjoying a revival of popularity in Chinese communities.  Many Chinese seek out these restaurants for foods that may cure health problems.  A customer comes into a health restaurant and tells the host what ails him.  The host listens carefully, then prescribes the customer's lunch (Brauchli 1995).  For someone recuperating from a recent operation, the host may give them chicken soup with ginseng and splayed gecko lizards to improve blood circulation and stimulate the formation of new blood cells.  If you have swollen neck glands, your lunch may be chicken and seahorse stew; for dizziness, fried rice with wolfberries (Brauchli 1995).<p> 


<b><a name="questionse">Mini-Case Questions</a></b>

<ul>

<li>Is McDonald's right in pursuing a strategy of offering double hamburgers and super size fries to cater to "large" appetites?<p>

<li>Does Taco Bell have a good strategy with its low fat line?<p>

<li>Why don't older consumers pay greater attention to health warnings?<p>

<li>Why are younger consumers (teens, twentysomethings) ignoring health warnings about fatty foods?<p>

<li>How much influence do restaurant smells and the sight of others eating hamburgers and fries have on consumers trying to stick to a low fat diet?<p>

<li>Do consumers ignore low fat fast foods because they think they won't taste good?  What does perception have to do with their reluctance?  How could promotions be designed to remove this stigma?<p>

<li>What do you think are the chances that Taco Bell can establish a sustainable competitive advantage with their Border Lights strategy?  What will it take for them to do so?  What will the competition do if Taco Bell is successful?<p>

<li>A recent survey showed that 83 percent of China's teens daily consume medicinal tonics to improve and protect their health (Brauchli 1995).  Will they also like Big Macs and Whoppers when those chains establish restaurants in China? <p>

<li>Many Americans enjoy Chinese restaurants in the United States.  Do you think there might be a market for traditional Chinese health restaurants here?<p>

</ul>

<b><a name="referencese">References</a>
</b><p>

Brauchelo, Marcus W. (1995), "If You Are What You Eat, This Story Is Food for Thought," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (March 13): A1, 9.<p>

de Lisser, Eleena (1995), "Taco Bell, Low-Price King, Will Offer Low-Fat Line," <i>The Wall Street Journal </i>(February 6): B1, 6.<p>

Gibson, Richard (1995), "At McDonald's, New Recipes For Buns, Eggs," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (June 13): B1, 3.<p>

Rudnitsky, Howard (1995), "Leaner Cuisine," <i>Forbes</i> (March 27): 43-44.<p>

Sullivan, R. Lee (1995), "Leaner Menus," <i>Forbes</i> (March 13): 154.
<p>

