<title>Mini-case: World Car</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">


<h2>Mini-Case:  Does The World Need Or Want A World Car?</h2>
   
The ambitious Ford 2000 Plan calls for the merger of Ford's operations in the United States and Europe, and later the Asian and Latin American organizations into one, giant, global corporation (Flint 1994).  The goal is to eventually integrate Ford designs and production so that Ford's world cars can be built anywhere, in any Ford plant, using one set of basic designs with only modest local variations.  The same platform, design, and manufacturing processes that Ford Europe uses to build small cars will also be used in the United States; U.S. Ford plants will focus on larger cars and trucks, which many be marketed worldwide.  The goal is to achieve cost savings through the increased efficiency that comes with engineering a car only once.  Ford is pushing its global strategy of bigger-is-better.<p>

Ford has already tried producing a world car, the Escort. However, while the Escort has been successful in Europe, it hasn't made money in the United States, even when modifications were made to make it more appealing to American consumers.  Ford has higher expectations for the Mondeo, Ford Contour, and Mercury Mystique.  These three models come from common ancestry, starting with the European version, the Mondeo, and progressing to the Contour and Mystique, which were introduced in the United States in September 1994.  The Mondeo was launched in Europe in 1993 and is very popular with Europeans, already selling over 600,000 units.  It cost Ford $6 billion over six years to develop the three cars (McElroy 1994).<p>

Some automobile marketing analysts believe that Ford may be going in the wrong direction.  Other automobile companies are taking the opposite strategy and spinning off regional units.  These smaller production centers are closer to the markets they will be courting.  Their more narrowly focused plants are positioned to deliver mass customized cars tailored to satisfy cultural differences and smaller market segments.  Decisions will be made at these regional production sites to deal with differences in work processes, consumers, and government regulations.  Lee Iacocca, former president of both Chrysler and Ford, questions Ford's decision, as he doubts that one product group can make decisions for both the North American and European continents (Flint 1994).<p>   

Ford's launch of its world cars in the United States was hampered by production problems; recalls, that left dealers without products and consumers with questions in their minds about the cars' reliability; high lease prices; and confusing product positioning.  The initial advertising campaign proudly declared that the Contour was the world's first "global car", but consumers seemed confused by what this meant.  They certainly weren't impressed with the claim.  Industry observers quickly criticized the car's positioning and its relatively high lease costs (Connelly 1995).<p>  

Because sales were weak throughout the fall, Ford decided to relaunch the cars in early 1995, with aggressive print advertisements that moved away from the "world car" theme and began promoting the Contour's value, as more car for less money (Warner and Suris 1995).  Ford's advertising agency for the Contour, J. Walter Thompson, concentrated on safety features, performance features, and competitive pricing (Halliday 1995).<p>

Ford's goal for 1995 was to sell 200,000 Contours, yet its sales were averaging below 13,000 per month.  Goals for the Mystique, were about 70,000 units annually, but its sales were averaging less than 3,000 per month.  When global production gears up, Ford plans to sell 800,000 Mondeo, Contour, and Mystique cars annually (Jost 1994).<p>

     
<b><a name="questionsf">Mini-Case Questions</a></b>

<ul>

<li>Are Ford's goals for the Contour and Mystique realistic?<p>

<li>What went wrong with Ford's initial strategy for marketing the Contour in the United States?<p>

<li>Is Lee Iacocca right, is Ford moving in the wrong direction?<p>

<li>Is Ford's strategy one of "Think global, act local?"<p>

<li>What are some problems that Ford can expect from centralizing its decision making?<p>

<li>What are some advantages that Ford's competitors can realize from decentralizing?<p>

<li>Does the world really need and want a world car?<p>

<li>Do American consumers really need and want a world car?  What do initial sales indicate?<p>

</ul>


<b><a name="referencesf">References</a></b><p>

Connelly, Mary (1995), "Ford Spends to Jump-Start Contour Cars," <i>Automotive News</i> (January 30): 1-2.<p>

Flint, Jerry (1994), "One World, One Ford,"<i> Forbes</i> (June 20): 40-        41.<p>

Halliday, Jean (1995), "JWT Reshapes Contour: For Ford's compact Sedan, JWT Changes Tack After the Model's Launch Falls Flat,"<i> ADWEEK Eastern Edition</i> (February 20): 4-5.<p>

Jost, Kevin (1994), "Ford Contour and Mercury Mystique,"        <i>Automotive Engineering</i> (October): 56-62.<p>

McElroy, John (1994), "Ford Contour and Mercury Mystique: Ford  Readies its $6 Billion Powerhouse for the American Market," <i>Automotive Industries</i> (October): 100-103.<p>

Warner, Fara and Oscar Suris (1995), "Ford Launching Comeback of Contour with New Ads," <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> (February 7): B1, 8.

<p>

