<html>
<head>
<title>Siegel IM - What To Do On The First Day</title>
</head>
<body background="/gifs/back/sandpapr.gif">
Instructor's Resource Manual to accompany<br>
MARKETING: FOUNDATIONS AND APPLICATIONS<br> 
by Carolyn F. Siegel<br>
Part I    Starting Points<br>
   
<h2>WHAT TO DO ON THE FIRST DAY</h2>
              
     Even a marketing instructor who has seen many first days can
usually remember the <b>very first</b>.  It's often a time for sweaty
palms and considerable nervousness.  Some hints for the first day
may be helpful for those facing it.  I can't promise that these
suggestions will cure all first day jitters, but this is the
routine that I follow each term, and it works for me!<p>
<ul>
<li><b><i>Be prepared</i></b>!  Make sure that copies of the syllabus are
     ready before class in sufficient numbers, usually with
     several extra copies for students who enrolled late.  Check
     the classroom in advance and count desks; if there aren't
     enough, bring in extra chairs.  If you intend to use the
     chalkboard, make sure you have chalk and an eraser.  If you
     plan to use equipment, such as an overhead projector, check
     to be sure there is one in the room and it works.  Position
     your transparency on the glass so that everyone in the room
     can see it.  If you need to use a wall screen, be sure you
     can reach the cord.  If you plan to use a lectern (podium),
     make sure it is at the correct height.<p>

<li><b><i>Check your roll before class</i></b>.  Say each name aloud before
     class.  If you are unsure of a pronunciation, check with the
     student in class as you call the roll.  Mark the phonetic
     pronunciation of unusual names on your roll so you can
     pronounce the name correctly at the next roll call.<p>

<li><b><i>Come to class on time</i></b>.  Coming late, particularly on the
     first day, sends students a very negative message.<p>  

<li><b><i>Firmly take charge</i></b>.  If students are talking when you come
     into the room, which is fairly typical, confidently walk to
     the lectern and greet them.  Welcome them to the class, tell
     them your name and the course title.  As you call the roll,
     ask for their help in correcting your pronunciation of their
     name.  At the end of the roll call, ask any student whose
     name was not called to come forward.  Write their name in an
     appropriate place on the roll.  If you intend to have
     students complete an information card on the first day of
     class, come equipped with enough cards.  Be prepared to
     write on the chalkboard or have a transparency master ready
     with the information on it that each student will be asked
     to provide.<p>

<li><b><i>Distribute your syllabus</i></b>.  Make sure that each student has a
     syllabus.  Carefully go over each point.  Ask for questions
     at anytime.  Emphasize the important points and clearly
     state the assignment for the next class meeting, referring
     to the syllabus.  Ask if anyone has a copy of the textbook
     with them.  Have them show the book to the class, so
     students who haven't purchased it will know what to look for
     in the bookstore.<p>

<li><b><i>Break the ice</i></b>. Everyone is a little on edge the first day. 
     To break the ice, you might share some observations about
     marketing, perhaps why you find it so interesting.  Briefly
     mention your academic or professional marketing experiences. 
     Students usually enjoy learning something about their
     instructors, so a brief biography of your marketing-related
     experiences should be well received.  Alternately, if your
     class is relatively small, ask each student to share some
     information about himself or herself, particularly about
     marketing work experiences and career goals.<p>

<li><b><i>Plan an orderly dismissal</i></b>.  When it is time to leave, tell
     the class that you look forward to seeing them again at the
     next class meeting.  Make it clear that <b>you</b> are dismissing
     the class.  Set the precedent from the first day that it is
     the instructor and not the clock that signals the end of a
     session.<p> 

<li><b><i>Try to relax</i></b>.  Most marketing instructors survive their very
     first day.  All of us know we can do it better next time! 
     Set that as your goal and learn from your mistakes.  Keep
     the first day in perspective.  While it is important to
     start firmly, relax and try to share a laugh or two with the
     class, particularly if you feel comfortable telling a joke
     on yourself.  Never tell a joke at the expense of a student.<p>
</ul> 
<p>
<hr>
<h4><i>We want to hear from you!</i></h4>
<h5>If you have any questions about this text, please feel free to contact Carl Helwing, Marketing Manager, by phone at 708/789-5382 or by email at <a href="mailto:chelwing@irwin.com">chelwing@irwin.com</h5></a>
<center>
<a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/maps/cedppbr.map"><img src="/ced/gifs/cedppbr.gif" border=0 ismap></a>
<img src="/gifs/mprule.gif"><br>
<address>Copyright &copy1995 McGraw-Hill Higher Education</address>
</center>
</body>
</html>



</DOC>
