<head>

<title>American Goverment</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center>
<a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/techdirect/maps/techdrbr.map"><img border=0 src="/techdirect/gifs/techdrbr.gif" ismap></a><br>
<img src="/techdirect/gifs/mprule.gif"><P>
</center>

<a href="gifs/amgvmtcv.gif"><img border=2 align=left hspace=15 vspace=10 src="smgifs/s_amgvmtcv.gif"></a>
<BR>
<h2>American Goverment Videodisc</h2>

<h4>Videodisc #23028</h4>
<BR clear=left>
<hr>This interactive videodisc, from Brown & Benchmark Publishers, utilizes videoclips from
C-SPAN and other sources, allowing students to experience what happens on the floor of
Congress, in committees, and elsewhere in Washington. 

A time line traces the development of campaign finance and related legislation from the
passage of the Civil Service Act in 1883.  By selecting a particular event, the student will
bring up more information on screen.  Your students will learn about lawmaking and
policymaking processes with a graphical flow chart.  High-quality graphics and text show
various steps in the process.  A chart representing the steps is displayed on screen.  By
clicking on the rectangle representing any of the steps, more information including
video becomes available to the user.  A glossary of terms also is included.

Side one covers the legislative and policymaking process within Congress and elsewhere,
using campaign finance as a specific example.  Side two includes five topics: the budgetary
process, civil rights, lobbying, the North American Free Trade Agreement, and the Supreme
Court. <EM>American Government</EM> also includes software that enables you, via Hypercard, to
operate your videodisc in conjunction with your Macintosh computer.


<br clear=left>
<hr>

