<title>Ocean Planet</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center>
<a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/techdirect/maps/techdrbr.map"><img border=0 src="/techdirect/gifs/techdrbr.gif" ismap></a><br>
<img src="/techdirect/gifs/mprule.gif"><P>
</center>

<a href="gifs/ocplancv.gif"><img border=2 align=left hspace=15 vspace=10 src="smgifs/s_ocplancv.gif"></a>

<h2>Ocean Planet CD-ROM</h2>

<h4>Windows CD-ROM #34448</h4>
<h4>Macintosh CD-ROM #34449</h4>
<BR clear=left>
<hr><a href="gifs/ocplan4.gif"><img border=2 align=right hspace=15 vspace=10 src="smgifs/s_ocplan4.gif"></a>
<BR>Investigate the last unexplored frontier on Earth, the ocean.  Over 30 minutes of high quality
video depicting all aspects of marine ecology, hundreds of compelling photographs, and
hypertext glossary words will bring the great deep to life.  <i>Ocean Planet</i> will show students
how the sun, Earth, moon, and oceans connect to form a complex system of    atmosphere
and weather.  Ask the experts--four renowned experts are on hand to answer compelling
questions about marine ecology.

<a href="gifs/ocplan5.gif"><img border=2 align=left hspace=15 vspace=10 src="smgifs/s_ocplan5.gif"></a>
<p>
<i>Ocean Planet</i> invites you to explore the breadth of undersea activity and the issues that
challenge aquatic life's delicate balance. Learn why the oceans are in danger and what you
and your         students can do to help preserve them. <i>Ocean Planet</i> is also an excellent
companion to The Smithsonian Institution's Ocean Planet Exhibition.
<br clear=left>
<hr>

