<title>American Geological InstituteVideodisc</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center>
<a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/techdirect/maps/techdrbr.map"><img border=0 src="/techdirect/gifs/techdrbr.gif" ismap></a><br>
<img src="/techdirect/gifs/mprule.gif"><P>
</center>

<a href="gifs/agicv.gif"><img border=2 align=left hspace=15 vspace=10 src="smgifs/s_agicv.gif"></a>
<BR>
<h2>American Geological Institute Videodisc</h2>

<h4>Videodisc #23257</h4>
<BR clear=left>
<hr>The <I>American Geological Institute Videodisc</I> is the ideal component to the visually oriented
study of earth sciences.  Enhance your instruction with images of more than 3,500
photographs, diagrams, animations and videos carefully selected and cataloged to support
standard earth science texts and lecture subjects. This comprehensive visual           
collection can be used as a resource for the subjects of physical geology, earth science,
oceanography, earth history, dinosaurs, environmental geology, astronomy, physical
geography, and human geography. A complete image directory accompanies the videodisc. 
Each illustration, photograph and moving segment is included.<P>

<B>This exciting videodisc features:</B>
<UL>
<LI> More than 150 animations of key geological processes.
<LI> Approximately 15 minutes of film footage from the U.S. Geological Survey Library and other sources.
<LI>     Nearly 2,000 photographs (including many by respected geologist and aerial photographer Doug Sherman).
<LI>     Almost 2,000 illustrations from WCB Earth Science Library.
<LI>     100 black-and-white photos by renowned geologist and aerial photographer John Shelton.
<LI>     Information on rocks, minerals, volcanic activity, plate tectonics, mountain building, and earthquakes. 
</UL>

<hr>

