<html>

<head>
<title>Realization Reports by Issue</title>
<! base href="rosenblum.toc.html">
<nextid>
</head>

<body>

<H1>Realization Reports by Issue</H1>

<hr><p>

<H3>Issue 0:  
<A href="rosenblum.000.html">
Hello and introduction to the goals of The Realization Report.
</A>
</H3>

<P><H3>
Issue 1:  
<A href="rosenblum.001.html">
Eurographics 92
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  Eurographics '92 was held in Cambridge, UK in
September 1992.  Eurographics is the major all-topics computer
graphics conference for Europe.  This report describes some
highlights of Eurographics '92.

<P><H3>
Issue 2:  
<A href="rosenblum.002.html">
University of Leeds: Graphics and Visualization
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  The University of Leeds is actively supporting
its own researchers with scientific visualization methodology, as
well as in coordination and cooperation within the British higher
education system.  Visualization research at Leeds primarily
focuses on both developing toolsets for scientists and
interdisciplinary research with scientists and engineers from
across the university.  The GRASPARC project is developing methods
for the interactive steering of numerical computations.

<P><H3>
Issue 3: 
<A href="rosenblum.003.html">
Visualization '92
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  The IEEE Visualization 92 Conference took place in
Boston, 19-23 October.  There was a full program of tutorials,
papers, panels, and case studies, and many items of interest for
visualization users, developers, and researchers.  This Report
summarises the principal results presented at the Conference.

<P><H3>
Issue 4: 
<A href="rosenblum.004.html">
HPCC
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  The keynote address at the IEEE Visualization 92
Conference [see The Realization Report, Issue No. 3] in Boston,
Oct. 1992, was given by Dr. Eugene Wong of the White House Office
of Science and Technology Policy.  He discussed the formation,
start-up, focus, and philosophy of the High-Performance Computing
Initiative.  Because of the high interest in HPCC, I am providing
a report on his talk.

<P><H3>
Issue 5:  
<A href="rosenblum.005.html">
ARRL: telerobotics
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: Advanced Robotics Research Ltd (ARRL) is located on the
campus of the University of Salford, England.  ARRL seeks to
develop a telepresence testbed, with special emphasis on the
ability to consider the human factors elements.  Current efforts
are in two parts: the virtual reality (VR) interface for
telerobotics and scene reconstruction using a laser ranging device.

<P><H3>
Issue 6: 
<A href="rosenblum.006.html">
W-Industries: VR for Entertainment
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  W Industries Ltd, located in Leicester, England, is
producing virtual reality products for the entertainment market.
They have marketed several commercially successful products.  This
report discusses the techniques and limitations of inexpensive,
"low" end virtual reality systems for the entertainment industry.

<P><H3>
Issue 7: 
<A href="rosenblum.007.html">
Freeform Curves and Surfaces '92
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: The Freeform Curves and Surfaces '92 meeting was held at
the Mathematical Research Institute Oberwolfach in June 1992.  It
is an international, invitation-only event for presenting recent
advances in Computer-Aided Geometric Design (CAGD).  CAGD is, of
course, a critical topic for manufacturing design.  This report
presents some highlights of Freeform Curves and Surfaces '92.

<P><H3>
Issue 8: 
<A href="rosenblum.008.html">
TNO-FEL: Simulation, Machine Vision, and VR
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: The Physics and Electronics Laboratory (FEL) of the
Netherlands Organization for Applied Scientific Research (TNO)
performs research in observation systems, information technology
and telecommunication systems (IT & Telecom), training and
simulation (T&S), and support decisions.  This report discusses
computer science research at FEL's Training and Simulation Division
in visual systems, high performance computing hardware, computer
vision for scene reconstruction, and virtual reality (virtual
environments).

<P><H3>
Issue 9: 
<A href="rosenblum.009.html">
EPFL & Univ of Geneva:  Character Animation
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  Daniel Thalmann at the Swiss Federal Institute of
Technology in Lausanne and Nadia Thalmann at the University of
Geneva are a married couple whose joint work in computer-generated
animation has long been leading edge.  Their current research is
primarily in physical-based and behavioral modeling as it applies
to the human figure.  Examples include animating human facial
movements, human hair, movement by human figures, and clothing.
They are beginning to integrate virtual reality (VR) technology
into this research.

<P><H3>
Issue 10: 
<A href="rosenblum.010.html">
ONERA: Fluid Dynamics Visualization
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  The (French) National Office for the Study of
Aerospace Research (ONERA) is a large scientific institute whose
departments span physics, optics, and other disciplines in addition
to the obvious topic of fluid dynamics in support of aerospace
design.  This report describes the activities in the Visualization
Branch of the Computing Center.  Visualization activities include
both visualization support and RACE-sponsored research into
distributed visualization.

<P><H3>
Issue 11:  
<A href="rosenblum.011.html">
EPFL & Univ. of Geneva:  Other activities
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  While visiting Nadia and Daniel Thalmann (see
Realization Report #9) at the University of Geneva and the Swiss
Federal Institute of Technology in Lausanne (EPFL), I also stopped
in at the Multimedia Laboratory at the University of Geneva and the
Peripheral Systems Laboratory at EPFL.  This report describes some
of the current activities at these two laboratories.

<P><H3>
Issue 12: 
<A href="rosenblum.012.html">
ECN: Scientific Visualization, esp. Fluid Flow
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: The Netherlands Energy Research Foundation (ECN) carries
out research to develop "sustainable" energy supplies, where
sustainable means that the energy is produced without limiting the
options of future generations.  Within ECN a software engineering
and research group investigates how computer science can best be
applied to ECN problems.  This report focuses on the visualization
research of Dr. Jarke van Wijk within this group.

<P><H3>
Issue 13: 
<A href="rosenblum.013.html">
Delft Univ. of Technology:  Fluid Flow Visualization
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: For reasons that are obvious to anyone who has heard the
story of the little boy with his finger in the dike, fluid
(specifically water) flow is an emphasized research topic in The
Netherlands.  Working closely with industrial partners, the
computer graphics group at Delft University of Technology focuses
on research into the visualization of fluid flow from computational
fluid dynamics (CFD) simulations.  Applications are primarily on
water flow, which has some distinct problems when compared with
aerospace-oriented CFD visualization.

<P><H3>
Issue 14:  
<A href="rosenblum.014.html">
Selected U.K. Activities
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  A large funder of information technology (IT) research
and development in the U.K. is the Joint Framework for Information
Technology (JFIT).  JFIT is a combination of the U.K. Science and
Engineering Council (SERC) and the Department of Trade and Industry
(DTI).  The following are selected IT items from JFIT publications.

<P><H3>
Issue 15:  
<A href="rosenblum.015.html">
CWI:  Parallel processing and Interation
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  The Center for Mathematics and Computer Science (CWI) in
The Netherlands is a 200 person national institute for pure
research. This report describes some of the activities of CWI's
Interactive Systems Branch.

<P><H3>
Issue 16:  
<A href="rosenblum.016.html">
ESPRIT: Information Day + HPC and Basic Research
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: Because of its ability to cross national boarders in
Europe, the European Strategic Programme for Research and
Development (R&D) in Information Technology (ESPRIT) has become a
premier source of funding for European research.  ESPRIT
Information Day was held in February to discuss the next round of
ESPRIT funding (ESPRIT-III).  This report provides a brief overview
of ESPRIT and the objectives and R&D tasks for two domains:  High
Performance Computing and its Applications and Basic Research.  A
second report will follow to describe the objectives and R&D for
selected additional domains. The R&D tasks for Basic Research
specifically includes a new task (R&D task 6.4) covering data
visualization and virtual reality.

<P><H3>
Issue 17: 
<A href="rosenblum.017.html">
ESPRIT: Microelectronics
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: Realization Report #16 presented an overview of ESPRIT,
a premier European R&D program for information technology and gave
the objectives and R&D tasks for the domains of High Performance
Computing and its Applications and Basic Research.  This combined
issue of the ONR Newsletters on Electronics and Computer Science
presents the ESPRIT-III program for Microelectronics.

<P><H3>
Issue 18:  
<A href="rosenblum.018.html">
GMD:  Connection-Machine-Based Visualization
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: The German Center for Mathematics and Computer Science
(GMD) has recently established a Scientific Visualization
Department in conjunction with a supercomputer center that serves
several large German research laboratories as well as universities.
The Visualization Department performs both basic research and
applications support.  Their work is primarily Connection Machine
based.  This report describes some of their activities.

<P><H3>
Issue 19: 
<A href="rosenblum.019.html">
ESPRIT:  Computer Integrated Manufacturing & Engin.
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: This report concludes a three part discussion of the
European Strategic Programme for Research and Development (R&D) in
Information Technology (ESPRIT) and ESPRIT Information Day with
some additional remarks about Information Day and by listing the
programs for the ESPRIT-III Domains of Advanced Business & Home
Peripherals and Computer Integrated Manufacturing & Engineering
(CIM&E).

<P><H3>
Issue 20: 
<A href="rosenblum.020.html">
Univ. of Marseille, Luminy: Medical Imaging
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: The Computer Science Dept. at the University of Marseille
- Luminy has recently expanded its focus to include computer
graphics.  This report describes the work of Prof. Sequeira, who is
setting up the graphics group.

<P><H3>
Issue 21:  
<A href="rosenblum.021.html">
U.K. News
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: A large funding agency for information technology (IT)
research and development in the U.K. is the Joint Framework for
Information Technology (JFIT).  JFIT is a combination of the U.K.
Science and Engineering Council (SERC) and the Department of Trade
and Industry (DTI).  The following are copied or abstracted from
selected IT items in JFIT publications.  
See also <a href="rosenblum.014.html">Realization Report #14</a>.

<P><H3>
Issue 22: 
<A href="rosenblum.022.html">
4th Eurographics Workshopon Visualization in Sci. Comp.
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: This report describes activities at the 4th Eurographics
Workshop on Visualization in Scientific Computing, held in
Abington, U.K. on April 21-23.

<P><H3>
Issue 23: 
<A href="rosenblum.023.html">
Fermat's Last Theorem
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  At a lecture in Cambridge (U.K.), Prof. Andrew Wiles
announced a solution to Fermat's Last Theorem, mathematics most
famous (previously) unsolved problem.

<P><H3>
Issue 24: 
<A href="rosenblum.024.html">
NAS International Lecture Series to Eastern Europe
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: This report briefly summarizes the Spring 1993 National
Academy of Sciences International Science Lecture Series (sponsored
by the Office of Naval Research (ONR) and the Air Force Office of
Scientific Research (AFOSR)).  This year's topic was information
science and the area visited was Eastern Europe.  Prof. John
Hopcroft of Cornell gave a series of lectures and discussions were
held with computer scientists in the five countries visited.

<P><H3>
Issue 25:  
<A href="rosenblum.025.html">
Parallel CFD '93
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: The Parallel CFD '93 Conference (CFD stands for
computational fluid dynamics) focuses on the entire range of CFD
parallel computation, from pre-processing and methods of solving
partial differential equations (PDE) though post-processing and
interdisciplinary applications.

<P><H3>
Issue 26: 
<A href="rosenblum.026.html">
Division Ltd.
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: A U.K. Company founded in 1989, Division Ltd. offers a
modularized software development system, as well as hardware, for
vr applications.  They have offices in Europe, the U.S. and Japan
and their systems are being used in several leading European
applications.

<P><H3>
Issue 27: 
<A href="rosenblum.027.html">
1st Eurographics Workshop on Virtual Environments
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  After discussions with Eurographics that resulted in
this event being formed, ONREUR is providing support for a research
oriented VR Workshop to be held just preceeding the annual
Eurographics conference in Barcelona.

<P><H3>
Issue 28: 
<A href="rosenblum.028.html">
Symposium on Parallel Numerical Mathematics
</A>
</H3>
Abstract: The Symposium on Parallel Numerical Mathematics,
sponsored by The Centre for Novel Computing, University of
Manchester was held on Sept. 9-10, 1993.  Located at the Manchester
Centre for Computational Mathematics (U.K.), the Symposium brought
together people interested in parallel computing with a nice
balance across different areas of scientific computing and
perspectives from both theory and practical experience.

<P><H3>
Issue 29:  
<A href="rosenblum.029.html">
The structure of ITC Programs within the EC
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  The report presents an overview of the structure of ITC
programs within the European Community (EC) and how these programs
are viewed by a member nation.  The report will be of value to
those wanting an overview or even needing a reference to the
occasional acronym appearing elsewhere for a European ITC program.

<P><H3>
Issue 30:
<A href="rosenblum.030.html">
Upcoming Conferences
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  The report lists selected upcoming European activities
in visualization, vr, graphics, and related areas.

<P><H3>
Issue 31:
<A href="rosenblum.031.html">
TBD
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  TBD

<P><H3>
Issue 32:
<A href="rosenblum.032.html">
First Eurographics Workshop on Virtual Environments + Other Refs. 
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  
The First Eurographics Workshop on Virtual Environments was
held on Sept. 7th in Barcelona, Spain as part of the Eurographics
annual conference.  The workshop resulted from discussions between
Eurographics and the ONR European Office and was designed to
provide a venue for European and U.S. researchers to discuss
current activity.

<P><H3>
Issue 33:
<A href="rosenblum.033.html">
Information Technology (IT) Projects in the U.K.
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  This report, taken primarily from selected
publications of the U.K.'s Department of Trade and Industry (DTI),
examines several IT projects of interest.

<P><H3>
Issue 34:
<A href="rosenblum.034.html">
Scuola Superiore Sant'Anna:  
VR force feedback dataglove and shoulder exoskeleton.
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  This report features the research
of Prof. Massimo Bergamasco
of the Robotics Laboratory of the Scuola Superiore Sant'Anna.  The
focus is research to develop datagloves and exoskeletons for VR.

<P><H3>
Issue 35:
<A href="rosenblum.035.html">
ONR Workshop produces Special Section of the March 1994 IEEE
Computer Graphics and Applications
</A>
</H3>
Abstract:  The ONR Workshop on Data Visualization was held in
Darmstadt, Germany in July 1993.  One product from the Workshop is
a Special Section of the March 1994 IEEE Computer Graphics and
Applications (CG&A).  This Special Section discusses research
issues for selected subtopics of scientific visualization.

<hr>
<p>

<H3>Special Issues of the Realization Report</H3>
(These issues are for U.S. Government Program Managers only):<P>

<ul>
<li>Special Issue on Research Directions in Computer-Aided
Geometric Design.

<li>Special Issue on Research Directions in Fluid Flow.

<li>Preliminary Report on the ONR Data Visualization Workshop.
</ul>

