<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 35</Title>
<NEXTID=36>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 35</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<a href="rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.europe.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

ONR Workshop produces Special Section of the March 1994 IEEE
Computer Graphics and Applications
............................................ Feb. 19, 1994
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Papers</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Acknowledgements</a><br>
<P>


<a href="#[2.0]" NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  The ONR Workshop on Data Visualization was held in
Darmstadt, Germany in July 1993.  One product from the Workshop is
a Special Section of the March 1994 IEEE Computer Graphics and
Applications (CG&A).  This Special Section discusses research
issues for selected subtopics of scientific visualization.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Larry Rosenblum, Workshop Chairman
   lrosenblum@onreur.navy.mil
</PRE>
<P>

<a href="#[3.0]" NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  One of the goals of the ONR European Office (ONREUR) is to
facilitate liaison, communication, and discussions of research
issues and progress among scientists on both sides of the Atlantic.
Toward this end I organized the ONR Data Visualization Workshop
which was held last July at the Fraunhofer Institute for Computer
Graphics in Darmstadt, Germany.  The workshop's sponsors were
ONREUR and the Computer Science Division of ONR.  The 30 attendees
included 16 members from Western Europe, 10 from the U.S., and 4
from Russia and the Far East.  The intent of the workshop was to
survey recent progress in scientific visualization and especially
to examine research requirements.
<P>

Members of the Workshop's working subgroups have continued their
efforts through the fall.  The result is a set of articles that
will appear next month as a Special Section of IEEE CG&A.  Some
Realization Report readers had a preview in the October 1993
Special Issue of the Realization Report on the ONR Data
Visualization Workshop where I provided a preliminary statement of
research issues as generated from the Workshop's results.  This
Realization Report Special Issue was released only to U.S.
government scientific program managers on the Realization Report
distribution list because the workshop attendees were hard at work
completing this final version.
<P>

<a href="#[4.0]" NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  To alert readers who may be interested in this Special
Section of IEEE CG&A, the following is a list of the papers and authors:
<P>

Research Issues in Scientific Visualization (Introduction)
<P>

<PRE>
  Larry Rosenblum, ONR European Office
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Research Issues in Volume Visualization
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Arie Kaufman, SUNY Stony Brook, USA
  Karl Heinz Hoehne, University Hospital Eppendorf, Germany
  Wolfgang Krueger, Center for Math. and Computer Science, Germany
  Larry Rosenblum, ONR European Office, UK
  Peter Schroeder, Princeton University, USA / GMD, Germany
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Research Issues in Perception and User Interfaces
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Jose Encarnacao, Fraunhofer Inst. for Computer Graphics, Germany
  Jim Foley, Georgia Institute of Technology, USA
  Steve Bryson, NASA/Ames Research Center, USA
  Steve Feiner, Columbia University, USA
  Nahum Gershon, MITRE, USA
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Research Issues in the Visualization of Large Data Sets
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Gregory Nielson, Arizona State University, USA
  Pere Brunet, Polytechnical Univ. of Catalonia, Spain
  Marcus Gross, Computer Graphics Center, Germany
  Hans Hagen, University of Kaiserslautern, Germany
  Stanislav Klimenko, Inst. for High Energy Physics, Russia
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Research Issues in the Foundations of Visualization
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Phillip Robertson, CSIRO, Australia
  Rae Earnshaw, University of Leeds, UK
  Daniel Thalmann, Swiss Federal Inst. of Technology, Switzerland
  Michel Grave, ONERA-DMI, France
  Julian Gallop, Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, UK
  Eric De Jong, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, USA
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Research Issues in Vector and Tensor Fields
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Lambertus Hesselink, Stanford University, USA
  Frits Post, Delft University of Technology, The Netherlands
  Jarke van Wijk, Netherlands Energy Research Found., The Netherlands
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Research Issues in Modeling Complex Object Shapes
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Tosiyasu Kunii, University of Aizu, Japan
  Yoshihisa Shinagawa, University of Tokyo, Japan
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Research Issues in Model-based Visualization of Complex Data
</PRE>

<PRE>
  Jarek Rossignac, IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, USA
  Miroslav Novak, Kingston University, UK
</PRE>

<a href="#[1.0]" NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  Thanks go to all Workshop attendees for their hard work in
generating this Special Section.  The help of the Workshop
Organizing Committee (Rae Earnshaw, Jose Encarnacao, Hans Hagen,
Arie Kaufman, Stas Klimenko, Wolfgang Kruger, Greg Nielson, and
Frits Post) is gratefully acknowledged as is the outstanding effort
of Martin Goebel of the Fraunhofer Institute for Computer Graphics
in handling local arrangements and organizational matters.
<P>

