<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 2</Title>
<NEXTID=3>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 2</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]"> Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]"> Background on the University of Leeds</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]"> Visualization Support and Projects</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]"> The GRASPARC Project</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  Abstract:  The University of Leeds is actively supporting
its own researchers with scientific visualization methodology, as
well as in coordination and cooperation within the British higher
education system.  Visualization research at Leeds primarily
focuses on both developing toolsets for scientists and
interdisciplinary research with scientists and engineers from
across the university.  The GRASPARC project is developing methods
for the interactive steering of numerical computations.
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  Some 90 years old, the University of Leeds serves 12,000
students, soon to rise to 16,000.  The University has several
computing facilities and a range of computers to support both
educational and research functions. There is an Amdahl 5860, but
the University is currently updating its research facilities using
Silicon Graphics and there are also a large number of Sun
workstations.  Twenty IBM-compatible clusters with servers form the
nucleus of undergraduate computing facilities.  Two Silicon
Graphics 8 processor power series serve as high-end computers for
the research staff.  A recent agreement with Silicon Graphics has
provided 70 SGI workstations for the research facility at low cost.
<P>

The University is also a heavy user of AVS (Advanced Visualization
Systems) data visualization software.  AVS is a modular system that
allows users to utilize graphical cues to link AVS-provided and/or
user generated modules.  The result is a visualization pipeline
that begins with the data set and ends with a rendered display.
The development of AVS and ApE, a similar product from the Ohio
State Supercomputer Center, were significant breakthroughs in
providing scientists with usable and powerful desktop tools.
Several other corporations now offer similar products.  The
Combined Higher Education Software TEam (CHEST), based at the Univ.
of Bath, acts as a 'broker' to make deals for British university
participants; products such as AVS are thus made available on
significantly more favorable terms than an individual institution
could obtain.  British universities and research institutions
appear to maintain closer coordination in both equipment and
research than one finds in the U.S.
<P>

The Computer Studies Dept. at Leeds consists of 45 persons, divided
roughly equally between computer science, artificial intelligence,
and information systems. British universities are being encouraged
to develop computer-based teaching materials.  This has led to a
push in multimedia research and development, and Leeds is currently
recruiting several multimedia researchers for the Computer Studies
Dept.
<P>

An active Computer Services Group, some 60 persons strong, provides
university-wide support.  An unusual asset of the Univerity, with
which the Group has close ties, is a full TV production studio that
does collaborative work with industry and government.  On the day
of my visit they were conducting a course for junior diplomats on
how to be interviewed.  A trained TV interviewer would ask tough
questions of them, and the results played back to help them better
their performance.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  Rae Earnshaw, a pioneer in computer graphics algorithms and
prolific author/editor of books on computer graphics (including two
recent ones on scientific visualization), heads the Graphics Group
within the Computer Services Group.  A university-wide, 100-
researchers strong Visualization Group has been formed to implement
visualization within various domain fields.  This group's thrust is
to support visualization across the University and assist
scientists in integrating visualization within their work.  A
recent change to project-oriented funding has assisted the group's
ability to "sign up" scientists.  Obviously, I could see only a
small sampling of this effort.
<P>

Dr. Tim David was using Wavefront Technologies' Data Visualizer
software toolkit to analyse thermally driven fluid flow.  He was
integrating the visualization process to in-house developed flow
code.  As has been seen across many scientific disciplines, the use
of volumetric techniques, in this case examining isosurfaces as
planar cross-sections of 3D volumes, produces dramatic knowledge
benefits for scientists whose previous tools had been contour plots
and other 2D tools.  Particle flow could also be represented using
"tracers" and the two techniques mixed.  Dr. David was pleased that
he could obtain effective visualizations using the Data Visualizer
with minimal effort on his part.  It illustrated the progress made
toward good desktop visualization over the past five years.  A
half-decade ago generating these displays would have required man-
years of programming effort.  However, his current research on
blood flow through the heart also shows the limitations of current
desktop technology.  He noted that for this application the desktop
displays discussed above were not adequate.   3D, time-varying
displays are needed.  Fluid flow representation in 3D is a leading-
edge visualization research topic.  ("Visualizing Vector Field
Topology in Fluid Flows" by James Helman and Lambertus Hesselink of
Stanford University from the May 1991 visualization issue IEEE
Computer Graphics and Applications (CG&A) will receive the CG&A
best paper award for 1991 at the IEEE Visualization '92
Conference).
<P>

Several visualization research projects are underway at Leeds.
Volume rendering, which permits seeing within a displayed volume
using transparency, has become a key 3D display methodology for
much of science.  In medical imaging it is often useful to
integrate volume rendering with traditional polygon methods, so
that one might have planes or surfaces visible within the volume.
Research at Leeds is extending the algorithms developed by Marc
Levoy at UNC and Stanford in speed and power.
<P>

A new, joint project between Leeds and the University of Manchester
will examine timing issues for remote visualization, i.e. when a
simulation process is run on one host and the results monitored by
a second host in a remote location via a network connection.  Three
levels of data abstraction will be examined: (1) scientific data
where the immediate results of the simulation process are
transmitted to the monitor process which is then responsible for
the graphics representation;  (2) graphical data where the
simulation process is augmented to also construct the abstract
graphical representation to the monitor process for rendering; and
(3) image data where the rendered picture is sent over the network
for display.  Several levels of networked links between the hosts
will be examined as well.  Many methods for remote display of data
have been developed in recent years.  A well-done analysis of the
timing and issues involved in these different approaches will place
such research on a firmer footing.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  The GRASPARC (Graphical environment for supporting parallel
computing) project is a software development effort in
visualization designed to produce an integrated environment that
can support not only numerics, graphics, and data management, but
also heterogeneous and distributed environments.  The stated aim of
the project is ".. to improve the interaction between the scientist
and the parallel computer through the development of interactive
visualization software, the exploitation of parallelism being
essential to ensure the user can work freely without the
'traditional wait' for either a computation to complete or an image
to be displayed" [1].  The project is a three year (17 man-year)
collaborative project funded jointly by the UK Department of Trade
and Industry and the Science and Engineering Research Council
(SERC).  The partners are NAG Ltd., the University of Leeds (School
of Computer Studies) and Quintek Ltd.
<P>

The primary work thus far has been to design a data base structure
that better supports the interactive steering of numerical
computations.  The system utilizes a "history tree" that includes
various branches taken when an investigator alters the computation
interactively.  A sample interaction, taken from a case study using
GRASPARC, would be to modify areas of a mesh where calculations are
seen (by examining the graphical overlay on the mesh) to be
inadequately modeled.  Using a mouse, the area is defined and the
solution recalculated.  The program's goal is also to assure that
GRASPARC takes advantage of developments in parallel hardware.
<P>

[Note:  With the current economic climate in Britain, research
grants from SERC and similar British funding agencies are
increasingly dependent upon cooperative research proposals between
universities and industry.  Several UK researchers have expressed
concern about the future of "pure" research in the UK.]
-------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>

[1] GRASPARC, An Overview of the Project.  For the information of
the attendees of the Open Workshop 10 June 1992 at the Department
of Trade and Industry, London.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact information:</b>
   Prof. Rae Earnshaw
   Centre for Computer Studies
   University of Leeds
   Leeds LS2 9JT, UK
   R.A.Earnshaw@leeds.ac.uk
</PRE>
<P>

<hr>
