<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 4</Title>
<NEXTID=5>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 4</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]"> Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]"> The High Performance Computing and Communication (HPCC) Initiative</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]"> Recent Events in HPCC</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]"> Summary</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a> Abstract:  The keynote address at the IEEE Visualization 92
Conference [see The <a href="rosenblum.003.html">REALIZATION REPORT #3</a>] in Boston,
Oct. 1992, was given by Dr. Eugene Wong of the White House Office
of Science and Technology Policy.  He discussed the formation,
start-up, focus, and philosophy of the High-Performance Computing
Initiative.  Because of the high interest in HPCC, I am providing
a report on his talk.
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a> The keynote address "High Performance Computing and
Communication (HPCC)" at the IEEE Visualization 92 Conference in
Boston, Oct. 21-23, was presented by Dr. Eugene Wong.  Dr. Wong is
Associate Director for Industrial Technology in the White House
Office of Science and Technology Policy (OSTP).  Previously, he was
a Professor of Computer Science at U.C. Berkeley and a founder of
Ingress Corp.  He discussed funding, the principal agencies, the
major components of the program, and the significant goals and
objectives.  Dr. Wong stressed that HPCC, as with other
Presidential Initiatives, emphasizes an underlying strategy.  HPCC
seeks to achieve a unification between business and scientific
computing, technology and applications, and computing and
communications.  He noted that visualization is a key topic that
will play a major role in the success of HPCC while at the same
time being influenced and modified by other aspects of HPCC
achievements.
<P>

OSTP focuses on life sciences, physical sciences, industrial
technology, and industrial policy.  They support Cabinet Councils,
the President's Council of Advisors for Science and Technology
(PCAST), and the Federal Coord. Council for Science, Engineering
and Technology (FCCSET).  Presidential Initiatives in science and
technology (S&T) are:
<P>

<PRE>
     FY 91:    Global Change
     FY 92:    Mathematics and Science Education
               HPCC
     FY 93:    Advanced Materials
               Biotechnology
     FY 94:    Manufacturing
</PRE>

The S&T program seeks knowledge of general truths, the means to
sustain and improve human life, and an appropriate government role
in supporting science, producing technology, and maximizing
benefit.
<P>

HPCC was expected to be an FY 91 start-up program; it took an extra
year, according to Dr. Wong, to assemble the appropriate political
consensus and focus (a 1989 OSTP Report initiated the effort).  It
has been called "one of the finest science and technology programs
government ever launched."  HPCC seeks to push technology to the
limit in speed, reliability, usability, and capacity.  It divides
into:
<P>

<PRE>
	1.   Systems        --        Hardware and Software
</PRE>
	2.   Applications   --        Grand Challenges
	3.   Networking     --        National Research & Educ. Network (NREN)
	4.   Basic Research and Human Resources
<P>

Dr. Wong called data visualization the "greatest symbiotic
relationship" with HPCC of all computer science topics.  He noted
that "HPCC makes visualization possible; visualization makes HPCC
usable."  He also noted the role of visualization in other
Presidential Initiatives:
<P>

<PRE>
     Global Change       --   Data Rendering
     Math & Sci. Education -- Virtual Experiments (simulated
                              experiments for education)
     Advanced Materials  --   Molecular synthesis
     Biotechnology       --   Drug design/DNA research
     Manufacturing       --   Product and Process Design
</PRE>

Dr. Wong used a Boeing production system, in which an electronic
"man" crawls into spaces within a computer generated model of an
airplane design for validation, as an example of how visualization
technology is becoming increasingly critical to the manufacturing
process.
<P>

Dr. Wong discussed HPCC's funding to date:
<P>

<PRE>
                    proposed            actual
     FY 92           638 M              655 M
     FY 93           789 M              718 M (house); 769 M (sen.)
     FY 94           956 M
     FY 95          1087 M
     FY 96          1202 M
</PRE>

In 1992 the program was funded above the proposed level; 1993 will
see a shortfall with the burden to fall most heavily on NSF.
<P>

Dr. Wong spoke of the importance of strategy (for HPCC a strategic
element was to push networking as an enabling technology).  He
suggested the chain:
<P>

<PRE>
     vision --->  strategy  --->  reality
</PRE>

He noted conflict between cultures at several stages:
<P>

<PRE>
          science vs. commercial
          application vs. technology
          scalable vs. modular systems
</PRE>

Scalable systems, such as highly parallel computers, play a large,
underlying role.  Dr. Wong pointed out that parallelism had
produced speedup factors of the order of 1000 in fields such as
wave mechanics and structural mechanics when measured against a
normalized metric.
<P>

Dr. Wong noted that applications have, until recently, come
primarily from weapons laboratories, but that this is now changing
rapidly.  He also remarked that Grand Challenges have the largest
budget within HPCC.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a> He concluded with highlights of recent events:
<P>

<PRE>
 -- HPCC Act of 1991 (credit to Sen. Gore)
      "a good example of bipartisanship producing good legislation"
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- Progress
      - Scalable systems delivered.
      - NREN (interim) traffic doubled and growing super-
           exponentially which will result in cultural
           changes of an unpredictable nature.
      - Grand Challenge Applications started
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- Catalytic effects on the entire industry
      CSPP: CEO's from the 12 largest computer companies form group
      to look at industry.  Results include a "peace pact" with the
      semi-conductor industry on trade issues with Japan and an
      examination of HPCC.  The examination of HPCC by CSPP was
      largely supportive, but with some criticism.
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- CSPP suggested management changes.  In response, within the last
      month, a National Coordinator Office for HPCC has been
      established at NIH.  The Director will be:
</PRE>

<PRE>
           Donald A.B. Lindberg, M.D.
           Director, Nat. Library of Medicine
           NIH
</PRE>

<PRE>
      Dr. Lindberg will also chair the FCCSET committee.  The
      functions of this office are program coordination, policy
      formulation, establishing a single point of contact, and
      providing institutional continuity.  The National Coordinator
      Office will continue to be located at NIH.
</PRE>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a> Summary:  Much of Dr. Wong's talk contained materials
available in previously published synopses of the HPCC initiative.
Nonetheless, it was quite interesting to hear the viewpoints of one
so closely associated with the initiative.  The point that an early
establishment of strategy was inherent in HPCC's generation and
early success was a recurring theme.  A second theme was the
symbiotic relationship between data visualization and HPCC sub-
areas.  Although the smallest of the presidential initiatives, it
has had a catalytic effect, according to Dr. Wong, because it has
been well focused.  The establishment of a National Coordinator
Office, in response to the CSPP criticisms, was news for many of us
in the audience.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

