<HTML>

<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 7</Title>
<NEXTID=8>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 7</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

The following report has been prepared by Prof. Greg Nielson of
Arizona State University.  Prof. Nielson is a leader in CAGD (and
scientific visualization) research, sitting on the editorial boards
of numerous journals.  Responsibility for any errors that may have
occurred during a minor reformatting is mine.
<P>

<PRE>
                                   --  Larry Rosenblum
</PRE>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Modeling and Visualization with Implicit Surfaces</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Topological Design of Sculptured Surfaces</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Embracing CAGD</a><br>
<b>6.0  </b><a href="#[6.0]">  Barycentric Coordinates for Convex Polytopes</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a> The Freeform Curves and Surfaces '92 meeting was held at the
Mathematical Research Institute Oberwolfach in June 1992.  It is an
international, invitation-only event for presenting recent advances
in Computer-Aided Geometric Design (CAGD).  CAGD is, of course, a
critical topic for manufacturing design.  This report presents some
highlights of Freeform Curves and Surfaces '92.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Gregory M. Nielson
   Computer Science and Engineering
   Arizona State University
   Tempe, Arizona 85287-5406
   nielson@asuvax.eas.asu.edu
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a> The Mathematisches Forschungsinstitut Oberwolfach was the
site for the "Freiformkurven und Freiformflaachen" meeting held
June 14-20, 1992.  Located in the Black Forest village of
Oberwolfach-Walke, Germany, the institute receives support from the
Volkswagen Foundation.  This allows very reasonable fees to be
charged to the attendees.  The facility is self-contained with
dormitory space and family style dining which greatly enhances
contact between the participants. The attendees for this meeting
consisted of people working in the area of Computer-Aided Geometric
Design (CAGD).  The area of CAGD emerged in the early 1970's and
since that time has grown into a vital and active area of study and
research.  Today it enjoys the support typically accorded any
scientific discipline:  workshops, seminars, textbooks, and
journals.  Much of CAGD is concerned with the development of the
science and technology for the computer-aided design, analysis, and
production of 3D objects such as cars, airplanes, and telephones.
This meeting was the fifth in a series of workshop/conferences on
CAGD held at Oberwolfach, with the first having been held in 1982.
Participation at Oberwolfach meetings is by invitation only and
these invitations are highly regarded in the scientific community.
This generally leads to very high quality talks on the latest and
best research.  The total attendance was about 60, of which 40 gave
presentations on recent research results.  The attendees were
primarily from Europe and the U.S.  Active research groups in CAGD
from the U.S. are located at Arizona State University, RPI,
University of Washington, University of Utah, Rice University,
Boeing in Seattle, and General Motors in Warren.  Representatives
from each of these groups were in attendance.  The active European
groups who were represented at this workshop are located at
University of Kaiserlautern, University of Stuttgart, Technische
Hochschule Darmstadt, Technische Universitat Braunschweig,
University of Oslo, Brunel University and University of Catalanya.
<P>

Rather than report on all the presentations, I have picked a subset
in the hope that my selection and comments will convey a sense of
what occurred at the meeting in a more compact and easily obtained
manner.  A list of abstracts is available from Institute Office,
Mathematisches Forschungsinstitut, Oberwolfach, Albertstrasse 24,
D-7800 Freiburg/Breisgau, Germany.
<P>

And now for comments on the four selected talks:
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  Modelling and visualization with implicit surfaces, Wolfgang
Dahmen, RWTH Aachen
<P>

Throughout the development of CAGD there have been two distinct
approaches to representing surfaces in 3D space: 1) Parametric
methods with a representation of the form (X(u,v), Y(u,v), Z(u,v))
which maps a two dimensional domain containing (u,v) to 3D space
and 2) Implicit methods which define a surface as a set of points
{(X, Y, Z) such that F(X,Y,Z) = 0}.  The parametric approach is
associated with spline functions and has been quite successful for
the general representation and design of free-form surfaces.  The
implicit approach is philosophically more closely related to the
concepts of Constructive Solid Geometry (CSG) and Solid Modeling.
<P>

Both approaches have long lists of pros and cons.  One of the most
detracting aspects of the implicit approach is the lack of
techniques for designing free-form surfaces.  Over the years there
have been some valiant attempts, but there are no real successes to
date.  This presentation describes the most recent attempt.  The
work is encouraging and interesting.  The authors develop
techniques for matching user specified normals and positions to
points of a triangulated net in 3D space.  They use implicit
patches which have algebraic defining functions of degree 3.  Some
rather impressive images were shown.  I believe this is the first
public announcement of these results and I look forward to seeing
future reports on this research.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a> Topological design of sculptured surfaces, Alyn Rockwood,
Arizona State University
<P>

The genus of an object reveals the number of holes that it has.  A
sphere has genus zero and a donut has genus one.  The genus is a
fundamentally important topological property of an object which
should be consistent with any mathematical representation.  For
example, the genus of a mathematical model of the surface of a
human skull should be the same as the skull it is attempting to
model.  Often, many topological properties are taken as by products
in the design and representation process.  This is not the case
here.  Rockwell makes the point that topology is primal geometry
and reports on a new surface design method based on a "marked"
polygon.  The marked polygon captures the topology of the mappings
from a polygon to the sculptured surface.  Three different
techniques for obtaining a parametric map of a surface with
predescribed genus are given.  One of the most interesting examples
is the mapping of the hyperdisk to a double torus.
<P>

The whole character of this work is very interesting, from the
involvement of an actual sculptor (Helaman Ferguson) with real
machined works of art to the novel and intriguing use of geometry
and topology.  I suspect we will see more on this in the future.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  Embracing CAGD - constraints on industrial application as
seen by the German automotive industry, Werner Dankwort, BMW,
Reinhold Klass, Mercedes Benz, Burkard Woerdenweber, Hella
<P>

A rather unique session was held one evening after dinner.  Werner
Dankwort (BMW), Reinhold Klass (Mercedes Benz), and Burkard
Woerdenweber (Hella - a German company that produces automobile
head lamps) gave an informal presentation on the current usage of
CAGD techniques and methodology in their respective companies.
Both Klass and Dankwort have given presentations at all four
previous meetings.  Thus, for most of the attendees their material
was incremental and was perceived as a current update about ongoing
projects.  In addition to their own research and development
projects, for many years both Klass and Dankwort have been actively
involved in the establishment of standards for the description and
distribution of geometric data.  This seems to get more attention
in Europe than the rest of the world.  They take this whole problem
much more seriously than most.  I think that most people consider
the problem of standards as being an important topic that should be
dealt with, but it is not a heavy weight research problem.  As a
result, most are not really very interested.
<P>

One interesting feature of this presentation was a one page sheet
of problems that the presenters felt needed attention by this
scientific community   One person jokingly asked if they would be
willing to issue a research contract based on these problems.  The
audience laughed and the presenters were silent.
<P>

<PRE>
     Here are the problems that were presented:
</PRE>

<PRE>
 problem 1: (application - digitizing, returning FEM data) edge
            detection from scattered point data
 problem 2: (application - digitizing, returning FEM data) surface
            approximation from scattered point/normal data
 problem 3: (application - "shape preserving" surface generation)
            specific - trimmed surface for corner blend (underlying
            surface exceeds corner blend for milling purposes)
            general - filling n-sided patch with trimmed surface
            maintaining edge conditions (epsilon-GCn condition)
 problem 4: (application - "shape preserving" surface generation)
            smooth cross-edge connection between trimmed surfaces
            (epsilon-GCn condition)
 problem 5: (application - "shape preserving surface modification)
            modelling techniques for b-rep. shells
 problem 6: (application - thick plates, milling) offsets of b-rep.
            shells
 problem 7: (application - thick plates, milling) rational offset
            surfaces
</PRE>

<a NAME="[6.0]"><b>[6.0]</b></a>   Barycentric coordinates for convex polytopes, Joe Warren,
Rice University and Tony DeRose, University of Washington.
<P>

Bernstein polynomials have been important from the very beginning
of CAGD.  The parametric versions of these polynomials are called
Bezier curves in CAGD and can be represented as Sum(i = 0, n) Bi
C(n,i) t^i(1-t)^n-i, where the point in 3D space, Bi, is called a
control point and is used to shape the curve.  The notation C(n,i)
is used for the combination of n taken i at a time.  The concept of
a Bezier curve is of theoretical interest and practical value.
Generalizing from one variable to a bivariate domain leads to
methods for surface representation and design.  Generalizing to
volume domains gives rise to techniques for animation and
deformation (morphing) of 3D objects.  In this presentation, the
authors are interested in generalizing to a general convex polytope
domain.  The basis functions Bi(t) = C(n,i)t^i(1-t)^(n-i) can be
obtained from the binomial expansion [ t + (1-t)]^n = t^n + ... +
C(n,i)t^i(1-t)^(n-i) + ...  + (1-t)^n.  The quantities t and (1-t)
can be viewed as the barycentric coordinates of an arbitrary point
in the domain.  This observation is the key idea to their approach
and so all that is needed is a representation of barycentric
coordinates for convex polytopes.  The authors develop a nice
representation based upon some very reasonable definitions and
assumptions.  Within certain restrictions, they show that this
representation is unique.  Several examples are discussed.  We
should also point out that these barycentric coordinate
representations are closely related to nodal functions used in the
finite element method (FEM).  The results of this work could lead
to ideas for improved techniques for solving PDE's over convex
polytopes.  It is a starting point.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

