<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 8</Title>
<NEXTID=9>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 8</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Visual Simulations and Parallel Computing</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Computer Vision</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Virtual Reality</a><br>
<b>6.0  </b><a href="#[6.0]">  Remarks</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  The Physics and Electronics Laboratory (FEL) of the
Netherlands Organization for Applied Scientific Research (TNO)
performs research in observation systems, information technology
and telecommunication systems (IT & Telecom), training and
simulation (T&S), and support decisions.  This report discusses
computer science research at FEL's Training and Simulation Division
in visual systems, high performance computing hardware, computer
vision for scene reconstruction, and virtual reality (virtual
environments).
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Dr. G. J. Jense
   TNO Physics and Electronics Laboratory
   Oude Waalsdorperwed 63
   P.O. Box 96864
   2509 JG The Hague
   The Netherlands
   email: hans.jense@fel.tno.nl
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  Unlike the U.S., The Netherlands does not have research
organizations directly under their Defense Department.  Instead,
research is performed at contact laboratories similar to the U.S.
Department of Energy research system (Los Alamos, Livermore, etc.).
This research, along with civilian sponsored research, is performed
in the 5,000 person TNO, spread over some 25 different
laboratories.  TNO receives about half of its funding from the
government and the remainder from contracts with industry and other
funding organizations.  Three of the larger laboratories within TNO
are FEL, PML (chemical research) and IZF (human aspects of
perception research).  The mission of TNO defense research is to
support the three armed forces with applied R&D and to transfer TNO
R&D technology to industry.
<P>

FEL's divisions and their functions are:
<P>

<PRE>
     Observation Systems ---> pure physics and sensor design
     IT & Telecom        ---> data processing for sensor systems
     T&S                 ---> computer science R&D
     Policy Support      ---> policy studies including war games
</PRE>

FEL has an annual turnover of 70.5M fl. ($ 42M) of which more than
half represents personnel costs.  Within T&S is the 25 member High
Performance Computing (HPC) Group.  This group focuses on visual
simulation, machine vision, autonomous systems, and a recently
started effort in virtual reality.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  The visual simulation effort is 5 years old.  The first
simulator is a trainer for firing a stinger missile at an incoming
aircraft.  Picture generation is performed by projecting the
scenery onto a large dome.  The system used an in-house developed,
20 processor transputer system and was delivered to the sponsor in
1991. The group's second system is an anti-aircraft, anti-armor
tank simulator.  The simulator allows looking in all directions but
the tank does not move.  Background images are precomputed and
integrated with target information.  The computer hardware is an
in-house developed 120 transputer system.
<P>

A new prototype simulator processes both objects and background
with unrestricted movements and enhanced realism.  This system uses
10 to 100 Intel I860 processors.  The graphics pipeline is
parallelized by assigning processors to computing vertical scan
lines.  Horizontal scan lines are avoided because typical
simulation images have known horizontal coherence (sky, trees,
etc.).  Thus, the processing load would likely be unbalanced.  A
more typical parallelization approach has been to assign processors
to a 2D area of the screen.  Comparisons will be run to validate
the parallel scanline method.
<P>

Each processor board of this new system contains one T805
transputer for control and two Intel I860 processors for
calculation.  Each processor has its own memory bank for storage of
data and programming.  There is no shared memory.  The processors
communicate via FIFO channels.  It has been tested with 4, 8, and
12 processors.  Data is exchanged using two 32-bit wide busses for
each board with claimed data throughput rates of up to 100 Mb/sec.
A host computer is required to start the system and control it at
run time.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  The machine vision effort I saw focused on vision for
autonomous and semi-autonomous systems.  The Teleman UKIS
(Universal Knowledge-based Imaging System) research program of the
European Atomic Energy Community is funding this effort.  The
program's goal is to develop methods for remote handling in
hazardous or disordered nuclear environments.  The system seeks to
utilize and fuse data from a laser rangefinder, a stereo vision
camera, and an ultrasonic imaging systems.  Equipment includes a
Dornier laser range camera and a Tecnomare stereo vision camera.
The Ultrasonic imaging and 2D modeling are being performed at a
different TNO laboratory.  FEL's research to date has been to
develop methods for scene and shape recognition using laser
rangefinder data.  The Dornier laser range finding device has a 32
deg by 64 deg field of view, an accuracy of 3 cm, and a 4 to 8 m
range.  The number of elements is 64 by 128 and the update rate is
1 scan/sec.
<P>

The range images were polygonalized by generating normals, growing
regions, and extracting planar regions.  The normal generation
includes modifying normals that are incorrect due to measurement
error or discontinuities (i.e. measurements from the edges of an
object).  An algorithm examines the surrounding normals and uses
them to assess the accuracy of (and correct if necessary) the given
normal.  Planar regions are then generated by using thresholds that
limit the angular variations of the normals and the distance from
the measured point to the proposed plane.  Algorithms that compare
the behavior of normals on planar segments for a conjectured larger
object have been used to successfully identify primitive objects
such as spheres, cylinders, and cubes.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  Virtual reality (VR) research centers on two problems driven
by other FEL research.  Telepresence is a potentially valuable tool
for (semi-) autonomous vehicle applications while VR's role in
simulations is more proven.  The stinger missile simulator (see
3.0) was developed and fabricated at a cost of 12M fl. ($6.7M); FEL
estimates a VR version could be constructed for one tenth the cost.
For VR development FEL is using Division Ltd.'s (U.K.) PROVision
transputer-based hardware and dVS software.  They use a Virtual
Research head mounted display and Polheumus magnetic sensors for
movement tracking, both in the head mounted display and in the
Division Ltd. mouse (which they use instead of a data glove).  The
LED display is 320 by 200.
<P>

Two applications are implemented, although improvements are
ongoing.  The first is a simulation of an astronaut trying to
maneuver around a space station.  The head-mounted display shows
the space station and a pair of thrusters, one for moving forward
and one for reverse.  The goal is to maneuver into the bay of the
space station and pick up an object.  It is based on a real
training exercise.  As usual, the first thing one does after
entering the virtual space is to try to fly through walls and
otherwise test the systems limits.  FEL has a collision detection
algorithm but has not yet implemented actions when collisions
occur.  So I was able to fly right through the spaceship.  Even
using a novice mode that did not provide a rotation component to my
movement when I fired the thrusters, virtually entering the cargo
bay of the space station was actually quite difficult.
<P>

The second application was simulation training for firing a stinger
missile.  An object the size and shape of a stinger missile is
placed on ones shoulder (mercifully they didn't use their other one
that is the correct weight!).  Since a portion of the stinger
appears in the virtual environment, it contained both computer-
generated and real components.  The virtual space had simple
scenery, as higher resolution scene generation requires more
computer power.  Also shown are the two guides which must align
properly for firing the missile.  Sound ("beeps") is used to help
fix on the target and the mouse controls fire the missile.  This
was the first time I had a significant problem with parallax in a
VR system.  The movable guide, which had to align with one of four
lines on a lower guide depending on the direction of the incoming
aircraft, was constantly below the second guide.  It needed to be
above.  The problem turned out to be the closeness of the two
guides which are on the missile barrel to my eyes and the dual
magnetic sensors on the top and front of the helmet.  Generally,
calibration for the spatial difference of these two magnetic
sensors is not necessary.  Here, because of the closeness of the
objects of interest, it is.  FEL is currently developing
calibration for this problem.
<P>

FEL is experiencing the usual set of VR hardware issues.  These
include the need for greater computer power for scene rendering,
for higher resolution and contrast in the LCD's of the head mounted
display, and for higher accuracy and longer range from the magnetic
sensors.  Nonetheless, they have the benefit of applying VR to
interesting problems that are appropriate for the technology.  They
expect that transitioning to in-house developed parallel computers
will help improve the scene rendering.
<P>

<a NAME="[6.0]"><b>[6.0]</b></a>  Primarily because of its mission, FEL has initiated a VR
research program quite similar to a longer running one at Advanced
Robotics Research Limited in the U.K. (see <a href="rosenblum.005.html">REALIZATION REPORT #5</a>).
Both seek to develop a telepresence testbed for robotic
manipulation and much of the equipment is identical or similar.
FEL has the advantage of also having in-house simulation
applications which can be brought to fruition more quickly than
telepresence.  Simulation (VR) research will provide equipment and
expertise that can then be applied to telepresence.  As part of a
large research laboratory that places heavy emphasis in areas where
VR technology can be expected to produce advances, the FEL VR
effort may benefit from the long term funding telepresence
applications will require.
<P>

FEL has close ties with the Delft Technological University, having
hired both MS and PhD Students.  They have good ties with other
universities and research institutions in The Netherlands as well.
Perhaps because the country's small size, these liaisons appear to
be quite strong across all institutions I visited in The
Netherlands and the research seems to benefit.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

