<HTML>

<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 9</Title>
<NEXTID=10>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 9</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Behavioral Modeling and Animation</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Physical-Based modeling</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  The Virtual Wardrobe</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  Abstract:  Daniel Thalmann at the Swiss Federal Institute of
Technology in Lausanne and Nadia Thalmann at the University of
Geneva are a married couple whose joint work in computer-generated
animation has long been leading edge.  Their current research is
primarily in physical-based and behavioral modeling as it applies
to the human figure.  Examples include animating human facial
movements, human hair, movement by human figures, and clothing.
They are beginning to integrate virtual reality (VR) technology
into this research.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Nadia Thalmann
   Miralab-CUI
   24 rue General Dufour, CH-1211
   Geneva 4, Switzerland
   thalmann@uni2a.unige.ch
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The Thalmanns are well known in U.S. research circles,
having spent over a decade in Canada before returning to their
native Switzerland three years ago.  Daniel heads a laboratory at
the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology in Lausanne (EPFL), one
of two federally funded universities in Switzerland.  EPFL is
French speaking, while the Federal Institute in Zurich is German
speaking.  Nadia holds an equivalent position as head of the
MIRALAB at the University of Geneva.  Both are professors.  As
noted in earlier Realization Reports, the title Professor is
different in most of Europe than in the U.S.  By comparison, it is
more select than a full professorship in the U.S.
<P>

EPFL is a new university and its recently built and under
construction buildings are modern in style.  There are 3,000
engineering students, both graduate and undergraduate.  The EPFL
computer science department is very structured.  There are 13
"Laboratories" within the CS Department.  Each Lab gets one floor
of the CS building, has one full professor, 1/2 of a secretary, and
three to four full time researchers paid by the school.
<P>

In sharp contrast the Academy of Geneva was created in 1559 through
the efforts of John Calvin.  Theology was predominant until the end
of the 17th century.  The Academy then opened it's doors to the
physical and natural sciences and, even later, to law and
philosophy.  In 1873 it was raised to the status of University.
Today there are some 11,500 students and 650 professors.  Unlike
most U.S. campuses, Geneva has buildings throughout the city and no
central campus.
<P>

The Thalmann's research is largely joint and will be reported that
way here (however, each heads their own research team at their
respective universities).  For over a decade the main thrust has
been animation of the human figure.  Current efforts include facial
movements (e.g. mouth, eyebrows), human hair, human walking, and
fitting the human figure with clothing.  Human "synthetic"
animation is well known in computer graphics as a difficult
problem.  The Thalmann's research traces a thread in computer
graphics research.  At first they used geometric methods for
modeling.  To define a "character's" (or "actor's") path, a curve,
generally a spline, would be defined by a set of control points
which the path must contain.  This spline would then define a path
for the character to follow.  The mid 1980's saw a shift from this
approach to physical-based modeling.  Now a character would have
his motion determined by predefined forces such as gravity.  So a
character is pulled toward an object by a set of physical-based
forces acting on the scene (rather than moving along a precomputed
curve).  Obstacle avoidance is performed by instituting a repellant
force when the character gets "too close".
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  Much of the Thalmann's research still involves physical-
based modeling.  However, behavioral modeling is a growing area of
interest.  Here the actor's motions are defined in terms of
behavior and personality now becomes part of a character.  Movement
is performed using vision-based obstacle avoidance.  In the
research I saw, an octree was used to represent the division of 3D
space.  The scene is generated by using standard computer graphics
methodology and then accessing the Z-buffer data.  Since the Z-
buffer is used for hidden surface removal, a range estimate to all
visible objects is thus obtained.  This processing seems analogous
to assuming very high-resolution data from an error-free laser
rangefinder.  The goal is to introduce personality traits to a
character and then to automate the character's movements using
behavior-based modeling.
<P>

Another research effort involves the synthetic generation of human
emotions.  Muscles in the mouth are modeled by a set of polygons.
Using techniques derived from Sederberg's work, a set of free form
deformations is applied to create movements.  The free form
deformations apply to a lattice surrounding the mouth.  The lattice
can be thought of as comprising a surrounding parallelipiped.  The
object (the mouth) is considered flexible within the
parallelipiped.  Thus, a deformation applied to the lattice will
also deform the polygon vertices and thus produce mouth movements.
Because the lattice is regular and contains relatively few points,
it appears to be easier to simulate mouth movements by deforming
the lattice and mapping the deformation onto the mouth than to
deform the more complex set of polygons that represent the mouth
directly.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  Another project is producing a kinematic model of human
walking.  Physical-based modeling of foot motion in the walking
process is performed, but a second model of the foot is maintained
for fine-scale correction.  When physical-based modeling equations
are applied to the foot, portions of the foot tend to go below the
plane of the ground at certain stages of the motion process.  This
occurs even when complex equations involving many variables are
used.  Corrections are made to the second model by identifying
certain key points on the foot.  Constraints on the second model
evaluate these control points and prevent the foot from going below
the surface of the floor.  The result is a quite realistic
rendering of the walking process.
<P>

A final example of physically-based modeling is the "Fashion Show".
Here the object is to dress a character using physical-based
modeling.  The character can select from a wardrobe.  Clothes are
represented as planar polygons with seams and attaching
information.  Physical modeling creates forces on the seams so that
the panels deform in 3D about the body.  Collision detection
assures that an outward force is applied when the clothes and the
body are about to make contact.  Eventually, the system reaches
stability and the figure is dressed.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  The Thalmann's are currently investigating the integration
of VR to their applications.  To date they have done an
architectural walk through without collision detection.  Some
ability to "pick up" a virtual object has been developed.
Interface hardware includes VPL data gloves and headsets.  Two SGI
computers are used for rendering, one for each eye.  The Thalmann's
are also investigating the data glove as an interface device for
interacting with animation frames for key-framing as well as to
control physical-based modeling.
<P>

Proposed VR research directions are interesting and unusual.
Research has begun with the goal of developing a virtual wardrobe,
an extension of the fashion show described above.  VR will become
the interface to allow the user to dress him/herself in virtual
clothing.  This is a potentially worthwhile exploration of human
interaction in virtual space.  And the ramifications for the
fashion industry are self-evident!
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

