<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 10</Title>
<NEXTID=11>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 10</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Visualization Tools</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Distributed Visualization</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  Abstract:  The (French) National Office for the Study of
Aerospace Research (ONERA) is a large scientific institute whose
departments span physics, optics, and other disciplines in addition
to the obvious topic of fluid dynamics in support of aerospace
design.  This report describes the activities in the Visualization
Branch of the Computing Center.  Visualization activities include
both visualization support and RACE-sponsored research into
distributed visualization.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Michel Grave
   ONERA
   BP 72
   92322 Chantillon CEDEX, France
   grave@bora.inria.fr
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  ONERA is a 2,500 person scientific institute that performs
government and industry studies in support of aerospace technology.
ONERA includes seven centers and has some of Europe's largest wind
tunnels.  Sixty percent of ONERA's staff are situated at its main
research site in Chantillon, a few kilometers outside Paris.  Among
those located here are the members of the Computing Department.
This Department is divided into two parts:  a research branch whose
focus is parallel computing AI and a computing center which serves
as a central computing resource similar to that found at most large
laboratories.  The research group uses Intel i860 based processors
and a newly installed Paragon for investigation of parallel
algorithms for AI.  The Computer Group maintains ONERA's Cray Y-
MP4/128 computer with CDC front ends and provides user services,
networking support, etc.  Within this Group is a seven person
visualization section, headed by Michel Grave.  The Group has SGI
computers, a Pixar, a frame buffer from UltraNet, and an assortment
of X- and Tektronix terminals.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  Any visualization center in a large laboratory must support
software packages and products that assist users in a variety of
chores.  The visualization section provides support for both the
AVS and the IRIS Explorer modular visualization software packages
[<a href="rosenblum.002.html">REALIZATION REPORT #2</a> discusses AVS activities in England].
Other supported software packages include GKS, the NCSA XImage and
XDataSlice programs for 2D and 3D data analysis in an X-Windows
environment (Note: NCSA-HDF format is supported on the CRAY), the
UTAH RLE program for processing run length encoded data (including
operations such as color manipulation, histograms, and
transformations) on the Cray and UNIX workstations, and support for
the CGM (Computer Graphics Metafile) format.  A variety of in-house
packages are also supported.  The most interesting of these are
PART_3D and VIF.  These are fluid dynamics packages that are now
several years old; they appear roughly comparable to the NASA/Ames
packages of the same time period.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  The major research project of the group is a RACE II
(Research and development in Advanced Communications technology in
Europe) sponsored effort to examine distributed visualization.
There are some 10 partners, but the two major ones are ONERA and
the computing facility at the University of Stuttgart.  The goal is
to allow joint viewing of computation at remote sites.  The first
year's effort has been to start an evaluation that will quantify
distributed results, i.e. to determine what portion of the
visualization chain is best done on the Cray and what portion on
the workstation.  For this purpose the visualization pipeline is
taken to be:
<P>

<PRE>
  Simulation ---> Mapping ---> Rendering ---> Display ---> User
</PRE>

where the rendering stage has three steps:
<P>

<PRE>
     Transformation ---> Rendering ---> Rasterization
</PRE>

The first problem faced was how to make timing measurements in the
same units for different platforms.  Timing modules were developed
and successfully tested.  The Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM)
software from Oak Ridge National Lab. (U.S.) was used to emulate a
parallel mode on a workstation.  One result is that when the
software for distributed mode execution executes, there is a 20%
overhead even if the second machine is not used.
<P>

Test cases include both sequential and non-sequential applications.
The non-sequential case involved looped-data generation displayed
by isosurfaces.  Thus, there is competition for CPU time between
the modules and large data sets must be passed.  It was found that
the ratio Cray/Workstation (SGI) was application dependent.  The
ratio was high for simulations but low for isosurface generation
and rendering.  Results to date indicate that the visualization
computation should be performed on the Cray, although Grave
includes the caveat that this conclusion is application dependent.
For this computation the time for the graphics (isosurface
generation) was small compared to the application itself.  There is
a lot of CPU overhead in data duplication, and another conclusion
is that shared data space is needed in a distributed environment.
Future work will examine data communication issues required to help
solve this problem.  (A new U.K. effort to quantify distributed
data visualization was reported in <a href="rosenblum.002.html">REALIZATION REPORT #2</a>).
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

