<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 11</Title>
<NEXTID=12>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 11</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  The Peripheral Systems Laboratory (EPFL)</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  The Multimedia Laboratory (University of Geneva)</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  While visiting Nadia and Daniel Thalmann (see <a href="rosenblum.009.html">REALIZATION REPORT #9</a>) 
at the University of Geneva and the Swiss Federal Institute of
Technology in Lausanne (EPFL), I also stopped in at the Multimedia
Laboratory at the University of Geneva and the Peripheral Systems
Laboratory at EPFL.  This report describes some of the current
activities at these two laboratories.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contacts:</b>
   Prof. Roger Hersch                 Prof. Simon Gibbs
   Peripheral Systems Lab.            Multimedia Lab.
   EPFL                               Univ. of Geneva
   CH - 1015                          CH - 1211
   Lausanne, Switzerland              Geneva, Switzerland
   hersch@eldi.epfl.ch                simon@cui.unige.ch
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The Peripheral Systems Laboratory develops new software and
hardware technology for advanced displays, printing devices,
photocomposers, and information servers.  The Laboratory's focus is
improved printing capabilities including the use of outline
character generation and automatic hinting for improving the
readability of bilevel and grey-scale characters on displays and
printing devices.  This work has been extended to color printing,
including new dithering algorithms for avoiding Moire effects and
producing higher quality output images.  Research also involves
fabricating hardware for fast input/output using processor and disc
array technology with parallel access.
<P>

One hardware system was being developed to provide fast access to
images on disc arrays.  The goal is rapid browsing through these
images.  The system uses parallelism to provide high-speed access
to pixmapped data.  There are 8 discs with 1 Transputer assigned to
each disc for processing.  The 2D images being retrieved are about
1 mbtye in size.  The data retrieval rate is 3 mbytes/second.  The
bottleneck is data throughput.  The new Transputer chip, when
released, is expected to significantly improve the data rate.  This
is one of several projects I have visited in Europe that were "on
hold" awaiting the new Transputer.
<P>

Improving typographic fonts is the subject of ongoing algorithmic
research.  To produce the best looking characters at a given size
on a specific printer, non-linear operations must be applied to
parts of the character shape.  To obtain improvements, grid
fitting-rules called hints are added to the character description.
A character is represented topologically in order to identify key
characteristic points.  Hinting methods are developed that produce
a subpixel displacement that is applied to certain parts of the
outline.  These algorithms have been extended from bilevel to gray-
shaded characters.  The results offer noticeable improvements over
standard filtering methods and are valuable for situations where
reading small text is important.  Human factors testing is
currently being conducted to quantify the gains from perceptual
hinting.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  The Multimedia Laboratory had presented an interesting and
unusual multimedia project called the Virtual Museum at
Eurographics 92 (see <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>) and I stopped by to see
recent progress.  This project is the work of a five member
subgroup of the laboratory called the Object-Oriented Group.  The
Virtual Museum is part of a ten year ongoing effort to develop a
test framework for multimedia.  Research includes investigation of
timing issues for multimedia and methods for hiding hardware
dependencies from the user.  The application is distributed over
several machines.  A Next is used as the sound server, an SGI as
the render server, and a Sun as the application server.  An Amiga
2000/Video Toaster combination provides video recording.  Using a
spaceball, a user "walks through" the Virtual Museum.  The group
strives to develop tools for the flexible design of hardware and
software components with all equipment under computer control.
<P>

Current research includes techniques for media synchronization and
further development of models for inclusion in the Museum.
However, much of the current research is devoted to investigations
of data modeling (with a realization that eventually data bases
must be specifically designed for multimedia applications).  Time
based-media, including digital video and audio, require notions of
data flow, timing, temporal composition and synchronization.  These
concepts are not contained in conventional data models.  This work
extends previous efforts that have dealt primarily with text and
images.
<P>

The basic abstraction for time-based media modelling is "temporal
sequences" of media elements, where this term includes video
frames, musical notes, etc.  These sequences are proposed to occur
as concatenated groups called "streams".  A formal set of
mathematical mappings are proposed to develop a procedure for
processing these primitives.  The mappings then become the basis
for higher level operands that provide a formal foundation for data
modelling.  Existing data bases do not support these multimedia
data models and new data base architectures are required to provide
the building blocks for better multimedia.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

