<!DOCUMENTTYPE htmlplus>
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 12</Title>
<NEXTID=13>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 12</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Applications</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Fluid Flow Visualization</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Comments</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  The Netherlands Energy Research Foundation (ECN) carries out
research to develop "sustainable" energy supplies, where
sustainable means that the energy is produced without limiting the
options of future generations.  Within ECN a software engineering
and research group investigates how computer science can best be
applied to ECN problems.  This report focuses on the visualization
research of Dr. Jarke van Wijk within this group.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Dr. Jarke van Wijk
   Netherlands Energy Research Foundation ECN
   Technology
   P.O. Box 1
   1755 ZG Petten, The Netherlands
   vanwijk@ecn.nl
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The Netherlands Energy Research Foundation (ECN) is a 900
person research organization investigating current and future
energy requirements and solutions.  They hold that fossil fuels,
nuclear energy, and renewable energy sources (solar, wind, hydro,
and biomass) are the three constituents of the energy supply
system, but their ratio of use will change.  ECN believes future
developments will be driven by environmental issues.  They focus on
long term solutions.  Their energy research program is divided into
five categories:  fossil fuels (including environmental research),
renewable energy, radiation technology, nuclear energy, and energy
studies.  ECN was originally oriented to nuclear energy and they
have a nuclear reactor.
<P>

In addition to the five units described above, there is a 200
person technology service unit.  The technology unit includes
mechanical engineering and finite element modeling, networking,
computational engineering, and computational physics.  Also
included in this unit are a 15 member software engineering and
computer science research group.  This group performs research into
software engineering, knowledge-based engineering (including ESPRIT
funded projects), and a two person visualization effort that is led
by Dr. Jarke van Wijk.
<P>

Van Wijk has become, in effect, a one man visualization center for
the organization.  About half of his time is spent performing
visualization for clients (mostly non-ECN) and the remainder on
performing research into new computer graphics algorithms (and
interfaces) for visualization.  His work is done on a Silicon
Graphics computer.
<P>

ECN's 1991 budget was 149.5 million guilders ($ 83M) of which
about 40% comes from a government grant.  Over 60% of the budget
goes for personnel expenses.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  One visualization effort helped Heineken understand a
problem in factory automation.  The scuffing of the beer bottles
against each other as they proceed down the conveyer belt in the
factory limits the number of times a bottle can be used.  To gain
understanding, a physically-based model of the bottles traveling on
the conveyer belt was developed at Delft Technical University and
visualized by van Wijk.  The beer bottles on the conveyor are
modelled as discrete elements and are shown as circles.  Contacts
between the bottles are shown as lines, with a width proportional
to the contact force.  Input data at each step includes the
coordinates, velocity, and other quantities describing both the
bottle and the properties of the contact.  The model has been
successfully verified using real data.  Output displays have helped
gain an understanding of the places on the conveyor belt where the
damage is really occurring and potential solutions are being
investigated using the model.
<P>

A second visualization application, performed using ship-design
software from the Maritime Research Institute Netherlands (MARIN),
shows the dynamics of a ship in sea waves.  The calculation of the
dynamics is done in the frequency domain, using a ship-
characteristics-dependent spectral transfer function for the six
degrees of freedom.  The sea surface is described by a wave model
and the user can specify a wave spectrum interactively with
parameters such as wind force.  Interactive analysis and animation
tools illustrate the ship's motion through the waves.  Another
application developed novel visualization techniques to assist ECN
scientists in understanding the behavior of molten mixture of
potassium and lithium carbonate.  By creating a tube frame to
visualize the local structure, the convex hull of a selected ion is
isolated.  Examining the motion of the convex hull over time using
animation, one notices that the convex hull of different ions have
differing spatial characteristics (especially average size).  These
spatial differences help explain the bonding and rotational
behavior of the molecules.
<P>

The use of animation in these applications has led to an analysis
of the requirements for interactive animation ("steering") of such
applications.  User interface techniques include manipulation via
a control panel, direct manipulation of a time graph, and keyboard
accelerators.  The combined use of spatial and temporal views on
the data helps the location and analysis of areas and time
intervals of interest.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  Two-dimensional fluid flow was an important topic in the
1980's and those algorithms have now been incorporated in
commercial software.  Many users of fluid dynamics have recently
taken to using such tools (cf. the report on the work of Dr. Tim
David, University of Leeds in <a href="rosenblum.002.html">REALIZATION REPORT #2</a>; also Dr.
Arthur Mynett of Delft Hydraulics).  A recent addition to this 2D
work has been the development of an interesting technique called
"spot noise."  Spot noise is based on the repeated addition of
randomly positioned spots on a surface.  A stochastic texture is
thus produced.  The properties of the texture can be varied by
changing the properties of the spot, such as shape, size, and
direction.  If these properties are changed as a function of the
data, then structure appears in the texture which contains useful
information about the flow.
<P>

The seminal paper by James Hellman and Lambertus Hesselink of
Stanford in my special issue on data visualization of IEEE Computer
Graphics and Applications was awarded best paper of 1991 by that
journal for its extension of two-dimensional fluid visualization to
3D.  Representing 3D vector fields and 3D flow surfaces is now an
important research area.  The Netherlands' visualization research
community, esp. Dr. van Wijk and Dr. Frits Post of Delft Technical
University, are among a small group at the forefront.
<P>

A common technique in fluid flow visualization is the insertion of
particles into the flow.  A variety of techniques follow:  the
particle's time-dependent position can be animated, stream lines or
stream surfaces can be generated, etc.  Each technique helps
illuminate different characteristics of the flow field and the
selection of technique(s) is problem specific.  Older particle
rendering methods have generally treated the particle as a point.
Van Wijk has shown that advantages accrue if the particle is
treated as consisting of very small facet, with an associated
normal.  Due to the facet's small size, the shape is irrelevant but
the knowledge of the normal assists in the visualization process.
These "surface-particles" are generated by user-defined particle
sources that have geometric and time-related attributes.
<P>

The user interface allows for both continuous and discrete release
of the surface-particles into the flow.  The rendering pipeline is
taken to be: shading, transformation, filtering, and scan
conversion.  The aim is to achieve good quality at a reasonable
cost.  The latest additions to this work are modified Gaussian
filters for the prevention of spatial and temporal artifacts and a
new method for computing and compensating for the surface-
particle's opacity.  A paper presenting this research will appear
in the July '93 special issue of IEEE Computer Graphics and
Applications.
<P>

A second area of current research is producing a new method for the
generation of "stream surfaces".  A stream surface is the trace of
a curve (think of a continuous stream of particles forming a curve)
in the flow as time varies.  When a large number of streamlines is
required to gain understanding, stream surfaces offer better
insight into the structure of the flow field.  Hidden surface
elimination and shading can then be used to provide depth and
orientation cues.
<P>

One approach to stream surface generation is to use a polygonal
mesh that approximates the stream function.  However, deformations
by convergent flow, divergent flow, and shear flow cause
difficulties.  In this research, the stream surface is represented
as an implicit surface f(x)=C.  After the initial calculation of f,
a family of stream surfaces is generated by varying C.  The shapes
of the originating curves are defined by the value f at the
boundary.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a> This is one in a series of reports that cover visualization
research activities at several organizations in The Netherlands.
Fluid flow and its visualization is an important research component
in The Netherlands and these researchers appear to benefit from the
close ties they maintain.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

