<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 13</Title>
<NEXTID=14>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 13</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  A Fluid Flow Visualization Testbed</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  The Power Probe</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Volume & Hybrid Rendering</a><br>
<b>6.0  </b><a href="#[6.0]">  Remarks</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  For reasons that are obvious to anyone who has heard the
story of the little boy with his finger in the dike, fluid
(specifically water) flow is an emphasized research topic in The
Netherlands.  Working closely with industrial partners, the
computer graphics group at Delft University of Technology focuses
on research into the visualization of fluid flow from computational
fluid dynamics (CFD) simulations.  Applications are primarily on
water flow, which has some distinct problems when compared with
aerospace-oriented CFD visualization.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Dr. Frits Post
   Faculty of Technical Mathematics and Informatics
   Delft University of Technology
   Julianalaan 132
   2628 BL Delft, The Netherlands
   email: frits@duticg.tudelft.nl
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  One hundred fifty years old in 1992, Delft University of
Technology (TU Delft) is Holland's oldest and largest school of
engineering.  TU Delft has 12 faculties (departments) serving over
13,000 students.  One of these is the Faculty of Technical
Mathematics and Informatics where Informatics is defined as
Computer Science and Information Systems.  The computer science
research concentrates on software engineering, theoretical
informatics and operating systems, with a focus on the quality of
the ultimate information system and the speed with which it can be
constructed.  A second research area is "technical applications,"
including CAD/CAM, computer graphics, and knowledge-based systems.
The computer graphics research is headed by Prof. F. W. Jansen.
Dr. Frits Post leads the research effort in data visualization.
This effort focuses on the visualization of 3D vector fields with
an emphasis on visualizing 3D fluid flows using data from
computational fluid dynamics (CFD) numerical simulations.
<P>

The computer graphics group contains some 9 people, 4 in
visualization.  Several of these are PhD students (who in Holland
are typically salaried university employees).  A PhD takes four
years after achieving an engineering degree.  This is the first
university degree obtained in Holland but is roughly the equivalent
to a U.S. masters degree.  Only in the last decade has the
university developed a regular graduate student program.  Because
of the newness of these programs and the lack of "post-doc"
positions, there is some uncertainty as to the transition path from
a completed doctorate to an employed research position in
universities or industry.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  One ongoing research project at TU Delft is the development
of a testbed for fluid flow visualization.  This project is
partially funded by Delft Hydraulics.  The goal is to provide the
characteristics that one would like in a testbed: easy program
development and integration of new techniques as they arise,
programmer access at the source code level for the addition,
replacement, extension, or division of modules, minimum software
overhead for prototyping, good debugging facilities, and
artificially generated data with known characteristics for
evaluating new methodologies.
<P>

The testbed is currently used for development of visualization
techniques for turbulent flow. Methods are developed to represent
turbulent flow as a mean velocity field and a turbulence intensity
field. The turbulence intensity is used to generate perturbations
of the velocity field, resulting in fluctuations of particle
motion. This is visualized by animation of particle motion.  In
addition, the lifetime of particles can be dynamically adjusted,
and extra particles can be launched, depending on the local
characteristics of the field.  Very dynamic areas in the flow field
result in more particles being launched and these die quickly when
leaving the turbulent area.  Techniques that include the use of
color and particle traces provide an overview of the process.
Another useful recent testbed addition has been the development of
a new user interface.  This has provided point and click, sliding
knobs for parameter control, and other interfaces, including some
for data probing, that assist both the novice and sophisticated
user in better interaction with the testbed.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  The Power Probe, under development by a graduate student who
divides his time between TU Delft and The Netherlands Energy
Research Foundation ECN, is a data probing device designed
specifically for 3D fluid flow analysis.  The probing portion of
the program is straightforward.  A point is picked out in 3D space
by manipulating a mouse while the display contains a cursor
location that moves with planes parallel to the axes planes shown
as a visual aid.  Alternately, a user can type in specific
coordinates if known.  The innovative aspect of this work is the
association of a glyph (a geometrical object with information
encoded in the geometry or associated attributes such as color)
with the data point and a small surrounding region.  Components of
the local flow field are derived and encoded onto the glyph.  The
components are derived by a decomposition of the velocity gradient
tensor, calculated in a local coordinate frame, where one axis is
aligned with velocity direction.  This results in quantities such
as the curvature of the stream line through the probe point,
convergence, shear, and helicity (rotation component).  Each of
these quantities is associated with a specific part of the glyph.
<P>

The glyph is arrow shaped with disks and rings at the base, and the
components of the local flow are mapped onto the shapes of parts of
the glyph, and patterns on the surface of the glyph.  So the glyph
direction and length symbolizes velocity and magnitude of the
velocity field at the point selected by the Power Probe.  To
develop the Power Probe, TU Delft researchers designed a set of
graphical primitives that visualize the quantities in an
intuitively understandable form.  The probe is currently being
integrated with a 3D CFD data set for evaluating the potential of
these methods to assist the fluid dynamicist in obtaining improved
understanding.  Certain extensions of this concept to regions of
interest, instead of single points, appear promising and will be
the subject of future research.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  Another research topic is hybrid rendering algorithms.
Volume rendering has been a leading topic in scientific
visualization over the last 5 years.  Classical rendering methods
portray surfaces while volume rendering allows viewing into the
interior of objects or viewing nebulous objects such as clouds.  As
volume rendering algorithms have improved, interest has grown in
hybrid rendering which allow volume rendered scenes that contain
geometrical objects such as slice planes.
<P>

Hybrid rendering can be achieved by converting volume data into
geometrical format for rendering, by converting geometrical data
into voxelized format for rendering, or by rendering each type of
data separately.  In the latter case, algorithms are required that
effectively merge pixel buffers containing volumetric and geometric
components. TU Delft is investigating new methods for this last
type of hybrid rendering.  Environmental studies serves as an
example application area, such as the dispersion of pollutants in
sea water.
<P>

The H-buffer rendering system consists of a buffer for storing
results (the H-buffer), algorithms for writing data into the
buffer, and a means of taking objects in the H-buffer and
calculating the color of a pixel from the elements stored in the
buffer.  The H-buffer works as a multi-layered Z-buffer, so that
for polygons and lines, volume and opacity information is
maintained.  Polygons are rendered into the H-buffer by storing an
object for each pixel covered by the polygon.  The boundary of the
volume is also stored into the H- buffer.  This boundary can be any
bounding object, but typically is just the extent of the volume.
Finally, rays are cast into the volume to render the volumetric
data.  The H-buffer then contains an ordered list of lines,
polygons, and volumetric data with entry and exit positions into
the volume known.  Before an object is merged, a ray is cast from
the entry point up to the object.  The resulting opacity and color
along the sub-ray are merged with the current pixel color until the
process terminates.
<P>

<a NAME="[6.0]"><b>[6.0]</b></a>  We have noted in other reports that the visualization
community in The Netherlands maintains close ties.  Combining this
issue with the reports on ECN (<a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>), FEL-TNO
(<a href="rosenblum.008.html">REALIZATION REPORT #8</a>), and Delft Hydraulics (to appear) yields
the flavor visualization activities in The Netherlands.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

