<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 14</Title>
<NEXTID=15>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 14</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Neural Networks for Business Applications</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Distributed Systems Engineering Journal</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Annual JFIT Technical Conference - 23-24 March 1993</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Compound Semiconductor Advanced Technology Program</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  A large funder of information technology (IT) research and
development in the U.K. is the Joint Framework for Information
Technology (JFIT).  JFIT is a combination of the U.K. Science and
Engineering Council (SERC) and the Department of Trade and Industry
(DTI).  The following are selected IT items from JFIT publications.
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  NEURAL NETWORK TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER PROGRAM
<P>

The L. 5.75 million ($9 M), three-year Neural Computing Technology
Transfer program will have two main parts: (i) an awareness
campaign concerned with raising general business awareness of
neural computing, and (ii) a program of clubs concerned with
building application demonstrators.
<P>

Good progress has been made on implementing both parts of the
program.  Touche Ross Management Consultants have been appointed to
assist the DTI to plan and manage the awareness campaign.  Touche
Ross will lead a consortium of organizations that will provide the
necessary marketing, technical, organizational, and
representational skills needed for the campaign.  Planning of the
awareness campaign is well advanced toward the launch of an initial
program of activities in January 1993.
<P>

Following the competitive call issued in August, over 70 outline
proposals for application demonstrator clubs were received.  A
short list has been selected and it is expected that the final
selection of the clubs to be supported will be completed early in
the new year.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  DISTRIBUTED SYSTEM ENGINEERING PUBLICATION TO BE LAUNCHED
<P>

New ground is broken with the announcement of a collaborative
journal to be published by three major learned bodies:  The British
Computer Society, The Institution of Electrical Engineers and The
Institute of Physics.
<P>

The journal, entitled Distributed Systems Engineering, will
concentrate on the problems of integration of processing, storage,
and communications networks to form an overall distributed
processing system.  Dr. Morris Sloman of Imperial College
summarizes: 'Any distributed system needs to be managed, secure,
and while working in the face of inevitable faults, must be able to
incorporate new user requirements and technological developments.'
<P>

The journal will publish practical engineering-oriented papers with
the emphasis on implementation experience rather than the
theoretical approach.  It will provide a forum for the developments
in distributing architecture and networking technology, allied with
the emergence of multimedia processing and storage, all reflecting
the rapid increase in both research and commercial activity in
distributing systems engineering.
<P>

The new journal will draw its readership from both the academic
research community and commercial and industrial implementors.  The
journal will be served by an international editorial board covering
all sectors of the science community.  The board will be controlled
by three Honorary Editors:  Prof. David Hutchison, Lancaster,
University; Dr. Morris Sloman, Imperial College; and Dr. Rafael
Alonso, Matsushita Information Technology Laboratory.
<P>

To be published quarterly, the first issue of Distributed Systems
Engineering will be available in July, 1993.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  1993 JFIT TECHNICAL CONFERENCE - SHOWPIECE FOR UK IT
<P>

Plans for the 1993 conference are progressing well.  The conference
is designed to be a showpiece for UK IT supported by JFIT.  It will
be of interest to IT research workers and managers involved in JFIT
programs as well as potential users and appliers of the technology.
The first technical conference in Sussex was widely hailed as a
successful and stimulating event.
<P>

We have planned a three-stream conference with three leading
figures giving overview talks in plenary sessions.  Two streams of
papers will be devoted to the Devices and Systems areas, and the
third stream will feature cross-boundary sessions on novel uses of
IT and neural computing.
<P>

There has been a remarkable response to our Call for Papers, and we
anticipate high-quality presentations over an range of topics.
Papers have been refereed and selected on the basis of significant
achievements, exploitation potential, and technical excellence.
<P>

To accompany the Conference there will be an exhibition with
approximately 100 posters and demonstrations by JFIT project teams.
<P>

The Conference will be opened by Mr. Robert Jackson, MP, of the
Office of Science and Technology.  Dr. Geoffrey Robinson, until
recently head of IBM Hursley Laboratories, and now Chief Advisor on
Science and Technology in DTI, will be the after-dinner speaker at
the Conference dinner on Tuesday evening.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a> SECOND CSATP PROJECT MOVES AHEAD
<P>

The second project in DTI's Compound Semiconductor Advanced
Technology Program (CSATP), High Efficiency Microwave Power
Amplifiers (HEMPA), is now well underway.
<P>

The project was developed under the auspices of JFIT as a
comprehensive package of activities concerned with research into
the improvement of DC to RF conversion efficiency of GaAs-based
solid-state devices especially for power applications.
<P>

High-frequency solid-state power amplifiers are key components in
a variety of communications and radar applications.  The
requirements of high output power and high device efficiency is a
critical system requirement but places ever more stringent demands
on component performance and the underpinning technologies.
<P>

HEMPA, therefore, targets key areas of technology such as GaAs MMIC
based amplifiers for driver applications, low-loss power combining
techniques and investigation of automated multi-carrier and
wideband measurement techniques.  Emerging solid-state devices
based on novel materials and device structures, as well as novel
circuit topologies and configurations, will also be examined.
<P>

Work on this three-year project, costing L. 1.3 million ($1.9 M)
started on the 1st April 1992 and involves the close collaboration
of British Aerospace Space Systems (lead partner), Brunel
University, Elettronica UK, ERA, and Phillips Research
Laboratories.  The project promises to make a major contribution
toward strengthening the UK microwave industry.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

