<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 15</Title>
<NEXTID=16>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 15</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Coordination Languages for Parallel Processing</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Lip Synchronous Animations & Scientific Visualization</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  The Center for Mathematics and Computer Science (CWI) in The
Netherlands is a 200 person national institute for pure research.
This report describes some of the activities of CWI's Interactive
Systems Branch.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Paul J.W. ten Hagen
   Head of Interactive Systems
   Centre for Mathematics and Computer Science
   Kruislaan 413
   1098 SJ Amsterdam
   The Netherlands
   paulh@cwi.nl
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The 200 person Center for Mathematics and Computer Science
(CWI) in Amsterdam is an independent research institute.  CWI is
part of the Mathematical Centre Foundation, a non-profit
organization founded in 1946, that fosters mathematics and computer
science research in The Netherlands.  CWI seeks to initiate
research that is subsequently transferred to universities, applied
research laboratories, or commercial organizations for further R&D.
CWI receives 70% of its funding from the Dutch NWO (National
Organization for Scientific Research).  The remaining 30% is
obtained through national research programs, European programs
(ESPRIT, RACE, BRITE, etc.) and contract research commissioned by
the industry.
<P>

CWI is located at the Watergraafsmeer Scientific Center (WCW) in
Amsterdam.  It benefits from the presence next door of the academic
computer center SARA which contains a CRAY Y-MP and a 512 processor
transputer system.  Several other Dutch research institutes are
also located at WCW, as is the mathematics and computer science
faculty of the University of Amsterdam.  CWI is the Dutch member of
ERCIM, the European Research Consortium for informatics and
mathematics.  This organization is a loose consortium of major
research laboratories throughout the EEC.  Other members are
CNR/IEI (Italy), FORTH (Greece), GMD (Germany), INESC (Portugal),
INRIA (France), RAL (U.K.), and SINTEF (Norway).
<P>

CWI's Interactive Systems Department consists of 20+ researchers.
Areas of investigation include multimedia, languages for parallel
processing, visualization, and graphics architectures.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  CWI believes that the management among a set of concurrent
processes arises in many applications and is a central concern in
parallel computing.  A language called MANIFOLD is being developed
to describe and manage the complex interconnections among
independent, concurrent processes.  The language is concerned not
with the capability of individual processes, but rather with how
their processes are interconnected and how these interconnections
change.
<P>

The basic components in the MANIFOLD model are processes, events,
ports, and streams.  CWI defines a process as a black box with well
defined ports of connection through which it exchanges "units" of
information with other processes in its environment.  A process has
its own private processor and memory.  A stream is a sequence of
bits that represent a reliable, directed flow of information in
time.  Streams and processes are connected through "ports", i.e.
regulated openings at the process boundaries.  Information placed
into one of its output ports by a process flows out only when it is
connected to a stream.  Finally, events are asynchronous, non-
decomposable messages broadcast by a process to its environment.
<P>

MANIFOLD is an ongoing effort with experimentation taking place on
a 512 processor transputer system.  CWI hopes to put the system on
a Connection Machine for further development and evaluation.
<P>

(For information on MANIFOLD, contact Ivan Herman, ivan@cwi.nl)
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  CWI is investigating the image processing of facial
movements with the goal of providing automated methodologies for
lip movements for applications like low-bandwidth image telephones
and animations.  In a typical setup, an actor would speak before a
camera.  Lip movements are then analyzed and fed into keyframes.
The goal is to automate the processing between keyframes.  The
difficulties lie in real-time computation, the analysis and
classification of mouth shapes, and compensating for significant
person-dependent differences.
<P>

The approach is to select and measure the lip area, perimeter,
mouth opening size, etc.  Keeping the lip corners connected during
speech is a problem that has been solved using mathematical
morphology.  For the whole face, registration is performed using
key points that are selected because they remain nearly invariant
(e.g. the bottom of the nose).  The techniques are not human
dependent - they can be used to create, for example, a talking
telephone with a mouth that moves.
<P>

CWI is beginning a new effort in scientific visualization.  They
expect to focus on computational steering, with an emphasis on
chemical reactions.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

