<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 16</Title>
<NEXTID=17>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 16</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  ESPRIT Overview</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  ESPRIT III/ESPRIT Information Day</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  High Performance Computing and its Applications</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Basic Research</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  Because of its ability to cross national boarders in Europe,
the European Strategic Programme for Research and Development (R&D)
in Information Technology (ESPRIT) has become a premier source of
funding for European research.  ESPRIT Information Day was held in
February to discuss the next round of ESPRIT funding (ESPRIT-III).
This report provides a brief overview of ESPRIT and the objectives
and R&D tasks for two domains:  High Performance Computing and its
Applications and Basic Research.  A second report will follow to
describe the objectives and R&D for selected additional domains.
The R&D tasks for Basic Research specifically includes a new task
(R&D task 6.4) covering data visualization and virtual reality.
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  Launched in 1984, ESPRIT was designed to become a European
information technology (IT) program that would overcome such
problems as a lack of university/industrial cooperation and funding
limitations on trans-national programs.  ESPRIT proposals are
required to have participants from two member states and typically
comprise a consortium of 4 to 10 members that range from university
research to industrial partners and end users.  At the Information
Day High Performance Computing (HPC) session it was indicated that
ESPRIT-III would closely examine consortiums with large numbers of
partners, with the implication of past problems.  Awards are highly
sought after, both by academics and leading industrial R&D
organizations, and highly competitive.  European colleagues
indicated to me that the acceptance was about 1 in 10.  ESPRIT is
administered by Project Officers under the Commission of European
Communities and awards are based on a review process.  From what I
could gather, the review process appears similar to that used by
the U.S. National Science Foundation.  ESPRIT does not fully fund
awards; rather the percent of funding is negotiable in the final
contract stage and tends toward 50% ESPRIT funding and 50% matching
funds, typically by the industrial partners.  Projects can be
proposed for up to 5 years duration.  A look at the yearly synopses
for the Computer-Integrated Manufacturing and Engineering portion
of ESPRIT revealed projects ranging from 4 to 60 months with most
concentrated between 2 and 4 years.
<P>

Members of the European Free Trade Association who are not EEC
members are permitted to participate with certain constraints.
Just before my visit to Switzerland in December, the Swiss had very
narrowly rejected a new European free trade pact.  Swiss
researchers were concerned as to whether this "no" vote would
prevent their participation in future ESPRIT projects.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  The ESPRIT-III 1993-94 program is 400 million ECU (European
Currency Units) or about $ 500 M in size.  The funding is divided
into 7 programs, although interdisciplinary proposals across
subdivision boundaries are accepted.  These program areas are:
<P>

<PRE>
   Microelectronics
   Design and Engineering Technology for Software Intensive Systems
   High Performance Computing and its Applications (HPC)
   Advanced Business and Home Systems - Peripherals
   Computer Integrated Manufacturing and Engineering (CIM&E)
   Basic Research
   Open Microprocessor Systems Initiative
</PRE>

The ESPRIT Information Day was held in Brussels in February for
potential proposal submitters.  It was not, however, a general
introduction to the ESPRIT program.  Rather, it was an opportunity
to hold discussions and ask questions of Project Officers and, in
afternoon sessions, to present short briefs on ones own expertise
in the search for partners to form a consortium.  The Program
Officers for each of the seven topic areas ran the all day meetings
in parallel and they were not uniformly structured.  I attended the
HPC session in the morning and the CIM&E afternoon session.  The
specific funding breakdown for each of the 7 domains was not known,
but it appeared from discussions that all would be approximately
equal except for Basic Research which would be one-half to two-
thirds of the others.
<P>

After an introductory session attended by all, the attendees
separated by domains.  The morning HPC session included a brief
overview of recent HPC projects, including the use of acronyms that
required much pre-knowledge.  This was followed by a question and
answer session between the Project Officers and the audience.  The
CIM&E afternoon session was organized to permit short briefings of
special capabilities or interests by potential submitters and allow
groups who might wish to combine efforts to talk.  It left me with
the impression that it was an unlikely method of finding
collaborators, yet the number of Information Day attendees has
risen dramatically since its conception a couple of years back and
the hallways were crowded.  I should also mention that bulletin
boards were available for soliciting partners and stating areas of
expertise.  Some of these ads were from leading institutions and
the area was full of people making notes.
<P>

The remainder of this report describes the High Performance
Computing and Its Applications and the Basic Research portions of
ESPRIT-III.  The detailed objectives and R&D tasks identify the key
priorities on which the bulk of the resources and efforts are
expected to be concentrated in 1993/94.
<P>

The following information is extracted from Specific Research and
Technology Development Programme in the Field of Information
Technology, ESPRIT Work Programme for 1993-94, DRAFT COPY.  Those
R&D tasks where major R&D work is already in hand in ongoing
projects are marked with an (*).
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>                       DOMAIN 3
         High Performance Computing And its Applications
<P>

The work in this domain aims to expand the application potential of
High Performance Computing and Networking (HPCN); to demonstrate
the cost-effective transfer of applications currently running on
conventional systems to HPCN environments; to act on new
applications which will foster the mastery of new functionalities
and levels of performance; to develop next generation HPCN
technologies and systems, especially those which improve the
processes of application transfer or development, and are easy to
use.  The application focus is on improving industrial and
commercial productivity.  The high performance systems addressed
concern parallel processing systems both shared memory and
distributed memory multiprocessors, clusters of workstations for
high performance applications and the integration of high
performance sub-systems into distributed client/server
relationships.
<P>

HPCN Applications
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To demonstrate within a two-year timescale the successful migration
of the 10 or 15 most relevant existing codes onto advanced parallel
computing environments in a way which is as far as possible
portable and scalable.  This should build confidence in the
effectiveness of HPC both technically and economically.
<P>

To develop and demonstrate within two to five years new
applications that could not be solved cost-effectively without HPCN
and which have an impact on industrial and commercial productivity.
<P>

R&D tasks
<P>

<PRE>
     Existing Applications
</PRE>

3.1  Migration of existing codes from, for example, the fields of
structural analysis, fluid dynamics, computational chemistry or
microbiology, the simulation of industrial processes, data
management and image processing.  The work in this project will
evaluate the effectiveness of software tools, language, extensions,
compilers and development environments which are particularly
relevant to the task of migrating existing codes to parallel HPC
systems and evaluating the resulting implementations.
<P>

<PRE>
     New Applications
</PRE>

3.2  New HPCN applications which reduce time to market and cost
through simulation and modelling of complex phenomenon for example
in the fields of mechanical impact and chemical research.
<P>

3.3  New applications which improve through HPCN information
management by planning, scheduling or quality enhancement, better
access and management of databases and complex data analysis.
<P>

3.4  New embedded systems applications of HPCN which are of
particular economic relevance, addressing complex signal
processing, pattern recognition, image processing, real time
systems involving data fusion and advanced surveillance systems.
Emphasis will be placed on the use of commodity components and
subsystems.
<P>

Basic HPCN tools and technologies
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To improve and consolidate the environment in which software and
applications for HPCN systems are developed, to encourage
standardisation and common practises amongst a widespread group of
vendors and users.  Architecture-independent programming, ease of
programming, general purpose, and predictable high level of
performance will be the main focus.
<P>

To provide generic software which eases the use of a wide range of
applications.
<P>

To continue to stimulate the development of next generation HPCN
hardware and software in accordance with user requirements.
<P>

R&D tasks
<P>

*3.5   Development of methodology, associated software tools and
supporting standards which will rationalise the development of
software for parallel systems and satisfy the production
requirements of commercial and technical applications.
<P>

*3.6   Provision of distributed programming environments, operating
systems and networking software compliant with emerging standards.
<P>

3.7    Development of widely applicable models of virtual shared
memory systems leading to scalable and general purpose execution
environments supporting HPC applications.
<P>

3.8    Development of visualisation interfaces which can be used to
support different imaging and simulations systems.
<P>

3.9    Development of user oriented software to embed within
complex simulation and design package to make the latter
significantly easier to use.
<P>

*3.10  The development of next generation hardware and software
includes advanced computational models interconnection systems and
algorithm for better exploitation of parallel systems.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>                       DOMAIN 6
                         Basic Research
<P>

Objective
<P>

The dual objective is to replenish the reservoir of new knowledge
and expertise on which industrial research must draw to generate
future technological breakthroughs, and to ensure the environment
for training tomorrow's researchers in the most effective way
possible, through research itself.
<P>

Basic Research achieves this objective by contributing to the
programme's main aims from an upstream position and reinforcing
interdisciplinary links.  To ensure focus and effective application
of resources, the priority R&D tasks for 1993/94 fall into seven
clusters taking sharp aim at major themes of industrial R&D,
notably software best practice, high performance computing and
networking, image processing, multimedia and basic, microelectronic
technologies.  Projects would mostly be of a horizontal and highly
interdisciplinary nature addressing problems with potential impact
in several industrial areas.
<P>

R&D tasks
<P>

*6.1   Theories and models for the design of heterogeneous systems:
Theories and models for the design of systems which include
elements of dissimilar nature, such as hardware/software components
discrete/continuous behaviours, multiparadigm, multilanguage
software components and multifunctional microsystems.
<P>

6.2    Basic aspects of multiple computing agents:  Novel
underlying theories and semantic principles for systems and
computational models based on multiple and cooperating agents such
as communication networks and distributed systems, massively
parallel computers, cellular automata, adaptive control and neural
networks.
<P>

*6.3   Foundations of visualization and multi-modal interfaces:
Graphics simulation and basic algorithms leading to new
applications to data interpretation and models of interaction with
virtual reality.
<P>

6.4   Basic approaches to multimedia data representation:  Basic
approaches to knowledge acquisition for, and machine learning from,
multimedia data representation including the theoretical aspects of
massive storage and retrieval for multimedia data, including
databases.
<P>

*6.5   Ultimate miniaturisation: Novel concepts, tools and
techniques for processing and validation on scales less than 10nm
relevant to electronic and optoelectronic applications.
<P>

*6.6   Advanced issues in device performance:  Ultimate performance
(speed, reliability, lifetime, storage density) achieved by: the
application of genuinely new concepts and materials for light
emission and display; optically assisted computing; single electron
electronics; and high temperature electronics.
<P>

6.7  New concepts for top-down microsystem design and the
simulation of microsystem Performance.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

<b>Standard Report Navigation</b><P>

