<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 17</Title>
<NEXTID=18>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 17</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

European Strategic Program for Research & Development in
Information Technology (ESPRIT) - A Blueprint for
Microelectronics in the new Europe
--------------------------------------------- 8 March 1993
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Overview</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  The ESPRIT Microelectronics Program</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a> presented an overview of ESPRIT, a
premier European R&D program for information technology and gave
the objectives and R&D tasks for the domains of High Performance
Computing and its Applications and Basic Research.  This combined
issue of the ONR Newsletters on Electronics and Computer Science
presents the ESPRIT-III program for Microelectronics.
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The ESPRIT program and ESPRIT Information Day were discussed
in <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>.  This report provides additional
information on the ESPRIT-III program by providing the objectives
and R&D tasks for the Microelectronics Domain.  The information
presented below is extracted from "Specific Research and Technology
Development Programme in the Field of Information Technology,
ESPRIT Work Programme for 1993-94, DRAFT COPY" that was provided to
Information Day participants.  It outlines the strategy in
microelectronics for the next round of ESPRIT funding and beyond.
It outlines the objectives and the R&D tasks both for Group V and
Group III-V based electronics and optoelectronics. It also outlines
the objectives and R&D tasks for micro-systems which integrate
various functions on the same chip, e.g. micro-electronics, optics,
mechanics.  Those R&D tasks where major R&D work is already in hand
in ongoing projects are marked with an (*).
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>                       DOMAIN 1
                        MICROELECTRONICS
<P>

The goal of the work in Microelectronics is to strengthen the
European ICs users' capabilities to develop advanced and innovative
electronic systems for a broad range of applications, by providing
them with a competitive European source of the necessary
technologies and tools.  The work on the development of CMOS
technologies and relevant design, manufacturing and packaging
techniques will be carried out in conjunction with JESSI (Joint
European Submicron Silicon) and making best use of the expertise
available in the Community at large.  Specific actions will be
taken in favour of the SMEs to establish favourable conditions to
their use of microelectronics, covering training aspects,
demonstration of IC capabilities and service.
<P>

The continuous trend towards higher levels of integration driven by
system manufacturers is reflected in the new approach of the work
programme, which is focussing its objectives on the following three
primary axes of R&D action:
<P>

<PRE>
     design, fabrication and test of complex ICs (ASICs and
     standard logic circuitry) based on the next generations of
     core semiconductor technologies;
</PRE>

<PRE>
     increased integration at system level, to be exploited in
     multifunctional Application Specific (Sub)-Systems (ASIS), by
     incorporating different electronic functions on the same chip
     (through the combination of different core technologies or
     variants) or at multichip level;
</PRE>

<PRE>
     development of microsystems, aimed at achieving the
     compatibility of different types of functions/processes on the
     same chip or at multi-chip level, and bringing together
     different semiconductor technologies with micro-optics and
     micromechanics.
</PRE>

To make best use of the resources, synergy will be promoted, both
vertically within one main strategic area (e.g. between users,
suppliers and researchers, from materials and technology
development to final assembly and testing) and across the three
different axes of action, as driven by the requirements of a
specific application field (such as automotive, telecom or
consumer).
<P>

The creation and evolution of international standards will also be
promoted and industry will be assisted in the early implementation
as well as in the evaluation of emerging standards, notably in the
design and equipment areas.
<P>

Complex ICs based on a single core technology
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To develop complex ICs (standard logic circuitry and ASICs) based
on a single core technology and aimed at major specific
applications as proposed by internal and external users, to provide
early access to the technology under development.
<P>

To cover coherently several CMOS technology generations,
encompassing development and qualification of today's technologies,
applied research to establish the next technology generation, and
explorative work towards the longer term generations.
<P>

To identify, from advanced applications (e.g. consumer, telecom),
specific requirements for technology development and design
support.
<P>

R&D tasks
<P>

*1.1  Development of CMOS processes and relevant design,
manufacturing, qualification and packaging techniques comprising:
<P>

<PRE>
     adaptation of 0.5 um CMOS technologies to the industrial
     requirements of specific applications.  Establishment of the
     next generation at 0.35 um and execution of the applied
     research work aimed at the following generation at 0.25 um,
     with a major focus on process integration and transferability
     for further industrial engineering.  Explorative work on the
     major issues which is necessary to address in order to fulfill
     the future requirements of 0.18 CMOS;
</PRE>

<PRE>
     development of equipment and materials including collaborative
     characterisation and qualification in support of the above
     process needs of European IC manufacturers, as well as low
     entry cost flexible equipment and components needed for lower
     volume quick turnaround manufacturing of ASICS, or as
     clustered platforms for the development of prototype
     processes;
</PRE>

<PRE>
     development of new semiconductor manufacturing concepts
     breaking the increasing investment spiral for ICs production
     or aimed at the optimization of the process cycle, yield, etc,
     or broadening the access of SMEs to the use of ASICs.  As part
     of the manufacturing improvements, work may address "mini
     environments", development of clean room concepts, materials
     and supply systems suitable for processing at the above target
     geometries, as well as safety and environmental issues.
</PRE>

*1.2  Application driven work notably for the area of
communications and transport, aimed at the development of
competitive III-V based microwave and millimetre wave ICs, with
particular Attention to materials (e.g. substrates) and design and
manufacturing methods.
<P>

1.3  Development of advanced packaging and assembly techniques for
single ICs, able to meet the electrical and functional requirements
of the above technologies, while maintaining a satisfactory
reliability/cost ratio.  Packaging requirements should already be
taken into account in the circuit design phase.
<P>

Multifunctional Application Specific Sub-Systems
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To integrate a larger part of a system on a single chip
(Application Specific (Sub)-System), through the flexible
combination of electronic (and possibly optoelectronic) functions
on the same chip or at multichip level, in order to match the
application requirements in terms of functionality, performance,
reliability and costs.
<P>

To demonstrate the industrial capabilities of the processes through
the fabrication of complex circuits, designed by qualified users,
including SMES, and preferably oriented towards prototypes and
applications.
<P>

To develop suitable design methodologies and techniques, specific
to the particular combination of functions.
<P>

To identify, from applications,, specific requirements for
technology development and design support.
<P>

R&D tasks
<P>

1.4  Development of BiCMOS and Flash memory processes, and relevant
design, manufacturing, qualification and packaging techniques
comprising:
<P>

<PRE>
     provision of processing and manufacturing capabilities of
     BiCMOS technologies, in particular for analog and mixed
     analog/digital ICs, with extensive users' participation.
     Consolidation of the work at 0.8 um and progress towards the
     next technology generation;
</PRE>

<PRE>
     development of Flash memories for specific applications,
     including their integration with logic circuitry (e.g. field
     programmable devices and microcontrollers for prototyping
     purposes) and use of this innovative technology in the
     broadest range of circuits and applications.  Consolidation of
     the work at 0.8 um and progress towards the next technology
     generation;
</PRE>

<PRE>
     application driven research on innovative design techniques,
     to master complexity, performance and mixed functionality,
     including design and test of mixed analog/digital ICs.  The
     work should build on commercially available frameworks and
     tools;
</PRE>

1.5  Development of other application driven multifunctional
technologies and relevant design techniques, including low power
technology for battery applications, smart sensors, smart power
technology, optical and optoelectronic Components and ICs for
signal processing and transmission, and high performance
interconnects.
<P>

1.6  Development and adaptation of equipment and manufacturing
techniques to meet the specific requirements posed by the
fabrication of ASIS, including low cost and reliability.
<P>

1.7  Development of advanced packaging, interconnection and
assembly technologies needed for the integration of multicomponent
subsystem, at single module/board level, fulfilling the system
requirements in terms of performance, miniaturization and
reliability.  Special attention should be given to the
incorporation of optical interconnects, as required by broadband
telecommunication applications.
<P>

Micro-system
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To integrate functions of different nature on the same chip or on
multi-chip modules, as resulting from the evolution of the VLSI
technologies and from the application of thin film and
semiconductor technologies to micro-optics and micro-mechanics.
<P>

To develop the critical materials, technology and design tools
acting as a bottleneck to the successful industrialisation of
advanced micro-systems in e.g. automotive, telecom, industrial
manufacturing and medicine.
<P>

To combine the available multidisciplinary expertise and
enhancement of the know-how in microsystem related technologies, in
order to ensure a strong industrial capability, and establishment
in the projects of a close interaction between academia,
manufacturers and users.
<P>

To identify, from applications, specific requirements for
technology development and design support.
<P>

R&D tasks
<P>

1.8  Development of innovative materials and processes capable of
support for the integration of mechanical microstructures, signal
processing, optical components, sensing and actuating mechanisms on
one chip or on multi-chip modules.
<P>

1.9  Development of suitable materials, equipment and fabrication
techniques for interconnection, packaging and passivation.
<P>

1.10  Development and integration of specific tools required for
the design and manufacturing of microsystems.  Research into
codesign and concurrent engineering.
<P>

1.11  Development or adaptation of equipment and manufacturing
techniques to meet the integration requirements of microsystems (in
particular with respect to pattern generation, deposition,
microetching, assembly and testing).
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

