<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 19</Title>
<NEXTID=20>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 19</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

ESPRIT Information Day #3 - the ESPRIT programs in Business & Home
Systems and Computer Integrated Manufacturing & Engineering.
<P>

--------------- March 16, 1993
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Information Day</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Multimedia and Peripheral Technologies/Applications</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  CIM&E</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>    This report concludes a three part discussion of the
European Strategic Programme for Research and Development (R&D) in
Information Technology (ESPRIT) and ESPRIT Information Day with
some additional remarks about Information Day and by listing the
programs for the ESPRIT-III Domains of Advanced Business & Home
Peripherals and Computer Integrated Manufacturing & Engineering
(CIM&E).
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a> presented an overview of (ESPRIT) and
discussed ESPRIT Information Day.  That report also provided the
objectives and R&D tasks for High Performance Computing and for
Basic Research.  <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a> discussed the ESPRIT
microelectronics program.  This report concludes my discussion of
ESPRIT-III/Information Day with further discussion and a
presentation of the ESPRIT-III programs in Advanced Business and
Home Peripherals (mainly multimedia) and CIM&E.
<P>

I had attended the High Performance Computing Session at ESPRIT
Information Day in the morning.  In the afternoon I switched over
to CIM&E, although this was a continuation of the morning session
and not a restart.  After some confusion about rooms was solved,
the group split into two parts.  I stayed with the Robots and
Sensing Technologies.  There followed a brief overview of the CIM&E
programmatic interest in this area divided into three parts:
manufacturing systems, novel application domains - robotics, and
mobile systems.  Examples of each were given by acronym and topic,
but not explained in detail.  For example, the novel application
domain - robotics mentioned three programs dealing with autowelding
of very large structures, ship repair, and low cost robotics
control.  The information on the associated programs is presumably
available in the ESPRIT program synopses books for the previous
year.  These were provided at a table in the lobby, although
collectively (for all 7 Domains) it would be more than one could
reasonably carry home.
<P>

Next followed a half-dozen short (less than 5 minute) presentations
from groups seeking partners for joint proposals.  They included a
group looking at new fruit sorting and packing (with quality
control) methods, presentations of robotics research from two major
universities, and a company looking at walking and climbing
vehicles in flexible configurations.  Perhaps the most interesting
was a 300 person British company with previous collaborative
success.  They had demonstrated by feasibility study an idea for
using acoustic waves and measured frequency shift to develop a
torque transducer for non-contact measurements and were seeking
partners for a demonstration project.  They stated the idea was
particularly applicable to electric cars.
<P>

The interdisciplinary nature of virtual reality (vr) and data
visualization led to their appearance in tasks across the 7 Domains
of ESPRIT.  VR appears explicitly in research tasks 4.10 (see
multimedia below) and 6.3 (see Realization Report (RR) #16 on basic
research).  It was also implicit in several CIM&E tasks and there
were several proposal ideas advertised in the main hallway (see RR
#16) that focused on VR for CIM&E.  One sample advertisement
involved using vr as part of 3D laser or water jet cutting systems.
Data visualization appears in High Performance Computing (task
3.8), Advanced Business and Home Systems (task 4.6) and Basic
Research (task 6.3).
<P>

The information presented below is extracted from "Specific
Research and Technology Development Programme in the Field of
Information Technology, ESPRIT Work Programme for 1993-94, DRAFT
COPY" that was provided to Information Day participants.  Those R&D
tasks where major R&D work is already in hand in ongoing projects
are marked with an (*).
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>                       DOMAIN 4
        Advanced Business and Home Systems - Peripherals
<P>

Work in this area aims to enable the development of open integrated
solutions focused on specific applications and promote the use and
vertical integration of multimedia and related display and memory
technologies, demonstrate the application in three distinct, but
inter-related fields: professional applications, business
applications and personal high volume electronics applications. It
is expected that existing standards will be taken into account and,
when justified, proposals for new standards will be made.
<P>

Multimedia applications
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To contribute to image and multimedia solutions for consumer,
professional and business applications, including the integration
of image-based services with existing administrative and technical
applications.
<P>

To develop systems that contribute directly to the competitivity of
the IT industry whilst addressing societal or cultural needs.
<P>

To trigger the take-off of significant business opportunities based
on interactive multimedia technology.
<P>

To contribute to the development of applications for "intelligent"
devices and systems for personal use.
<P>

R&D tasks
<P>

4.1    Development of solutions for business administrative
systems.  This will include work in databases, workflow, toolkits
for advanced applications, electronic signatures and payments.
<P>

4.2    Development of consumer solutions addressing entertainment
and information services, including development of portable
personal assistant applications.
<P>

*4.3   Development of multimedia authoring and publishing features,
to serve a variety of users (from consumer to professional), and
addressing issues such as standardisation, conformance testing,
copyright protection and delivery.
<P>

4.4    Definition and development of generic multimedia systems to
support a broad range of vertically integrated services such as
multimedia tourist information, TV and video (distribution, imaging
and simulation systems, technical product information, the
documentation of cultural artifacts, education, games and
entertainment.
<P>

*4.5   Extension and enhancement of integrated low-cost systems
allowing users to interact with home automation devices and to
benefit from value-added services.
<P>

Peripheral technologies
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To contribute to the development of the peripheral subsystems
required to build multimedia systems.  The subsystems need to
address functions such as image display, storage, requirements for
mobility and portability.
<P>

To contribute to the reduction of the physical size and power
consumption of the subsystems.
<P>

R&D Tasks
<P>

*4.6   Development of low cost high resolution thin screen display
components needed for television, desktop and mobile computers as
well as a wide range of other types of product.  In particular work
is required on improvements in visual quality of displays
especially for portable machines.  Priority will be given to active
matrix LCD technology but work on other technologies and types of
display will also be considered.
<P>

4.7  Development of storage subsystems able to support multimedia
technologies in particular real-time high-definition video.
<P>

Multimedia technologies
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To contribute to the development of the technologies required for
acquisition of multimedia information of multimodal interaction
with the user.
<P>

To develop digital processing tools required for multimedia
applications and services, including virtual reality.
<P>

R&D tasks
<P>

*4.8   Development of tools to safeguard copyright material which
is stored and disseminated in digital form; definition of means
that will enable parties to monitor and control their particular
contribution.
<P>

*4.9   Development of the hardware and software platforms required
by multimodal/multimedia authoring and delivery systems supporting
multimedia group-working in complex heterogenous environments,
including mobile systems and assuring on-line access to remote
repositories of multimedia information.  Target applications
domains include the upgrade of existing professional applications
(e.g. health care, finance, film production studios, etc.).
<P>

4.10   Development of hardware and software tools and components
for such emerging domains as dark room functions, digital video
coding for recording and transmission (for example in digital
television), virtual reality and user interaction components for
home systems.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>                       DOMAIN 5
        Computer Integrated Manufacturing and Engineering
<P>

To contribute to the improvement of the competitive position of the
European manufacturing and engineering industries by encouraging
the development of advanced IT solutions for cleaner and highly
efficient industrial operations and processes.
<P>

To support an integrative approach embracing engineering, logistics
and operations, process automation and business functions, in a way
which takes account of social, organisational economic and
environmental concerns.
<P>

Architecture and infrastructure for CIME
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To develop a single infrastructure, allowing cost effective
integration within an open system architecture, building on
emerging standards in open distributed processing, network
administration, enterprise modelling and interchangeable product
data.
<P>

To promote migration from proprietary systems.
<P>

R&D Tasks
<P>

*5.1   Development of product modelling standards, interfaces,
protocols and tools with emphasis on shared/integrated database
interfaces for product model data and on formats for knowledge
representation and exchange.
<P>

*5.2   Development of communications services at the level of the
production process, the production plant and between interlinked
enterprises, and their interconnection.
<P>

5.3    Definition and provision of tools to support enterprise
modelling techniques, with emphasis on migration paths for
progressive enterprise integration.
<P>

Management and design of industrial enterprise
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To develop system components which are of easily manageable size
and conform to widely accepted standards, allowing their ready
assimilation in the integration strategy of a company, so that
smaller companies are also able to invest in the available
technology on a step-by-step basis.  These should take account of
concepts such as lean production and concurrent engineering which
are crucial to the fruitful introduction and application of ITC in
a factory environment.
<P>

R&D Tasks
<P>

5.4    Development of tools, based on data, product and process
modelling, to simulate products and their production processes and
optimise performance over the complete lifecycle of the product.
<P>

*5.5   Improving quality assurance and quality management by the
development of advanced IT-based systems which enhance and
eventually replace existing manual documentation and control
systems and provide a process for rapid access to quality
information and records.
<P>

5.6    Development of advanced IT for environment friendly design
i.e. the design of products to minimise their environmental impact
over the complete product lifecycle, from design, through
manufacture and use, and on to disposal of disassembly for
recycling.
<P>

5.7    Provision of tools for concurrent design of products,
manufacturing systems and of industrial plant including the
associated control systems, taking account of construction, safety
and maintenance aspects.
<P>

*5.8   Development of interactive and collaborative production
management systems including support for multi-site, multi-supplier
operations and enabling efficient distribution of goods between and
inside industrial enterprises.
<P>

*5.9   Development of an integrated, suite of simulation tools to
enable enterprises to evaluate product and manufacturing
strategies.
<P>

Mechantronics, Robotics and Sensing Technologies
<P>

Objectives
<P>

To develop and integrate available and emerging technologies to
achieve new levels in quality and functionality in both capital and
consumer products, with priority given to systems which meet the
high degrees of programmability, flexibility and integration
demanded by the market.
<P>

R&D Tasks
<P>

*5.10  Development of integratable IT-based autonomous components
for open, and reconfigurable production and handling systems.  The
systems would be capable of handling rigid and non-rigid materials.
<P>

5.11   Development of low cost, intelligent sensors and
microsystems and their integration into production systems.  This
would address discrete parts manufacture, process plant and
environmental monitoring and control.
<P>

5.12   Development of autonomous systems for disassembly and
recycling of products in nonstructured environments, and functional
integration of IT for handling products for which design and
manufacturing descriptions are not available, and so would need to
incorporate the ability to recognise shapes and identify materials.
<P>

Microsystem Manufacturing and Integration
<P>

Objective
<P>

To facilitate the high volume/high variety manufacturing of
microsystems, which encapsulate the complex system know-how of
industrial users to enable rapid uptake of advanced microsystems
technology, and demonstrate the potential of microsystems in a
variety of products.
<P>

R&D Tasks
<P>

5.13   Functional integration of microsystems and their
incorporation in a range of capital and consumer products which
would benefit from the introduction of microsystems.  Work would
focus on the manufacture and assembly of such systems and include
information processing and standardisation issues.
<P>

5.14   Provision of migration paths from current sensor-based
systems to microsystems which require certification and licenses to
operate, based on emerging standards.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

