<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 20</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

The University of Marseille - Luminy:  Medical Imaging and
Architectural Reconstructions
.............................. April 8, 1993
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Medical Imaging</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Architectural reconstructions</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  The Computer Science Dept. at the University of Marseille -
Luminy has recently expanded its focus to include computer
graphics.  This report describes the work of Prof. Sequeira, who is
setting up the graphics group.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Prof. Jean Sequeira
   G.I.A. Faculte des Sciences de Luminy
   163, Ave. de Luminy - Case 901
   13288 Marseille Cedex, France
   sequeira@gia.univ-mrs.fr
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The University of Marseille - Luminy is located in the
southwest suburbs of Marseille in the Luminy Science and Technology
Park on the road leading from Marseille to the pretty coastal town
of Cassis.  The science faculty of Luminy was founded in 1968 and
includes 2,300 students and 200 teachers/research workers.  The
science faculty is actually a teaching and research section of the
University of Aix-Marseille II.  The faculty includes 7
departments: computer science, mathematics, molecular and cellular
biology, chemistry, physics, social sciences, and sciences of the
land, sea, and environment.
<P>

The research emphasis in the computer science faculty at Marseille
- Luminy includes logical programming, automatic demonstration and
knowledge representation, natural languages, and speech
recognition.  The department is best known for its role in the
creation and development of the PROLOG logical programming language
that played such a prominent role in the Japanese 5th generation
computer systems project.  Prof. Sequeira has recently joined the
faculty to expand the department into computer graphics.  Prof.
Sequeira previously spent over a decade at the IBM Paris Scientific
Center where he participated in projects on geometric modeling,
workstation design, and medical imaging.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  Prof. Sequeira's most recent research, which he is
continuing in Marseille, involves surface based methods for 3D
medical image reconstruction (see also the work of Dr. Ayache at
INRIA - Sophia Antipolis in an upcoming Realization Report).  The
goal of such research is to develop methods that will take data
measured as cross sections and associate a geometric 3D model with
this set of points.  The approach is performed in two parts.
First, interactive methods are used to identify sets of points to
be associated with tubular cavities.  Next, free-form surfaces made
of uniform B-spline patches are computed automatically to represent
these cavities.  The junctions between the surfaces are computed
automatically as sets of Bezier-Gregory patches.  The methods is
also applicable when only a few data points are present or when the
points are not homogeneously distributed in space.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  The School of Architecture of Marseille - Luminy is located
in a separate part of the industrial park.  Several members of this
School are integrating computer graphics and archaeology.  In
particular they produced a 13 minute animation, shown on French
television, that uses animation to follow the time evolution of
Marseille.  Geometric models of buildings and other architectures
are constructed in a manner that permits overlaying the
architectural qualities native to a given era.  Programming was
performed using object-oriented programming languages.  Prof.
Sequeira and the group performing the architecture modeling will be
working together to continue and expand this effort.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

