<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 21</Title>
<NEXTID=22>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 21</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

JFIT: Information Technology in the U.K. (April 93)
--------------------------- 27 April 1993
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  The World's First 35 mm Video Camera</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Product Design - Future Requirements</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Monolithic Microwave IC Manufacturing Facility</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Intelligent Autonomous Vehicles Conference</a><br>
<b>6.0  </b><a href="#[6.0]">  U.K. Microengineering Common Interest Group</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  A large funding agency for information technology (IT)
research and development in the U.K. is the Joint Framework for
Information Technology (JFIT).  JFIT is a combination of the U.K.
Science and Engineering Council (SERC) and the Department of Trade
and Industry (DTI).  The following are copied or abstracted from
selected IT items in JFIT publications.  See also <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>.
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a> FIRST 35mm VIDEO CAMERA
<P>

A 35mm diameter video camera called Peach, believed by VLSI vision
to be the world's first, has been developed (i.e. the first camera
which measures 35mm in diameter across its housing -- about the
size of a postage stamp).  The camera is based on a single-chip
sensor.  The chip is a CMOS silicon chip which includes a 312 x 287
pixel sensor array and associated digital and analog support
circuits including automatic exposure and gain control.
<P>

The original camera on a chip is based on world-class vision
research carried out at Edinburgh University and funded under JFIT.
<P>

As a consequence of the success of the work, a start up company,
VLSI Vision Ltd. (VVL), was set up to exploit the chip.  VVL's
camera product represents a strong example of how JFIT R&D programs
can lead to innovative, competitive IT systems.  The work also
highlights the vital impact silicon ICs can have in providing the
basis for new systems concepts and products.
<P>

In a new collaborative project, VLSIVision, Renishaw Metrology, and
the University of Edinburgh are now researching into the problems
of a CAD system to implement the camera for specific applications.
Clearly the ability to program vision chips quickly and efficiently
will provide an important advances in the development of future
products.
<P>

Finally, for those interested in further technical details, the
video camera provides a CCIR-standard monochrome output signal
using 5V levels generated by the sensor chip.  It draws 40mA under
a 75 ohm load from a regulated 7 to 12V dc supply.  VVL claims this
allows the device to run for 15 hours powered by an alkaline PP3
battery.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a> SERC/IMechE MEETING ON IT AND PRODUCT DESIGN
<P>

SERC and the Institute of Mechanical Engineers (IMechE) hold a
jointly organized and funded annual meeting on a topic of current
interest.  This year the subject was 'IT and Product Design', with
the aim of identifying the research and development issues that the
community should be tackling over the next 5-10 years, and thus
produce an 'innovation' agenda for direction of effort.
<P>

This year's meeting, held in St. Albans from 8-10 December, was
attended by about 50 people from a variety of backgrounds,
including a mixture of overseas visitors, industrialists, and UK
academics.
<P>

The conclusions from the meeting have now been brought together
into a report.  The main finding was that there should be a
coordinated program of work addressing how designers carry out the
design process when assisted by computer-based tools, demonstrator
projects to support the scientific understanding required in the
construction of the next generation of design tools, and forward
looking projects to prototype the design tools of the future.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a> NEW GaAs THREE INCH LINE OPENS
<P>

On 27 January 1993, the new GaAs Integrated Circuit manufacturing
line was officially opened by GEC-Marconi Materials Technology
Ltd., Caswell.  This new Class 10 'state-of-the-art' facility is
now Europe's finest Monolithic Microwave IC manufacturing facility
and is a key part of the company's aim to maintain its position as
Europe's leading GaAs commercial foundry.  GEC's commitment to the
exploitation of its GaAs technology base has been underlined by its
capital investment of over L.10 million ($16 million) in the new
line.
<P>

Whilst GEC has clearly invested heavily in R&D programs to support
its technology base, JFIT projects have also played an important
part in establishing its GaAs capability.  The recently completed
collaborative projects on 'Low Damage Plasma Processing', 'Improved
Substrate Materials', and the 'Advanced Lithography Research
Initiative'  have all supplied new process techniques which are
being introduced to the new manufacturing line.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a> INTELLIGENT AUTONOMOUS VEHICLES WORKSHOP
<P>

The first IFAC International Workshop on Intelligent Autonomous
Vehicles (IAV's) is to be held at the University of Southampton,
UK, on 18-21 April 1993.
<P>

The aim of the workshop is to provide a forum in which new and
emerging system methodologies and technologies for the design and
development of IAVs can be discussed openly.  Many of the
approaches under discussion will be generic by nature and therefore
applicable to land, sea, and space vehicles.  Thus the workshop is
well suited for engineer and technologists from a range of
professional backgrounds, disciplines, and industries with a common
interest in intelligent autonomous systems.
<P>

An opening keynote address will be given by Prof. J.M. Brady,
University of Oxford, entitled 'Future Aspects of IAV Research'.
Over 70 papers will be presented and there will be several poster
sessions.  Each registered participant will receive a bound copy of
the pre-prints which will include both the paper and poster
presentations.
<P>

Sessions will be devoted to sensors, machine perception,
intelligent control, intelligent guidance, navigation, mission
planning and management, design and architectures, integrated
vehicle systems and other specialized topics.
<P>

It should be noted that it is the intention to restrict the number
of attendees to the workshop to approximately 100; this is in order
to encourage all the delegates to acquaint themselves with each
other and for them to make an active contribution to the workshop
proceedings.  In order to engender such friendly comradery, the
main workshop social function is a medieval banquet with
entertainment at the Abbey, Beaulieu.
<P>

<a NAME="[6.0]"><b>[6.0]</b></a> FORMATION OF THE UK MICROENGINEERING COMMON INTEREST GROUP
(MCIG)
<P>

In response to the high level of interest expressed at the recent
Microengineering meeting held at the Lucas Advanced Engineering
Center, it has been decided to go ahead with the formation of the
Common Interest Group.
<P>

The  initial idea for the group was suggested by the UKSG (UK
Sensors Group), and the DTI has agreed financial support to aid its
formation.  The aim of the group is to promote and catalyse all
aspects of microengineering research and development in the UK and
to act as a source of information on Europe.  The group will seek
to represent the UK microengineering community to Government, the
EC and other agencies.
<P>

Benefits of membership to MCIG include access to a series of major
meetings covering a wide range of subjects.  These meetings will
cover technology markets and information topics.  In addition, a
number of smaller specialist seminars will be arranged to cover, in
detail, specific areas of common interest.  Members will be
informed of recent developments and related activities within their
countries through a regular newsletter.  Opportunities will exist
within the group for members to share in collaborative work and so
bring mutual benefit to those concerned.  The group has been
coordinated initially by a steering committee with representatives
from Imperial College, Lucas, Druck, and Central Research
Laboratories.  An executive committee meeting will be elected at
the first members meeting, which will be held in early June.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

