<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 22</Title>
<NEXTID=23>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 22</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

The Fourth Eurographics Workshop on Visualization in Scientific
Computing.
......................April 28, 1993
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Overview</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Theory and Applications</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Architecture and Dataflow Systems</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Virtual Reality and Working Group Discussions</a><br>
<b>Appendix  </b><a href="#[Appendix]"> - Workshop Programme</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  This report describes activities at the 4th Eurographics
Workshop on Visualization in Scientific Computing, held in
Abington, U.K. on April 21-23.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Julian Gallop, jrg@inf.rl.ac.uk (workshop co-chair)
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The 4th Eurographics Workshop on Scientific Visualization
was held at Coseners House, Abington, U.K. (Abington is near
Oxford).  Coseners House (the Cook's House) is the standing remains
of an old abbey that has been turned by Rutherford Appleton
Laboratory into a facility for meetings and workshops for a maximum
of about 50 people.  The actual workshop had an attendance of 30,
selected from submitted papers.  The papers were approximately
equally divided between theory, visualization architectures
(primarily dataflow software), and case studies from a variety of
disciplines.
<P>

The workshop began with a change in leadership, as Mr. Michel Grave
of ONERA (see <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>) stepped down after four years
as head of the Eurographics Visualization Group.  Michel was given
thanks as the person most responsible for organizing the workshop
series.  He introduced Dr. Jarke van Wijk of the Netherlands Energy
Research Foundation ECN  (see <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>), the new
Visualization Group chairman.  The two Workshop co-chairs, Mr.
Julian Gallop of Rutherford Appleton and Dr. Jeremy Walton of NAG
Ltd., then outlined the workshop format and procedure.  I gave an
opening presentation that discussed the ONR computer science
research program, the structure and visualization activities of the
IEEE Computer Society, and some recent developments in synthetic
environments.  The remainder of the workshop consisted of paper
presentations, one panel discussion, and a few hours devoted to
working group discussions.
<P>

Since this is a closed workshop and paper titles are not generally
available, the conference program is given in the appendix.  A
selection of the papers will be published in book form by Springer-
Verlag (some were presented as "work in progress").  The
participants received looseleaf-bound workshop proceedings.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  The workshop presentations were divided roughly equally into
three parts: algorithms and techniques, architectures and systems,
and applications.  One interesting paper was by van Wijk and
Tissen.  This presented the molecular modeling work discussed in
<a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>, where a combination of simple glyph
representation and the time-dependent convex hull of a molecule was
used to study the molten carbonate fuel cell.  The motion of the
convex hull, with molecule parts glyph represented, gave new
information about possible docking sites.  The applications papers
were of uniformly high quality although they ranged from
inexperience-in-visualization physicists and others deriving
knowledge through first use of data visualization methods through
the applied visualization work of experienced users.
<P>

Brian Collins of the IBM U.K. Center in Winchester presented an
archaeological reconstruction of the Dresden Frauenkirche in "From
Ruins to Reality - The Dresden Frauenkirche".  This church,
according to Collins the most important example of German
Protestantism architecture, collapsed from heat damage from the
resulting fire storm two days after the bombing of Dresden in 1945.
<P>

Communist rule prevented its reconstruction, but it is now hoped to
rebuild the church at an estimated cost of DM 160 million ($107
million) and 10 year's time.  Collins discussed how all available
documentation on the architecture was used in the computer graphics
reconstruction to establish realism.  Detailed architectural
drawings and old photographs were input into the geometric CATIA 3D
model.  The project was split into several parts, resulting in
separate models for the outside and inside (and portions of the
inside).  The building is very complex and detailed, and Collins
credited CATIA with enabling results to be achieved within 5 weeks.
<P>

The geometric model was supplemented with scanned images and
information available from other churches.  Additional methods
included using a color palate editor, warping 2D images onto a 3D
surface, and texture mapping.  The geometric model was then
transferred from CATIA to TDImage for photorealistic rendering and
generating camera positions.  Finally animation was produced by
incorporating the camera trajectory and geometric model into IBM
Data Explorer.  Much of the project used 9000 machine hours on IBM
RISC System/6000 workstations over 12 weeks.  The latter stages
were performed on the IBM Power Visualization System.  With its 32
processors, 21 Gbyte disk subsystem, and 1 Gbyte shared memory,
there was a dramatic time reduction from weeks to days.  A final
point made by Collins was that, if the Church reconstruction does
not happen, this will become the best historical record of the
church.  What will happen to this record, asks Collins, as digital
formats change over the coming years?
<P>

Another interesting application paper, "Visualization of
Telecommunications Network Data", was presented by Walker et al. of
BT (British Telecom) Laboratories.  The authors presented
conclusions from two studies of interest to BT management: results
of a Sunday discounting price experiment and correlation between
outages and lightening strikes.  The methodology used was not new,
but interest lay in the application to commercial data.  The
visualizations were effective and the authors stated that, after a
few minutes of initial skepticism, members of the BT Board were
very receptive to this type of presentation.  If this experience
can be generalized, it will open broad new marketplaces to what has
been known to date as "scientific visualization" (although many of
us have already opted for the term "data visualization").
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a> Pagendarm and Choudary of DLR (the German aerospace research
laboratory) are experienced in fluid flow theory and visualization.
<P>

Their paper "Visualization of Hypersonic Flows -- Exploring the
Opportunities to Extend AVS" evaluated the potential of the
commercial visualization system AVS (Advanced Visualization System
- one of the most widely used module-based visualization systems).
Their interest was to see to what degree AVS could serve as a post-
processing system for numerical flow analysis and, in particular,
to explore the extensibility and flexibility of AVS to incorporate
new algorithms and requirements.  They presented an animation that
used advanced flow algorithms.  Their conclusion was that AVS was
a stable and flexible platform for visualization, but restrictions
such as the definition of an unstructured cell data type required
(or at least was made easier by) performing certain functions
outside AVS.
<P>

Several papers and the panel dealt explicitly with AVS, or with
comparisons between AVS and other modular-based commercial systems.
<P>

I wonder if, on the whole, these differences are not of greater
concern to the vendors, who must differentiate to sell products,
than to the scientific end user!  However, one area where the
differences are important is for use within distributed
visualization systems.  The Computing Center at the University of
Stuttgart has been involved with ONERA and others (see <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>)
in developing distributed visualization.  In
"Architectures of Distributed Visualization Systems and their
Enhancements" by Wierse et al., an evaluation is made of AVS, IRIS-
Explorer, IBM Data Explorer, and the newer Visage (see the IEEE
Visualization 92 conference proceedings) specifically for
distributed visualization.  Several strengths and weaknesses are
noted for each system; in particular, weaknesses on systems lacking
shared memory (e.g. Cray) are noted.  The authors conclude by
presenting their own design.  The architecture is AVS-like on the
"top" end, but uses a data system that permits both local and
remote shared data spaces.  They avoid connectivity between modules
and place an "administrator" on each machine.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  Two papers were presented on virtual reality (VR).  The
first, "Integrating Virtual Environments into the Dataflow
Paradigm," presented work in progress at the National Center for
Supercomputing Applications (NCSA) Urbana, USA that is beginning to
look at the role of VR in the scientific visualization process.
Projects include cosmology, molecular dynamics, and heavy equipment
simulation.  I believe that NCSA initially implemented the
NASA/Ames Virtual Windtunnel VR system; they now have a variety of
VR devices for input and display.  This was one of two U.S. papers
presented at the workshop.
<P>

"Realtime Sonification to enhance the Human-Computer Interaction in
Virtual Worlds," discussed a toolkit for using sound in a VR
environment developed at FhG-IGD (Frauhofer Institute for Computer
Graphics) in Darmstadt, Germany. The work was quite interesting and
several examples were given, such as playing a virtual drum.  The
experiments to date, however, did not explore the use of sound in
a virtual environment for obtaining knowledge from a data set.
<P>

Four working group sessions were held, pairwise in parallel.  Each
lasted about 1 1/2 hours with a report given back to the entire
workshop by the session leader.  I attended "Virtual Reality and
Multimedia" and "Visualization Methods and Techniques."  The VR was
largely a presentation and discussion by the two or three people in
the group familiar with VR/visualization applications to the
others.  The audience questioned the role of multisensory
immersion; indeed, even VR proponents do not yet claim demonstrable
scientific results.  Multimedia received a more animated
discussion.  It was agreed that multimedia would be important in
the presentation process, rather than the discovery process.
Current multimedia scientific publication efforts were discussed,
such as the multimedia cdrom from last year's Supercomputing 92
Conference.  The participants felt that publication methods would
change over the next decade and two working group members
volunteered to investigate a possible Eurographics multimedia
publication.
<P>

The "techniques" working group focused on high-dimensional data
spaces.  The participants felt that this critical topic has seen
only limited research, perhaps because it is so difficult.
Techniques mentioned by participants were the use of iconic
representation (e.g. the Chernoff "faces"), the embedded-axes
method (Beshers and Feiner, IEEE Visualization 92), ordered
parameters (Mihalisin et al., CG&A 1991 and Ward et al., IEEE
Visualization 90), and the work at IBM by Inselberg.  Chernoff's
and Feiner's research was ONR sponsored, incidently.  A second
research topic discussed was extending vector field visualization
methods to tensor fields.  The work of Hesselink (IEEE
Visualization 92) was mentioned as seminal.  Two members of the
audience, Dr. van Wijk and Prof. Hans Hagen, gave brief mention of
their respective work in progress in tensor field representation.
I had recently spoken with an ONR scientific manager who felt the
need for such results in his mechanics program, so it was good to
see this topic beginning to be addressed.
<P>

In concluding this report, I extend my thanks to Michel Grave,
Julian Gallop, and Jeremy Walton for inviting me to speak at the
workshop.  The workshop was both enjoyable and valuable, a pleasing
combination.
<P>

<a NAME="[Appendix]"><b>[Appendix]</b></a> The Workshop Programme
<P>

