<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 23</Title>
<NEXTID=24>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 23</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Discussion</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  At a lecture in Cambridge (U.K.), Prof. Andrew Wiles
announced a solution to Fermat's Last Theorem, mathematics most
famous (previously) unsolved problem.
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  One of the beauties of number theory is the existence of
problems that are extremely simple to state and comprehend, but
which have defied solution by leading mathematicians for centuries.
<P>

The most famous of these is Fermat's Last Theorem which states that
the equation
<P>

<PRE>
                     N         N         N
                    X    +    Y    =    Z
</PRE>

has no positive integer solutions (X,Y,Z) for any integer N, where
N>2.  N=2 is, of course, the Pythagorean theorem for right
triangles and has many solutions in integers (e.g. (3,4,5) or
(5,12,13)).  In the 17th century the French mathematician Pierre de
Fermat wrote in the margin of a letter to a friend that he had
found an admirable proof of the theorem, but the margin was too
narrow to contain it.  Mathematicians have been perplexed ever
since!
<P>

In a June 23 lecture at the Newton Institute for Mathematics in
Cambridge (U.K.), Prof. Andrew Wiles, a British-born mathematician
now at Princeton Univ., announced a solution.  The proposed
solution, incidently, is reported to owe little to computer
technology and to be based on previous work by Prof. Matthias Flach
of Heidelberg Univ.  Both Wiles and Flach did their doctoral
studies at Cambridge, a traditional seat of excellence for number
theoretic research.
<P>

In what now seems a previous lifetime, my PhD was from this area of
number theory (Diophantine equations) that deals with the solution
of polynomial equations by integers or rational numbers.  I'll
venture a few comments that rely on the accuracy of ancient
memories.
<P>

An intriguing question for mathematical historians is "did Fermat
have a proof, or even really think he did"?  There is no other
known instance of Fermat's having claimed proofs of theorems that
he did not demonstrate, so we conjecture that he did indeed believe
he had a proof.  By trivial factorization when N is not a prime, it
is sufficient to demonstrate the conjecture for all odd primes.
This leads to the study of quadratic number fields that take the
form for a given prime P of
<P>

<PRE>
               (A + B*sqrt(P))/2
</PRE>

where A and B are integers with certain constraints on A and B that
depend on whether P is congruent to 1 or 3 modulo 4.  These
quadratic number fields satisfy the usual axioms for a number
field, but some have a remarkable property:  An important property
of the integers is that they are uniquely factorizable into a
product of primes.  However, certain quadratic number fields
contain numbers that have more than one representation as products
of prime factors.  If memory serves, it was about 1970 when the
issue of exactly which quadratic number fields did not have the
unique factorization property was finally put to rest.
<P>

The above relates to Fermat's Last Theorem because if all quadratic
number fields had unique factorization, there would be a moderately
short, elegant (and "admirable" ) proof.  And, in the days before
the algebraic representation of quadratic fields was developed,
there were subtle ways of implicitly making this erroneous
assumption.  This is at the heart of a long history of incorrect
solutions for Fermat's Last Theorem and is a likely source of
Fermat's error.
<P>

Why the fascination with this problem?  Certainly its accessibility
is a factor.  But problems such as Fermat's Last Theorem really
become important not for the problem itself, but rather for the new
branches of mathematics that arise in the quest for a solution.
Portions of modern algebra have roots here.
<P>

Logicians have demonstrated that, given the axioms of number
theory, one can write down theorems that are true but cannot be
proven true.  There were those who thought Fermat's Last Theorem
might be an example of a true but unprovable theorem.  Prof. Wiles
solution will surely be scrutinized in the coming months.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

