<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 24</Title>
<NEXTID=25>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 24</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

The National Academy of Sciences/ONR+AFOSR International Science
Lecture Series, Spring 1993, in Eastern Europe.
.............................................. 29 June 1993
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  The Spring '93 Lecture Series</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Conclusions</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Acknowledgements</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  This report briefly summarizes the Spring 1993 National
Academy of Sciences International Science Lecture Series (sponsored
by the Office of Naval Research (ONR) and the Air Force Office of
Scientific Research (AFOSR)).  This year's topic was information
science and the area visited was Eastern Europe.  Prof. John
Hopcroft of Cornell gave a series of lectures and discussions were
held with computer scientists in the five countries visited.
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The National Academy of Sciences holds an ongoing lecture
series under the sponsorship of ONR and AFOSR.  This year's
selection for scientific topic was information science and the
selected lecturer was Prof. John E. Hopcroft of Cornell University.
<P>

The ONR European Office played a major role in establishing the
contacts, meeting sites, and agenda for the lectures, discussions,
and visits.  Between May 23rd and June 8th the lecture series was
conducted in Eastern Europe (with a brief stop in "West" Germany).
We conducted lectures and held meetings with computer scientists in
the Federal Republic of Germany, Poland, Hungary, Russia, and the
Ukraine.
<P>

This is the lecture series' third year.  Previous years' topics
were oceanography and material science.  The goals are to conduct
discussions with colleagues, especially in places where contact
with U.S. scientists may be limited, about the current and future
directions of the field and for all participants to gain a better
understanding about the nature of current research directions in
both the host country and the U.S.
<P>

For anyone not familiar with him, Prof. John Hopcroft is the Joseph
C. Ford Professor of Computer Science and Associate Dean for
College Affairs in the College of Engineering, Cornell University.
Prof. Hopcroft is widely recognized for his pioneering work in the
theoretical aspects of computing, especially in the areas of
analysis of algorithms, formal languages, automata theory and graph
algorithms.  The four books on formal languages and on algorithms
that he has co-authored with Professor J. D. Ullman and Dr. A. V.
Aho are classics of the field.  His most recent work is in the
study of solid modeling, robotics, and information capture and
access.  For his pioneering efforts, Prof. Hopcroft was awarded the
1986 A. M. Turing Award.  He is a fellow of the American Academy of
Arts and Sciences, the American Association for the Advancement of
Science, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, and
the National Academy of Engineering and a member of the National
Science Foundation's National Science Board.
<P>

John and I participated throughout.  Others attending all or part
of the lecture series were Dr. Arthur Diness (Technical Director,
ONR European Office), Dr. Andre van Tilborg (Director of Computer
Science, ONR),  Dr. Charles Holland (Director of Mathematics and
Computer Science, AFOSR), Dr. Norman Metzger (Executive Director of
the Commission on Physical Sciences, Mathematics, and Applications,
National Research Council, National Academy of Sciences), Dr.
Nicholas Bottka (Liaison Scientist for Electronics, ONR European
Office), and Prof. Miroslaw Malek (University of Texas - Austin)
who many of you know from his days at ONREUR.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  This report briefly summarizes the events in order to
provide the flavor of the lecture series.  I will not go into
details or provide conclusions here; a future publication is
anticipated and I will point Realization Report readers to it at
that time.  I omit discussions of dinners or receptions, although
these proved useful methods of making contacts and holding
individual discussions.
<P>

Except in the Federal Republic of Germany, where the arrangements
were made directly with the Center for Mathematics and Computer
Science (GMD), the Academy of Science of the host country was
involved in hosting the lecture and other aspects of the visit.
Prof. Hopcroft's lecture was entitled "Computing, Communication and
the Information Age."  It was a two part talk: the first dealt with
research issues in computational geometry while the second
projected computer science topics that will arise in the 1990's.
The latter's central thesis was that the use of and interface to
the computer will become the key issues in computer science (rather
than the design of the hardware and system).
<P>

Federal Republic of Germany:  John's lecture was at GMD in Schloss
Birlinghoven, just outside of Bonn (see <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>).
Prof. Dennis Tsichritzis, who heads GMD, was John's student some
years ago and the lecture provided an opportunity for them to have
an enjoyable reunion.  The lecture was held in a small castle that
has been refurbished as a lecture hall; there was much artwork,
etc. -- a unique site for a presentation.  It was followed by a
choice of one of four simultaneous demonstrations for both us and
the lecture attendees.  The afternoon featured a round table
discussion on both technical and sociological issues in the future
of computer science.
<P>

Poland:  The visit was designed to overlap with the ONR-sponsored
International Workshop on Models for High-Performance Computing.
This workshop was arranged by Prof. Miroslaw Malek of the Univ. of
Texas (Austin), who also made the arrangements for both John's
lecture and a round table discussion.  We arrived on the second day
of the workshop; Dr. Nico Habermann of NSF had given an invited
talk on the opening day.  The workshop had a strong selection of
U.S. and Western European attendees as well as a good
representation of Polish computer scientists within the specialty.
The workshop closed at noon on the day after we arrived so that
John could give an afternoon lecture at the Staszica Palace to
workshop attendees and others.  The next day John gave a more
specialized lecture on electronic prototyping, followed by
discussions with colleagues from the University of Warsaw and the
Polish Academy of Sciences.  (Note:  After lecturing in a castle
and a palace, John's revised site criteria for his future invited
lectures may provide difficulties for organizers!).
<P>

Hungary:  The one-day visit began with John's morning lecture.
After lunch, John gave a lecture on electronic prototyping that
provided an in-depth discussion of research issues in computational
geometry.  Hungary has an active research community in related
areas and an animated discussion followed.  The day concluded with
a round table discussion with leading Hungarian researchers.
<P>

Russia:  This visit was the longest stopover of the lecture series.
<P>

In addition to John's lecture, several visits and round table
discussions were held.  Institutions visited included Moscow State
University and its Research Computing Center, the Keldysh Inst. of
Applied Mathematics of the RAS, the Computing Center of the RAS,
the Institute of Precision Mechanics and Computer Technology
(IPMCT) of the RAS, and the Dept. of Informatics, Computing
Technology, and Automation of the RAS.  In the course of these
visits we saw the Russian ELBRUS supercomputer and held discussions
with Prof. Babaian, its designer.  The ELBRUS series of
supercomputers uses modular pipelined processors (MKP).  Each MKP
processes a vector and a scalar instruction stream with peak
performance of 500 mflops achievable in each stream.  An unusual
visit was to a special High School for Information Sciences.
Several student demonstrations made it clear that the students are
programming (mostly in C, with some smalltalk, modula2, and lisp)
at a high level of proficiency.  We were impressed that the
projects involved using software packages at an advanced level as
well as programming.  Indeed, all of us judged the entire
scholastic program at this school impressive.
<P>

Ukraine:  Our final stop was a one day event in the Ukraine.  John
gave a morning lecture that was very well attended.  The question
and answer period lasted an hour and a half!  After lunch, the day
concluded with group discussions between us and our Ukrainian
colleagues.
<P>

<a NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  This report is a brief summary of the lecture series.  I
anticipate subsequent publication of an in-depth article.  One
point that was mentioned in all Eastern European stopovers: lack of
hard currency is preventing East European scientists from certain
involvements that are required to be active at the frontiers of
science.  Especially mentioned were the lack of availability of
Western journals and the inability to attend conferences in the
West.  Those of you who receive extra copies of journals as guest
editors or authors may wish to consider forwarding some of these to
colleagues in Eastern European countries for distribution.
<P>

<a NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  Acknowledgements:  The trip was highly successful with well-
attended lectures and much interchange between the U.S. delegation
and senior members of the host country.  Credit for this must be
given to those scientists in the host country who put forth so much
time and effort toward the planning:  Prof. Dennis Tsichritzis, Dr.
Gilbert Kalb, and Dr. Wolfgang Krueger in Germany; Prof. Piotr
Chrzastowski in Poland; Prof. Gabor Renner in Hungary; Prof.
Stanislav Klimenko, Prof. Victor Ivannikov, and Prof. Dmitrii
Koryagin in Russia; and Dr. Slava Knyazhnitsky in the Ukraine.
Special thanks go to Prof. Koryagin and Dr. Knyazhnitsky for the
assistance provided while in Russia and the Ukraine, respectively.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

