<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 25</Title>
<NEXTID=26>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 25</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

The Parallel CFD '93 Conference
.......................... July 21, 1993
<P>

The following report has been provided by Dr. Pierre Leca, Head of
the Parallel Processing Division at ONERA, France.  ONERA is the
French National Office for the Study of Aerospace Research and has
been described in <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>.  Responsibility for any
errors that may have occurred in a minor reformatting/editing is
mine.
<P>

<PRE>
                                        -- Larry Rosenblum
</PRE>

<P>
<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Conference Highlights</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  The Parallel CFD '93 Conference (CFD stands for
computational fluid dynamics) focuses on the entire range of CFD
parallel computation, from pre-processing and methods of solving
partial differential equations (PDE) though post-processing and
interdisciplinary applications.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Dr. Pierre Leca
   leca@onera.fr
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The parallel CFD annual conference provides a platform that
enables applied mathematicians, computer scientists, engineers and
physicists to exchange their experience on parallel algorithms and
numerical methods for efficient flow simulation.  Topics of
interest include pre-processing techniques, cost-effective
solutions of linear and non-linear PDE modeling complex flows,
post-processing techniques, and multidisciplinary applications.
This year's conference was held in Paris on May 10-12 and was
organized by A. Ecer (Purdue Univ.), J. Periaux (Dassault-
Aviation), and P. Leca (ONERA) with the support of the GAMNI
association (Groupement pour l'Advancement des Methodes Numeriques
de l'Ingenieur) and the sponsorship of several organizations and
computer manufacturers.  The Parallel CFD '93 Conference had around
170 attendees with a strong participation from France, Germany, the
United Kingdom, and the United States.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  A diversity of topics was covered by the conference and it
was interesting to notice the importance of PVM software (Parallel
Virtual Machine, a public domain software) as a means to start
experimenting with the message-passing programming model.  Also
noteworthy is the need for the development of domain decomposition
methods to guarantee an efficient implementation of implicit
schemes with unstructured meshes on massively parallel computers.
Further, the use of adaptive meshes on this kind of computer poses
challenging problems of data structure management and load
balancing.  The availability of shared memory would be of great
help.  Some of these problems are being studied within the
framework of APPARC (a consortium of universities and research
organizations that includes ONERA).
<P>

T. Iwamiya (NAL Chofu, Japan) gave a very interesting invited
presentation about the Numerical Wind Tunnel (NWT) Program.  The
talk described the large effort made by NAL to install a very
powerful (more than 200 Gflops peak) 140 processor parallel machine
which has just been designed in conjunction with Fujitsu.  The talk
"Heterogeneous Computational Aeroelasticity" given by Ch. Farhat
(Univ. of Colorado, Boulder) was also noteworthy.  Farhat indicates
that multidisciplinary applications -- the coupling of numerical
models -- is emerging as a new research theme.  The presentation of
P. Schiano (CIRA, Italy) about CIRA activity in parallel CFD also
contained many interesting insights.
<P>

A special session was devoted to the computer manufacturers (with
a panel session moderated by W. Jalby from Versailles Univ).
ARCHIPEL, CRAY Research, IBM, INTEL-SSD, KSR, and TELMAT were
represented.  One must remark that the fuzziness of what was said
about the HPF language seems to indicate that the future of this
language as an emerging standard is not so clear.  A final remark
is about the important participation of the delegates of the
industry:  ALV-List, Aerospatiale, Boeing, CEA, Dassault-Aviation,
DORNIER, EDF, GDF, MATRA, Simulog, and SNECMA all sent some of
their engineers indicating that the use of numerical simulations on
such advanced computers has become of great interest to these
companies.
<P>

Next year the Parallel CFD '94 conference will be organized in
Japan by Dr. Satofuka (Univ. of Kyoto).  This move to Japan instead
of the U.S. shows that advanced techniques for simulating complex
fluid flows attracts a growing community of researchers and
engineers around the world.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

