<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 28</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

Symposium on Parallel Numerical Mathematics (by Eric Grosse)
.......................... September 21, 1993
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Conference Highlights</a><br>
<P>


<a NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a> This Symposium covers recent work in the area of parallel
numerical analysis.  Speakers, drawn from industry and academia,
covered both algorithmic advances and applications of parallel
methods.  Algorithmic topics included matrix computations and
nonlinear optimization while applications included auto crash,
microelectronics, and oil reservoir simulation.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Tom Franklin
   tomf@computer-science.manchester.ac.uk
</PRE>
<P>

<a NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a> The Symposium on Parallel Numerical Mathematics, sponsored by
The Centre for Novel Computing, University of Manchester was held
on Sept. 9-10, 1993.  Located at the Manchester Centre for
Computational Mathematics (U.K.), the Symposium brought together
people interested in parallel computing with a nice balance across
different areas of scientific computing and perspectives from both
theory and practical experience.
<P>

The Department of Pure and Applied Mathematics has an active group
of staff with specialist interests in numerical analysis, who are
responsible for teaching the subject at the undergraduate and
postgraduate level and undertaking and directing research in this
area.  In the recent U.F.C. review of research in British
Universities the Department's record in this area was given a high
rating.  The present head of the numerical analysis group is
Professor C.T.H.Baker.
<P>

<a NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a> A spectrum of parallel architectures were represented in
talks at the symposium:  virtual shared memory (e.g. KSR),
networked workstations, and massively parallel SIMD.  In a pleasing
push toward portability, some of the speakers were even able to
demonstrate good performance on all these architectures.
<P>

Higham made the point that on the KSR machine, only the GEMM matrix
multiply primitive has been highly optimized and he showed how to
get a fast polar decomposition from this.  Kagstrom, building on
the same observation, has built a full collection of matrix-vector
primitives based on GEMM and showed instances in which the package
outperforms even the vendors' tuned libraries on the Cray and the
IBM RS/6000. The GEMM-based BLAS will appear in
<netlib@research.att.com>.  Kagstrom also brought a laptop to
demonstrate CONLAB, implementing the popular MATLAB operations and
augmented by a simulator, compiler, and visualization tools for
parallel computing primitives.  Contact <bokg@cs.umu.se>.
<P>

Sorensen described the implicitly restarted Arnoldi method for
getting a few eigenvalues of huge matrices.  He showed important
applications in computational fluid dynamics, structural analysis,
chemistry, and biology.  To get a copy of the ARPACK code, contact
<sorensen@rice.edu>.
<P>

Bjorstad and Grosse showed good speedups on model problems from oil
reservoir simulation and VLSI device simulation, using the additive
(for MPP) or multiplicative (for networked workstations) form of
the overlapping Schwarz method of domain decomposition.
<P>

Other speakers were:  Filippone (distributed memory architectures),
Gladwell (ordinary differential equation boundary value problems),
Lonsdale (crash-simulation), McKinnon (dynamic programming),
Torczon (pattern search).
<P>

Parsys introduces 25 gigaflop parallel computer
.......................... Sept. 22, 1993
<P>

Parsys, a small British firm, is a spin-off from Thorn EMI which
holds a 16% share of the company.  Parsys began within Thorn EMI,
but spun off as an independent company with L 600,000 ($ 930,000)
of venture capital after Thorn exited the parallel processing
business by selling off INMOS, maker of the Transputer chip.  The
Parsys computers are Transputer-based.
<P>

The Parsys SN9400, the first of a planned range of 9000-series
parallel computers, is being introduced this week at the World
Transputer Congress in Aachen, Germany.  Capable of 25 gigaflops,
the machine will sell for L 4 million ($ 6.2 million).  The machine
is based on the 3.3 million transistor INMOS T9000 Transputer chip,
released this March after a prolonged delay.  The current T9000 is
slower than the INTEL Pentium chip, but claims advantages in the
communications link between processor and memory segments so that
data can be moved more rapidly.
<P>

