<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 29</Title>
<NEXTID=30>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 29</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<A HREF = "rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.disclaimer.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

<PRE>
</PRE>

The report given below is reprinted with permission of the U.K.'s
Dept. of Trade and Industry.  It presents an excellent overview
of the structure of ITC programs within the European Community
(EC) and how these programs are viewed by a member nation.  The
report will be of value to those wanting an overview or even
needing a reference to the occasional acronym appearing elsewhere
for a European ITC program.
<P>

Portions of the current program for ESPRIT III, the major
Community IT program, have been described in detail in
<a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>, <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>, and <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a> 
and observations about ESPRIT
and its structure can be found in those reports.
<P>

A few comments and conclusions (from the report and from my
discussions with European program managers):
<P>

<PRE>
 -- ITC is expected to become the largest single economic
      sector within the EC, totaling 10% by the year 2000.
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- Future programs will be more focused and more  downstream
      (i.e. toward end-user products).
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- Some tensions remain between the roles of EC programs
      and those of individual countries.
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- EC project funding will continue at up to the 50% level,
      with the industrial partners expected to contribute the
      remainder.
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- The previous item may be a contributing factor to
      concerns about how well the programs are serving
      smaller potential industrial partners.
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- Funding requires consortiums with members from at least
      two countries; competitive benefits are given to those
      with member(s) from the poorer EC countries.
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- Projects with a large number of potential partners will
      experience increased scrutiny in the review process.
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- The lack of mobility for researchers between countries
      (language, pensions, benefits, etc.) remains a concern.
</PRE>

<PRE>
 -- Virtual reality is expected to be a component in the
      Fourth EC Framework (starting in 1995) within ESPRIT,
      RACE, and the telematics programs.
</PRE>

<PRE>
                                             -- Larry Rosenblum
</PRE>

<PRE>
                R&D IN EUROPE: THE GENERAL SCENE
</PRE>

Information and communications technologies are only one part,
albeit the largest part, of Europe's collaborative research and
development effort.  This effort is focused through a variety of
complementary programmes and mechanisms to achieve various common
objectives.  Most programmes are conducted under the auspices of
the European Community, though some schemes have a wider
participation.  This introductory article aims to sketch the main
strands of collaborative European R&D in general, with later
articles focusing on aspects of the information and
communications technologies.
<P>

The European Community took the first step towards the
coordination of research in a broad structure in 1984, with the
first Framework Programme covering the years 1984 to 1987.  The
second Framework Programme (1987-91) marked the adoption of a
comprehensive political strategy on technology, as part of the
Single European Act.  The aim of this policy is to strengthen the
international competitiveness of European industry in
high-technology sectors in the face of competition - above all
from the U.S. and Japan - in global markets.  The third Framework
Programme (1990-94) is under way and plans for the fourth are
being discussed.
<P>

Europe cannot afford, nor is it necessary, to tackle every area
which offers future potential.  The aim is to concentrate on
projects that can be conducted more rationally, more
cost-effectively and more efficiently at European level, and
which promise real added value as a result of cross-border
cooperation.  The success of the European projects depends to a
large extent on their innovative value, and the success of the
single internal market will depend to a large extent on the
application of this innovation.
<P>

The current Framework Programme covers research in six areas,
grouped into three categories:
<P>

<PRE>
     (1) Enabling technologies:
          Information and communications technologies
          Industrial and materials technologies
     (2) Management of natural resources:
          Environment
          Life sciences and technologies
          Energy
     (3) Management of intellectual resources:
         Human capital and mobility.
</PRE>

The focus of the collaborative industrial projects in the
Framework programme is precompetitive research, and their funding
is on a shared-cost basis, with the Community providing up to 50%
of the cost.  Shared-cost actions involve contracts with industry
and universities; other funding mechanisms for Community R&D
include "direct action", as for the EC Joint Research Centre;
"concerted action", involving the coordination of national
efforts; and "cooperative research action", where the Community
contributes to the cost of collaborative projects for small
firms.
<P>

Other European initiatives include several whose memberships
extend beyond the member-nations of the EC.  Examples include
EUREKA, a series of industry-led collaborative development
projects for new products or services (with public funding at the
discretion of national governments); COST (Cooperation on Science
and Technology), a concerted-action programme of collaborative
projects across a broad range of technologies; the European Space
Agency; and the European Science Foundation, a non-governmental
agency whose members are national scientific societies and
research councils.
<P>

It is the intention of the Commission and the EUREKA Secretariat
to seek enhanced synergy between these two complementary
mechanisms.  However, the management and funding structures are
quite different and should not be confused.
<P>

IT AND COMMUNICATIONS:  ESPRIT AND ELSEWHERE
<P>

Within the "enabling technologies" part of the, EC's
Framework-III Programme, the Information and Communications
Technologies (ICT) effort is focused on three specific
initiatives.  These are the European Strategic Programme for
Research and development in Information Technology (ESPRIT);
Research and development in Advanced Communications technologies
in Europe (RACE); and the Telematics Programme.  This article
outlines their history and current status, beginning with points
from a recent report commissioned by the European Commission from
an independent review board chaired by Dr. Wisse Dekker, chairman
of Phillips Electronics.  The "Dekker Report" undertook rigorous
evaluation of some significant elements of the second Framework
Programme.
<P>

A competitive arena:
<P>

The Dekker review board declared in its report that extensive use
of information and communication technologies coming from an
indigenous industrial base will be highly significant in assuring
future prosperity within the EC.  European ICT output now
represents about 5% of EC gross domestic product, and on only
modest growth estimates it will reach 10% ~ and will represent
the largest single economic sector by the year 2000.  Virtually
all the working population is affected by the products of these
industries, and a similar proportion of other services and
industrial sectors depend on ICT for their efficiency and
competitiveness.
<P>

The Community's ICT industries are facing unprecedented
pressures.  Margins are being eroded as markets are opened to
full competition, high levels of investment are needed to develop
and manufacture the next generation of products, faster response
times are essential to remain competitive in the marketplace,
with related pressures on quality, delivery and price.
<P>

Despite all this, the review board believed that Europe's
industry was capable not only of surviving, but also of thriving
in this highly competitive arena.  Industrial horizons must be
set on international markets, and companies must be strong enough
to play a major part in global alliances as they develop.
<P>

<PRE>
 From its assessment of the ICT industrial scene and the
</PRE>
positioning of industrial scene and the positioning of European
industry, Dekker concluded that industry rooted in Europe must be
supported and encouraged through Community actions in order to
sustain high-quality employment and raise the level of ICT
services to enhance European competition.  Dekker considered in
turn ESPRIT, RACE and DRIVE activities in Framework 11.
<P>

ESPRIT
<P>

For the IT community, ESPRIT is the best-known of all the
European R&D initiatives.  Launched in 1984, virtually in
parallel with Britain's Alvey Programme of advanced IT research,
ESPRIT I was the result of action by the Commission in response
to a call by the so-called "Round Table" of 12 leading European
IT companies.  The aims of the programme were to underpin the
technology base of the IT industry, foster collaboration, and
assist in the standards arena.  ESPRIT I (1984-88) was followed
by ESPRIT II (1988-92) and the current programme, ESPRIT III,
launched in 1991.
<P>

As with all the EC ICT programmes, the essence of ESPRIT is
collaboration across national boundaries.  The programme is open
to companies, academic institutions and research bodies; projects
must as a rule involve organisations from at least two
member-states; and the basic level of Community support is 50% of
project costs.  The current ESPRIT III covers six technical
areas:
<P>

1.  Microelectronics.  Here the aim is to strengthen the
Community's capability in the design and manufacture of
leading-edge integrated circuits and to ensure their ready
availability in Europe.  This is seen as complementary to the
Joint European Submicron Silicon Initiative (JESSI), a EUREKA
project.  The emphasis is on application-specific integrated
circuits (ASICS) because of their wide applicability.
<P>

2.  Information processing systems and software.  Objectives are
to apply software-intensive systems design and engineering to
user needs; develop information servers and their interfaces
appropriate to user tasks and level of expertise; and develop
advanced architectures and their applications.  High-performance
computing and networking now constitutes a separate area in its
own right.
<P>

3.  Advanced home and business systems and peripherals.  Work in
this area aims to develop user-friendly support or cooperative
working; promote the development and use of multimedia systems;
develop loosely coupled distributed systems; and promote the
introduction of the "intelligent home".
<P>

4. Computer integrated manufacturing and engineering.  This area
covers the whole range of CIM activities including architectures
and communications, the design of manufacturing systems and
products, management and control, and robotics and shop-floor
systems.
<P>

5.  Basic research actions.  Intended for academic and other
research organisations rather than for industry, these research
actions aim to improve the potential for future advances in
information technologies, reinforce interdisciplinary links and
ensure the environment for training tomorrow's researchers
through research itself.
<P>

6.  Open microprocessor initiative.  This horizontal initiative
will interact with and build on the results of all the
technological areas, and on standards and other developments
worldwide.  The goal is to extend the concept of open systems and
standards to the microprocessor systems environment.
<P>

According to the Dekker review board, ESPRIT II's achievements
are impressive.  The programme has had a major impact on European
cooperation between companies, between industry and academia, and
between organisations in different countries.  ESPRIT has been
responsible for a cultural change in the ITC community in Europe,
whereby a whole generation of scientists and engineers are now
thinking on a European, rather than national, level.
<P>

Since the beginning, ESPRIT has involved over 1,500 participants
in over 600 projects, and good techno-logical results have been
achieved.  But in the view of the review board - while accepting
that projects were precompetitive and not directed towards
product development - the industrial "yield" has been
disappointing and there had been little focus on standards,
particularly in the microelectronics area.  Also, many of the
positive results are not in core business areas or in
significantly large market sectors.
<P>

After a comprehensive assessment of the various elements of the
organisation and performance of ESPRIT, Dekker concluded by
arguing as follows: The programme should not continue in its
present form.  ESPRIT's industry-led, technology-push approach is
capable of producing good results but is not achieving the lift
in European competitiveness that is now called for.
<P>

The scope of ESPRIT has been so broad, and the objectives built
into the programme so numerous, that its sense of strategic
direction has been dissipated.  To clarify the focus and reduce
administrative overheads, a set of smaller, interrelated
programmes, each with just a few key objectives is now needed.
User needs should receive greater emphasis.
<P>

RACE
<P>

The aim of RACE is to establish a strong European manufacturing
industry in broadband communications, and to accelerate the
emergence of a competitive Community market for
telecommunications equipment and services, while working towards
uniform standards throughout Europe.
<P>

In its first phase, the programme developed Integrated Broadband
Communications (IBC) demonstration equipment and standards, and
created a technological base for advanced IBC equipment and
services.  The second phase, part of Framework III, is focusing
on eight priority areas:
<P>

<PRE>
      IBC research and development;
      Intelligence in networks; flexible communications
        resource management;
      Mobile and personal communications;
      Image and data communications;
      Integrated services technologies;
      Information security technologies;
      Advanced communications experiments;
      Test infrastructures and interworking (a horizontal
        R&D area supporting the other seven areas).
</PRE>

RACE projects involve collaboration between industry, academic
institutions and telecommunications operators.  Up to 50% of
project costs may come from Community funds.
<P>

In the report, Dekker noted that RACE had a positive impact in
encouraging European public network operators to work together to
map out the way in which advanced telecommunications networks
should develop; and had succeeded in accelerating the
standardisation process.  Also, a number of exploitable results
had emerged as spin-offs along the way.
<P>

Dekker noted an important difference in the impact of RACE
between the two main market areas with intelecommunications-
switching and transmission equipment for the public network
operators; and customer equipment.  RACE had concentrated on the
former sector where, after a period of consolidation European
companies were strong both in markets and technology.  Europe was
much weaker in customer equipment, though new opportunities would
open up in areas such as new mobile communications products and
video telephones.
<P>

Since RACE had successfully completed its consensus - building
and network specification tasks, Dekker suggested that the
programme should not be continued in its present form.  This was
not to say that telecommunications research should not continue
to be supported; opportunities to capitalise on the strong
technological position of the European telecommunications
industry should emerge within the demand-side focused themes,
which the board proposed should be identified for a successor
programme.
<P>

DRIVE
<P>

The DRIVE programme differed from ESPRIT and RACE in having a
very low budget, but its objectives were clear, demand-side and
pan-European.
<P>

A number of DRIVE projects pursued long-term and highly ambitious
goals, such as vehicle and curbside communications systems to
ensure a safe convoy driving with minimal driver attention.
Other projects would have an impact in the shorter term, based
more on systems integration than on additional research effort.
A continuation of this dual approach, preferably in two separate
future programmes, would help to raise Europe's competitiveness,
Dekker suggested.
<P>

Another beneficial feature of DRIVE projects, noted by Dekker, in
comparison with ESPRIT and RACE (which were dominated by
industrial and academic participation) was the involvement of
service providers and city and regional authorities.  National
purchasing authorities had begun to work with potential suppliers
from other countries, so making a positive contribution towards a
single market in procurement.
<P>

The Telematics Programme
<P>

Projects in this Framework Ill programme are designed to
stimulate the development of a trans-European electronic
information exchange infrastructure.  Though sharing basic
characteristics with other Community programmes - international,
precompetitive, industry-led, eligible for 50% from Community
funds - the Telematics programme differs from them in two
important respects: the projects are based on existing
technologies, wherever possible, and in Framework II are
concentrating on the needs of users in seven specific sectors
throughout the Community.  The sectors are:
<P>

1.  Trans-European networks between public administrations: To
facilitate inter-operability of networks and systems between
member states, in order to help implement the "four freedoms of
movement" - goods, persons, services and capital - arising from
the completion of the Single Market.
<P>

2.  Transport services: Building on the former DRIVE - Dedicated
Road Infrastructure for VEhicle safety - Framework II programme
discussed above and relevant EUREKA projects, to improve the
safety and efficiency of passenger and goods transport services,
to reduce the impact of transport on the environment.
<P>

3.  Health care: Building on the former AIM - Advanced
Informatics in Medicine - programme, to develop tools, techniques
and practices supporting a common European approach to
health-care, informatics, and telecommunications.
<P>

4.  Flexible and distance learning: Building on the former DELTA
- Developing European Learning through Technological Advance -
programme, to pursue implementation strategies, technology and
system development, and pilot testing and validation.
<P>

5.  The libraries programme: Among other goals, to promote the
availability and accessibility of modern library services
throughout the Community; introduce new information technologies
into libraries cost-effectively; and encourage standardisation.
<P>

6.  Linguistic research and engineering: To develop a basic
linguistic technology for computer applications, where natural
language is an essential ingredient, in order to help overcome
language problems within the Community.
<P>

7.  Telematic systems for rural areas: Among other goals, to
create the conditions for geographically dispersed small
businesses to provide more diverse employment opportunities and a
more balanced economic activity in rural areas; and establish a
basis for improved services to dispersed and isolated
populations.
<P>

<PRE>
     NATIONAL VERSUS EUROPEAN: THE QUESTION OF SUBSIDIARITY
</PRE>

The vexed question of subsidiarity within the European Community,
debated at length in Britain's consideration of the Maastricht
Treaty, is highly relevant in the context of collaborative
research and development.  Which activities are better conducted
nationally, and which ones demand a European dimension?  And,
looking ahead, what are the implications of cooperation on a
global scale, as research and development patterns increasingly
reflect global industrial trends?
<P>

Community actions in research, technological development and
demonstration must respect the principle of subsidiarity, the
European Commission declares in its working papers for Framework
IV, "whereby the Community takes action in accordance with the
thematic content of this framework programme only if and insofar
as the objectives of the action cannot be sufficiently achieved
by member-states and can, therefore, by reason of scale or
effects be better achieved by the Community".
<P>

Large projects, for example, may be too expensive to be mounted
nationally and, if they can strengthen the technology base of
Community industry, then it may be desirable to mount them on a
European basis, despite the higher total costs inherent in
collaboration.  But size is not the only criterion.
<P>

In essence, the main benefits of joint European programmes and
projects are that: costs are pooled; risks are shared;
potentially profitable cross-frontier collaborative links are
forged; access is provided to new ideas; and influence can be
exerted over emerging standards and specifications.  However, the
total mass of European S&T can only be mobilised effectively if
the European programmes remain transparent and open.
<P>

There are also drawbacks: international joint projects usually
take longer and cost more than national ones, and make great
demands on management time, they restrict flexibility; they raise
questions of intellectual property rights; and they can suffer
from participants objectives.  On the other hand, success in
jointly overcoming the problems of today's projects will ease the
solution of tomorrow's.
<P>

All collaborative projects make sense only if each of the
participants has some special expertise or other resource to
contribute to the venture.  This sometimes results when an
organisation obtains specific expertise in a national programme.
<P>

National collaborative projects and programmes can share many of
the benefits listed above for international collaboration.  They
are appropriate in the many cases where the nature, scale and
scope of the project do not require action at the international
level.  Planning and execution of U.K. National IT programmes
takes full account of European programmes.  Britain aims to avoid
duplication of effort, but complementarily and synergy go further
than this.
<P>

National programmes are important in teaching companies how to
collaborate, in building national technological strengths and in
overcoming particular market failures.  U.K. programmes also aim
to plug gaps, so that specifically U.K. priorities are covered.
National technology-transfer activities also have a role in
promoting the uptake of European-developed technology within the
U.K.  National academic research projects provide credibility for
groups to launch into European ventures, while enhancing the U.K.
training environment in key areas of science.
<P>

The perceived interactions between European and U.K. national
research objectives and actions will help shape the British
Government's forthcoming White Paper on U.K. science and
technology.  Thus, there are changes afoot both nationally and in
Europe this year, as Britain's science policy is redefined and
Europe's next Framework programme moves towards final definition
and approval.
<P>

Historically, there are clear parallels in broad aims between the
U.K. Alvey Programme and the Community's ESPRIT in the early
1980's.  Together, the two programmes built up a collaborative
research culture which is now the norm.  Both programmes featured
joint projects between industry and academia but, initially, only
the British programme included academic - only basic research
projects - adopted by the European programme in ESPRIT II.  In
the academic projects as in the industrial ones, there must be
real complementarity between the partners; projects must be
conceived as European proposals for sound reasons.
<P>

In both European and national collaborative projects, industrial
representation has been strong from the larger companies, who
have been quick to recognise the benefits.  For small and
medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), however, the overheads of
collaboration have proved a formidable deterrent especially where
those overheads extend to European collaboration - though these
companies can be well-placed to carry research through to
exploitation.
<P>

Both the Commission and national governments are making a
determined effort at present to improve the extent and quality of
coordination between national and European programmes, not only
in research, but in technology transfer also.  In recent years,
ESPRIT activities have been a key input in the selection of areas
to be addressed in national programme!  In other words, to try to
adjust the national activities, to achieve complementarity with
the European programmes.  Now the expectation is that national
activities will themselves influence the European programmes.
<P>

Participation in national R&D programmes can prepare companies
for collaborating in European programmes and projects, one result
of which is to gain access to new technology arising from the
larger-scale activity.  The same principle is now beginning to be
applied between Europe and the rest of the world, with Europe
similarly gaining access to new technology arising from global
cooperation in research.
<P>

TOWARDS FRAMEWORK IV.
THE IMPACT OF MAASTRICHT
<P>

As a result of the Treaty on European Union (the Maastricht
Treaty), the fourth Framework Programme will be much broader in
scope than its predecessors.  As well as continuing the R&D
patterns established in the earlier programmes, the new framework
will extend to encompass also all R&D carried out in support of
the Community's major common policies-such as agriculture,
fisheries, energy and transport.  Limits for the total annual
expenditures on Community research and development for the years
1993-1999 have been agreed, but the pattern of this spending
within the fourth Framework Programme has yet to be decided.
<P>

The European Commission has initially identified three
fundamental objectives for Framework IV. to support industrial
competitiveness; contribute to satisfying society's needs; and
support the various common policies of the Community.  "An
appropriate combination of continuity and novelty" in addressing
these aims is suggested.
<P>

The Framework Programme is likely to embrace four types of
activity - (1) cooperative research, technological development
and demonstration programmes within the Community; (2) a
broadening of cooperation on such programmes with outside nations
and international organisations; (3) dissemination of results and
technology transfer from the Community programmes; and (4)
stimulation of the training and mobility of researchers in the
Community.
<P>

The Commission's initial proposal is that the first of the above
four main activities should address 35 core themes, grouped in
five broad areas: (1) information and communication technologies;
(2) industrial technologies; (3) environment; (4) life sciences
and technologies; and (5) energy.
<P>

In the area of information and communication technologies, the
core themes are likely to include key elements for IT systems,
software engineering and best practice, high-performance
computing and networking image technologies, electronic networks
and linguistics, ICT support for function integration in
manufacturing, advanced communications, information exchange
between administrations, and technologies for integrated and
optimised transport systems.
<P>

Actions in these research areas would be complemented by
initiatives in the other three proposed activities:
<P>

<PRE>
       R&D cooperation would be strengthened with industrialised
     nations outside the Community; with central and eastern
     European countries; with developing countries and with other
     European bodies and schemes; and thought the existing COST
     (European Cooperation in Science and Technology) mechanism.
</PRE>

<PRE>
       Beneficial application of R&D results would be encouraged
     by improving the flow of information between research and
     industry; between research and the scientific community;
     between research and society; by technology transfer leading
     to the integration of technologies by industry; and by
     special incentives for small and medium-size enterprises.
</PRE>

<PRE>
       Training and mobility of researchers in the Community
     would be stimulated by easing post-doctorate mobility
     between countries; developing Community networks for
     cooperation; increasing cooperation between industry and
     academia; and providing incentives for developing new
     skills.
</PRE>

In new guidelines for Framework IV, put forward recently by
Antonio Ruberti, the Commissioner responsible for research policy
and education, a key element is the shift in emphasis away from a
set of programmes and activities, and towards the framing of a
Community research policy.  Since the Community's own research
effort represents less than 4% of total government research
funding in the 12 member-states.  Professor Ruberti foresees
greater integration between national and European activity,
including closer coordination between laboratories and some
networking mechanism for technology assessment.  Limited
financial and human resources imply also a greater selectivity in
research, according to Professor Ruberti, including a greater
concentration on generic technologies which have a wide
industrial impact.
<P>

These are the general principles within which the future
programmes and projects in the information and communication
technologies are expected to be mounted.  The Framework IV
Programme is seen as one of the first implementations to follow
the ratification of the Maastricht Treaty, and processing of the
Commission's proposals by the European Parliament and Research
Council is expected to take about six months.  It had been hoped
that ratification in June 1993 would lead to the implementation
of Framework IV by the end of the year, but delays in the
ratification process could affect this timescale.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

