<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 32</Title>
<NEXTID=33>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 32</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<a href="rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.europe.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

First Eurographics Workshop on Virtual Environments + Other Refs.
...................................... January 3, 1994
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Software Design for VR</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  Human Factors</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Additional Remarks</a><br>
<b>6.0  </b><a href="#[6.0]">  Additional VR references</a><br>
<P>


<a href="#[2.0]" NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  The First Eurographics Workshop on Virtual Environments was
held on Sept. 7th in Barcelona, Spain as part of the Eurographics
annual conference.  The workshop resulted from discussions between
Eurographics and the ONR European Office and was designed to
provide a venue for European and U.S. researchers to discuss
current activity.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Dr. Martin Goebel, Workshop Chair
   Fraunhofer Inst. for Computer Graphics (FhG-IGD)
   Wilhelminenstrasse 7
   D-6100 Darmstadt, Germany
   email: goebel@igd.fhg.de
</PRE>
<P>

<a href="#[3.0]" NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  One goal of the ONR European Office is to initiate new
activities such as workshops on emerging scientific topics in order
that scientists world-wide can have the opportunity to meet,
discuss, evaluate, and simply get to know each other's work.
Discussions between myself and European and U.S. colleagues
indicated that virtual reality was a good topic for a new European
activity.  Accordingly, I engaged in discussions with colleagues on
the Eurographics Board of Directors about generating a Workshop.
The result was the 1st Eurographics Workshop on Virtual
Environments, held on Sept. 7, 1993 as one of four Eurographics
workshops that preceded the Eurographics '93 annual conference in
Barcelona.  The Workshop was supported in part by the ONR European
Office and the U.S. Army Research Institute European Coordination
Office.  The fine organizational job performed by the Workshop
Chairman, Dr. Martin Goebel of FhG-IGD, and the Local Arrangements
Chairwoman, Prof. Danielle Tost of the Polytechnical University of
Catalonia, contributed greatly to the Workshop's success.
<P>

<a href="#[4.0]" NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  VR software toolkits are now being designed to assist in
developing a VR environment.  One European commercial system, dVS
by Division Ltd., was described in <a href="rosenblum.002.html">REALIZATION REPORT #2</a>.  The
paper "Virtual Design - A Generic Virtual Reality System" by P.
Astheimer, W. Felger, and S. Mueller of the Fraunhofer Institute
for Computer Graphics (IGD) in Darmstadt, Germany describes another
approach.  The toolkit has been designed and applied primarily for
applications such as architecture, interior design, and historical
reconstruction that creates photorealistic scenes.  A radiosity
system precalculates the color value of polygon patches and an
integrated ray tracer is also used.  The IGD toolkit is based on a
central data storage scheme with both runtime modules (such as a
collision detector) and configuration-time modules (such as the
radiosity calculator) using the central data storage.  Objects are
grouped into sets for modeling.  For rendering they are transformed
into a flat and referenceless but fast, interpretable cache
structure.  Libraries are provided for graphics, acoustics,
simulation, display, navigation, and interaction.
<P>

"Design Issues for Virtual Reality Systems" by Roger Hubbold, Alan
Murta, Adrian West, and Toby Howard of the University of
Manchester, England, presented a discussion of central issues to
the design of a software VR architecture.  Key issues are the
support of diverse and complex applications, the demand for high-
quality interaction with its associated time management problems,
and the need for maintaining a continuity of the experience.  The
paper discussed some of the numerous and complex trade-offs which
must be made in a VR software system design.  The Univ. of
Manchester's system, AVIARY, provides a hierarchical and extensible
model where processes are linked by a communications system.
AVIARY interprets and controls the virtual world using processes
that fall into the categories of human input, output to the user,
virtual environment managers, and virtual environment servers.  A
main goal is to provide platform independent parallel and
distributed processing.
<P>

<a href="#[5.0]" NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  "The Virtual Treadmill: A Naturalistic Metaphor for
Navigation in Immersive Virtual Environments" by M. Slater, A.
Steed, and M. Usoh of the University of London, England, gave
results from an experiment to judge people's reactions to traveling
in an immersive environment by "walking on the spot".  A tracking
sensor on a head-mounted display provides positional data of head
motions while the participant performs a variety of actions,
including walking in place.  A pattern recognizer learns to
recognize the participants walking motions.  Movement in the
virtual environment is then achieved by simulating the kinds of
kinesthetic actions and sensory perceptions involved in walking.
This method was compared to the alternative of using a hand-held
pointing device.  Preliminary results, based on a small sample
size, suggest that the walking on the spot method may enhance the
participants sense of presence, but there is not yet sufficient
evidence to suggest that it is advantageous with respect to the
efficiency of navigation.  Some subjects did become tired; this is
an obvious limitation of requiring human motion.  Further
experiments are planned.
<P>

<a href="#[6.0]" NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  There were several U.S. papers, including an invited talk by
Steve Bryson of NASA/Ames on "Why Application Development is So
Hard - Virtual Reality as a Research Field," and a panel discussion
was held that included both U.S. and European experts.  Both Bryson
and the panel noted how few actual applications yet exist, although
good prototypes are certainly becoming more commonplace.
<P>

There are tentative plans to expand the Workshop into a two day
event at Eurographics 94 in Oslo and then make VR a significant
part of the Eurographics 95 conference in The Netherlands.  The
European Commission may also provide funding for the 94 event.  In
any event, Workshop participants expressed the view that the event
was valuable and merited continuation in an expanded format.
<P>

The Workshop proceedings were published as EG93 VR - Eurographics
Technical Report Series ISSN 1017-4656.  Expansion of the papers
into a book was anticipated by the Workshop chairman.
<P>

<a href="#[1.0]" NAME="[6.0]"><b>[6.0]</b></a>  Three other recent publications may be of interest to those
wanting more detail on European activities in VR:
<P>

[1]  "European Activities in Virtual Reality," J. Encarnacao, M.
Goebel, and L. Rosenblum, IEEE Computer Graphics and
Applications, Vol. 14, No. 1, Jan. 1994.
<P>

[2]  Virtual Reality Systems, RA Earnshaw, MA Gigante, and H.
Jones (eds.), Academic Press, London, UK, 1993.
<P>

[3]  Computers and Graphics, M. Goebel (ed.) Vol. 17, No. 6, Nov. 1993.
<P>

[1] overviews numerous European activities and briefly discusses
European funding.  [2] has an international set of authors, but
focuses primarily on European activities.  [3] was a special issue
on VR with many European papers.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

