<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 33</Title>
<NEXTID=34>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 33</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<a href="rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.europe.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

Information Technology (IT) Projects in the U.K.
....................... Jan. 26, 1994
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Sleep Analysis with Neural Networks</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  Racecar Performance Monitoring and other BCS IT Award winners</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  HCI Reduces Commercial Aircraft Pilot Error</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Flame Detection by Imaging</a><br>
<b>6.0  </b><a href="#[6.0]">  New Communications Signal Processing and Coding Initiative</a><br>
<b>7.0  </b><a href="#[7.0]">  Telematics Program Review</a><br>
<P>


<a href="#[2.0]" NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a>  Abstract:  This report, taken primarily from selected
publications of the U.K.'s Department of Trade and Industry (DTI),
examines several IT projects of interest.
<P>

<a href="#[3.0]" NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a> NEURAL NETWORKS ASSIST IN UNDERSTANDING SLEEP DISORDERS
<P>

The Department of Engineering Science of the University of Oxford
is collaborating with the Oxford Medical Division of Oxford
Instruments in a project to develop an automated system for the
analysis of sleep disorders.  The evaluation of sleep disorders is
one of the fastest growing sectors of US and European healthcare.
It relies principally on the continuous analysis of the
electroencephalogram (EEG) during sleep.  At present, a set of
rules proposed more than 20 years ago is still being used by human
experts to classify successive 30 second segments of the EEG sleep
record into one of six categories (wake, dreaming sleep, and four
stages of progressively deeper sleep), but the rules are
notoriously difficult to apply and inter-observer correlation is
often very low.  The lack of agreement among trained human experts
on all but very typical data segments has made the automation of
the 'sleep scoring' process an almost impossible task.
Consequently, there is no expert system available for the analysis
of the sleep EEG.
<P>

It as been suggested that neural networks might offer a promising
alternative for problems such as these, where the extraction and
application of rules are tasks that cannot be performed very
reliably.  Over the last 4 years a sleep-analysis system was
developed.  It is based on a radial-basis function (RBF) neural
network architecture that combines both unsupervised and supervised
learning.  Starting with no a priori assumptions about the number
of states which may exist within the EEG during sleep, a clustering
analysis using a Kohonen feature map was performed on a database
consisting of EEG signals parameterized on a 1 second time scale
using a 10-coefficient Kalman filter.  The topology preservation
properties of the Kohonen algorithm made it possible for the
trajectories generated by successive frames of coefficients to be
tracked over time.  Three distinctive types of trajectories in the
sleep EEG were identified and a description of the sleep process
was obtained at the output of the RBF network, which claims to be
more precise than the arbitrary six-state classification of the
rule-based system.
<P>

The neural network analysis system has now been used to analyze not
only whole-night recordings from normal subjects but also the EEG
of patients with severe sleep disorders whose records had
previously been deemed to be unscorable.  The University of Oxford
has been working with Oxford Medical to transfer the neural network
technology and first prototypes should be available in early 1994
for evaluation in a number of clinical centers.
<P>

Further information: Dr. Lionel Tarassenko, Department of
Engineering Science, University of Oxford, Parks Road, Oxford OX1
3PJ.  Tel:  0865-273-151.
<P>

<a href="#[4.0]" NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a> SYSTEM FOR RAPID PROTOTYPING AND MONITORING OF RACING CARS
WINS BRITISH COMPUTER SOCIETY (BCS) IT AWARD
<P>

A computerized system for monitoring the performance of the McLaren
Formula One racing car is one of the winners of this year's BCS
Information Technology Awards.  The success of the McLaren racing
team is dependent upon its back-up team, and in McLaren's case the
back-up team's success is dependent on its wholly integrated
approach to engineering, using computers at the design and
manufacturing stages.  The system also monitors the car during the
race and allows the data to feed back into the design process.
<P>

Other winners this year were ICL for DAIS, which provides
technology that allows the development and integration of business
applications across a variety of hardware and software platforms.
It provides tools that allow users both to protect their existing
investment in database technology and to utilize modern, client-
server technology.
<P>

Thames Water Utilities were the third winner, for the trunk
scheduling system for the London Water Ring Main.  PC-based
scheduling for optimization of pump usage led to an ability to
incorporate a high degree of automation within the repetitive
scheduling task.
<P>

<a href="#[5.0]" NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  CUTTING PILOT ERROR IN COMMERCIAL AVIATION
<P>

Since the 1960s, commercial aviation has witnessed a substantial
reduction in the number of accidents per passenger mile.
Unfortunately, over the same period, the percentage of accidents
ascribed to pilot error has remained constant.  Many instances of
pilot error can be traced back to a lack of situational awareness;
either the crew misinterpreted the information with which they were
presented, or the speed and complexity of events allowed too little
time for correct decision making.
<P>

The MBRAWSAC (Model-Based Reasoning Applied to Warning Systems for
Aircraft Cockpits) project has brought together a multi-
disciplinary team in a three-year investigation of solutions to
this problem of situational awareness.  The partners in this
collaboration are Smiths Industries Aerospace and Defence Systems,
British Airways, and the University of Bristol Department of
Psychology.  Funding has been provided by DTI and the UK Science
and Engineering Research Council (SERC) through the Joint Framework
for Information Technology (JFIT).
<P>

The project has two main strands:  system design and human factors.
The starting point for the research has been an examination of
existing warning system design.  In the modern cockpit, aircraft
system information is provided by a central warning system.  Should
a malfunction occur, primary system parameters can be displayed on
a central panel together with associated warning messages.
Interpretation becomes difficult for the pilot when malfunctions in
one system lead to abnormalities in related systems.  When this
results in multiple warning, aircrew must identify the most
important symptom, or the root cause of the problem, in order to
take appropriate action.
<P>

The human factors team have used structured interviews and a large-
scale questionnaire survey to identify pilots' requirements for
advanced warning systems, and to assess difficulties associated
with current designs.  Meanwhile, the aim of the system effort has
been to use model-based reasoning techniques to achieve early
detection of malfunctions, together with isolation of primary
causes.  An additional feature of this work has been the
combination of goal hierarchies and constrain-satisfaction methods
to generate sequences of recommended crew actions in the event of
complex or multiple failure situations.  Work is also being
undertaken to determine how the information generated by the new
system can best be displayed.
<P>

Further information: Dr. C.R. Ovenden, Smiths Industries Aerospace
and Defence Systems, Bishops Cleeve, Cheltenham, Glos GL54 4SF.
<P>

<a href="#[6.0]" NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  FLAME DETECTION BY IMAGING
<P>

Conventional fire detectors are essentially single-element infrared
and/or ultraviolet devices.  While these can be extremely sensitive
to the characteristic electromagnetic radiation emitted by flames,
they are also liable to be put into alarm by everyday sources such
as arc-welding, lightning, torches, hot machinery, etc.
<P>

Reducing the incidence of false alarms is particularly important
for high-risk installations where an alarm may mean activation of
a suppression system or an automatic call to the emergency
services.  Another disadvantage of a single element detector is
that the signal is integrated over the field of view, so that
signals from small distant fires will be lost in the background
radiation.  In response to the need for a detector that does not
suffer from the above problems, the Signal Processing Group at
Cambridge University Engineering Department and a team from Kidde-
Graviner Ltd. (a division of Fire and Safety International) have
joined forces to work on developing and building one of a new
generation of fire detectors.  This incorporates an imaging system
in the form of a monochrome CCD video camera (made to work in the
near-infrared by means of a colored glass filter) which constantly
surveys the risk area, coupled to dedicated processors which take
the incoming data and execute algorithms to decide whether or not
a flame is present.  It is intended that the imaging detector
should be capable of recognizing flames in a way similar to that
used by the human brain.
<P>

The real-time system, which uses a field-programmable gate array
for the initial grabbing and preprocessing of the incoming image
data, and RISC processors for the algorithm implementation, will
shortly be ready for field testing.  Real-time tests will enable us
to decide on the ultimate form of the detection algorithm.  Current
working algorithms include the use of spatial and temporal
statistics of flames, neural networks classifiers, and
morphological filters.  Depending upon the results of the real-time
testing, one, or some combination, of these techniques will
ultimately be used.  It is envisaged that a working prototype
system will be available by December 1993.
<P>

Further information: Dr. W.J. Fitzgerald, Signal Processing and
Communications Group, Cambridge University Engineering Department,
Trumpington Street, Cambridge, CB2 1PZ, Tel:  0223 332 719.
<P>

<a href="#[7.0]" NAME="[6.0]"><b>[6.0]</b></a>  NEW SERC FUNDING INITIATIVE FOR COMMUNICATIONS SIGNAL
PROCESSING AND CODING
<P>

The Communications and Distributed Systems Committee is launching
a new research initiative in communications signal processing and
coding (SPC).  SPC represents a core element of information
technology, and forms an important growth area in electronics.
Over the last 5-10 years there has been a vast increase in the
application of signal processing and coding techniques in civil and
military electronic systems.  In Europe today, digital signal
processing and coding products and systems form a billion dollar
market.  The long-term goal of the new Program is to ensure that
algorithm development in the universities proceeds in parallel with
VLSI processor development and industrial system applications.  The
SPC approach to this goal is to bring about substantial
improvements in the processing algorithms on which future smart
communication systems will be built.
<P>

Projects supported under the Program will be of two types:
academic-only, and collaborative with industry (although funding
will not be available to industrial partners).  The call for
proposals has been circulated, and the closing date for the first
round of applications will be 1 March 1994.
<P>

For further details: Secretary to CDS Committee:  Deborah Miller,
Room 0062, SERC, Polaris House, North Star Avenue, Swindon, SNA
1ET, tel:  0793 411 436, E-mail sdpm0@uk.ac.rl.ib.
<P>

<a href="#[1.0]" NAME="[7.0]"><b>[7.0]</b></a> TELEMATICS REVIEWED
<P>

The Mid-Term Review Board, under the chairmanship of Brian Oakley,
has recently completed its report on the Telematic Program.
<P>

The Board was asked to review the Program as a single entity with
reference to the objectives of the Framework Program as a whole,
and to the Framework Telematics Program in particular.  The latter
included the contribution of the JFIT Telematics Program to the
furtherance of Community policies in the various application areas,
strengthening of the scientific and technological basis of European
industry and achievement and success of the internal market.
<P>

The report recognizes that the seven areas of the Program are
largely concerned with applications and with applications systems
engineering.  This means that user involvement is not just
desirable, it is essential if successful exploitation is to be
achieved.  When the user involvement is strong, and the users
themselves know what they want and are prepared to cooperate to
achieve it, the Program is at its best.
<P>

The Board found a very general welcome for the Telematics Program
and enthusiasm from the project participants.  Principal
recommendations and conclusions included:
<P>

<PRE>
  *  the Program needs a stronger strategic vision for the future;
  *  the Program should be kept together and run by a single team;
  *  continued user involvement is essential to meet objectives;
  *  the Program should be organized to maximize development and
       use of generic solutions;
  *  the development of relevant standards remains a high priority;
  *  the Board recommends a substantial increase in the budget for
       telematics, an activity where systems development work is
       likely to lead to exploitation.
</PRE>

Further information: Keith Gunner, DTI, Tel:  071-215-1227.
<P>

<hr>
