<HEAD>
<Title>THE REALIZATION REPORT: Issue No. 34</Title>
<NEXTID=35>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>THE REALIZATION REPORT: 
Issue No. 34</H1>
<hr>
<H3>by
<a href="rosenblum.html">Larry Rosenblum</A>,
<a href="onr.europe.html">ONR FFO European Office</A>
</H3>
<hr><p>
<i>The ONR European Office Computer Science Newsletter that
focuses on
European and Middle Eastern activities in data visualization,
virtual reality, and enabling technologies for these
disciplines.
</i>
<hr><p>

Scuola Superiore Sant'Anna:  VR force feedback dataglove and
shoulder exoskeleton.
..........................February 15, 1994
<P>

<strong>Contents:</strong><br>
<b>1.0  </b><a href="#[1.0]">  Abstract</a><br>
<b>2.0  </b><a href="#[2.0]">  Background</a><br>
<b>3.0  </b><a href="#[3.0]">  GLAD-IN-ART + dataglove</a><br>
<b>4.0  </b><a href="#[4.0]">  The Shoulder-to-hand force feedback exoskeleton</a><br>
<b>5.0  </b><a href="#[5.0]">  Other ARTS Lab projects</a><br>
<P>


<a href="#[2.0]" NAME="[1.0]"><b>[1.0]</b></a> This report features the research of Prof. Massimo Bergamasco
of the Robotics Laboratory of the Scuola Superiore Sant'Anna.  The
focus is research to develop datagloves and exoskeletons for VR.
<P>

<PRE>
<b>Contact:</b>
   Prof. Massimo Bergamasco
   Scuola Superiore S. Anna
   Via Carducci, 40
   56127 Pisa, Italy
   Tel: +39 50 560108
   fax: +39 50 559215
   email: bergamasco@sssupl.sssup.it
</PRE>
<P>

<a href="#[3.0]" NAME="[2.0]"><b>[2.0]</b></a>  The Sant'Anna School of University Studies and Doctoral
Research of Pisa was set up in 1987 by merging the School of
University Studies and Doctoral Research with the Sant'Anna
Conservatoire.  Both institutions have long traditions.  The School
of University Studies and Doctoral Research can be traced back to
the Ferdinand I College and the Puteano College.  The Ferdinand
College was founded in 1593 at the behest of the Grand Duke to
admit students of the Faculties of medicine and law.  The Puteano
College was founded in 1605 by Archbishop Carlo Antonio Dal Pozzo
to admit students of the Faculties of medicine, law, and philosophy
who came from the town of Biella.
<P>

The 1987 merger created a single institution that was modeled on
the Scuola Normale Superiore (of Pisa) which has a long history as
a distinguished Italian university for arts and science.  With the
University of Pisa also present, the small city of Pisa -- about a
50 minute train ride west of Florence -- is a major scientific
research center for Italy.
<P>

The School is composed of two branches:  The Faculty of Social
Sciences which includes economics, management, law, and political
science, and the Faculty of Experimental and Applied Sciences which
includes Agrarian Studies, Engineering, and Medicine.  The School
of Engineering focuses on Bioengineering, Innovation Management,
Information Technology, Microelectronics, and Robotics.
Specialties are sensors and measurement of biomedical parameters,
architectures for real-time information systems, software
engineering, solid state electronic devices, component development
techniques, and robotic systems for applications in non-structured
environments.  The school is small and admission is highly
competitive based primarily on national testing.
<P>

The Advanced Robotics Technical Systems (ARTS) laboratory was
established in 1986 by Bergamasco and another professor, both from
the University of Pisa.  It focuses on virtual environment issues,
the control of industrial robots including the development of
tactile sensors for robots, and the use of robots for biomedical
applications.
<P>

The school, incidently, is a short walk from the Leaning Tower of
Pisa.  The Tower leans because of unstable soil exacerbated by a
particularly heavy bell tower at the top.  The Tower has been
closed for some time while engineering efforts are being made to
prevent further "leaning", so I was not able to climb up for the
"panoramic" view of Pisa.
<P>

<a href="#[4.0]" NAME="[3.0]"><b>[3.0]</b></a>  GLAD-IN-ART (Glove-Like Advanced Interface for the Control
of Manipulation and Exploratory Procedures in Artificial Realities)
is an ESPRIT funded project.  As noted in earlier discussions of
ESPRIT (see <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>, <a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>, 
<a href="rosenblum.001.html">REALIZATION REPORT #1</a>, <a href="rosenblum.002.html">REALIZATION REPORT #2</a>), these projects
are multi-partner collaborations which must span at least two EC
countries.  For this project the participants are AITEK SRL (IT),
Scuola Superiore Sant'Anna (IT), Trinity College Dublin (IRL),
Video Display Systems (IT), and Technology Applications Group (UK).
<P>

One goal of the project, now successfully completing after 3 years,
is to develop an instrumented glove to be worn by the human
operator and capable of recording the hand geometrical
configuration in the control space.  This information is used to
control a virtual hand in artificial space and allow more natural
and accurate interactions than could be achieved with other 3D,
interactive devices.  The project developed kinesthetic and force
feedback sensations for the users wrist and hand.  Proposed
applications are remote operations (telepresence) in space and
hostile environments, physiotherapy, and biomedical robotics.
<P>

The dataglove structure wraps around the hand and supports
kinesthetic sensors for the fingers.  Flexion-extension and
abduction-adduction movements are recorded by the sensors.  The
glove has 12 motors, one for each phalanx of each finger (i.e. 3
per finger) with the little finger excluded.  The glove contains 23
sensors.  Each finger has 3 strain gage sensors and one magnetic
sensor.  Two mechanical sensors and one made of conductive plastic
monitor the wrist joint.  The final force feedback glove will use
only strain gages for force and conductive plastic for all fingers
and other points of measurement.
<P>

A computer model with graphics has been developed for the
dataglove.  The model contains 28 contact points for the phalanges
and 3 for the palm.  Understanding the geometric areas of contact
with an object for different user motions is generating both
tactile feedback requirements and also a physical-based model that
can determine if an object has been picked up.  The latter will
improve on current models that just measure geometrical proximity
for this purpose.
<P>

<a href="#[5.0]" NAME="[4.0]"><b>[4.0]</b></a>  I must be unlucky with prototype datagloves, for the glove
was being repaired and I was unable to test it (see also
<a href="rosenblum.005.html">REALIZATION REPORT #5</a>).  However, I was able to test the other
component: a shoulder-to-hand force feedback exoskeleton system to
which the glove will attach.
<P>

The system is a 7 degree-of-freedom (DOF) exoskeleton wrapping up
the whole arm and supported by the shoulder and trunk of the
operator.  It is gravity compensated, so that the operator does not
bear the weight of the system.  The DOF's match the corresponding
human joints:  flexion-extension and abduction-adduction at the
shoulder, rotation of the arm, flexion-extension of the elbow,
prono-supination movement of the forearm, and flexion-extension and
abduction-adduction of the wrist.  Each joint on the exoskeleton is
actuated by means of DC servomotors located on the structure.  The
motion of each joint is obtained through a tension, tendon-based
transmission system that includes complex cable routings for the
elbow and forearm joints.  Torque sensors measure the differential
tension of the cables actuating each joint.
<P>

I tested the system by moving around and against a simply modeled
geometric object containing planar sides in virtual space.  The
results were impressive as the system was responsive and the force
feedback strong and accurate.  The response delay to my movements
was noticeable, but this was attributable to the need to process
using several workstations: two low-end SGI's for graphics and a PC
with a Transputer card for control with an ethernet connection (a
high-end SGI is being obtained).  The claimed innate system delay
is 2 msec.  Bergamasco has studied the operation of the tendons of
the human forearm and hand.  He notes that the actual interaction
is more complex than the current modeling by one cable to push and
one to pull.  In actuality there is a redundancy of tendons
generating a motion.  Implementation of these ideas is a future
direction.
<P>

<a href="#[1.0]" NAME="[5.0]"><b>[5.0]</b></a>  Tactile feedback is a potentially valuable companion to
force feedback.  A new 5 year EC funded project, SCATIS, is
attempting to develop a tactile sensor that would be sensitive to
both temperature and textures.  Started in 1992, the project's
first year saw a definition and specification of possible systems.
Another EC-funded (TIDE - Technology for Disabled and Elderly
people) project will redesign the GLAD-IN_ART structures of
rehabilitative purposes.  A third project uses a PUMA robot with a
force and tactile sensor attached.  By passing over the surface of
the object, the tactile sensor determines the roughness.  An expert
system performs a classification by hardness and roughness, where
the object has predetermined characteristics from a small class of
objects.  Bergamasco felt that these ideas might be extensible to
a larger class of partially known or unknown objects.  A final
project uses PVDF (a piezoelectric polymer) as part of an
ultrasound sensor to permit the control of wheelchairs by the
disabled.
<P>

<hr>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

