</DOCHDR>
<title>TTCP STP-11</title>

<img src="../gifs/banner-logo.GIF">

<H1>TTCP STP-11 - Secure Information Systems</H1>

<H2>What is TTCP STP-11?</H2>


There is a treaty among the United States, the United Kingdom, Canada,
Australia, and New Zealand called The Technical Cooperation Program
(TTCP), under which collaborative research is organized and relevant
research information is exchanged.  Subgroups are organized under the
treaty, each identified by a letter of the alphabet and covering a
particular technology area.  Under each subgroup there are Technical
Panels (TPs), each identified by a number and covering a particular
aspect of the technology or particular problem.  Subgroup S covers
Communications Technology and Command and Control Information Systems.
Technical Panel 11 (STP-11) is concerned with technology for secure
life cycle management, security architectures and technical strategies
for securing information systems, and security of specific applications
of high military interest.  TTCP works through cooperation and
coordination of research activities;  it has no budget.
<P>
Or, more briefly and bureaucratically:
<blockquote>
STP-11 meets under the auspices of The Technical Cooperation Program (TTCP),
Combined Policy Committee Subcommittee on Non-Atomic Military Research 
and Development (NAMRAD) and is governed by the Policies, Organizations, 
and Procedures in NAMRAD issued under the authority of the Subcommittee 
on NAMRAD of the Combined Policy Committee.  
</blockquote>

<H1>History</H1>

STP-11 began life as XTP-1, under Subgroup X, whose scope was
Computing Technology.  Subgroup X, Technical Panel 1
(or XTP-1, for short) covered Trustworthy Computing Technologies.

XTP-1 first met officially in the fall of 1986.  Since then, a variety
of activities, workshops, and exchanges of software tools for research
and development purposes have been carried out under its auspices.  These
include the development of the RS-232 repeater problem as a test case
for the application of formal methods, numerous exchanges of software
for automated theorem proving, and organization of a workshop on the
effective use of automated reasoning technology.  Current collaborations
include efforts to document research progress in multilevel secure
relational databases, to organize an international ATM INFOSEC
testbed, and to develop generalised threat models. 
<p>
In 1995-96, the TTCP structure was reorganized, and activities
previously carried out under Subgroup X were realigned.  In this
process, XTP-1 was re-formed under Subgroup S as Technical Panel
11 (STP-11) on Secure Information Systems.  The scope of Subgroup
S is Communications Technology and Command and Control Information
Systems.

<H2>Roster (under construction)</H2></a>

<a href="uksecbib.html">
 <H2>UK Security Citations Bibliography (1.4MB)</H2></a>

<a href="epl.html">
 <H2>US and other Evaluated Products Lists</H2></a>

<H2>On-line resources</H2>
<ul>
  <li> Australia
  <ul>
      <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.cs.uq.oz.au/pub/SVRC/techreports/">
           Software Verification Research Centre (SVRC) technical reports</a>
  </ul>
  <li> Canada
  <ul> 
      <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.cse.dnd.ca/pub/">
            Communications Security Establishment technical reports</a>
  </ul>
  <li> United States
  <ul>
      <li> National Institute of Standards and Technology 
           <a href="http://csrc.ncsl.nist.gov/">
            Computer Security Resource Clearinghouse</a>
      <li> Space and Naval Warfare Systems Command, 
           <a href="http://infosec.nosc.mil/infosec.html">
            Information Security Office</a>
  </ul>
</ul>
<hr>
<H2>TTCP Home Pages</H2>
<ul>
