/security/Multics. 

Adobe Systems Incorporated. Postscript Language Tutorial and 
Cookbook. Reading, Mass.: Addison-Wesley; 1988; ISBN: 0-201-10179-3.
/Languages/Postscript/manual.

Adobe Systems Incorporated. Postscript Language Program Design. 
Reading, Mass.: Addison-Wesley; 1988; ISBN: 0-201-14396-8.
/languages/Postscript/manual.

Adobe Systems Incorporated. Postscript Language Reference Manual. 
Reading, Mass.: Addison-Wesley; 1988; ISBN: 0-201-10174-2.
/languages/Postscript/manual.

Adra, Hicham N.; Sandberg-Maitland, William (CGI Information Systems 
& Management Consultants). Formal Verification of a Network Security 
Device: A Case Study. in: 14th National Computer Security Conference; 
1991 Oct; Washington. USA: NIST/NCSC; 1991; 1: pp.226-236. 
An automated formal verification study of a commercial network 
security device, the SmartCrypto, is described. A high level view of 
relevant formal verification techniques using the m-EVES environment 
is given. A description of the SmartCrypto is provided, as well as a 
brief overview of the m-EVES system. The uses and roles of 
Verification plans, environmental and device-specific models, and 
other planning techniques are discussed in the context of this case. 
Observations are made concerning the proof process and the problem of 
tractability which may apply to similar projects.
/Verification/network Security.

Adrion, W. R. Issues in Software validation, verification and testing. 
1980 Sep. 
ORSA/TIMS Bull. (1980 TIMS-ORSA Conf.) 10(80)
/Verification/Testing. 

Adrion, W. R.; Branstead, M. A.; Cherniavsky, J. C. Validation, 
verification and testing of computer software. 1982 Jun. 
ACM Computing Surveys 14(2) pp.159-192
This survey paper describes the alternatives to verification. It 
primarily concentrates on the tools and techniques that can be used for 
testing that programs are correct. A brief discussion of proof based 
systems and of the use of simulations is given.
Exhaustive testing of all but the simplest systems is impossible. The 
paper presents two alternatives to exhaustive testing: functional 
testing, which ensures that each category of use has been tested, and 
structural testing, which ensures that each segment of code is tested
/verification/testing/survey. 

Aerospace Computer Security Conference: Protecting Intellectual 
Property in Space. 1985. 
IEEE Computer Society Press
/security/protection. 

Aggarwal, S.; Courcoubetis, C.; Wolper, P. Adding Liveness Properties to 
Coupled Finite-State Machines. ACM Trans on Programming Languages 
and Systems. 1990 Apr; 12(2): 303-339.
Informal specifications of protocols are often imprecise and 
incomplete and are usually not sufficient to ensure the correctness of 
even very simple protocols.  Consequently, formal specificaiton 
methods, such as finite-state models, are increasingly being used.  The 
selection/resolution (S/R) model is a finite-state model with a 
powerful communcation mechanism that makes it easy to describe 
complex protocols as a collection of simple finite state machines.  A 
software environment, called SPANNER, has been developed to specify 
and analyse protocols specified with the S/R model.  SPANNER provides 
the facility to compute the joint behaviour of a number of finite-state 
machines and to check if the 'product' machine has inaccessible states, 
states corresponding to deadlocks, and loops corresponding to 
livelocks.  So far, however, SPANNER has had no facility to 
systematically deal with liveness conditions.  For example, one might 
wish to specify that, although a communication channel is unreliable, a 
message will get through if it is sent infinitely often, and to check 
that the infinite behaviour of the protocol viewed as an infinite 
sequence will always be in some w-regular set (possibly specified in 
terms of a formula in temporal logic or as an w-automata).  In this 
paper we show that with very minor modifications to the implemented 
system, it is possible to substantially extend the type of properties 
that can be specified and checked by SPANNER.  This is done by 
extending the S/R model to include acceptance conditions found in 
automatons on infinite words, which permits the incorporation of 
arbitrary liveness conditions into the model.  We show how these 
extensions can be easily incorported into SPANNER (and into essentially 
any finite-state verification system) and how the resulting system is 
used to automatically verify the correctness of protocols.
/Algorithms/Verification/Algorithmic Verification 
/Correctness/Finite-state Machines/Verification Tools.

Agha, Gul. Concurrent Object-Oriented Programming. CACM. 1990 Sep; 
33(9): 125-141.


Agnew, C. E.; Baran, P.; Caulkins, D. C.; Cerf, V. G.; Crane, R. C. ARPANET 
Management Study: New Application Areas. 1974 Aug 5. 
Cabledata Associates
(Quarterly technical rept. no. 2, May-Jul 74, R-160, Cabledata 
Associates Inc Palo Alto Calif
/Networks/ARPANET/WAN. 

Ahituv, N.; Lapid, Y.; Neumann, S. Processing Encrypted Data. 1987 Sep. 
Communications of ACM 30(9)
pp.777-780
/crypto. 

Aho, A.; Hopcroft, J.; Ullman, J. The Design and Analysis of Computer 
Algorithms. 1974. 
Addison-Wesley, Reading, Mass
/program design/program analysis. 

Air Force  Cryptologic Support Center (Kelly AFB, San Antonio, Texas). 
Computer Based Instruction for Computer Systems Security Officers - 
an Example. in: 12th National Computer Security Conference; 1989 Oct 
10; Baltimore. USA: NIST/NCSC; 1989: 505-514. 
/security/administration.

Akkoyunlu, E. A.; Ekanadham, K.; Huber, R. V. Some Constraints and 
Tradeoffs in the Design of Network Communications. 1975 Nov. 
ACM SIGOPS OSR 9(5) Proc. 5th Symp. OSP
/Networks. 

Akl, Selim G. Digital Signatures with Blindfolded Arbitrators Who 
Cannot Form Alliances. 1982 Apr. 
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1982 Symp. Security and Privacy
/digital signatures/Crypto. 

Akl, Selim G. Digital Signatures - a Tutorial Survey. 1983 Feb. 
IEEE Computer 16(2) pp.15-24
/crypto/Digital Signatures/tutorial. 

Akl, Selim G.; Denning, Dorothy E. Checking Classification Constraints 
for Consistency and Completeness. 1987. 
Classification constraints are rules for assigning access classes to 
data when they are entered into a database. In order that a given set of 
constraints specify meaningful classes, they should be consistent, that 
is, not define conflicting classes for the same data. This paper gives 
algorithms for checking the consistency and completeness of a set of 
classification constraints defined on a database schema. The 
techniques use computational geometry to compute intersecting 
regions in a multidimensional space, where each region is defined by a 
classification constraint or integrity constraint.
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 196 - 201
This paper follows on from the previous year's paper where 
classification constraints are applied to database views. It argues that:
 classification constraints must be considered with integrity 
constraints, and
 classification constraints must be simple otherwise nobody will 
understand them or their interactions with the other constraints.
However, the need for consistency checks arises from the resultant 
classification by each rule being given as a single value. Since not all 
rules would be expected to be equally important in every case there 
seems to be no reason why all rules applying to an object should result 
in the same classification. Therefore there is no use for the 
consistency checks if the least upper bound of all the classifications 
from the rules is taken. Completeness could be covered by a default 
rule, for example that all objects should be classified according to 
their source.
/security/multilevel security/databases/classification 
constraints/integrity constraints. 

Akl, Selim G.; Taylor, P. D. Cryptographic Solution to a problem of 
access control in a Hierarchy. 1983 Aug. 
Queen's Univ, Kingston, Ontario, Canada
ACM Trans. Comput. Syst. 1(3) pp.239-48
/Crypto/security/multilevel security. 

Akyildiz, Ian F.; Benson, Glenn S. (Georgia Inst. of Technology). A 
Security Reclassifier for a Local Area Network. in: European Symposium 
on Research in Computer Security; 1990 Oct 24; Toulouse. France: 
AFCET; 1990: 85-95.

Albert, A. A. Some mathematical aspects of cryptography. 1941 Nov. 
AMS 382nd Meeting, Manhattan, Kans
/mathematics/Crypto. 

Aleliunas, R. Randomized Parallel Communication. 1982 Aug. 
ACM SIGACT-SIGOPS Symp. Principles of Distributed Computing
/communications. 

Alford, M. W. A requirement engineering methodology for real-time 
processing requirements. 1977. 
IEEE Trans. Software Eng SE-2 pp.60-69
/requirements. 

Allan, Bob. What Managers Really Need to Know About LANs. IEEE 
Network. 1989 Nov; 3(6): 15-19.
/networks/tutorial/LAN/Introduction.

Allen, F. E. Control Flow Analysis. 1970. 
ACM SIGPLAN Notices 5(7) Proc. Symp. Compiler Optimization pp.1-19
/verification/program analysis. 

Allen, F. E. Interprocedural data flow analysis. 1974. 
IFIP Proc. Congress 1974, North Holland, Amsterdam pp.398-402
/verification/program analysis. 

Allen, F. E.; Cocke, J. A program data flow procedure. 1976 Mar. 
CACM 19(3) pp.137-147
/verification/program analysis. 

Almes, G. T.; Lazowska, E. D. The Behavior of Ethernet-like Computer 
Communications Networks. 1979 Dec. 
ACM SIGOPS OSR 13, Proc. 7th Symp. OSP
/Networks/Ethernet/LAN. 

Alvarez, Donald L. (MIT Center for Space Research). Site Preparedness 
for the Next Network Emergency. in: 12th National Computer Security 
Conference; 1989 Oct 10; Baltimore. USA: NIST/NCSC; 1989: 601-604. 
/security/networks/viruses/worms.

Alves-Foss, Jim; Levitt, Karl (University of California). Verification of 
Secure Distributed Systems in Higher Order Logic: A Modular Approach 
Using Generic Components. in: 1991 IEEE Computer Society Symposium 
on Research in Security and Privacy; 1991 May; Oakland, California. 
USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1991: pp.122-135. ISBN: 0-8186-
2168-0.
In this paper we present a generalization of McCullough's 
restrictiveness model as the basis for proving security properties 
about distributed system designs. We mechanize this generalization for 
an event-based model of computer systems in the HOL (Higher Order 
Logic) system to prove the composability of the model and several 
other properties about the model. We then develop a set of generalized 
classes of system components and show for which families of user 
views they satisfy the model. Using these classes we develop a 
collection of general system components that are specializations of 
one of these classes and show that the specializations also satisfy the 
security property. We then conclude with a sample distributed secure 
system, based on the Rushby and Randell distributed system design and 
designed using our collection of components, and show how our 
mechanized verification system can be used to verify such designs.
/Distributed Systems/Verification/TNIU/HOL.

Ambler, Allen L.; Good, Donald I.; Brown, J. C.; Burger, Wilhelm F.; Cohen, 
Richard M.; Hoch, Charles G.; Wells, R. E. Gypsy: A language for 
specification and implementation of verifiable programs. 1977 Mar. 
SIGPLAN Notices Vol 12 (3) pp.1-10 (proc. ACM Proc. Conf. Language 
Design for Reliable Software)
pp.1-10
in: Gehani N, McGettrick A D (eds): Software Specification Techniques, 
Addison-Wesley, International Computer Science Series, ISBN 0-201-
14320-9
Gypsy was developed as an integrated programming and specification 
language to support specification, coding and verification of systems 
software, with particular emphasis on communications software. This 
paper describes the salient features of Gypsy and gives a worked 
example of Gypsy's use that encompasses all of its features
/Verification/Languages/Gypsy/GVE. 

