Bevier, William R.; Hunt, Warren A. , Jnr.; Young, William D. Toward 
Verified Execution Environments. 1987. 
Current verification technology provides tools for the verification of 
programs written in a high-level language. Even verified high-level 
programs may not satisfy their specifications when executed, due to 
errors in lower-level software and hardware. We discuss an attempt at 
eliminating this problem with the design of an execution environment 
consisting of a compiler, operating system and processor, each of 
which has been mechanically verified.
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 106 - 115
Computational Logic are currently employed on a research programme 
to design a verified execution environment. This paper summarises the 
objectives of the programme and the current work status.
The environment will have three principal components: a compiler for a 
formally-specified subset of Gypsy 2.05 called Micro-Gypsy, an 
operating system and a processor (the FM8501). The intention is to 
specify each component in the Boyer-Moore logic and to mechanically 
check correctness using the Boyer-Moore theorem prover.
The choice of language is motivated by the desire to use the existing 
GVE toolset to develop verified application software - in Micro-Gypsy - 
which can then be compiled and run on the verified environment. The 
authors claim that this strategy allows a much higher degree of 
confidence in correct program execution than is possible with 
conventional designed systems, but that 'our belief in correct program 
execution....depends only on the soundness of our verification tools (the 
Boyer-Moore theorem prover and the correct fabrication of the 
processor'.
The paper discusses the verification of a simple multi-tasking 
operating system. The verification results include isolation of tasks, 
protection of the operating system from tasks, correctness of 
operating system services, and correct termination of the operating 
system.
The operating system runs on the lowest level component, the FM8501 
microprocessor, for which implementation of the instruction set of the 
processor (using combinational and sequential circuits) has been 
mechanically verified.
The verification of the compiler, operating system and processor have 
proceeded independently and, as the authors admit, the task of 
integrating this work is not trivial. Future work will address the 
design of a new verified processor which adds some necessary 
facilities missing from the FM8501.
/security/formal specification/verification/hardware/FM8501. 

