Cohen, F. Models of Practical Defenses Against Computer Viruses. 
Computers & Security. 1989 Apr; 8(2): 149.
Note: Abstract in TechGnosis June 1989 (PO689-17).
Prevention of infection by computer virus can only be guaranteed by 
limiting information sharing or functionality.  This paper examines 
complexity-based virus detection mechanisms which detect 
modifications and prevent secondary infections.  The philosophical 
issues involved in providing protection against viruses are discussed 
and the structure of dependencies within an information system is 
considered.  A mathematical model of change control within a trusted 
computer system is described and features of the mechanisms used 
identified.  An alternative to dependency relations is proposed.  
Implementations for untrusted systems are outlined and the optimality 
of the mechanisms employed considered.  The role of the environment in 
viral protection, practical limits of the techniques proposed and 
practical implementations of the systems are discussed.
/security/viruses.

Cohen, Fred. Models of Practical Defenses Against Computer VIruses. 
Computers & Security. 1989 Apr; 8(2): 149-160. ISSN: 0167-4048.
/viruses.

