Cullyer, W. J. Formal Specification of VIPER Microprocessor. 1984. 
RSRE Memo No 3738
/RSRE/Viper/Specification/Architecture. 

Cullyer, W. J.; Pygott, C. H. Application of Formal Methods to the VIPER 
Microprocessor. 1987 May. 
RSRE
IEE Proceedings 134 Pt E (3)
The VIPER 32-bit microprocessor has been invented at the UK Royal 
Signals and Radar Establishment (RSRE) for use in highly safety-
critical military and civil systems. Throughout, formal mathematical 
methods have been used to prove that the gate-level realisations 
conform to a top-level specification. The paper explains the various 
layers of documentation produced, starting with the use of LCF-LSM 
(based on Meta-Language, ML) at the higher levels, proceeding via the 
use of ELLA hardware description language at lower levels, to multiple 
VLSI implementations . It is intended to show that this route for 
designing synchronous VLSI circuits promises a practical means for 
industry to produce validated designs.  Referenced in: Leonard, Timothy 
E., 'Specification of Computer Architectures: Survey and Annotated 
Bibliography'.  ( Cambridge University Computer Laboratory Technical 
Report No. 188)
/formal specification/verification/VLSI/VIPER/LCF/LCF-LSM. 

