Fitch, John A.; Hoffman, Lance J. (George Washington University). The 
Cascade Problem: Graph Theory Can Help. in: 14th National computer 
Security Conference; 1991 Oct; Washington. USA: NIST/NCSC; 1991; 1: 
pp.88-100. 
This paper presents a new approach, based on finding shortest paths in 
a graph, for solving the cascade problem. The result is an efficient 
(O(N^3)) algorithm, where N is the number of security domains in the 
network. The paper provides background on the cascade problem, 
generalises the problem from its traditional military roots, and then 
applies the shortest path technique to a military example. The shortest 
path approach appears quite general and provides a method based on 
established mathematics for evaluating network security.
/Cascade Problem/Graph Theory/Shortest Path/Network Security/Risk 
Analysis.

