Moser, Louise E. Graph Homomorphisms and the Design of Secure 
Computer Systems. 1987. 
In designing and analyzing the structure and security of a large scale 
computer program or system, one is often interested in how it is 
constructed out of pieces or in the flow of information through it. The 
concepts of dependency, connectivity and separability which arise in 
security verification are handled well by graph theory. As is shown in 
this paper, graph homomorphisms are particularly useful for describing 
the hierarchical/modular design of a system and for demonstrating the 
security of information flow.
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 88 - 96
In this paper Louise Moser discusses the application of graph theory to 
the design and analysis of large scale secure systems. Directed graphs 
are used in which the vertices (nodes) represent processes and edges 
(arcs) represent information flow from a source vertex to a destination 
vertex. Graphs therefore provide a simple language in which to express 
the architecture of information systems.
For the specification of secure systems, the paper goes on to discuss 
coloured graphs in which the vertices are 'coloured' (or attributed) with 
the classification of information handled by those processes. 
Homomorphisms are used to characterise valid decompositions of 
systems described by graphs. The paper proves some theorems about 
the properties of homomorphisms and these are illustrated in the 
context of the security related examples.
The content of this paper appears sound and the techniques may be 
useful for specifying the architecture of some systems. The security 
policy enforced by a system is implemented in the colour of the 
vertices and the direction of information flow. A possible drawback of 
this approach is that coloured graphs assume a static labelling of 
vertices. The work described in this paper will only be of interest to 
theoreticians as it is only at an early stage of development and it is 
unclear in which direction it will continue.
/security/multilevel security/information flow. 

Moses, R.;  Clark, E. R. (UK CCTA/BIS Applied Systems  Ltd). Risk 
