Nash, Michael J.; Poland, Keith R. (Gamma Secure Systems, Camberley). 
Some Conundrums Concerning Separation of Duty. in: 1990 IEEE 
Computer Society Symposium on Research in Security and Privacy; 
1990 May 7; Oakland. USA: IEEE; 1990: 201-207. 
Note: This paper describes a commercial two signature 
authorisation/authentication system, which is both sensible and well-
defined and points out that it does not meet the TCSEC criteria or Clark 
Wilson Rules. The paper goes on to describe the implementation of the 
system using the RGL250 portable authenticator. While raising a few 
general points the paper does not contain information of any great 
intellectual density.
This paper examines some questions concenring commercial computer 
security integrity policies.  We give an example of a dynamic 
separation of duty policy which cannot be implemented by TCSEC based 
mechanisms alone, yet occurs in the real commercial world and can be 
implemented efficiently in practice.  We examine and describe a 
commercial computer security product in wide use for ensuring the 
integrity of financial transactions, show that it implements a well 
defined and sensible integrity policy that includes separation of duty, 
yet fails to meet either the TCSEC criteria or the Clark and Wilson 
rules.
/authentication.

