Needham, Roger M.; Herbert, Andrew J. The Cambridge distributed 
computer system. 1982. 
Cambridge University Computer Laboratory
Addison-Wesley
0-201-14092-6
This book describes the philosophy of the system that has grown up 
around the Cambridge Ring at the Cambridge University Computer 
Laboratory. Originally the only machines connected were a number of 
minicomputers (2 PDP/11s, a PDP/7, the CAP computer and a DG NOVA 
computer), and the network was used for file transfer between these. 
There was a spurt of activity that led to a number of other machines 
being added, including a printer server (to which files could be 
transferred). As more machines were added, a 'name server' was 
needed, which was implemented on a Z80-based single card computer; 
this Z80 card was used for many more small server machines, each 
providing a separate service.
The next addition to the network was a number of computers with no 
peripherals other than the network; this required protocols to allow 
machines to be allocated to users, loaded with suitable bootstrap 
programs, talked to by their user, and returned when no longer 
needed/used. In addition to the resource manager to handle these 
machines, there was also a need for a network-wide authentication 
mechanism.
The book describes the current state (February 1982) of the system 
including, in an informal style, the protocols used by the various 
servers.
/Terminal Concentrator/Session Manager/Resource 
Management/Networks/Name Server/File Storage/Distributed 
Computing/Cambridge Ring/LAN/Authentication. 

Needham, Roger M.; Lauer, H. C. On the Duality of Operating System 
