Needham, Roger M.; Schroeder, M. D. Using Encryption for Authentication 
in Large Networks of Computers. 1978 Sep. 
Xerox PARC report CSL-78-4
This paper discusses the use of encryption to achieve authenticated 
communication in computer networks. It presents example protocols 
for the establishment of authenticated connections, the management of 
authenticated mail and for signature verification and document 
integrity guarantee. Both conventional and public-key encryption 
algorithms are considered as the basis of such protocols.
The most important algorithm is the one used for two parties to 
establish a new conversation key for use between them. The method 
employs the services of a trusted (by all parties) authentication server 
which knows the encryption keys of all possible parties. Both private- 
and public- key versions of this protocol are presented.
The problems of this kind of method are related to the inadvisability of 
keeping the secret keys of all participants in the authentication server, 
the difficulty of getting them there and their selective revocation once 
participants suspect that their key has been compromised.
2T6; T93. 
security/protocols/authentication/crypto/Networks/DES/Single 
Key/key management/. 

