Neely, Richard B.; Freeman, James W. Structuring systems for Formal 
Verification. 1985. 
Ford Aerospace and Communications Corp, Palo Alto CA
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1985 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.2-13
This paper describes the problems inherent in system verification 
where the system is considered as a single black box, and describes a 
method of decomposing the system so that the composition can be 
verified.
The concept of a 'Trust Domain' is introduced; each individual trust 
domain is a component with a well defined functional boundary, which 
is entitled to assume the validity of certain assertions about its 
environment. In return, there are certain properties about its behaviour 
that can be expected, and these typically form part of the 
environmental assertions of other trust domains.
A trust domain can be 'verified' by proving that within the limited 
scope implied by the environmental assumptions it will not allow any 
violations of its derived constraints. An 'untrusted' component is a 
trust domain with no derived contraints; within the assumed 
environment it has no restrictions.
A language has been developed to describe trust domains and their 
structural and contraint relationships, for example: 'node domain A 
shall contain boundary node C; adjoin link B; associate C with B; derive 
for B constraint Y; constraint Z; receive from C constraint X; end A;'. 
This language has been used to describe the Multinet Gateway System, 
and work is underway to translate TD descriptions to Gypsy 
automatically.
Trust domains appear a useful tool to describe components of 
distributed system, where the policy imposed by each component is 
several levels down from the overall security policy, and where a 
number of configurations may require verification. The technique is not 
restricted to multilevel security, and has the advantage that the proof 
of individual trust domains should be understandable.
/Verification/Trust Domains/Multinet Gateway/Decomposition/Gypsy. 

Neilson, J. O.; Wuebker, F. E. Design Experiences from the Multilevel 
