Nessett, D. M. (Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory). Layering 
Central Authentication On Existing Distributed Terminal Services. in: 
1989 IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy; May 1; Oakland, 
California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 1989: 290-299. 
Note: This paper deals with the implementation of a secure logon 
protocol in the context of a distributed system with a single 
administering authority. The implementation is achieved by an attempt 
to layer the authentication protocol over existing terminal protocols. 
The intent is to evaluate the feasibility of this approach in general and 
also to establish requirements in terminal architecture design that 
would help to support secure logon.
The need for centralised authentication becomes apparent when 
considering the procedures necessary to expurgate an infiltrator and 
restore secure operations when the password database is scattered and 
partially replicated throughout a distributed system.
The paper discusses logon protocols, comparing around the horn with 
remote procedure call protocols. It concludes that the former is 
more secure as host logon information does not have to pass through a 
potentially vulnerable terminal process, however it suffers from the 
disadvantage that most terminal protocols require session initiation by 
the terminal process rather than the contacted host.
Despite these security considerations, the system implemented uses 
the RPC protocol, as the horn protocol could not be easily layered above 
an existing virtual terminal protocol.
VMS systems linked by DECNET were chosen as the test architecture. 
The virtual terminal protocol (for technical reasons) was chosen to be 
CTERM. This apparently has a rather RPC flavour and is was principally 
this that led to the decision to use an RPC logon protocol despite the 
security considerations. It is proposed to support session security 
labelling (not supported by the host architecture) by means of trusted 
terminal multiplexers.
There are a number of (unsolved) problems:
 underlying architectures have a significant effect on the choice of 
logon protocols;
 the question of authorization is still not addressed;
 the protocol is sensitive to the underlying virtual terminal protocol, 
leading to increased maintenance costs;
 passage of reusable host logon information through a vulnerable 
terminal process leads to a risk of disclosure;
 if such a disclosure occurs then (in the RPC format) there is no easy 
method to support distribution of information about the compromise, 
since an advantage of RPC is that there is no need for authenticator-
host protocols to be set up;
 multi-level security - the multiplexor solution leads to the need for 
dedicated hardware and net work topology constraints.
The paper concludes with a list of recommendations to future system 
designers which basically boil down to a statement that if secure logon 
protocols and session security labelling are required in a distributed 
environment, then full consideration should be given to these 
requirements at the concept design stage.
/authentication/networks/protocols.

Nessett, Dan M. A Critique of the Burrows, Abadi and Needham Logic. 
ACM OSR. 1990 Apr; 24(2): 35-38.

Nessett, Daniel M. Factors Affecting Distributed System Security. 1986 
Apr. 
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1986 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.204-222
This paper describes some important factors, other than node 
evaluation levels and network topology that affect distributed system 
security; these factors may invalidate attempts extend existing 
concepts of single-computer security to networks. Those discussed 
include the difficulty of integration with existing systems, perhaps 
with different physical environments which may vary with time; and, 
the lack of a single authority with responsibility for the overall 
security of the networked systems.
