Parenty, Thomas J. (Sybase). The Incorporation of Multi-Level IPC into 
UNX. in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy; May 1; Oakland, 
California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 1989: 94-99. 
Note: This presentation covered the six types of inter-process 
communication (IPC) provided by the UNIX operating system. These 
were: Files, Pipes, FIFOs, Shared Memory, Messages and Semaphores.
All of the above mechanisms work well provided all processes sharing 
the object are at the same security level. Covert channels appear, 
however, once multi-level use is attempted.
The covert channel produced by multi-level file sharing arises out of 
the ability of a highly classified process to manipulate shared locks to 
a file. This can be read by a less classified process as it tries to set an 
exclusive lock on the same file. A solution is proposed that makes use 
of Reed and Kanodias eventcounts and sequencers.
A covert channel is possible when using pipes and FIFOs between 
processes operating at different security levels. When the pipe 
capacity is reached then the highly classified process may affect the 
lower classified process by either reading from the pipe or not. Two 
solutions are suggested, both of which involve the relaxation of the 
integrity of the pipe.
A similar problem arises with the use of message queues. The author 
mentioned that this problem has already been solved the Trusted Mach 
operating system and that this solution is equally applicable to UNIX.
Semaphores can be used with no changes in their semantics except 
those restrictions based on security levels which decide which 
processes can perform which operations.
The overall conclusion of the presentation was that although secure 
multi-level communication was not possible in UNIX as is, by making a 
few changes to some underlying mechanisms and by implementing some 
additional system calls it should be possible and that such 
modifications would simplify the building of trusted and untrusted 
multi-level applications using UNIX.
/security/multilevel security/operating systems/UNIX.

Parker, Donn B. Computer Abuse Perpetrators and Vunerabilities of 
