Patkau, B. H.; Tennenhouse, D. L. The Implementation of Secure Entity-
Relationship Databases. 1985. 
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1985 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.230-236
The Entity-Relation Data Model views a database as a collection of sets 
which are themselves collections of elements; sets are entity sets or 
relation sets; relationship sets each connect groups of entity sets, and 
each relation in the set references one element in each element set in 
the group. The model is suitable for knowledge bases used for expert 
systems or intelligence work. This paper describes the implementation 
of an E-R DBMS for a 'large civilian non-industrial organisation doing 
investigation', and the security policy which was based on an Access 
Group Model. An Access group is a set of users with common rights; 
users belong to one or more groups, each resource belongs to one group, 
and resources can only be accessed by those in the owning group. The 
first order security violations that the system attempts to prevent are 
unauthorised retrieval or modification. The second order violations, 
existence detection, might happen accidentally with low probability, 
but deliberate attempts would be detected before they worked. The 
third order violations, interference, do not appear to be discussed in 
the paper.
