Pernul, G. (University of Vienna, Austria). Security Constraint 
Processing During Multilevel Secure Database Design. 8th Annual 
Computer Security Applications Conference; 1930 Nov 4; San Antonio, 
Texas. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1992: pp. 75-84. ISBN: 0-
8186-3115-5.
Security constraints effect the structural as well as the dynamic part 
of a database. Thus, a design technique for multilevel secure databases 
must capture both the semantics of the data as well as the behaviour of 
the system. We describe the technique of applying a semantic data 
model to express the semantics and secrecy of data and of applying 
data flow diagramming to describe the impact on the security of the 
system functions. For this purpose we develop secure data schemas and 
secure function schemas. As secrecy constraints defined on the data 
and on the functions are influencing each other the design technique 
offers a joint data/function-based design for the construction of 
multilevel secure databases.
/semantic data model/data flow diagram/multilevel secure database.

Pernul, G.; Luef, G. (University of Vienna). A Multilevel Secure 
Relational Data Model Based on Views. in: 7th Annual Computer Security 
Applications Conference; 1991 Dec; San Antonio, Texas. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1991: pp.166-177. ISBN: 0-8186-2280-6.
In order to overcome certain limitations when applied to relational 
databases, a data model is introduced that is not fully based on the 
Bell-LaPadula security paradigm. The starting point is a conceptual 
relational database schema and a set of views, representing user 
groups and applications. Based on the definition of views, the relations 
of the conceptual schema are decomposed in a set of disjoint 
fragments. Fragments and views are the granularity of data to which 
we provide automated security labeling. In order to keep fragmented 
databases consistent during database update we give algorithms used 
to keep the integrity. Databases based on this model contain data at a 
variety of classifications, serve a set of users cleared only to access 
certain data items and may be implemented by using a general purpose 
database management system extended by a trusted component 
supporting mandatory access control.
/databases/relational databases/multilevel security/Models.

