Note: This paper attempts to address data integrity by means of non-
interference-style policies. One result is that post hoc authorisation is 
allowed, in contrast to earlier work.
	Each transaction has an author, and some other system user must 
act as 'authoriser' for that transaction; the 'authoriser' will be 
different for different types of transaction, but separation of duty 
requires that the authoriser is always distinct from the author
	The author derives an appropriate non-interference-style purge 
function and non-interference statement such that unauthorised 
transactions do not affect the future course of the system and the data 
therein.

