Popek, Gerald J.; Farber, D. A. A model for verification of data security 
in operating systems. 1978 Sep. 
UCLA
CACM 21(9) pp.737-49
This describes the verification of the kernel of the UCLA secure 
operating system. The paper gives a specification language suitable for 
describing an abstract machine and defines security properties with 
respect to that description; it then applies these to the UCLA kernel. 
Finally it discusses the verification of the kernel.
An abstract machine is described by its state together with a set of 
instructions that operate on that state. The state of the system is 
defined in terms of objects; the instructions of the abstract machine 
are defined by the objects that they access. The security property of 
such an abstract machine is defined in these terms.
The specification notation is then applied to the UCLA kernel. The 
verification is discussed, but not in detail. The discussion deals with 
verifying that the specification of the kernel agrees with the security 
model, and that the specification of the kernel is consistent with the 
code that actually implements it.
/Verification/UNIX/UCLA UNIX/Trojan Horse/Security/security models. 

