Proctor, N. The Restricted Access Processor: An Example of Formal 
Verification. 1985. 
SYTEK
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1985 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.49-55
The Restricted Access Processor (RAP) is a guard device being 
developed by CSC for NASA; SYTEK is responsible for developing a 
suitable security model and TLS, verifying the model and TLS 
correspond, and demonstrating the code to TLS correspondance. The 
paper describes how two rounds of the verification process were 
performed, and the techniques in use for the third round.
The RAP is intended to connect uncleared users to a system containing 
both classified and unclassified data, so that the former type can be 
accessed while ensuring the latter is neither read nor altered. All 
message blocks released by the RAP are to be validated and sanitised; 
if any block is invalid, all blocks of the message are to be logged. 
Blocks containing classified data can be recognised as invalid.
The first round was primarily a feasability study, to show that 
verification was practicable. The model was written with a Pascal-like 
syntax, and was about 7 pages long; the TLS, in SPECIAL, was about 67 
pages. A formula generator was produced which took the TLS and a set 
of invariants and produced a set of lemmas to be proved. A theorem 
prover was also developed, that took a set of formulae and applied a 
series of simplifications; any formula that could not be simplified to 
TRUE was automatically split into a number of formulae which were 
then simplified; if unproven, these were output to the user who could 
resubmit them. The major problem with the prover is the user had little 
control over the way it worked.
For round two, the model was rewritten in SPECIAL, with simplified 
phrasing and all existential qualifiers eliminated, and the TLS was 
revised. The theorem prover was replaced by a checker, driven by user 
commands. The model increased to 12 pages to SPECIAL, and the TLS to 
90; to prove the 300 formulae took 20 hours CPU time on a VAX to 
process the 18000 commands needed. The task was made possible by 
makeing the checker automatically save command lists, which could be 
edited and replayed at will.
A change in the RAP design required a third round, still ongoing. The 
major change to the tools for this stage was to simplify the use of 
command lists. The main conclusions so far are: keep prover simple and 
so user-predictable; keep manual checks simple; use simple 
expressions in TLS; use a restricted subset of SPECIAL; and, allow 
proofs to be reused.
/Verification/RAP/RAP Guard/Guard/formal 
specification/security/theorem proving/theorem checkers/SPECIAL. 

Proctor, Norman; Wong, Raymond (Odyssey Research Associates & 
Oracle Corporation). The Security Policy of the Secure Distributed 
Operating System Prototype. in: 5th Annual Computer Security 
Applications Conference; 1989 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1989: pp.95-102. ISBN: 0-8186-2006-4.
The experimental Secure Distributed Operating System, SDOS, is the 
first software development project to use a composable property as its 
mandatory security policy. The security policy also includes a fine 
granularity of discretionary access control immune to Trojan horse 
attacks. The high degree of assurance that composability makes 
practical and the richness of the discretionary controls lead SDOD to 
employ balanced assurance, that is, the assurance measures are fitted 
to the portion of the security policy whose enforcement is being 
assured. Like the Cronus distributed computing environment it is 
derived from, SDOS uses an object model with abstract operations on 
various types of system objects and permits an application to extend 
the paradigm to new types of application objects with new operations. 
The SDOS security policy and enforcement can likewise be extended for 
an application's security policy and enforcement.
/Secure Architectures/distributed systems/operating systems/SDOS.

