Rangan, P. Venkat (University of California - Berkeley: Computer 
Science Division). An Axiomatic Basis of Trust in Distributed Systems. 
in: IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy; 1988 Apr 18; Oakland Ca. 
Washington DC: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1988: pp.204-211. ISBN: 
0-8186-0850-1.
Note: Both the lecture and the paper were very difficult to appreciate 
and to follow: the lecture in particular suffered from a surfeit of 
information.
The concept of trust is extremely important in computer security: 
without it systems cannot be both secure and functional. This paper 
attempts to formalise trust using a modal logic in which beliefs may 
be expressed - trusts are then proper axioms used derive the truth of 
beliefs.
The paper introduces a logic of belief in which the beliefs of agents can 
be expressed. The semantic interpretation of belief is based on a 
possible-world semantics.
A system is modelled as a set of agents capable of sending and 
receiving messages. The state of a particular agent is the set of 
messages sent and received by that agent. The state of the system is 
the set of agent states. Each agent can hypothesise about the global 
state of the system from their local states. These 'guesses' at the 
global states are known as possible states and are characterised for 
each agent by the possibility relation.
Informally, an agent will believe a proposition if that proposition is 
true in every state that that agent currently considers possible.
The agent believing a proposition is not the same as that proposition 
being true. The truth of beliefs is derived by trusts.
Trusts must be true in all possible states. This is achieved by placing 
constraints on the possibility relation that force the trust to be true. 
These constraints are on the possible states and so consequently on the 
messages that an agent can send or receive.
The paper demonstrates this through examples that are extremely 
difficult to follow. In themselves the examples are very simple and it 
is difficult to ascertain whether the complexity is inherent in the 
theory or in the exposition. The underlying motivation about 
formalising trust is valid and worthy of further research.
Computing systems are evolving into large distributed systems 
interconnecting organizations and even countries.  The relationships 
among these organizations are characterized by the need for 
competition and cooperation without a common trusted  agent.This 
paper presents an axiomatic theory of trust in distributed systems.  
The paper introduces basic notions about developing a logic or theory, 
and shows that modal logics of belief, with their Kripke style possible-
worlds semantics, are appropriate for basing a theory of trust on. A 
modal logic of belief is reviewed, and a model of the distributed 
system is constructed so that the logic is sound and complete with 
respect to the model.  Any sentences in the logic may then be added to 
the logic as axioms and these axiomatic sentences are considered as 
trust specifications.  Methods to map a formal trust specification on to 
mechanisms for its implementation in the distributed system. are 
presented.  Trust and security are closely related in distributed 
systems.  Security specification and verification methods can be 
integrated into the theory of trust.  The trusts required in public key 
based secure communication are analyzed.  A theory of trust has many 
applications, such as design of authentication servers based on trust 
relationships, and design of mechanisms that are tolerant to failures in 
trusts.
/security/security models/trust/distributed systems.

Rao, K. N. (Hughes Aircraft Co.). Security Audit for Embedded Avionics 
Systems. in: 5th Annual Computer Security Applications Conference; 
1989 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1989: 
pp.78-84. ISBN: 0-8186-2006-4.
This paper describes the design of security audit subsystems for real 
time embedded avionics systems. The selection criteria of auditable 
events and the design of the audit functions are described. The data 
storage requirements and the data compression features of embedded 
avionics systems are analyzed. Two data compression algorithms 
applicable to avionics systems are described. Huffman encoding is 
optimal but Fibonacci encoding is shown to be nearly optimal and better 
suited for airborne avionics systems. The memory capacity needed for 
audit data storage is computed for typical avionics missions.
/Audit/Avionics/Data Compression.

