RSRE. The SMITE Modular Compilation System. : RSRE; 1988 Mar; 
SMITE/CLH-15. 
Note: This paper gives an outline of the ideas underlying the Modular 
Compilation System to be used in the SMITE secure computer.  This 
system prevents users losing track of which generation of source text 
gave rise to which object code, by binding both together into an 
abstract data object, called a module.  Operations give access to the 
latest versions and require both to be updated together.  Linking 
modules together to form an executable object is performed 
automatically, so it becomes impossible to forget to relink after 
updating a module.  Configuration control and mixed language working 
can also be provided.
7T/0.
SMITE.

RSRE. SMITE on a Chip. : RSRE; 1987 Mar; SMITE/SRW-6. 
Note: This paper proposes using the design principles of RISC 
architecture, the Ten15 abstract machine and the essential protection 
properties of capability computers, to produce a single chip SMITE CPU.  
The intention is that these CPUs could be combined into multi-
processor configurations up to the limits imposed by the bus.
7T/0.
SMITE.

RSRE. The SMITE Object Oriented Backing Store. : RSRE; 1988 Mar; Memo 
4147. 
Note: The SMITE system will support high assurance, yet flexible multi-
level secure applications.  The SMITE multi-processor capability 
computer is being developed, based on RSRE's Flex computer 
architecture, to provide a suitable environment.  This paper describes 
the protection mechanisms built in software on top of these.
7T/0.
SMITE.

RSRE. SMITE-RSRE's Computer Architecture for Multi-level Security. 
Malvern: RSRE. 

RSRE. SMITE-RSRE's Computer Architecture for Multi-Level Security. 
Malvern: RSRE; 1988 Sep; SMITE/PCB&SRW-28. RSRE. 
Note: This paper describes the overall SMITE programme and highlights 
some of the demanding research topics which must be solved to produce 
high assuracne, high functionality computer architectures.
Operational requirements for government command information 
systems (CISs) are increasingly calling for a combination of 
sophisticated database management systems with high assurance 
multi-level security.
Unfortunately, the secure computer architectures currently available 
can only deliver functionality at the expense of assurance, or 
conversely assurance at the expense of functionality and performance.
The SMITE multi-processor computer architecture provides support for 
abstract data types by means of first class procedures and a tagged 
capability instruction set.  Many aspects of SMITE will be formally 
specified using the Z language.  SMITE software will be written for an 
algebraic abstract machine known as Ten15 which will facilitate the 
formal analysis necessary for high assurance and provide alternative 
lower assurance versions of SMITE on other processors for less 
demanding markets.
/security/multilevel security/verification/capabilities/formal 
specification/Z/Ten15/SMITE.

