Rushby, John M. Proof of seperability. 1981 May. 
SSM/11 (revised SSM/8), University of Newcastle upon Tyne, Computing 
Laboratory
The report starts with a rather doubtful discussion of the use of access 
control verification and information flow analysis. It then proceeds to 
set out conditions for secure isolation. The first condition is deemed to 
be too strong, a weaker condition is introduced which ignores covert 
(timing) channels. This condition is also considered too strong and a 
third condition is introduced which ignores the problems of one regime 
crashing the whole machine (and thus passing one bit of information!). 
The main body of the paper attempts to be a formal establishment of 
the conditions for secure isolation. Unfortunately some important 
proofs are omitted which means that following the arguments 
rigorously requires considerable effort. The final step is to introduce 
asynchronous input and interrupts but the formal analysis which has 
gone before does not apply to the new scheme. This leaves the 'Proof of 
Separability' hanging on a number of unproven assertions which are 
based upon the previous results without any formal derivation. The 
ideas are based upon a conceptual network which runs on a time-shared 
machine and cannot be applied directly to a real network.
/Verification/Separation Kernel/Separation/Security 
Kernel/Information Flow/formal specification/Access Control. 

Rushby, John M. Proof of separability, a verification technique for a 
class of security kernels. 1982 Apr. 
5th Int. Symp. Programming, Turin, Italy
This is the published version of the University of Newcastle Computer 
Laboratory report SSM/11, with some proofs omitted completely rather 
than sketched.
/Virtual Machines/Verification/Security Kernel/Proof Of 
Separability/Separation. 

Rushby, John M. Security Kernel for Embedded Systems. 1984. 
7th DoD/NBS Computer Security Conf.
/security/security kernels/embedded systems. 

Rushby, John M. The Security Model of Enhanced HDM. 1984 Sep. 
7th DOD/NBS Computer Security Conf.
An interesting paper especially for formal models and verification 
people. It suggests that 'Enhanced HDM' is incorporating some of the 
work on non-interference which is not surprising given that it is all 
happening at SRI.
/Verification/HDM/EHDM/non-interference/security models. 

Rushby, John M. Specification and design of secure systems. 1981 Mar. 
