/security/separation/security kernel. 

Rushby, John M. Verification of secure systems. 1981. 
technical report 166 (SSM/9), University of Newcastle upon Tyne, 
Computing Laboratory
This report largely superceded by report SSM/9, which has been 
published in ACM OSR 15(5), Proc 8th Symp OS Principles.
The major thrust of this paper is that most of the existing work has 
attempted to concentrate all security related features into the kernel 
and that this tends to obscure the various essentially independent 
aspects of security control. Also the proof of the security of a system 
has rested upon a proof of the specification by information flow 
analysis and then a proof that the specification is implemented 
correctly, this second stage has tended to be illustrative rather than 
formal but is also the area in which flaws are usually found. It is 
asserted that exising work has rested upon the spurious argument 'It is 
too hard to prove X but we can separate this into parts A and B, it is 
difficult to prove A so we do not need to prove B'. The tendency to put 
too much into the security kernel has led to systems where 'trusted 
processes' are given the right to violate the fundamental principles 
(such as the star-property) on which the system is built with no 
attempt to constrain this privilege to the minimum required. The 
proposed solution is to separate the control of resource sharing from 
the control of security. The kernel is responsible for ensuring that 
different regimes cannot pass information from one to another except 
along known and controlled paths. Security policy is enforced by an 
authority regime to and from which all allowed paths lead. The kernel 
can then be verified by 'proof of separability' to ensure that each 
regime runs in an abstract machine with well known properties and no 
uncontrolled communication channels, the regimes with security 
responsibilities can then be verified by information flow analysis since 
they operate in an environment isolated from the untrusted parts of the 
system and without the unpleasant dynamic sharing forced upon the 
system by the existence of real asynchronous I/O devices and 
interrupts.
/Verification/Security Kernel/Information Flow/Access 
Control/security. 

Rushby, John M. Verifying security properties of operating systems. 
1982 Dec. 
Computing lab, Univ of Newcastle upon Tyne
IEE Colloquium on 'A review of verification methods for software and 
digital systems - or how to show that a program will actually do what 
you want it to do' 4/1-4
