Rybczynski, A. X.25 Interface and End-to-End Virtual Circuit Service 
Characteristics. 1980. 
IEEE Trans. Commun COM-28, pp.500-510
X.25 is the CCITT standard interface protocol for packet switching 
networks that defines the message structure required by data terminal 
equipment (DTE) to interface to a public packet network conforming to 
CCITT standards. The X.25 standard consists of three levels of protocol: 
the physical layer (V.24 which is RS232, and X.21), the data link (or 
frame) layer (balanced link access procedures or LAPB, which is 
compatible with ANSI's ADCCP and HDLC) and the network (or packet) 
layer. These three layers conform to the lower three layers of the OSI 
basic reference model's lowest three layers.
After a general description the paper describes the X.25 end-to-end 
virtual circuit service characteristics including the way that virtual 
circuits are established and cleared, the data transfer process and 
error recovery mechanisms. The same topics are then discussed when 
viewed as X.25 packet level interface characteristics.
The optional user facilities of X.25 are described including the 
provision for a closed user group facility.
The paper concludes with a description of the relationship of X.25 to 
the OSI basic reference model as proposed by both ISO and CCITT (in 
which it finds differences) and future developments (X.25 has since 
been extended to a 1984 version which is more compatible with ISO's 
network layer service)
/standards/protocols/X.25. 

