Sandhu, Ravi (Ohio State University, Department of Computer Science). 
Transformation of Access Rights. in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security 
and Privacy; May 1; Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 
1989: 259-268. 
Note: The basic idea of the paper seems to be to formulate a framework 
that is sufficiently generic as to be able to describe a whole spectrum 
of access control policies. This rests on two kinds of transformation of 
rights: internal transformation and grant transformation.
This was a fiendishly difficult talk to follow and, indeed, the paper is 
pretty obscure too. It seems to be yet another capability machine 
formulation but with additional layers of obscurity. The whole thing 
looks too baroque to be of much use but since I have not yet mastered it 
I may be doing it an injustice. There just may be some useful ideas here 
for modelling integrity policies.
/security/security models.

Sandhu, Ravi S. (Center for Secure Information Systems & George Mason 
University). The Typed Access Matrix Model. in: 1992 IEEE Computer 
Society Symposium on Research into Security and Privacy; 1992 May 4; 
Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; : pp. 122. 
The access matrix model as formalized by Harrison, Ruzzo, and Ullman 
(HRU) has broad expressive power. Unfortunately, HRU has weak safety 
properties (i.e., the determination of whether or not a given subject can 
ever acquire access to a given object). Most security policies of 
practical interest fall into the undecidable cases of HRU. This is true 
even for monotonic policies (i.e., where access rights can be deleted 
only if the deletion is itself reversible). In this paper we define the 
typed access matrix (TAM) model by introducing strong typing into HRU 
(i.e., each subject or object is created to be of a particular type which 
thereafter does not change). We prove that monotonic TAM (MTAM) has 
strong safety properties similar to Sandhu's Schematic Protection 
Model. Safety in MTAM's decidable case is, however, NP-hard. We 
develop a model called ternary MTAM which has polynomial safety for 
its decidable case, and which nevertheless retains the full expressive 
power of MTAM. There is compelling evidence that the decidable safety 
cases of ternary MTAM are quite adequate for modeling practical 
monotonic security policies.
/Access Control.

Sandhu, Ravi S.; Gurpreet, S. Suri (George Mason University). A 
Distributed Implementation of the Transform Model. in: 14th National 
Computer Security Conference; 1991 Oct; Washington. USA: NIST/NCSC; 
1991; 1: pp.177-187. 
The Transform access-control model is based on the concept of 
transformation of access rights. It has previously been shown that 
Transform unifies a number of diverse access control mechanisms such 
as amplification, copy flags, separation of duties and synergistic 
authorisation. It has also been shown that Transform has an efficient 
algorithm for safety analysis of the propagation of access rights (ie. 
the determination of whether or not a given subject can ever acquire 
access to a given object). In this paper we propose a distributed 
implementation of Transform. Our design is based on capabilities with 
identities of subjects buried in them. This ensures unforgeability of 
capabilities as well as enables enforcement of "mandatory" controls on 
propagation of capabilities from one subject to another. The design 
provides for immediate, selective, partial and complete revocation on a 
temporary as well as permanent basis.
/Distributed Systems/Secure Architectures/Capabilities.

Sandhu, Ravi S.; Jajodia, Sushil (George Mason University). Honest 
Databases that can keep Secrets. in: 14th National Computer Security 
Conference; 1991 Oct; Washington. USA: NIST/NCSC; 1991; 1: pp.267-
282. 
Polyinstantiation has generated a great deal of controversy lately. 
Some have argued that polyinstantiation and integrity are 
fundamentally incompatible, and have proposed alternatives to 
polyinstantiation. Others have argued about the correct definition of 
polyinstantiation and its operational semantics. In this paper we 
provide a fresh analysis of the basic problem that we are trying to 
solve, ie. How can an honest database keep secrets? Our analysis leads 
us to the concept of restricted polyinstantiation wherein we show how 
to solve this problem without compromising on any of the following 
requirements: secrecy, integrity, availability of service, element-level 
labeling and high assurance. This is the first solution to meet all these 
requirements simultaneously.
/Polyinstantiation/Databases/Security.

Sandhu, Ravi; Jajodia, Sushil (George Mason University). Integrity 
Mechanisms in Database Management Systems. in: 13th National 
Computer Security Conference; 1990 Oct 1; Washington. USA: NIST; 
1990; 2: 526-540. 

Sandhu, Ravi S.; Suri, Gurpreet S. (Center for Secure Information 
Systems & George Mason University). Non-Monotonic Transformation of 
Access Rights. in: 1992 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on Research 
into Security and Privacy; 1992 May 4; Oakland, California. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1992: pp. 148. 
The concept of transformation of access rights was recently introduced 
in the literature by Sandhu. It has been previously shown that 
monotonic transformations unify a number of diverse access control 
mechanisms such as amplification, copy flags, separation of duties and 
synergistic authorization. In this paper we demonstrate the importance 
and expressive power of non-monotonic transformations. A formal 
model called Non-Monotonic Transform (NMT) is defined. A distributed 
implementation of NMT is proposed using a client-server architecture. 
The implementation is remarkably simple and modular in concept. It is 
based on access control lists and allows for a variety of powerful 
revocation operations.
/Access Rights.

