Saydjari, O. Sami; Beckman, Joseph M.; Leaman, Jeffrey R. (NCSC). LOCK 
Trek: Navigating Uncharted Space. in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security 
and Privacy; May 1; Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 
1989: 167-175. 
Note: LOCK, the NCSCs LOgical Coprocessing Kernel project, is aiming 
for beyond A1 secure computer design, by providing an open system 
architecture platform on which to develop secure systems. The primary 
objective of the project is to develop universal INFOSEC modules for 
general computers. There are two such reusable hardware modules. The 
System-Independent Domain-Enforcing Assured Reference Monitor 
(SIDEARM) is a COMPUSEC module enforcing separation of different 
levels of classified information. The Bulk Encryption Device (BED) is a 
COMSEC module providing cryptographic services. These modules are 
expected to reduce system development time. Other goals include 
publishing module interface specifications, and developing an A1 
secure prototype (expected to be delivered in September 1990).
A common problem when considering security issues is that of 
degradation of performance. Once the Memory Management Unit has been 
loaded it does not cause a performance burden, and the SIDEARM is not a 
bottleneck. The main problem is context switching.
To show that LOCK is generic it was decided to port an existing 
operating system on top of the LOCK TCB. Integration consists of 
moving security related functionality from the operating system to the 
TCB. The differences between LOCK/ix and UNIX System V are set out in 
Section 5.
The verification approach adopted consists of journal-level proofs 
establishing human proof strategy, and the GVE providing machine 
checks. The kernel interface software is approx. 8K lines of code. 
Kernel Extensions, which are implementation dependent, are in the 
range of 5 - 10K lines of code. The SIDEARM consists of 10K lines of C, 
with some high level TCB interface code.
In BED, the algorithm used is currently limited to the CCI type I module, 
but it is hoped that exportable modules will be able to be used in 
future, to extend releasability. Other plans include the publishing of 
interface control documents, to encourage industry development, and to 
develop secure applications (eg databases).
The LOCK program seems to be a reasonable approach that has 
developed over many years. Its history, design principles and trade-
offs, and the verification approach are documented in this well written 
paper.
/security/multilevel security/formal 
specification/hardware/cryptography/LOCK/SIDEARM.

