Schaefer, M.; Hubbard, B.; Sterne, D.; Haley, T. K.; McAuliffe, J. N.; 
Wolcott, D. (Trusted Information Systems, Inc.). Auditing: A Relevant 
Contribution to Trusted Database Management Systems. in: 5th Annual 
Computer Security Applications Conference; 1989 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. 
USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1989: p.232. ISBN: 0-8186-2006-4.
Note: At publication time the paper had not yet been cleared for public 
release. Copies may be obtained by contacting the authors. (Trusted 
Information Systems, Inc., Glenwood, MD 21738).
This paper introduces new and controversial issues in the area of 
trusted database management system (TDBMS) audit mechanisms. The 
paper describes the results of an on-going study that examines audit 
issues in the context of trusted database management systems 
(TDBMS). The study, funded by the Rome Air Development Center (RADC), 
consists of a survey of the state-of-the-art, an analysis of issues 
raised, and an assessment of future relevant research. The scope of the 
study is broad, and includes a variety of security policies and TDBMS 
architectures intended for commercial and defense applications. Issues 
of interest have included those associated with capture, storage, 
protection, reduction, and analysis of audit data. The study is based on 
extensive interviews with a number of researchers and product 
development groups, and an examination of audit in its historical and 
trusted systems contexts. The authors have found that little guidance 
is provided for either what needs to be audited in TDBMS contexts or 
when, how, or even where audit data should be captured or recorded. We 
have found that audit objectives and implied requirements may be 
specific to each application and security policy. We have also found 
that surprisingly little attention has been given in practice to the 
analysis of TDBMS audit data. In addition it appears to be fruitful to 
explore the use and correlation of data collected from several different 
layers of the composite system (opening system and DBMS) 
architectures. An unanticipated result, somewhat beyond the initial 
scope of the study, was revealed when the authors asked about the 
verisimilitude of event recording in an audit trail. If the audit 
subsystem records that a specific event occurred, how can it be 
determined that the event actually took place? The authors have 
concluded that the credibility of the audit trail is intimately tied to 
the strength of assurance that a TDBMS enforces its security policy 
with sound mechanisms. A lack of audit credibility appears in some 
cases to be symptomatic of more fundamental weaknesses in 
assurances. Thus, the authors believe that is utility in analyzing an 
audit trail's credibility as a means of assessing the trust 
characteristics of a system's security architecture. Tentative 
conclusions drawn from preliminary application of this analysis 
technique are presented.
/databases/Audit/TDBMS.

Schaefer, Marvin (Trusted Information Systems Inc.). Symbol Security 
Condition Considered Harmful. in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security and 
Privacy; May 1; Oakland California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 1989: 
20-46. 
Note: In this paper the author talks at some of the history underlying 
the TCSEC, and in particular the formal specification and evaluation 
aspects and shows how the use of formal methods can weaken rather 
than strengthen an evaluation if improperly used.
The thesis of the paper is that formal methods are good (a) provided 
they supplement rather than supplant other techniques, and (b) the 
discipline needed for the use of formal methods is carried through into 
the whole approach to development and evaluation. A number are 
particular problems with the use of formal methods are discussed in 
detail:
 few system designers have experience of formal methods, and thus 
tend to be learning on the job - which means they may not be fluent 
enough to be able to relate code to specification;
 If the code is close to the specification, it can be inefficient; if 
not, it is difficult to demonstrate consistency (and inconsistency is 
more likely);
 Abstract specifications can have too little detail, making the 
theorems and proofs too superficial to be of value; if the detail is 
present, then the specification is probably too big to understand or to 
analyse with existing tools;
 Tools may not support notions such as concurrency and asynchrony 
that may be vital in a realistic implementation;
 The tools are fallible;
 The tools are limited in their abilities, in that one false axiom or one 
inconsistency in a specification can allow all theorems to be proved 
true (and proved false, but who looks to prove false something they 
want to prove true?).
While formal specifications and analysis can lend assurance that the 
system is secure at at least one level of the design, it is essential to 
demonstrate by thorough and rigourous testing that the top-level 
design concepts have been faithfully carried through to the 
implementation, and that design decisions made at intermediate stages 
for proagmatic or practical reasons have not lost security.
An interesting paper for those who are interested in the history of the 
TCSEC, and an important lesson on the limitations of formal methods 
and the need for integrity of implementation and information.
/security/multilevel security/formal specification/TCSEC.

