Schou, Corey D.; Kilpatrick, John A. (Idaho State University). 
Information Security: Can Ethics Make a Difference? in: 14th National 
Computer Security Conference; 1991 Oct; Washington. USA: NIST/NCSC; 
1991; 1: pp.305-312. 
Information is a vital organisational asset that affects ongoing 
decision making. It has a finite life span therefore if it is delayed in 
its distribution, it has reduced value; if a proper user fails to have 
access, it has no value. The objective of attempts to secure the 
organisational information system is to see that unauthorised use is 
not possible, that destructive viruses are not introduced, and that 
unauthorised study and alteration of records and files does not occur 
during the distribution of data and information throughout the 
organisation while guaranteeing that proper users have easy access to 
their information. Are these objectives strictly technical problems, or 
is it possible and appropriate to broaden the scope to include the 
ethical issues that are raised as the security system is developed and 
installed? The argument in this paper is that it is both appropriate and 
necessary to consider the broader issues.
/Security/Ethics.

