This paper proposes that real-time auditing be built into modern 
systems at the design stage, and puts forward a mechanism for doing 
this in a systematic way. The transaction-based system model to which 
they apply auditing is a commercial type system, but results should be 
generally applicable.
The mechanism is based on a system-wide rule-based 'trigger' detector 
which activates data capture at a module level. Thus far it is quite 
hand-waving, and the rule-based engine could be the proverbial can of 
worms. However, the description of the proposed mechanism below 
this, with nomenclature and some examples, could be quite useful. It 
includes an outline and example of a proposed language.
/security/audit. 

