Seiden, Kenneth F.; Melanson, Jeffrey P. (DEC). The Auditing Facility for 
a VMM Security Kernel. in: 1990 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on 
Research in Security and Privacy; 1990 May 7; Oakland. USA: IEEE; 1990: 
262-277. 
Note: This paper follows on from the Overview of the VAX VMM given at 
the start of the conference. It describes how auditing is provided 
within the VMM Security Kernel. Again the need to produce a production 
quality system was a prime requirement.
The Security Kernel carries out auditing constantly. If the audit log 
becomes full then the system simply stops. Once the audit log becomes 
75% full reminders are sent to the Auditor that the log is filling up. 
DEC estimate that an archive of audit data is only necessary about once 
per week.
The Audit Trail layer is about halfway down the security kernel. Its 
position is determined by the fact that only higher layers may make use 
of its facilities. Lower layers are unable to do so.
When an auditable event occurs it is the responsibility of the layer in 
which the event occurs to generate an audit request to the Audit Trail 
layer. The Audit Trail layer will action an audit request providing 
certain thresholds related to classification and severity are exceeded. 
Alternatively the requesting layer may demand that the event be 
audited whatever the thresholds.
The Audit Trail layer simply buffers audit events. It does not write 
them to the Audit log itself. This is an area where the layering breaks 
down. Since the Audit Trail wishes to write to the audit log (which is a 
file) it should sit above the Files layer. However the Files layer needs 
to sit above the Audit Trail to perform its own audit. The solution of 
duplicating the Files code in the Audit Trail layer is clearly 
unattractive. Instead an Audit Logger layer is introduced at a high level 
in the layered structure. The Audit Logger calls the Audit Trail (at 
times determined by event counts and elapsed time) and drains the 
Audit Trail buffers to the audit logs. Thus technically the Audit Trail 
does not call the Audit Logger but from a purists point of view its a 
cheat!
A simple privilege mechanism is used to gain Separation of Duties. The 
VMM supports a System Manager, a Security Manager and an Auditor. The 
Auditor will log on as an ordinary user and then requests the privileges 
of an Auditor. These will have been set up by the Security Manager. If 
the Auditor has successfully obtained his privilege he may execute 
audit commands. An extra privilege is required to delete audit 
information. The audit log is at System High, so no user with a lesser 
clearance, even if he obtains the Auditor privilege, will be able to 
access the log. If security events trigger alarms the Auditor is 
informed. However, only the System Manager, in general, has the power 
to recover from the alarm.
As mentioned earlier audit data are buffered before being written to 
the audit log. This introduces problems of sequencing and also data loss 
at times such as system crashes. The paper goes into some detail about 
the mechanisms used to prevent and recover from such problems.
For readers building an audit system this paper provides a good survey 
of the practical problems to be forced. Note that it is a paper on Audit 
Collection and not Audit Analysis.
The VAX security kernel is a prototype security kernel implemented as 
a virtual machine monitor (VMM) for the VAX architecture.  The VAX 
security kernel is capable of emulating one or more virtual machines
(VMs) on a single physical machine allowing multiple copies of virtual 
machine operating systems to execute concurrently.  The system 
presently supports both VMS and ULTRIX as virtual machine operating 
systems.
A fundamental component of any security kernel is the ability to 
produce an audit trail of security relevant events.  While there are 
numerous examples of auditing subsystems at the DoD Trusted 
Computer System Evaluation Criteria (TCSEC) [5] C2 or B1 level, there 
is much less experience with the requirements at the B2 level and 
above.  This paper describes the design and implementation of the VAX 
security kernel auditing facility, built to satisfy the requirements at 
the A1 level.
/security/audit/VAX security kernel.

