Shieh, Shiuhpyng Winston; Gligor, Virgil D. (University of Maryland). A 
Pattern-Oriented Intrusion Detection Model and its Applications. in: 
1991 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on Research in Security and 
Privacy; 1991 May; Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Computer Society 
Press; 1991: pp.327-342. ISBN: 0-8186-2168-0.
Operational security problems can lead to intrusion in secure computer 
systems. We justify the need for, and present, a pattern-oriented, 
intrusion detection model that can be used to analyze object privilege 
and data flows in secure computer systems to detect operational 
security problems. This model can address context-dependent intrusion, 
such as use of covert storage channels and virus propagation, and has 
been used to build an intrusion detection system for Trusted Xenix. 
Pattern-oriented intrusion detection is expected to complement, not 
replace, current statistical approaches to intrusion detection.
/Intrusion Detection/Pattern-Oriented/Xenix.

Shieh, S-P W.; Gligor, Virgil D. (University of Maryland, College Park, 
MD). Auditing the Use of Covert Storage Channels in Secure Systems. in: 
1990 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on Research in Security and 
Privacy; 1990 May 7; Oakland. USA: IEEE; 1990: 285-295. 
Note: The paper starts by describing the problems of auditing covert 
channels, such as transmitter receiver ambiguity, disguised use of 
covert storage channels and insufficient granularity of recorded time. 
It then shows that a computer system designed for minimal 
satisfaction of the TCSEC evaluation criteria, would be unable to 
detect the use of covert storage channels. Finally the paper describes a 
covert storage channel auditor for secure Xenix. The production of the 
auditor was prompted by the B2 evaluation of Secure Xenix. 
The paper itself is complex and should be classed as heavy reading.
In this paper we define requirement for auditing covert storage 
channels and illustrate some fundamental problems which appear in 
most computer systems.  We argue that audit subsystems designed to 
minimally satisfy the TCSEC requirements [1, 2] are unable to detect 
many instances of covert channel use, and hence require major design 
and implementation changes before they are able to detect all use of 
covert storage channels.  Finally, we present the design of a Secure 
Xenix tools for covert-channel audit that has been in operation since 
July 1989.  Results of experiments indicate that the tool is able to 
detect all use of covert storage channels without raising false alarms.
/audit/covert channels/Secure Xenix.

Shieh, Wen-Gong; Weems, Bob; Kavi, Krishna M. (The University of Texas 
at Arlington). An N-grid Model for Group Authorization. in: 6th Annual 
Computer Security Applications Conference; 1990 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. 
USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1990: pp.384-392. ISBN: 0-8186-
2105-2.
The n-grid model for group authorization and access control extends 
the NTree representation of two-dimensional partial orders and 
incorporates the implicit authorizations of the MCC model. The n-grid 
is a representation of multi-dimensional partial orders, permitting the 
inclusion of relationships among user (subject) groups, object groups, 
and access-right groups. Each (unique) element in an authorization 
class is represented as a vector, facilitating efficient implementation. 
The model contains two parts: the access control part for mapping 
implicit authorizations onto an n-grid, and the propagation part for 
restricting a user's membership to a single subject group.
/Access Control/security models/N-Grid Model.

