/Crypto. 

Simmons, G. J. Half a loaf is better than none: some novel message 
integrity problems. 1981 Apr. 
Sandia Nat Labs, Albuquerque NM
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1981 Symp. Security and Privacy
After categorising various methods of identifying people and their 
rights do do something, the paper describes PPIV (Positive Personnel 
Identity Verification). In this system, which was implemented in 1980 
at Sandia National Laboratories, morphological data (weight, hand 
geometry), a 5-digit PIN and access rights (locations and times) are 
held RSA-encrypted on a card using a private key; the public key is held 
in equipment guarding individual portals, and used to decrypt the 
information on the card so the person presenting the card can be 
checked.
/RSA/Public Key/Crypto/Morphology/Authentication. 

Simmons, G. J. How to (Selectively) Broadcast a Secret. 1985. 
Sandia Nat Labs, Albuquerque NM
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1985 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.108-115
This paper describes a flaw (that occurred on the page omitted from 
the proceedings) in a software protection scheme presented at the 
1982 IEEE symposium, and then develops a revised protocol for the use 
of a tamper-resist Secure Cryptographic Module (SCM) that prevents 
the use of unlicenced software. The SCM contains a (DES) crypto unit 
with its own private key, and the licenced user of a piece of software 
is given a composite of the private keys for the software and the SCM. 
Proper use of the protocol results in a useable form of the software 
being loaded into the internal memory of the SCM ready for use.
The protocol can also be viewed as a way to broadcast messages which 
can only be understood by those with permission to do so.
/Tamper Resist Module/Software Protection/Secure Cryptographic 
Module/SCM/Protocols/DES/Crypto. 

