Sincoskie, W. D.; Farber, D. J. SODS/OS: a Distributed Operating System 
for the IBM Series/1. 1980. 
ACM SIGOPS OSR 14(3) pp.46-54
This paper describes a distributed operating system in which processes 
are contained objects. A process consists of code and its context, 
which in turn consists of a capability table plus some static 
information. The operating system provides the process with private 
memory space and maps it onto the physical processor. The process 
cannot alter its own context, to change it it issues system calls. All 
inter-process communication is via unidirectional FIFOs.
System processes are location-independent and the system can cause 
migration of processes without the process being aware of the 
movement. All process data interactions are made to appear the same 
as process to process interactions so as to maintain this independence. 
The primitive message types and system calls needed to support this 
model are described.
/distributed systems/IBM. 

