Smith, G. W. (George Mason University, Fairfax, Va.//National Defense 
University, Washington DC.). Modeling Security-Relevant Data 
Semantics. in: 1990 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on Research in 
Security and Privacy; 1990 May 7; Oakland. USa: IEEE; 1990: 384-391. 
Note: This is a short but pleasant paper which introduces a means of 
talking about the security relationships between objects in a database. 
The Semantic Data Model for Security (SDMS) is a graphical technique 
which enables the requirements for security in a database to be 
illustrated in an easy to understand fashion. Suggested future work 
includes formalising SDMS to allow the user to reason about the 
requirements expressed.
The author is concerned with the raft of issues which sit beneath the 
standard MAC and DAC concerns. The usual security model uses 
statements like all objects are classified. SDMS allows the 
specifier of a particular application to describe the classification of 
each of the entities in the database. He can also describe the 
classification of associations between entities and he can prescribe 
features such as the hiding of the existence of certain entities and 
associations. The model also provides a method for describing how 
aggregates of data should be classified. Since there is no formal 
description of the model its main use is as an aid to designers and 
security officers to provide a good intuition as to the required security 
features.
The work follows on from an earlier technique for describing integrity 
in databases. There is, perhaps, a lesson to be learned from the paper in 
that not much thought has been given to the presentation of security in 
graphical or diagrammatic form. While diagrams are bound to be 
informal, with all the attendant risks of ambiguity and 
misunderstanding, they do provide a good way for the human brain to 
gain a quick intuition about the subject matter. Much has been made of 
this in traditional Software Engineering methods and perhaps it should 
be more to the fore in security.
A database system must have knowledge of the semantics (the 
properties) of the data it manages to accomplish its tasks.  For a 
multilevel secure database system to provide effective multilevel 
support to users, it must have knowledge of the security-relevant data 
semantics.  Modeling the data semantics of an application domain has 
been a subject of research for many years in the database community, 
but these efforts only address integrity properties of data.  This paper 
demonstrates the use of an extended data model that represents both 
integrity and secrecy aspects of data.  This modeling technique can be 
used as a database design tool and, more importantly, as a vehicle by 
which domain experts, database designers, and security officers can 
precisely define the security requirements for an application domain.  
A second contribution is a comprehensive taxonomy of security 
relevant data semantics that must be captured and understood to 
implement a multilevel secure automated information system.
/security/multilevel security/databases/data modelling.

Smith, Gary W. (Goerge Mason University). Going Beyond Technology to 
Meet the Challenges of Multilevel Database Security. in: 12th National 
Computer Security Conference; 1989 Oct 10; Baltimore. USA: 
NIST/NCSC; 1989: 1-10. 
/security/multilevel security/databases/multilevel databases.

Smith, Gary W. (George Mason University, School of Information 
