Smith, T. A. User definable domains as a mechanism for implementing 
the least privilege principle. 1986 Sep. 
Proc. 9th NCSC/NBS computer security conference pp.143-148
This paper proposes that users be allowed to define the information to 
which they currently require access. A Trojan Horse would then be 
unable to get at things which the user would normally have access to 
but did not intend to update. The proposed mechanism is supported by 
some mathematics describing a security policy by means of sets. It is 
essentially an extra layer of discretionary policy. The difficulty might 
be pursuading users to use it.
/trojan horse/access domains. 

Smith Lloyd R. (Information Systems Integrity). Disaster Recovery form 
$138 Million Fire. in: 13th National Computer Security Conference; 
1990 Oct 1; Washington. USA: NIST; 1990; 2: 392. 

Snapp, Steven R.; Brentano, James; Dias, Gihan V.; Goan, Terrance L.; 
Heberlein, L. Todd; Ho, Che-Lin; Levitt, Karl N.; Mukherjee, Biswanath; 
Smaha, Stephen E.; Grance, Tim; Teal, Daniel M.; Mansur, Doug 
(University of California). DIDS (Distributed Intrusion Detection 
System) - Motivation, Architecture, and An Early Prototype. in: 14th 
National Computer Security Conference; 1991 Oct; Washington. USA: 
NIST/NCSC; 1991; 1: pp.167-176. 
Intrusion detection is the problem of identifying unauthorised use, 
misuse, and abuse of computer systems by both system insiders and 
external penetrators. The proliferation of heterogeneous computer 
networks provides additional implications for the intrusion detection 
problem. Namely, the increased connectivity of computer systems gives 
greater access to outsiders, and makes it easier for intruders to avoid 
detection. IDS's are based on the belief that the intruder's behaviour 
will be noticeably different from that of a legitimate user. We are 
designing and implementing a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection 
System (DIDS) that combines distributed monitoring and data reduction 
(through individual host and LAN monitors) with centralised data 
analysis (through the DIDS director) to monitor a heterogeneous 
network of computers. This approach is unique among current IDS's. A 
main problem considered in this paper is the Network-user 
Identification problem, which is concerned with tracking a user moving 
across the network, possibly with a new user-id on each computer. 
Initial system prototypes have provided quite favorable results on this 
problem and the detection of attacks on a network. This paper provides 
an overview of the motivation behind DIDS, the system architecture and 
capabilities, and a discussion of the early prototype.
/Intrusion Detection/DIDS/Distributed Systems.

Snekkenes, Einar (Alcatel Telecom Norway AS). Exploring the BAN 
Approach to Protocol Analysis. in: 1991 IEEE Computer Society 
Symposium on Research in Security and Privacy; 1991 May; Oakland, 
California. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1991: pp.171-181. ISBN: 
0-8186-2168-0.
The BAN (Burrows, Abadi and Needham) approach to analysis of 
cryptographic protocols transforms a correctness requirement into a 
proof obligation of a formal belief logic. It is shown that the BAN 
protocol annotation rules make flaws due solely to protocol step 
permutation undetectable by the BAN logic. This is illustrated by a 
short example. In a recently published critique of the BAN logic 
D.Nessett uses the BAN logic to prove the correctness of an insecure 
protocol. In the style of BAN logic we define the concept of a 
terminating idealized protocol. We then show that the protocol due to 
D.Nessett belongs to the class of non-terminating protocols.
/BAN/Crypto/Protocols/Verification.

Snekkenes, Einar (Norwegian Defense Research Establishment). Roles in 
Cryptographic Protocols. in: 1992 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on 
Research into Security and Privacy; 1992 May 4; Oakland, California. 
USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1992: pp. 105. 
In protocols for the distribution of symmetric keys, a principal will 
usually either take on the role as a session key provider or as a session 
key user. A principal taking on the role as session key user may also act 
as the master or the slave. We show that methods for the analysis of 
cryptographic protocols that fail to properly handle multiple roles do 
not yield dependable results.
We present a protocol KP, similar to the Needham and Schroeder 
symmetric key distribution protocol. By means of an example, we then 
show how a multi-role flaw in KP can be utilized by an adversary to 
obtain a session key.
Using a method due to Burrows, Abadi and Needham, and the one due to 
Bieber, we show that KP seems to be suitable for secure key 
distribution. Finally, the approach due to Bieber is modified to 
facilitate the detection of the class of multi-role flaws.
/Cryptography.

Snow, C. R.; Whitfield, H. An Experiment with the Newcastle Connection 
Protocol. 1986 Nov. 
Softw. Pract. Exper. 16(11) pp.1031-1
An experiment is described in which a set of Unix systems linked 
together into a Unix United system by means of the Newcastle 
Connection Protocol is also linked to a system with a dissimilar 
structure. It demonstrates that the Newcastle Connection technique can 
be used to connect together operating systems with differing 
structures and philosphies. The non-Unix system, known as Nimrod, 
offers a set of services which can be mapped onto requests for service 
from standard user processes running on a remoted Unix system. The 
services offered by Nimrod are restricted to those required for 
providing remote input and output to a terminal, but the results of the 
experiment suggest that increasing the range of services offered would 
be possible, despite the substantial differences in structure between 
Nimrod and Unix. Some of the problems associated with greater levels 
of inter-system connection are also discussed.
2T534. 

