Sollins, Karen R. (MIT). Cascaded Authentication. in: 1988 IEEE 
Symposium on Security and Privacy; 1988 Apr 18; Oakland Ca. 
Washington DC: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1988: pp.156-163. ISBN: 
0-8186-0850-1.
Note: A lightweight paper addressing the issues raised when invocation 
of services is cascaded through a list of nodes.
Messages across a system carry a passport, constituted from cleartext 
and encrypted sections. Each node of the journey, on receiving the 
passport, adds its identification and a list of constraints on the further 
use of the passport to the cleartext. The identification of the next node 
of the journey and the constraints are appended to the encrypted 
section which is then encrypted further using the node's private key. 
The paper shows how the constituents of the passport - an encrypted 
section, a list of nodes and a list of constraints - provide a number of 
benefits.
At any time (and certainly at the final node) the authentication service 
can provide a validation of the passport (i.e. encrypted section => 
cleartext). To guarantee this authentication of the passport there must 
exist either a centralised authentication service (common to all nodes) 
or a set of co-operating authentication services that trust each other. 
Pairwise authentication between adjacent nodes is also neccessary.
The methods outlined in the paper are not breaking any new ground. 
Further the claim that it is 'efficient enough to be usable' is dubious 
due to the fact that each node on the journey re-encrypts the passport 
using its own private key. The authentication of a passport that has 
travelled over N nodes will need N decryptions.
This paper addresses a problem that has arisen in building distributed 
systems in which incomplete trust exists and program composition is 
necessary.  The problem is to permit authentication for both access 
control and accounting when cascading invocations.  The problem can be 
identified as one of providing cascaded authentication.  A mechanism 
has been developed which is called passports that are passed along 
with each stage of the cascade and digitally signed at each transaction.  
The information thus signed is that which is critical to the 
authentication.  The contributions of the work are both in recognizing 
the problem and in devising a solution that is efficient enough to be 
usable, although there will be some cost associated with such a 
mechanism.
/security/authentication/cryptography/networks.

Solomon, D. J. Processing Multilevel Secure Objects. 1981 Apr. 
MITRE Corp Bedford MA
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1981 Symp. Security and Privacy
The paper describes an architecture for handling multilevel objects, 
and outlines a proposed intelligent secure terminal to text process 
multilevel documents. The technique suggested is to use a series of 
worker processors, each handling data at one level, with a trusted 
feedback monitor and untrusted foreman processor. A trusted host 
interface is assumed and it is assumed that the host can somehow hold 
multilevel objects securely. The proposed design relies on the high 
performance of a dedicated single-user system, and the task time 
predictability when processing text; hardware separation of processes 
in processors is easier to verify than logical separation.
/Security/Multilevel Security Objects/Security/Multilevel 
Security/MITRE. 

