/formal specification/languages/Z. 

Spivey, J. M. Understanding Z. 1987. 
Oxford PRG
Oxford University (D Phil Thesis)
The specification language Z, originally developed by J R Abrial at the 
Oxford PRG, is a notation and style for expressing formal 
specifications. It is based on the theory of typed sets, and a central 
feature is the notion of a schema. This paper presents (in Z) a 
denotational semantics for Z, discusses various issues that arose from 
the work, and compare the approach with other methods of describing 
the semantics.
/formal specification/Z/languages. 

