Sterne, Daniel F. (Trustes Information Systems, Inc.). On the Buzzword 
"Security Policy". in: 1991 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on 
Research in Security and Privacy; 1991 May; Oakland, California. USA: 
IEEE Computer Society Press; 1991: pp.219-230. ISBN: 0-8186-2168-0.
Although the term "security policy" is fundamental to computer 
security, its conflicting meanings have obscured important conceptual 
distinctions, especially where concerns other that confidentiality are 
involved. A clearer definition is needed to 1) clarify routine technical 
discourse 2) facilitate resolution of key research issues, and 3) 
establish the scope of security research and standardization efforts. 
The terms security policy objective, organizational security policy, and 
automated security policy are proposed. These terms are based on 
simple generalizations of ideas that underlie the Trusted Computer 
System Evaluation Criteria (TCSEC). Yet, they describe a view of 
security that is more precise, more general, and different than 
"confidentiality, integrity, and assured service". Their usefulness in 
clarifying conceptual and terminological issues is illustrated through 
examples.
/Security Policy/Confidentiality/Integrity/Assured Service.

Sterne, Daniel; Branstad, Martha; Hubbard, Brian; Mayer, Barbara; 
Wolcott, Dawn (Trusted Information Systems, Inc.). An Analysis of 
Application Specific Security Policies. in: 14th National Computer 
Security Conference; 1991 Oct; Washington. USA: NIST/NCSC; 1991; 1: 
pp.25-36. 
The TCSEC is concerned primarily with the DoD confidentiality. As a 
result, for many applications systems that satisfy the TCSEC may 
nevertheless provide an insufficient base for security policy 
enforcement. This paper summarises a study whose objective is the 
identification of a broader range of security policies that merit 
automated support, particularly in tactical computer systems. The 
study analysed operational requirements of a collection of tactical and 
non-tactical application scenarios. Synopses of several example 
scenarios are presented, and the findings of the study discussed. The 
study suggests that while many policies are application specific there 
exists a core of policy elements common to a broad range of such 
policies, and that this core merits automated support in future trusted 
systems.
/TCSEC/Security Policy/Access Control/Roles/Integrity/Denial of 
Service.

