Su, Tzong-An; Chung, JiYong; Oszoyoglu, G. (University of Toledo//Case 
Western Reserve University). On the Cell Suppression by Merging 
Technique in the Lattice Model of Summary Tables. in: 1989 IEEE 
Symposium on Security and Privacy; May 1; Oakland, California. USA: 
IEEE Computer Society; 1989: 126-135. 
Note: A statistical database (SDB) is a database that provides simple 
summary statistics about its individuals, and supports statistical data 
analysis. Summary tables are tabular representations of summary data. 
For a given aggregate function and a set of attributes used to describe 
the individuals of an SDB, all possible summary tables form a lattice. 
Security is a major problem in this area, since a sensitive statistic can 
disclose too much confidential information about an individual. Size-
one cells are, by definition, sensitive and the main security problem in 
the lattice model of summary tables.
The Cell Suppression by Merging (CSM) Technique is discussed. Given 
any size-one elementary cell which has to be suppressed (i.e. not 
revealed to users) select a size greater-than-one elementary cell with 
which to merge it, and suppress them both. Any cell in the lattice 
which contains exactly one of these cells is also suppressed.
A major aim is to minimise information loss. Since information lost is 
determined by the percentage of suppressed cells in the lattice, the 
number of suppressed cells should be minimised. Heuristics for 
minimum information loss are presented.
In this paper, query probabilities are incorporated into the model and 
the CSM technique is extended into the generalised lattice model 
environment, where additional summary tables are formed by secondary 
attributes. In conclusion, CSM is a very useful cell level inference 
control technique with respect to minimising information loss.
The presentation suffered as it was difficult to understand the speaker 
and poor quality, handwritten viewfoils were used. This detracted from 
what is an interesting paper.
/privacy/databases/statistical inference.

Su, Tzong-An; Ozsoyoglu, Gultekin. Data Dependencies and Inference 
Control in Multilevel Relational Database Systems. 1987. 
We investigate the inference problems due to functional dependencies 
(FD) and multivalued dependencies (MVD) in a multilevel relational 
database (MDB) with attribute and record classification schemes, 
respectively. For FDs, we show that, to prevent compromised, the 
security levels of attributes must be assigned by using the knowledge 
of functional dependencies. Under the assumption that all the 
attributes in the database have been assigned classification levels 
acording to real world requirements, we first determine the set of 
functional dependencies to be taken into account. Then, we prove that 
changing the minimum number of attribute levels to prevent 
compromise is an NP-complete problem. However, assuming that the 
number of functional dependencies involved in inference is low, we give 
an exact algorithm to adjust the minimum number of attribute levels so 
that no compromise due to functional dependencies occurs. For MVDs, 
we give a necessary and sufficient condition for compromise due to a 
single MVD, and then propose an algorithm to prevent single MVD 
inferences.
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 202 - 211
This paper goes into great detail about the theory of data dependencies. 
It is an unfortunate characteristic of database theory that great 
complexity must be encountered to state a result that appears obvious: 
this paper is no exception.
The functional dependency information is dealt with in a more 
comprehensible fashion in Denning and Lunt's paper but the multivalued 
dependency work is new. Join dependencies have not been covered 
although these are rather exotic and difficult to identify in real life.
The result is that the classification of a value must dominate the 
classification of a value upon which it depends.
The algorithms for removing dependencies have two problems:
 although they are satisfactory for column classification, in row 
classification they introduce an inference channel in the attempt to 
remove one, and
 they assume total ordering of classifications.
/security/multilevel security/databases. 

