Sutherland, David. A Model of Information. in: 9th NBS/NCSC National 
Computer Security Conference; 1986 Sep. ; 1986: pp.175-183. 
Note: The author presents a new security property, deducibility, in this 
far from lucid paper.  In the model, users can see a view of the system 
that is a function of the states through which it has passed in its life 
time (a 'possible world').  In effect, their interface to the system is 
described by this function.  Assuming a user knows the information 
function corresponding to his own interface and that of another 
interface, information can flow from his interface to the other if the 
set of possible worlds that could account for the view he sees does not 
produce all possible outputs at the other interface.  The user will be 
able to deduce that a user of this other interface cannot be seeing 
certain outputs.  Informally, a system has the deducibility property 
when a user observing events at his low level interface cannot deduce 
anything  about the sequence of inputs delivered to a higher level 
interface.
/security/security models/deducibility.

Sutherland, I.; Perlo, S.; Varadarajan, R. (Odyssey Research Associates). 
