ACM SIGOPS OSR 19(2) pp.6-39
This paper reports on recent (1985) work in the design and 
implementation of operating systems for computer network 
environments. The workshop had the express intention of bringing 
together an international group of researchers. The ten sessions dealt 
with much of the state of the art research both in operating system 
projects, such as: the Newcastle Connection, Apollo's DOMAIN, Project 
Admiral, the Cedar file system and, Cambridge's Mayflower project; and 
in recent thinking about upcalls, broadcasting, persistent objects, and 
remote procedure calls. This paper summarises all the sessions. A 
session on high availability systems may be particularly relevant in the 
security field.
/distributed systems. 

Swaminathan, Kishore. Negotiated Access Control. 1985. 
University of Massachusets, Amherst, MA
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1985 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.190-196
This paper proposes a set of protocols which would allow access 
control procedures to be associated with shared resources. Access 
control policies are decided by the resource creator rather than a 
system-wide policy, so to support MLS policies one would have to build 
a suitable ACP into the kernel to be associated with each resource - 
perhaps allowing the creator to add secondary controls - and then 
protect the kernel from modification by the resource. The work was 
based on the author's experience with the Guthenberg distributed OS 
kernel, and has not yet been implemented.
/Networks/Kernels/Guthenburg/Access Control. 

