Tanenbaum, A. S. Computer Networks. 1981. 
Prentice-Hall Inc., Englewood Cliffs NJ
This book gives a very comprehensive consideration of computer 
communications networks in general, and with particular reference to 
the functional issues and protocols relevant at each layer of the OSI 
seven layer model. The model is applied even to protocols which were 
developed without its benefit.
The ISO reference model is introduced in the first chapter. The book 
then goes on to introduce the other main sources of protocols: 
ARPANET, SNA, DECNET and X.25. Following chapters deal in turn with 
each of the ISO layers in detail, with examples.
Network security and privacy is covered under the heading of the 
presentation layer. It deals mostly with encryption. The use of the 
presentation layer in virtual terminal protocols and file transfer 
protocols is explored. Network and distributed operating systems, 
distributed computation and distributed data base systems are briefly 
covered by the chapter on the application layer.
The book also gives an excellent reading list and bibliography. All in 
all, a very good introduction and survey of networking, particularly 
with regard to the practical implications of ISO standards.
/standards/OSI. 

