8T/0.
SMITE.

Terry, P. F. The SMITE Approach to Security. 1989 Jan 8. 
SMITE is a novel computer architecture implementing a new security 
policy model. It is proposed as the best available technology which may 
be used to develop information systems for operational use where high 
assurance of complex confidentiality and integrity based security 
policies is required.This report records the results of work carried out 
by Retix Systems for CC1 division RSRE. This contract provided a peer 
review of their architecture proposals, characterised the essential 
architectural elements and formulated the security oriented top level 
model. In this way it provided a baseline definition of SMITE to aid the 
future way forward for the project.
RSRE Report 89014: SMITE Ref: 89014. 
Architecture. 

Terry, Phil; Wiseman, Simon (TSL//RSRE). A 'New' Security Policy 
Model. : TSL/RSRE; 1988. 
A Model of Security is presented which integrates notions of 
confidentiality and commercial integrity.  This model has been 
developed to fulfill the needs of the RSRE SMITE project because 
existing modelling approaches proved to be inadequate.  The paper 
introduces the model and subsequently compares and contrasts it with 
existing approaches.

Terry, Phil; Wiseman, Simon (Retix Systems//RSRE). A 'New' Security 
Policy. in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy; May 1; 
Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 1989: 215-228. 
Note: This paper describes a security model, including both 
confidentiality and integrity properties, for the RSRE SMITE project. 
The presentation wisely avoided details of the formal model, and 
concentrated on the motivation for the model and its relationship to 
selected other models (BLP, Biba, Clark-Wilson; no event-based 
models).
The confidentiality part of the model is state-based (since this is 
claimed to be more familiar to security practitioners), with entities 
(not subjects and objects) whose attributes represent classification, 
role, trusts, conflicting roles and other data. There is no notion of 
secure state; SMITE can handle a very fine granularity of policy, and 
its typing system leads more naturally to the definition of secure 
transitions. Also mentioned in the presentation (but not in the paper) 
were an information flow axiom and a conditional non-interference 
statement to ensure the consistency of the model.
The integrity part of the model is split into two issues: correctness 
of state integrity and appropriateness of transitions (a distinction 
also implicit in Clark-Wilson). The examples in the presentation were 
that accounts must only be amended with a correct program is a 
correctness integrity problem, and can money be transferred into a 
clerks own account? is an appropriateness problem. Separation of 
duty is modelled as n-man rules applied to single operations, and not as 
composable sequences of smaller operations each performed by single 
users of distinct roles.
Future work includes: the conditional non-interference proof using m-
EVES (when available from Canada), examples of the model in action, 
and the use of the model to re-examine DBMS security.
There are several novel features of this model, notably operations 
having several requesters, separation of duty treated as a constraint on 
an n-man operation, and the relationship between role and trust 
attributes of entities. There appear to be some loose ends in this 
approach, for example an interpretation of user input/output, and a 
better justification of the split between roles and trusts. The meaning 
of requests is unclear; there seems to be no guarantee that information 
really does flow only from the entities named as observed in the 
request (  perhaps this is an assumption implicit in the models level 
of abstraction). The formal integrity property is a problem, in that it 
appears to disallow newly-created objects (which are counted as 
observers?), and the three transition rules do not seem to 
conform to the integrity property. Nonetheless, this model includes 
some new and promising ideas, especially in its view of 
appropriateness, and its future development should be of interest.
/security/multilevel security/security models.

Terry Phil F.; Wiseman, Simon R. (TSL Communications Ltd/RSRE). On 
the Design and Implementation of a Secure Computer System. Malvern: 
HMSO/TSL; 1988; Memorandum 4188. 
Note: Defines a security model, informally, but using Z definitions, 
which is claimed to be more realistic than, say, Bell and LaPadula.  
Considers some problems with capability architectures and shows how 
SMITE is better.  Finally shows, again informally, how SMITE supports 
the model.
/SMITE/SCP3/SCP/Capabilities.

Testa, C. J.; Wilner, B. D.; Gilgor, V. D. (Infosystems Technology, Inc.). 
Trusted RUBIX Architecture and Policy Model Interpolation. 8th Annual 
Computer Security Applications Conference; 1930 Nov 4; San Antonio, 
Texas. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1992: pp. 97-110. ISBN: 0-
8186-3115-5.
A multiuser relational DBMS system, Trusted RUBIX, has been designed 
and implemented to satisfy the requirements of the TCSEC at the B2 
class. In this paper the architecture of Trusted RUBIX is presented, its 
integration within the B2 UNIX System V platform is discussed, and the 
adaption and interpretation of the SeaViews security policy model in 
Trusted RUBIX are explained. The lessons learned from this design and 
implementation exercise are also discussed.
/Trusted RUBIX/DBMS/multiuser/SeaViews.

Theofanos, Mary Frances (Martin Marietta Energy Systems Inc). A 
Systematic Approach to Software Security Evaluations. in: 12th 
National Computer Security Conference; 1989 Oct 10; Baltimore. USA: 
NIST/NCSC; 1989: 423-432. 

Thomas, Ian. PCTE Interfaces: Supporting Tools in Software-Engineering 
Environments. IEEE Software. 1989 Nov: 15-23.

Thomas, Martyn. Development Methods for Trusted Computer Systems. 
Formal Aspects of Computing. 1989 Jan; 1(1): 5-18. ISSN: 0934-5043.

Thomas, Tim (Motorola Inc, Microcomputer Division). A Mandatory 
Access Control Mechanism for the UNIX FIle System. in: 4th Aerospace 
Computer Security Applications Conference; 1988 Dec 12; Orlando, 
Florida. USA: IEEE: pp.173-177. 
Note: This paper describes a scheme in which the name of any file has 
the same classification as the contents of a file, so that low-clearance 
users are not aware of the names of highly-classified files. If a low-
clearance user attempts to create a file which has the same name as an 
existing highly-classified file, the user is informed of the failure to 
create the file, but a fixed time delay is inserted, to decrease the 
bandwidth of this covert channel. By inserting the delay only on 
failures, which will be infrequent in normal operation, the covert 
channel bandwidth is reduced without causing unnecessary delays to 
successful create operations.
	A major problem with the file name classification scheme 
appears to be that every directory becomes a multi-level object. This 
means that every program which manipulates directories must be 
trusted, or that a set of trusted directory handling procedures must be 
available, and only these may access directories. This seems to diverge 
from the Unix philosophy of directories being, as far as possible, just 
like files.
The concept of using a delay in 'unexpected' cases seems useful for 
reduction of covert channel bandwidth seems viable, provided that it is 
appropriately implemented. Discussion with the speaker revealed that, 
in his implementation, the delay is created using the Unix 'sleep' 
facility, which allows a process change to occur during the 'sleep'. This 
means that, in this implementation, the system is still vulnerable to 
attack by several processes acting in concert, each attacking in turn, 
while the others 'sleep it off', This could be rectified by using a 'busy' 
loop as the delay, but, obviously, performance will suffer if the 
'unexpected' case occurs frequently. It seems likely that an optimal 
compromise could be found (perhaps delay inversely proportional to 
probability of 'unexpected' event).
It should be noted that, by using appropriate coding, the data rate 
through one of these 'asymmetric covert channels' can be increased to 
at least twice that which is obtained using straightforward encoding.
/security/multilevel security/file servers/operating 
systems/UNIX/covert channels.

Thompson, D. J. et al. Prototyping to Explore MLS/DBMS Design. 
Computers and Security. 1989 May; 8(3): 229.
Note: Abstract in TechGnosis, June 1989 (PO689-51).
The application of prototyping, using Prolog, in the design of multilevel 
secure databases (MLS/DBMS) is examined.  The concept is illustrated 
by and MLS/DBMS prototype based on the Bell and LaPadula model.  This 
paper considers the design issues, including commercial applications, 
involved in building the Prolog prototype. Features of the current 
prototype are discussed, including the security policies used by the 
prototype and how data stored in the prototype is separated.  
Appendices illustrate a sample run of the MLS/DBMS prototype.
/security/multilevel security/databases.

