Thuraisingham, M. B. (MITRE). A Multilevel Secure Object-Oriented Data 
Model. in: 12th National Computer Security Conference; 1989 Oct 10; 
Baltimore. USA: NIST/NCSC; 1989: 579-590. 
/security/multilevel security/databases/object-oriented 
databases/multilevel databases.

Thuraisingham, M. B. (The MITRE Corporation). Secure Query Processing 
in Intelligent Database Management Systems. in: 5th Annual Computer 
Security Applications Conference; 1989 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1989: pp.204-214. ISBN: 0-8186-2006-4.
In a multilevel secure database management system, users cleared at 
different security levels access and share a database with data at 
different sensitivity levels. A serious threat to database security, not 
adequately addressed at present, is the inference problem. That is, 
users acquire unauthorized information from the responses that they 
legitimately receive. It is the inferencing capability and deductive 
power of intelligent database systems that could provide viable 
approaches for handling the inference problem. In this paper is 
described secure query processing in intelligent database systems. The 
types of database systems that are considered are augmented 
relational systems, fuzzy relational systems and object-oriented 
systems.
/databases/multilevel security/Inference.

Thuraisingham, M. B.; Keefe, T. F.; Tsai, W. T. (Honeywell//Univ. of 
Minnesota). A Multilevel Security Model for Object-Oriented Systems. 
11th NCSC; 1988 Oct 17; Gaithersburg. Gaithersburg: NBS/NCSC: pp.1-9. 
Note: The model discussed in this paper supports a data sensitivity 
level classification scheme appropriate for use in multilevel secure 
database management systems; data is classified on the basis of 
content, context, time and the possibility of aggregation. In order to 
avoid the problem of overclassification of data, the security model 
allows a subject to work with the lowest clearance level necessary to 
complete a task.
	In order to avoid the problem of a lowly-cleared subject either 
overwriting a highly-classified object, or making use of a covert 
channel if he cannot use its name, a form of polyinstantiation is used, 
so that a single name may refer to more than one object.
/security/multilevel security/databases/object-oriented 
databases/multilevel databases.

