Tsai, C. R. Covert Channel Analysis in Secure Computer Systems. 
Maryland: Department of Electrical Engineering, University of Maryland; 
c1987 Aug. 
/security/verification/covert channels.

Tsai, Chii-Ren; Gligor, Virgil D. (University of Maryland Department of 
Electrical Engineering). A Bandwidth Computation Model for Covert 
Storage Channels and its Applications. in: 1988 IEEE Symposium on 
Security and Privacy; 1988 Apr 18; Oakland Ca. Washington DC: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1988: pp.108-121. ISBN: 0-8186-.0850-1.
Note: The idea is to obtain more realistic estimates for covert channel 
capacities on a shared system, including factors such as noise 
scheduling delays, 'think times' etc. Bandwidth limitations of covert 
channels based on worst-case analysis can lead to serious degradations 
of performance. Using such an analysis would allow for example the 
implementation of dynamically adjustable bandwidth limitations and 
thus minimize the impact on performance.
The work is based on Markov chains and queuing theory and appears to 
be well-founded. It was one of the few papers to present firm, usable 
results.
Most practical policies for handling covert storage channels are based 
on band-width limitation techniques.  In this paper we present a Markov 
model for bandwidth computation and its application to Secure Xenix.  
The model can be used for computing the bandwidth of both individual 
channels and aggregated channels (i.e., serial and parallel aggregation).  
Based on this model, a tool has been built and experiments conducted to 
determine the factors that affect the bandwidth of covert storage 
channels (i.e., noise, scheduling delays, load, 'think times').  The  tool 
can be used to compute the minimum delays for each channel under 
various loads and program behaviour.  Thus, it enables the placement of 
dynamically-adjustable delays in multiprogrammed systems, which 
guarantees minimum performance impact.
/security/multilevel security/covert channels/verification.

Tsai, Chii-Ren; Gligor, Virgil D.; Chandersekaran, C. Sekar. A Formal 
Method for the Identification of Covert Storage Channels in Source 
Code. 1987. 
A formal method for the identification of covert storage channels is 
presented and its application to the source code of the Secure Xenix 
kernel is illustrated. The method is based on the identification of all 
visible/alterable kernel variables by using information flow analysis 
of language code (e.g., C language code). The method also requires that 
after the sharing relationships among the kernel primitives and the 
visible/alterable variables are determined, the non-discretionary 
access rules implemented by each primitive be applied to identify the 
covert storage channels. The method can be generalized to other 
implementation languages, and has the following advantages: it leads to 
the discovery of all storage channels in kernel implementations; it 
helps determine whether the non-discretionary access rules are 
implemented correctly; and, it can be automated.
An additional important aspect of applying this method to a kernel 
interface is the discovery of all kernel variables that are modified 
directly or indirectly through that interface. The analysis of the 
modification scenarios provides the necessary conditions for all kernel 
penetration. This implies that, in any kernel that enforces both a non-
discretionary security and an integrity policy, penetration instances 
are the dual of covert storage channels instances.
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 74 - 86
The method described in the paper is founded on the identification of 
all visible/alterable kernel variables using information flow analysis 
of language code. The method is currently based on analysis of C 
programming language semantics but apparently can be generalised to 
other programming languages with similar control structures.
The paper explains that early attempts to identify covert channels have 
focussed on analysis of formal top level specifications of operating 
system kernels and trusted processes. While it is important to catch 
these flaws as early as possible in the design process it is claimed 
that total reliance on analysis of top level specifications is inadequate 
and can lead to the discovery of 'false flows' i.e flows which appear in 
the analysis but not in the code. In part the problem lies in imprecise 
correspondence arguments between specifications and code, but more 
significantly specifications do not contain sufficient detail of data 
structures and code to detect flows caused by the implementation 
language semantics - eg control statements, pointer assignments.
The paper summarises the authors' experience in applying the method to 
the secure Xenix kernel. The analysis of the entire kernel code is 
complete and was done manually prior to the availability of a support 
tool now being implemented. The results of the analysis are interesting 
and show that the method is successful at finding covert channels of 
surprising subtlety - in all fewer than two dozen channels were 
identified.
As this method is concerned with identifying security weaknesses in 
implemented systems, this paper should interest people involved with 
the evaluation of secure systems; furthermore, the support tool would 
make a valuable addition to an evaluation facility.
/covert channels/Secure Xenix/security/multilevel security/security 
kernels/verification/Secure Xenix. 

Tsai, C-R; Gligor, Virgil; Chandersekaran, C. S. On the Identification of 
Covert Storage Channels in Secure Systems. IEEE Trans. on Software 
Engineering. 1990 Jun; 16(6): 569-580.
Note: Revised version of IEEE Symposium paper.
A practical method for the identification of covert storage channels is 
presented and its application to the source code of the Secure Xenix 
kernel is illustrated. The method is based on the identification of all 
visible/alterable kernel variavles by using information-flow analysis 
of language code (e.g. C language code).  The method also requires that, 
after the sharing relationships among the kernel primitives and the 
visible. alterable variables are determined, the nondiscretionary access 
rules implemented by each primitive be applied to identify the 
potential storage channels.  The method can be generalised to other 
implementation languages and has the following advantages: 1) it helps 
discover all potential storage channels in kernel code, thereby helping 
determine whether the nondiscretionary access rules are implemented 
correctly; 2) it helps avoid discovery of false flow violations and their 
unnecessary analysis; and 3) it helps identify the kernel location where 
audit code and time-delay variables need to be placed for covert-
channel handling.
