Turn, Rein (California State University, Northridge Ca.). Information 
Privacy Issues for the 1990s. in: 1990 IEEE Computer Society 
Symposium on Research in Security and Privacy; 1990 May 7; Oakland. 
USA: IEEE; 1990: 394-399. 
Note: This paper presented an appeal for more interest to be taken in 
privacy as opposed to security. Privacy was defined as the rights of 
individuals to determine the extent that information should be given to 
others.
It was pointed out that the vast majority of work presented at the 
conference on security and privacy was about security. Now that many 
countries have data privacy laws it is appropriate that there should be 
more technical work in the area.
Information privacy deals with protecting individuals against potential 
violations of their rights due to collection, storage and use of personal 
information by the government and private sector organisations. The 
privacy protection laws enacted in the 1970s are inadequate and 
limited in scope.  New applications of computer-communications 
technology involving personal information are now emerging for the 
decade of the 1990s and create new potential for privacy violations.  
The basics of privacy protection, examples of the new technologies and 
the need for new privacy laws are discussed in this paper.

