Tymes, L. R. Tymnet - a Terminal Oriented Communication Network. 
1971. 
AFIPS Conf. Proc. 38 pp.211-216
This is the standard reference for the US public packet-switching wide 
area network that developed from Tymshare Inc.'s internal terminal 
network used by their public time-sharing service.
Network switches are interconnected by voice-grade lines. A central 
supervisor creates a virtual connection route for each call at call 
initialization and flow control is performed on a link-by-link basis for 
each virtual connection. Messages between nodes contain data for up to 
20 different calls, packed into 66-byte frames. Data is repackaged at 
each node into new blocks for the next hop.
The network was designed to fulfil the needs of the full duplex 
terminal in the ten to thirty character per second range. The paper 
itself describes this requirement, gives the system's topology and 
hardware and then gives a detailed description of the virtual circuits 
set up between terminal and host through the network. It then 
describes the network supervisor used to establish the virtual circuits
/TYMNET/network example. 

