Unger, E. A.; Harn, Lein; Kumar, Vijay (Kansas State University & The 
University of Missouri at Kansas City). Entropy as a Measure of 
Database Information. in: 6th Annual Computer Security Applications 
Conference; 1990 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE Computer Society 
Press; 1990: pp.80-87. ISBN: 0-8186-2105-2.
An estimate of the information a database contains and the 
quantification of the vulnerability of that database to compromise by 
inferential methods is the subject of this paper. Such a measure could 
be used to evaluate the deterrent value of extant protection methods 
and provide a measure of the potential for inferential compromise 
through the use of one of the known attack tools. In this paper, we 
explore the use of the concept of entropy a defined for information by 
Shannon for the purpose of quantifying information content in a 
database and develop a measure of vulnerability based on entropy. Use 
of the measure, when exact disclosure through the use of a tracker is 
anticipated, is characterized for both static and dynamic databases at 
design and operational time.
/TDBMS/Entropy/Vulnerability/databases.

