Unger, Elizabeth; Keller-McNulty, Sallie (Kansas State University). The 
Deterrent Value of Natural Change in a Statistical Database. in: 13th 
National Computer Security Conference; 1990 Oct 1; Washington. USA: 
NIST; 1990; 2: 748-757. 

Unger, Elizabeth; McNulty, Sallie Keller; Connelly, Paul (Kansas State 
University & AT&T Corporation). Natural Change in Dynamic Databases 
as a Deterrent to Compromise by Trackers. in: 6th Annual Computer 
Security Applications Conference; 1990 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1990: pp.116-124. ISBN: 0-8186-2105-2.
There has been considerable research in database security and 
inference control; however, that research deals primarily with 
statistical databases. Although some of the mechanisms proposed to 
deter compromise artificially introduce dynamicism into these 
otherwise static databases, very little effort has been devoted to the 
area of natural dynamics. The purpose of this work is to determine a 
deterrent value for natural change in dynamic databases. More 
specifically, we investigate how the changing value of an attribute 
prevents the inference of the confidential value of that attribute for 
any particular record. Assuming a restricted query set size, we 
calculate bounds of deterrence to compromise by the individual, 
general, and double trackers.
/TDBMS/Dynamic Databases/security.

