Vaccaro, H. S.; Liepins, G. E. (Los Alamos National Laboratory//Oak 
Ridge National Laboratory). Detection of Anomalous Computer Session 
Activity. in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy; May 1; 
Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 1989: 280-289. 
Note: This paper describes a system called W&S (Wisdom and Sense) 
developed at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
The aim is to make the job of CSSO (Computer System Security Officer) 
less of a bind and therefore more likely to be done properly. The worse 
aspect of this post seems to be the inspection of reams of boring audit 
data. W&S is an attempt essentially to preprocess this audit data 
(possibly in real time) and reduce it to a form containing events only of 
interest from a security point of view. The approach taken is to set up 
a rule base describing likely and acceptable behaviour (by human input 
or analysis of historical audit data) and check off events against this 
rule base.
The rule base in W&S is a highly compacted tree structure, claimed to 
hold a rule per 6-7 bytes of storage, and can be held in memory 
(presumably for performance considerations) typically occupying 0.5-
1.0 Mbyte.
The authors define a thread as a sequence of audit records that are 
related in specified field values, such as user Fred and terminal 
tta1 (the user-terminal combination being a common thread). The 
system keeps a rolling value for the degree of anomaly (the figure of 
merit FOM) for a thread and alerts the CSSO when a threshold is 
exceeded. Previous slight anomalies decay in FOM contribution with 
time (event number).
The essential points seem to be that the rule base contains local 
computer use patterns, can be made to contain rules relating to 
security policies, relieves a human being of the typically unmanageable 
task of inspecting reams of audit data, and can do all this in very 
nearly real time using workstation class hardware.
The system is intended to support logon and normal security protocols 
and not supplant them. Furthermore, it is clear that this system lies on 
top of an operating system (the discussion has a VMS flavour) and 
therefore does not rely on system software modification.
The obvious risks are:
 if a system has already been penetrated when W&S is set up, then 
subversive behaviour by one or more users will be incorporated in the 
rule base as normal behaviour;
 the rule base has to be updated with new historical data as computer 
usage is unlikely to be static but have trends, enabling an attack where 
the hostile slowly expands his or her subversive activities;
 W&S obviously cannot withstand a direct successful attack on the 
rule base itself, such an attack will rapidly compromise the rule base 
as the rules are human-readable (this is held to be a feature).
/audit/intrusion detection/Wisdom and Sense.

Vaccaro, Hank. Resolver Concepts. 5th Intrusion Detection Workshop; 
