Varadarajan, Rammohan (Informix Software, Inc.). An Overview of 
Informix-Online/Secure. in: 14th National Computer Security 
Conference; 1991 Oct; Washington. USA: NIST/NCSC; 1991; 2: pp.407-
416. 
This paper discusses the architecture of the Informix trusted DBMS 
product, INFORMIX-OnLine/Secure, a solution for open system 
environments based on the Trusted Database Interpretation's trusted 
subject architecture description. INFORMIX-OnLine/Secure runs as a 
trusted application on secure UNIX platforms. It provides row level 
labeling, supports a large label space, provides multimedia capability, 
and supports on-line transaction processing. It has a small trusted 
computing base (TCB) that adheres to the "least privilege" doctrine.
/INFORMIX/UNIX/Databases.

Varadharajan, Vijay (Hewlett-Packard Laboratories). Notification: A 
Practical Security Problem in Distributed Systems. in: 14th National 
Computer Security Conference; 1991 Oct; Washington. USA: NIST/NCSC; 
1991; 2: pp.386-396. 
This paper considers a practical problem that arises when considering 
scenarios in distributed computing environments. In a distributed 
object system, the dependency between objects is common phenomenon. 
This in turn implies that changes occurring in an object's state will 
affect the behaviour of other objects. For correct operation of the 
system these changes need to be properly notified to the other 
cooperating objects. Such situations are very common in many office 
applications and we consider one such typical case, namely the 
producer-consumer scenario and examine its security implications. We 
consider a solution to this problem, referred to as the Notification 
Problem. The solution is based on the increasingly publicized Kerberos 
authentication system. Note that Kerberos forms part of the OSF's 
Distributed Computing Environment (DCE). We then consider the trust 
implications of the proposed solution which leads us to the more 
general problem of proxy or delegation in distributed systems. We 
conclude the paper by proposing an extension of the Kerberos system to 
handle proxy situations.
/Distributed Systems/Security/Kerberos/Notification Problem.

Varadharajan, Vijay; Allen, Phillip; Black, Stewart (Hewlett Packard 
Laboratories). An Analysis of the Proxy Problem in Distributed 
Systems. in: 1991 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on Research in 
Security and Privacy; 1991 May; Oakland, California. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1991: pp.255-275. ISBN: 0-8186-2168-0.
This paper looks at the problem of delegation of rights, or proxy in 
distributed object systems. We present two signature-based schemes 
to achieve delegation which require different inter-object trust 
assumptions. These schemes have been instantiated using public key 
and secret key based cryptographic techniques. We also consider 
additional trust implications which arise from these implementations. 
Then we consider the issue of revocation of delegations and propose 
several ways of achieving this. These solutions have been compared 
with the mechanism proposed in the Distributed System Security 
Architecture. Finally, to conclude the paper, we consider the Kerberos 
authentication system and propose extensions to implement the 
delegation scheme.
/Authentication/Distributed Systems/Proxy/Protocols/Kerberos.

Varadharajan, Vijay; Black, Stewart (Hewlett-Packard Laboratories). 
Formal Specification of a Secure Distributed Messaging System. in: 
12th National Computer Security Conference; 1989 Oct 10; Baltimore. 
USA: NIST/NCSC; 1989: 146-171. 

Varadharajan, Vijay; Black, Stewart (Hewlett-Packard Laboratories). A 
Multilevel Security Model for a Distributed Object-Oriented System. in: 
6th Annual Computer Security Applications Conference; 1990 Dec; 
Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1990: pp.68-78. 
ISBN: 0-8186-2105-2.
Distributed systems are vulnerable to a number of security attacks. In 
this paper we look at the security problems of object-based distributed 
systems, and propose a model based on labelling for multilevel 
security. The purpose of this model is to preserve the information flow 
security in a distributed object-oriented system. We consider the basic 
concepts of the object paradigm, and also the security threats to such 
systems. We postulate various modelling possibilities, and produce a 
specific set of security properties which describe a multilevel secure 
object model. This particular model should not be considered as a 
panacea, but rather should demonstrate how the various modelling 
decisions are reflected in an actual model. We conclude with a 
discussion of possible avenues of future research.
/security models/multilevel security/Distributed Object-Oriented 
System.

Varadharajan, Vijay; Black, Stewart. Multilevel Security in a 
Distributed Object-Oriented System. Computers and Security. 1991 Feb; 
10(1): 69-72.

Veeder, Robert N. (Executive Office of the President). Making Eligibilty 
for Federal Benefits Determinations Under the Computer Matching and 
Privacy Protection Act of 1988 (P. L. 100-503). in: 12th National 
Computer Security Conference; 1989 Oct 10; Baltimore. USA: 
