Vinter, Stephen T. (BBN Laboratories). Extended Discretionary Access 
Controls. in: 1988 IEEE Symposium on Security & Privacy; 1988 Apr 18; 
Oakland Ca. Washington DC: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1988: pp.39-
49. ISBN: 0-8186-0850-1.
Note: This paper discusses a design intended to overcome some of the 
problems of implementing discretionary access controls using access 
control lists.
The general features of the operating system design were presented in 
a separate paper at this symposium (Casey, Vinter et. al.); it is based 
on the idea of objects being instances of abstract data types. For each 
object, the access control list consists of a series of 'contextual client 
identities' (CCI), each of which incorporates a role; a client can invoke 
an operation on an object if his current CCI is in the ACL and the role is 
appropriate for that operation on that type of object. (In fact, a user 
has a set of current CCI's, and the operation is permitted if any are 
appropriate.) For each abstract data type, the operations can be grouped 
according to the role required to invoke the operation, and typically 
there will be more than one operation in each group; in addition, the 
roles would be applicable to a variety of abstract data types.
The scheme also allows for proxy CCI's, so that, for example, a print 
manager can access the file to be printed on behalf of the user, without 
having to have the print manager appearing in the ACL for the file. The 
proxy CCI can be restricted to apply only to a given set of objects, so 
the manager being given the proxy CCI does not have the full rights of 
the client on whose behalf he is acting. Proxy CCI's are like capabilities 
in that they are transferrable access rights; as with normal 
capabilities, they must be unforgeable.
Unlike capabilities, proxy CCI's cannot be used to identify the object to 
be operated on. When a client supplies a proxy CCI, the kernel adds it to 
the current CCI set for the manager, and it is the responsibility of the 
manager to remove it when no longer required. Managers that cannot be 
trusted to do this removal can, if required, be set up so that they 
cannot obtain proxy CCI's.
The design is an attempt to try and combine some of the features of 
capabilities into an ACL-based system, with much of the complexity 
required in the type managers handled by automatic code generation 
from interface specifications. The authors admit that it is a paper 
study and requires more work to determine its usefulness in practice.
Presents a discretionary access control mechanism proposed for a 
secure distributed operating system being designed at BBN 
Laboratories.  The DOS is an object-oriented system that used access 
control lists to authorize access to objects.  Discretionary controls are 
implemented in a type-specific manner inside the managers of objects.  
Several extensions to conventional access control lists are proposed, 
including a limited form of privilege transfer (temporarily passing a 
subset of one's rights to an object to another user), module 
interconnection control (granting exclusive rights to a program 
independent of who is executing it), support for direct operations 
(operations invocable only by a human via a trusted path), roles (sets of 
rights across many different types of objects that correspond to 
specific activities; e.g., administrator, operator, etc.), and restricted 
roles (rights with a more stringent policy of distribution).  A technique 
for automatically generating access control implementations is 
presented that is based on nonprocedural specifications, and an 
implementation approach is proposed that allows the generated code to 
be embedded with high assurance in untrusted object managers using 
hardware protection rings.  The concepts and mechanisms are 
illustrated with a simple banking example.
/security/DAC.

Vissers, C. A. Interface, a Dispersed Architecture. 1976 Jan. 
ACM SIGARCH 4(4) Proc. 3rd Symp. Computer Architecture
/architectures. 

