Waldhart, Neil A. (TRW Systems Integration Group). The Army Secure 
Operating System. in: 1990 IEEE Computer Society Symposium on 
Research in Security and Privacy; 1990 May 7; Oakland. USA: IEEE; 1990 
May 7: 50-74. 
Note: The ASOS project is intended to produce a portable, secure and 
configurable operating system for real-time, tactical applications, 
that is capable of being evaluated (depending on the configuration) at 
C2 through to A1. An alternative way of viewing it is as the 
development of a family of operating systems sharing common design 
elements, user interface and user documentation. This talk gave an 
overview of the development, and described some of the lessons 
learned.
As with the applications they are intended to support, the two existing 
ASOS implementations (one targetted at C2, the other at A1) are 
almost completely written in Ada  the Ada packages were used to 
assist meeting the abstraction and data handling requirements called 
up by the TCSEC. Compile-time constant and conditionals are used to 
produce a variety of configurations, for example whether the system 
has multilevel support (C2 or A1). As ASOS-based systems are intended 
for tactical applications, it was deemed practicable to restrict the 
programs that can be run on a given system to those installed at sysgen 
time. The Ada runtime support library is implemented as nonkernel 
software, copies of which run in the same, unprivileged domain as the 
Ada program it supports.
Trusted software outside the ASOS kernel also runs in an unprivileged 
mode, making calls to the ASOS functions either directly or via the Ada 
runtime support library, but is permitted one or exemptions to the 
security policy (as needed to fulfil its role). Amongst the trusted 
functions implemented this way are the system administrator 
interface, the line printer spooler and the secure audit capture (which 
creates the audit trail and sends audit alarms to the system 
administrator interface).
The formal model for the MLS (A1-targetted) version covers both 
confidentiality and integrity; for the former, the model supports both a 
simple security policy and a star-policy, whereas for integrity there is 
only a simple security policy. Gypsy and the GVE were used for the 
FTLS, with the GIFT tool (developed by Computational Logic Inc) for 
covert flow analysis. Evaluation would be specific to a particular 
configuration of the system.
The project found that the programming staff  even senior and 
experienced programmers  took time (3-6 months) to become 
proficient in the use of Ada and more importantly in the subtleties of 
designing for security. Software development would have been eased if 
more automated tool support had been available  it would have been 
cost-effective spending time at the start of the project writing 
suitable tools and better debuggers. On the formal side, Gypsy was 
found good for the formal specifications, and mapped fairly cleanly 
down to Ada code, but the GVE was thought to leave much to be 
desired: it is difficult to master, labour-intensive and has a user-
unfriendly interface (as least on the Symbolics machines used by the 
project). A major omission which would greatly improve the utility of 
GVE is assistance in reproving assertions after minor specification 
changes.
In all, an interesting presentation for anyone proposing to implement a 
secure system of any scale.
The Army Secure Operating System is a family of operating systems 
intended to serve the tatical needs of the U.S. Army.  It is currently 
comprised of two systems designed to be certifiable to Classes C2 and 
A1 of the DoD Trusted Computer System Evaluation Criteria (TCSEC).  
Both operating systems proved a common user interface, support real-
time applications written in Ada, and are configurable and easily 
portable to alternate hardware architectures.  A Brief overview of the 
development is presented, including a description of the 
hardware/software architecure, the current status of the project, and 
a review of lessons learned during the three-year development.
/security/operating systems/ASOS/TCSEC.

Waleffe, D. de; Quisquater, J. -J (Philips Research). Better Login 
