Walker, S. T. Network Security Overview. 1985. 
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1985 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.62-76
This paper defines some standard terms such as various operating 
modes, and then discusses 4 different secure network configurations of 
increasing complexity. In this discussion there appears to be a 
fundamental flaw in his thinking, which restricts information from 
being passed to a process running at a higher clearance in a remote 
host, simply because the writing process cannot receive any 
acknowledgement from the receiving process. This argument is in 
general fallacious if there is a trusted component in either host, since 
this can handle any network level ackowledgements, retries, etc.
The paper also discusses the WWMCCS Information System (WIS) and 
IS/A AMPE.
/WIS/WAN/WWMCCS/Networks/Security/Multilevel Security/I-S/A 
AMPE/Security/review. 

Walker, Stephen T. (Trusted Information Systems Inc.). Network 
Security: The Parts of the Sum. in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security 
and Privacy; May 1; Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 
1989: 2-9. 
Note: The presentation began with an overview of the different network 
security components (e.g. encryption, network protocols and trusted 
system principles) and the relationships between them, the author 
pointing out that these components, and the groups addressing them, 
should really work together even though it may be painful to do so.
The author suggested that rather than treat encryption as a completely 
separate box, as in end-to-end link encryption, it could be useful to 
apply encryption to the host itself, for instance, as a method of 
downgrading by scrambling. This would have the advantage of keeping 
the trusted decision over what is data and what is header inside the 
host, thus reducing the complexity of the cryptographic peripheral.
An example was given of how this could be applied to a PC running a 
trusted operating system. The trusted OS would make use of the 
encryption device to downgrade sensitive data. An untrusted 
application could then append a non-sensitive header and transmit the 
message. It was pointed out, however, that this mode of operation was 
not approved by current security doctrine.
The presentation finished by going through the good and bad news in 
network security so far. The good news was that there is an almost 
universal demand for low trust (C2, B1) systems and that the demand 
for higher (B2+) systems was steadily growing. The bad news was that 
most products currently available were still only attaining around C2 
level. The reasons given for this were that the evaluation process is 
too hard, not only for technical reasons but for financial and 
bureaucratic reasons as well.
/security/multilevel security/networks.

