Weber, D. G.; Lubarsky, R. The SDOS Project - Verifying Hook-up 
Security. 1987. 
Open systems, now common in many small computers, have given the 
user logical access to all parts of his or her system. At the same time, 
the computing environment is moving out of the computing center and 
into the office and home, giving users physical access to their systems. 
This movement of the computing environment necessitates a 
mechanism to prevent the user from physically accessing certain parts 
of his or her system if logical security (of the type which limits the 
user's ability to make copies, change code etc.) is to be reliable. This 
paper describes the development of a physical security system for 
protecting electronic circuits from unauthorized access. This system 
can be user to ensure that logical security mechanisms will remain 
uncompromised. The requirements, design criteria, and implementation 
of the system are discussed with an orientation towards practicality 
and manufacturing.
Proc 3rd Aerospace Computer Security Conference, December 1987
/Security/security models/verification/hook-up/SDOS. 

Weber, Ron. Control in Electronic Funds Transfer Systems: A Survey and 
Synthesis. Computers & Security. 1989 Apr; 8(2): 123-138. ISSN: 0167-
4048.

Weems, Bob P.; Shieh, Wen-Gong; Jaseemuddin, Muhammad (The 
University of Texas at Arlington). Complete Containment Sets and their 
Application to the Inference Problem. in: 7th Annual Computer Security 
Applications Conference; 1991 Dec; San Antonio, Texas. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1991: pp.187-200. ISBN: 0-8186-2280-6.
An approach to the inference problem in database security is described. 
This new approach is based on existing ideas in query containment 
theory. This theory may be used to generalize query modification, a 
query answering approach that allows a user to write a query that is 
beyond his access privileges, but the system will construct a set of 
similar queries that is within his privileges. This generalization may 
also be used to approach the inference problem. Examples of 
formalizing inference problems within the framework of queries are 
given, along with an algorithm for the detection of inference violations. 
Finally, suggestions are made for query answering to avoid inferences 
at several granularities by blocking all answers for a query, component 
queries, individual tuples, or individual values.
/databases/Inference/Query Modification/Complete Containment Set.

