2T247. 

Weingart, Steve H. Physical Security for the Abyss System. 1987. 
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp on Security and Privacy, pp. 52 - 58
This paper describes some of the techniques used to implement a 
physically-secure, tamper-reacting processor for the storage and use 
of encipherment keys. The aim is to ensure that an attacker cannot 
learn the values of the keys currently being held, nor modify the device 
so that keys subsequently loaded can be determined. In addition, 
deciphered data held within the device should also be secure.
The major defence technique is to wrap the whole device in very fine 
multi-strand wire acting as a resistance element, and then potted in an 
opaque material that is harder than the insulation on the wire. Physical 
attacks are likely to cause breaks or shorts, and the change in 
resistance causes the protected RAM to be erased.
This paper is reassuring, in that it indicates that it feasible to produce 
in quantity  tamperproof devices for commercial use. If this were not 
practicable, it would certainly be impossible to produce such devices 
to government and military standards in large numbers.
/security/Abyss/Software protection/Tamper detection/hardware. 

Weingart, Steve H.; White, Steve R.; Arnold, William C.; Double, Glen P. 
(IBM). An Evaluation System for the Physical Security of Computing 
Systems. in: 6th Annual Computer Security Applications Conference; 
1990 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1990: 
pp.232-243. ISBN: 0-8186-2105-2.
Physical security technology is being used more often to protect the 
integrity of computing systems and the assets they contain. A physical 
security rating system is defined in terms of the difficulty of mounting 
a successful physical attack against it, quality assurance, 
documentation and system testing. An evaluation system is presented 
for determining adequate physical security, as a function of the 
environment in which the system is placed and the value of the assets 
resident in the system.
/Risk Assessment/Evaluation/Physical Security.

