Weissman, C. Security Controls in the ADEPT-50 Time-Sharing System. 
1969. 
AFIPS Conf. Proc. (1969 FJCC) pp.119-133
The ADEPT-50 time sharing system was one of the earliest systems to 
incorporate a formal security model. The formal security model used is 
called the High Water Mark model. Each subject and object has a 
security class, and the model defines an ordering on the security 
classes that corresponds to a lattice (although it is not identified as 
such). A subject can invoke an operation on an object if and only if the 
level of that subject in the lattice is at least that of the object. The 
High Water Mark model is of particular interest since it is one of the 
few security models to be implemented on an operational system
/Verification/Security Models/Security/Security/Multilevel 
Security/High Water Mark Model/Formal specification/Adept-50. 

