White, Steve R.; Comerford, Liam. ABYSS: a Trusted Architecture for 
Software Protection. 1987. 
ABYSS (A Basic Yorktown Security System) is an architecture for the 
trusted execution of application software. It supports a uniform 
security service across the range of computing systems. The use of 
ABYSS discussed in this paper is oriented towards solving the software 
protection problem, especially in the lower end of the market. Both 
current and planned software distribution channels are supportable by 
the architecture, and the system is nearly transparent to legitimate 
users. A novel use-once authorization mechanism, called a token, is 
introduced as a solution to the problem of providing authorizations 
without direct communication. Software vendors may use the system to 
obtain technical enforcement of virtually any terms and conditions of 
sale of thir software, including such things as rental software. 
Software may be transferred between systems, and backed up to guard 
against loss in case of failure. We discuss the problem of protecting 
software on these systems, and offer guidelines to its solution. ABYSS 
is shown to be a general security base, in which many security 
applications may execute.
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 38 - 51
The problem addressed by this paper is the need to ensure that 
commercially-supplied software is only used by the purchaser in 
accordance with the terms and conditions set by the vendors. It would 
not appear that the paper is of direct relevance to the COMPUSEC 
community.
The mechanism suggested is based on the idea of having critical parts 
of the software being executed on a separate, physically-protected 
processor, which is also used to hold decryption keys for the software 
supplied on a read-once token. The paper goes into some detail of the 
architecture, including ways in which safety backups of the keys can be 
taken and used, and how rights-to-execute can be transferred (if 
permitted) from one protected processor to another.
It was claimed that the production cost of the protected processor 
could be of the order of tens of dollars, with the added production cost 
to the software vendors being the cost of the token. As the scheme 
makes software piracy more difficult, 'honest' customers could benefit 
considerably if vendors are able to substantially reduce the price of 
their software.
/security/Abyss/software protection/hardware/crypto. 

White, Stev R.; Comerford, Liam. ABYSS: An Architecture for Software 
Protection. IEEE Trans. on Software Engineering. 1990 Jun; 16(6): 619-
629.
