Williams, James G. (The MITRE Corporation). Modeling Nondisclosure in 
Terms of the Subject-Intrusion Stream. in: 1991 IEEE Computer Society 
Symposium on Research in Security and Privacy; 1991 May; Oakland, 
California. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1991: pp.64-77. ISBN: 0-
8186-2168-0.
This paper gives a formal definition of nondisclosure for a computing 
system and describes a functional decomposition of the system into 
two kinds of activities, namely the selection and execution of subject 
instructions. It then gives security requirements for each of the two 
resulting subsystems and proves that if each subsystem satisfies its 
security requirements, then the entire system satisfies the given 
nondisclosure property. Finally, in order to show how security can be  
enforced by the system, an access-control model is given for subject-
instruction processing that guarantees satisfaction of the given 
security requirements for subject-instruction processing.
/Models/Nondisclosure/Subject Instruction Stream.

Williams, John C.; Dinolt, George W. (Ford Aerospace). Formal Model of a 
Trusted File Server. in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy; 
May 1; Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Cmputer Society; 1989: 157-166. 
Note: This paper presents a security model of a file server, aimed at a 
large distributed system being developed by Ford Aerospace. The 
approach to the modelling is to treat a component as a black box, and to 
define security properties with respect to sequences of input and 
output events. No explicit state is defined for a component.
The security condition on the file server is a relation on input and 
output histories, which is to hold at all times, and is concerned only 
with compromise of data, rather than functionality. Requests to the 
file server may result in ACK or NAK responses, depending on whether 
the requested operation was performed. The model specifies that for 
each read response, the data in that response must be identical to the 
data in the most recent write response for that block, and the security 
levels of the read and write responses must be an exact match. The 
model assumes that an operation has only been completed once an ACK 
response has been issued, and that the security label of that response 
is the definitive representation of the level at which the operation was 
performed.
It is claimed that spontaneous creates, or an ACK response to a create 
request having a different security label to the request, are not a 
compromise problem. (Since if the label changes somehow, then the 
original requester will no longer be able to read the file). This is hard 
to believe, since there appears to be nothing to stop a trojan horse in 
the file server signalling the contents of one (high-level) file by 
modulating the creation of other (low-level) files. This would 
contradict the claim that operations on distinct files are non-
interfering.
The paper argues that non-interference was not a suitable technique 
for this model. The idea is that the real world sensitivity of data 
can change (by some unspecified means elsewhere in the system), and 
so in a file server with no regrade facility, the correctness of the 
delete operation is crucial for security. (However there seems to be no 
requirement for a delete response to be issued at all, and so the file 
would still be considered to exist, even if the datas real 
classification had changed). The assertion that their approach is an 
extension of non-interference is not convincing, especially since the 
incorporation of some non-interference statements in the model could 
have prevented the covert channel mentioned above.
The current status of this project is that the security model and 
implementation code have been written in Gypsy, the code has been 
verified against the model, and translation to C has been performed by 
hand. The server runs on a distributed testbed. Work is in progress on a 
grader server, and the problems of hook-up are being studied.
This work is of interest in that an event-based security model has been 
followed through almost to the level of the final code. There appear to 
be flaws in some details of the model, but these may be minor enough 
to be treated as part of a covert channel analysis of the 
implementation, and so elements of the modelling approach might merit 
closer examination.
/security/multilevel security/formal specification/security models.

Williams, John C.; Dinolt, George W. A Graph-Theoretic Formulation of 
Multilevel Secure Distributed Systems: an Overview. 1987. 
Research in developing formalisms for secure distributed systems 
reveals that a graph-theoretic model captures the fundamental notion 
of trust, while permitting a rigorous and elegant decomposition into 
lower levels of implementation. With such a model, security labels 
need be applied to directed edges only, not to events, ports. processes, 
messages, or whatever. Moreover, the usual concept of 'secure state' 
does not lend itself to defining security in a distributed system, 
whereas our Model guarantees secure transitions in precisely this 
context.
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 97 - 103
In this paper graph-theoretic techniques are described for specifying 
multilevel secure distributed systems.
A system is modelled by a labelled, directed graph whose configuration 
changes over time according to a set of security related events. The 
vertices (nodes) of the graph represent processes and directed labelled 
edges (arc) represent classified information flow. Events which affect 
a particular vertex are linearly ordered, otherwise they can occur 
concurrently or in parallel. The occurrence of an event at a vertex can  
transforms the graph by the creation or deletion of incoming or 
outgoing edges.
The paper discusses a Bell-LaPadula-like model of security where 
information is allowed only to flow upwards with respect to the 
lattice structure of security labels. In this context the paper goes on to 
motivate the definition of an untrusted process - this is a vertex 
which, for every event relevant to it, satisfies the condition that the 
label on every outgoing edge dominates the label on every incoming 
edge which has existed to date. While this definition of trusted and 
untrusted process seems to fit the context of the paper it should not be 
viewed as a general definition of these concepts.
The technical content of the paper is complex, and, unfortunately, is 
not very well expressed. However, the paper deserves further study as 
it combines the issues of security modelling and the description of 
parallelism in the behaviour of distributed systems.
/security/multilevel security/distributed systems/security models. 

