/workstations/Operating systems. 

Wilson, Jackson (TRW Defense Systems Group). A Security Policy for an 
A1 DBMS (a Trusted Subject). in: 1989 IEEE Symposium on Security and 
Privacy; May 1; Oakland, California. USA: IEEE Computer Society; 1989: 
116-125. 
Note: This paper describes the security policy of the database 
management system, ASD (an acronym for A1 Secure DBMS). The system 
is currently at the prototype stage running on a prototype operating 
system targeted for A1 certification.
The DBMS is implemented as a trusted subject of a secure operating 
system, i.e. it implements its own mandatory access control (MAC). 
This has been done to avoid the performance/resource penalties of 
using a Hinke-Schaefer type architecture and should also allow the 
DBMS to be evaluated on different secure operating systems without 
having to re-evaluate the operating systems themselves.
The security policy is given in two parts, the first part states the 
constraints that any operating system must meet in order for it to be 
able to host securely ASD, the second (much larger) section describes 
the security policy of the DBMS TCB layer (i.e. the DBMS kernel plus 
trusted processes, e.g. system security officer processes).
The requirements on the secure operating system are essentially that 
it should prevent tampering with or bypassing of the DBMS TCB and that 
it should provide isolation of processes, user authentication, clearance 
checking and output labelling.
The security policy of the DBMS TCB is basically a variation of the Bell 
and LaPadula Model with the restrictions that the security level of a 
subject remains fixed throughout its lifetime and the sensitivity level 
of an object may only be changed by a trusted subject.
/security/multilevel security/databases/formal 
specification/security policies.

Wilson, Jackson (TRW Defense Systems). Views as the Security Objects 
in a Multilevel Secure Relational Database Management System. in: 
1988 IEEE Symposium on Security & Privacy; 1988 Apr 18; Oakland Ca. 
Washington DC: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1988: pp.70-84. ISBN: 0-
8186-0850-1.
Note: This paper from TRW advocates that, in the database world, a 
suitable interpretation for the abstract classified Object of 
Bell/LaPadula is the view.
Some terminology: relation=table; tuple=row (of a table); attribute 
identifies column of table and therefore an element (=field) of a tuple.
Although'view' is carefully defined in the paper as 'predefined named 
retrieval query which defines a virtual relation', evidently what is 
meant by view is 'a virtual relation predefined by a named retrieval 
query'. A virtual relation is constructed on demand from the actual 
'base relations' stored in the database.
The paper begins by assuming that data (elements or tuples) can be 
classified apriori, and we thus need to differentiate between the 
views of a given relation permitted to unclassified users and top-
secret users.
An interesting feature, provided automatically by any serious 
relational DBMS, is the ability to in effect classify data by content. For 
example, we may define a view, which we choose to call 'top-secret', 
such that any element with attribute 'Flight-cargo' and value 
'nuclearweapons' falls into that view. This is because the view is all 
that data which answers (predefined) query, and the query-definition 
may specify the inclusion of data with flight-cargo='nuclearweapons'.
In practice, this feature would seem essential, since presumably 
responsible judgment of appropriate classification is not practical 
separately for every piece of data in large databases. By setting out 
definitions ahead of time, data can be made self-classifying.
Further, explicit classification or labelling mechanisms become 
unnecessary without any loss of fineness of granularity. A disadvantage 
is that definitions of secure views are very revealing and must be 
protected as part of the TCB.
Completeness and consistency may be problematic: solutions are 
proposed. Other advantages and disadvantages are discussed.
The last part of the paper is subsumed to some degree by the Garvey 
and Wu paper so will not be reported on here.
An interesting paper. Describes a proposed approach, not a working 
system.
Presents a mandatory security policy for a multilevel secure relational 
DBMS with views as the security objects, discusses advantages and 
disadvantages of using views as the security objects, describes a 
method for ensuring the completeness and consistency of the set of 
secure views, and describes an approach to implementing views as the 
security objects.
/security/multilevel security/databases/security policies.

Wilson, K.; Massoglia, M. Kernelized Virtual Machine Facility-370: 
