Windley, Phillip J. (University of California, Davis). A Hierarchical 
Methodology for Verifying Microprogrammed Microprocessors. in: 1990 
IEEE Computer Society Symposium on Research in Security and Privacy; 
1990 May 7; Oakland. USA: IEEE; 1990: 345-357. 
Note: The author begins by pointing out the large amount of effort 
which has been required for verifications which have been achieved to 
date of the correctness of microprocessor designs. The authors goal 
is to provide a framework in which a student can complete in six 
months a verification of a microprocessor comparable to VIPER.
The case of VIPER is significant: the proof of VIPER remains incomplete 
because of the large case-explosion which occurred and the size of 
proofs in each case (the funding ran out before all the cases could be 
considered). This is judged to be primarily because the decisions about 
levels of abstraction in the description of VIPER were forced upon the 
verifier, and they were wrong, in that they did not control the case-
explosion, or rather the size of each case. The verifier was faced 
essentially with proving many lemmas (one for each instruction, i.e. 
128), each such that the proof involved some expressions several pages 
long.
Windleys approach is to decompose the system description into a 
hierarchy of state-machines, each of which is an interpreter for the 
execution of the machine above it. The bottom layer is not a state-
machine but a circuit. A system description is presented at four levels 
of abstraction. These are called Macro Level Interpreter, Micro Level 
Interpreter (i.e. microcode engine), Phase Level Interpreter (the four 
phases or subcycles of the microcode engine) and finally Electronic 
Block Model.
A correctness proof is then performed for each pair of adjacent levels, 
which are then composed for the final result. Briefly, the results 
required are to the effect that, for example, when a given instruction is 
selected for execution, the transformation of the micro-level state 
produces the correct transformation of the macro-level state.
Specifications and lemmas are presented, in HOL, for a simple 
microprogrammed microprocessor. The exposition is admirably clear. 
This is another microprocessor whose primary purpose is pedagogical, 
and thus was specified by the verifier. (Is is significant that, of all the 
verifications of microprocessors to date, VIPER is the only one not 
specified by its verifier?)
Windleys approach is based on finding levels of abstraction which 
reduce the cost of number-of-cases times per-case complexity. He 
claims dramatic or order-of-magnitude reduction in verification 
costs, and the claim seems convincing in the case of microprogrammed 
systems. For example, the number of instructions at the phase-level 
is only four.
Windley mentioned in his presentation that the word 
microprogrammed in his title was too restrictive and the approach 
was more generally applicable. It may well be so in principle, but it 
still remains to be shown.
To date, several microprocessors have been verified using formal 
methods.  The only successful verification efforts, however, have been 
on relatively simple microprocessor architectures (fewer than 32 
words of micro instruction store, small instruction set, limited 
features for supporting operating systems, etc.).  The goal of the 
research reported here is to develop methodologies for verifying such a 
microprocessor.  This paper presents a hierarchical methodology for 
decomposing microprocessor verifications which reduces the necessary 
effort by more than an order of magnitude.  A secondary result of the 
research is a verified microengine that can be used to quickly 
implement verified microprocessors with varied architectures.
/formal specification/verification/HOL.

Wing, J. M. Using Larch to Specify Avalon/C++ Objects. IEEE Trans on 
Software Eng. 1990 Sep; 16(9): 1076-1088.

Wing, J. M.; Nixon, M. R. Extending Ina Jo with Temporal Logic. 1986 Apr. 
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1986 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.2-13
This paper describes a study of the feasability of adding mechanisms to 
handle temporal logic to the formal specification language Ina Jo (part 
of the FDM system). This should allow the advantages of formal 
specifications - precision, lack of ambiguity, and amenability to 
machine analysis - to cover systems with concurrency, such as 
operating systems, multiprocessors, and distributed systems.
Ina Jo is based on an underlying model of a nondeterministic state 
machine; specifications consist of global state, assertions and state 
transitions. The paper presents as an example of a specification for a 
secure network (where users have to check with an Access Controller 
before communicating, and then a Key Distribution Centre issues 
cryptovariables for permitted communications).
The lessons learned were: it is relatively easy to extend Ina Jo in this 
manner due to the underlying nondeterministic model; applications 
should drive which logical system to choose; and, there should be a 
written formal definition of specification languages.
As this was only a study paper, it is unclear how much the extensions 
would slow down the proof tools.
/verification/Ina Jo/FDM/Temporal Logic. 

Wing, Jeanette M. A Specifier's Introduction to Formal Methods. 
Computer. 1990 Sep; 23(9): 8-26.
/formal specification/verification.

Winkler-Parenty, Helen (Sybase). Approaches to Building Trusted 
Applications. in: 13th National Computer Security Conference; 1990 Oct 
1; Washington. USA: NIST; 1990; 2: 697-706. 

Winkler-Parenty, Helena B. (Sybase, Inc.). Considerations on TCB 
Subsetting. in: 5th Annual Computer Security Applications Conference; 
1989 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE Computer Society Press; 1989: 
pp.105-106. ISBN: 0-8186-2006-4.
The Trusted Database Management System Interpretation (TDI) provides 
a general taxonomy of popular security architectures, and guidance on 
evaluation considerations. An architecture that has received 
considerable attention is hierarchical trusted computing base (TCB) 
subsetting. This architecture is intended to allow database 
management systems (DBMS) to take advantage of the effort expended 
in producing and evaluating trusted multi-level operating systems. This 
paper explores the advantages and disadvantages that result from use 
of this security architecture. Another architecture, functional 
modularization of a TCB, is presented. This architecture gives the DBMS 
much greater control over its security policy and resource management 
than the TCB subsetting approach, allowing for fuller functionality and 
performance.
/Secure Architectures/TCB.

Winkler-Parenty, Helen (Sybase). SYBASE: The Trusted Subject DBMS. in: 
13th National Computer Security Conference; 1990 Oct 1; Washington. 
USA: NIST; 1990: 589-593. 

Winkler-Parenty, Helen (Sybase). Trusted Systems Interoperability. in: 
13th National Computer Security Conference; 1990 Oct 1; Washington. 
USa: NIST; 1990; 2: 567-569. 

Winkler, J. R.; Page, W. J. (Government Information Systems). Intrusion 
and Anomaly Detection in Trusted Systems. in: 5th Annual Computer 
Security Applications Conference; 1989 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1989: pp.39-45. ISBN: 0-8186-2006-4.
Secure systems and networks generate vast amounts of audit 
information that may reveal unusual situations or patterns of use. 
While such analysis is usually performed only after other evidence is 
uncovered, a strong need exists for real-time analysis. The system we 
describe is a real-time network and host security monitor which 
allows both interactive and automatic audit trail analysis. Audit 
records - tokens of actual user behavior, are examined in context of 
user profiles - measures of expected behavior. This system combines a 
set of statistical tools for both interactive and automatic analysis of 
audit data, an expert system that works in conjunction with the 
statistical tools, and a hierarchical set of audit indicators which are 
based on an Indications and Warning model. The application of the model 
allows us to both collect audit events at a fine level of granularity, as 
well as effectively direct intrusion and anomaly detection by defining 
levels of concern. A set of discrete tools, capabilities, and components 
are implemented in a hybrid design utilizing control concepts from 
operating systems theory and problem-solving concepts from 
blackboard AI systems.
/Risk Management/Intrusion Detection/Audit/Expert System.

Winklet, J. R. (Planning Research Corp). A UNIX Prototype for Intrusion 
and Anomaly Detection in Secure Networks. in: 13th National Computer 
Security Conference; 1990 Oct 1; Washington. USA: NIST; 1990; 1: 115-
124. 

Winskel, G. A Complete Proof System for SCCS with Modal Assertions. 
