Wiseman, S. R. Control of Confidentiality in Databases. Computers & 
Security Journal. 1990 Jan 1(9 (1990)).
Note: SMITE Ref: 1003.
Providing the confidentiality of the information held in a database is 
one of the most important aspects of database security. The problems 
are described and solutions are considered, with particular reference 
to the impact of the confidentiality controls on basic database 
integrity and the availability of the database.
9 (1990) 529-537.
Confidentiality/databases/Integrity/Availability.

Wiseman, S. R. The Control of Integrity in Databases          
 Procs. of the Fourth IFIP WG11.3 Workshop on Database Security; 1990 
Jan 9; Halifax, England. ; 1990 Jan 9; SMITE Ref: 1001. 
Providing security in databases is a difficult task and it is essential to 
separate the concerns of confidentiality and integrity Unfortunately, 
high assurance confidentiality controls and useful integrity controls 
are largely incompatible. In answer to IFIP WG11.3 Question 4, this 
conflict can only be solved by fitting a less powerful data model to the 
security model. Most solutions have preserved the full functionality of 
the database, but weakened the integrity controls. The alternative, 
taken by SWORD [Wood90], is to restrict functionality so that integrity 
may be properly enforced. This of course begs the question, "What 
integrity controls should a secure database provide?", and this paper 
offers an answer.
Databases/integrity.

