Wiseman, S. A Secure Capability Computer System. 1986 Apr. 
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1986 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.86-94
This paper gives a brief outline of the RSRE Flex computer, and then it 
describes how it will be used to achieve various objectives in a secure 
computing system, such as abstract types. This paper describes Flex, a 
capability computer currently implemented on ICL Perq equipment; 
RSRE are currently developing secure hardware known as SCP3 to 
support Flex.
The RSRE view is that capabilities are items of data; holders can copy 
them, or use them to access objects, but they cannot be forged. FLEX 
allows capabilities and scalars (`normal' data) to be stored in the same 
block (segment) - this differs from all other implementations of 
capability architectures. Procedures are small objects, binding 
together the code and an execution environment (non-local variables); 
as these objects are execute only, the environment is protected. 
Objects can be given a key, and can have unlocked or locked 
capabilities; for the latter type, a key is required before access is 
permitted.
Procedure objects and object locking together allow a user-extensible 
abstract data type mechanism. In the paper, a `classified file' is given 
as an example of an abstract data type, and the problem of an editor 
(used to sanitise) containing a Trojan horse is brought up. This leads to 
the idea of a High water mark (HWM) mechanism, and a trusted type 
manager that can read/set the HWM; this in turn leads to the need for a 
trusted Command Line Interpreter, to ensure downgrading is controlled 
by the user.
Persistent storage on the Flex is capability based, but cannot contain 
main-store capabilities. Discs are treated as write-once storage. FLEX 
does not have a security policy such as MLS, but provides (by means of 
the protection inherent in capabilities combined with the procedure and 
abstract type mechanism) means for providing a tailored security 
policy.
/SMITE. 

Wiseman, S. R. The SMITE Object Oriented Backing Store. 1988 Jan 3. 
The SMITE computer system is to be provided with a write once backing 
store that allows objects to be stored permanently. Capabilities are 
used for addressing objects and on the fly garbage collection is used to 
recover inaccessible objects. This paper describes the proposed 
implementation of the backing store and its garbage collector.
RSRE Memorandum 4147: SMITE Ref: 4147. 

