Wiseman, Simon; Terry, Phil; Wood, Andrew; Harrold, Clare (RSRE). The 
Trusted Path between SMITE and the User. in: 1988 IEEE Symposium on 
Security and Privacy; 1988 Apr; Oakland Ca. Washington DC: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1988: pp.147-155. ISBN: 0-8186-0850-1.
Note: The Trusted Path currently being developed for RSRE's SMITE is 
described, the proposal is radically different to the trusted paths 
available on current systems. The SMITE Trusted Path is a screen 
editor, rather than a command interface supporting a very limited 
number of commands.
The Trusted Path to SMITE is, therefore, an order of magnitude more 
complex than existing trusted paths. The paper describes how the novel 
SMITE architecture will be used to support the secure implementation 
of the interface.
Examples from the Z specification of the editor are included in the 
paper, with an indication that an attempt will be made to implement a 
high assurance version of the Trusted Path using stepwise refinement 
carried out by hand.
The implementation of the Trusted Path is heavily dependent on the 
SMITE architecture, and not applicable to more conventional 
architectures.
If signalling channels can only be driven by the Trusted Path, they 
cannot be exploited by Trojan Horses in untrusted software.  To this 
end, the SMITE system aims to provide a general purpose Trusted Path, 
based on a screen editor, which would act as the users' normal 
interface to the system.  The feasibility of the approach relies on the 
use of a sympathetic computer architecture, which supports a fine 
grain of protection.
