Wittbold, J. Todd; Johnson, Dale M. (MITRE). Information Flow in 
Nondeterministic Systems. in: IEEE Computer Society Symposium on 
Security and Privacy; 1990 May 7; Oakland. USA: IEEE; 1990: 144-161. 
Note: The main thesis of the paper is that the combinatorial 
information-flow properties (e.g. Sutherlands Nondeducibility, or 
descendants of Goguen and Meseguers Noninterference) can be 
satisfied by a nondeterministic system and still contain illegitimate 
channels. Shannons communication theory has an important part to 
play here. Examples are given to show the intrinsic inadequacy, for non-
deterministic systems, of purely possibilistic properties which do 
not take probabilities into account.
The paper begins by motivating and introducing a property called 
nondeducibility on strategies, which is a generalisation of 
Sutherlands Nondeducibility. An example is given of a noisy system 
which satisfies Sutherlands Nondeducibility, and yet, by exploiting 
feedback, allows a noiseless channel from transmitter to receiver. The 
transmitter is able to control outputs to the receiver, even though the 
receiver can deduce nothing about actual inputs made by the 
transmitter. The receiver is able however to deduce the transmitters 
strategy, where a strategy is a function used by the transmitter to 
determine next input from previous inputs and their observed effects. 
In the absence of feedback, a strategy is just an input string.
This property is contrasted with McCulloughs Generalized 
Noninterference (aka hookup or restrictiveness), and a 
simplification of it called forward correctability. Thus, in a purely 
possibilistic framework, there are three properties: Nondeducibility (on 
strings), which is too weak; Nondeducibility on strategies, which is 
just right; and Forward Correctability, which is too strong. The third of 
these implies the second, which implies the first. Forward 
Correctability, and hence McCulloughs restrictiveness, is too strong 
because it assumes that the receiver can make deductions from the 
entire history of inputs and outputs, both high and low, up to the point 
of interest.
Next, resource contention systems are introduced, as models for 
connection of transmitter, receiver and noise-process. From a 
contention system, a nondeterministic state machine may be 
constructed, and it is the latter which may or may not have the 
property (e.g. nondeducibility on strategies).
It is shown how the channel capacities depend upon the probability 
distribution of the events of the noise process. It is then conjectured 
that for any contention system, if the corresponding machine has no 
illegitimate flows (i.e. satisfies any of the properties mentioned 
above), then there is a noise-distribution for which all channels have 
zero capacity. This conjecture is shown to be false, by counterexample. 
Thus it is possible to have a resource contention system which 
satisfies every one of the combinatorial security properties 
[considered so far], but nevertheless must have channels of positive 
capacity.
It is interesting to speculate whether the same would hold of the 
property of McLeans Flow Model, presented at the same conference.
The principal aim of this paper is to give an analysis of some recent 
combinatorial theories of computer security from the perspective of 
information theory.  The theories analyzed are information-flow 
theories based on the concept of nondeducibility.  They are intended to 
be applicable to nondeterministic systems that may be networked.

Wofsey, M. M. Advances in Computer Security Management Volume 2. 
1983. 
editor
Wiley Heyden
0-471-26234-X
2T57. 
security. 

Wong, K. Computer Crime - Risk Management and Computer Security. 
