/Crime. 

Wong, R. M.; Berson, T. A.; Feiertag, Richard J. Polonius: An Identity 
Authentication System. 1985. 
SYTEK
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc. 1985 Symp. Security and Privacy pp.101-107
After discussing various problems with passwords (static, user chosen 
and so guessable, handled carelessly, and subject to both eavesdropping 
and exhaustive search attacks) and some common solutions, the paper 
defines the goals of an identification scheme to be that it addresses 
security issues, it must be easy to administer, and that it must be 
portable portable (commercially-developed units have an extra 
requirement to be profit earning). The paper describes POLONIUS, a 
family of products by Sytek including an Authentication Server and a 
PassPort. The latter is a calculator-like device to which users type in 
their PIN. Once this is done, users can identify themselves to the AS, 
which yields a challenge number to be typed in to the PassPort. The 
identification protocol is completed by the user typing in to the AS the 
challenge response calculated (from the challenge number, the quoted 
PIN and an internal unique secret number) and displayed by PassPort.
Use of POLONIUS means that users do not have to entrust knowledge of 
their PINs to, say, an ATM, and the PIN is not transmitted in clear over 
any transmission lines. It does require that the PassPort has to protect 
its secret number so that it will not be revealed by physical tampering 
or by systematic challenge entry.
The paper has an discussion on one-time pads, that is irrelevant in that 
the PassPort does not contain one. The AS does contain a one-time pad, 
but this is used as part of the challenge number generator in 
incorporation with a challenge count for the user (updated at each 
authentication attempt).
/Smart Cards/POLONIUS/Passwords/PassPort/One-time 
Pad/Identification/Authentication. 

Wong, Raymond M. (Oracle Corporation). A Comparison of Secure UNIX 
Operating Systems. in: 6th Annual Computer Security Applications 
Conference; 1990 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE Computer Society 
Press; 1990: pp.322-333. ISBN: 0-8186-2105-2.
Note: Introduction (part of): Since the publication of a number of early 
papers describing the design of secure UNIX operating system 
prototypes, and a Trusted Computer System Evaluation Criteria (TCSEC) 
B2 feasibility study for UNIX, the industry has seen the introduction of 
a number of secure UNIX products and the evaluation of one of these 
products by the National Computer Security Center (NCSC) at the TCSEC 
B1 class. In addition, a number of standards bodies including IEEE POSIX 
1003.6, TRUSIX, Open Software Foundation, UNIX International, X/Open, 
and 88Open have all taken up the issue of standardization of secure 
UNIX features. We can expect that in 1990 and certainly by 1991 almost 
every major UNIX operating system vendor will have introduced either a 
C2 or B1 class compliant product. Furthermore, developments in secure 
UNIX technology are likely to continue as evidenced by AT&T's intent to 
introduce a B2 class compliant secure UNIX with System V release 4.0 
Enhanced Security sometime in 1991 and OSF's plans to meet B3 in 
their OSF/2 operating system. This paper is a summary of a recent 
study conducted by Oracle in determining the similarities and 
differences in the various secure UNIX implementations that are now or 
will shortly be available. The five systems that were surveyed for this 
study are: 1) AT&T System V/MLS, Release 1.1, 2) SunOS MLS, Version 
1.0, 3) SecureWare Security Module Package Plus, Version 1.0, 4) 
Addamax B1st Trusted System Kit for System V 3.0, Release 1.0 and 5) 
Trusted Xenix, Version 1.0.
/UNIX.

