Wood, A. W. (RSRE). Using Ada for Embedded Secure Systems. Procs. of 
The Seventh lnternational IFIP TC'11 Conference on Information 
Security; May 15; Brighton, UK. ; SMITE Ref: 1013. 
Since its definition the Ada language has aroused much strong feeling 
about how it can be used in a secure system. In this paper, we show, by 
introducing the notion of 'type security', that strict controls must be 
placed on the use of the language by untrusted software in order to gain 
reasonable assurance. However, it is shown that these controls can be 
implemented without resort to an Ada subset. We thus propose a 
method of building a secure system in Ada which allows almost free 
expression within both trusted and untrusted software.
Ada/Type Enforcement.

Wood, A. W. WATT Syntax and Rationale. 1992 Jan 21. 
WATT is the name of a current DRA research project which aims to 
develop a software tool for checking the 'type security' of Ada 
programs. In this document we provide an abstract description of WATT 
by detailing the amended Ada syntax against which the tool will check 
the code submitted to it. After presenting the syntax, the document 
discusses the rationale behind it. Finally, some further issues that may 
be taken up in future designs for WATT are listed.
