Woodward, John P. L. Exploiting the Dual Nature of Sensitivity Labels. 
1987. 
One of the major goals of MITRE'S Compartmented Mode Workstation 
(CWM) project is to assure that compartmented intelligence data 
processed on workstations has proper security labels associated, such 
that data is neither under- nor over-classified. The CMW labelling 
strategy is different than that used in traditional secure systems (as 
suggested by the Department of Defense Tusted Computer System 
Evaluation Criteria), and revolves around associating two types of 
security information with objects: mandatory access control levels 
(MACLs), and sensitivity labels. MACLs are analogous to what are 
traditionally called security levels, and represent a failsafe level at 
which an object must be protected. Sensitivity labels accurately 
represent the classification of the data in the object, and also 
represent necessary handling restrictions. Supporting both MACLs and 
sensitivity labels for objects makes the system easier to use, helps 
prevent overclassification of data, and provides the capabiity of 
associating handling restrictions with data
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 23 - 30
This is the third of three papers from MITRE on the Compartmented 
Mode project. This paper addresses what may be regarded as an 
ambivalence in the meaning to be assigned to sensitivity labels.
Although the author does not say so outright, the ambivalence arises 
apparently from a divergence between theory and practice: the practice 
is to disregard the 'markings' content of a label as the basis for 
mandatory access control. (These markings are nothing to do with 
discretionary access).
Thus in this paper, which seeks to codify this practice and support it 
explicitly through system design, a distinction is drawn between:
 What is called a (floating) sensitivity label on data, which is 
computed dynamically as the least upper bound of all labels of data 
which has actually been accessed in the preparation of this data. This 
serves for labelling output 'accurately', i.e. without danger of 
overclassifying, and performs the error-prone computation of 
combinations of labels automatically.
 What is called mandatory access control level (MACL) - a second kind 
of label which represents a ceiling for a floating label and, being a 
property of both subject and object, serves as the basis for mandatory 
access control. The floating label cannot be allowed to float upwards 
indefinitely, or there is no control.
A more descriptive name for these two kinds of labels might be 'actual' 
and 'potential'.
This system differs from conventional controls apparently in two 
respects: simplified versions of classification and clearance are 
compared for granting access, and the system keeps track of an actual 
upper bound for the sensitivity of an object (which starts off 
UNCLASSIFIED for a newly created empty object and floats up). Note 
that there is here a notion of an empty object, so that an object can be 
distinguished from its contents. This is unlike the conventional 
treatment, and is an advance.
/security/multilevel security/security policies/labels/compartmented 
mode workstation. 

