/formal specification/languages/Gypsy/Z.

Young, William D.; McHugh, John. Coding for a Believable Specification 
to Implementation Mapping. 1987. 
One criterion for 'Beyond A1' certification according to the DoD Trusted 
Computer Systems Evaluation Criteria will be code-level verification. 
We argue that, while verification at the actual code level may be 
infeasible for large secure systems, it is possible to push the 
verification to a low level of abstraction and then map the 
specification in an intuitive manner to the source code. Providing a 
suitable mapping requires adhering to a strict discipline on both the 
specification and code sides. We discuss the issues involved in this 
problem, particularizing the discussion to a mapping from Gypsy 
specifications to C code
IEEE Comp. Soc. Proc 1987 Symp. Security and Privacy, pp. 140 - 148
John McHugh talked on some 'rules of thumb' for manually translating 
Gypsy to C. He began the presentation with a disclaimer, advising that 
the way to produce verified code is not to use Gypsy, rather we should 
design new languages and environments with this goal in mind. 
However, noting that Gypsy is the language of choice for many security 
applications, this paper is intended to address a translation discipline 
from specification to code.
The salient points of the discipline are:
 Preserve modularity of the specification
 Study semantics of specification and implementation languages
 Subset the languages so as to use only those features with a well-
defined semantics
 Translate similar data structure and operations consistently 
 Optimise cautiously.
The paper also contains an example of translating Gypsy sequences to 
C, and gives some guidelines on how code performance can be enhanced. 
The paper should be of interest to system designers using Gypsy to 
develop secure systems up to A1 certification.
/security/formal specification/verification/security/Gypsy. 

