Yu, C-F; Gligor, Virgil D. A Specification and Verification Method for 
Preventing Denial of Service. IEEE Trans on Software Engineering. 1990 
Jun; 16(6): 581-592.
Note: Revised version of IEEE Symposium paper.
In this paper, we present a specification and verification method for 
preventing denial of service in absence of failures and of integrity 
violations.  We introduce the notion of 'user agreements' and argue that 
lack of specificaitons for these arguments and for simultaneity 
conditions makes it impossible to demonstrate denial-of-service 
prevention, in spite of demonstrably fair service access.  We illustrate 
the use of this method with an example and explain why current 
methods for specification and verification of safety and liveness 
properties of concurrent programs do not handle this problem.  The 
proposed specification and verification method is meant to augment 
current methods for secure system design.
/Denial of service/liveness/safety/security/specification/temporal 
logic/verification.

Yu, Che-Fe (GTE Laboratories Incorporated). An Authorization Plan for 
Commercial Service Systems. in: 6th Annual Computer Security 
Applications Conference; 1990 Dec; Tucson, Arizona. USA: IEEE 
Computer Society Press; 1990: pp.376-383. ISBN: 0-8186-2105-2.
Commercial service systems should allow customers to control their 
service configurations. The challenge is to make this feature feasible 
in such a way that the system is easy to administer while ensuring the 
security of both customer's service and the control system itself. We 
argue that simple security mechanisms such as access control lists 
used in general-purpose computer systems are insufficient for 
administration control and authority delegation in commercial systems. 
We propose a security policy called an "authorization policy" suitable 
for administration and authorization controls. This security policy is 
enforced through a unified protection mechanism called an "access 
control hierarchy". The application of this access control hierarchy is 
demonstrated by examples.
/Access Control/Access Control Hierarchy/Security Policy.

Yu, Che-Fn; Gligor, Virgil D. (GTE Laboratories/Univ of Maryland). A 
Formal Specification and Verification Method for the Prevention of 
Denial of Service. In: 1988 IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy; 
1988 Apr 18; Oakland Ca. Washington DC: IEEE Computer Society Press; 
1988: pp.187-202. ISBN: 0-8186-0850-1.
Note: This paper received the (joint) best paper award from the IEEE 
program committee because of its comprehensive treatment of a 
difficult and formerly generally avoided topic.
It presents general skeleton specifications showing the areas which 
must be defined in order to verify the prevention of denial of service. 
The skeletons specify not only aspects of a service but also aspects of 
its users. It argues that the latter, a user-agreement, is always 
necessary even though the user's conformance to it cannot be checked 
by the service itself, because some reliance inevitably must be placed 
upon users to ensure, for example, that resources allocated by the 
service are eventually returned.
A user-agreement consists of liveness and safety statements about 
both an individual user's service invocation sequence and the service 
invocation sequence formed by the sum of all its users.
A user's invocation sequence is said to be safe if the operations 
invoked are only those allowed to that user and, where those operations 
consume and release resources, occur in an order which does not return 
unallocated resources. A service's invocation sequence is said to be 
live if their is always a sub-sequence of operations which will take a 
user out of a blocked condition into one in which execution can be 
resumed.
A complete service-specification model consists of a user-agreement 
specification and a service specification. The latter is divided into a 
specification of the service's sharing mechanisms and the sharing 
policies which the mechanisms are required to maintain. The sharing 
policies: simultaneity and fairness, together with the user-agreements, 
define the service's finite waiting time (FWT) policy.
The simultaneity policy ensures that a user will continue to have 
oportunities to progress provided the user-agreement is upheld. If 
progress is dependent upon a number of conditions this policy ensures 
that they will eventually all become true simultaneously.
The fairness policy then ensures that a user will not be blocked for 
ever assuming it has many oportunities to make progress. The service, 
will not, for example, continually allow other users to make progress 
at the expense of any given user.
Two examples, a resource allocator and Dijkstra's dining philosophers, 
are then used to illustrate the approach in practice. The example 
policies are written in temporal logic, which is well and briefly 
described in appendices, and which seems to be well suited to the task.
In this paper a formal specification and verification method for the 
prevention of denial of service in absence of failures and of integrity 
violations is presented.  The notion of 'user agreements' is introduced, 
and an argument presented that lack of specifications for these 
agreements and for simultaneity conditions makes it impossible to 
demonstrate denial-of-service prevention, in spite of demonstrably 
fair service access.  The use of this method is demonstrated with two 
examples and it is explained why current methods for specification and 
verification of safety and liveness properties of concurrent programs 
have been unable to handle this problem.  The proposed specification 
and verification method is meant to augment current methods for 
secure system design.
/security/availability/security models/temporal logic.

Yu, K. W. Date Encryption Based Upon Time Reversal. Computing Journal. 
